<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-12 00:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3943 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBA-REDSOX-INDIANS-NY     10-12 0983
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-INDIANS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED SOX WIN SERIES WITH A 12-8 VICTORY OVER INDIANS 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By JOE LAPOINTE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ The American League Championship Series will be a
shuttle showdown pitting a team without a World Series championship
since World War I against a team without a World Series
championship since last October.
</P>
<P>
   The Boston Red Sox, wild cards, damaged goods and heartbreakers
for decades, earned the right Monday night to move on to face the
powerful defending champion New York Yankees, whom they have never
faced in a post-season series. They did it with a 12-8 victory in
Jacobs Field over the Cleveland Indians, their third victory in
three days, to win the series by three games to two.
</P>
<P>
   Their primary heroes this time were Troy O'Leary, who knocked in
seven runs with two home runs, and Pedro Martinez, who came back
from a back injury to pitch six innings against a team that scored
1,009 runs this season, the most in half a century. In that span,
Martinez gave up no runs and no hits while striking out eight. It
was the first time a team has won a first-round series after
trailing by 0-2 since Seattle did it to the Yankees in 1995. In the
final three games, the Red Sox outscored the heavy-hitting Indians
by 44-18.
</P>
<P>
   No rational baseball fan would give the Red Sox a chance against
the talent-laden Yankees, who have rested since Saturday night and
have a pitching staff filled with starring starters. Except for
Martinez, who cannot pitch until Game 3, Boston has no dependable
starting pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   Bret Saberhagen, Monday night's starter, was hit hard for the
second time this series and driven from the mound in the second
inning. The second-best starter in this series was Ramon Martinez,
Pedro's older brother, who has just come back from shoulder surgery
and pitched much of the season in the minor leagues.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the Red Sox fielding skills are questionable. Their
best position player, Nomar Garciaparra, is playing despite pain in
his right wrist that idled him for one game in this series. But
baseball is not always a logical or rational game. Sometimes, as it
was in the last six days, it can be strange and wonderful.
</P>
<P>
   The four-of-seven-game series against the Yankees begins on
Wednesday night at Yankee Stadium. The winner will meet either the
Mets, the National League wild card, or the Braves in the World
Series. This is the first time both wild cards have advanced to the
league championship series.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the third inning, the two teams had combined for
15 runs, half as many as they scored on Sunday night in Game 4, a
23-7 Red Sox victory in Fenway Park that evened the series at two
victories each. But on Monday night, the runs were more evenly
distributed.
</P>
<P>
   The Indians led by 8-7. The Red Sox tied it at 8-8 in the top of
the fourth on a sacrifice fly by John Valentin, his second rbi of
the night and his 12th of the series.
</P>
<P>
   Pedro Martinez entered to start the bottom of the fourth. He had
pitched four innings in Game 1 here, but left with muscle pain in
his back. Generally considered the best pitcher in baseball,
Martinez went 23-4 with a 2.40 earned run average and 313
strikeouts. Before the game, Manager Jimy Williams had hinted that
his star might come out of the bullpen. ``He feels a lot better,''
Williams said. ``He's had a steady progression of feeling better
the last three days. So, I mean, that's a good sign. Can he pitch
is probably what you really want to know. I really think he can.
You know, we have to find the right spot.''
</P>
<P>
   In his initial inning, Martinez retired the side in order. But
the middle batter, Kenny Lofton, left the game in pain, with a
dislocated left shoulder, which he injured while diving into first
base after grounding out to Mike Stanley with Martinez covering.
Although Lofton had only 2 hits in 16 trips to the plate in this
series, he was a .301 hitter in the regular season and he is a
speedy leadoff man and is one of the better center fielders. Lofton
was taken to a local hospital to stay overnight for X-rays and
observation.
</P>
<P>
   The radar gun showed Martinez throwing his fastest pitches in
the range of 90 to 95 miles an hour. In the middle innings, the
game changed character, settling into a duel between Martinez and
Sean DePaula of the Indians.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Thome hit a two-run home run in the first inning off
Saberhagen and another in the third off Derek Lowe. In the previous
four games, Thome had two home runs and six rbi. For the Sox,
Garciaparra had a two-run homer in the first off Charles Nagy and
O'Leary had a grand slam off Nagy in the third.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the sixth, Martinez had thrown three scoreless
innings, walking two batters but striking out four in that span.
The lusty cheering, so frequent earlier, had subsided, and the
45,114 Cleveland fans broke only occasionally into spasms of
nervous pleading with Martinez in command.
</P>
<P>
   But they were frequently on their feet, wringing their hands.
Although much is made of the Red Sox not winning the World Series
since 1918, the Indians also have a long championship drought,
since 1948.
</P>
<P>
   In the top of the seventh, the Indians brought in Paul Shuey,
their third pitcher. After Indians Manager Mike Hargrove ordered
Garciaparra walked intentionally for the second time in the game,
O'Leary responded exactly the same way, for the second time: with a
home run. This one, also on the first pitch, scored only three
runs, giving the Sox a lead of 11-8. O'Leary's seven rbi tied him,
at least temporarily, with Valentin and two other players for the
record for rbi in a single game in post-season play. Valentin tied
the record the night before.
</P>
<P>
   In the bottom of the seventh, Martinez retired the side in
order, recording two strikeouts, the last pitch at 94 mph, and the
only sound to be heard was a kind of hush.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-12-99 0006EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
