<SLUG> BC-HKN-RANGERS-ISLES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN IT'S ISLANDERS VS. RANGERS, IT'S ALWAYS INTENSE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By TARIK EL-BASHIR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNIONDALE, N.Y. _ Despite all the new faces on both benches, the
Rangers-Islanders rivalry remains as intense as ever.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Rangers showed they were the more talented team
Monday night, but the New York Islanders fed off emotion and the
boisterous, sold-out home crowd at Nassau Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   The game appeared headed into overtime after the Islanders came
back to tie the score late in the third period, but the Rangers got
a controversial goal from Stephane Quintal with less than three
minutes remaining and escaped with a 4-2 victory.
</P>
<P>
   Quintal's game-winner, scored at 17 minutes 14 seconds, on a
slap shot from the point, slid past the Islanders' goalie, Felix
Potvin, who was bumped. The Islanders argued that it was the
Rangers' Kevin Stevens who made the contact, but replays showed
that it was in fact Jamie Heward, the Islanders' defenseman, who
rammed Potvin. The contact was just hard enough to slightly spin
Potvin as the puck entered the crease.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stevens didn't interfere,'' said Rangers coach John Muckler.
``He was interfered with by their player, and he pushed him away
from the goalkeeper. But Stevens didn't touch the goalkeeper.''
</P>
<P>
   The game went out of control in the third period as emotions
boiled over. It began with the ejection of the Islander defenseman
Rich Pilon for repeatedly cross-checking Stevens from behind in
front of the Islanders' goal. Then, moments later, Darren Langdon,
the Rangers' enforcer, stuck out his leg and tripped the Islanders'
captain and best player, Kenny Jonsson.
</P>
<P>
   Langdon was promptly jumped from behind by the Islanders giant
defenseman Zdeno Chara, who attempted to pound Langdon's head into
the ice.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's just an ongoing thing for the last 10 years,'' Stevens
said of his battles with Pilon Monday night. ``He plays hard but
sometimes he gets carried away.''
</P>
<P>
   One might expect that the rivalry would lack the intensity of
matches in recent years because both teams were overhauled during
the off season. The Rangers have 11 new players; the Islanders have
eight.
</P>
<P>
   But game was intense, from start to finish. The players were
quickly caught up in the emotion of the rivalry, and they fed off
the crowd's energy.
</P>
<P>
   The first 20 minutes were especially entertaining. The opening
period featured everything a good hockey game is supposed to have _
hard hitting, a couple of scraps and several good scoring
opportunities for both teams.
</P>
<P>
   The fireworks started early. Steve Webb of the Islanders slammed
into the Rangers' Manny Malhotra behind the visiting net, opening a
cut on Malhotra's face. Malhotra left the game briefly to get
stitched up.
</P>
<P>
   That, however, was just the start of the physical play. Moments
later the Islanders' rugged defenseman Rich Pilon was hit with a
roughing penalty for giving Stevens a facial with his glove. And
the rough stuff escalated.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a great game, every night should be like that,''
Muckler said. ``I don't think it's dead. The Islanders worked very
hard. They are a young hockey club and they are going to get
better. We were well prepared for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Heward tied the game with a power play goal at 12:34 of the
third period. Pinching in deep, Heward took a pass from Mark
Lawrence just outside the crease and beat Rangers' goalie Kirk
McLean to the far post, tying the game at 2-2.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers took a 2-1 lead in the second period on goals by
Kevin Stevens and Todd Harvey, and they spent the rest of the night
trying to hold onto that advantage, which they eventually lost late
in the third period.
</P>
<P>
   The game settled down in the second period as the Rangers, who
outshot the Islanders 25-14 through two periods, grabbed a 2-1
lead.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Stevens opened the scoring early in the period, rifling
the puck toward the net, where it deflected off Tim Connolly's
skate and past Felix Potvin at 2:00. Then, Todd Harvey made the
score 2-0 at 7:25, knocking in a rebound to give the visitors a
commanding 2-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   But the Islanders did not fold, instead regaining some of their
earlier momentum midway through the period. Buoyed by the
outstanding play of Felix Potvin, and the ineptness of the Rangers'
struggling power play, the Islanders cut their deficit to 2-1 on a
goal by Brad Isbister at 9:42.
</P>
<P>
   Theoren Fleury scored the Rangers' final goal into an empty net
with 23 seconds remaining.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's disappointing because we worked so hard,'' said the
Islanders' Gino Odjick. ``But you can't make those kinds of
mistakes in the final minute.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
