<HEADLINE>
GORE FINDS ARIZONA FRIENDLY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service
 clients)  
 By JOHN KAMMAN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
PHOENIX - Just before the nation's largest labor organization
issues its weighty endorsement, Vice President Al Gore cruised
through one of the least unionized states offering him self as the
candidate most willing to fight for working families.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Gore, who expects to receive the AFL-CIO endorsement on Oct. 13,
when that group votes at its national convention, told reporters
during a visit to a construction site in Phoenix that he is
``hopeful'' the union nod will be his.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know yet,'' Gore told reporters when asked whether he
was confident of the endorsement. ``I'm hopeful, but I don't have
the official word.''
</P>
<P>
   Later on Oct. 11, AFL-CIO political director Steve Rosenthal
told report ers in Los Angeles that Gore had received the necessary
two-thirds majority of the organization's execu tive council over
the weekend. The vice president is scheduled to address the Los
Angeles convention after the endorsement vote on Oct. 13.
</P>
<P>
   Explaining why he was campaigning in Arizona, Gore said he
believes the eventual party nominees will fight for the state in
the general election.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Arizona is going to be a battleground state in the
election of November 2000,'' said Gore, who is facing an
unexpectedly tight race with former New Jersey Sen. Bill Bradley
for the Democratic party's nomination.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there are a lot of people here _ not only Democrats,
but also independents and moderate Republi cans _ who don't want to
put our economic prosperity at risk, and they are a little
concerned that the Repub lican Party is drifting farther and
farther to the right.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore made the remarks after attend ing a fund-raiser that broke
a record for the amount of money raised by state Democrats for a
non-Arizona Democratic presidential candidate.
</P>
<P>
   The event, held at Eddie Matney's restaurant on Camelback Road,
eas ily pushed Gore's Arizona state fund-raising total past the
$250,000 mark _ far surpassing the $126,000 reported by Bradley at
the end of the July campaign finance reporting pe riod.
</P>
<P>
   Gore also used the fund-raiser to highlight his supremacy in the
en dorsement game. Among those who have signed on with Gore are 28
Democratic state lawmakers, three supervisors from two counties,
three councilmen from two cities and three mayors.
</P>
<P>
   Although Gore retains a wide lead in Arizona _ the most recent
survey by Arizona State University pollster Bruce Merrill showed
him ahead 42 percent to Bradley's 22 percent _ experts say Bradley
has been closing on Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Local pollsters suspect Gore's lead has shrunk appreciably in
recent weeks as the vice president has struggled to present himself
as a charismatic leader who could beat the GOP front-runner, Texas
Gov. George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   The candidate's more sprightly im age was on full display Oct.
11 as he schmoozed with local schoolchildren, issued off-the-cuff
remarks at his fund-raiser and later made an im promptu stop at a
local construction site.
</P>
<P>
   Arriving in the morning at Sky Harbor International Airport,
Gore bounded down the stairway from his airplane at the Lincoln J.
Ragsdale Executive Terminal and was greeted by half a dozen
dignitaries led by U.S. Rep. Ed Pastor, Arizona's only Democrat in
Congress, and Janet Napolitano, Arizona attorney gen eral.
</P>
<P>
   Gore was also met by representatives from unions, civil-rights
organiza tions, Hispanics, the clergy, senior citizens, veterans
and others.
</P>
<P>
   A disabled World War II veteran who identified himself as
73-year-old Duke Wellington of Glendale stood among welcomers with
the aid of a walker and held high the only homemade Gore sign in
evidence, although there were numerous pro fessionally printed
versions.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the only one who has done anything for us,'' Wellington
said of Gore's support for veterans' issues. Republican
presidential candidate Sen. John McCain ``signed on to have a
cutback in veterans' bene fits,'' he contended.
</P>
<P>
   Elected officials in attendance in cluded Maricopa County
Supervisor Mary Rose Wilcox and Phoenix-area lawmakers Sens. Mary
Hartley and Chris Cummiskey and Reps. Leah Landrum and Carlos
Avelar.
</P>
<P>
   Among others on hand were six leaders of Local 99 of the United
Food and Commercial Workers, whose international union endorsed
Gore on Oct. 10; Ray Arvizu, the newly elected president of the
U.S. Hispanic Chamber of Commerce; Ramon Gomez, leader of the Na
tional Civil Rights Movement; the Rev. Oscar Tillman, outgoing
presi dent of Arizona's branch of the National Association for the
Ad vancement of Colored People; and the Rev. Benjamin Thomas,
pastor of Tanner Chapel A.M.E. Church.
</P>
<P>
   Later, Gore used a tour of Kenil worth Elementary School in
central Phoenix, where overcrowding has forced students to
transform a media room into a classroom, to highlight his proposal
for a national school construction policy.
</P>
<P>
   Sporting his now trademark tan-col ored suit, Gore examined a
cluster of classrooms under construction at the school, then
attended a sixth-grade class, where he grabbed a micro phone and
kneeled before students, asking and answering questions in
Oprah-like fashion.
</P>
<P>
   The candidate also showed off his bilingual abilities, answering
some questions in Spanish.
</P>
<P>
   ``By investing more and building more classrooms and hiring more
teachers, we can reduce the number of students in each classroom,''
Gore told the 45 students in Arcelio Martinez's class.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not just a question of money; it's a question of
standards and reforms. But it cannot be done without money.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore told the students that he was responsible for helping to
push through federal subsidies for Internet services in low-income
school dis tricts, a program he boasted was ``the biggest infusion
of federal money into the public schools ever.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the children appeared less interested in Gore's policy
positions than in grilling him about his personal life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Does the country accommodate your need for food?'' one student
asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``No. No. My family and I buy our own food,'' Gore answered.
``Thank you for asking, though.''
</P>
<P>
   A second student asked Gore how much money he made, and a third
informed the vice president he wanted him as a father, ``so you can
give me some money.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore had no response.
</P>
<P>
   The class also inquired about Gore's preferred car model.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jeeps,'' Gore said, managing to stay on message. ``I like
American cars. Made by the UAW (United Auto Workers).''
</P>
<P>
   Later in the day, Gore visited the construction site of a
building at 24th Street and Camelback, where he shook hands with
about 30 members of the local construction, electrical and
pipe-fitting unions.
</P>
<P>
   During a picture-taking session with the hard-hat-wearing
workers, Ron Harvey, an electrician, yelled out, ``Kick McCain's
butt!''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the Republican Party has ever shown any interest
in organized labor at all,'' Harvey, a Gore supporter, said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
