<SLUG> BC-GOVMEX-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HULL HEADS DELEGATION TO MEXICO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service
 clients)  
 By GRACIELA SEVILLA  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
Gov. Jane Hull heads to Mexico City on Oct. 12 to seek top support
for her guest worker proposal, which she says would combat illegal
immigra tion while easing U.S. labor short ages.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hull, who has been in office since 1997, will be making her
first trade and protocol visit with Mexican President Ernesto
Zedillo. The labor program is just one of many Arizo na-focused
proposals she plans to discuss during the week.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Hull grabbed headlines from her counterparts at the
Border Governor's Conference in Tijuana, Baja California Norte, by
declaring that Arizona would be an ideal place to test an updated
version of the braceros program that was begun in the 1940s as a
way to ease war-re lated labor shortages.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an issue I want to keep at the forefront,'' said Hull,
who is sched uled discuss her idea with Zedillo; Rosario Green,
Mexico's secretary of foreign relations, and federal immi gration
officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, I'd like (their) support.''
</P>
<P>
   Hull will lead a 40-member delega tion that includes Arizona
business chiefs and state agency heads who will be included in a
series of meetings with cabinet ministers and top officials.
</P>
<P>
   Among the subjects topping Hull's agenda for her Oct. 13 talk
with Zedillo are:
</P>
<P>
   - Arizona's push to establish the CANAMEX trade corridor _ a
four-lane highway system stretching from Mexico City across the
border at Nogales and continuing north to Alberta.
</P>
<P>
   - A plan to allow U.S.-secured fi nancing for real estate and
other investments made in Mexico by U.S. companies and citizens.
</P>
<P>
   - Opportunities to increase ex changes of faculty and students
among Arizona and Mexican uni versities, as well as increase collab
oration in business, science and engineering.
</P>
<P>
   The four-day trip is the latest in a string of pilgrimages to
Mexico City by governors from U.S. states as far from the border as
Florida, Idaho and New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   As a border-state governor, Hull says she's well aware of how
shifts in Mexico's economy and government policies affect Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   For example, border towns have been shaken in recent years,
first by the peso devaluation in December 1994, which sharply
reduced Mexi can spending, and lately by spiraling illegal
immigration through Douglas.
</P>
<P>
   But proximity to Mexico has benefits as well. Since 1991, Mexico
has been Arizona's No. 1 trade partner, with exports to Mexico
skyrocketing since the North American Free Trade Alliance took
effect in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, roughly 19 percent of Arizona's foreign exports,
worth about $2.7 billion, were sold to Mex ico, according to
Stephanie Turner, Mexico liaison for the Arizona De partment of
Commerce.
</P>
<P>
   Hull and her delegation will be getting a first-hand look at a
Mexico in transition. The trip comes just as the presidential
campaign season has begun.
</P>
<P>
   Under Zedillo, the ruling Institu tional Revolutionary Party has
loos ened its former steel grip on Mexico's politics. For the first
time, the president is relinquishing his option to hand-pick his
successor. Instead, the party will hold a pri mary to determine its
candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Since the last presidential election in 1994, the country's two
leading opposition parties also have gained strength, a change
expected to in crease the competitiveness of the elections.
</P>
<P>
   Zedillo also has continued to open up Mexico's economy to
privati zation and foreign investment. Plans to dismantle the
Federal Utility Commission, which controls electric power for the
country, is an item of great interest to the heads of the Arizona
utilities traveling with Hull.
</P>
<P>
   Next month, Hull hopes to further her Mexico agenda by touring
the Arizona border with Jesus Reyes Heroles, Mexico's ambassador to
the United States. She also plans to follow up on invitations to
hold trade meetings with the governors of Sinaloa and Jalisco
states early next year.
</P>
<P>
   Hull says she intends to keep Mexico on her permanent agenda,
but some critics say she was slow to turn her attention south of
the border.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to her predecessor, Fife Symington, who cultivated
close ties with his Sonoran counterpart and vigorously defended
Mexico in na tional debates, Hull has been less vocal about Mexican
issues until recently.
</P>
<P>
   Symington met first with Zedillo's predecessor, Carlos Salinas,
in 1993 and had three visits with Zedillo between 1994 and 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Hull has met Zedillo briefly in March, when he stopped at Puerto
Penasco for the groundbreaking of a Rocky Point resort being built
with Arizona investment.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after her election to her own term as governor last
November, she received a letter of congratulations from Zedillo
inviting her to Mexico City.
</P>
<P>
   The governor said she has been busy with state issues and unable
to find time to travel to Mexico City until now.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took us a little while to get down there, with the way I
came into office,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Hull's policy adviser on Mexico, Margie Emmermann, who also
served Symington, said Symington was forced to take a prominent
stand on Mexican issues because he served at a time when Mexico was
besieged by crisis, including the peso devalua tion and Congress'
questions about Mexico's fight against drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Since Hull has been in office, how ever, the Mexican economy has
been rebounding and U.S. relations have been on the upswing. As a
result, Emmermann says, events have not pushed Hull to the
frontlines on Mexico issues.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, says Gail Howard, director of economic development for
Ari zona State University, Hull has qui etly continued support for
cross-border partnerships since she replaced Symington as governor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe Governor Hull hasn't been quite as public as Governor
Syming ton was, but certainly the activity level hasn't slowed
down,'' said Howard, one of the authors of the Arizona-Sonora
strategic economic development plan.
</P>
<P>
   For her part, Hull says she hopes her trip to Mexico will stoke
the fires of NAFTA.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's exciting to be able to go and sit down with the president
of Mexico about how we continue to keep NAFTA alive,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Among the VIPS traveling with Hull are CEOs and top executives
of a cross-section of Arizona companies, ranging from Art Martori,
a Phoenix businessman whose Mazatlan resort development represents
the largest private Arizona investment in Mex ico, to the
family-run Active Screw &AMP; Fastener from Tucson.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to send the message that NAFTA is for everybody by
taking a balance delegation,'' Em mermann said. ``We want people to
understand that you don't just sell, you buy, and you don't just
have investment going in, you have invest ment going out.''
</P>
<P>
   Other members of the delegation include the presidents of the
Univer sity of Arizona and ASU and executives from the state's
three largest utilities.
</P>
<P>
   Emmermann anticipates that some voters may question a governor's
international venture.
</P>
<P>
   ``Arizona is one of many states visiting Mexico,'' Emmerman
said. ``I think it's important that people here recognize that.
It's competetive now. We just can't sit back and let other states
try to gain ground on us.''
</P>
<P>
   Howard agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we were to be outdone in Mexico by Iowa, it would truly be
a sad thing,'' she said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
