<HEADER>
A3961 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-HKN-DUCKS-LADN-(SLANG     10-12 0508
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-DUCKS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPEEDY DUCKS BITE SHARKS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOUG SPOON  
 c.1999 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Give the Anaheim Mighty Ducks a five-on-three
man advantage twice in a one-minute span and their speed is bound
to be a factor.
</P>
<P>
   Teemu Selanne, who had one goal and no assists in the Ducks'
first three games, had three assists in this one. Add to the mix a
TV replay judge who takes a goal away from the opposition and the
result is an Anaheim victory. At least it was on Monday, when the
Ducks were both opportunistic and fortunate in beating the San Jose
Sharks 5-3 before an announced crowd of 13,571 at the Pond.
</P>
<P>
   Fredrik Olausson and Oleg Tverdovsky scored power-play goals
with a two-man advantage in a 53-second span, giving Anaheim a 3-1
lead after the first period. A goal by Marty McInnis at 2:40 of the
second gave the Ducks a 4-1 lead and knocked Sharks goaltender Mike
Vernon out of the game. At that point, momentum was all on the side
of the Ducks.
</P>
<P>
   Yet it took some tight checking and consistent defense to help
the Ducks hold on for the victory after a shaky second period in
which San Jose appeared to tie the score at 4-4 until Ron Sutter's
goal was disallowed following a review.
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks outshot the Sharks 18-4 in the final period for a
38-25 overall advantage. The period's only goal was an empty-netter
scored by Steve Rucchin with two seconds remaining.
</P>
<P>
   That was enough for the Ducks to hold onto the lead built around
two power-play goals late in the first period.
</P>
<P>
   With the score tied at 1-1, San Jose's Mike Ricci was sent to
the penalty box for holding at 17:08. Then at the 18:07 mark, Owen
Nolan was sent off for bowling over Ducks goaltender Guy Hebert.
Given a 5-on-3 advantage, it took the Ducks only 58 seconds to
score when Olausson beat Vernon with a low slap shot from the slot.
</P>
<P>
   That goal released one Sharks player from the penalty box, but
Vincent Damphousse was sent in following the goal on a delayed
penalty for obstruction. Handed another 5-on-3 power play, the
Ducks made the score 3-1 when Tverdovsky beat Vernon with a
one-timer from deep in the right faceoff circle at 19:55.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think our 5-on-4 still needs a little work, but when you
give us a 5-on-3 . . .'' Ducks left wing Paul Kariya said. ``I'm
just glad we're getting better creating scoring chances 5-on-5.''
</P>
<P>
   Then at 16:30, Hebert gave up a short rebound of a shot by
Sutter and the puck landed at his feet in a pile of bodies just
outside the crease. The puck trickled across the goal line, but
after a review of the play it was determined that Sutter had kicked
the puck into the net and the goal was disallowed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like a quarterback taking a couple hits,'' said Hebert.
``I made the save, watched the puck fall loose, and the next thing
I knew my face was in the snow with a guy on top of me and all hell
breaking loose.''
</P>
<P>
   Tverdovsky, acquired from Phoenix in the off-season, had a goal
and an assist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-12-99 0057EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
