<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-100GREATEST-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHARGERS OVERCOME HEAT, HUMIDITY, DOLPHINS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PETE ALFANO 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   This time, the war metaphors often used in football were
appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   Players suffering from cramps were helped off the field like
wounded soldiers by their teammates, many of whom were walking on
unsteady legs themselves. The winning and losing locker rooms
looked like field hospitals as some players were hooked to IVs to
replenish fluids, while others stretched out on the floor or on
training tables, too weary to move or talk. When they could summon
the energy, they peeled off their uniforms in slow motion,
grimacing from the aches and pains.
</P>
<P>
   Four hours after the AFC playoff game between the San Diego
Chargers and the Miami Dolphins began in the oppressive heat and
humidity in Miami's Orange Bowl, Rolf Benirschke kicked a 29-yard
field goal to give the Chargers a dramatic 41-38 victory in one of
the more memorable playoff games in NFL history.
</P>
<P>
   The Chargers didn't win this game, however, as much as they
survived. They squandered a 24-0 first-quarter lead and trailed the
Dolphins 38-31 in the fourth quarter, tying the score with only 58
seconds remaining in regulation. They wasted their first
opportunity to win in overtime when Benirschke missed a relatively
easy 27-yard field-goal attempt, and escaped defeat when the
Dolphins' Uwe von Schamann had two field-goal tries blocked.
</P>
<P>
   One was by Kellen Winslow, the Chargers' All-Pro tight end, who
did yeoman service on special teams. As the game wore on, the muggy
conditions took their toll on the future Hall of Fame receiver, who
fought off leg cramps to catch 13 passes for 166 yards and a
touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   The quarterbacks for both teams were as hot as the weather. Dan
Fouts of the Chargers passed for 433 yards and three touchdowns,
while Don Strock of the Dolphins threw for 403 yards and four
touchdowns. One came on the last play of the first half, ``the hook
and lateral'' devised by Dolphins coach Don Shula. Strock completed
a 15-yard pass to Duriel Harris, who lateraled to Tony Nathan
trailing the play. Nathan ran 25 yards for a touchdown, cutting the
Chargers' lead to 24-17 and changing the momentum of the game.
</P>
<P>
   The Chargers survived, but a week later, they faced new
adversity. They lost the AFC Championship Game to the Cincinnati
Bengals in a game played in frigid Riverfront Stadium, where the
wind-chill factor was 40 degrees below zero. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-12-99 0113EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991012.0020 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-12 01:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3964 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-FBN-JETS-JAGUARS-NYT &LR;      10-12 1023
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-JETS-JAGUARS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAGUARS BEAT JETS, 16-6 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By GERALD ESKENAZI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ A New York Jets team still searching for
its identity could hardly afford the lapses it committed on Monday
night against the Jacksonville Jaguars, a quality club.
</P>
<P>
   There was no consistent running and no clutch passing (at one
point the Jets were 1 for 10 on third-down plays), and despite an
effective defense, there simply weren't enough points scored to
prevent still another defeat.
</P>
<P>
   Jacksonville's 16-6 victory sank the Jets' record to 1-4,
keeping them in the basement of the highly competitive American
Football Conference East. They are the only club in the five-team
division with a losing record and the only one without a victory
over a divisional rival. The Jaguars improved to 4-1 and moved into
a tie with Tennessee for the AFC Central lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's about as poor an offensive performance as we've had in
a long time, maybe ever since I've been here,'' said Jets Coach
Bill Parcells, who is in his third season with the team.
</P>
<P>
   He pointed out, though, that the Jets were still in the game
late in the fourth quarter because of their defensive efforts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's still early in the season,'' Parcells said. ``I know it's
slipping a little bit now, but I'm just not ready to give in to
it.''
</P>
<P>
   You know the Jets are in trouble when Jaguars tight end Kyle
Brady, a former Jet, is running neck and neck in catches with
Keyshawn Johnson for much of the game.
</P>
<P>
   And certainly the Jets' failure to convert on third down _ they
did it only twice in 14 attempts _ reflected a team with hardly any
thrust.
</P>
<P>
   Rick Mirer averaged just over 4 yards a pass play, his 19
completions on 38 attempts good for a mere 164 yards. Although
Johnson led receivers with 8 catches for 94 yards, his two longest
gains came on a final, failed drive in the closing seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Brady finished with five catches for 42 yards.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets' final chance to mount a drive for a tie came with less
than four minutes remaining when they found themselves 98 yards
away. But a pass to Eric Green on fourth-and-6 from the Jets' 6
wasn't held, and the Jaguars took over and kicked a final field
goal to clinch the victory.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells speaks of the Jets' diminished margin for error since
the series of injuries that has transformed this club from one of
the most high-scoring, innovative teams to one that looks at times
as if it is just trying to get by.
</P>
<P>
   With the injured Vinny Testaverde, Leon Johnson and Wayne
Chrebet out of the lineup, that margin for error was squeezed on
Monday night. There were plays that made the Jets often look
distracted: the inexperienced Robert Farmer bobbled a kickoff in
the end zone, and Corey Sawyer saw a punt bound past him that
turned into an 83-yard kick.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a swarming Jets defense did its best to chase Mark
Brunell, the Jaguars quarterback, who was escaping time and again.
Often, though, he was forced to throw the ball away.
</P>
<P>
   Brunell's faked handoffs, his scampering ability and his
left-handed passing had the Jets' defense on its heels early. The
Jaguars went on a 13-play drive that consumed nearly six and a half
minutes and ended with James Stewart's 3-yard touchdown run.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets had gone three and out in their opening series on short
runs. But Johnson soon took advantage of the rookie cornerback
Fernando Bryant. The 6-foot-3-inch Johnson, who had a 5-inch height
advantage on Bryant, snared a 16-yard Mirer pass. But the drive
failed.
</P>
<P>
   So did most of what the Jets attempted in the opening half. A
Mirer pass intended for Quinn Early bounced off his hands, bounced
off Johnson and wound up being snared by the Jaguars' Blaine
McElmurry.
</P>
<P>
   Jacksonville got a 32-yard field goal by Mike Hollis, who was
brought close enough by Kyle Brady's 10-yard reception.
</P>
<P>
   Dwight Stone took the ensuing kickoff 43 yards to midfield for
the only exciting Jets play of the half. It helped set up John
Hall's 33-yard field goal with less than two minutes remaining,
cutting the Jacksonville lead to 10-3.
</P>
<P>
   But Hollis increased the lead again early in the third quarter
with a 44-yard field goal after Reggie Barlow beat Marcus Coleman
for a 32-yard pass play with Brunell.
</P>
<P>
   Mirer's problems were hardly unexpected. The Jaguars came in
having stopped opposing quarterbacks from completing a pass more
than 50 percent of the time.
</P>
<P>
   That statistic was punctuated in Monday night's third quarter:
Mirer threw three passes and completed only one, for 7 yards.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets got another field goal from Hall in the fourth quarter,
a 42-yarder, to move within 7 points at 13-6. That score was
significant for Hall. It was his longest field goal of the season
and came from the general distance that has given him problems
throughout his career. He had converted less than half his attempts
from the 40 to the 49.
</P>
<P>
   Monday night marked the only time this year that Parcells would
coach against a former assistant _ unless Jim Fassel of the Giants,
who play the Jets on Dec. 5, is considered.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells hired Fassel as the Giants' quarterback coach back in
1991, shortly after the team won the Super Bowl. But Parcells quit
in the spring for health reasons, and Fassel never coached under
Parcells in a game.
</P>
<P>
   Besides Jaguars Coach Tom Coughlin, other former assistants to
Parcells who made it as head coaches were Ray Handley, who
succeeded Parcells on the Giants; current Jets assistant head coach
Bill Belichick, who ran the Cleveland Browns, and Chris Palmer, a
one-time assistant at New England, who now coaches the Browns.
</P>
<P>
   Coughlin, who has molded the Jaguars in his image much as
Parcells has done with the Jets, was the Giants' receivers coach
for three seasons in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells came in with a winning record of 5-1 against his former
assistants: His Patriots were 2-1 against the Belichick-coached
Cleveland Browns, and 3-0 against the Coughlin-coached Jaguars,
including two playoff victories. Under Parcells, of course, the
Jets defeated the Jaguars in the divisional playoffs last January.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
