A3972 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r f BC-LA-FILM-PRODUCT-LADN     10-12 0505
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LA-FILM-PRODUCT-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
L.A. SEES SPURT IN FILM PRODUCTION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DAVE McNARY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- After lagging behind the 1998 pace in seven of
eight months, activity increased in September in Hollywood
entertainment production outside studio lots, an industry agency
reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Overall for-profit production in September rose 6.1 percent to
the equivalent of 2,679 days, reflecting a 15.5 percent gain in
movie work and an 81 percent jump in commercials, although TV
activity fell by 14.4 percent and music video work dropped by 3.9
percent, according to the Entertainment Industry Development Corp.
</P>
<P>
   But since activity already was fading fast in September of 1998,
the increase last month failed to get it back to the 1999 pace. The
year-to-date production rate lagged by 6 percent overall -- by 12.7
percent in feature films and by 9.7 percent in television.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are seeing a continuation of the same trends of flat
production,'' said EIDC chief Cody Cluff. ``There are no real
surprises since there were sharp fall-offs at this time last year.
TV has been a bit sluggish coming back from hiatus.''
</P>
<P>
   Cluff said runaway production to lower-cost locales that have
aggressively offered tax breaks, such as Vancouver and Toronto, has
put a damper on Hollywood production of made-for-TV movies, while
studios have been holding down costs and cutting back on the number
of feature films.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rest of this year looks very much like more of the same,''
said Cluff, whose agency obtains the permits for the producers in
80 percent of the off-lot film and video work in Los Angeles
County. ``Commercials should be fairly strong, TV will be strong,
and features may be up slightly.''
</P>
<P>
   Major features being shot at Los Angeles area locations include
Eddie Murphy's ``The Nutty Professor 2''; ``Gone in 60 Seconds,'' a
car-thief action project with Nicolas Cage; Cuban missile crisis
drama ``13 Days'' with Kevin Costner; ``Bounce'' with Ben Affleck
and Gwyneth Paltrow; an untitled Cameron Crowe project with Frances
McDormand; ``One Night at McCools'' with Paul Reiser, Matt Dillon
and Liv Tyler; and ``Coyote Ugly,'' a Jerry Bruckheimer project.
</P>
<P>
   Several studios plan to close for a longer-than-usual holiday
break at the end of this year, possibly to give themselves more
time to deal with potential Y2K problems. But Cluff said he doubts
the coming of the millennium will have much impact on production
activity.
</P>
<P>
   Between 1994 and 1997, off-lot activity in Los Angeles soared
before declining in 1998 and this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would expect next year to look very similar, with a lot of
episodic TV shot in L.A. and a reasonable level of pilot
activity,'' he said. ``We'll see the same low-budget
movies-of-the-week going to Canada. I don't expect to see a
resurgence of features because of the budgetary pressures. We'll
also see lower-budget independent projects filmed at a higher
rate.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
