<HEADLINE>
TWO STARS SHINE BRIGHTLY IN PAC-10 GLOOM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ As far as can be determined, there is no
coaching-controversy angle for Washington's game Saturday against
Arizona State.
</P>
<P>
   Sun Devils coach Bruce Snyder never succeeded Rick Neuheisel.
Nor has he publicly complained that the Washington coach cheated.
He has never coached a Seattle team, as did Dennis Erickson.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Snyder has not bellyached about Neuheisel's contract,
sideline dress, singing, hair color, play calling or substitution
patterns.
</P>
<P>
   Absent these talking points, for the first time in Neuheisel's
rookie year at Washington, we are left with a plain old college
football game between two plain old football teams, one 3-2 and the
other 2-3.
</P>
<P>
   Jeez. That means this week's stories are about ... players?!
</P>
<P>
   Sure enough.
</P>
<P>
   Just in time, too. The Pac-10's two best will be at Husky
Stadium: ASU running back J.R. Redmond and UW quarterback Marques
Tuiasosopo.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, arguments can be made for Stanford wide receiver Troy
Walters and UCLA wide receiver Danny Farmer. But, please, no
arguments for defensive players.
</P>
<P>
   Bad as the Pac-10 is this year, the defense by conference
members could not be more embarrassing if played in orange fright
wigs, oversize shoes and red noses.
</P>
<P>
   Check out this stat: USC leads the conference in scoring defense
at 24.2 points given up per game. For perspective, that's nearly a
touchdown worse than the highest number since the league began
keeping the stat in 1954: The '97 ASU team surrendered 18.5 points
a game.
</P>
<P>
   For further perspective, the famed Arizona ``Desert Swarm'' in
1992 has the Pac-10 record low at 8.9, followed by the '92
Washington unit's 9.2.
</P>
<P>
   For a conference whose leaders traditionally used to give up
only a couple of touchdowns a game, the '99 defenses are rubble
where once were walls.
</P>
<P>
   But enough about defenseless defenders. In Redmond and
Tuiasosopo, there is some serious star power in a league that is
otherwise nearly lights out.
</P>
<P>
   Redmond, who is recovering from a shoulder separation Saturday
against Notre Dame, was a preseason Heisman Trophy candidate who
led the Pac-10 last year in all-purpose yards, including 254
against Washington in the 42-38 loss to the Huskies.
</P>
<P>
   Said Neuheisel: ``There's reasons why he's considered a top-10
pick in the NFL draft.''
</P>
<P>
   The virtues of Tuiasosopo are slightly more elusive, though far
more influential in the UW season. The fact is that teams can load
up to stop Redmond, as Notre Dame did last weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Loading up to stop Tuiasosopo is not possible.
</P>
<P>
   While Washington's line and running backs deserve credit for
some of the improvement in the offense _ the Huskies have averaged
almost 39 minutes of possession time in their three consecutive
wins _ Tuiasosopo's versatility has made it difficult for defenses
to do anything but play Washington straight up.
</P>
<P>
   Tuiasosopo made the point well Saturday on the opening drive
against the Beavers. Running the option around the right side, he
kept the ball until three defenders were taking him down. Then he
flipped a long, dangerous pitch to running back Willie Hurst, who
one-handed the ball behind him and scored from 41 yards.
</P>
<P>
   It was the kind of ``no-no! ... yes-yes!'' play that makes
football coaches familiar with the acronym EKG. It's also the kind
of play that defines stars.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Marques thinks he can make that play, then I think it's a
good decision,'' Neuheisel said. ``That's why you recruit big-time
athletes.''
</P>
<P>
   As Snyder put it, ``I think he's a really amazing performer.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuiasosopo's deftness with the option is no real surprise. What
has improved this season is his sometimes suspect throwing.
</P>
<P>
   He's hitting on 58 percent of his passes with seven touchdowns
and five interceptions. Partly because of a lack of speed at wide
receiver, Tuiasosopo is still not throwing deep _ his longest
completion is 36 yards _ but he's also only a junior.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still believe he can be a very talented drop-back
quarterback on Sundays,'' Neuheisel said, referring to an NFL
future.
</P>
<P>
   But early on, it was what he wasn't doing in the mental game
that left Tuiasosopo aghast.
</P>
<P>
   ``I apologized to the team for my poor play in the first two
games,'' he said, referring to losses to BYU and Air Force. ``I
wasn't doing everything I could do.''
</P>
<P>
   He bumped up the work load in practice _ more film study, route
practice with receivers and playbook self-tests.
</P>
<P>
   ``My responses to every situation had to be cleaner and
faster,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The results are most obvious in the fourth quarter. Through five
games, he has 28 completions in 40 attempts for 338 yards and four
TDs, with one pick. He also has rushed for 62 yards, giving him 400
yards of total offense in final periods.
</P>
<P>
   However, none of those accomplishments contribute to
controversies about coaching. It just makes for entertaining,
winning football, a consolation prize for which Huskies fans must
learn to adjust.
</P>
<P>
   Art Thiel is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
