<SLUG> BC-FBN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVEN PARCELLS CAN'T SAVE THIS SEASON FOR THE JETS 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By MIKE FREEMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ Recently, Bill Parcells privately
fretted that the season was one of the most disastrous and painful
of his coaching career. Then, at about 10:20 p.m. on Monday, as the
Jacksonville Jaguars jumped to a 10-0 lead over the New York Jets,
effectively ending the game, things got worse for the all-world
coach. His season became as dead as the artificial turf at Giants
Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets' season is over. It's dead. And not even a miracle
worker like Parcells can revive it.
</P>
<P>
   The man who put the knife to Parcells's throat with
Jacksonville's 16-6 victory was his good friend, Tom Coughlin,
coach of the Jaguars. The two men are buddies, but this is
business.
</P>
<P>
   Coughlin may have done Parcells a favor, putting him out of his
misery fairly early in what promises to be a frustrating season for
the Jets. This is a bad year for an American Football Conference
East team to start its first five games with just one victory like
the Jets have done. That is because there are three probable and
four possible playoff teams in Buffalo, Miami, New England and
maybe the Indianapolis Colts.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets are not offensively equipped to compete with their
division neighbors. What was once unthinkable is now a reality. The
Jets are the worst team in the AFC East.
</P>
<P>
   Here's why. The Bills have one of the most dangerous offensive
players in the league in Doug Flutie. (The Jets have Rick Mirer.)
The Dolphins have Dan Marino and Cecil Collins. (The Jets have Rick
Mirer.) The Patriots have Drew Bledsoe, and the Colts have Peyton
Manning, two outstanding passers. (The Jets have you-know-who.)
</P>
<P>
   In order to bounce back from a 1-4 start, New York would need a
strong passer. Having wide receiver Keyshawn Johnson in the arsenal
isn't enough. Running back Curtis Martin isn't enough. As Marino
showed on Sunday against Indianapolis and Flutie showed against
Pittsburgh, quarterback play often makes all the difference in a
game.
</P>
<P>
   Mirer is not one of those difference makers. He is incapable of
leading the Jets on a winning steak of five or six games, which is
what the team would need just to keep up with the Joneses. Or even
the Colts.
</P>
<P>
   It is clear that Parcells, calling the plays on offense, does
not trust Mirer. On New York's first offensive series, Mirer did
not throw a pass, a conservative and curious move for a team in
such a dire situation. Mirer might not be any good, but to not have
him throw one pass on the opening series? What kind of tone does
that set for an offense?
</P>
<P>
   Mirer's longest pass completion of the first half was 16 yards.
Parcells mostly restricted Mirer to short throws and screen passes.
Last week against Denver, which had yet to win a game, Parcells,
figuring he had nothing to lose, let Mirer throw downfield more.
This game, Parcells pocketed the deep routes.
</P>
<P>
   It did not take long for the Jaguars to take advantage of the
Jets' dreary offensive situation. New York's defense played hard,
but without any chance offensively, Jacksonville began to wear New
York down. The first touchdown drive went 61 yards in 13 plays. The
Jaguars' second scoring drive ended with a 42-yard Mike Hollis
field goal.
</P>
<P>
   So with over five minutes left in the first half the Jaguars had
a 10-0 lead. For most teams that is not an insurmountable number,
but for the Jets it is. They had already lost.
</P>
<P>
   Mirer is not the kind of player, like Flutie, for example, who
gets tougher as the situation darkens. As the Jets fell further
behind, 13-3 in the third quarter, Mirer's throws got sloppier,
picking up a wobble here and there. One third-down pass sailed a
foot over Johnson's head, causing the emotional wide receiver to
curse angrily as he walked toward the Jets sideline. Mirer finished
the game having 19 completions for 164 yards on 38 attempts with 2
interceptions.
</P>
<P>
   The question for the Jets now is what will this season do to
Parcells? Maybe, he can salvage an 8-8 finish _ if that happened
he'd deserve coach of the year. A much more likely scenario is four
or five victories. That, of course, would tear up the coach inside,
but would it inspire him to return for another shot, or cause him
to walk away in frustration?
</P>
<P>
   The Jets' season may be done, but all is not lost. Like the
turf, all the Jets will have to do this off season is tinker.
Quarterback Vinny Testaverde will return from his injury, and later
this season Wayne Chrebet will be back. The Jets can reload and
make a legitimate championship run.
</P>
<P>
   But that is a long way away. Until then, brace for an ugly
season. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
