<SLUG> BC-BKN-CLIPPERS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
 CLOSS BATTLING TO STAY 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY HILL  
 c.1999 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Finally realizing his NBA career may be on life
support, Keith Closs is attempting to make the necessary
preparations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got to treat every day like my last day,'' said Closs, a
7-foot-3 enigma now entering his third NBA season after
masquerading as a potential shot-blocking fiend for the Lakers'
entry in the 1997 Summer Pro League at Long Beach State. That
performance convinced former Clippers coach Bill Fitch the team
would be wise to sign Closs to a multi-year deal.
</P>
<P>
   As a rookie under Fitch, he played 740 minutes spread across 58
games. In the lockout-compressed season of 1999, Closs' confounding
disinterest earned 87 minutes in 15 games for Chris Ford.
</P>
<P>
   Closs, who's on the books for $1.6 million this year and a club
option for another $4 million over two additional seasons, is
candid about the history of his NBA production.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't prepare myself the last two years,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Why not?
</P>
<P>
   ``A sour attitude and immaturity.''
</P>
<P>
   It didn't help that when Closs' number was called, his lack of
dedication to getting stronger (he may exceed 215 pounds if his
last meal included dessert) allowed opposing centers to push him
around.
</P>
<P>
   But in the first week of Clipper basic training this season, the
agile lefty has shown signs of competence. In a recent scrimmage,
he grabbed 15 rebounds, and even scored 15 points as an innocent
bystander while some slick passing was being committed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I'm doing so-so,'' said Closs, who realizes he needs
to take many steps forward before being considered a legitimate
backup center. ``Everyone says I'm playing well. But there's still
a lot of room for improvement.''
</P>
<P>
   Ford, who had to deal with that sour attitude and immaturity
last season, has chosen to wait before turning cartwheels.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been coming on time and doing the things he's supposed to
do,'' Ford said. ``Hopefully, it will continue.
</P>
<P>
   __ Wright's place, time: &UR; !off! &LR;  When free agent Lorenzen Wright
priced himself out of the Clipper market, his subsequent
sign-and-trade deal with Atlanta yielded two future first-round
draft picks.
</P>
<P>
   It also cleared a path for Brian Skinner, a second-year Clipper
who has the size (6-9, 250), strength and lunch-pail approach to
take Wright's minutes as the backup center/power forward.
</P>
<P>
   After extensive off-season work, Skinner - the team's choice
with the 21st pick in the 1998 draft - appears ready to make an
impact.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brian's going to have to give us minutes,'' Ford said. ``He's
going to have to produce.''
</P>
<P>
   In 258 minutes over 21 games last season, Skinner produced 2.5
rebounds and 4.1 points per game. Those numbers should grow.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do have to be more of a force,'' said Skinner, who also is
aware of his job description. ``I'm a role player, someone who does
all the dirty work.''
</P>
<P>
   Having NBA experience followed by a full training camp is a
comfort.
</P>
<P>
   ``This biggest difference this year is that I've learned to slow
the game down,'' said Skinner, who admitted to feeling like he was
caught in a whirlwind as a rookie. ``It feels slower now; I can see
things develop.''
</P>
<P>
   So can teammate Maurice Taylor.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's going to be a very important part of this team,'' Taylor
said of Skinner. ``It looks like his skills have caught up to his
body. Brian's always going to be in great shape. He's one of the
strongest guys in our conference.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Fast breaks: Veteran point guard Eric Murdock, acquired from
New Jersey in exchange for Johnny Newman (who was acquired from
Cleveland in the Lamond Murray deal) injured his left ankle in
Sunday night's scrimmage and will miss tonight's exhibition opener
vs. the Golden State Warriors at the San Jose Arena. ... Ford is
expected to start the same five that finished last season - Troy
Hudson and Eric Piatkowski in the backcourt, with Tyrone Nesby and
Taylor at forward, and Michael Olowokandi in the middle.
</P>
</TEXT>
