<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-12 01:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3981 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-FBC-CUSA-EXPANSION-HN     10-12 0972
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-CUSA-EXPANSION </SLUG>
 -HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY WIZIG  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
Starting in 2001, the University of Houston will no longer be the
lone Texas school in Conference USA. Texas Christian University is
leaving the Western Athletic Conference to join C-USA in all sports
two years from now.
<TEXT>
<P>
   In other action taken by the 14 C-USA presidents Monday in New
York:
</P>
<P>
   Southern Methodist, considered a possible defector from the WAC
with the Horned Frogs, was not issued an invitation to join C-USA.
</P>
<P>
   South Florida, a C-USA member in all other sports, was added as
a football member starting in 2003. It will become a Division I-A
independent two seasons before that and likely will play several
C-USA schools in the interim.
</P>
<P>
   East Carolina, already a Conference USA football member, will
compete in all other sports starting in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of the presidents' decisions, C-USA will have a
14-team basketball conference and an 11-team football conference.
Commissioner Mike Slive indicated no additions are planned in the
foreseeable future.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about SMU, which reportedly initiated discussions with the
conference before TCU, Slive said, ``The board (of presidents) has
finished its consideration of expansion for the moment.'' But,
added Slive, ``You never say never.''
</P>
<P>
   UH president Arthur Smith again referred to the obvious
advantages to the Cougars of adding another Texas school.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be a significant effect in reducing travel costs,
and it is a school our fans can easily travel to,'' said Smith.
</P>
<P>
   Said Cougars football coach Kim Helton: ``It is an honor to have
another Texas institution playing football in our conference, and
it is exciting to revive this rivalry. The addition of South
Florida brings even more credibility. I believe this expansion
solidifies us as one of the toughest football leagues, top to
bottom.''
</P>
<P>
   Slive noted that until they become full-fledged league members,
the conference will provide ``scheduling help'' for South Florida
in football and East Carolina in basketball and other sports.
</P>
<P>
   Once all 14 schools are in place, the most likely basketball
alignment will consist of two divisions of seven schools. Each
would play its division rivals home-and-home, with four games
against teams in the other division making a total of 16 conference
games. The addition of SMU would have resulted in an unwieldy
15-team basketball league, although the resulting 12 football
members would have fostered a natural two-division alignment and
league championship game.
</P>
<P>
   Slive indicated a football playoff is not an urgent concern at
the moment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the board or the athletic directors felt that (a
football playoff ) was a driving force in our thinking,'' Slive
said. ``Rather, it is, How do we best deal with our market, and how
do we make football and basketball grow? We're a league that has
made a marriage of football and basketball work, and this doesn't
change that.''
</P>
<P>
   While Slive declined to reveal financial details, TCU reportedly
will pay a $2 million entry fee.
</P>
<P>
   Adding TCU gives the conference a presence in the nation's
seventh-biggest TV market (Dallas-Fort Worth), but neither TCU nor
SMU seems to produce large audiences. The Frogs, however, have had
more successful football and men's basketball programs of late.
Last season's Sun Bowl win over Southern Cal under new coach Dennis
Franchione was TCU's first bowl victory in 41 years. And Billy
Tubbs has coached the Frogs to a 101-56 basketball record in five
years, including one NCAA Tournament trip and two NIT appearances
over the last three seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Slive described the additions to a league that is in its fourth
football season and approaching its fifth basketball season as
``part of our continued growth in a rational, reasonable way. There
were some important parts of the country we want to be in.''
</P>
<P>
   With TCU headed to its third conference in a seven-year period
(since the dissolution of the Southwest Conference was announced),
Rice president Malcolm Gillis said: ``We are quite pleased SMU is
staying in the WAC. This is pretty good news. There was a view that
both might go (to C-USA). I never thought that, because I couldn't
see how they (C-USA) would want two schools in one TV market.''
</P>
<P>
   TCU athletic director Eric Hyman referred to the advantages of
playing in a conference based in the Central and Eastern time zones
without a direct reference to the WAC's problems with media
attention in the western United States. Said Hyman, ``The
association with Conference USA enhances our brand identification
and places TCU in a position to take advantage of the marketing of
the entire institution. TCU's vision is to have a nationally
prominent athletics program, and that vision is the driving
influence behind our future membership in C-USA.''
</P>
<P>
   Jim Copeland, SMU's athletic director, began discussions with
C-USA more than a year ago. The Mustangs will move into their new
$56.5 million, 32,500-seat football stadium next year.
</P>
<P>
   Said Copeland, ``We just need to strengthen our own program and
the WAC.''
</P>
<P>
   East Carolina has done that in short order, hiring Bill Herrion
from Drexel and spending $12 million to improve its basketball
arena as part of a $50 million upgrading of facilities in the last
five years. The Pirates currently compete in the Colonial Athletic
Association in all sports but football, where they are ranked No.
23.
</P>
<P>
   South Florida, largely a commuter school in the Tampa-St.
Petersburg market, has 36,000 students and averaged more than
30,000 in football attendance in its first two seasons. Lee Roy
Selmon, the pro and college football Hall of Famer, launched the
Bulls' highly successful fund-raising effort for the football
program.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-12-99 0155EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
