<DOCNO> NYT19991012.0030 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-12 01:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3982 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKN-ROCKETS-MOBLEY-HN     10-12 0844
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ROCKETS-MOBLEY-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JONATHAN FEIGEN  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
Rockets coaches finally had to kick Cuttino Mobley off the court.
It was the offseason, his time. But he was working so hard, pushing
himself so relentlessly, that he was wearing out.
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``The guy plays every day,'' Rockets coach Rudy Tomjanovich
said. ``He's a guy we had to tell (to) take a little time off this
summer to recharge himself. He got a little bit stale.''
</P>
<P>
   Mobley just couldn't bear to remove himself from the floor. He
was too quick for the defenders who would make their way to the
Westside Tennis Club pickup games of NBA players. His shot was too
sure. Teammates had begun to clear out for him, even in the
relatively unstructured world of pickup basketball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just playing ball,'' Mobley said. ``That's what I do.''
</P>
<P>
   Mobley finally banished himself from the Westside court for a
few days. But when the Rockets reconvened last week for training
camp and Monday's return to their usual workout facility, there was
no letup. He was too quick for most defenders. His shot was sure.
Teammates cleared out for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more you play, the more mentally tough you get,'' Mobley
said. ``It's getting easier for me. I'm more comfortable with what
I'm doing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I worked hard. I worked on everything. I worked to mold myself
into a complete player.''
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, Mobley has become a different player than he was
as a rookie last season. He was confident then _ ``I've always been
confident,'' he says _ but the swagger seemed almost affected, as
if he had to announce his intention of making it in a league that
had allowed him to be drafted in the second round.
</P>
<P>
   This season, he seems no less confident but more self-assured,
more grounded. His play, while still explosive, has been
controlled.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's just maturity,'' Tomjanovich said. ``He is growing as a
player. It's all been there. That's what we saw.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets, meanwhile, have grown around Mobley, and every
change seems to have benefited him as if designed only for him.
</P>
<P>
   The trade to acquire Steve Francis assured the planned move of
Mobley from point guard to off guard.
</P>
<P>
   With Francis and Shandon Anderson in the backcourt, the Rockets
became determined to run, fitting Mobley's high-speed talents.
</P>
<P>
   And because they had to deal Michael Dickerson to land Francis,
even the acquisition of Anderson did not take away Mobley's
opportunity to play the shooting-guard position that better suits
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cuttino is playing great,'' forward Charles Barkley said.
``He's at his more natural position now, the two guard.
</P>
<P>
   ``He can't see but out of one eye when he plays the point. He's
a better scorer than a passer, plain and simple. He's got retinitis
pigmentosa. When he dribbles the ball at the point, he can't see.
But he's a better scorer.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Mobley's vision is fine. But Barkley was not
convinced.
</P>
<P>
   ``There had to be a reason he was missing all those wide-open
guys,'' Barkley insisted. ``Something had to be wrong with his
eyesight.''
</P>
<P>
   Mobley, as he did throughout his rookie season as one of
Barkley's favorite targets, quickly responded.
</P>
<P>
   ``He couldn't see on `D' at all,'' Mobley said. ``It was
retinitis both-eyes-atosa.''
</P>
<P>
   Mobley does not deny, however, he was out of position last
season as the Rockets' starting point guard.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always had confidence, but you play at different levels at
different positions,'' Mobley said. ``I've always been a two, a
scorer. I'm back at my real position. I'm sure I improved, but I'm
at my natural position. It gives me the opportunity to be more
aggressive.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a learning experience. It helped me to be better
prepared. It will help me a lot at the two.''
</P>
<P>
   Tomjanovich said the Rockets always knew Mobley was better
suited to off guard. He needed Mobley at the point last season and
asked him to do the best he could. But as a shooting guard, Mobley
can be a weapon, one of the reasons for the Rockets' rampant
optimism.
</P>
<P>
   ``At point, the matchup is with a smaller guy that can stay in
front of him more,'' Tomjanovich said. ``When he had his big games
early, it was as a two. I think he's a tough matchup for a two.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's really attacking the basket. He is sort of ending up in
an iso situation. He gets those openings in the offense, and he's
really attacking. Putting him at point guard sort of neutralized
his strength _ that's being a very good ball-handler at the two.''
</P>
<P>
   But as strong as that part of his game might be, Mobley might be
even more effective in the open court.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just fits his strength,'' Tomjanovich said. ``He's an
open-court guy, a great runner, great endurance. He attacks the
basket aggressively, but he sets that up with the outside shot.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Mobley, ``I think I have the advantage because I'm a real
quick two. It should be a lot of fun, especially with Steve and
Shandon with me. It's a lot of fun playing with guys that want to
run up and down.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
