<DOCNO> NYT19991012.0031 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-12 01:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3983 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-FBN-COWBOYS-IRVIN-HNS     10-12 0699
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-IRVIN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JODY GOLDSTEIN  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
The Cowboys' devastating loss to the Philadelphia Eagles on Sunday
took a back seat to concern for a teammate.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The news Monday was as good as they could have hoped as the
Cowboys learned receiver Michael Irvin had returned to Dallas and
is expected to be able to play again sometime this season.
</P>
<P>
   Irvin suffered trauma to his spinal cord when his helmet slammed
into the artificial turf as he was being tackled during the first
quarter of Sunday's 13-10 Dallas loss at Veterans Stadium. Irvin
was on the ground for 10 minutes and was eventually strapped to a
stretcher and sent via ambulance to the spinal unit of a
Philadelphia hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Irvin spent the night in the hospital but was able to walk out
Monday afternoon. He wore a protective collar around his neck but
was able to make the flight home.
</P>
<P>
   Irvin will see specialists in the Dallas area. There is no
timetable for his return, but it is not believed to be a
career-ending injury. Irvin, who has missed games because of
suspension, has not missed a game with an injury since 1990.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really too hard to tell how long he's going to be out
right now,'' Cowboys trainer Jim Maurer said. ``We're optimistic
that Mike will be back this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Doctors in Philadelphia discovered swelling and herniated disks
in two spots in Irvin's spinal cord, one injury to the C3-C4
cervical vertebrae, the other farther down in the C6-C7 vertebrae.
The latter is thought to be a pre-existing condition not related to
Sunday's injury.
</P>
<P>
   But Irvin will undergo an MRI Wednesday, which will be compared
to one made immediately after the injury. Doctors will then be able
to evaluate if the swelling has been reduced. Irvin is on
medication to help alleviate that swelling.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they got a pretty good picture of everything he
incurred,'' Maurer said.
</P>
<P>
   Irvin reported some numbness, particularly in his hands,
immediately after the hit. He never lost consciousness or suffered
paralysis, though he complained of neck pain. By Monday, he had
full motor functions intact.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's one of the reasons he's being released as early as
today,'' Maurer said.
</P>
<P>
   Irvin will definitely miss Monday night's contest in New York
against the Giants. The Cowboys will not speculate further.
</P>
<P>
   Ernie Mills replaced Irvin after the injury and caught two balls
for 16 yards. Jason Tucker and Jeff Ogden also filled in, Tucker
catching one pass for six yards. The Cowboys will also use rookie
Wane McGarity, who has been on the inactive list for the past two
games.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys' offense, which had 191 yards in the first half,
managed only 109 in the second, largely because of the lack of a
passing game. Quarterback Troy Aikman completed 21 of 39 attempts
for only 177 yards, with two interceptions.
</P>
<P>
   With Irvin out of the game, the Eagles were able to key on
Rocket Ismail, taking away the Cowboys' deep threat. Ismail caught
a game-high seven passes for 88 yards, 25 on a reception early in
the fourth quarter. Aikman's next-longest completions of the
afternoon were a pair of nine-yarders, one to Emmitt Smith for a
touchdown, the other to tight end David LaFleur.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, their attention goes to Rocket at that time,''
Aikman said. ``But they did a nice job of getting underneath our
intermediate stuff and forcing us to come underneath. And that's
fine. Those things happen, and there's nothing wrong with that. We
just didn't establish anything. Rocket did as well as he could do.
</P>
<P>
   ``Michael has been a great player for this organization for a
long time. He's made a lot of big plays in a lot of big games.
We're going to miss his presence, and we'll miss his competitive
spirit.''
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys coach Chan Gailey said he will explore the possibility
of adding another receiver if doctors determine Irvin will be out
for several weeks. Former Cowboy Alvin Harper has already made his
interest in returning to the team known. Harper, who has been out
of the NFL since the end of the 1997 season, was at Valley Ranch
working out for the coaching staff last week.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
