<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-12 01:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3984 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-BKN-MAVERICKS-PACK-TE     10-12 0655
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-MAVERICKS-PACK-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PACK SHAKEN BY MISTAKEN IDENTITY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DWAIN PRICE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ On Aug. 9, Robert Pack's beeper was mysteriously
``blowing up'' with one 911 message after another. Soon afterward,
his mother telephoned from Houston.
</P>
<P>
   What had the Pack household in an uproar was a ``New York Post''
story that said the Mavericks' point guard had been arrested in
Harlem, N.Y., in the wee hours of the morning and charged with
harassment and criminal contempt for violating an order of
protection against an ex-girlfriend. The story went on to say that
Pack arrived at the woman's home at 3:20 a.m. and started shouting
threats at her.
</P>
<P>
   The only problem with the story is that Pack was nowhere near
Harlem. He had been at his mother's home in Houston the night
before, and caught a flight back to Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   After an investigation, it was discovered that another man _
Anwar Bostick of West Orange, N.J. _ had been posing as Pack. The
damage done to Pack's name and reputation is still being assessed
by Pack's lawyer, Anthony Hilliard, who is out of the country and
couldn't be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to get to the point of me being exonerated from
everything that he's possibly done as Robert Pack, including
getting married,'' Pack said. ``From my understanding, he married a
girl last December, and he supposedly met her in August as Robert
Pack. So we know for at least a year, he's been saying he's Robert
Pack.''
</P>
<P>
   What Pack doesn't understand is how a mixup such as this could
occur.
</P>
<P>
   ``\RBostick\S doesn't resemble me at all, that's the crazy
thing,'' said Pack, a dark-skinned African-American. ``I haven't
met him, but from my understanding he's a light-skinned guy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sad part is he was able to wine and dine women with
limousines, and they would think he could do that from being a
professional player. But before they knew it, he would either have
their credit cards and was doing some things with it. That was
tricky.''
</P>
<P>
   One reason the impersonation succeeded as long as it did was it
occurred when the NBA had locked out its players in a labor
dispute.
</P>
<P>
   ``\RBostick\S had the perfect alibi with us being locked out and
him being able to entertain the women during that period of time,''
Pack said. ``He knew he didn't have to be on the road, and he
didn't have to be at practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``But they caught him, and he's been arrested.''
</P>
<P>
   Pack signed as a free agent with the New Jersey Nets on July 31,
1996, and was involved in a nine-player trade that sent him to the
Mavericks on Feb. 17, 1997. He never purchased a home in New Jersey
and said having his name dragged through a police report for
something he didn't do has cause irreparable harm.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had just left my mother's house \Rin Houston\S on a Sunday
night for a family dinner, and I had to come to Dallas because I
wanted to do my workout schedule,'' Pack said. ``Then she called me
and said, `Baby, you said you were catching a plane and you were
going back to Dallas.' I said, `Yeah, I told you that.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Then she said, `They've got you in New Jersey harassing some
woman.' She knew it wasn't me, but I know deep down it hurt her
immediately to see my face coming across the ``New York Post'' with
a picture in there saying something that she knew I wouldn't have
possibly done.''
</P>
<P>
   Pack said women need to be more skeptical when guys say they are
professional athletes. He also said the incident has forever
changed his life, and that a lawsuit will likely be forthcoming.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's funny when you watch TV shows, or movies, where people's
identities have been stolen,'' Pack said. ``You see that and you
sit back and wonder, `Man, that's tough; that would be terrible to
go through.'
</P>
<P>
   ``But when it actually hits home, and to be a part of it, it was
devastating. And I don't think the whole thing is over.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
