<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-IRVIN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS LOOK TO OTHER RECEIVERS AS IRVIN SIDELINED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RAY BUCK 
AND CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ The prognosis for Cowboys wide receiver Michael
Irvin to play again this season is excellent. Precisely when he
will return has not been determined, but the Cowboys anticipate he
could be out as long as six to eight weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Irvin, who suffered a spinal contusion that resulted in fluid
and swelling of the spinal cord after being driven to the turf
head-first during Sunday's 13-10 loss at Philadelphia, was released
yesterday from Thomas Jefferson University Hospital after being
held overnight for observation.
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys owner Jerry Jones sent his private jet to take Irvin's
wife, Sandi, from Dallas to Philadelphia yesterday morning to be
with her husband. The plane returned both of them to Dallas late
yesterday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is premature as to when he will return to the field,'' said
Jones, ``but based on everything that has been done so far, and
these were among the best spine specialists in the world, we are
optimistic that Michael will return this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wouldn't be coming back to Dallas this soon unless
everything was positive.''
</P>
<P>
   Irvin will wear a collar to stabilize his head and neck for at
least a week. The 33-year-old receiver will be definitely be out
for Monday night's game against the New York Giants at The
Meadowlands.
</P>
<P>
   Irvin has all his motor skills after experiencing some numbness
and loss of feeling in his extremities while lying motionless on
the Veterans Stadium turf for nearly 20 minutes Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The timetable for Irvin's return will begin to be defined when
the spinal cord swelling subsides. He is on anti-inflammatory
medication to reduce the swelling, according to Cowboys trainer Jim
Maurer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Michael will be \Rsidelined\S for awhile,'' said Cowboys coach
Chan Gailey. ``How long we don't know yet, but it will be for
awhile.''
</P>
<P>
   A Cowboys source said it could be as much as six to eight weeks.
Irvin has not missed that many games since he sat out the first
five of the 1996 season due to a drug suspension.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday, Gailey explained what the Cowboys will be missing
without Irvin in the lineup.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know there was a great deal of confidence and a great
relationship between Troy \RAikman\S and Mike on that one side,''
Gailey said. ``And the great season Rocket \RIsmail\S was having,
and the threat he was bringing on the other side, created a great
balance for our passing attack. We're going to have to find a way
to keep teams off balance and not allow them to take away one
side.''
</P>
<P>
   Ismail, who leads the Cowboys with 20 catches for 376 yards,
benefited in the first four games while opponents focused double
coverage on Irvin. Gailey figured that double coverage was going to
swing to Rocket's side and open up some play-making opportunities
for Irvin.
</P>
<P>
   Those opportunities now will probably fall to veteran Ernie
Mills and rookie Wane McGarity.
</P>
<P>
   Mills became a go-to receiver last season when he caught 28
passes for 479 yards, four touchdowns and a 17.1 yards-per-catch
average. As part of the tandem replacing Irvin, Mills will likely
be used in more a possession role, running the third-and-eight
routes.
</P>
<P>
   McGarity, the rookie from Texas, brings speed and quickness to
the mix. He has been inactive the past two games behind former TCU
reciever Jason Tucker, who is more versatile, according to Cowboys
coaches. But McGarity's quickness off the line could lead to some
big plays.
</P>
<P>
   Tucker and second-year receiver Jeff Ogden will continue to play
in the Cowboys' four-wide offense. Aikman showed some confidence in
Tucker by looking for him in the fourth quarter Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Jones said the Cowboys will not look outside to sign a receiver
such as former Cowboy Alvin Harper, who worked out for the team
last week, right now.
</P>
<P>
   And certainly, one player cannot replace Irvin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Michael has made a lot of big plays in a lot of big games for
us,'' Aikman said. ``We'll miss his presence. We'll miss his
competitiveness. Hopefully, it's only two weeks. But we don't
know.''
</P>
<P>
   Irvin was ``upbeat and laughing with his wife,'' yesterday,
according to Jones. Maurer said that Irvin earlier was heavily
sedated and immobilized to ensure his comfort overnight at the
hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ``Michael has done well,'' Maurer said. ``He has been on some
medication to help with the swelling that has occurred in his neck.
\RThe biggest concern\S is probably the subsiding of the fluid and
general symptoms that he might incur _ neck stiffness, soreness.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Andrew Dossett, a Cowboys team physician, will evaluate
Irvin tomorrow, but Maurer said even then, because of the spinal
cord swelling and the early stage of the injury, a prognosis for
his return might not be known until later.
</P>
<P>
   ``The priority is Michael's health,'' Gailey said. ``We're
fortunate ... it's not like not like he will be out forever or will
never play again.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
