u s BC-BBN-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-     10-12 0815
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ROBERTSON-COLUMN </SLUG>
 -HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
DaleRobertson
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
ATLANTA _ By all accounts, Astros fans are either hurt, sad, angry
or frustrated, or some combination thereof, depending on the time
of day and the alcohol content of the beverage in front of them.
They want answers, accountability. They're tired of talk. They're
demanding results.
</P>
<P>
   In short, they've become just like Braves fans.
</P>
<P>
   Everything is relative, isn't it? There may be three people here
outside the Atlanta organization who thought the Braves' beating
the Astros was a big deal, worthy of a champagne body spritzer. The
Mets' arrival for the National League Championship Series,
Atlanta's eighth since 1991, hardly elicits more than a loud scoff.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Mets?'' Braves fans are saying. ``Didn't we teach them a
lesson already? Didn't we just finish using their ugly mugs to drag
the infield?
</P>
<P>
   ``The Mets? Forget about it. Bring us the Yankees, and then
we'll get excited.''
</P>
<P>
   The Braves may be baseball's undisputed team of the decade, but
that's based on regular-season consistency, not postseason magic.
Remember, they have exactly one more world championship than the
Astros do, and they haven't gone to the World Series the last two
years, either, losing first to the rent-a-Marlins and then to the
plucky Padres.
</P>
<P>
   Atlantans, by and large, are bored with the Braves. The Tomahawk
Chop is passe. Ted and Jane hardly turn heads anymore. Greg Maddux,
Tom Glavine and John Smoltz might as well be Curly, Larry and Moe
except to the most hard-core faithful. As for Chipper Jones, what's
he got to be so chipper about?
</P>
<P>
   Hit the ball, chump.
</P>
<P>
   It's show-us-the-money time in Atlanta. Enough talk; give us the
walk. Perhaps the worst thing the Braves could have done this
season is to win 103 games despite a run of illness and injury
almost equal to what the Astros endured. See, it kept expectations
normal, which is to say Atlanta must win the World Series or be
branded a big bust.
</P>
<P>
   New York's AL pinstripes, not its NL pinheads, are the challenge
the Braves are expected to meet head-on. The Mets are the
undercard, practically beneath their contempt, if you'd heard Bobby
Cox's boys dissing them _ with good reason _ last month.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the tough-talking wild cards come in with the same
nothing-to-lose attitude the Marlins and Padres possessed before
them. Since things tend to even out over the long haul in baseball,
New York's losing nine of 12 to the Braves this year, including
five of six during a 10-day September swoon, may be bad for the
Atlantas now, given how October tends to bring out the insecurity
and self-doubt in them.
</P>
<P>
   The Houston series couldn't have provided much of a lift. The
Braves know they were lucky to escape the Astros unharmed. Only
Kevin Millwood, the upstart member of the Fab Four starting
rotation, pitched impressively, and only Brian Jordan swung a
heroic bat.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there's little in the matchups to suggest the Mets stand
a chance. New York wouldn't even have made the playoffs if
Cincinnati hadn't found a way to lose two of three in Milwaukee on
the final weekend. Bobby Valentine is the greatest also-ran manager
since Gene Mauch, and his team was plotting a mutiny until its
fortunes suddenly turned at the last possible moment.
</P>
<P>
   OK, the Mets showed something in beating the 100-game winners
from the desert. But the Diamondbacks were really just a puffed-up
expansion team with deep pockets playing in a division full of
overpaid underachievers. They weren't ready to be here, and now
they are gone.
</P>
<P>
   For the Braves, the NLCS has practically become their
birthright. However, their experiences in same haven't been
especially life-giving. Tonight's starter, Maddux, for example, is
3-6 with a 3.96 ERA in league championship play. Glavine's vitals
are 3-8, 3.93. His eight defeats are a record for the round.
</P>
<P>
   Smoltz alone (6-2, 2.58) has been routinely exceptional in the
NLCS, yet elbow problems made a mess of his latest season, and the
Astros reaffirmed his vulnerability Saturday with their too-little,
too-late rally.
</P>
<P>
   Millwood was magnificent with his one-hitter against Houston
after a breakthrough regular season. But this is his first
postseason, and as the pressure mounts, his inner strength will be
challenged accordingly. Playoff-wise, he remains a bit of an
unknown quantity.
</P>
<P>
   We favor the Braves to win because they are the Braves, but we
view them with extreme suspicion nonetheless. A superior team to
this one lost three in a row to San Diego a year ago, then bowed
out in six, dropping all three at home by batting .140 and scoring
only two runs.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros ran Atlanta's Turner Field postseason losing streak
to four last week before Millwood stopped the bleeding. So,
honestly, a Mets victory wouldn't be that amazin'.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
