<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MODANO, SYDOR FEEL READY TO GO
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Mike Modano remembers sitting in his hospital
room, not too long after being told by doctors that he was very,
very lucky not to be paralyzed.
</P>
<P>
   Then, Stars defenseman Darryl Sydor walked in.
</P>
<P>
   ``What in the heck happened to you?'' Modano asked.
</P>
<P>
   His eye blackened and bloody, scrapes lining his temples, Sydor
looked worse than a groggy and sore Modano felt.
</P>
<P>
   Now, only 10 days removed from that scene, Modano and Sydor were
once again talking yesterday. Of how the heck they've managed to
return so quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Both players participated in full-contact drills yesterday at
practice, including getting bumped and banged and tested, and said
they felt good enough afterward to play again. So coach Ken
Hitchcock said he expects them to be in his lineup when the Stars
play San Jose at 6:30 tomorrow night at Reunion Arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``This could've been it for both of them ... ,'' Hitchcock said,
stopping himself before he ventured into a very, very scary land of
what ifs. ``What we got away with was the best-case scenario
because it could've been much worse with both players. You catch
breaks individually and collectively, and this was one we caught
breaks on with both guys.''
</P>
<P>
   What-ifs remain a scary territory of contemplation for Modano
and Sydor.
</P>
<P>
   Sydor suffered a hairline fracture to his left eye socket after
being punched repeatedly in the back of the head by Anaheim winger
Jim McKenzie. He had blurred vision and swelling, and if the
swelling continues he might not play tomorrow night.
</P>
<P>
   Modano suffered a broken nose, ligament damage in his neck and a
mild concussion after crashing awkwardly into the boards when
Mighty Ducks defenseman Ruslan Salei pushed him from behind.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could've been a lot worse,'' Modano said. ``I've heard that
every day since.''
</P>
<P>
   The physical wounds basically have healed, though.
</P>
<P>
   The emotional aftershocks remain to be dealt with.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think myself lucky so much as Mike,'' Sydor said.
``Mine was a freak thing. Mentally, I'm not going to change my
game. I'm going to still play in people's faces. But I think
mentally for Mike that's a big thing, and that's where he's got to
be strong.''
</P>
<P>
   Modano said he isn't sure what he's going to be feeling. A
little nervous, a little excited, a little tentative all rolled
into a big ball of apprehension when he steps onto the ice for a
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think any injury you come back from you want to get out
there and get involved as soon as you can, if that means taking a
hit or seeing how you stand up in traffic or the physical part of
the game,'' Modano said. ``I think everybody who comes back from
injuries, knees or shoulders, after that first big hit or first big
play that you kind of feel you are back and ready.''
</P>
<P>
   And to be honest, he'd like to get that out of the way on his
first shift.
</P>
<P>
   The hits will be the big tests for Modano and Sydor. They felt
great last week, but they were skating around like two friends at
Rockefeller Plaza at Christmas. Yesterday, when Stars defenseman
Derian Hatcher was casually bumping them, was another test.
</P>
<P>
   And he's on their team.
</P>
<P>
   So imagine when Sharks defenseman Gary Suter comes flying in
trying to send them flying into the boards. It's the reason that
Sydor said he's not going to return until he's for sure he's 100
percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want another hit or another blow and then make it
worse, that's for sure,'' said Sydor, who will be wearing a visor
to protect himself.
</P>
<P>
   Stars winger Grant Marshall, who returned after breaking a bone
in his neck earlier in his career, said the key is just coming to
terms with getting hit again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I realized that if I wanted to pursue playing hockey, I had to
know if I could go or not go,'' Marshall said. ``So the next game I
was available to play and doctors said I could play, I forced
myself to play and go out there and take a hit and hit somebody.
And if it hurt or if I was going to be gun shy, then I knew I was
never going to play hockey again.''
</P>
<P>
   The test likely comes for Modano and Sydor tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, I get right in there and play the way I played,''
Modano said. ``I can't picture myself, visualize myself, playing
any other type of game than the way I play. It's fast and really
uptempo, and a lot of times you crash into the end boards or lose
your balance and go tumbling.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
