<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-INDIANS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARTINEZ RESCUES RED SOX
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ Pedro Martinez wasn't supposed to play the rest of
the series after straining a muscle in his back in the opener.
</P>
<P>
   Troy O'Leary might as well not have been playing; he had just
two hits in 16 at-bats in the first four games.
</P>
<P>
   The Boston Red Sox, though, are in the American League
Championship Series for the first time since 1986 because of the
heroics of the injured pitcher and the inept batter.
</P>
<P>
   Coming out of the bullpen, Martinez didn't allow a hit in the
final six innings, and O'Leary hit two home runs and drove in seven
runs as the Red Sox defeated the Cleveland Indians, 12-8, at Jacobs
Field last night, completing an improbable comeback from a 0-2
deficit to win the American League Division Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the playoffs,'' Red Sox manager Jimy Williams said. ``You
can have three-game winning streaks in the playoffs. You see it
during the course of the season. Does it happen very often? No. But
we fought out of that 2-0 hole. A lot of people contributed.''
</P>
<P>
   The biggest contributions in the deciding game came from O'Leary
and Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   O'Leary hit a grand slam in the third inning, rallying the Red
Sox from a 5-2 deficit, and a three-run home run in the seventh to
break an 8-8 tie. Both home runs came after the Indians
intentionally walked Nomar Garciaparra, Boston's best hitter.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been like that all year because of the player he is,''
O'Leary said. ``Sometimes I respond, sometimes I don't. Tonight was
a good game.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Leary was an unlikely hero. He was hitting .118 in the series
after striking out in the first inning.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez, on the other hand, was expected to provide heroics.
But not this way.
</P>
<P>
   Before the series began, those few people who gave the Red Sox
half a chance to upset the Indians did so because of Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   The slender right-hander is the acknowledged best pitcher in
baseball after going 23-4 with a 2.07 earned-run average and 313
strikeouts during the regular season. After working Game 1, he
would come back in Game 5 and pitch the Red Sox into the next
round.
</P>
<P>
   That scenario seemingly ended when the strained muscle that
knocked him out after four innings of the opener looked serious
enough to end his _ and the Red Sox's _ season.
</P>
<P>
   He tried to play catch Saturday, but had to call it quits after
a handful of slow tosses.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first time I tried to pick up a ball I was in pain,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   He tried again Sunday and lasted a little longer, but didn't
look ready to pitch in an over-40 game, let along a big-league
playoff game.
</P>
<P>
   But yesterday, Williams announced before the game that Martinez
felt much better and might be available.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement was greeted with no small amount of skepticism.
If Martinez was better, why in the world didn't Williams start him?
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, it looked like a ploy to throw off the Indians, perhaps
an attempt to disrupt Indians manager Mike Hargrove's strategy,
when first starter Bret Saberhagen and then reliever Derek Lowe
were pounded for a combined eight runs in the first three innings
as Martinez watched from the bench.
</P>
<P>
   But Martinez jogged to the bullpen to warm up, and entered the
game in the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't leave until he was carried off by his teammates after
striking out Omar Vizquel to end it.
</P>
<P>
   ``My back felt a little tighter in the last few innings,'' he
said. ``But the adrenaline at that point, and knowing we had the
lead, kept me going. I wasn't going to let go. I decided I was
going to be out there as long as I could.''
</P>
<P>
   Six no-hit innings by Martinez normally wouldn't be that
remarkable, not even against a powerful Indians lineup that scored
1,009 runs during the regular season and already had scored eight
when he entered the game. Martinez is that good.
</P>
<P>
   The way he did it last night, though, was unexpected.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez usually relies on a darting, exploding fastball that
reaches the upper-90 mph range, complemented by an outstanding
changeup and a curveball.
</P>
<P>
   But the back injury had robbed him of his best stuff. His
fastball never got out of the low 90s.
</P>
<P>
   So instead of a power pitcher, he became a crafty right-hander,
a Greg-Maddux-at-his-best clone. His effectively used his off-speed
pitches, the curve and changeup, and mixed in his fastball to keep
the Indians off balance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't throw my fastball the way I wanted,'' he said. ``I
just tried to hit my spots.''
</P>
<P>
   He still somehow managed to strike out eight in his six innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was outstanding,'' Hargrove said. ``His velocity wasn't
used to what we were seeing, but his off-speed pitches were good.
He pitched. He made his pitches when he needed to.''
</P>
<P>
   Because he did, and because O'Leary hit the two home runs, the
Red Sox completed the incredible comeback. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
