<HEADER>
A3989 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBN-METS-BRAVES-HNS &LR;      10-12 0687
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-BRAVES-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
By CARLTON THOMPSON 
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
ATLANTA _ The New York Yankees and the Toronto Blue Jays each have
won a pair of World Series in the 1990s. But ask anyone about the
team of the decade, and the answer will roll off their tongue with
a deep southern accent.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Atlanta Braves have been a model of consistency over the
last 10 years, winning eight division titles and appearing in the
National League Championship Series for the eighth consecutive time
(there were no playoffs in 1994).
</P>
<P>
   Not since 1990 _ when Cincinnati bumped off Pittsburgh _ has the
NL pennant been up for grabs without the Braves having a hand in
the decision.
</P>
<P>
   As the 1900s reach their end, a quick tally seems appropriate
with regard to the Braves' status as the team of the decade: four
trips to the World Series, one championship less than the Yankees
or Blue Jays. With the Yankees' hopes still alive for a third World
Series title (all since 1995), perhaps the team-of-the-'90s title
is up for grabs.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves get another crack at solidifying their case beginning
tonight when they host Game 1 of the NL Championship Series against
the New York Mets at Turner Field.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't won as many as we would have liked to, but what the
heck,'' Braves pitcher John Smoltz said. ``This is what you play
for, what you go to spring training for _ to have a chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who cares if we're the team of the decade or not? All we care
about is that we've got a chance to win again.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mets normally aren't in the business of doing favors for the
Yankees, but they would be more than happy to assist their Big
Apple neighbors on this one.
</P>
<P>
   If there is any team the Mets harbor more animosity toward than
the Yankees, it's the Braves. The feeling is mutual. The Mets and
Braves get along about as well as Santa Claus and the Grinch that
stole Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   The New Yorkers all but gift-wrapped the NL East Division title
for the Braves by losing nine of 12 games against their rivals,
including five of six over the last 10 days of the season.
</P>
<P>
   A few of the Braves pronounced the Mets dead after that stretch.
And while the Mets survived on life support until the very end,
they ultimately rose from the ashes.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves, who won the NL East by seven games, entered the
postseason with the look of a team that was supposed to be there.
The Mets looked like a team that was lucky to be there.
</P>
<P>
   But both dispatched their Division Series opponents with ease to
set up this showdown.
</P>
<P>
   No matter how clean the slate is, memories of being manhandled
by the Braves in the regular season must be lingering somewhere in
the back of the Mets' minds.
</P>
<P>
   Advantage, Braves? Maybe, maybe not.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you throw out the records,'' said Braves manager Bobby
Cox, falling back on a tired cliche. ``I guess nobody ever believes
the managers when they say that, but it's true.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it's the type of assessment only a fellow manager could
understand.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're due for some good things to happen to us against this
club, and I think they know it, too,'' Mets manager Bobby Valentine
said.
</P>
<P>
   Those who believe in fate claim destiny is on the Mets' side. If
they get past the Braves and the Yankees win the American League
pennant, the Subway Series so many were predicting in March would
become a reality.
</P>
<P>
   On the NL side, the Braves might have a thing or two to say
about that.
</P>
<P>
   ``This series is 0-0,'' said Braves third baseman Chipper Jones,
who almost single-handedly forced the Mets to the brink of
postseason elimination. ``The first team with four wins is going to
the World Series. They're riding a lot of momentum, and they've
been playing well for the last month.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, it would be an upset if the Mets won the series.
</P>
<P>
   ``The expectations are that they've pretty much handed it to us
all year,'' Mets general manager Steve Phillips said of the Braves.
``We're going in as the underdog without much to lose.''
</P>
<P>
   The stakes are much higher for the so-called team of the '90s.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
