<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-NOTES-TEX </SLUG>
 
WHO WILL PITCH FOR RED SOX? (For use by NYTimes News Service
clients) 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ Jimy Williams' hair was still dripping from the
celebratory champagne after his Red Sox won this series when the
first question came about the next one.
</P>
<P>
   Who's going to pitch against the Yankees, Jimy?
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to turn your rosters in when? Wednesday?'' he said.
``What is today? Monday? We'll just savor this moment right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams indeed wanted to enjoy the moment after his team
completed its 0-2 comeback against the Cleveland Indians. And he
usually is loathe to look more than a few minutes into the future.
</P>
<P>
   But there's more to it than that. The Red Sox pitching staff is
in disarray after surviving the Indians, and the thought of who
might pitch against the New York Yankees in the American League
Championship Series is something he doesn't want to think about.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know who is going to pitch,'' Williams said. ``Someone
is going to pitch, though. I'm being very honest, and I'm not
trying to evade the question or hem and haw around, because I
really don't know at this moment.''
</P>
<P>
   The Game 1 starter won't be staff ace Pedro Martinez, who threw
97 pitches in six innings of relief last night. OFFENSIVE EXPLOSION
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox were given up for dead when they left Cleveland
after losing the first two games, but their offense got them off
life support. After scoring just five runs in the first 22 innings
of the series, they pounded Indians pitching for 44 in the final
22.
</P>
<P>
   ``An MVP for this series?'' Williams said. ``I'd have to say it
was the whole team. Maybe that sums it up.'' PASSING THE CHARACTER
TEST
</P>
<P>
   Even though his team lost last night, letting the Red Sox
complete the comeback from the 0-2 deficit, manager Mike Hargrove
was proud of the way the Indians responded after being pounded in
Game 4, 23-7.
</P>
<P>
   The Indians scored eight runs in the first three innings before
being shut out the rest of the way by Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought this ballclub came out and showed a lot of
character,'' Hargrove said. ``Some stuff I read questioned the
character of this club, and I think that was answered tonight. We
got our butts handed to us, and we came out and played tonight. We
made the Red Sox play to win.'' LOFTON INJURED
</P>
<P>
   Indians center fielder Kenny Lofton left the game after
dislocating his left shoulder in the fourth inning.
</P>
<P>
   Lofton hit a sharp grounder to first baseman Mike Stanley, who
stopped it with a lunge to his right. Lofton and Red Sox pitcher
Pedro Martinez raced for the bag, and Lofton went into a dive when
he was a couple of steps away.
</P>
<P>
   He slid hard over the base, and stayed down in obvious pain. He
had to be helped to the clubhouse, where the diagnosis was made.
</P>
<P>
   Lofton was replaced by Dave Roberts. PITCHING WOES
</P>
<P>
   Indians pitchers Dave Burba and Steve Reed are bothered by
strained flexor pronators in their right forearms, making them
unavailable last night.
</P>
<P>
   Burba had to leave after four innings of his start against the
Red Sox in Game 3 because of pain in his forearm. The arm had been
bothering him for about three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Reed pitched 11/3 innings in Boston's 23-7 victory in Game 4,
and allowed eight runs on seven hits and a walk. THE LAST WORD
</P>
<P>
   Red Sox outfielder Troy O'Leary, on looking forward to the first
two games of the ALCS at Yankee Stadium: ``Now we have to go on and
play the Yankees in the jungle.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
