<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-12 01:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3991 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-TCU-LEBRETON-COLUMN-T     10-12 0707
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TCU-LEBRETON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER THE HANDSHAKES, TCU WILL DO NICELY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LEBRETON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For TCU, now comes the hard part.
</P>
<P>
   Blending into the new neighborhood. Keeping the lawn trim.
Trying to keep that ornery dog, Billy Tubbs, from barking all
night.
</P>
<P>
   Good luck on that last one.
</P>
<P>
   Bound for Conference USA, in just 19 months the Horned Frogs can
put Fresno and San Jose in their rear-view mirrors.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing personal. It's just that in the stripped-down Western
Athletic Conference, the Frogs were destined never to fit in. If
you don't believe that, you probably didn't stay up until the wee
hours three weeks ago, watching TCU lose to Fresno State and
wondering why anyone should care.
</P>
<P>
   In the WAC, it always seems to be half-past midnight.
</P>
<P>
   In Conference USA, TCU should be able to forge easier
friendships at reasonable hours. The WAC's showcase games usually
get squeezed in just before Conan O'Brien. C-USA, on the other
hand, is made up of schools from places that TCU alums have
actually been to.
</P>
<P>
   What do Memphis, Tulane, Houston, Cincinnati, Alabama-Birmingham
and Louisville have in common with TCU? A lot, when you think about
it.
</P>
<P>
   They are schools whose athletic programs have enjoyed periodic
success, even though several are private universities toiling in
the shadow of Big State U. In addition, Tulane, Houston,
Cincinnati, St. Louis, Marquette, North Carolina Charlotte and
DePaul have carved market niches, however modest, in communities
where the headlines tend to be dominated by professional sports.
</P>
<P>
   The C-USA family is an intriguing coalition of up-and-comers and
those-were-the-days-ers. The feeling here is that there won't be
many TCU followers who won't get stoked about a road trip to West
Point, home of Army. Tulane offers the Frog Faithful the Superdome
and a weekend in New Orleans. And Southern Miss has slain enough
football giants in its lifetime to capture even the most casual
fan's attention.
</P>
<P>
   In Tubbs' case, he won't have to worry about the strength of his
annual basketball schedule. Cincinnati, Louisville, DePaul and UAB
will give Tubbs' tournament politicking some instant ballast.
</P>
<P>
   In the WAC, there was always the chance that the Frogs could get
ambushed down some lonely, avocado-lined highway. It's been a lot
more than four time zones that have separated Hawaii and TCU.
</P>
<P>
   The Frog Faithful, no doubt, are distressed by the news that
rival SMU was not invited into C-USA.
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, right. For maybe two minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it was just a matter of odd numbers, as they said, that
prompted C-USA presidents not to extend a welcoming hand to Stan
and Muffy University. But think about it. Is there anything about
SMU that makes you think the Ponies will ever be perennial gridiron
powers again?
</P>
<P>
   This is not your daddy's SMU. This SMU likes to think of itself,
rightly or wrongly, on the same terms as Vanderbilt, Princeton and
_ dare we say it? _ Harvard. To a coach trying to win in today's
college football, that means it's always going to be
third-and-long.
</P>
<P>
   When the Southwest Conference split, TCU felt the rump-kick to
get its act together. The Committee of 100 helped carve a vision
for the school's athletic future. Hiring Tubbs was huge. Hiring _
and then re-signing football coach Dennis Franchione _ may have
been even bigger.
</P>
<P>
   The word is that TCU never blinked when it mentioned that there
might be a sizable ``entrance fee'' to join Conference USA.
</P>
<P>
   For the Frogs, it's going to be a long way from the dark day
when the old SWC split apart. Tubbs and Franchione will be able to
tell recruits about the new league's TV contracts with Fox and
ESPN. They'll be able to promise them games in big-TV markets like
Chicago, St. Louis, Tampa, Houston and Charlotte.
</P>
<P>
   It'll be a league that the Frogs can win in. There won't be any
backfields of fleet Californians to chase. Franchione will be able
to look a recruit in the face and tell him he'll probably go to a
bowl game during his four years.
</P>
<P>
   The hard part will be blending in. Shaking new hands. Letting
the C-USA presidents know that they made the right decision.
</P>
<P>
   The feeling is going to be mutual.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-12-99 0159EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
