<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-12 02:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3992 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBA-REDSOX-INDIANS-1S     10-12 1032
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-INDIANS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED SOX WIN PLAYOFF SERIES WITH A 12-8 VICTORY OVER INDIANS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs for rewriting throughout)  (ART ADV: Photos are being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(sw) 
 By JOE LAPOINTE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ The American League Championship Series will be a
shuttle showdown pitting a team without a World Series championship
since World War I against a team without a World Series
championship since last October.
</P>
<P>
   The Boston Red Sox, wild cards, damaged goods and heartbreakers
for decades, earned the right Monday night to move on to face the
powerful defending champion New York Yankees, whom they have never
played in a post-season series. They did it with a resilient 12-8
victory in Jacobs Field over the Cleveland Indians, their third
victory in three days, to win the series in an upset, three games
to two.
</P>
<P>
   Their primary heroes this time were Troy O'Leary, who knocked in
seven runs with two home runs, and Pedro Martinez, who came back
from a back injury in a relief role to pitch six hitless and
scoreless innings against a slugging team that scored 1,009 runs
this season, the most in half a century.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez struck out eight despite his throwing muscles
tightening as the night wore on. He credited the adrenaline of the
big moment. In the ninth inning, he ran to the mound, grabbed the
ball and stood there impatiently waiting for his catcher.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't going to let go,'' Martinez said. ``I decided I had
to be the one who had to be out there. I had to be out there as
long as I could.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the first time a team has won a first-round series after
trailing by 0-2 since Seattle did it to the Yankees in 1995. In the
final three games, the Red Sox outscored the heavy-hitting Indians
by 44-18. O'Leary, who went 0 for 5 on Sunday night in a 23-7
victory in Boston, hit both home runs after Cleveland pitchers
intentionally walked Nomar Garciaparra. ``Sometimes, I respond,
sometimes, I don't,'' O'Leary said. ``Now, we'll just have to go on
and play the Yankees in the jungle.''
</P>
<P>
   No rational baseball fan would give the Red Sox a chance against
the talent-laden Yankees, who have rested since Saturday night and
have a pitching staff filled with starring starters. Except for
Martinez, who cannot pitch until Game 3, Boston has no dependable
starting pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   Bret Saberhagen, Monday night's starter, was hit hard for the
second time this series and driven from the mound in the second
inning. The second-best starter in this series was Ramon Martinez,
Pedro's older brother, who has just come back from shoulder surgery
and who pitched much of the season in the minors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know who's going to pitch,'' said Jimy Williams, the
Boston manager. ``I'm not trying to hem and haw and evade the
question. I really don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the Red Sox fielding skills are questionable. Their
best position player, Nomar Garciaparra, who hit a two-run home run
on Monday night, is playing despite pain in his right wrist that
idled him for one game in this series. But baseball is not always a
logical or rational game. Sometimes, as in the last six days, it
can be strange and wonderful, and teams can seem to be blessed.
</P>
<P>
   O'Leary, speaking of the group, said: `` We have _ what's that
word you want to say? _ camaraderie-type thing. We've got a lot of
heart on this team. Pedro showed it. He came out, he was hurt and
he pitched today like the Cy Young winner that he is.''
</P>
<P>
   As he said this, his voice softened and his face took on a look
of total sincerity and gratitude. Martinez responded: ``Thank you.
Just like you. You looked like mvp's today, the team, to me, all of
you are mvp's.''
</P>
<P>
   Jim Thome hit a pair of two-run home runs for the Indians, who
have not won the World Series since 1948 but have qualified for the
playoffs as Central Division winners the last five seasons. Mike
Hargrove, their manager, said: ``We got out butts handed to us last
night and our guys came out tonight and showed up to play, and it
just didn't happen for us. We made the Red Sox play to win.''
</P>
<P>
   The four-of-seven-game series against the Yankees begins on
Wednesday night at Yankee Stadium. The winner will meet either the
Mets, the National League wild-card team, or the Braves in the
World Series. This is the first time both wild-card teams have
advanced to the League Championship Series.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the third inning, the two teams had combined for
15 runs, half as many as they had scored on Sunday night in Game 4.
But on Monday night, the runs were more evenly distributed. The
Indians led by 8-7. The Red Sox tied it at 8-8 in the top of the
fourth on a sacrifice fly by John Valentin, his second rbi of the
night and his 12th of the series.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez entered to start the bottom of the fourth. He had
pitched four innings in Game 1 here, but left with muscle pain in
his back.
</P>
<P>
   Generally considered the best pitcher in baseball, Martinez went
23-4 with a 2.40 earned run average and 313 strikeouts. In his
initial inning, Martinez retired the side in order. The radar gun
showed Martinez throwing his fastest pitches in the range of 90 to
95 miles an hour. In the middle innings, the game changed
character, settling into a duel between Martinez and Sean DePaula
of the Indians.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the sixth, the lusty cheering, so frequent
earlier, subsided and the 45,114 Cleveland fans broke only
occasionally nervous pleading with Martinez in command. His six
hitless innings were the second longest in the post-season, next to
Don Larsen's perfect game in 1956.
</P>
<P>
   In the top of the seventh, the Indians brought in Paul Shuey,
their third pitcher. After ordered Garciaparra walked intentionally
for the second time in the game, O'Leary responded exactly the same
way, for the second time: with a home run. This one, also on the
first pitch, scored only three runs, giving the Sox a lead of 11-8.
O'Leary's seven rbi tied him with Valentin for the record for rbi
in a single game in post-season play. Valentin had done it the
night before. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-12-99 0202EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
