<HEADER>
A4022 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON     10-12 0936
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CANNING CARTS MEANS CITY OF CANS
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By SCOTT OSTLER 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR;  SAN FRANCISCO _Third Street as it cuts through SoMa and over
the Lefty O'Doul Bridge is Tin Can Alley.
<P>
   It's the main artery for a small army, pushing shopping carts
loaded with cans and bottles through San Francisco's new boomtown,
past the new Giants ballpark and to a recycling center just across
Mission Bay.
</P>
<P>
   (Yes, the cans are aluminum, not tin, and Third Street is hardly
an alley, but grant me a little poetic license, OK?)
</P>
<P>
   What happens next week when Willie Brown's supermarket-cart
rescue task force starts executing the mayor's orders to confiscate
the carts from the homeless?
</P>
<P>
   What will be the impact on the recycle guys, and on the mountain
of cans and bottles they pluck off the streets every day?
</P>
<P>
   It's a symbiotic relationship, these people and the city. They
are like the birds that hop around the rhino's back, eating the
insects.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you take away our bread and butter and we can't recycle, we
can't make no money,'' says Mike, on a nonunion lunch break with
JoJo, a fellow recycler, on the sidewalk on Harrison, a couple
blocks off Tin Can Alley.
</P>
<P>
   The cops will hand out plastic bags to replace the carts. Mike
and JoJo chuckle at the thought of trying to lug 200 pounds of
bottles and cans in a bag, three or four miles to the center. From
Market Street to the center is already a two-hour schlepp. And the
Lefty O'Doul Bridge is currently closed for repairs, which adds a
long detour.
</P>
<P>
   A full cartload of cans and bottles nets you  &LR; $4 to $5 at the
recycling yard, and a hard worker can bring in a couple loads a day
_ ``Three loads, if you're desperate,'' Mike says.
</P>
<P>
   These are the lazy homeless people you often hear about.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't break into cars, we don't mess with anybody,'' JoJo
says. ``All we want is to be left alone, make money and do a little
panhandling on the side.''
</P>
<P>
   And Mike says, ``Let me go on record saying we don't steal these
carts. They're at the recycle place. You leave one, take another,
they're all over. We don't steal 'em from the markets.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike is wearing a baseball cap with the logo of Norcal Waste
Systems. The company motto is stitched on the back of the cap:
``Together Everyone Achieves More.''
</P>
<P>
   CULTURE VULTURES: In the Marin Independent Journal, a call for
volunteers at the Falkirk Cultural Center:
</P>
<P>
   ``Help is needed in the tattoo parlor of the dead, the lost
pirate's room, and the mad scientist's lab.''
</P>
<P>
   Looks like Al Davis is recruiting front-office staffers again.
</P>
<P>
   SPEAKING OF DEAD and haunted projects: A note in Monday's column
questioning the 49ers' commitment to keeping the team in town and
building a new stadium drew a call from Sam Singer, agent for
Denise DeBartolo York, 49ers owner-to-be.
</P>
<P>
   ``The stadium-mall project is stalled, but not necessarily
dead,'' Singer said. ``Denise is very committed to making it
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Singer says John York, Denise's husband, has personally scouted
four new NFL stadiums in preparation for the San Francisco project.
And both sides of the DeBartolo clan are working hard to finalize
the deal that will give Denise the 49ers, three racetracks and
corporate headquarters in Ohio, and give brother Eddie DeBartolo a
ton of stock and real estate.
</P>
<P>
   What about the stadium-mall plan, to which city voters pledged
to contribute $100 million?
</P>
<P>
   Singer says the agreement with the city doesn't specify mall,
but a ``revenue-producing'' part to the stadium. ``Could be mall,''
he said, ``or fill-in-the-blank.''
</P>
<P>
   Foto-Mat?
</P>
<P>
   RETIREMENT is doing strange things to the mind of Rod Stewart _
the former attorney, not the former ``Hot Legs'' rocker.
</P>
<P>
   ``Driving in our rural areas,'' Rod muses, ``I ponder this
ancillary of the probability theory: If an infinite number of
rednecks riding in an infinite number of pickup trucks fire an
infinite number of shotgun rounds at an infinite number of highway
signs, they will eventually produce all the world's great literary
works in Braille.''
</P>
<P>
   STEAMING UNDER the Golden Gate on Saturday for Fleet Week, the
aircraft carrier Abraham Lincoln's radar tower came within 10 feet
of clanging into the bottom of the bridge.
</P>
<P>
   The civilians on board the Honest Abe marveled at the crew's
calculations of the clearance-by-a-whisker. Alas, an inside source
says nobody bothered to make any such calculation, that the safe
passage under the bridge was a matter of pure luck. And maybe the
weight of the well-fed civilians on board.
</P>
<P>
   RIP TIX, SUPES SAY: Supervisor Gavin Newsom is picking up
support for his proposal to make San Francisco a friendlier place
by having meter maids rip up tickets if scofflaws return to their
cars while tickets are being written.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, be kind to meter cheaters who are hogging a rare parking
space while you and I circle the block like losers in a game of
musical chairs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where I used to walk five years ago,'' says Scott Lepich, ``I
no longer can because of increased car traffic, people parking on
the sidewalks and in driveways while they pick up a soda or drop
off the dry cleaning.''
</P>
<P>
   Let the meter maids save their bonhomie for us meter-feeding
saps.
</P>
<P>
   MORE FLEET WEEK: Waiting to board the Larkspur Ferry at the
Embarcadero, an elderly British gentleman flinched when the Blue
Angels screamed several feet overhead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Christ,'' he said, ``it's like bloody Dunkirk.''
</P>
<P>
   IF JERRY FALWELL and his sexual spin doctors get you
straightened out, so to speak, what does that make you? A
recovering homosexual?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
