<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-12 03:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4023 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-TESTING-FIRMS-SFCHRON     10-12 1230
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TESTING-FIRMS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCHOOL TESTING FIRMS FACE INCREASED SCRUTINY
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By NANETTE ASIMOV 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR;  It was a screwup of monumental proportions, one that robbed
thousands of children of their summer.
<P>
   Nearly 3,000 students in New York City spent summer vacation in
the classroom this year after they were erroneously told that their
test scores were so low they would be held back a year if they did
not attend summer school. Someone at the testing company had pushed
the wrong button, and the scores came out wrong.
</P>
<P>
   The nightmarish situation could easily happen in California _
especially if the company that scored this state's standardized
test slips up again. This summer, 90,000 students in 44 school
districts received the wrong scores; 60,000 students were told
their numbers were lower than they really were.
</P>
<P>
   That was not the only mistake by the test's publisher, Harcourt
Educational Measurement. The company, which is not the same as the
one that caused the errors in New York, also blended the scores of
English-language learners with those of fluent English speakers,
making it appear that the English learners' scores had doubled in
one year.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the publisher, state educators and Gov. Gray Davis are
under pressure to avoid more mistakes as California moves into a
new era of high-stakes testing _ creating an exam that high school
students will have to pass before receiving a diploma and using
scores from the statewide Stanford 9 exam to develop the most
extensive school-ranking system in state history.
</P>
<P>
   The scoring blunders sounded an alarm in California this summer,
and the state Department of Education is preparing to look closely
over Harcourt's shoulder when the company scores next year's tests.
</P>
<P>
   ``The process will be very different, with full-scale
monitoring,'' said Bob Anderson, manager of the academic standards
office in the Department of Education. ``We will be watching every
step of the way.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the department was unable to act as a watchdog
because it held no contract with Harcourt. Instead, each of the
state's 1,100 school districts had a separate contract with
Harcourt _ a system rejected by state lawmakers this year.
</P>
<P>
   As California relies more on tests to judge children _ and
schools _ here is what is at stake:
</P>
<P>
   -- State takeovers of schools: Using the scores from last
spring's Stanford 9 test, the state has already identified 430
schools with below-average scores. Those schools must now design
and carry out an improvement plan. If their scores do not get
better in two years, administrators can be replaced.
</P>
<P>
   -- Public scrutiny: Starting in December, the state is supposed
to use Stanford 9 scores to assign each school a ranking of 1 to
10, with 10 being a top performance. A second 1-to-10 ranking will
compare schools with those with similar students by income level
and English skill.
</P>
<P>
   -- Student retention: Now that the state is requiring school
districts to end ``social promotion'' _ the practice of promoting
students who have not mastered the skills of the current grade _
districts could use the Stanford 9 exam to help identify students
for summer school or retention.
</P>
<P>
   -- Withholding a diploma: The state Board of Education is
expected to adopt an ``exit exam'' by October 2000, testing for
English and mathematics. State law requires that the test be given
for the first time to the class of 2004 _ this year's
eighth-graders _ and that students start trying to pass the test in
10th grade.
</P>
<P>
   California is one of dozens of states using testing to hold
districts accountable for low performance and to establish
consequences for schools.
</P>
<P>
   But the danger of unintended consequences _ like forcing
thousands of New York children to sweat through summer school
unnecessarily _ have Californians scrambling for a fix.
</P>
<P>
   ``The potential for unintended consequences increases as you
attach higher and higher stakes to a test,'' said Gerry Shelton, a
testing expert with the state Department of Education.
</P>
<P>
   This is especially true if there is pressure on the test
publishers to provide lots of data quickly, he said _ not only test
scores, but results broken down by ethnicity, gender, income and
language skill.
</P>
<P>
   It was especially true in California this year, when Harcourt
found itself with less than three weeks to score 4.3 million exams
_ the largest testing load in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Harcourt delivered the tests late to 136 districts. A domino
effect set in, and by June 1, when all 4.3 million tests were due
at the publishing company for scoring, many had not arrived. By
June 8, most were in.
</P>
<P>
   The delay meant the company had only three weeks to score the
tests, create subreports, verify data and give everything to the
state to check and ensure accuracy before posting results on the
Internet by a June 30 deadline.
</P>
<P>
   It did not happen.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, the statewide posting of scores was delayed three
more weeks while the Education Department and the company tried to
untangle scoring errors for English language learners, charter
school students and students in year-round schools.
</P>
<P>
   In an attempt to ease the tight schedule and eliminate the 1,100
separate contracts, state lawmakers passed AB366. The bill, which
Gov. Gray Davis signed Friday, extends the Internet posting
deadline to July 15 and authorizes a single contract between the
Education Department and Harcourt.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll get some relief from that,'' said Jack Dilworth, a
Harcourt executive. ``It will give us time to check things.''
</P>
<P>
   Dilworth said the company not only needs more time to check
things, but also needs to check them better. So Harcourt is
conducting an internal audit, beefing up its data-verification
procedures, improving its computer programs and hiring a liaison to
the state.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the company's work and the new law, even advocates of
the push for accountability have concerns about using a single test
to make important judgments about children and their future.
</P>
<P>
   ``I worry that we're in danger of putting too many eggs in one
basket,'' said state schools superintendent Delaine Eastin. ``This
(Stanford 9) test is designed to do certain things, and if we try
to make it do too much, some kids may get hurt along the way.''
</P>
<P>
   Leslie Demersseman, president of the California School Boards
Association, agreed. ``We have to be careful and make sure that we
don't hurt kids by holding them back based on inaccurate, invalid
test scores or increase our dropout rate because the standards we
set are so incredibly high,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   A 1999 report of the National Academy of Sciences on appropriate
uses of tests supports the view that teachers should judge the
competency of would-be graduates by looking at students' overall
high school performance, the kinds of classes taken, academic
portfolios and other clues that provide a broader picture of each
student than one test can provide.
</P>
<P>
   ``We issued very strong cautionary language against making
graduation decisions on the basis of a single examination,'' said
Mike Feuer, who headed a committee that wrote the report.
</P>
<P>
   ``The moral of this whole story is one that we have been trying
to teach for a long time,'' he said. ``Testing is imperfect and
inexact, and the consequences to children in school can be quite
dramatic.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
