<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-12 09:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4096 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u v BC-TEACHING-HOSPITALS-BU     10-12 0903
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEACHING-HOSPITALS-BUDGET-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:  
  
</HEADLINE>
  
 Tuesday, Oct. 11, 1999
<TEXT>
<P>
   Teaching hospitals, the crown jewels of American medical
education and research, are facing historic financial difficulties
as the result of cutbacks in the federal Medicare program.
</P>
<P>
   Those cuts were part of the 1997 Balanced Budget Act that helped
produce the first balanced federal budget since 1969. But the
achievement of the BBA has come at a severe cost to Medicare
health-care providers, such as nursing homes, home health agencies,
therapists and teaching hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   Responding to their complaints about the Medicare cuts in the
1997 BBA, Congress and the Clinton administration are expected in
the next several weeks to restore some of the funding. The proposed
restoration is known in Congress as the ``BBA-fix.''
</P>
<P>
   In a package of stories and photos being filed today, Hearst
Newspapers examine the impact, the politics and the history of
teaching hospitals _ and their financial problems stemming from the
Medicare cuts.
</P>
<P>
   The stories include profiles of five teaching hospitals, as well
as an overview of the Medicare debate and a look at the other
interest groups seeking a share of the ``BBA-fix.''
</P>
<P>
   Editors wishing a two-day series may consider this lineup:
</P>
<P>
   DAY ONE: The story slugged TEACHING-HOSPITALS and one or more of
the hospital profiles.
</P>
<P>
   DAY TWO: The story slugged MEDICARE-LOBBYISTS and one or more of
the hospital profiles.
</P>
<P>
   If you have questions about the stories, please call Chuck Lewis
at the Washington bureau of Hearst Newspapers, 202-298-6920. If you
have questions about the photos, please call Joe Cavaretta,
director of photography at the San Antonio Express-News, at
210-250-3210.
</P>
<P>
   The stories and photos are for release Sunday, Oct. 17.
</P>
<P>
   TEACHING-HOSPITALS (Washington) _ Already battered by the
transition to cost-conscious managed care in the 1990s, the
nation's 400 premier teaching hospitals could lose their life
support if Congress fails to restore diminishing Medicare payments,
their advocates say. Congress and the Clinton administration are
now weighing whether to restore some of those cutbacks. By DAN
FREEDMAN and JUDY HOLLAND.
</P>
<P>
   MEDICARE-LOBBYISTS (Washington) _ Teaching hospitals aren't the
only health-related groups lobbying Congress for relief from the
Medicare cuts that the lawmakers and President Clinton imposed two
years ago in the drive to balance the federal budget. Also seeking
their share of an expected restoration of Medicare dollars are
nursing homes, home health care agencies, managed care providers
and physical, occupational and speech therapists. By JUDY HOLLAND
and DAN FREEDMAN.
</P>
<P>
   ALBANY-HOSPITAL (Albany, N.Y.) _ Highly specialized services
like neonatal care have helped improve the odds for premature
babies over the past decade. But such intensive medical care comes
with a cost. And doctors and hospital administrators at the Albany
Medical Center believe the decreasing subsidies for teaching
hospitals is putting research, training and sophisticated care _
especially for the poor _ at risk. By SYLVIA WOOD.
</P>
<P>
   HOUSTON-HOSPITAL (Houston) _ For the first time in recent
memory, Methodist Hospital is losing money on its day-to-day
business operations. Methodist, one of the nation's largest
private, nonprofit hospitals and a teaching hospital for the Baylor
College of Medicine, will end the year in the red, due mainly to
federal cutbacks imposed by the Balanced Budget Act of 1997. By
CAROL CHRISTIAN.
</P>
<P>
   SAN-ANTONIO-HOSPITAL (San Antonio) _ Lisa Ochoa calmly completes
her rounds in the busy emergency center of University Hospital and
confides: ``I've been in this system for seven or eight years and
every year it gets harder. It's mainly because they're so many of
them,'' she says, motioning toward patients, ``and so few of us.''
Unwittingly, the graduate medical student described a main concern
for teaching hospitals dealing with the Balanced Budget Act of
1997. By NICOLE FOY.
</P>
<P>
   SAN-FRANCISCO-HOSPITALS (San Francisco) _ Concerned about
looming Medicare cuts and intense local competition, the University
of California at San Francisco and Stanford University decided two
years ago to merge their four hospitals into a private, non-profit
corporation. Their marriage has been rocky, however. By ULYSSES
TORASSA.
</P>
<P>
   SEATTLE-HOSPITAL (Seattle) _ The federal government's budget
balancing act of 1997 looks like the AIDS virus _ a slow-acting,
unseen agent that will eventually erode the ability of teaching
hospitals affiliated with the University of Washington to rebound
from even the smallest wound or challenge. ``Any kind of a cut here
gets more quickly into the muscle and bone,'' says Robert
Muilenberg, executive director of the University of Washington
Medical Center. By TOM PAULSON.
</P>
<P>
   MEDICARE-BIAGGI (Bronx, N.Y.) _ Mario Biaggi, a former New York
cop-turned-congressman who fought for the elderly during his 20
years on Capitol Hill, says he now knows first-hand about holes in
the nation's safety net for the aged. At 81, Biaggi, has received
hundreds of hours of physical and occupational therapy, nursing
care and help from home health aides since his health started
slipping in February. That assistance has been cut because of the
reductions in Medicare payments brought on the Balanced Budget Act
of 1997. By JUDY HOLLAND.
</P>
<P>
   (END)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-12-99 0920EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
