<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-12 10:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4104 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-TEACHING-HOSPITALS-2T     10-12 0987
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEACHING-HOSPITALS-2TAKES-$ADV17-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEACHING HOSPITALS STRUGGLE TO SURVIVE MEDICARE CUTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, Oct. 17)   (Photos available on the Wieck database)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN FREEDMAN and JUDY HOLLAND  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Already battered by the transition to
cost-conscious managed care in the 1990s, the nation's 400 premier
teaching hospitals are facing the removal of their life support if
Congress fails to restore diminishing Medicare payments, their
advocates say.
</P>
<P>
   Affiliated with 125 medical college residency programs, these
hospitals are centers of cutting-edge medical research as well as
training grounds for future generations of physicians. Their
history is rich with medical breakthroughs such as organ
transplants and open-heart surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Even though teaching hospitals make up less than 1 percent of
the nation's 5,000 hospitals, they host 40 percent of the neonatal
intensive care units, 53 percent of the pediatric intensive care
units and 70 percent of the burn units. They provide 44 percent of
all care for the most impoverished patients.
</P>
<P>
   Teaching hospitals are at the vortex of a pitched battle in
Congress over whether to restore some of the $112 billion in
Medicare cuts that were made by the landmark Balanced Budget Act of
1997. That law was acclaimed for eliminating the federal budget
deficit for the first time since 1969. It also succeeded in halting
the rise in Medicare spending, which rose just 1.5 percent last
year, compared with 11 percent annual growth since 1980.
</P>
<P>
   But it came at a price.
</P>
<P>
   Medicare provides federal health insurance to 34 million senior
citizens and five million disabled people.
</P>
<P>
   As Congress and the White House grapple over plans for federal
spending for fiscal year 2000 that began Oct. 1, they appear likely
to restore at least some of the Medicare cuts. The questions are
how big any restoration would be and which programs would benefit.
</P>
<P>
   Teaching hospitals are not alone in seeking a Medicare
transfusion from Congress. Home health care agencies, nursing
homes, managed care health plans, and occupational, physical and
speech and hearing therapy groups all are vying for the same
dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Competing priorities _ defense and Social Security, for instance
_ make the size of any ultimate ``give back'' uncertain. Teaching
hospital advocates are pinning their hopes on legislation
introduced by Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan, D-N.Y., which would
prevent further cuts from taking place.
</P>
<P>
   The final details are likely to be hammered out by the end of
the month.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton has proposed spending $7.5 billion over 10
years on a Medicare fix. Senate Finance Chairman Sen. William Roth,
R-Del., proposes spending $1 billion to $1.5 billion next year. The
issue has become part of Hillary Rodham Clinton's Senate campaign
in New York _ home to 122 teaching hospitals and 12 medical
schools, more than any other state.
</P>
<P>
   At its core, the debate over teaching hospitals is a case study
in what happens when politics and social policy collide in
Washington. It also raises broader questions over how far the
federal government should go in shoring up the U.S. medical
education system at a time when managed care is leveling health
care costs and when medical economists worry about an over-supply
of some medical specialists.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you don't have teaching hospitals, you're certainly not
going to have cutting edge state-of-the-art medicine,'' said Sen.
Dianne Feinstein, D-Calif., among those leading the charge on
Capitol Hill. Failure to shore up teaching hospitals will lead to
``more deaths and we'll have a sicker population,'' Feinstein said.
</P>
<P>
   Under the Balanced Budget Act, the basic Medicare formula for
payments to all hospitals was cut $71 billion over a five-year
period, 1998 to 2002. Among the cuts that hit teaching hospitals
the hardest:
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Indirect Medical Education,'' worth about $4 billion
annually, was slashed 29 percent over five years.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Disproportionate Share'' payments to hospitals with a heavy
caseload of the poorest patients were reduced five percent over
five years. Two-thirds of those payments went to teaching hospitals
and were worth $4.5 billion annually.
</P>
<P>
   The Association of American Medical Colleges, which is urging
Congress to freeze the Medicare reductions, says about 30 percent
of teaching hospitals are now in the red. By 2002, if Congress does
nothing, 50 percent will be losing money, the AAMC says.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are huge, huge hits,'' said Dr. Jordan Cohen, the
association's president.
</P>
<P>
   The 1997 Medicare cuts compounded a teaching hospital financial
problem already very much in gear. Managed care plans view teaching
hospitals as overly expensive. These plans drive hard bargains in
terms of payment rates and sometimes steer patients away from major
academic medical centers altogether.
</P>
<P>
   As teaching hospitals began feeling managed care's pinch, they
came to rely more heavily on Medicare's special funding streams.
Once those began drying up last year, many hospitals faced deep
financial losses.
</P>
<P>
   Some academic medical centers have turned to the Hunter Group, a
St. Petersburg, Fla.-based consultant group for help in cutting
costs, often resulting in unpopular staff layoffs.
</P>
<P>
   One Hunter client, the University of Pennsylvania Health System,
which runs four teaching hospitals in Philadelphia, lost $90
million in 1998 and expects to lose at least $150 million in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Last May, the gigantic hospital and medical school system with
18,000 employees eliminated 1,100 positions.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. William Kelley, Pennsylvania Health System CEO, said the
hospitals were being eaten away by an ``invisible cancer.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll make it break even,'' he said. ``But we won't be the
creators of the future of medicine the way we have been.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Detroit Medical Center, a seven-hospital system affiliated with
Wayne State University, lost $106.1 million in 1998 and $93.2
million in the first seven months of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Another Hunter Group client, the Detroit system in January cut
2,000 positions from its workforce of 18,600.
</P>
<P>
   The loss of so many employees has had a devastating impact on
the hospitals, according to workers and officials of Local 79 of
the Service Employees International Union, which along with another
union represents 2,800 workers there.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are very short staffed,'' said Deborah Clark, a housekeeper
at the center's Sinai-Grace Hospital. Because of layoffs, Clark
worked 28 straight days in August and September and now sometimes
cleans up to 27 rooms and bathrooms daily, double the pre-layoff
number.
</P>
<P>
   In New York City, about 18,000 teaching hospital jobs _ eight
percent of the total in the city _ were lost between 1994 and 1998,
according to the Greater New York Hospital Association.
</P>
<P>
   A statewide study by the group found that New York's teaching
hospitals and medical colleges spend $21 billion annually and
employ over 250,000. They generate $1.85 billion in tax revenues
for New York state and $1 billion for New York City.
</P>
<P>
   ``Teaching hospitals to New York are the same as oil wells to
Texas and silicon to California,'' said the association's
president, Kenneth Raske.
</P>
<P>
   Many large institutions have been forced to merge, including
Columbia-Presbyterian Hospital and New York Hospital in New York
City and the teaching hospitals of the University of California at
San Francisco and Stanford University.
</P>
<P>
   Some universities are getting out of the hospital business.
George Washington University, which runs a medical school in
Washington, sold its hospital to Universal Health Services Inc., a
for-profit hospital chain. Others teaching institutions such as
Mount Sinai Medical Center-University Circle in Cleveland are
canceling residency programs altogether.
</P>
<P>
   Advocates for teaching hospitals say that if the cuts continue,
the hospitals might not be able to put the genie back in the
bottle.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not like a light switch,'' said Cohen of the AAMC.
``You can't turn these places off and then say `Oh, we went too
far, let's turn them back on.' You lose staff, you lose the
expertise, and you lose the ability to sustain the momentum for
these very complex and important programs.''
</P>
<P>
   The AAMC is spearheading a joint lobbying effort in Congress to
support Moynihan's bill that would freeze cuts to Medicare's
Indirect Medical Education funding at current levels.
</P>
<P>
   The group is sponsoring an advertising blitz. ``If Medicare cuts
continue,'' one ad warns, ``about the only place you'll find a
teaching hospital with the latest advances in medicine will be on
`ER,''' the popular television show.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the AAMC is playing what it considers to be its
trump card: Enlisting medical school deans and hospital CEOs to
plead the case of teaching hospitals before key senators and House
members from their home states.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, A. Wallace Conerly, dean of the medical school at
the University of Mississippi Medical Center, has flown to
Washington to visit his old family friend and fellow Mississippian,
Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott.
</P>
<P>
   The AAMC has no organized political action committee, the legal
apparatus for groups and corporations collecting and disbursing
candidate donations. But its chief ally, the American Hospital
Association, is a major player in the campaign finance world. The
AHA's PAC forked over $1.07 million to candidates in the 1998
election cycle, the 12th largest amount among trade groups,
according to Federal Election Commission records.
</P>
<P>
   During the same time period, the AHA also gave $103,000 in
``soft'' money to Republican Party committees, and $64,600 to
Democrats, according to Common Cause, the campaign finance watchdog
group.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not chopped liver,'' said AHA vice president Richard
Pollack, the group's chief lobbyist. ``We're trying to pull as many
levers as possible. Do PACs provide access? Yes. Do they buy votes?
No.''
</P>
<P>
   Pollack said the group is investing over $10 million to get
hospitals a break out of this year's congressional budget tussle.
The effort includes the advertising campaign, flying groups of
hospital executives and employees into Washington, and making sure
the issue is publicized in key primary states such as New Hampshire
and Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   The AHA's lobbying effort emphasizes issues of concern to all
hospitals, not just teaching hospitals. But the two coordinate
their efforts closely along with the National Association of Public
Hospitals, the Federation of American Health Systems (which
represents for-profit hospitals) and other groups.
</P>
<P>
   Arrayed against them are a potent alliance of health system
skeptics and key members of Congress, many of them conservative
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   In their view, teaching hospitals _ especially the larger
academic medical centers _ are dinosaurs that haven't adjusted to
the managed care era. They question whether taxpayers should
subsidize all of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the questions you have to ask is does it make sense for
a single metropolitan area to have six academic medical centers?''
said Gail Wilensky, chair of the Medicare Payment Advisory
Commission, established by Congress in the Balanced Budget Act to
advise it on Medicare issues.
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear how much of teaching hospitals' problems stem from
Medicare cuts, and how much from managed care, said Wilensky.
Either way, she added, they have resisted market pressures that
have affected all other elements of health care.
</P>
<P>
   ``Teaching hospitals hired a lot of faculty and expanded
aggressively in the 1980s,'' she said. ``They haven't done very
extensive, aggressive audits (to trim waste). It's certainly very
hard to say there isn't more they could do.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. William Thomas, R-Calif., chairman of the House Ways and
Means subcommittee that oversees Medicare, characterized the
typical major teaching hospital as ``a big downtown `ER' hospital
that doesn't represent the direction in which medical care is
going.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, he added that he has no problem with some teaching
hospitals getting help from the government, possibly separate from
Medicare.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
