<DOCNO> NYT19991012.0063 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-12 10:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4107 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-MEDICARE-LOBBYISTS-2T     10-12 1130
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDICARE-LOBBYISTS-2TAKES-$ADV17-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEACHING HOSPITALS VIE WITH OTHER GROUPS FOR MEDICARE FUNDS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, Oct. 17)   (EDS: Photos available on the Wieck database.)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JUDY HOLLAND and DAN FREEDMAN  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Teaching hospitals aren't the only health-related
groups lobbying Congress for relief from the Medicare spending cuts
that the lawmakers and President Clinton imposed two years ago in
the drive for a balanced federal budget.
</P>
<P>
   Also fighting for their share of an expected restoration of
Medicare dollars are nursing homes, home health care agencies,
managed care providers and physical, occupational and speech
therapists.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers and independent analysts, such as the Congressional
Budget Office, acknowledge that some federal health programs were
slashed too deeply when Medicare was cut by $115 billion, a key
element of the 1997 Balanced Budget Act (the BBA.)
</P>
<P>
   This realization is fueling a push for Congress to restore some
of the cuts as the lawmakers write spending bills for the new
fiscal year that began Oct. 1. The new funding is referred to in
Congress as the ``BBA-fix.''
</P>
<P>
   Advocates for the different groups vying for restoration of
Medicare funds have been making their cases in congressional
hearings and in the hallways, armed with industry surveys and
heart-wrenching anecdotes.
</P>
<P>
   Solid data is in short supply.
</P>
<P>
   The agency that runs Medicare, the Health Care Financing
Administration, is still gathering information to measure the
effect of the cuts _ many of which have yet to take hold. Because
the data isn't yet in, some key lawmakers are leaning toward a
short-term fix, such as one that would restore funds over one or
two years.
</P>
<P>
   As this high-stakes lobbying campaign rages, campaign
contributions have flowed from those jostling for a share of
returned Medicare money.
</P>
<P>
   The well-heeled American Health Care Association, which
represents the nation's nursing homes, ponied up $722,580 to House
and Senate candidates in the 1997-98 election cycle, federal
records show. Smaller players, such as the National Association for
Home Care, shelled out $37,000 in that period, federal records
show.
</P>
<P>
   Teaching hospitals boast that they don't even have a political
action committee, preferring to position themselves above the
fund-raising fray.
</P>
<P>
   Financial heavy hitters such as managed care plans also fork
over large donations in soft money, the unlimited contributions
that are supposed to go toward issue advocacy and party building,
as opposed to individual candidates. The nation's 10 largest
managed care plans shelled out $560,250, in 1997-98, according to
Common Cause.
</P>
<P>
   Following are the five main interest groups jockeying for more
Medicare funding:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OCCUPATIONAL, PHYSICAL AND SPEECH THERAPY &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Medicare pays physical, speech and occupational therapists to
help elderly or disabled people regain muscle strength, walk,
relearn how to swallow or speak, or how to dress or eat, often
after a stroke or an injury.
</P>
<P>
   THE CUTS: The 1997 Balanced Budget Act capped Medicare payments
for speech and physical therapy for each patient at a combined
total of $1,500 a year, and also limited occupational therapy to
$1,500 a year, except at hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   Before the cuts, only occupational and physical therapists in
business for themselves had an annual Medicare limit of $900 per
patient. Therapists working at nursing homes, rehabilitation
centers and physician's offices weren't capped.
</P>
<P>
   BACKDROP: Medicare payments to outpatient therapy providers had
been growing 25 to 35 percent a year from 1990 to 1996, according
to the Medicare Payment Advisory Commission.
</P>
<P>
   TOP LOBBYISTS: The three major therapy-related groups, known as
the Tri-Alliance, are represented by:
</P>
<P>
   --Patrick Cooney, 31, a former congressional staffer, is chief
lobbyist for the American Physical Therapy Association, with 70,000
members.
</P>
<P>
   --Jim Potter, 37, a former staffer for the American Medical
Association, is director of government relations for the American
Speech-Language Hearing Association, with 100,000 members.
</P>
<P>
   -- Christina A. Metzler, 47, a 15-year veteran of lobbying on
health issues, represents the American Occupational Therapy
Association, with 60,000 members.
</P>
<P>
   THEIR CASE: Cooney says the cuts are forcing some seniors to
ration their care because they are afraid of busting the limits. He
says the combined cap on physical and speech therapy forces elderly
and disabled people to make a cruel choice: ``They're asking a
patient to either walk or talk.''
</P>
<P>
   Metzler says many patients now get their occupational therapy
from untrained aides because they have exceeded the spending
limits. She also says about 30 percent of occupational therapists
report layoffs or lost jobs since the Medicare cuts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fewer therapists, means less therapy, means less healing for
the patients,'' Metzler says.
</P>
<P>
   THEIR GOAL: Therapists want no limits on Medicare spending for
the sickest patients.
</P>
<P>
   About one in seven Medicare beneficiaries needing rehabilitation
therapy will exceed the caps this year, according to Stephanie
Maxwell, a senior analyst at Congress's Medicare Payment Advisory
Commission.
</P>
<P>
   CHAMPIONS: Sen. Charles E. Grassley, R-Iowa, chairman of the
Senate Special Committee on Aging, Sen. Harry Reid, D-Nev., and
Reps. Richard M. Burr, R-N.C., Jim McCrery, R-La., Frank Pallone,
D-N.J., and Ben Cardin, D-Md.
</P>
<P>
   &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NURSING HOMES &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The 17,000 nursing homes across the nation care for 1.6 million
elderly and disabled people.
</P>
<P>
   THE CUTS: Before the 1997 cuts, Medicare reimbursed nursing
homes for such high intensity services as chemotherapy.
</P>
<P>
   Now nursing homes get a fixed amount per patient from Medicare
for room, board and medical treatment, which averages about $230 to
$300 a day, depending on a patient's medical condition.
Rehabilitation therapy in nursing homes also was capped at between
$1,500 and $3,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   BACKDROP: While Medicare payments to nursing homes rose 33
percent a year from 1990 to 1997, the number of patients increased
about 10 a year, according to the Medicare Patient Advisory
Commission.
</P>
<P>
   TOP LOBBYISTS: Bruce Yarwood, 57, a former nursing home manager,
is the key lobbyist for the American Health Care Association,
representing 12,000 nursing facilities.
</P>
<P>
   Also: Haley Barbour, former chairman of the Republican National
Committee, and Vic Fazio, former veteran Democratic congressman
from Sacramento, are lobbyists for the Alliance for Quality Nursing
Home Care, representing 12 of the nation's largest nursing home
chains.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   THEIR CASE: Yarwood says many nursing homes are cutting out such
services as dialysis, chemotherapy or ventilators because Medicare
doesn't pick up enough of the costs.
</P>
<P>
   The Medicare cuts have hurt the nursing home industry. One of
the nation's largest nursing home chains, Vencor, with about 300
homes in 46 states, filed for bankruptcy protection in September.
Sun Healthcare Group, a national chain with 385 homes, is in
default on its debt, and several regional nursing home chains are
faltering financially.
</P>
<P>
   THEIR GOAL: Nursing home advocates want Medicare to cover costs
for the sickest patients who require the most costly treatments.
They also want an across-the-board increase in Medicare funding.
</P>
<P>
   CHAMPIONS: Sens. Orrin G. Hatch, R-Utah, Pete V. Domenici,
R-N.M., Thomas A. Daschle, D-S.D., and Bob Kerrey, D-Neb.
</P>
<P>
   &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MANAGED CARE PLANS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Many managed care plans, such as HMOs, contract with Medicare to
provide health coverage to elderly and disabled people.
</P>
<P>
   THE CUTS: The 1997 Balanced Budget Act lowered Medicare payment
rates to these plans, which receive a fixed payment for each
patient, regardless of the patient's medical needs. To stop HMOs
from preferring relatively healthy patients, the federal government
decided to pay higher rates for sicker patients and lower rates for
healthier ones. The result: HMOs get fewer Medicare dollars.
</P>
<P>
   BACKDROP: At the time of the cuts, CEOs of some managed care
organizations were being paid annual salaries of $5 million to $15
million. Recently, federal auditors have said Medicare was
overpaying managed care providers who contract with Medicare. These
Medicare-managed care plans care for 16 percent of Medicare's 39
million enrollees.
</P>
<P>
   TOP LOBBYIST: Karen M. Ignagni, 45, a veteran staffer of the
A.F.L-C.I.O, was criticized as a turncoat six years ago when she
left the labor organization and went to work as president and chief
lobbyist for the American Association of Health Plans, a trade
association for the managed care industry.
</P>
<P>
   THEIR CASE: Ignagni says managed care plans that serve Medicare
beneficiaries have dropped 720,000 enrollees because the plans
don't find them profitable. She says managed care plans ``have
become the pinata of health care.''
</P>
<P>
   THEIR GOAL: Health plans want Medicare payments to managed care
plans to grow in step with traditional Medicare spending, rather
than the annual 1/2 percent reductions scheduled through 2002.
</P>
<P>
   CHAMPIONS:
</P>
<P>
   Reps. Michael Bilirakis, R-Fla, and Peter Deutsch, D-Fla.
</P>
<P>
   &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HOME HEALTH CARE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Home health care, commonly known as the ``visiting nurse''
program, is the federal Medicare benefit that pays for nurses,
aides and therapists to provide part-time care in the homes of ill
elderly or disabled people.
</P>
<P>
   THE CUTS: Before the 1997 Balanced Budget Act, Medicare didn't
limit the number of home health visits but set the cost of a
nursing visit, for example, at an average of $101. The 1997 cuts
forced that down to an average of $87.
</P>
<P>
   The Medicare cuts also put a lid on the amount that home health
care providers could spend on average for each patient each year.
Annual spending limits generally range from $1,200 to $8,000, based
on what the provider spent on patients in the past.
</P>
<P>
   BACKDROP: When Congress made the cuts, home health care was the
fastest growing part of Medicare, expanding an average of 25
percent a year from 1990 to 1997, according to the Government
Accounting Office. There also had been several scandals involving
home health providers squandering federal funds on such items as
gourmet popcorn, turkeys and luxury cars.
</P>
<P>
   TOP LOBBYIST: Val J. Halamandaris, 56, the son of a Utah Coal
miner, is the president of the National Association of Home Care,
the industry's largest trade association, with about 6,000 members.
Halamandaris was counsel to the Senate Special Committee on Aging
and the House Select Committee on Aging for a total of 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   THEIR CASE: Halamandaris says the 1997 Medicare cuts have
prompted the closing of more than 2,486 or one-quarter of the
nation's home health agencies, which are private businesses or
hospitals that provide home care.
</P>
<P>
   More are expected to fold because they have overspent caps
imposed by Congress and now must repay the federal government. The
closings have left a growing number of rural counties and poor
urban areas without home health care, says Halamandaris.
</P>
<P>
   Many providers are turning away patients who need the most
intensive and chronic care (the most expensive ones), he says.
</P>
<P>
   Since the cuts, the number of people receiving home health care
has fallen from 3.5 million to 3 million, according to estimates by
the association. Many of those who no longer receive home care have
landed in hospitals, nursing homes or are cared for by family
members, the association says.
</P>
<P>
   THEIR GOAL: Home health advocates want Congress to head off an
additional 15 percent cut slated for next Oct. 1 and they want no
limits on reimbursements for taking care of the sickest patients.
</P>
<P>
   CHAMPIONS: Sens. Susan M. Collins, R-Maine, Christopher ``Kit''
Bond, R-Mo., Jim M. Jeffords, R-Vt., and Reps. J.C. Watts, R-Okla.,
and John E. Peterson, R-Pa.
</P>
<P>
   &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TEACHING HOSPITALS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The nation's teaching hospitals receive about $9 billion a year
from Medicare to train medical residents and help cover the higher
cost of their traditionally sicker and poorer patients.
</P>
<P>
   THE CUTS: The Balanced Budget Act of 1997 slashed the Indirect
Medical Education payment, a fee added to each Medicare payment to
subsidize the cost of more intensive treatment for the severely
ill. The fees were cut by 29 percent over five years through 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Disproportionate Share Hospital payments, which go to
institutions that serve unusually large numbers of poor people,
were cut by 5 percent over five years.
</P>
<P>
   The 1997 Balanced Budget Act also capped the number of residents
allowed at teaching hospitals at 1996 levels.
</P>
<P>
   THE BACKDROP: At the time of the cuts, many of the nation
largest teaching hospitals had 28 percent profit margins for
Medicare hospitalized patients. The new Medicare rules have shrunk
these margins, forcing mergers, staff cutbacks and the decisions by
some universities to sell their money-losing hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   TOP LOBBYIST: Richard M. Knapp, 58, who has a PhD in hospital
and health administration from the University of Iowa, is the chief
lobbyist for the American Association of Medical Colleges, which
represents 400 major teaching hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   THEIR CASE: Advocates say more than 40 percent of the major
teaching hospitals in this country will be losing money by 2002.
Financial troubles are causing devastating cutbacks in medical
research and jeopardizing the education of the nation's future
doctors, they argue.
</P>
<P>
   THEIR GOAL: Teaching hospitals want to eliminate any further
cuts to the Indirect Medical Education and to the Disproportionate
Share Hospital payments.
</P>
<P>
   CHAMPIONS: Sens. Daniel Patrick Moynihan, D-N.Y., Edward M.
Kennedy, D-Mass., Dianne Feinstein, D-Calif., and Rep. Charles
Rangel, D-N.Y., the top Democrat on the key House Ways and Means
panel.
</P>
<P>
   (END)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-12-99 1005EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
