<DOCNO> NYT19991012.0065 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-12 10:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4109 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-ALBANY-HOSPITAL-$ADV1     10-12 0826
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALBANY-HOSPITAL-$ADV17-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEACHING HOSPITALS PROVIDE SPECIALIZED MEDICAL CARE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, Oct. 17)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SYLVIA WOOD  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Born at 23 weeks, Baby K. almost didn't make it
and her twin sister died. Too young to breathe on their own, such
preemies face an uphill struggle.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is right on the edge,'' said Dr. David Clark, the
director of the Children's Hospital at Albany Medical Center, where
Baby K. has spent the past 10 weeks in a full-service neonatal
intensive care unit, the only one of its kind in a 25-county region
of northeastern New York.
</P>
<P>
   These units, with access to sophisticated technology and
experienced medical staff, have helped improve the odds for
premature babies over the past decade. But such intensive medical
care comes with a cost. Albany Medical Center, like other teaching
hospitals, is struggling to pay for neonatal and other highly
specialized services as it grapples with federal budget cuts.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, Congress authorized higher Medicare payments for
teaching hospitals because of the costs they incur in training
graduate medical students, conducting research and operating
state-of-the-art technology. The Balanced Budget Act of 1997 cuts
those subsidies by between $2.9 billion and $7.1 billion for the
five-year period from 1998 to 2002.
</P>
<P>
   In the first two years of the act, Albany Medical Center lost
about $11 million in Medicare reimbursements. That figure is
expected to climb to $45 million by 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Albany Medical Center, which employs 6,409 full- and part-time
employees, has been able to operate in the black, despite the lost
revenue. Over the past three years, it has sought to save money by
leaving 165 positions unfilled, by implementing across-the-board
budget cuts and by consolidating administrative offices.
</P>
<P>
   The medical center, with its $445 million annual operating
budget, also has been looking at new sources of revenue, including
expanding its lucrative out-patient surgery department and by
seeking more federal research grants.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Albany Medical Center has seen its slim operating surplus
get even smaller over the past five years. Administrators are
increasingly nervous about how to save money without cutting into
the programs that have helped define the center's mission as a
place for research, quality medical education and advanced medical
care.
</P>
<P>
   ``If these budget cuts from the BBA continue, I don't know where
the money is going to come from,'' James J. Barba, president and
board chairman of the Albany Medical Center, said of the Balanced
Budget Act.
</P>
<P>
   Although the medical center has no plans to eliminate programs,
Barba has not ruled out that possibility.
</P>
<P>
   The prospect of reduced services at teaching hospitals has
prompted an outcry from some hospital and industry leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have no vision at all as a nation where we're going as a
health care system,'' said Daniel Sisto, president of the
Healthcare Association of New York.
</P>
<P>
   With studies showing that for every dollar spent on teaching
hospitals, the state gets a $3 return in research money and
economic development, Sisto believes the federal cuts are
misguided.
</P>
<P>
   Not only are government subsidies being trimmed but some private
insurance companies have gone bankrupt, leaving hospitals to foot
the bill for unpaid claims. Others are late making payments or
frequently dispute bills, adding to the financial uncertainty.
</P>
<P>
   ``The particular vulnerability of teaching hospitals is that
they have special missions that non-teaching hospitals don't have
... and for which the reimbursements that are now available are
simply becoming inadequate,'' said Dr. Jordan J. Cohen, president
of the Association of American Medical Colleges.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to the stress at Albany Medical Center is the growing
cost of caring for the uninsured.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the medical center provided about $18 million in free
care, up from $15 million five years ago. While all hospitals are
required to care for patients regardless of their ability to pay,
Albany Medical Center tends to get those uninsured patients who are
sickest and who have the largest bills.
</P>
<P>
   In New York alone, the number of uninsured has grown to 3.2
million people from 2.4 million in 1986. More than 700,000 of the
uninsured are children, including Baby K, who was born at Albany
Medical Center in early August.
</P>
<P>
   The financial problems presented by the federal budget act have
been compounded in New York by the state Health Care Reform Act of
1996. That law also eliminated some government reimbursement for
charity care, graduate medical education and bad debt.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've done everything asked of us ... yet the federal and
state governments are still saying cut more, cut more,'' Barba
said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Sylvia Wood can be reached at 518-454-5445 or by e-mail at
swood(at)timesunion.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
