<SLUG> BC-HOUSTON-HOSPITAL-$ADV17-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAYLOR'S TEACHING HOSPITALS FEAR CUTS IN THE NUMBER OF RESIDENTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, Oct. 17)   (For use by New York Times
 By CAROL CHRISTIAN  
 c.1999 Houston Chronicle   HOUSTON _ For the first time in recent
memory, The Methodist Hospital in Houston is losing money on its
day-to-day business operations. The 80-year-old institution is one
of the nation's largest private, nonprofit hospitals and the
primary adult teaching hospital for Houston's Baylor College of
Medicine. Last year, the hospital that serves as home base for
world-renowned heart surgeon Dr. Michael DeBakey netted $24 million
on its business operations. This year the hospital will end in the
red, due mainly to federal funding cutbacks imposed by the Balanced
Budget Act of 1997.
<TEXT>
<P>
   That law reduced Medicare reimbursements to all hospitals and
will cut Methodist's funding by a total of $127.3 million over five
years. By comparison, Methodist's annual Medicare reimbursement in
1997 was $190 million, according to Peter W. Butler, president and
chief executive officer of Methodist Health Care System, which
includes The Methodist Hospital. For 2002, the hospital can expect
$178 million from Medicare _ $36.5 million less than it was slated
to receive under previous legislation, Butler said. ``Hospitals are
facing financial pressures for a variety of reasons, but the
most-often cited reason, as is the case with Methodist, is federal
funding cutbacks of the Balanced Budget Act,'' Butler said. In the
past, Congress authorized higher Medicare payments for teaching
hospitals because of the costs they incur in training graduate
medical students, conducting research and operating
state-of-the-art technology. The Balanced Budget Act cuts those
subsidies by between $2.9 billion and $7.1 billion for the
five-year period from 1998 to 2002.
</P>
<P>
   So far the cutbacks have not affected patient care at Methodist,
Butler said. For Methodist and other teaching hospitals, the cuts
could mean fewer medical residents accepted for training, a move
that could affect not only patient care in the short term, but
health care on the whole for years to come, hospital administrators
said. Dr. Ralph D. Feigin, president of Baylor College of Medicine,
said the reduction in medical residents accepted for training could
begin as early as 2000. Baylor has about 950 residents, most of
whom are allocated among Methodist and six other Baylor primary
affiliated teaching hospitals. Some residents, such as those in
orthopedic and plastic surgery, rotate among all seven.
</P>
<P>
   Feigin said hospital administrators are particularly concerned
about funding for training residents in primary care areas other
than family practice and internal medicine. This includes
obstetrics/gynecology and pediatrics. Feigin said the refrain has
been the same: ``We don't know if we're going to have the money to
be able to train specialists.'' For now, Methodist's income from
investments is offsetting the current federal cutbacks, but
long-term losses are on the horizon, Butler said. Butler came to
Methodist in 1997 from Detroit's Henry Ford Health System; before
that, he worked at Rush-Presbyterian-St. Luke's Medical Center in
Chicago. ``I've been in the business now 25 years, and I've never
seen anything like this in terms of the financial challenge,''
Butler said of the fiscal squeeze on teaching hospitals. Of the
$127.3 million that Methodist is losing, $30 million represents
cuts in federal reimbursements for the hospital's medical
education. ``It's not like non-teaching hospitals are getting off
the hook,'' Butler said. ``It's just that there's an added burden
on teaching hospitals.'' As a teaching hospital, Methodist has
about 200 residents _ doctors who have completed medical school but
are still in training. Texas requires physicians to do at least one
year of residency before they can be licensed. Most doctors also
pursue ``board certification'' in a speciality indicating they have
been trained to the highest standards in that field. Training for
the certification exams can add up to seven years to a physician's
academic career. It is more expensive for hospitals to train
specialists than primary-care physicians, not just because it takes
longer, but also because more types of faculty members are needed.
For example, training a cardiovascular surgeon might involve 10
subspecialties such as interventional catheterization, regular
catheterization, echocardiology, exercise physiology, and others.
Methodist has no plans now for reducing the number of residents or
reducing residents' salaries, Butler said. The average salary for
first-year medical residents at Houston hospitals is $34,000, which
equals the national median _ half are lower and half are higher,
Feigin said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you cut people's salaries here, you wouldn't attract
residents,'' he said. ``You wouldn't have to worry about cutting
slots; the whole program would dry up.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;
</P>
<P>
   (Carol Christian can be reached at 713-220-7491 and by e-mail at
carol(at)christian.com)
</P>
