<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAN-FRANCISCO-HOSPITALS-$ADV17-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAY AREA TEACHING HOSPITALS FIND THEIR MERGER IS A ROCKY ONE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, Oct. 17)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ULYSSES TORASSA  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Concerned about looming Medicare cuts and
intense local competition, the University of California at San
Francisco and Stanford University decided two years ago to merge
their four hospitals into a private, non-profit corporation.
</P>
<P>
   Their idea was that the Bay Area's two major academic medical
centers could compete in the marketplace and cut costs better
together, even though they are 30 miles apart. The marriage has
been rocky, however, and the joint venture named UCSF Stanford
Health Care lost $73 million in the just-ended fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
   Some 2,000 jobs are being cut, a hospital is closing, and
fingers are being pointed in many directions.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the blame is being assigned to the Balanced Budget Act
of 1997, which lowered Medicare formulas that once rewarded
teaching hospitals for the extra costs of training doctors and
treating complex cases. The Balanced Budget Act cuts those
subsidies by between $2.9 billion and $7.1 billion for the
five-year period from 1998 to 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Medicare makes up $390 million _ or 26 percent _ of revenue at
UCSF Stanford. This year, the hospital system will lose $28 million
in Medicare revenue, with the cuts slated to increase each year
until 2002. At that point, the system will be down $46 million
compared to what it would have received under the old formula.
</P>
<P>
   All told, the system with a annual budget of $1.5 billion,
expects to lose $169 million over a five-year period from the
formula changes.
</P>
<P>
   Medicare cuts aren't solely that cause of turmoil at UCSF
Stanford Health Care. Mismanagement, overspending, frozen Medicaid
payments, and an extremely competitive managed care environment
have also hurt the 2-year-old merger.
</P>
<P>
   Besides job cuts, the losses have led UCSF Stanford officials to
close the emergency room and all in-patient services at one of its
four hospitals, UCSF/Mount Zion Medical Center in San Francisco. It
has the highest proportion of Medicare patients of any of the
system's hospitals, and was blamed for the majority of its losses.
</P>
<P>
   The closure, set for the end of this year, only added fuel to
the controversy swirling around the troubled merger. Both partners
are re-thinking the marriage and may take steps to separate some or
all of their functions.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the University of California, which owns half of
the system, believe the cuts in Medicare have played a large role.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a movement nationally to undermine and destroy the
strong medical enterprise this country has built up,'' UC President
Richard Atkinson told UC Regents recently in discussing the
merger's problems.
</P>
<P>
   In that same meeting, UCSF Chancellor Michael Bishop said the
federal budget has been balanced on the backs of academic health
centers, and extensive restructuring and downsizing are inevitable.
The hospitals may even fail, he said, a prospect he finds
``intolerable.''
</P>
<P>
   Philip Lee, former UCSF chancellor and a former assistant
secretary of health, said the big problem is the environment in
which the hospital system operates.
</P>
<P>
   In California, academic medical centers are hurting badly in a
medical economy where a cutthroat managed care system has pushed
monthly premiums per member paid to hospitals for private insurance
to under $90 per month.
</P>
<P>
   But in Wisconsin, where the average monthly payment is $115,
teaching hospitals have been able to absorb the Medicare cuts
without tremendous strain.
</P>
<P>
   ``The impacts are felt in an area that's competitive with a lot
of managed care,'' Lee said. ``When you've got that, you're in
trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   Another fear is that the cuts will hurt the medical training
that goes on in the hospitals. UCSF trains about 950 residents each
year at the UCSF Stanford hospitals. At Stanford's medical school,
about 350 residents are trained at the hospital system.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Uylsses Torassa can be reached at 415-777-2424.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
