<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-12 10:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4114 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-SEATTLE-HOSPITALS-$AD     10-12 0914
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEATTLE-HOSPITALS-$ADV17-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEATTLE-AREA TEACHING HOSPITALS SAY THEY ARE ALREADY LEAN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, Oct. 17)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TOM PAULSON  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ At Harborview Medical Center, the Balanced Budget Act
of 1997 looks like the AIDS virus _ a slow-acting, unseen agent
that will eventually erode the teaching hospital's ability to
rebound from even the smallest wound or challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will absolutely devastate Harborview and other such
hospitals over the next decade,'' said David Jaffe, executive
director of Harborview, the Pacific Northwest's regional trauma
center. ``There is no way for us to adjust to these cuts in
Medicare and remain viable for long.''
</P>
<P>
   In the past, Congress authorized higher Medicare payments for
teaching hospitals because of the costs they incur in training
graduate medical students, conducting research and operating
state-of-the-art technology. The Balanced Budget Act cuts those
subsidies by between $2.9 billion and $7.1 billion for the
five-year period from 1998 to 2002.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're already operating at a very lean level,'' said Robert
Muilenberg, executive director of the University of Washington
Medical Center, who said the hospital's margin right now is about
3.1 percent and expected to decline to near zero by the new year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any kind of a cut here gets more quickly into the muscle and
bone,'' Muilenberg said.
</P>
<P>
   The UW Medical Center and Harborview, a teaching hospital for
the UW, expect to be harder hit by the cuts because of the
additional costs of medical education, research and caring for more
of the uninsured.
</P>
<P>
   As an example of how the UW already gets disproportionately
squeezed by federal payment schedules, Dr. John Coombs, vice
president for medical affairs, pointed to reimbursement for medical
residents.
</P>
<P>
   The state of New York receives about $194,000 per medical
resident per year, Coombs said, while the UW receives only $44,000
per resident per year from Medicare's Graduate Medical Education
fund.
</P>
<P>
   New York's reimbursement rate was arrived at years ago, largely
based on hospitals' existing expenses, Coombs said, which has had
the unintended effect of rewarding those hospitals that operate
most inefficiently.
</P>
<P>
   That formula doesn't even come close to reflecting today's
costs, Coombs said, and these new across-the-board reductions in
payments mean the UW will experience nearly a 30 percent cut in
Medicare payments for graduate medical education over the next five
years _ a reduction of $38 million, from $131 million to $93
million.
</P>
<P>
   Leo Greenawalt, president of the state hospital association,
says the cuts have much more of an effect in actual dollars in the
Northwest than it does on the eastern seaboard because this region
already has an efficient, low-cost system that avoids duplication
of services.
</P>
<P>
   ``In New York City, they have too many hospital beds and
actually could do with one or two fewer hospitals,'' Greenawalt
said.
</P>
<P>
   Hospital administrators everywhere are predicting doom and
destruction from the cuts in Medicare reimbursements. That's
particularly true in the case of teaching hospitals. They are
asking Congress to freeze cuts in Medicare, rather than continuing
to phase them in, as the act now requires.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone agrees with the case made by the teaching
hospitals. The skeptics include Richard Keck, vice president for
business development at Swedish Hospital Medical Center in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every hospital's going to get hit by this,'' Keck said. ``In
fact, I'd say the bigger impact is going to be on smaller and rural
hospitals because of their smaller operating margin.''
</P>
<P>
   Institutions like the UW Medical Center and Harborview already
receive higher reimbursements, such as through Medicaid and
additional sources of government funding such as research grants
and contracts that aren't available to private hospitals like
Swedish, Keck said. And the UW competes directly in the health care
marketplace with Swedish, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The medical research and education mission of the University
of Washington is a crown jewel for this region and it deserves our
support,'' Keck said. ``But their hospital is just another hospital
... and we should all have to play by the same rules.''
</P>
<P>
   He contends that medical schools don't necessarily have to
operate their own hospitals to continue to do medical education and
research. The University of Minnesota, Keck noted, recently got out
of the hospital business and instead trains doctors in
collaboration with other area hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   Coombs said the notion that the UW hospital should be viewed as
``just another hospital'' in a competitive marketplace fails to
take into account the fact that the hospital is integral to the
UW's research and teaching missions.
</P>
<P>
   And Jaffe said there's no debate that Harborview will be hurt by
the Balanced Budget Act, Jaffe said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Harborview's bottom line is essentially break-even right
now,'' Jaffe said. With the coming cuts in Medicare, he said,
Harborview will bleed nearly $20 million over five years.
</P>
<P>
   ``With these cuts, the very foundation of our system is
threatened,'' Jaffe said. By the time the public notices the true
cost of cutting Medicare, he lamented, it will be too late.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could take decades to recover,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Tom Paulson can be reached at 206-448-8318 or
tompaulson(at)seattle-pi.com)
</P>
