<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-12 10:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4116 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-MEDICARE-BIAGGI-$ADV1     10-12 0773
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDICARE-BIAGGI-$ADV17-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER LAWMAKER COMPLAINS CONGRESS CUT FUNDS FOR CARE HE NEEDS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, Oct. 17)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JUDY HOLLAND  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRONX, N.Y. _ Mario Biaggi, a former New York
cop-turned-congressman who fought for the elderly during his 20
years on Capitol Hill, says he now knows first-hand about holes in
the nation's safety net for the aged.
</P>
<P>
   At 81, Biaggi, a widower, suffered a broken hip last May and has
difficulty walking because of multiple bullet wounds he received
during his 23-year-career on the police force. He also suffers from
an irregular heart beat.
</P>
<P>
   He trembles as he stands with both hands on his metal walker and
complains that he can't pull on his own stockings. He depends on
others, such as the concierge of his building, a home health aide
or a friend, to button his shirt.
</P>
<P>
   Biaggi has received hundreds of hours of physical and
occupational therapy, nursing care and help from home health aides
since his health started slipping in February.
</P>
<P>
   But Montefiore Medical Center, a Bronx teaching hospital that
provides those services, says Biaggi could lose them because of
Medicare cutbacks.
</P>
<P>
   When Congress sliced Medicare by $112 billion in 1997 as part of
a plan to balance the federal budget, it put new limits on the
services that home health agencies can offer. Biaggi has already
busted the $4,900 average annual limit that Montefiore can spend on
patients under the new Medicare limits.
</P>
<P>
   So far this year, Montefiore has spent more than $18,500 on
Biaggi's home health care and has had to balance that cost against
expenses for other patients with fewer health problems, says Susan
Schulmerich, the program's executive director at the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't have too many Biaggis,'' she says. ``If you have too
many Biaggis, you get killed. There's going to come a point where
we're going to have to discharge him (from the home care program)
and he won't have anyone to exercise him,'' Schulmerich says.
Without such help, she adds, he could ``lose his muscle strength''
and become ``dangerous to himself, and the likelihood of him
falling again (would be) very high.''
</P>
<P>
   Biaggi is one of an estimated million elderly and disabled
people who are facing curtailed therapy or nursing services in
their homes because of Medicare cuts.
</P>
<P>
   Biaggi says he has lobbied his former Capitol Hill colleague,
Rep. Charles B. Rangel of New York, the top Democrat on the House
Ways and Means Committee, to restore funding for home health
care.``I say, `Charlie, do it for me,''' Biaggi says.
</P>
<P>
   Congress and the Clinton administration are scrapping over
federal spending for the 2000 fiscal year that began Oct. 1.
Lobbyists for teaching hospitals, nursing homes, home health
agencies and physical therapy groups are vying for a share of
restored Medicare spending now being considered by Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Biaggi sees it as ``ironic'' that he championed causes of the
elderly during his congressional career but now fears a future
without adequate care in his old age.
</P>
<P>
   He recalls the 1970s and '80s when he joined the late Rep.
Claude Pepper, D-Fla., in investigating abuses in nursing homes.
</P>
<P>
   Now he fears he may end up in one.
</P>
<P>
   Living alone in a modest apartment in the upscale Riverdale
section of the Bronx, Biaggi says his income consists of Social
Security and pensions from his 23 years in the New York Police
Department and 20 years in the House of Representatives.
</P>
<P>
   He says he can't afford to pay the $152 that a physical
therapist charges for each home visit or the $52 a day that a home
health aide would cost to help bathe and dress him and prepare his
food.
</P>
<P>
   Biaggi resigned from Congress in 1988 after he was found guilty
of illegally receiving $1.8 million in stock and cash from Wedtech
Corp., a South Bronx tool and die shop, for which he had sought
government contracts. He was sentenced to eight years in jail but
was released after 26 months because of a worsening heart condition
and nerve damage in his legs.
</P>
<P>
   He was also convicted of accepting an illegal vacation from
Meade H. Esposito, the former Brooklyn Democratic leader, in
exchange for seeking to arrange government contracts for a client
of Esposito's insurance firm. Biaggi drew a two-and-a-half year
sentence in that case.
</P>
<P>
   He insists he was innocent in both cases and says fines and
legal expenses zapped his finances. Speaking of his fear that he
might someday forced to move to a nursing home, he says it would
``damage the psyche,'' and cause him to lose ``my zest for life.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
