<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-12 10:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4137 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-FLA-CHAIRORIGIN13-COX     10-12 1020
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLA-CHAIRORIGIN13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Electric titans clashed over electrocution
 &HT;    By Michael Browning
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ We owe the electric chair, Florida's
most shocking piece of furniture for the past 75 years, to an
elderly New York drunk who happened to touch the terminals of an
electrical generator in Buffalo on Aug. 8, 1881.
</P>
<P>
   The old toper died instantly. Purely by chance, his lightning
demise was witnessed by Dr. Albert Southwick, a dentist and former
steamboat engineer. Southwick was so struck by the lightning
swiftness and apparent painlessness of the death that he described
the episode to a friend, New York state Sen. David McMillan.
McMillan had the ear of Gov. David B. Hill, who asked the New York
Legislature to consider how the new force of electricity might
replace hanging as a method of capital punishment.
</P>
<P>
   On June 4, 1888, the legislature passed a law establishing
electrocution as the state's method of execution. The law directed
the state Medico-Legal Board to look into the best way of
implementing the new method of execution.
</P>
<P>
   A macabre economic feud between two prominent inventors, Thomas
Alva Edison and George Westinghouse, played an important role in
developing the electric chair. James E. Penrose traces the
controversy in his ``Inventing Electrocution,'' a 1994 article in
the journal, ``American Heritage of Invention and Technology.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither Edison nor Westinghouse was interested in humane capital
punishment. Instead, both fought to have their preferred type of
current adopted as the national standard for electricity. Millions
of dollars were at stake.
</P>
<P>
   Edison favored direct current (DC) as an energy source.
Westinghouse believed alternating current (AC) was cheaper, more
efficient and did not require the thick copper wiring DC current
needed for conduction. Because copper was so expensive in the late
19th century, Edison decided to attack Westinghouse on another
front: He would prove AC current was dangerous, even lethal.
</P>
<P>
   In 1887, Edison set out to discredit AC current by inviting
reporters to a public demonstration at his laboratory in West
Orange, N.J., during which he lured a number of dogs and cats onto
a metal plate wired to a 1,000-volt AC generator. The animals were
electrocuted, and the press gave the grisly demonstration extensive
coverage.
</P>
<P>
   So: AC or DC? The board appointed by the New York legislature
turned to a couple of Columbia University scientists for a
solution.
</P>
<P>
   On July 30, 1888, Dr. Harold Brown and his assistant, Dr. Fred
Peterson, administered a series of DC shocks to a large
Newfoundland mix dog. The voltage was gradually increased to 1,000
volts, and the dog remained alive, though clearly in great pain.
Then Brown administered a coup de grace with a jolt of just 330
volts of AC current.
</P>
<P>
   On Dec. 5, 1888, Brown and Peterson electrocuted two calves and
a 1,230-pound horse. The New York Times' account of the experiment
ends with the observation that ``alternating current will
undoubtedly drive the hangmen out of business in this state.''
</P>
<P>
   On Dec. 12, Brown and Peterson submitted their report to the New
York board. They urged electrocution be carried out with the victim
sitting in a chair, rather than floating in a tank of water or
strapped to a rubberized table. It is a macabre might-have-been:
The thought that we might be discussing ``the electric tank'' or
``the electric table'' today, instead of the electric chair.
</P>
<P>
   The two experimentalists also recommended using AC current.
</P>
<P>
   Furious at the bad publicity, inventor Westinghouse wrote a
letter published in The New York Times Dec. 13, 1888, accusing
Brown of acting ``in the interest and pay of the Edison Electric
Light Company.''
</P>
<P>
   But it was too late. In March 1889, Brown met with Austin
Lathrop, superintendent of New York prisons, to arrange for
purchase of Westinghouse AC generators to power the electric chair.
Because Westinghouse refused to sell directly to the prisons, the
state resorted to subterfuge to acquire three generators for about
$8,000.
</P>
<P>
   The first man to be electrocuted was William Kemmler, who, on
March 29, 1889, killed his lover, Matilda ``Tillie'' Ziegler, with
an ax in Buffalo. Ironically, Buffalo was then known as the
``Electric City of the Future.'' Kemmler was sentenced to death two
months later.
</P>
<P>
   Inventor Westinghouse was so desperate to avoid having his AC
current associated with death that he paid for legal appeals for
Kemmler on the grounds that electrocution was cruel and unusual
punishment, a debate that continues in Florida to this day. Edison
and Brown both testified that it was painless and humane. Kemmler
lost two appeals.
</P>
<P>
   The first electric chair was designed in 1890 by Edwin R. Davis,
an Auburn Prison electrician. It closely resembles the modern
version. Davis tested it with large slabs of meat.
</P>
<P>
   On Aug. 6, 1890, Kemmler was electrocuted in the chair at Auburn
Prison. The first jolt did not kill him. A second was administered,
and he was pronounced dead.
</P>
<P>
   ``The man never suffered a bit of pain,'' said executioner's
assistant George Fell.
</P>
<P>
   ``Strong men fainted and fell like logs on the floor,'' wrote a
reporter for the New York Herald.
</P>
<P>
   ``They would have done better with an ax,'' fumed George
Westinghouse.
</P>
<P>
   But electrocution was the wave of the future. In 1896, Ohio
introduced electrocution, and in 1898, Massachusetts followed suit.
New Jersey was 1906, Virginia in 1908 and North Carolina in 1910.
Soon thereafter, at least 20 states were using electric chairs,
making it by far the most popular means of execution. At Sing Sing
alone, 614 men were electrocuted before New York abolished the
death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   Today, only four states still use the chair: Florida, Georgia,
Alabama and Nebraska. More and more states have switched to lethal
injection, among them Kentucky and Tennessee within the past year.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Browning writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm
Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
