<DOCNO> NYT19991012.0073 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-12 10:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4138 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-FLA-CHAIRSHOCK13-COX     10-12 0981
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLA-CHAIRSHOCK13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A high-voltage discussion: How the chair kills
 &HT;    By Michael Browning
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Though the electric chair is designed to
kill, not injure, the same processes are at work whenever anyone
gets an electric shock, be it lethal or non-lethal.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond causing tremendous cell and nerve damage, electric shocks
scar and change the brain in ways doctors still don't understand.
Survivors lose short-term memory, forget multiplication tables,
suffer pain for years afterward. Often the post-shock symptoms, or
sequelae, take months to manifest themselves.
</P>
<P>
   When executed criminals are taken to the District 8 Medical
Examiner's Office in Gainesville and autopsied, they show two
distinctive postmortem traits. First, there is a burn on the calf
of the leg where the ground plate of the electric chair made
contact. Second, when the skull is sawed open and the top is popped
off with a tool known as the Virchow skull-breaker _ it looks like
a large key _ there is a pudding-like mass of coagulated blood atop
the brain.
</P>
<P>
   One of the foremost experts on electricity's effects on the
human body is Dr. Raphael Lee of the University of Chicago. Lee,
who was awarded a MacArthur ``genius'' grant and used it to acquire
a Ph.D. in electrical engineering on top of his medical degree,
spoke at a special conference given at Tampa General Hospital in
1996.
</P>
<P>
   The power of man-made electricity can be far more devastating
than natural lightning, Lee explained, because the contact lasts
longer. Power lines carry an average of 7,000 to 10,000 volts.
</P>
<P>
   The electric chair, by contrast, only applies 2,000 volts to its
occupant. Volts measure the potential force of an electric charge
from source to ground _ a bucket of water poured off a cliff will
have more force than a bucket of water tipped over on level ground.
Amperes, or amps, measure actual electrical current and are
dependent on the size of the voltage, and the length and
connectivity of the wires and switches through which the current
passes.
</P>
<P>
   A small vacuum cleaner's motor may only use 3 amps of
electricity. A large, heavy, janitorial vacuum cleaner may use 9 to
11 amps.
</P>
<P>
   Males begin to feel electric shocks at 1 milliamp, Lee explains.
Females sense current at half a milliamp. Why? It is not that women
are more sensitive, it is that their fingertips tend to be smaller,
and the charge is thus concentrated in a smaller area.
</P>
<P>
   ``At 16 milliamps, the muscles of the forearm go into spasm.
This is the `no-let-go threshold,''' Lee said. It happens because
flexor muscles in the hand are so much stronger than extensor
muscles. Both are paralyzed, but the inertia of the more powerful
flexor muscles overrules the weaker extensors, so the hand grips
the source of the electricity in a helpless, clamped claw.
</P>
<P>
   If the charge is 60 milliamps or more, there is enough
electricity to cause a lethal arrhythmia in the heart, Lee said.
</P>
<P>
   ``At 1.5 milliamps, you see direct destructive effect on the
submembranes of the muscles and nerves,'' Lee continued. The human
body encased in skin has a resistance equal to 750-1,000 Ohms, from
hand tip to foot tip, the doctor said. But, said Lee, once the skin
is burned through, ``the body basically acts like a bag of saline
solution.'' It is an extremely good conductor.
</P>
<P>
   The epidermis is 200 microns thick. Anything over 200 volts
breaks through the epidermis and opens a window in the skin. The
skin is burnt away in a millisecond.
</P>
<P>
   ``At 10 amps, which is the level in most electrical accidents,
you get injuries to the skin, skeletal muscles, nerves and
endothelial cells of blood vessels.''
</P>
<P>
   The protocol for execution in Florida's electric chair calls for
three bursts of electricity. The electrocution cycle is two minutes
or shorter in duration. In the last five executions, an average of
about 2,000 volts and 9 to 10 amps were administered in the first
burst of electricity, lasting eight seconds. The second jolt is 4
amps and 650 volts, delivered for 22 seconds, and the third 10 amps
and 1,500 volts for four seconds.
</P>
<P>
   District 8 Medical Examiner William Hamilton, who has performed
autopsies on 30 executed men, including serial killer Ted Bundy,
testified in writing before the Florida Supreme Court during this
summer's inquiry into whether the electric chair constituted cruel
and unusual punishment, as Death Row inmate Thomas Provenzano
argued.
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton's opinion, summarized in the court's decision: ``The
delivery of 10 amps to the human body with the path of the current
being from the head to the leg results in immediate death,
immediate loss of consciousness, immediate massive depolarization
of the nervous system, and a rapid rise in the temperature of the
internal tissues in the path of the current ...
</P>
<P>
   ``The path of current would be from the top of the head through
the brain and brain stem, through the center of the body, and then
exiting through the electrode on the leg.'' Hamilton testified that
immediate death would also result if the current were only 4 amps.
</P>
<P>
   Electroshock therapy may offer a clue whether the electric chair
causes pain, said another expert, Dr. B.J. Wilder, professor
emeritus at the University of Florida in neurology and
neuroscience.
</P>
<P>
   Wilder testified that during electroconvulsive (electroshock)
therapy, in which the brain is stimulated with electricity to
produce a controlled convulsion, 250 to 300 milliamps, or 250/1000
to 300/1000 of 1 amp, is used. Wilder testified that electrical
currents of this level cause the patient to lose consciousness, and
that upon regaining consciousness, the patient does not report any
pain.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Browning writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm
Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
