r a BC-FLA-ELECTRICCHAIR13-C     10-12 1892
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLA-ELECTRICCHAIR13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Florida Supreme Court rules 'Old Sparky' chair is not a torture
device
 &HT;    By Michael Browning
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ For three quarters of a century now,
doomed prisoners have sat down in a certain oaken chair, in a
certain room at the Florida State Prison outside Starke, never to
rise of their own volition again. Thursday marked the silver
anniversary of the electric chair in Florida, a form of execution
that spits sparks in our minds and consciences.
</P>
<P>
   Flames, smoke, gasps, groans and sudden effusions of blood have
all accompanied the grim proceedings in the chair, known as ``Old
Sparky'' to inmates and free citizens alike. The 1923 chair,
hand-carved by inmates, was retired in May. But its circuitry,
including the console and the three original hand-thrown
knife-switches, has been moved to the successor-chair and is still
used after all these years.
</P>
<P>
   How did we get here?
</P>
<P>
   Prior to 1923, executions in Florida were performed locally,
usually by hanging, within the various counties where the condemned
had committed their crimes and been sentenced to death.
</P>
<P>
   Between 1848 and 1922, there were 223 legal hangings in Florida
_ including a slave named Celia, who was hanged in Duval County on
Sept. 22, 1848, for the stabbing death of her master, Jacob Bryan.
Perhaps the last local hanging in Florida was held on Feb. 24,
1922, in Alachua County.
</P>
<P>
   In 1923, the Florida Legislature changed the method of execution
to electrocution, which New York had been using since 1890. Inmates
at the Florida State Prison carved the heavy, three-legged chair
from oak. The very next year, at 2:48 p.m. on Oct. 7, 1924, Frank
Johnson of Duval County became the first man to die in it. Johnson
was executed for the December 1923 murder of Atley B. Terrell, a
locomotive engineer, during a train robbery.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Florida has executed 240 people by electrocution.
The state has conducted nine triple executions, three quadruple
executions and 21 double electrocutions. On March 23, 1942, four
men were executed in just 53 minutes, according to Death Row
records. At the time, Prison Superintendent L.F. Chapman called the
rapid-fire executions ``terrible but necessary.''
</P>
<P>
   The last double execution was on the morning of May 12, 1964,
when Die Dawson of Gadsden County and Emmett C. Blake of Bay County
were executed 28 minutes apart.
</P>
<P>
   An electrocution is an unspectacular event, says retired
corrections officer Lt. E.E. Griffis of Raiford, a 38-year veteran
of the prison system. Griffis has attended several executions. His
son, John, another corrections officer, shaved serial killer Ted
Bundy's leg so it would make cleaner contact with the base plate of
the electric chair when Bundy was executed on Jan. 24, 1989.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not much to it,'' the elder Griffis said. ``Their
chest swells up, and they lunge up against the straps. And their
fists ball up and slobber comes out of their mouths and their leg
swells under the ground plate. After a while, I quit going. They
all looked the same.''
</P>
<P>
   Lately, however, several ghastly executions have called the
electric chair into question again. In 1990, Jessie Tafero's head
caught fire when a cellulose sponge was used to improve the contact
between the electrode and his scalp, instead of a sea sponge. In
1997, a foot-high tongue of fire erupted from Pedro Medina's head,
and earlier this year Allen Lee Davis was heard to gasp and moan
during his execution, the first in the state's new oaken chair.
Davis, who weighed over 300 pounds, also suffered a nosebleed that
may have begun before the knife-switch was thrown.
</P>
<P>
   But after hearing expert testimony from both sides, the Florida
Supreme Court ruled Sept. 24 that the chair was not a torture
device and did not violate the stricture against ``cruel and
unusual punishment.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Execution inherently involves fear, and it may involve some
degree of pain. That pain may include pain associated with affixing
straps around the head and body to secure the head and body to the
electric chair. However, any pain associated therewith is necessary
to ensure that the integrity of the execution process is
maintained.''
</P>
<P>
   The high court's conclusion: ``Execution by electrocution in
Florida's electric chair as it exists in its present condition as
applied does not constitute cruel or unusual punishment, and
therefore, is not unconstitutional.''
</P>
<P>
   The original ``Old Sparky'' is hidden away today in a storage
room at the Florida State Prison at Starke, according to Department
of Corrections communications director C.J. Drake. When the chair
was retired, corrections officials received two offers to acquire
it for display: one from Tallahassee entrepreneur Devoe Williams
and the second from the Bradford County Historical Museum in
Starke. Both were declined, on the advice of the Museum of Florida
History.
</P>
<P>
   ``The electric chair, which was used in Florida through much of
this century, is unquestionably of historical significance to the
state. This execution device has been the center of some of the
most publicized debates over the death penalty in the last 30
years, including the execution of such well-known felons as
Theodore Bundy. Its historical significance is not only to the
state of Florida, but since capital punishment is a widely debated
issue, exists on a national level as well. While the need to
preserve this object is clear, its exhibition on the other hand is
controversial. At the present time, the exhibition of Florida's
electric chair may not be appropriate,'' wrote William Pfeiffer,
assistant secretary of state.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a piece of furniture,'' Drake said. ``The electrical
apparatus associated with it, the console and switches and so on,
have been installed on the new chair. All that is left is an old
oak chair in storage.''
</P>
<P>
   Old Sparky was, in fact, falling apart. Engineers reported that
the chair's seat and left rear leg were cracked and that its left
arm was ``weak and very loose,'' and likely to snap off. One screw
was missing. ``We can conclude that it will fail in the near
future,'' the state's consultants reported.
</P>
<P>
   It was replaced in the dead of night last May by a new, sturdier
chair, also made of oak. This chair was fashioned by guards, not
inmates, at the Florida State Prison shop. The new chair has the
same veneer as its predecessor, though its two back legs are
slightly angled toward the rear.
</P>
<P>
   SIDEBAR: Last words, last meals and the bizarre handiwork of
`The Fry Guy'
</P>
<P>
   Though final meals for the condemned are supposed to cost no
more than $20, the rules are sometimes stretched. Michael Alan
Durocher, executed in 1993, requested five pounds of jumbo shrimp
for his final repast _ and got them, even though they cost $40. In
the shadow of the chair, most inmates usually ask for steak,
sometimes for steak and lobster. Those scheduled to be executed in
the morning get a standard breakfast of steak and eggs too, but the
steak is always cut up beforehand, as knives and forks are not
allowed.
</P>
<P>
   _ When Florida resumed executions on May 25, 1979, John
Spenkelink was the chair's first guest. Spenkelink is alleged to
have quipped: ``Capital punishment: Them without the capital get
the punishment.'' On the morning of his death, a popular disc
jockey on WAPE in Jacksonville known as ``The Greaseman'' played
the sound of frying bacon and dedicated it to Spenkelink.
</P>
<P>
   _ Among murderer Ted Bundy's personal effects, gathered up after
his execution on Jan. 24, 1989, was a bottle of suntan lotion, the
kind that works without sunlight. Prison officials theorized that
Bundy, who escaped from prison in Colorado before making his way to
Florida, was hoping against hope to escape from Death Row and
camouflage his prison pallor. Bundy refused his steak-and-egg
breakfast.
</P>
<P>
   _ Gerald Stano, 46, was electrocuted on March 23, 1998. A serial
killer who preyed on prostitutes, runaways and teenaged girls,
Stano wolfed down a Delmonico steak, baked potato with sour cream
and bacon bits, French bread, salad with bleu cheese dressing, a
half gallon of mint chocolate chip ice cream, and two liters of Dr.
Pepper. His last words: ``Know that I love you all and cherish your
love. Thanks for staying with me when people ridiculed you. I am
innocent.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Florida is third in the nation in the number of executions
since 1976. Texas leads with 189. Virginia is second with 70, and
Florida has executed 44 people since capital punishment was
reinstated.
</P>
<P>
   _ A tongue of fire a foot high spurted from Pedro Medina's head
when he was executed on March 25, 1997. Medina had been convicted
of stabbing an elderly woman who helped him. Florida's Attorney
General Bob Butterworth, responding to the botched execution,
commented: ``People who wish to commit murder, they better not do
it in the state of Florida, because we may have a problem with the
electric chair.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Of the 53 jurisdictions in the United States _ the 50 states,
the District of Columbia, the federal court system and the military
_ all but 13 have the death penalty. Besides the District of
Columbia, these states have abolished capital punishment: Maine,
Vermont, Rhode Island, Massachusetts, West Virginia, Iowa, North
Dakota, Minnesota, Wisconsin, Michigan, Alaska and Hawaii.
</P>
<P>
   _ Giuseppe Zangara, prisoner No. 24996, was executed on March
30, 1933, and is buried in the potter's field behind Union
Correctional Institution. His metal name-plate is misspelled
``Zangana.'' Zangara was an unemployed bricklayer who almost
changed world history when he tried to assassinate President-elect
Franklin D. Roosevelt in Miami on Feb. 15, 1933. He missed, thanks
to an alert woman in the crowd who jostled his arm at the last
second. The shot killed Chicago Mayor Anton Cermak instead. Zangara
was tried, convicted and executed in just over five weeks. His last
words: ``Push-a da button.''
</P>
<P>
   _ A woodworker calling himself ``The Fry Guy,'' from Newell,
N.C., is offering full-sized replicas of Florida's electric chair
at a Web site located at
http://www.wbworks.com/olesparky/chair.html. Each chair costs $995
plus $45 shipping and handling. Allow 4-6 weeks for delivery. Each
chair is equipped with a vibrating buzzer to simulate the delivery
of a real electric charge.
</P>
<P>
   _ 241 people have been executed in Florida's electric chair
since 1924, all but one of them men. As of March 1, 1999, there
were 390 people on Death Row in Florida, four of them women, six of
them juveniles who committed capital crimes and were tried and
sentenced as adults. Some 138 Death Row inmates are black, 213 are
white and 39 are classified as ``other.'' Women on Death Row are
housed in a state prison in Pembroke Pines. Men are housed in Union
Correctional Institution and the Florida State Prison at Starke.
</P>
<P>
   _ Oldest inmate executed: Charlie Grifford, 72, executed on Feb.
21, 1951.
</P>
<P>
   _ Youngest inmates executed (both 16 years old): Willie Clay,
sentenced from Duval County, executed Dec. 29, 1941, and James
Davis, sentenced from Alachua County, executed Oct. 9, 1944.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Browning writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm
Beach, Fla. E-mail: michaelbrowning(AT)pbpost.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
