<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Healthy kids owe this doc a huge debt
 &HT;    By Emily J. Minor
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Dr. David Martin was a man who cared
about kids, a man who fought for public health, a man who tried to
mask his compassion for the underdog with a tough exterior. But it
only partially hid his tender heart. Cathy Cohn first met him in
the 1980s when Dr. Martin started Healthy Mothers/Healthy Babies
Coalition, the organization Cohn is now head of.
</P>
<P>
   Cohn had always admired him. How could you not? She loved this
man's great mind, his vision, his ability to spot a social problem
and nail it right then and there. She'd even been privvy to his
wonderful twinkling smile a time or two.
</P>
<P>
   But when she read his obituary in the newspaper this week, it
got to her in a way she'd never expected.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm telling you, it has inspired me so much. I'm going to
carry it around with me. You talk about people wanting to make
their mark on this Earth. This was a man who did it.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. David Martin was 85 years old when he died at Hospice
Monday. He was frail. He was sick. But at his memorial service
Wednesday night, no one talked about that. They talked about a man
who went to Duke University on a tennis scholarship in 1931, then
turned it down two years later so he could study medicine under the
man who founded the prestigious Duke Medical School.
</P>
<P>
   They remembered the young doctor who was the only pediatrician
in town during World War II. A man who delivered babies to black
women when no one else would. He drove to Pahokee to take care of
migrant children and fought for public polio clinics. He preached
infant immunization and got properly outraged _ and properly busy _
when infant mortality rates soared in the county. He started a
seizure clinic for people with epilepsy and promoted the use of
pediatric nurse practitioners in health clinics.
</P>
<P>
   Then he retired and helped found Healthy Mothers/Healthy Babies,
an organization that helps new mothers pre- and post-natal. What
started on a shoestring and a whim in 1986 now has a $2 million
annual budget.
</P>
<P>
   Again and again, Dr. Martin did what so many of us only dream of
doing. He looked at the world, listened to his conscience and then
helped the children.
</P>
<P>
   Andi Levine first met him in 1963 when she was a new nurse,
fresh out of college. The doctor with the big heart and big
expectations was her mentor for the next 36 years. ``He gave me
confidence and he gave me courage,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Andi Levine was there for the final months of the old doctor's
life. He would call. ``I want to see you,'' the dying man would say
to his old nurse. So she'd go over. She'd walk into the doctor's
bedroom, careful to veil the emotion from seeing him frail and
alone in that bed. She'd kiss his forehead. She'd take his hand.
</P>
<P>
   And then they would talk. Two old friends in the twilight of a
man's life.
</P>
<P>
   But this was not just any man.
</P>
<P>
   And his was not just any life.
</P>
<P>
   Emily J. Minor writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla. E-mail: emilyminor(at)pbpost.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
