r f BC-MONEYTALK-COLUMN13-CO     10-12 0734
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONEYTALK-COLUMN13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Personal Social Security estimate will give workers a clearer
view
 &HT;    By Hank Ezell
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The federal retirement system is coming to your
mailbox, and it wants to help.
</P>
<P>
   No kidding: In the next year, most American workers over 25 will
get an individual estimate of how much retirement money to expect
from Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   It's the Social Security Administration's way of telling you
what to expect _ and what to worry about _ as you plan your
retirement.
</P>
<P>
   All estimates are based on past earnings and current law.
Clearly the numbers will be closer to reality for people who plan
to retire in a few years than for those who yearn to retire in a
few decades.
</P>
<P>
   But at any age, you can get some good from the statement. Here's
how:
</P>
<P>
   _ Your retirement benefit. The statement shows whether you have
qualified for a monthly payment and how much it might be.
</P>
<P>
   Your estimates could be off the mark if your future income
changes drastically in the future.
</P>
<P>
   More importantly, the level of benefits may well decline, or at
least stop growing, as more and more baby boomers retire.
</P>
<P>
   But it's a starting point as you begin to figure your future
needs and where the money is coming from.
</P>
<P>
   _ Other benefits. The statement also shows the disability
payment you would receive if you were out of work before retirement
and the benefits certain survivors would receive if you die this
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The vast majority of younger Americans have little or no
information about these benefits,'' said Social Security
Commissioner Kenneth S. Apfel.
</P>
<P>
   Since many workers don't have disability insurance at work and
haven't bought their own life insurance, knowledge of these federal
benefits is important. Bear in mind that 30 percent of today's
20-year-olds will suffer some disability before they are 67.
</P>
<P>
   _ Early or late retirement. You'll learn your normal retirement
age when you're eligible for the full benefit. That ranges from 65
to 67, depending on the year you were born.
</P>
<P>
   A recent survey from the Employee Benefit Research Institute
showed that 59 percent of Americans believe they will be eligible
for Social Security earlier than the law actually allows. Those who
want to retire early are more likely to believe _ erroneously _
that they will be entitled to benefits early.
</P>
<P>
   The statement also shows how much you will be eligible for at
age 62, at normal retirement age and at age 70. For some, rewards
for working longer will be significant. ``We hope this will help
people start thinking about when their income will be adequate to
retire,'' said Apfel.
</P>
<P>
   _ Checking your records. You'll get a table of your recorded
earnings, for Social Security purposes, for each year. If there are
mistakes, you have a chance to get them fixed. The statement lists
a phone number to call.
</P>
<P>
   _ Getting started. The estimates will demonstrate that Social
Security is a foundation, not a full retirement plan. Apfel hopes
the statements will stimulate workers, particularly the young, to
begin assembling their own retirement resources.
</P>
<P>
   Others believe that a wake-up call is the most important point.
``What most Americans will probably discover is that Social
Security alone will not be enough,'' said Don Blandin, president of
the American Savings Education Council. ``They will need to take
additional steps to secure their financial future.''
</P>
<P>
   ABOUT THE STATEMENT
</P>
<P>
   _ Recipients: Workers over 25 who are not now receiving Social
Security benefits. That's 125 million people.
</P>
<P>
   _ What it says: How much each recipient might receive in
retirement and disability benefits.
</P>
<P>
   _ Timing: Expect to receive a statement three months before your
birthday. The first statements go out this month, to people with
January birthdays.
</P>
<P>
   _ Your record: Social Security's version of your past income, on
which your benefits will be based.
</P>
<P>
   _ Your contributions: There's an estimate of how much you will
pay into the system over a full career.
</P>
<P>
   _ Customized reports: For a statement based on different
retirement ages or changing future income, go to www.ssa
</P>
<P>
   .gov/mystatement on the World Wide Web or call 1-800 772-1213.
</P>
<P>
   Hank Ezell writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
