<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-12 10:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4142 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-WIGGINS-COLUMN13-COX     10-12 0882
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WIGGINS-COLUMN13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    God is asked for patience, a cure
 &HT;    By Ron Wiggins
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ I was sitting in church among
Alzheimer's sufferers and their spouses, wondering if Alzheimer's
patients worship.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, their caregivers pray to heaven for strength to carry
on.
</P>
<P>
   And just as certainly, according to the Rev. Doug Fountain,
Alzheimer's families have spiritual needs that too often are not
met in traditional houses of worship. Fountain, who leads an
Alzheimer's support group out of Epiphany Lutheran Church in
suburban Lake Worth, had announced that at 12:30 p.m. on Oct. 3, he
would lead an interfaith service for Alzheimer's families.
</P>
<P>
   The service began, with Fountain beaming avuncularly at the 11
couples before him, his smile of welcome flooding the sanctuary and
lapping against its doors. He began not with a prayer or hymn, but
with a simple pledge.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will try to make this service as pleasurable and
spiritually fulfilling as possible, whatever your faith.''
</P>
<P>
   Pleasurable? I wondered. What if half the congregation took a
notion to wander off? As for spiritually fulfilling, how can that
be assured when Your God and My God might be strangers?
</P>
<P>
   ``We are here,'' the pastor continued, ``to worship the one God,
our Lord, our father. You and I are one together in God.''
</P>
<P>
   And so we were. We sang ``Amazing Grace,'' ``How Great Thou
Art,'' and ``Just a Closer Walk With Thee.''
</P>
<P>
   I am not a worshiper, just a wonderer, and yet during the chorus
of ``Just a Closer Walk With Thee,'' my eyes brimmed as I recalled
that it was my mother's favorite.
</P>
<P>
   The church got very quiet when Fountain spoke. He had, he said,
spent some time looking through Scriptures with Alzheimer's
families in mind, and he came up with something from Genesis right
off the bat.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Lord God said it is not good for man to be alone.''
</P>
<P>
   The irony probably escaped few of the caregivers, who lose
companionship even as their spouses' demands pile on.
</P>
<P>
   A woman one pew in front of me and to my left slipped her arm
around her husband's shoulders and adjusted his collar. Then, with
her fingertips, she caressed the hairs on his neck. I shivered.
</P>
<P>
   Then, Fountain continued, God sought a companion for Adam, and
brought one forth with elective surgery. Eve walked beside Adam,
Fountain continued, ``two fleshes become one, bound inextricably
together.''
</P>
<P>
   God, the optimist.
</P>
<P>
   In the post-Eden world, Fountain noted somberly, ``Things happen
to the flesh.''
</P>
<P>
   The children leave, and where life once promised to become
simpler, a time to enjoy blessings, a stranger named Alzheimer
moves in, stealing the loved one by degrees, leaving the caregiver
bereft, yet weighted down with responsibilities. And alone.
</P>
<P>
   So it sometimes seems to the beleaguered spouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Lord is my refuge and strength,'' said Fountain, quoting
the psalmist. ``We come to him now in worship and praise and love.
</P>
<P>
   ``But what of those times we get angry _ angry at God?'' the
pastor asked.
</P>
<P>
   Then he answered: Sometimes it helps to get mad.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even at God,'' he told the congregation. ``You know what? The
Lord doesn't turn his back on us. At these times, he asks us to get
back to where you belong, back to your faith. We can rejoice even
in the midst of difficulty, in the midst of suffering.''
</P>
<P>
   Often, said Fountain, the best way to get through a bad patch is
by laughter, with the support and fellowship of people facing the
same hardships. This lesson he said he learned among the members of
the Alzheimer's support group he counsels.
</P>
<P>
   ``You haven't lived,'' he chuckled, ``until you've gone to the
Deli-House at 10 a.m. on a Saturday morning and just listened to
these folks laughing and cutting up.''
</P>
<P>
   The clergyman closed with a prayer, taking requests. What was it
they wished from God? Only they could tell him.
</P>
<P>
   ``A vaccine to cure this terrible disease,'' a female caregiver
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Patience!'' said another.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have patience,'' Fountain observed. ``Let's pray that the
cause of the need for patience be lifted, that a medical cure be
found.''
</P>
<P>
   As the service came to a close, it occurred to me not once was
there a disturbance, and I mentioned it to the pastor afterward.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't expect that there would be,'' he said. ``But you must
understand that even when there isn't a problem, the caregivers
worry that there will be, and they retreat into themselves. Here,
they don't have to fear embarrassment.''
</P>
<P>
   I stood aside, waiting for the couples to pass the pastor.
Usually, it was difficult to tell who was the caretaker and who was
the Alzheimer's patient. Only then did I begin to understand the
anxiety of the caregiver. One moment, the loved one is gentle and
composed, seemingly normal, and a moment later there might be an
outburst or loss of bladder control.
</P>
<P>
   As the last couple walked toward the parking lot, Fountain
favored me with another of his total immersion smiles and said:
</P>
<P>
   ``Here, they don't have to be afraid. We provide them a safe
place.''Ron Wiggins writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm
Beach, Fla. E-mail: ronwiggins(AT)pbpost.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
