<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-COLUMN13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    So-called presidential material is mockery of representative
system
 &HT;    By John Young
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ Presidential politics has turned into amateur
hour.
</P>
<P>
   A cast of impostors has crashed the gala and gained more
attention than deserved.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Bauer demonstrates that all one needs is a mailing list and
Puritan ideology to become a presidential contender.
</P>
<P>
   Pat Buchanan shows that all one need do is work a bellicose word
processor.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Forbes demonstrates that all one needs is a Fortune _
oops, wrong magazine.
</P>
<P>
   At a time when Jesse (the Id) Ventura can become governor and
talk about presidential aspirations, when Donald Trump and Warren
Beatty can surmise that the nation needs them, when Oprah Winfrey
has to demur and say she has a real job _ entertainment mogul _ and
no time to be the vice president Trump wants her to be, what we
have is a masquerade ball.
</P>
<P>
   Are we getting what we deserve?
</P>
<P>
   George Bush has a resume that is heavy on references and light
on accomplishments. At least he has held an elective office.
Elizabeth Dole, who has held some meaty jobs but no elected office
she didn't marry, appears to be running chiefly on the fact that
she can hold a microphone and walk at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   There are non-pretenders running, people who, like Bush,
actually have won an election, negotiated with a governing body,
examined omnibus budgets.
</P>
<P>
   But there are damn few.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes, Buchanan, Trump, Beatty, Dole, Bauer. Not a stint as
county commissioner among them.
</P>
<P>
   All there is is talk. Apparently that is enough.
</P>
<P>
   America should be disgusted, as more and more in Minnesota are,
by Ventura and his position. The disgust should have nothing to do
with what Ventura has said in Playboy or any other venue since his
election. (Give him a venue, he'll talk.) It should have to do with
what little he did to serve the commonweal before he talked his way
into the center stage.
</P>
<P>
   Ventura deserved credit for charisma (of course, give credit
also to a Democrat and a Republican as compelling on-air as a
Mylanta milk shake.) Jesse rode to victory on more than the
nose-ring vote. He won regular Joes without body ornaments. On the
basis of what?
</P>
<P>
   On the basis of refreshing banter, eye-contact,
throw-the-rascals-out exuberance. Observers came expecting a freak
show. They saw a skilled barker. He really connected _ like Oprah
on the tube, like Beatty on-screen.
</P>
<P>
   There's a peculiar reaction in the wake of Jesse's comments in
Playboy, among other things, trashing organized religion and
dismissing the Tailhook scandal: Credit is given to him for being
candid. He didn't tell us what he thought we wanted to hear. He
told us what he was really thinking. Suddenly, that's enough. All
we want is a shock jock at the mike. Give it to us. Talk dirty to
us. We'll love you for it. We want a leader with a 1-900 number on
his chest.
</P>
<P>
   And if you think this is reserved for the Reform Party, whose
search for a standard-bearer sounds like medication roll-call at
the state hospital, you missed last week's convention of the
hard-right National Federation of Republicans. There, Forbes,
Buchanan, Bauer and Alan Keyes bashed Bush for saying that there
might be reasons for government beyond invasive holy wars on
personal choices (which, let's be clear, sound OK to Bush as well.)
</P>
<P>
   Keyes got an ovation calling for abolition of the income tax.
Forbes, who won the convention's straw poll, called for an
elimination of all individual taxes beyond a 17 percent flat tax.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, they got an ovation. But they could say things like this.
They've never negotiated a government budget. They've never had to
compromise a day in their lives, never had to find a coalition to
break a stalemate, never had to yield the floor to someone with a
differing opinion, never had to reason with a diverse constituency,
never had to make anything work in the complex, agonizingly messy
forum of representative democracy. Yeah, let's elect one of them.
</P>
<P>
   John Young writes for The Waco Tribune-Herald, Waco, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
