<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FENG-SHUI-CARDS13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Go Fish: How to feng shui all on your own
 &HT;    By Heather Graulich
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Mae Chin Williams, a feng shui
consultant based in Ohio, has reduced the 3,000-year-old Chinese
art of placement into a 65-card deck called the Feng Shui Card
System. If you can play Go Fish, Mae Chin promises, you can feng
shui your home or office in a jif.
</P>
<P>
   I decided to test the cards _ which retail for $14.95 at places
like Borders and Amazon.com _ on my own home, an old Dutch Colonial
housing myself, my husband, a 16-month-old baby and two fat cats.
</P>
<P>
   The idea is, you start at the top of the deck and select the
cards that apply to your house's layout, which direction it faces,
etc. Then you follow the suggestions on the card for making feng
shui improvements, if needed.
</P>
<P>
   The cards include many of the common-sense aspects of feng shui
decorating, such as putting furniture where it creates a pleasant
flow rather than at awkward angles. But you'd have to be a true
believer to set up an aquarium with eight red fish and one black
fish as a means of creating ``successful energy flow.''
</P>
<P>
   Here are some highlights:
</P>
<P>
   _ Locate the direction of the main entry of your home with the
compass: The card system includes a plastic compass, about the size
of a nickel, which was not reliable. But, hey, I live on the South
Florida grid pattern and would have to be a complete idiot not to
know that my entry faces west. (And if I didn't know, I could pick
up The Complete Idiot's Guide to Feng Shui ($18.95, MacMillan).
</P>
<P>
   _ If the front entrance faces west, you may have many children:
So says the card. The card never went through labor. The card also
says ``west represents the metal element (and) metal represents the
possibility of creating a large family.'' I decide this could be
true if A.) a big chunk of metal bops me on the head and I
hallucinate that I'm Ethel Kennedy or B.) The metal happens to be
gold bullion, magically appearing on my doorstep.
</P>
<P>
   _ Does any large tree overshadow and/or block your main entry
view or path? Apparently, this obstructs positive energy from
entering the home, which is a problem, because four acacia trees
line our driveway and extend their brittle, leaf-dropping branches
right over the entryway. The card says it's OK to chop these down,
but doesn't offer a solution if the trees happen to belong to your
84-year-old neighbor.
</P>
<P>
   _ Does your home have any extensions? We have a new deck on the
east side of the house. The card says an eastward extension
``brings energy that is good for raising children.'' The cards are
mocking me!
</P>
<P>
   _ Is your staircase in direct alignment of the main entry and
does the staircase divide two living areas? Yes. This splits the
energy, the card says, meaning that one of the rooms will rarely be
used. In our case, it's the dining room, which is used, justor its intended purpose. (Is it bad feng shui to change diapers on
your dining table?) The card suggests putting a floor plant on the
staircase landing to correct the energy flow. A couple of plants on
top of a table will have to do, because our fattest cat, Cato,
likes to eat plants left on the floor, then vomit. I don't know
about diapers on the dining table, but that can't be good feng
shui.
</P>
<P>
   _ Decorating with antiques or used furniture is not recommended:
Well, bring me a Dumpster. The card explains that antiques and used
furniture can carry with them the bad karma of a previous owner,
transferring it to your home. But I happen to like antiques.
Although, I must admit, it now feels a little weird to own a
mattress that once belonged to a friend of mine.
</P>
<P>
   His cat died on it.
</P>
<P>
   My energy suddenly feels negative.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
