<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Finding the right feng shui consultant
 &HT;    By Heather Graulich
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Practicing feng shui falls into two
categories: the do-it-yourselfers and those who hire help. The more
than 200 books in print can help if you want to go the self-taught
route, but choosing a feng shui consultant is a little trickier,
especially now that it's trendy, says Nancilee Wydra, founder of
the Feng Shui Institute of America near Vero Beach and a feng shui
consultant since 1974.
</P>
<P>
   There are no industry standards or licensing in feng shui
(although Wydra is working to establish these). There are no
professional associations to call for member referrals. And while
some people study feng shui for years, others take weekend
workshops and call themselves consultants.
</P>
<P>
   ``So many people just started feng shui yesterday,'' she warns.
``The public has to be careful. It can be snake oil or the best
thing you've ever done.''
</P>
<P>
   Wydra offers these tips for hiring a consultant:
</P>
<P>
   _ Ask what school of feng shui the consultant follows to help
choose someone most compatible with your ideas and beliefs. Tibetan
Black Sect Buddhist feng shui, for example, is close to the
traditional Chinese feng shui and follows Eastern philosophies.
Pyramid School, which Wydra founded, uses more Westernized ideas,
while Compass School and the Four Pillars are linked to Chinese
astrology.
</P>
<P>
   _ Find out how much studying the consultant has done. Ask
whether he or she attended a program, how long it was, and whether
there was a mentoring program. The more detailed the course of
study, the more knowledgable the consultant. Be wary of someone who
asks only for your birth date in order to conduct a consultation _
their advice will skim the surface of feng shui, Wydra says.
</P>
<P>
   _ Ask for references from the current year and the two previous
years. This lets you check customer satisfaction while learning how
long the consultant has been working.
</P>
<P>
   _ Expect to pay about $60 to $150 per hour for the consultant,
and expect the consultation to take up to 3 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Heather Graulich writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm
Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
