<HEADER>
A4149 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-FENG-SHUI13-COX     10-12 1136
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FENG-SHUI13-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Does your home need a little Feng shui?
</P>
<P>
   By Heather Graulich
</P>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Here's how you can tell feng shui has
gone mainstream:
</P>
<P>
   It's now a verb.
</P>
<P>
   As in, ``I feng shuied my house.''
</P>
<P>
   Like ``network'' and ``dialogue'' before it, feng shui has hit
the big time, so popular that it's not only the ancient Chinese art
of placement, but the act of placement.
</P>
<P>
   Confused? You can look it up in Webster's Collegiate Dictionary,
which added the two-part word just last year, along with other
popular words such as ``gazillion'' and ``buffalo wings.''
Webster's says feng shui (pronounced ``fung shway,'' literally
meaning wind-water in Chinese) is only a noun, but try telling that
to its legions of practitioners, consultants and authors.
</P>
<P>
   An Internet search turned up more than 200 books on the subject,
and three separate feng shui workshops have been held locally in
the past two weeks, drawing hundreds of people. Even the folks who
bought O.J. Simpson's Brentwood mansion used a feng shui consultant
to get rid of any negative energy left behind.
</P>
<P>
   In case you've missed the feng shui bandwagon, it is, according
to Webster's, ``a Chinese geomantic practice in which a structure
or site is chosen or configured so as to harmonize with the
spiritual forces that inhabit it; also: auspicious orientation,
placement or arrangement as determined by feng shui.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, the way your house sits on its lot, the
direction the doors face, where you put your furniture, where you
hang your art, what kinds of symbolic decorations and colors you
use _ all of these things, and more _ can affect your moods,
health, relationships and financial success.
</P>
<P>
   Feng shui has been around for more than 3,000 years, but its
burgeoning popularity in the West, experts say, is a side effect of
our hectic, stressed lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it ties in with spirituality,'' says Carol Cannon,
president of Environmental Placements Inc., a Delray Beach firm
specializing in feng shui for corporate clients.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are seeking (spirituality) and seeking harmony and
calmness and peace in their lives. It's just another way to help
make your life more positive.''
</P>
<P>
   That's why Cheryl Carpentier of Stuart decided to give it a try.
Carpentier, owner of The Cabinet Gallery and vice president of the
National Kitchen and Bath Association's South Florida chapter,
recently held a feng shui workshop for local NKBA members.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anything that makes you a better designer only improves what
you're offering your client,'' says Carpentier, who designs custom
kitchens. ``I think there's a lot of principles in feng shui that
are useable.''
</P>
<P>
   Principles such as not having your back to the kitchen entrance
when you work at the kitchen island or stovetop. This is less
welcoming to others in the room and, in the case of the stove, can
be dangerous if you're startled when someone comes up behind you.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Carpentier says, she probably wouldn't go so
far as performing a ``clearing'' for a client. In feng shui,
clearings are done to eliminate negative energy by saying a prayer
or waving burning sage over the area, Cannon says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Am I going to go out and do that? No. I think my customers
might wonder about me,'' Carpentier says. ``I work with builders a
lot and I can't imagine them taking me seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite feng shui's popularity _ and many of the common-sense
design philosophies it uses _ it can raise eyebrows for some of the
near-religiosity surrounding it, Cannon says. She primarily follows
Tibetan Black Sect Buddhist feng shui, a traditional type rooted in
Eastern philosophies.There are several other feng shui styles,
including the Compass School (which uses strict compass directions)
and the Four Pillars (linked to Chinese astrology).
</P>
<P>
   Such links to spiritualism make some people wary. One of
Cannon's clients, the o a large South Florida company, swore
Cannon to secrecy after she performed feng shui at the company's
headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   Others are more open about their belief in feng shui, such as
Health Communications in Deerfield Beach, publishers of the
``Chicken Soup for the Soul'' books. Their headquarters, plus the
home of president Peter Vegso, were ``feng shuied'' by Cannon. She
is also working with the developers of the new Spa Atlantis in Fort
Lauderdale to apply feng shui principles to several new buildings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a progressive company and we're open to new ideas and
new (ways) of doing business,'' says Health Communications
spokeswoman Kim Weiss. ``(The feng shui) is definitely a point of
conversation. There are believers and skeptics, but we have a high
percentage of believers. There are plants where there weren't
plants and mirrors that make the space seem bigger. The place is
very livable now.''
</P>
<P>
   Weiss cites the example of a large column in one part of the
office that Cannon determined was ``blocking the positive energy.''
They covered it with mirrors to make it seem to disappear and the
department nearest the column became much more productive, she
says.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, feng shui's success lies largely with the person
using the space, says Nancilee Wydra, founder of the Feng Shui
Institute of America in Vero Beach and the most-published American
author of feng shui books. Her Sept. 26 workshop in Delray Beach
attracted 126 people, ``from 23-year-old boys with their baseball
caps on backward to 80-year-old couples,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Feng shui isn't about place,'' she says. ``It's about the
human experience of place.''
</P>
<P>
   Wydra created the Pyramid School style of feng shui, a type that
diverges from traditional Chinese feng shui to account for the
differences between Eastern and Western cultures. (For example,
Chinese feng shui often uses talismans like the octagon-shaped
bac-gua mirror, which reprsents the ``I Ching,'' or all possible
combinations of masculine and feminine forces in the world. These
icons hold little meaning for Americans, who may prefer talismans
important to them, such as family photos.)
</P>
<P>
   But, she says, to truly reap the benefits from any style of feng
shui, a person must approach it with an open mind. Like the placebo
effect in medicine, the positive act of believing that something
will work can make good things happen. And besides, feng shui
devotees point out, it does no harm to try it.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you believe something is going to work, then that belief
means you're already 50-percent there,'' Wydra says. ``When you
have belief, you're far more likely to achieve your goals than when
you don't.''
</P>
<P>
   Heather Graulich writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm
Beach, Fla. E-mail: heathergraulich(AT)pbpost.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
