<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A natural `Miss Hathaway' learns to live with it
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Soon after her days on ``Laugh-In,''
Lily Tomlin made the transition to film. Some of her thoughts on
her movie roles:
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Nashville'' (1975) _ ``It was a great break for me, because
at that time very few people crossed over from television, and
especially someone like me who was doing such characters as
Ernestine. People thought that's who I was. And of course (director
Robert) Altman never watched television. I only found out later
that that part had been written and conceived for Louise Fletcher.
At the time, I just thought I was very lucky to get it. It was my
first film and I got nominated (for an Academy Award).''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``All of Me'' (1984) _ ``That's one of my favorites, because I
think it's a really funny, charming movie. At first, I wasn't going
to take the part, because there was a certain lack of consciousness
about some things. Because my character was so aristocratic and
autocratic, but in the bed scene, when I'm in (Steve Martin's) body
when he's with Victoria (Tennant), in the script he was slapping
her. I said, `That's going to look awful.' So we finally worked it
out that he spanked her, so it was just silly and playful.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The Beverly Hillbillies'' (1993) _ ``That's one that
surprised me. I turned it down at first. I didn't want to be Miss
Hathaway, you know? Even my mother called me, `Oh, I heard you're
going to be Miss Hathaway. You're just going to be perfect.' And I
would think, `I'm not Miss Hathaway. That's all there is to it.'
And of course, I must have been Miss Hathaway, because I actually
got many of my best reviews ever for a movie. So my maturity allows
me to accept this now.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Flirting With Disaster'' (1996) _ ``That's another one of my
big favorites. I read the script so many times and every time I'd
read it I would laugh out loud. It was pretty popular in the big
cities, in the East and the West, but the middle of the country
didn't like it. They don't like hand-held camera.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
