r l BC-FENG-SHUI-TIPS13-COX     10-12 0501
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FENG-SHUI-TIPS13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Feng shui in a hurry: Top 10 tips from the experts
 &HT;    By Heather Graulich
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Chinese art of feng shui is more than 3,000 years old, and
trying to figure out all its symbols and meanings sometimes feels
like it might take that long. We asked several local feng shui
consultants to boil it down. Here is their condensed list of tips:
</P>
<P>
   1. Clear out the clutter. ``Clutter accumulates dead energy,''
says Nancilee Wydra, founder of the Feng Shui Institute of America.
``It congests us, makes us unable to do things.'' Her rule? If you
haven't used it or worn it in 18 months, chuck it.
</P>
<P>
   2. Position your bed and desk so you don't have your back to the
door. ``It makes you vulnerable,'' says Carol Cannon, president of
Environmental Placements, a firm that specializes in feng shui for
corporate clients.
</P>
<P>
   3. Create places for conversation, such as two chairs at right
angles. People tend to talk to each other more in this position
than if they face each other or sit side-by-side. Ideally, this
area is in a ``technology-free'' part of the house where you ban
TVs, telephones and computers.
</P>
<P>
   4. Create a place to eat that is honored and doesn't feel empty.
If you have a big dining table but usually only two people for
dinner, sit together (at right angles) at one end of the table and
create a display of art and candles at the other end.
</P>
<P>
   5. Create a ``power wall'' in your living room that is a
representation of what you want out of life. This is the wall
opposite the main entrance to the room. At feng shui consultant
Wendy Victor's home in Palm Beach, Fla., the power wall is over the
fireplace mantle, where her husband, Mike, placed a tranquil
painting of a boat on a lake. The painting reflects the beauty and
peacefulness the Victors strive for in their lives.
</P>
<P>
   6. Engage the senses. People feel good outdoors because all of
their senses are affected. Inside, use flowers, the movement of a
flickering candle, the sound of water running in a tabletop
fountain and other objects to keep the house from feeling sterile.
</P>
<P>
   7. Embrace nature by filling your home with live healthy plants
or clean silks.
</P>
<P>
   8. Use all the rooms of your house. If you don't use a room,
change its purpose so you will. ``If you don't use it, you become
underpowered,'' Wydra says.
</P>
<P>
   9. Don't forget the outside of your house. ``Get in a car and
let a friend drive you back to your house. If you approach it from
a point where you can just look at it, instead of focusing on the
road, you might see some dead (plants) or other outside clutter,''
Cannon says.
</P>
<P>
   10. And don't forget the garage, if that's where you usually
enter your home. ``Honor that space as you would the front door,''
Wydra says. Wendy and Mike Victor have done this by covering the
interior walls of their garage with a mural of plants, birds and
animals.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
