<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-12 10:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4153 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-NUTS-AND-BOLTS13-COX     10-12 0730
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NUTS-AND-BOLTS13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NUTS &AMP; BOLTS: Steam shower or sauna? Looks like a dead heat
 &HT;    By James Cummings
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Some reader questions fall completely outside my
area of expertise. For today's questions on saunas and vinyl
siding, I spent about a week on each, looking through books,
surfing the Web and talking to experts on the phone.
</P>
<P>
   Still, I haven't been completely stumped yet.
</P>
<P>
   E.B. of Trotwood, Ohio, plans to have a house built, and he
wants to include either a home sauna or a steam shower. He wanted
to know the advantages and disadvantages of each, including health
benefits, costs, energy consumption and so on.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Solution: Saunas are small rooms with wooden benches that
usually have a heater mounted on the wall or in a corner. They
provide dry heat, but in most you can toss a little water onto
stones on top of the heater to add humidity to the air. Steam
showers are shower stalls that are watertight from floor to
ceiling. A steam generator, usually placed in a nearby room or
closet, produces steam that is pumped into the sealed shower stall
through nozzles. Saunas and steam showers do essentially the same
thing, and choosing one over the other is mostly a matter of
personal taste.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Sean Convery, medical director of the Miami Valley Sports
Medicine Center, said saunas and steam showers both open your
pores, make you sweat and relax your muscles and joints. Convery
said some people feel steam helps their sinuses and skin, but he
knows of no clinical studies backing up that claim.
</P>
<P>
   Saunas and steam showers both take some getting used to, so they
should be used for 10 minutes or less at first. Avoid them
altogether if you have a history of heart problems or high blood
pressure or if you're pregnant. Prepare for the intense heat by
drinking three to four glasses of water beforehand. Move slowly
when you're ready to leave. The heat can make you dizzy if you're
not used to it. Saunas and steam showers don't help you lose
weight, they don't draw impurities out of your body and, although
they may ease cold symptoms temporarily, they don't shorten a
cold's duration.
</P>
<P>
   Troy Cyrus, assistant sales manager of a Watson's store in
Cincinnati, said he sells steam-shower systems for about $3,500 to
$4,500. Installation costs vary with the amount of plumbing work
that must be done and the elaborateness of the shower stall.
Portable sauna units that come in two halves that a homeowner can
snap together in 10 minutes sell for about $3,600. One of the most
popular models Cyrus sells is a 5-by-7-foot sauna that sells for
about $4,700. The energy consumption of a sauna or steam shower
varies with the size and efficiency of the heater or steam
generator.
</P>
<P>
   ADDING NEW SIDING TO AN OLD HOUSE
</P>
<P>
   R.P. is rehabilitating an old house and wants to put vinyl
siding on the exterior walls. The problem is the old walls are in
less-than-perfect shape. The walls are sided with traditional
overlapping wooden slats, and many of the slats are cracked or
damaged. Some have holes through which insulation was previously
added. R.P. wants to know whether he should use a house-wrapping
material such as Tyvek or if he should apply something like tar
paper commonly used in roofing to seal the house before installing
the vinyl siding.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Solution: Representatives of New Haven Construction, a
housing-rehabilitation specialist, and All Seal Home Improvement, a
siding specialist, both said foam boards are the backing of choice
for vinyl siding on an old house. All Seal Vice President Bill
Stacy said 1/4-inch foam board adds a layer of insulation while
providing a level surface underneath the new siding. ``It makes the
siding look better if it's attached to a flat foam board,'' Stacy
said. A synthetic house wrap or tar paper might be acceptable, but
not preferred. Stacy said any wrap with a metallic or shiny surface
should be avoided because it can trap heat under the vinyl and
damage the installation.
</P>
<P>
   Have an idea, question or concern? Contact James Cummings by
e-mail: jamescummings(AT)coxohio.com; or write to the Features
Department, Dayton Daily News, 45 S. Ludlow St., Dayton, Ohio
45402.
</P>
<P>
   James Cummings writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
