<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TESTDRIVE-COLUMN13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Chevrolet refines a meal ticket
 &HT;    By Russ DeVault
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Although not particularly noticeable on the road, the
Chevrolet Cavalier really stands out when General Motors and the
rest of the auto industry look at the bottom line: The Cavalier is
Chevy's best-selling sedan. Its 1999 sales through September were
up 7 percent from last year to 217,345 vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   In '98, the Cavalier had sales totaling 256,099, making it No. 6
overall.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, GM doesn't want to do anything radical to its volume
leader, so the 2000 Cavalier gets some exterior tweaking _
body-color trim and repackaged taillamps _ and some mechanical and
interior refinements. The noticeable changes include making air
conditioning standard on all five models and _ finally _ switching
the heater/AC controls and radio so that the stereo is on top of
the center dash stack and therefore easier to reach and operate.
The General scores ergonomic points for this.
</P>
<P>
   It's interesting to note, too, that the radios are significantly
improved, with power bumped to 50 watts. The upgraded ones have the
Radio Data System, which allows traffic and weather bulletins to
interrupt the use of the radio, cassette and CD players to keep
drivers well-informed.
</P>
<P>
   Prices have evolved a bit, too _ upward, of course. The base
Cavalier coupe is $13,066, the base sedan is $13,165, the LS sedan
is $14,710, the two-door Z24 is $16,270 and the Z24 convertible is
$19,735.
</P>
<P>
   In-town and interstate driving in an LS sedan and a Z24 coupe
prove that both Cavaliers remain people-friendly, for the most
part. They seem solid enough with sound overall ergonomics _ not
just those relating to the stereo and heater/AC _ and fairly good
seats with good interior room for what are subcompact cars.
</P>
<P>
   A new safety feature is the traction control system available
with the automatic transmission. It operates when the Cavalier is
in drive, but is switched off when the shifter is changed to a
lower gear, a useful feature if the car becomes stuck in snow or
mud.
</P>
<P>
   The automatic transmission is about as smooth as they get in
cars in the Cavalier category _ competitors include the Ford
Escort, Honda Civic and Dodge/Plymouth Neon. Neither the base
2.4-liter four-cylinder engine (115 horsepower at 5,000 revolutions
per minute) nor the twin-cam version (150 hp at 5,600 rpm) is
overwhelmingly strong, but they manage, respectively, 135 and 155
pounds-feet of torque. Push it, and the stronger four-banger gets
the 2,600-pound Cavalier to 60 mph in a respectable eight seconds
or so.
</P>
<P>
   The cabin's fairly quiet most of the time _ brisk acceleration
brings in the usual engine and exhaust noise _ and visibility is
good. Brake and steering feel is good _ the sportier Cavaliers can
be real fun to drive _ and the instrumentation and controls are
like the seating _ competent, but not extraordinary.
</P>
<P>
   The overall balance of standard features, utility, economy and
last-a-while styling is good, and that, quite simply, explains the
success of the steadily evolving Cavalier.
</P>
<P>
   _ Test vehicle: 2000 Chevrolet Cavalier LS front-drive sedan
</P>
<P>
   _ Price as tested: $16,280 (base: $14,710)
</P>
<P>
   _ Drivetrain: optional 2.4-liter four-cylinder engine (150
horsepower), four-speed automatic overdrive transmission
</P>
<P>
   _ Safety features: dual air bags, power anti-lock brakes,
height-adjustable front shoulder belts, daytime running lights
</P>
<P>
   _ Other options on test vehicle: keyless entry system, $410;
deck lid spoiler, $150; upgraded AM/FM radio with CD player, $50
</P>
<P>
   _ EPA figures: 22 mpg regular unleaded city, 30 mpg highway
</P>
<P>
   Russ DeVault writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
