 Tuesday, Oct. 12, 1999     
 Editors      The Hearst News Service will file the following for
Wednesday. If you have questions, please call Tim Spence at
202-298-6320.    (The ``HNS'' tag appears in all sluglines.)   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   PRIZE-WINNER (San Francisco) _ Ahmed Zewail's winning of the
Nobel Prize was forecast nine years ago by a scientific journal in
Philadelphia. The California Institute of Technology scientist won
the Nobel Prize for chemistry Tuesday for demonstrating that a
rapid laser technique can observe the motion of atoms in a molecule
as they occur during a chemical reaction. By KEAY DAVIDSON.
</P>
<P>
   QUAKE-PREPAREDNESS (San Francisco) _ Because he runs San
Francisco's Office of Emergency Services, many might guess that
Lucien Canton would be the most prepared of all. But even Canton,
who was a military reservist for the Federal Emergency Management
Agency when the Loma Prieta quake rolled through the Bay Area 10
years ago, said the experience had made him realize he could do
better. By ANATASIA HENDRIX.
</P>
<P>
   BATTLESHIP-IOWA (San Francisco) _ After years of effort, the USS
Iowa will soon have a permanent berth in the port of San Francisco
as an educational and tourist attraction, Rep. Lynn Woolsey,
D-Calif., has announced. By ANDREA WOO.
</P>
<P>
   WOODSTOCK-POLICE (Albany, N.Y.) _ Ten New York state troopers
and two supervisors were suspended for cavorting with nude women
during the fiery riots that closed Woodstock '99, the agency
announced. By ALAN WECHSLER.
</P>
<P>
   TIRE-FIRE (Westley, Calif.) _ They've battled big blazes from
the Persian Gulf to the Gulf of Mexico, emerging victorious more
than 100 times. Now Dwight and Randy Williams, a brother-sister
team that possesses one of the world's great firefighting
pedigrees, are face-to-face with something they've never
confronted: a smoldering 40-acre expanse of 7 million tires. By
JANE KAY.
</P>
<P>
   RETAILERS-DATA (San Francisco) _ California has a new law that
restricts the kinds of information grocery stores can solicit in
exchange for letting customers use various reward or loyalty
programs that offer price discounts. By GEORGE RAINE.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-REVIEW-ROMANCE (Undated) _ It's hard to say a bad word
about a film like ``Romance'' without sounding prudish,
anti-intellectual or both. When it comes to critical booby traps,
you can't do better (or worse) than an explicit French movie about
the sexual exploits of a bored young woman. Praise it and prove
your mettle. Pan it and look like a dunce. Enter the dunce. By AMY
BIANCOLLI.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   DECORATING (Undated) _ Don't be frustrated at the thought of
starting a decorating project. If you can read and follow basic
instructions, a myriad of self-help books can guide you through the
process of creating or transforming a room to fit your personal
style and needs. By FRANCES INGRAHAM HEINS.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   OUTDOORS-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ Every time you drop your
fishing line, in the back of your mind is the thought that maybe,
just maybe, you might catch the fish of a lifetime. That is exactly
what happened this past week to Mike Chadwick of Bolinas, Calif.
But he not only thought it, he did it. By TOM STIENSTRA.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MORSE-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ How does that political slogan on
top of San Francisco taxicabs go? ``World-class city, world-class
mayor, any questions?'' I have a question. Why does such a
beautiful city have such ugly, vicious, no-class politics? Why
would San Franciscans have any of the so-called major candidates as
a mayor? Most people wouldn't let them walk their dog. By ROB
MORSE.
</P>
<P>
   LYNCH-COLUMN (Albany, N.Y.) _ Since the last election, New
York's Gov. George Pataki has turned into the Man Who Never Comes
to Dinner. Not long ago, he got a big raise. Now, apparently, he
won't come to work unless he also gets a signing bonus.The problem
seems to be, in the context of New York politics, that George
Pataki sees himself in a dead-end job with no room for advancement.
By DAN LYNCH.
</P>
<P>
   DEAFNESS (San Francisco) _ The moment of realization, when it
comes, is often surprising. ``Oh! She's deaf!'' one woman gasped
recently. Unfortunately, the knowledge all too often never dawns,
leaving the impression that I'm either rude, strange, or both. I'm
not antisocial. I just can't hear. By LISA A. GOLDSTEIN.
</P>
