<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-12 11:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4189 &Cx1f; kan-z
r e BC-MOVIE-POLLACK-KANSAS-     10-12 0702
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-POLLACK-KANSAS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A DIRECTIVE OF LOVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBERT W. BUTLER  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Sydney Pollack looks back on a directing career highlighted
by films as varied as the mountain man saga ``Jeremiah Johnson,''
the romance ``The Way We Were'' and the comedy ``Tootsie,'' what he
sees is love.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never been able to make a film that doesn't have a love
story of sorts in it,'' Pollack said in a phone interview from New
York, where his latest film, ``Random Hearts,'' was having its
premiere.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're all relationship movies in one way or another, no
matter what the form. They can be Westerns like `Jeremiah Johnson'
or action pictures like `Three Days of the Condor,' but the nerve
at the center of each is always romance. Even a comedy like
`Tootsie' is still a love story.''
</P>
<P>
   Was this a conscious choice?
</P>
<P>
   ``Not at all _ at least, not at first,'' Pollack said. ``It's
become a conscious thing, but not because I'm trying to imitate
myself. It's just that my affinity for love stories has been
written about often enough that I say to myself, `I guess it's
true.' Why is that? Why do I make so many love stories?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know. But while I don't mind seeing a movie without a
love story because it only takes up a couple hours of my time, I'm
pickier when it comes to making movies. That's two years of my
life, and I know I'll get bored with the process if there isn't an
interesting relationship at the story's core.''
</P>
<P>
   The relationship at the center of ``Random Hearts'' may be the
most complex Pollack has ever attempted to depict. Based on Warren
Adler's 1984 novel, it's about a police officer (Harrison Ford) and
a U.S. Representative (Kristin Scott Thomas) who lose their spouses
in the crash of a jetliner. The two are drawn together when they
realize his wife and her husband were having an affair.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a difficult one to crack,'' Pollack said. ``The way
these people meet is not conducive to a love story. But that was
the thing that fascinated me. The trick was to figure out a way to
get this couple together.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, a love story stands or falls on the basis of
obstacles. From `Romeo and Juliet' to `Dr. Zhivago' to `Brief
Encounter,' it is the degree of impossibility of the lovers getting
together that creates tension. And I don't think I could have found
a premise as challenging as this one.''
</P>
<P>
   Usually, Pollack said, Ford's and Scott Thomas' characters would
have little in common. But here they are bound together by grief at
the loss of a spouse and by rage generated by betrayal.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question we always had to ask is which would take
preference _ grief or rage?'' Pollack said. ``When sex happens to
these people, it isn't really love. It happens in this unplanned,
desperate way that is inappropriate and humiliating for both of
them. It's more about rage, grief and the need for revenge than it
is about lust. All these feelings pile up until they spill over.
</P>
<P>
   Although he's known primarily as a director, Pollack has in
recent years found himself in front of the camera, first as Dustin
Hoffman's flustered agent in``Tootsie,'' then as a man with a huge
midlife crisis in Woody Allen's ``Husbands and Wives,'' and most
recently as a rich, amoral hedonist in Stanley Kubrick's ``Eyes
Wide Shut.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I started my career as a kind of fifth-rate actor,'' he said.
``I made my living by teaching acting, actually, from the time I
was 19. But I never did anything that was great shakes as an actor.
It's a good thing I became a director or I'd have starved.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``Random Hearts'' he plays a very contemporary character, a
political media consultant who knows all about spin control,
innuendo and image building.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason I cast myself is that I work cheap,'' Pollack
confided. ``I'd spent all my money on Harrison Ford.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I really enjoyed this character. He's an absolute cynic,
very much a product of the '90s political system. He's the guy who
lives by the sound bite, the focus group, the
say-anything-to-get-elected mentality. But he's not really a bad
guy because he lets you know up front that this is how he
operates.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
