<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-12 11:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4193 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-DENIM-FASHIONS13-COX     10-12 1516
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DENIM-FASHIONS13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The dirt on denim
 &HT;    (EDS: With sidebars at end of story.)
 &HT;    By Staci Sturrock
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ In the past few years, the jeans
business has been fueled by different shapes. Surely you've worn or
have studiously avoided one of the following: Legs so wide they
could easily slip over an elephant's foot; low-slung waists that
flirt with disaster; or highwater hems that bare the meatiest part
of your calves.
</P>
<P>
   Now, jeans are getting kicked in the back pocket by a slew of
new details that render them either more refined or more rugged.
</P>
<P>
   They're purposely ripped up or they're festooned with velvet
ribbons. Blue jeans are dyed so dark they almost look black, or
they're subtly outfitted with red seams reminiscent of the original
Levi's.
</P>
<P>
   Even the Gap, which wants ``everybody in cords, vests and
leather'' this fall, is sitting pretty on the denim bandwagon. The
retailer has expanded its line of garden-variety jeans to include
denim with daintily beaded roses running up and down the legs.
</P>
<P>
   Gucci is credited with goosing denim's recent upsurge in sales
(46.7 million pairs of women's jeans were sold in the first quarter
of this year, a 5.3 percent increase over the same period a year
ago). After Gucci designer Tom Ford feathered and decorated denim
for the glitterati, the embellished look made its way to the mall.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are looking at denim as a fashion statement rather than
as a staple to have within your wardrobe,'' says Karen Koza,
director of public relations for the Fashion Association.
</P>
<P>
   Jeans traditionally sell well in Florida because the state
``created a laidback and casual lifestyle,'' says Melissa Goff of
Burdines. ``Jeans are indicative of that lifestyle and of us.''
</P>
<P>
   JC Western Supply in West Palm Beach has an inventory of roughly
20,000 pairs of jeans, and there's not a fringed hem among them.
Which doesn't bother Brigitte Halsey, whose family has run the
Congress Avenue store for 40 years.
</P>
<P>
   Embellished is ``going to be big, and it's going to be gone,''
she says. ``If they come in here asking for them now, they won't be
asking for them in January. . . . The style of Levi's, Lees and
Wranglers are what our customers will come back to buy tomorrow,
next month and next year.''
</P>
<P>
   Cynthia Nellis, who watches fashion trends for about.com,
agrees. ``I think embellished is a fad. . . . Darker dye is a
toss-up. It's a little safer. It's a classic, just a different
color.'' Nellis, who is based in Dallas, says, ``I'm not seeing
tons of embellished jeans on the street, but everybody's showing
it.''
</P>
<P>
   So what should you buy that will still look sharp a year from
now? ``I don't know if jeans really count as investment dressing or
not. You can get a nice pair for under $60,'' Nellis says. ``But a
mid-range color or black is probably safest.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides, the fashion industry hopes that you'll be ready to
spring for the next big thing in denim: Calvin Klein's CK Jeans in
``dirty denim,'' which has been blasted, whipped, dyed and
sandpapered almost beyond recognition. The collection will be
unveiled next spring with a you-can't-miss-it ad campaign starring
10 emerging musicians.
</P>
<P>
   Blue jeans have a thoroughly American heritage, right? Well,
sort of.
</P>
<P>
   Technically, denim is cotton twill weave fabric of white and
blue threads. It was first woven on the looms of Nimes, France,
which explains the origin of its name: serge de Nimes (''twilled
fabric from Nimes'').
</P>
<P>
   The word ``jeans'' comes from ``Genes,'' French for the port
city of Genoa, Italy, where sailors wore sturdy work pants.
</P>
<P>
   During the gold mining boom of the 1850s, a young Bavarian
immigrant named Levi Strauss arrived in San Francisco trying to
make a buck.
</P>
<P>
   He gamely tried to sell a miner some canvas tents, but the old
codger said, ``You should have brought pants!''
</P>
<P>
   Strauss listened. He started sewing pants from brown canvas and
later switched to denim, which he dyed blue with indigo. Strauss
took out a patent for his durable jeans in 1872.
</P>
<P>
   Can you wear denim to your white-collar job?
</P>
<P>
   _ Yes, if you keep it clean.
</P>
<P>
   Jeans ``that are free of holes, tears, stains, paint or other
signs of abuse are totally acceptable in a dressed-down
environment,'' say Chic Simple's Kim Johnson Gross and Jeff Stone.
</P>
<P>
   _ Yes, if you accessorize wisely.
</P>
<P>
   No tennis shoes or sneakers, says Karen Koza of the Fashion
Association. Women can dress up jeans with a string of pearls or a
cashmere sweater set, say the Chic Simple folks.
</P>
<P>
   _ Yes, if your jeans aren't too tight.
</P>
<P>
   Stick to a classic, relaxed fit or choose denim with a little
stretch in it.
</P>
<P>
   _ Yes, particularly if your denim is dark.
</P>
<P>
   ``People that I talk to get around it by wearing black jeans
because they're a little dressier,'' says Cynthia Nellis, a fashion
expert with about.com.
</P>
<P>
   The care and feeding of denim
</P>
<P>
   Denim is about as durable as fabrics come. That's why it's the
uniform of choice for cowboys and construction workers. But that
doesn't mean you can abuse denim indefinitely.
</P>
<P>
   The folks at Whirlpool suggest washing denim in warm water. (Try
hot water if you've rolled around in the mud.)
</P>
<P>
   To reduce wear and tear, shut off the dryer when your denim item
is just dry and remove it promptly to prevent any wrinkles from
setting.
</P>
<P>
   Denim as muse
</P>
<P>
   Whether ripped and faded, safety-pinned to within an inch of
their lives, or starched stiff, blue jeans have been the pant of
choice for many a musician. No wonder jeans pop up in so many
lyrics and a fair number of song titles:
</P>
<P>
   Venus in Blue Jeans, Jimmy Clanton
</P>
<P>
   Forever in Blue Jeans, Neil Diamond
</P>
<P>
   Baby Makes Her Blue Jeans Talk, Dr. Hook
</P>
<P>
   Blue Jean, David Bowie
</P>
<P>
   Tight-Fittin' Jeans, Conway Twitty
</P>
<P>
   Venom Wearin' Denim, Junior Brown
</P>
<P>
   Denim as museum
</P>
<P>
   You can visit Levi Strauss' oldest surviving factory, which
opened in November 1906 (earlier factories were felled by the San
Francisco earthquake of April 1906).
</P>
<P>
   At the adjoining Levi Strauss Museum, see exhibits about the man
and the company; see vintage garments; view classic Levi's
commercials; and take a walking tour of the factory.
</P>
<P>
   The museum and factory are at 250 Valencia St. in San Francisco.
Phone is (415) 565-9159.
</P>
<P>
   How much denim do you own?
</P>
<P>
   _ According to the Cotton Incorporated Lifestyle Monitor, women
between the ages of 16 and 24 own an average of eight pairs of
jeans each. Women 56 to 70: About two.
</P>
<P>
   _ Wal-Mart sells three pairs of jeans every second of every day.
</P>
<P>
   _ Denim is the biggest end-use category for cotton, accounting
for almost 25 percent of all cotton produced.
</P>
<P>
   A denim dictionary
</P>
<P>
   BEADED _ Intricate beadwork on the waistband, down the legs and
hanging off the hems is a favored embellishment of jeans makers
this fall. Some beading calls to mind Native American jewelry,
others create pretty floral patterns. ``It's all glam rock. Just
like in the '70s when we put all that stuff on the jeans,'' says
Cynthia Nellis, about.com fashion expert.
</P>
<P>
   BEATEN UP _ Call them ``vintage'' if you must, but ``destroyed''
is closer to the truth. If your mother saw you walking around in
these pre-distressed jeans, with their ripped pockets and holey
knees, she'd make you change before leaving the house.
</P>
<P>
   CUFFED _ Want to cuff correctly? Choose an extra-long pair of
dark jeans. Fold the hems just once _ we're talking four to six
inches _ to reveal the pants' pale underside.
</P>
<P>
   DRAWSTRING _ Buttons and zippers still secure flies, but
drawstrings cinch some waists. Some jeans also come equipped with
sewn-in ``belts'' of ribbons or beads that are for decoration only.
</P>
<P>
   EMBROIDERED _ Appliques, strips of brocade and velvet ribbons
add color to denim, particularly at the hem where several inches of
embroidery can stack up almost to the knee.
</P>
<P>
   JACKETS _ Denim jackets are receiving the same kind of fussing
over in fabrics and detailing that jeans are. ``They're back in a
big way,'' says Melissa Goff, Burdines fashion director. ``In a
casual setting, that's the only kind of jacket you need to get
through the winter.''
</P>
<P>
   RAW _ ``Raw'' doesn't refer to the stiff feel of this denim, but
rather its super-slick, unwashed state (which usually requires dry
cleaning). Also called ``rinse'' or ``dark dye.'' ``Everybody's got
a different name for it,'' says Nellis.
</P>
<P>
   RING SPUN _ Ring Spun denim is woven so the cotton fibers are
twisted in one uniform direction, which gives the yarn added
strength and makes for an extra-smooth texture.
</P>
<P>
   SELVAGE _ Jeans woven on old, narrow shuttle looms have a red
seam refered to as ``selvage'' that can be seen when cuffs are
turned up. It's a detail meant to hearken back to the original
Levi's.
</P>
<P>
   STRETCH _ The addition of a synthetic such as Lycra or polyester
gives denim's cotton a little more give.
</P>
<P>
   Staci Sturrock writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
