<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-12 11:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4194 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-MAKEUP-THERAPY13-COX     10-12 0535
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAKEUP-THERAPY13-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Cosmic cosmeticians promise color therapy for the spirit
</P>
<P>
   By Staci Sturrock
</P>
<P>
   C. 1999 Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Any old lipstick can colorize your
mouth. A really great lipstick can ``calm and revitalize your
evolving mind.''
</P>
<P>
   At least that's what the folks at Tony &AMP; Tina's Vibrational
Remedies believe.
</P>
<P>
   The fledgling makeup company sells Mood Balance Lipstick, Color
Frequency Eye Shadow, Cosmic Lights powder and New Age wisdom.
</P>
<P>
   And, yes, they're serious.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure there are some people out there who think we're just
doing this as a marketing concept. But if they would talk to us and
read beyond just one or two sentences, they'd realize that we're
sincere,'' says Tina Bornstein, co-founder and creative president
of Vibrational Remedies.
</P>
<P>
   Tony and Tina, who are married, were painters and writers before
launching their makeup company 2 1/2 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   They had produced a conceptual art show of seven bottles of nail
polish that corresponded to the seven chakra colors, pointing out
that they believed those hues to be more therapeutic than anything
sold at the cosmetics counter. (''Chakra,'' Tina says, is Sanskrit
for ``wheels of light'' and refers to energy centers in the human
body.)
</P>
<P>
   The show flopped, but through the help of creative visualization
books, the couple imagined themselves a company that would allow
them to spread the word about color therapy.
</P>
<P>
   Three weeks later, they found an investor, and Tony &AMP; Tina's
Vibrational Remedies was born. In their airy New York loft office,
employees can participate in weekly yoga sessions and space is
reserved for shows by emerging artists.
</P>
<P>
   Products include Hair Wands (temporary hair mascara), Color
Effects (nail polish) and, of course, lipstick that contains
essential oils such as bergamot, used for its antidepressant
effects.
</P>
<P>
   ``The lipsticks are named after positive ways that women feel,''
Tina says. Loved, Connected, Seductive, Centered.
</P>
<P>
   The nail polishes are named for the effect they can have after
being reflected on throughout the day. Detox, a dull navy blue,
cleanses your mind, body and spirit. Focus, a glossy silver white,
opens your cosmic consciousness. And Understanding, a shiny hot
pink, promotes giddiness.
</P>
<P>
   So how do you coordinate lips and nails when you have to
consider color and effect? Don't overthink it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Go with your intuition. Everyone has all the knowledge inside
themselves to guide them,'' says Tina, explaining that your
intuition is connected to your spleen chakra. ``It's not random.
You do have internal instincts that are guiding you.''
</P>
<P>
   All of this is scientifically and culturally based, she says.
``Since the dawn of time we've been affected by color. It's been a
great source of study, theory and mysticism.''
</P>
<P>
   But Tina herself doesn't wear much makeup.
</P>
<P>
   ``I come to it from the consumer point of view. If I'm going to
wear it, it has to be therapeutic for me in some way.''
</P>
<P>
   Staci Sturrock writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla. E-mail: stacisturrock(AT)pbpost.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
