<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991012.0104 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-12 11:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4200 &Cx1f; kan-z
r l BC-FOOD-STYLING-2TAKES-K     10-12 0941
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-STYLING-2TAKES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STYLISTS MAKE FOOD IN PICTURES LOOK GOOD ENOUGH TO EAT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JILL WENDHOLT SILVA  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Delores Custer is feeling a bit jittery.
</P>
<P>
   But it's not the coffee. In the magic world of food styling, the
coffee turns out to be as caffeine-free as a cup of water with a
few drops of Kitchen Bouquet, a food coloring agent.
</P>
<P>
   Custer, a New York-based food stylist, is nervous about an
interview she gave to the New York Times Magazine. A 20-year food
styling veteran who teaches at the Culinary Institute of America,
she rarely gives interviews anymore because food journalists tend
to fixate on the so-called tricks of the trade.
</P>
<P>
   ``They always want to know the tricks,'' she says, ``and I think
everyone has this idea that we work with fake food and we don't
cook the real food.''
</P>
<P>
   Ironically Custer confides her frustrations to members of the
Association of Food Journalists attending a food-styling seminar at
the Disney Institute in Orlando, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're always trying to keep food alive until the photographer
is ready to shoot,'' she says. ``The `tricks' that we do are only
because of time. We all love a natural look, particularly in
editorial.''
</P>
<P>
   So why use colored water as a stand-in for a cup of joe?
</P>
<P>
   The mud-puddle brown hues of real coffee appear black on film.
Not very appetizing.
</P>
<P>
   As one of the most sought-after food stylists in the country,
Custer has clients that include Kraft Foods, Pillsbury, Nestle,
Nabisco, Kellogg's and McDonald's. Some of her recent work can be
seen in Betty Crocker's newest cookbook, the ``I Can't Believe It's
Butter'' ads featuring Fabio and nearly every cereal box in
America.
</P>
<P>
   Yet as a bleary-eyed, bed-headed America faces Custer's work
over its morning cereal bowl, few have even the faintest inkling of
just what it takes to make food look this good.
</P>
<P>
   Style before substance
</P>
<P>
   Like a makeup stylist who can turn a gawky, waiflike model into
a ravishing runway beauty, food styling is all about accentuating
the model's positive attributes.
</P>
<P>
   Good makeup, a hairstylist, a fan for that windblown look and
flattering light only enhance appealing features.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise a smudge of lipstick can give an unripe pear a
rosy-ripe glow. A spritz of glycerine on a waxed glass can make
iced tea appear icy cool with condensation. A dab of vegetable oil
gives asparagus an emerald-green sheen.
</P>
<P>
   Armed with a tackle box of tools including squirt bottles,
tweezers, toothpicks, skewers, eyedroppers, turkey basters,
surgical gauze and cotton swabs, the food stylist primps and prods
the food to an image of perfection.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes that means intentionally undercooking the Thanksgiving
bird so the skin doesn't wrinkle up, then brushing it with Kitchen
Bouquet or Angostura bitters to simulate the browning effect. If it
begins to dry out as it sits on the set, Pam cooking spray can
restore a moist, succulent look.
</P>
<P>
   Such techniques used to be learned on the job or working with
other stylists who already had broken into the business, but these
days, professional development seminars and workshops help food
stylists create a network.
</P>
<P>
   At Food on Film IX, a biannual conference sponsored by the Twin
Cities Home Economists in Business and the International
Association of Culinary Professionals held in Minneapolis, food
stylists, prop stylists, photographers, art directors and the odd
food editor can get a handle on the basic techniques.
</P>
<P>
   Topics include the art of plate composition, how to scout for
props, how to shop for the best produce, tips for working with
chocolate and how to prep for a big job.
</P>
<P>
   Food stylists typically work as part of a team that includes a
prop stylist, a photographer and an art director who conceptualizes
``the look'' they are after based on where the photograph will be
used for advertising or editorial display, print or TV.
</P>
<P>
   ``People always ask me, `Why doesn't my food look that good?' ''
says Marie Piraino, a Boston-based food stylist with credits in
Cooking Light and Eating Well magazines. ``If you had a person
obsessing over every detail of it for four hours, it would look
that good!''
</P>
<P>
   Filling in the missing senses
</P>
<P>
   It's true that we eat with our eyes, but without a sense of
touch, taste or smell, food photography must help the viewer
imagine what their senses are missing.
</P>
<P>
   To illustrate what food stylists can do to create the illusion
of touch, taste and smell, Custer often uses two side-by-side
photos of the same shot to emphasize her point.
</P>
<P>
   The first shot shows fried eggs, English muffins, a bowl of
cereal, a glass of orange juice made from concentrate and coffee
the way a home cook would prepare it.
</P>
<P>
   The second shot includes the exact same items prepared the way a
food stylist might prepare it for a photo shoot:
</P>
<P>
   - Organic eggs, for example, take the place of regular because
they typically contain yokes with a deeper shade of yellow. The
eggs are cooked in oil to keep edges smooth and whites whiter. A
total of six dozen eggs are cracked before the stylist is satisfied
with the spread of the whites.
</P>
<P>
   - A home cook may just lay an orange slice on a plate for
garnish; the food stylist twists it to give it height, which
reflects more light and drips glycerine on it to give the slice a
fresh, dewy look.
</P>
<P>
   - The cereal flakes are handpicked with tweezers. A shallow
amount of milk is used so the flakes can ``stand'' on top, and
drops of ``milk'' made from a denser mixture of confectioners'
sugar and water allow for more control. MORE
</P>
<P>
   (denser mixture of confectioners' sugar and water allow for more
control.)
</P>
<P>
   Fashion plates
</P>
<P>
   As with hemlines in fashion, food styles come and go.
</P>
<P>
   Look at a Betty Crocker cookbook from the '50s, and the layers
of the cakes are perfect, the swirls of frosting a work of art,
each flourish like a series of commas hammered on a typewriter.
</P>
<P>
   Then pick up a copy of Martha Stewart Living. The layers are
slightly crooked. Even something as seemingly pedestrian as
Tupperware is permissible as a prop because it represents a casual
attitude.
</P>
<P>
   ``We try to manipulate the food as little as possible so it
looks as alive as possible,'' says Susan Spungen, food editor for
Martha Stewart Living magazine and a keynote speaker at Food on
Film IX.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there has to be an integrity to the food so I try to
cook as if we will eat it. If it really is good enough to eat, I
think it will look that way in the photo.''
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Trade Commission regulates the way products can be
advertised. Serving portions must be reasonable, and the food can't
be doctored. Perhaps one of the most infamous cases dates from 1969
when Campbell's soup used marbles to help the vegetables in its
Hearty Man Vegetable stew float to the top for a TV commercial.
Such deceptions are not allowed when advertising a product to
consumers, and some food companies keep lawyers on the set to avoid
potential problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's always the desire to make something bigger, better.
You really have to think about it,'' Custer says. ``You should try
to be as true to the consumer as possible. It's not fair when the
food does not look like what we produce.''
</P>
<P>
   Wary of such ethical dilemmas, an advertising shot for a carton
of ice cream would never use fake ice cream. But a shot of an
ice-cream sundae used as a background item in a banquet might be
permissible.
</P>
<P>
   The idea is to enhance and to stretch, but not cheat. And
sometimes it takes nothing more than framing the food so we can see
it the way the camera does.
</P>
<P>
   ``The camera sees food in a different way than we do. It has one
eye. We have two,'' Custer says. ``When a camera looks at that,''
she says, pointing to a salad of lettuce and tomato sitting on a
work table in the classroom//kitchen, ``that's all it sees. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``If we went like that,'' she says, forming a picture frame with
her thumbs and index fingers, ``they'd say, `Wow! Isn't that
beautiful?' ''
</P>
<P>
   The challenges of faking it
</P>
<P>
   By JILL WENDHOLT SILVA
</P>
<P>
   The Kansas City Star
</P>
<P>
   It's a food stylist's nightmare: a ``hero'' that weeps, then
dissolves into a puddle in front of the camera.
</P>
<P>
   Enter the stunt doubles, look-alikes that can cool their pointy
heels on the set for hours without so much as a drip.
</P>
<P>
   Made from a mixture of corn syrup, shortening, confectioners'
sugar and a few drops of food coloring, fake ice cream is
technically edible, if not exactly delectable.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, but how does it look?
</P>
<P>
   After scooping up a dozen perfectly textured mounds, I can vouch
for its authenticity. It is a dead ringer for the real thing.
</P>
<P>
   Photographer Tammy Ljungblad and I recently went into the
kitchen to try our hand at making fake ice cream. We got the recipe
at a food-styling conference.
</P>
<P>
   Our first batch of vanilla ice cream came together in a snap. A
few skirts of Hershey's syrup and we moved on to chocolate. Then we
tried strawberry.
</P>
<P>
   At first the food processor gummed up with a sticky pink ooze.
To turn the soupy muck into a more workable dough required a
mushroom cloud of confectioners' sugar. Instead of the 1-pound box
called for in the recipe, it took 5 to arrive at the right
consistency.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of a frustrating hour of scooping and sculpting, a
dozen Play-dohlike blobs lined the kitchen counter.
</P>
<P>
   From the lineup we picked our ``hero,'' the most photogenic
scoop. A real beaut, our specimen exhibited a nice ``bark''
(textured ridges) and ``ruffles'' (the flounce around the edge
where the scoop mounds onto the cone).
</P>
<P>
   After sorting the pristine cones from the duds, I pressed the
best scoops lightly atop and tiptoed to ``location,'' a
weather-beaten swing on the photographer's porch. Only two stunt
doubles landed creamside-down on the concrete patio.
</P>
<P>
   Using fake ice cream, we had plenty of time to adjust the
lights. But after a few meter readings, the fuse box blew. Even
after repeated trips to the basement, the cones kept their cool.
</P>
<P>
   After taking a couple of Polaroids, we tweaked our composition
and put the image on real film.
</P>
<P>
   Elapsed time: Nearly 5 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Perfect pizza pulls
</P>
<P>
   By JILL WENDHOLT SILVA
</P>
<P>
   The Kansas City Star
</P>
<P>
   Admittedly Judy Peck Prindle's recipe for the perfect pizza
includes a few odd ingredients _ an emery board, a few thumbtacks.
</P>
<P>
   Prindle, a Los Angeles-based food stylist with more than 30
years of experience, specializes in ``cheese pulls.'' That's when a
slice of pizza, taken just so from the whole pie, reveals a drippy
web of luscious melted cheese.
</P>
<P>
   To stylists, pizza and ice cream are the two most temperamental
food groups.
</P>
<P>
   On a location shoot for a national pizza company, Prindle once
spent 10 days prepping hundreds of pizzas. Working from a portable
kitchen hauled in on a semi-truck, she hired four or five
assistants for what turned out to be a 30-second TV ad.
</P>
<P>
   Prindle demonstrated her skills at Food on Film IX, a recent
conference in Minneapolis.
</P>
<P>
   Wearing two pairs of cotton utility gloves (less clumsy than
mitts), she pulls barely cooked pizza crusts from the oven. When
the crusts are cool enough to touch, she begins ``grooming'' them,
using an emery board to sand off rough edges.
</P>
<P>
   On an imperfect pizza crust she spreads a mound of grated cheese
and toasts it to a light brown. After allowing it to cool, she uses
tweezers to remove each crisscrossed ``eyelash.'' Later she'll
reapply them to the rim of the crust to give it more character.
</P>
<P>
   The pepperoni is cooked separately in a 325-degree oven 21/2
minutes, then she blots each slice with paper towels and sprays
them with an antioxidant to prevent curling.
</P>
<P>
   When it's time to construct the pizza, Prindle uses a soft
paintbrush to spread a token amount of sauce on the crust. Then
come the cheese and other toppings, before the pizza is lightly
baked, about 15 minutes in a 400-degree oven.
</P>
<P>
   Prindle had hidden a few thumbtacks under pepperoni circles to
keep the pizza from sliding off its board and a triangular spatula
under a precut piece to ease removing it. She had ``laced'' some
extra slices of cheese to hide the cuts.
</P>
<P>
   For melting the cheeses laces, she uses a clothes steamer. When
the laces look good and gooey, she lets the pizza rest a bit before
pulling the piece up and out, freezing the motion at the moment the
cheese is stretched to quivering.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-12-99 1137EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
