<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIME TO RECLAIM CITY HALL 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROB MORSE  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ How does that political slogan on top of San
Francisco taxicabs go? ``World-class city, world-class mayor, any
questions?''
</P>
<P>
   I have a question. Why does such a beautiful city have such
ugly, vicious, no-class politics? Why would San Franciscans have
any of the so-called major candidates as a mayor? Most people
wouldn't let them walk their dog.
</P>
<P>
   One guy would sell your dog to the highest bidder. Another guy
would kick your dog, later tell you he's reformed and then refer
you to his book on how to walk dogs. The other guy lost your dog
four years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Jordan, Clint Reilly and even Mayor Willie Brown, a
politician so famous he's been on the cover of almost every
magazine in the land, are losers.
</P>
<P>
   These candidates have one character flaw in common. That
character is named Jack Davis. Davis is easily recognizable by his
knowing smile, prematurely platinum hair, the sycophantic political
writers who surround him and the politicians who never turn their
back on him.
</P>
<P>
   At his birthday party a few years ago, our leading political
figures watched sadomasochistic sex acts and Jack Daniels bottles
put to innovative uses.
</P>
<P>
   Davis is the unelected thug-in-chief of San Francisco, famous
for fisticuffs, foul mouth and extracting favors from government, a
man who crushes mayors just for fun.
</P>
<P>
   Davis is the consultant who got Jordan elected mayor in 1991 as
revenge against his enemy, former Mayor Art Agnos. Davis ran City
Hall for a while, then turned on Jordan to help get Brown elected.
Later he ran Brown's winning campaign for a new football
stadium-mall project, which Reilly opposed.
</P>
<P>
   Now Davis is doing a bang-up job for Brown, portraying Reilly as
a man with a history of violence against women.
</P>
<P>
   If the Borgias moved to the hills of West Virginia, they
couldn't come up with nastier and more ingrown feuds.
</P>
<P>
   Davis gives credit where credit is due, complimenting Reilly,
his former mentor as a political consultant. ``He gave me my
start,'' Davis told me not long ago. ``He made this profession what
it is today.''
</P>
<P>
   And they both helped make San Francisco politics the cesspool it
is today.
</P>
<P>
   Consultants became more important than politicians in the early
1980s. The consultants filled a political vacuum, as kingmakers,
king-breakers, high-paid lobbyists for big business and sources for
journalists. And they answered to no one.
</P>
<P>
   Now Reilly has become accountable, much to his personal
discomfort, by running for mayor.
</P>
<P>
   The press bears some responsibility for Davis. The first thing
we can do is stop calling him a ``bad boy political consultant.''
It makes Davis sound cute.
</P>
<P>
   I have to admit, it's interesting to talk to Davis. It's also
interesting to talk to hit men and street bullies. But from now on,
I'll just call him Jack Davis.
</P>
<P>
   We know who's likely to win the Nov. 2 election. Jack Davis,
hands down and dirty. Oh yeah, and Willie Brown.
</P>
<P>
   The other night I was watching television and there was the now-
familiar face of Reilly telling us that in the past he'd had his
problems, but he'd quit drinking in 1981.
</P>
<P>
   No, he wasn't advertising one of those 30-day rehab centers.
This was his way of responding to the Brown campaign's charges that
in 1980 he'd beaten up a female campaign worker, charges packaged
by Davis like a cluster bomb in advertising and even a Web site.
And the mailers haven't even started arriving.
</P>
<P>
   Reilly is a political consultant who now has a fool for a
client. He would have warned any other client to be prepared for
everything in his past to be exposed, but didn't seem ready.
</P>
<P>
   As for Jordan, he got elected in 1991 and made his only splash,
a literal one, at the end of his term. Why would he want to come
back?
</P>
<P>
   The biggest question is one that should have been settled four
years ago. Why hasn't Brown dumped Davis? Brown dominated state
politics from Sacramento. Brown is the boss of a political machine
in a one-party town. He's one politician who shouldn't be afraid of
turning his back on Davis.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Brown likes having Davis around for entertainment value.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Brown likes to set Davis loose on his enemies.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Brown thinks Davis does a good job.
</P>
<P>
   The Brown administration has been one disappointment after
another, and the survival of Davis is one of them.
</P>
<P>
   We've been talking about the unelected rule of Davis for a dozen
years and three mayors. It's time the people took back the city.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-12-99 1218EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
