<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LYNCH-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT EVER HAPPENED TO GEORGE PATAKI? 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN LYNCH  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Since the last election, New York Gov. George
Pataki has turned into the Man Who Never Comes to Dinner. Not long
ago, he got a big raise. Now, apparently, he won't come to work
unless he also gets a signing bonus.
</P>
<P>
   It's safe to assume that George Pataki is not in Albany.
Anything beyond that is guesswork. His staff virtually never puts
out a schedule for him anymore.
</P>
<P>
   The problem seems to be, in the context of New York politics,
that Pataki sees himself in a dead-end job with no room for
advancement. With a presidential election looming, he seems
fanatically devoted to impressing Texas Gov. George W. Bush in
hopes of nailing down the second spot on the Republican ticket. Or,
as a consolation prize, a Washington Cabinet post.
</P>
<P>
   In short, Pataki appears obsessed with the prospect of never
again setting foot in Albany. That's hardly an irrational desire
for a man whose job description requires him to deal with the
sharpies, dolts, dupes and wide-eyed innocents of the New York
Legislature. Still, the governor's obvious passion to escape the
job New Yorkers elected him to can have its drawbacks for other
people.
</P>
<P>
   Consider that political action committee Pataki set up in
Virginia, for example. Much of the $400,000 the committee raised to
promote Pataki's national political ambitions came from
contributors who kicked in more than they could have under New York
state law. And about half that total has come from contributors
with financial interests directly affected by the state government
the governor runs.
</P>
<P>
   Take, for instance, Bell Atlantic, the telephone company. Under
New York law, corporations can give statewide officeholders no more
than $5,000 a year. Individuals can give them no more than $30,500.
Bell Atlantic kicked in $50,000 to the Virginia committee.
</P>
<P>
   That violates no New York or Virginia law, but the money was
donated at a time when Bell Atlantic was seeking permission from
the New York Public Service Commission to offer long-distance
service within this state.
</P>
<P>
   Take Bay Networks. That's a company with a five-year,
$27-million contract to provide New York state with phone
equipment. The contract expires next June. Bay Networks kicked in
$35,000 to the Virginia committee.
</P>
<P>
   And, as just one more example, take Peter Lewis. He's chairman
of an Ohio-based company called Progressive Insurance. He gave the
governor's Virginia committee $25,000 in April. A month before, his
company had applied for a $125,000 state grant to create a new
regional office in downtown Albany. By sheerest coincidence,
apparently, the company got the grant a month after the
contribution was made to the Virginia committee.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Chichester is a former Pataki aide who now runs a private
business that produces an intriguing Web site. It's called
empirepage.com. Chichester says that political loyalty plays a huge
role in deciding which companies benefit from state largess in this
administration.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, Assembly Speaker Sheldon Silver introduced
into the lower house a bill that would force statewide
officeholders to disclose contributors to out-of-state political
committees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every New Yorker,'' the speaker said, ``has the right to know
who is making financial contributions to their elected officials _
wherever the accounts are kept.''
</P>
<P>
   Predictably, the bill passed the Assembly, which is controlled
by Democrats. Predictably, the State Senate, controlled by the
governor's party, failed to pass it.
</P>
<P>
   In and of itself, ambition is not at all a negative trait in a
politician. But ambition without a proper sense of propriety is
different. You have to worry about a politician who'll tell you
that honesty is the best policy.
</P>
<P>
   And then behave as though dishonesty runs a close second.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Lynch is a columnist for the Albany Times Union, P.O. Box
15000, Albany, NY 12212.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
