KANSAS CITY STAR BUDGET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Kansas City Star plans to move the following stories for use
by clients of the NYTimes News Service for AMs and PMs of
Wednesday, Oct. 13. If you have any questions, please call The
Star's News Desk at (816) 234-4720.
</P>
<P>
   FORFEIT. Legislative hearing in St. Louis addresses the Claire
McCaskill report on forfeitures. State Auditor McCaskill also holds
two news conferences. Photo. 30. Karen Dillon.
</P>
<P>
   REPORT (with FORFEIT). A lot of agencies and prosecutors just
stiffed the auditor's office, refusing to return a survey she sent.
9. Karen Dillon.
</P>
<P>
   TAX: We look at the sales tax burden in Kansas City and the
metropolitan area, even nationwide, to see how we stack up. Matt
Campbell. 30. Graphic chart.
</P>
<P>
   KIDS: The Partnership for Children announces its annual report
card. Overall grade stayed the same as last year, at C plus. This
is the first year the grade hasn't gone up, and the lack of
immunizations is responsible. Graphic. Donald Bradley. 15.
</P>
<P>
   EDBD. The Kansas Board of Education meets today to try to figure
out how to rewrite the new science standards, now that three
national science groups have denied their permission to use
copyright materials that formed the basis of the document. Kate
Beem. Photo.
</P>
<P>
   CREME. Creme de la Creme, a new nursery and preschool in
Leawood, Kan., looks like nirvana for little kids. There's the
Beauty and the Beast soundtrack wafting throughout the
21,000-square-foot building, the Trike Autobahn on the manicured
playground outside, the model train rolling around a track near the
ceiling of the faux Victorian streetscape. And that's just the
trappings. Every 30 minutes, preschoolers are moved to a different
activity, from French to math to creative movement. Tuition at
Creme runs almost twice as high as the area average _ it's $12,000
a year for preschoolers _ but satisfied parents say their
children's happiness is worth it. Yet child development experts
warn that high cost does not equal high quality. Kate Beem. Photo.
45.
</P>
<P>
   PRAY. Forced to rescind a new policy allowing school prayer over
the intercom, the Augusta, Kan., school board is now considering a
proposal that would allow a minute of silence in each classroom at
the start of the school day; clearly the question of school prayer
is not settled in this town. John L. Petterson. 25.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS BUDGET OFFERS:
</P>
<P>
   CARE _ A public forum on the ``unintended consequences'' of the
Balanced Budget Act of 1997 on health care providers is being held
by U.S. Rep. Dennis Moore of Kansas at Shawnee Mission Medical
Center Tuesday morning. Julius Karash.
</P>
<P>
   HEASTER _ Jerry Heaster column.
</P>
