<HEADLINE>
BOOKS MAKE HOME DECORATING EASY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By FRANCES INGRAHAM HEINS  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Don't be frustrated at the thought of starting a decorating
project.
</P>
<P>
   If you can read and follow basic instructions, a myriad of
self-help books can guide you through the process of creating or
transforming a room to fit your personal style and needs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Room Redux: The Home Decorating Workbook,'' by designers Joann
Eckstut and Sheran James (1999 Chronicle Books, $29.95), is an
interactive guide to home decorating for real people.
</P>
<P>
   That's also the theme for ``Traditional Home Signature Style:
Creating Beautiful Interiors'' (1999 Meredith Books, $39.95), where
learning the decorating rules allows you to break them, especially
to find your personal decorating style.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our book helps to answer questions, as if we were standing in
the corner of the room,'' said James, a partner with Eckstut in
their hands-on Manhattan-based design service, Room Redux.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people know what they want, but not quite how to get
there,'' James said. ``The book basically answers questions that a
designer asks their client and themselves before beginning a job
and how to go about finding the solutions from there.''
</P>
<P>
   James named the five basic principles to designing a room:
harmony, rhythm, emphasis, scale and balance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once you learn the principles, you can apply them to any
room,'' James said. ``We also designed the book so that you can dip
in and out of it for any reason,'' from selecting fabrics to
placement of furniture, window treatments, color, flooring,
lighting or architectural needs.
</P>
<P>
   The format is a workbook with colorful illustrations by Andras
Halasz. Graph paper and furniture templates re-create your floor
plans, and pockets keep fabric, carpet and wallpaper samples, paint
chips and product information. An extensive and comprehensive
resource index lists places you can call and go that are open even
to people who aren't professional designers. An attached elastic
bookmark also can be used to hold the covers together so you don't
lose any samples.
</P>
<P>
   The book focuses on what it takes to create finished, decorated
rooms.
</P>
<P>
   ``The book is designed to give you the outline of the basic
principles that every designer knows, except that you are in charge
of taking those principles and applying them to your taste,''
Eckstut said. ``There are no deep, dark secrets when it comes to
decorating a room for yourself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Take your time and build a room, furnishing it a little at a
time. All you need is a game plan and know what you are looking
for.''
</P>
<P>
   She explained that each chapter looks at the difficulty and cost
of the projects. ``The nuts and bolts section provides the
practicalities, which are the standards, measurements and kind of
facts you need to make it all happen.''
</P>
<P>
   James stressed that the book allows you to decorate at your own
pace and make it fun.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you preplan each project or room, there won't be so many
surprises and anxiety along the way,'' James said. ``Don't worry
about making mistakes if you do. The biggest mistake is to not
attempt something.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The editors of Traditional Home magazine filled ``Traditional
Home Signature Style: Creating Beautiful Interiors'' with rich
photographs and chapters on each of eight interior designers.
</P>
<P>
   Each chapter includes an in-depth profile of the designer,
including design philosophies and preferences. Divider sections
between chapters, featuring photographs of each designer's
projects, cover key decorating elements _ scale and proportion,
color, fabrics, furniture, antiques, lighting and collections.
</P>
<P>
   ``Find things you love and build around them,'' writes Karol
DeWulf Nickell, editor-in-chief of Traditional Homes. ``Designers
will be the first to tell you that they'd rather not start from
scratch. Their best work is a combination of what you love and what
they know. While fine art, furnishings and rugs provide excellent
jumping off points for an interior, less stately objects such as
collected china or glassware, or a new fabric or wallpaper can also
inspire.''
</P>
<P>
   Most importantly, you need to be honest about what you want,
writes Nickell, and how much time and money you are willing to
commit.
</P>
</TEXT>
