<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRIZE-WINNER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOBEL WINNER WAS TOUTED NINE YEARS AGO AS A TOP CANDIDATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By KEAY DAVIDSON  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Ahmed Zewail, named Tuesday as the winner of the
Nobel Prize for chemistry, was designated nine years ago by a
scientific journal in Philadelphia as a likely winner someday.
</P>
<P>
   The California Institute of Technology scientist won the prize
fnstrating that a rapid laser technique can observe the
motion of atoms in a molecule as they occur during a chemical
reaction.
</P>
<P>
   The Scientist, a highly respected news tabloid that covers
politics and intellectual trends in science, listed Zewail among
``Scientists With the Right Chemistry To Win A Nobel Prize'' in its
Sept. 17, 1990, issue.
</P>
<P>
   In an unusual move, the journal stressed Zewail's eligibility
for the prize although his career violated the basis for most of
the publication's candidates for the prize. The journal forecast
future recipients of the chemistry prize based on a computer survey
of the number of times that their research papers had been cited by
other scientists in the footnotes of articles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Important as (Zewail's) research is, he has not yet garnered a
large enough number of citations to be selected here. It is
conceivable, however, that the Nobel Committee may choose to honor
such a researcher,'' wrote the article's author, Angela Martello.
</P>
<P>
   In most cases, Martello added, ``High citations records and
stellar research careers generally go hand- in-hand,'' evidence
that a scientist's work is noticed by his or her peers.
</P>
<P>
   The journal is published by a Philadelphia firm that uses
computers to track the world's scientific literature.
</P>
<P>
   That same year, Caltech named Zewail to its first Linus Pauling
professorship in chemical physics, named after the famed chemist _
himself a two-time Nobelist, in chemistry and peace _ who later
became a controversial advocate of the medical merits of vitamin C.
</P>
<P>
   In the mid-1970s, Zewail spent two years as an IBM Fellow at
UC-Berkeley.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, in an unusual honor for the esoteric field of
chemical physics _ Zewail's specialty _ Egypt, his native land,
issued two postage stamps in his honor that bear his face. The
stamps come in different currency values.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
