<SLUG> BC-OUTDOORS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REELING IN THE REAL THING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TOM STIENSTRA  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Every time you drop your fishing line, in the
back of your mind is the thought that maybe, just maybe, you might
catch the fish of a lifetime. That is exactly what happened this
past week to Mike Chadwick of Bolinas. But he not only thought it,
he did it.
</P>
<P>
   That hookup came just a few seconds after dropping his line in,
and after a 3 1/2-hour fight, he landed the fish of the year, a
5-foot, 140-pound bluefin tuna, an exotic rarity for the coastal
waters of the San Francisco Bay area. He was aboard the Outer
Limits out of Sausalito, which ventured about 40 miles out to sea
near that 601 Fathom Spot looking for albacore.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right off, it took off on a 250, 300-yard run,'' Chadwick
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just hung on. We didn't even see the fish for 2 1/2 hours.
We finally saw the thing, and everybody was saying, ``It looks like
a submarine.'''
</P>
<P>
   Chadwick, 39, is a union stagehand at the Orpheum Theater in San
Francisco. Three weeks ago, he caught an 82-pound opah, another
rare and exceptional catch for Bay Area waters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been trying to go out on albacore trips twice a week,''
he said. ``You don't have to fly to Mexico, don't have to fly to
Costa Rica. I mean, how can you pass it up, right here close to
home?''
</P>
<P>
   HUGE MIGRATION: As cold weather begins to sweep across Canada,
the annual fall flight of ducks and geese has commenced, with 105
million ducks projected to make the trip south this fall, the
highest number in 50 years in North America.
</P>
<P>
   DFG DELIBERATES: The controversy over Moto Duck, which
introduces powered movement to decoys and is staggering in its
ability to draw ducks down to a marsh, still has not been addressed
with a clear answer by the state Department of Fish and Game,
approval or denial. By law, they are still legal and tens of
thousands of the new invention will be in use in the new season.
</P>
<P>
   WILD WINGS: A wildlife art show featuring color photography of
birds in California opened last week at the visitor center at the
San Francisco Bay Wildlife Refuge, located at the eastern foot of
the Dumbarton Bridge. For information, call 510-792-0222.
</P>
</TEXT>
