<SLUG> BC-QUAKE-PREPAREDNESS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
S.F. EMERGENCY CHIEF PLANS FOR NEXT QUAKE  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ANASTASIA HENDRIX  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Because he runs San Francisco's Office of
Emergency Services, many might guess that Lucien Canton would be
the most prepared of all.
</P>
<P>
   But even Canton, who was a military reservist for the Federal
Emergency Management Agency when the Loma Prieta quake rolled
through the Bay Area in 1989, said the experience had made him
realize he could do better.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like most people, there were things I knew I should do that I
hadn't done, like bracing my bookcases and putting latches on
cabinets,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Canton's family was fortunate that their home was spared any
significant damage, and since it was well-stocked with basic
necessities _ and power was not disconnected _ there was minimal
inconvenience.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the memory of being in Golden Gate Park with his son and
daughter, then aged 4 and 3, that fateful afternoon 10 years ago is
far from forgotten. The force of the quake tossed his son from a
playground slide, and sent other parents rushing with their
children to hover beneath a concrete picnic bench. Canton held his
daughter tight on his lap, describing his own reaction as calm and
``not overly concerned.''
</P>
<P>
   With his son unhurt and his daughter barely fazed, they started
walking home accompanied by the eerie cacophony of wailing car
alarms. The gravity of what had happened sank in when he arrived
and saw the shock on his wife's face, then the TV images of homes
ablaze in the Marina District, fallen freeways and the broken Bay
Bridge.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's when the stress level started climbing through the
roof,'' Canton recalled. ``After I made sure the family was all
right, I came in (to work) right away.''
</P>
<P>
   The dead signals caused a traffic nightmare, so now he keeps a
bubble light _ essentially a portable flashing light that can be
stuck on the roof _ in his car.
</P>
<P>
   He also added basic first aid and emergency kits to both his car
and his wife's. He collected off-season camping gear and other
useful things and stored it together. They did some serious
thinking and came up with a strategy for connecting with their
children if they were away from home or at school.
</P>
<P>
   Their food and water storage is maintained as always _ though he
thinks it's time for another rotation as he mentions this. And yes,
the bookcases and cabinets in their new home have been braced.
</P>
<P>
   Just in case.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-12-99 1328EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
