<DOCNO> NYT19991012.0116 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-12 13:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4263 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e BC-OPERA-BRIDGE-REVIEW-H     10-12 1151
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OPERA-BRIDGE-REVIEW-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE VIEW FROM THIS `BRIDGE' IS SPECTACULAR 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CHARLES WARD 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ William Bolcom's new opera, ``A View From the
Bridge,'' suggested the unthinkable in its premiere: A classic
American play could be better served by a musical reinterpretation.
</P>
<P>
   Commissioned and presented by the Lyric Opera of Chicago,
Bolcom's treatment of Arthur Miller's play offered a remarkable _
even triumphant _ alternative that intensified even further the
tragedy of the longshoreman Eddie Carbone.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL; 
An operatic setting of ``A View From the Bridge`` has substantial
interest to Houstonians.
</P>
<P>
   The opera is the first of three major premieres this season. To
come is John Harbison's ``The Great Gatsby`` at New York's
Metropolitan Opera and Carlisle Floyd's ``Cold Sassy Tree`` for
Houston Grand Opera.
</P>
<P>
   As well, the Alley Theater is offering a highly regarded
production of the play to open its season.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Yet with the story pared to its essentials, and Bolcom's
kaleidoscopic music giving it pungent reinforcement, the opera made
Miller's tale about Eddie's obsession with his niece even more
wrenching to me than in the Alley's fine staging.
</P>
<P>
   Strength was present top to bottom in Bolcom's second work with
the Lyric Opera (his first, ``McTeague,'' premiered in 1992-93).
</P>
<P>
   Led by University of Houston graduate Kim Josephson (Eddie),
Catherine Malfitano (his wife, Beatrice) and Timothy Nolan (the
lawyer Alifieri, who narrates the story), the cast was impeccably
assembled.
</P>
<P>
   Josephson was a fine singing actor, and Malfitano found a role
she fit perfectly. Nolan offered the right mix of emotional horror
and resigned storytelling.
</P>
<P>
   The sleeper success, however, was tenor Gregory Turay as
Beatrice's cousin Rodolfo, who has illegally immigrated from Italy
with his brother Marco.
</P>
<P>
   Miller and Arnold Weinstein produced as fine a compression of
the play as might be wanted. The principle additions _ a Greeklike
chorus to make the play's roots clearer, and an aria for Marco _
only reinforced the pungency. (Weinstein has been Bolcom's
lyricist/collaborator since 1959.)
</P>
<P>
   American conductor Dennis Russell Davies, long a champion of
American music from his bases in Europe, conducted a grand,
sweeping performance. It was melting with lyricism reflecting the
hopes of young people and horrifying with dissonance as Eddie's
obsession becomes more and more destructive.
</P>
<P>
   Director Frank Galati so deftly staged the performance that the
web of domestic dysfunctionality tightened almost imperceptibly and
thus more powerfully.
</P>
<P>
   The sets and costumes of Santo Loquasto, the projections of
Wendall K. Harrington and the lighting of Duane Schuller created an
atmospheric evocation of Brooklyn's Red Hook district in the 1950s.
</P>
<P>
   Girders, walls of old brick and constantly shifting projections
of images from the period established a place where hard manual
labor supported the tough lives of the people in Red Hook.
</P>
<P>
   The projections were the key, shown on three screens. Two large
ones were hung at the stage's left side and rear; the third, a
trapezoid, formed the sharply raked roof of Eddie's house (a
slightly elevated platform, left of center, with a very tall
chimney to hold the roof/screen and a raised bedroom area). When a
viewer paid attention to the projections, the realism was
fascinating.
</P>
<P>
   And, of course, Bolcom's music propelled the maelstrom of
unrecognized and unexpressed emotions that come to the surface as
Eddie's disintegration whirls more and more out of control.
</P>
<P>
   Like much of Bolcom's music, his score for ``A View From the
Bridge`` will be liked or disliked for its rampaging eclecticism.
</P>
<P>
   Eclecticism is something Americans know from the music of, most
notably, Leonard Bernstein, but Bolcom's is far more sweeping in
grasp and deft in execution.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, it so defines Bolcom's style that arguments over it are
really arguments over his style in general and, ultimately, over
the taste of the listener.
</P>
<P>
   In ``View,'' he could move swiftly from an almost outlandish
accompaniment of ``Paper Doll,'' the tune that becomes Rodolfo's
way to provoke Eddie, to the intense but finely modulated
dissonance and rhythm that paced the build of both acts' climax so
effectively.
</P>
<P>
   With his music, Bolcom showed once more how well music can
nonverbally articulate emotional currents and how much more power
words have when reinforced by the music.
</P>
<P>
   The most important aspect of the libretto was how emotional
issues came more emphatically to the forefront through the
compression of scenes and dialogue:
</P>
<P>
   Bea's acute awareness of life around her, particularly the
warped relationship between Eddie and Catherine (sung with girlish
charm and then steely anger by Juliana Rambaldi). The niece's
blindness to the uncle's obsession _ and then her bitterness when
she learns that Eddie betrayed the cousins, including her future
husband, Rodolfo, by anonymously tipping off immigration officers.
</P>
<P>
   Rodolfo's springlike innocence, captured in the aria ``I Love
the Beauty of the View at Home,'' celebrating the glories of New
York City. It is the kind of the hit number composers yearn to
write. Akin to Carlisle Floyd's ``Ain't It a Pretty Night`` from
his ``Susannah,'' it is sure to join the standard repertoire of
lyric tenors.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the depth of Marco's disillusionment, only partly
revealed in the play but brought to thrilling vividness in the aria
Miller added at the request of Bolcom.
</P>
<P>
   In ``To America I sailed on a ship called Hunger,'' so achingly
sung by Mark McCrory, Marco laments how he will have to return to
Italy on the same ship that brought him to the United States. He
will return home with nothing but more misery for his family, whom
he hoped to nurse to a better life through working in America.
</P>
<P>
   How the aria was used was the finest example of the opera's
superb dramaturgy.
</P>
<P>
   Marco sang it in jail, after he has been arrested as an illegal
immigrant. In the play the scene involves a confrontation between
the lawyer Alfieri and Marco over a pledge of good behavior. All
that was jettisoned in favor of a brilliantly executed way to give
voice to Marco's motivation.
</P>
<P>
   Such touches were present throughout the performance and
propelled the audience to offer seemingly genuine enthusiasm for
the work at the performance's conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   How far Bolcom's new opera travels will depend on the resources
of opera companies. Scenically, it easily can be simpler.
Musically, it will require great singers and an excellent orchestra
to plumb the emotional depths of a major addition to American
opera.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Charles Ward can receive electronic mail via the Internet. Address
comments to charles.wardchron.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
