<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOODSTOCK-POLICE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
N.Y. STATE POLICE PENALIZE 12 POLICEMEN FOR WOODSTOCK FROLICKING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ALAN WECHSLER  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Ten New York state troopers and two supervisors
have been suspended for cavorting with nude women during the fiery
riots that closed Woodstock '99, the agency has announced.
</P>
<P>
   In one case, a supervisor was reduced in rank because of his
actions and those of troopers under his charge during the July
show.
</P>
<P>
   More than two months after troopers were accused of posing with
nude women or taking their patrol cars through a topless carwash,
State Police Superintendent James W. McMahon announced their
punishments Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was appalled at the conduct and action of a handful of
troopers who brought discredit to the agency and themselves,''
McMahon said. He also said he was pleased with the conduct of most
of the more than 500 troopers present at the end of the Woodstock
concert.
</P>
<P>
   McMahon had announced the suspension of one of the supervisors
soon after the incident was made known.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 190,000 people came to the mostly peaceful, three-day
concert July 23-25 at the former Griffiss Air Force Base in Rome.
But at the show's end that Sunday night, hundreds of fans set
dozens of fires and caused millions of dollars in damage from
looting, burning and rioting. ndred troopers were called to
the scene to help restore order, a task that wasn't completed until
dawn the next day.
</P>
<P>
   Near the end of the riot, a Syracuse newspaper reporter
witnessed a group of troopers asking two young women, one from
Albany and one from Saratoga Springs, N.Y., to take off their
clothes and pose with them for photographs. The women complied.
</P>
<P>
   When news of the incident made headlines, McMahon ordered an
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   The supervisor on duty was immediately suspended. He later was
the subject of an administrative hearing, which recommended that
the officer receive a one-step reduction in rank and a significant
suspension.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, six troopers voluntarily accepted penalties
consisting of multiple-day suspensions and formal censures.
</P>
<P>
   The investigation also included troopers who paid to have their
patrol cars washed at a topless carwash. Four troopers and one
supervisor were given censures and multiple-day suspensions from
the incident.
</P>
<P>
   State Police refused to provide the names of any of the
officers, saying it was an internal matter, and declined to provide
any more details on the suspensions, which have been completed.
</P>
<P>
   Martha Lefevre, a Saratoga Springs resident and mother of one of
the two women who stripped and posed for the officers, said earlier
this week she was not concerned about whether the troopers involved
would be punished.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a big deal,'' she said. ``(But) when I found out about
the rapes that went on, I just said, `Thank God she wasn't one.'
Thank God she got back OK.''
</P>
<P>
   Four rapes were reported during Woodstock, including one that
allegedly took place in a crowd of slam dancers. Police are still
investigating.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-12-99 1347EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991012.0118 </DOCNO>
