<HEADER>
A4265 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-CHINA-POPULATION-1013     10-12 0821
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-POPULATION-1013-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CHINA VOWS NEW 'LEAP' TO BRING ZERO POPULATION GROWTH
 &HT;    400&AMP;ADD
 &HT;    By JOSEPH ALBRIGHT and MARCIA KUNSTEL 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service (at)
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ On the day world population reached six billion, China
confounded speculation that it might relax its one-child policy for
the next century.
</P>
<P>
   At a meeting Tuesday just off Tiananmen Square, officials of the
world's most populous country pledged a new ``historical leap'' in
birth control with a goal of ending all growth in China's
population by the mid-21st century.
</P>
<P>
   Their objective is to stabilize China's population at about 1.6
billion people in around 2045, by which time India is projected to
be the most populous nation on the globe. Despite China's
long-standing target of just one child per family, its population
still swells at 1 percent a year _ adding 10 million new mouths to
feed annually.
</P>
<P>
   The audience in the Great Hall of the People heard a letter from
Prime Minister Zhu Rongji pledging the support of China's top
communist leadership for ``the whole set of family planning
principles and measures which have long been effective.''
</P>
<P>
   Though the prime minister didn't provide a blueprint of these
ongoing population measures, they include widespread promotion of
IUDs, condoms and abortions, as well as heavy encouragement of
female sterilization especially for Chinese women who have borne a
second child.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any mood of relaxation and blind optimism could lead to a
rebound in our fertility rate and the deterioration of our
population environment,'' said Zhang Weiqing, the director of
China's state family planning commission.
</P>
<P>
   Only a month ago there were headlines in the Financial Times and
other Western publications suggesting that China had decided to
loosen its 20-year-old one-child policy, supposedly because leaders
had concluded that China's once-exploding population was under
control.
</P>
<P>
   But one speaker after another took to the podium Tuesday calling
for China to strive even harder to convince the Chinese masses to
have fewer children in the new millennium.
</P>
<P>
   Liu Peng, the deputy chief for propaganda of the Chinese
Communist Party Central Committee, said every newspaper and
television station in China must run programs to publicize birth
control objectives.
</P>
<P>
   One purpose, he said, is to convince China's 900 million
villagers and small town dwellers that families get rich not by
having more children but ``by science and technology and working
hard.''
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Begin optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   During the 1950s and 1960s Chinese couples often had six and
seven children during times when healthcare was improving. The
resulting population surge left China's leaders alarmed at
prospects of coping with demands for food, housing and jobs. In the
early 1970s China adopted a
</P>
<P>
   cautious population control policy of marrying late and having
fewer babies under the slogan ``late, spaced and fewer.''
</P>
<P>
   Fertility dropped, but not enough to satisfy the policymakers.
So in 1979 China adopted the ``one-child'' policy that mandated
most families have a single child, meting punishment in the form of
fines, job discrimination and community ostracism against those who
failed to comply.
</P>
<P>
   In some villages where local family planning officials were
exceptionally zealous in fulfilling quotas for low birth numbers,
women were coerced into being sterilized or even having late-term
abortions.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   The one-child policy has not been universal. The minority ethnic
groups that make up 5 percent of China's population have generally
been allowed two or more children per family, for example.
</P>
<P>
   And in many provinces, rural families have been governed by a de
facto ``one-son'' policy in recent years. If a couple gives birth
to a girl, they have another chance to create the son considered so
important to peasant farmers.
</P>
<P>
   The result has been that rural families having a girl first will
continue trying for a boy, resorting to sex-selective abortions
when ultra-sound scans indicate a female fetus. Several provinces
are trying to enforce prohibitions against the use of ultra-sound
for sex identification, partly because in some locales it has
dramatically skewed the male-female
</P>
<P>
   population ratio.
</P>
<P>
   Sex-selection abortions are less prevalent in cities. Urban
families have continued to be under heavier pressure to stick with
the one-child policy, yet have become somewhat more accepting of
girl children.
</P>
<P>
   While birth control has been almost exclusively an issue for
married couples, singles are beginning to be targeted as well for
purposes of both health and population. In major cities, especially
around university campuses, condom machines have appeared just in
the last few months.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-12-99 1348EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991012.0119 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-12 13:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4266 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-CHINA-POPULATION-1013     10-12 0821
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-POPULATION-1013-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CHINA VOWS NEW 'LEAP' TO BRING ZERO POPULATION GROWTH
 &HT;    400&AMP;ADD
 &HT;    By JOSEPH ALBRIGHT and MARCIA KUNSTEL 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service (at)
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ On the day world population reached six billion, China
confounded speculation that it might relax its one-child policy for
the next century.
</P>
<P>
   At a meeting Tuesday just off Tiananmen Square, officials of the
world's most populous country pledged a new ``historical leap'' in
birth control with a goal of ending all growth in China's
population by the mid-21st century.
</P>
<P>
