hard.''
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Begin optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   During the 1950s and 1960s Chinese couples often had six and
seven children during times when healthcare was improving. The
resulting population surge left China's leaders alarmed at
prospects of coping with demands for food, housing and jobs. In the
early 1970s China adopted a
</P>
<P>
   cautious population control policy of marrying late and having
fewer babies under the slogan ``late, spaced and fewer.''
</P>
<P>
   Fertility dropped, but not enough to satisfy the policymakers.
So in 1979 China adopted the ``one-child'' policy that mandated
most families have a single child, meting punishment in the form of
fines, job discrimination and community ostracism against those who
failed to comply.
</P>
<P>
   In some villages where local family planning officials were
exceptionally zealous in fulfilling quotas for low birth numbers,
women were coerced into being sterilized or even having late-term
abortions.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   The one-child policy has not been universal. The minority ethnic
groups that make up 5 percent of China's population have generally
been allowed two or more children per family, for example.
</P>
<P>
   And in many provinces, rural families have been governed by a de
facto ``one-son'' policy in recent years. If a couple gives birth
to a girl, they have another chance to create the son considered so
important to peasant farmers.
</P>
<P>
   The result has been that rural families having a girl first will
continue trying for a boy, resorting to sex-selective abortions
when ultra-sound scans indicate a female fetus. Several provinces
are trying to enforce prohibagainst the use of ultra-sound
for sex identification, partly because in some locales it has
dramatically skewed the male-female
</P>
<P>
   population ratio.
</P>
<P>
   Sex-selection abortions are less prevalent in cities. Urban
famile continued to be under heavier pressure to stick with
the one-child policy, yet have become somewhat more accepting of
girl children.
</P>
<P>
   While birth control has been almost exclusively an issue for
married couples, singles are beginning to be targeted as well for
purposes of both health and population. In major cities, especially
around university campuses, condom machines have appeared just in
the last few months.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
