<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   COURT-NICHOLS (Washington) _ The Supreme Court rejects an appeal
by Terry Nichols, convicted in the 1995 Oklahoma City bombing that
killed 168 people and injured hundreds more. The action means that
his conviction stands, and he must serve his life sentence. In his
appeal, Nichols had argued that his federal conviction for
conspiring to use weapons of mass destruction should be overturned
because he never intended to hurt anyone. By MARK HELM.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington)_ With the official embrace of the
AFL-CIO, the scary roller-coaster that is the campaign of Vice
President Al Gore now moves up. But with Bill Bradley closing in on
him, Gore's momentum is sure to dip again before the ride is over.
My money is still on Gore to get the Democratic nomination, but
he's having to work for it. By MARIANNE MEANS.
</P>
