<DOCNO> NYT19991012.0125 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-12 14:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4275 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-PUTIN-BOS &LR;      10-12 0877
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-PUTIN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH YELTSIN AILING, PRIME MINISTER STEPS UP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID FILIPOV  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Russian Prime Minister Vladimir Putin still wears the
perpetually bland expression only a former KGB spy such as he could
love. But in two short months, that unsmiling countenance has
become the universally recognized face of Kremlin leadership.
</P>
<P>
   Virtually unknown to Russians when President Boris N. Yeltsin
appointed him in August, Putin has gone from nowhere to everywhere.
He has emerged as the Kremlin's point man on the fight against
terrorism and the de facto commander in chief in the war against
separatist militants in the North Caucasus.
</P>
<P>
   He has shown that he is that rare Moscow politician who can
create consensus in Russian society and among the country's warring
factions.
</P>
<P>
   When Yeltsin was hospitalized recently with what the Kremlin
described as a case of the flu, Russians wondered whether his
designated successor would take over sooner than anybody thought.
Putin is suddenly the man of the moment.
</P>
<P>
   Putin for president? When Yeltsin named Putin in August, it
seemed highly improbable that an obscure career intelligence
officer with minimal political experience could overtake the
favorites by next summer's presidential vote.
</P>
<P>
   The idea does not seem so far-fetched. Opinion polls released
last week show Putin in third place with the support of about 15
percent of voters. That is up from less than 1 percent just a month
ago, but more importantly, only a few percentage points behind the
current front-runners, former Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov and
Communist leader Gennady Zyuganov.
</P>
<P>
   The main source of this newfound popularity is Putin's leading
role in Russia's latest campaign to crush Islamic rebels in
Chechnya, whom he blames for a deadly wave of apartment bombs last
month. If the army's efforts collapse amid heavy losses, as some
analysts fear they might, Putin's political star may plummet as
quickly as it has risen.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Putin has been able to project the image of a competent
military gradually establishing control in Chechnya. On Sunday,
Putin said Russian troops intended to expand the security zone they
were setting up in the north of the separatist region.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goal is to eliminate all bandit formations and absolutely
exclude any conditions for their revival,'' Putin said in an
interview aired on Russian television.
</P>
<P>
   Putin's tough talk and equally resolute action have appealed to
Russian voters who are fed up with their leaders' inability to
protect them from crime and violence. Now more than 50 percent of
Russians approve of the job Putin's government is doing.
</P>
<P>
   Putin's rise has no doubt been aided by the powerful Kremlin
coterie known here as The Family, who need a friendly candidate to
win the next election to protect the wealth they have accumulated
over the past eight years of Yeltsin's presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Putin has skillfully built on the advantages he has been handed.
Not satisfied with favorable coverage on Kremlin-controlled
television, Putin has set up a single press center that gives the
official line on Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   Aware that no serious political contenders could criticize his
Caucasus policy given the current public mood, Putin met with four
former premiers, all of whom lead rival electoral blocs, to win
their public backing on his Caucasus policies.
</P>
<P>
   Mindful that the poor state of the military helped bring about
defeat in the 1994-1996 war in Chechnya, Putin has courted the
generals by promising $1 billion in new spending and vowing to
update the country's security doctrine.
</P>
<P>
   This is a very presidential way for the prime minister to be
acting. Some have questioned whether The Family is preparing for
Yeltsin to step down early to help clear the way for Putin.
</P>
<P>
   The Kremlin has denied such talk, and Monday said that Yeltsin
was feeling better. But Yeltsin, 68, has rarely looked healthy
since undergoing major heart surgery in 1996. As Yevgeny Kiselyov,
host of the weekly television news program Itogi, put it, ``no one
believes in talk about the latest flu.''
</P>
<P>
   Kiselyov argued that Yeltsin should hand over his powers to his
prime minister. More than 90 percent of 16,500 viewers who took
part in a phone poll agreed.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin, notoriously jealous of his power, has not made any
formal transfer of duties. But lately, Yeltsin has rarely been seen
or heard from.
</P>
<P>
   Putin was the one who promised Russian troops would beat back an
incursion of Chechen-led rebels into the southern republic of
Dagestan in August and September. Putin then announced that Russian
troops would pursue the rebels into Chechnya. It was Putin who
linked the bombs in Moscow with Chechen rebels. And Putin promised
that if ``we catch them in the toilet, we will rub them out in the
outhouse.''
</P>
<P>
   While Russian airstrikes have caused heavy civilian casualities
in Chechnya, the military has so far moved more cautiously in an
effort to prevent a repeat of the heavy losses it suffered in the
last campaign. And the Russian media has so far played down the
setbacks the military has suffered.
</P>
<P>
   The main problem for Putin now is how to keep it that way.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
