<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-12 14:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4283 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-RESCUE-TEAM-BOS &LR;      10-12 1140
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RESCUE-TEAM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
US DISASTER RELIEF TEAMS GO GLOBAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SHARON MOSHAVI  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dean Tills, a 38-year-old structural engineer with graying
sideburns and oval wire-rimmed glasses, looks like a man who
belongs behind a desk. Most days, that's where he is, sitting in
his ergonomic chair and helping design office buildings and parking
garages.
</P>
<P>
   Lately, things have been different. Tills flew halfway around
the world to climb over twisted concrete and into crumpled
buildings, looking for survivors of the massive earthquake that
shook Taiwan in September and killed more than 2,000.
</P>
<P>
   Other newfound colleagues, including firefighters, medics,
seismic-device operators, and sniffer-dog handlers, have been
speeding around the globe in recent weeks to help Taiwan and
Turkey, which was struck by an even deadlier earthquake in August.
They were on alert last week when another big earthquake, measuring
7.5 on the Richter scale, rocked southern Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   To Tills, the work is certainly more dangerous _ but more
stimulating _ than the office grind. ``The blood starts pumping and
the heart really goes,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Tills's education in disaster is rooted in being a volunteer
with the Fairfax County, Va., Fire and Rescue Department, a
100-member international disaster relief team and one of only two
such units that Washington sends worldwide when catastrophe
strikes.
</P>
<P>
   Most team members are professional firefighters and medics who
take a break from fighting northern Virginia blazes when disaster
strikes the globe. They are an elite, specially-trained unit that
operates seismic devices and telescopic cameras.
</P>
<P>
   The unit includes skilled members who volunteer, like Tills,
such as doctors, engineers, and canine handlers with their house
pets-turned-sniffer-dogs.
</P>
<P>
   The Fairfax team has been busy lately. It spent four days of
round-the-clock rescue work in Taiwan. In August, most of its
members were in Turkey, trying to find survivors of the earthquake
in which an estimated 15,000 were killed.
</P>
<P>
   That was Tills's first quake. At one point, he crawled through a
tunnel carved beneath a crumbled structure, trying to determine the
best way to rescue survivors without causing the building to come
down on their heads.
</P>
<P>
   ``I realized that here I was, sandwiched underneath this
building, and one little aftershock and I would be gone,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Five years ago, he saw an ad that the Fairfax department had
placed looking for engineers. Why did he answer it? The need for a
little excitement in his life, he admits, plus an altruistic streak
he says he inherited from his father, a former chief operating
officer for the American Red Cross.
</P>
<P>
   Now Tills doesn't want to stop, much to the dismay of his wife.
Including the two quakes, he's been along with the rescue team for
a hurricane and the Oklahoma City bombing. ``It's in my blood
now,'' he said, as the unit prepared to head home from Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   That's a feeling echoed by many of his colleagues, who say they
are motivated by empathy and adrenalin. ``Going into some of these
buildings no one in his right mind would go into and knowing that
any moment it could be lights out, there's a sense of energy that's
indefinable,'' said Lieutenant Gerry Morrison, a rescue squad
officer.
</P>
<P>
   Or as one rescuer put it, ``Mechanics like it when cars break
down, don't they?''
</P>
<P>
   Six hours after the quake measuring 7.6 on the Richter scale
struck Taiwan, the Fairfax County's 19-person advance team left on
a charter flight, stopping to refuel in Seattle, Anchorage, and
Siberia.
</P>
<P>
   A few hours later came the rest of the team on a C-5A military
aircraft: 72 rescuers, 70,000 pounds of equipment, and three
tractor-trailers. Within 36 hours, the US team was struggling to
find survivors in a 16-story Taiwanese building tilted at a
30-degree angle, and whose bottom five stories had plummeted
underground.
</P>
<P>
   It took the American rescuers eight hours to pull out a
32-year-old man trapped in a hole 20 feet below ground on what had
been the third floor of the building. He was hanging upside down,
his right leg trapped under debris.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Joseph Barbera, a rescue team volunteer and emergency
physician at George Washington University Hospital, wedged into the
hole along with two rescue specialists. Barbera medicated the man
and inserted two intravenous drips to stem dehydration.
</P>
<P>
   Then, he advised rescuers on how to chip away at the concrete
without damaging the leg. ``Succeeding to help someone who is
entombed and slowly dying is a great feeling,'' said Barbera.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Turkey, where the US team saved countless lives, in
Taiwan members recovered just the one man. Rescuers said the nature
of the buildings' collapse made it more difficult to find
survivors. Also, not as many people were trapped as in Turkey.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the best technical search team in the world,'' said
Dick Owens, team leader of the US Agency for International
Development, which contracts out to Fairfax County for its
international rescue service. Thirty-two rescue teams from 18
countries went to Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   Fairfax's techniques ranged from high-tech to low-tech, from man
to beast.
</P>
<P>
   ``What makes a good rescue dog is social skills. He's got to
love people, and have a good temperament,'' said retired
veterinarian Brooke Holt, who has been taking her 10-year-old
mixed-breed Leni on missions for nearly a decade.
</P>
<P>
   In Taiwan, Holt sent Leni into a collapsed building through a
window, and directed him through the area by verbal command. When
it was deemed safe enough, she followed him in.
</P>
<P>
   The United States' role in international disaster relief began
after the 1986 Mexico quake. Back then, the Dade County, Fla.,
department sent a few firefighters to help out. That made the US
government realize that it wanted an effective international
disaster unit.
</P>
<P>
   Since then both Fairfax and Dade formed rescue units, which are
the only two certified by the US government for overseas work.
Fairfax was able to develop an independent rescue unit because of
its large size _ 1,300 firefighters _ and its convenience to air
force bases and authorities in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The group has handled disasters manmade and natural: from
bombings in Nairobi and Oklahoma City to quakes in Armenia and
Columbia. ``We've never had a death or a serious injury,'' said
Captain Michael Reilly.
</P>
<P>
   After each mission, the group engages in a critique, trying to
figure out which methods worked and which didn't. As the group met
in a hotel outside Taipei, most of the rescue team members showed
no outward signs of fatigue.
</P>
<P>
   ``The adrenalin is still high,'' said medical specialist Lorenzo
Thrower. ``If something else hits, we're ready right now. Our
trucks are loaded.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-12-99 1413EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
