<HEADER>
A4289 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-HARVARD-RELATIONS-BOS     10-12 1567
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HARVARD-RELATIONS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARVARD STARTS MENDING FENCES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KATE ZERNIKE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMBRIDGE, Mass. _ At a reception earlier this year, Harvard
president Neil Rudenstine celebrated the appointment of the
university's new chief emissary to the world outside its gates.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Grogan, the appointee, spent 10 years at Boston City Hall
working for mayors Kevin H. White and Raymond L. Flynn and another
12 years in urban development, and he knew many in the crowd of
community activists and city officials at the reception. Some were
still smarting from Harvard's secret purchase of 52 acres in the
Allston section of Boston, assembled over nearly a decade before
the university disclosed it two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Grogan began by saying he was touched that people had welcomed
him by saying that the secret purchases ``wouldn't have happened if
you were here.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The truth is,'' Grogan said, breaking into a grin, ``if I'd
been here, we would have gotten a hundred acres.''
</P>
<P>
   The audience laughed, taking it for the joke it was. Still, it
had a ring of truth.
</P>
<P>
   By their own account, Harvard's top administrators have embarked
on an aggressive campaign to prove that the university is a good
neighbor to what it now deferentially refers to as its ``host
cities.'' Harvard officials would like to show Boston and Cambridge
that it is not, in Grogan's words, ``the Kremlin on the Charles.''
</P>
<P>
   In doing so, they want to avoid another public relations fiasco
like the one the secret Allston purchases triggered. They also hope
that improved relations will smooth the path to more development,
as the world's richest university looks to grow into the next
century.
</P>
<P>
   Harvard officials estimate they will spend $1.1 billion on
construction projects over the next five years, particularly as
they look to enhance offerings in the sciences and at the business
school. To them, the logical site for expansion is across the
river, in Boston. Of the university's 444 acres, slightly more than
half are in Boston, although much of that is already developed.
</P>
<P>
   While many urban universities have thrown themselves into
rehabilitating their surrounding communities over the last few
years, Harvard has remained largely aloof, at least by reputation.
As Boston Mayor Thomas M. Menino singsonged in mimicking what he
called the arrogance of the 1997 Allston purchase, ``We're from
Hahvahd, and we're going to do what we want.''
</P>
<P>
   University officials say they have always done good works in the
community, but they have simply done them quietly. Now, however,
they have new interest in publicizing them. As the university looks
to develop, better relations aren't just a nicety; they're a
necessity.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the only time we're talking to people in public life is
when we have a transaction, chances are we're going to have
problems,'' Grogan said. ``On the other hand, if you're doing lots
of things together, you can deal with the stream of specific
transactions in a better context.''
</P>
<P>
   So if what Allston residents called the land grab marked the low
point in town-gown relations, the last few weeks have seen a
remarkable attempt at reconciliation.
</P>
<P>
   First, Harvard announced it would pay the city of Boston $40
million in lieu of taxes over the next 20 years, payments that
Grogan had sought when he was in City Hall and a 45 percent
increase over what the university has been paying. It also agreed
to build 288 units of graduate-student housing in Allston, which
the mayor had sought to ease the tight rental market. Then Harvard
turned over 775 units of affordable housing to residents of
Boston's Mission Hill section, where it had acquired land through
eminent domain in 1969.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, Rudenstine spoke to the Greater Boston Chamber of
Commerce, touting the $2 billion in economic benefits Harvard
provides to Boston and Cambridge, which were detailed in the
release of a 70-page report. Officials say that in the next few
months there will be an announcement of another initiative to help
the city, with ``significant university resources'' behind it.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past it's been, `I'm Harvard; don't bother me.' I think
you've seen that change,'' said Menino, who warmly introduced
Rudenstine at the chamber luncheon. ``They're still Harvard, but
they understand this is a different era. If they want to do
anything with that land, they have to be more involved. And they
want to help.
</P>
<P>
   ``I welcome that, I'm not cynical about it,'' the mayor added.
</P>
<P>
   In fairness, Harvard hasn't entirely deserved the reputation as
a bad neighbor. Paul Guzzi, head of the chamber of commerce,
recalls working at a boys club in Boston in his own days as a
Harvard undergraduate. It was just one of hundreds of
community-service programs operated by college students each year.
In Cambridge, the school decided without fanfare not to build any
more high rises in Harvard Square, to preserve the neighborhood
atmosphere, Rudenstine said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the perception stuck. In part, it was natural in a
class-conscious city that a 350-year-old university would be seen
as elitist.
</P>
<P>
   Grogan acknowledges buying into that image himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not very flattering to remember that period,'' Grogan
said of his own days in City Hall in the 1970s. ``We had an
undeveloped relationship, a very narrow conception of all these
institutions. We took them for granted in all sorts of ways. It was
the Proposition 2 1/2 era of strangling the city's revenues, and we
were fond of pointing out how much tax-exempt properties the
universities had. We viewed Harvard as particularly remote.''
</P>
<P>
   After the Allston purchase was disclosed, Menino complained that
Harvard had not done enough to provide scholarships for Boston
students. The mayor tried unsuccessfully to use increased
scholarships as a condition for Harvard's completion of new
construction on the business school and an athletic complex in
Allston.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't the way to go about a land acquisition,'' Guzzi said
recently. ``But that was just part of the bigger issue.''
</P>
<P>
   It may also have been the catalyst to better relations.
</P>
<P>
   The most obvious improvement was the choice of Grogan in April
as vice president of government, community, and public affairs. He
was picked for the post while serving as head of a low-cost housing
initiative in Washington and New York.
</P>
<P>
   Grogan replaced Jim Rowe, who had been well connected in
Washington, reflecting what Harvard then saw as its most important
outside link.
</P>
<P>
   Now the focus is closer to home. To maintain the excellence at
Harvard, and the recent record-setting $2.325 billion fund-raising
is said to be dedicated to that goal, the university will have to
build.
</P>
<P>
   ``This really came out of a sense of things being tight in
Cambridge,'' Rudenstine said. ``Considering the constraints in
Cambridge, we have to look to Boston, and it makes sense that we
just have to have someone whose experience is more in that area.''
</P>
<P>
   Other universities have periodically put out reports documenting
their economic impact on the surrounding community. Harvard had
never done done so until this year. Grogan called news outlets the
weekend before it was released, trying to make sure it was well
publicized.
</P>
<P>
   Other universities are far ahead of Harvard in paying attention
to their host cities. Trinity College in Hartford, Yale in New
Haven, and the University of Pennsylvania in Philadelphia have all
engineered major rehabilitations of run-down neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   Grogan argues that those schools were forced to do more.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just didn't have reason to do it before,'' he said. ``Those
areas are in very serious distress. We have just the opposite. We
have a very attractive city around us. Neil feels very strongly
that, instead of taking that for granted, we should be investing in
it affirmatively.''
</P>
<P>
   Some community activists say the push is showing signs of
working. In Allston, residents have been working on a Harvard task
force to shape the new development. They say they appreciate that
the business school has paid attention to their request that its
new buildings face Allston, instead of treating it as the backyard.
</P>
<P>
   ``People aren't so much angry anymore, but they're
apprehensive,'' said Boston City Councilor Brian J. Honan, who
represents Allston. ``They're the largest landlord. Their endowment
and political power make them intimidating.''
</P>
<P>
   Residents say they want more information from Harvard,
particularly on what it intends to do with a 12-acre site and
another 5-acre site near the business school.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if they are waiting for a certain period of time, they
have to have some idea of what they're going to do,'' Honan said.
``How long can a person sit on a piece of property and not develop
it?''
</P>
<P>
   Personal relations mean a lot, however, and Honan is among those
who believe that Grogan's arrival marks an improvement in public
and community relations.
</P>
<P>
   Harvard officials insist that the increased public relations
effort isn't just for show.
</P>
<P>
   ``People ask me, `What's the purpose of all this?' '' McCluskey
said. ``It could be viewed as sort of a reminder, to ourselves and
to others. It's not just to say, `Look how valuable Harvard is,'
but to recognize that we have a continued responsibility to play a
constructive role in the future.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
