<SLUG> BC-LANGUAGE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORTHCOMING, A FORTHRIGHT SOLUTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAN FREEMAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   All over the usage map there are small but dedicated bands of
resisters fending off new usages _ the bad, the ugly, sometimes
even the good and useful. John S. Wollam of Falmouth speaks for one
such group when he protests ``the use of forthcoming when the
obvious intent is to convey the concept of forthright.''
</P>
<P>
   Forthcoming in the sense Wollam dislikes _ ``open, honest,
generous with information'' _ has been gaining on us in the past
few decades, it's true. And it got a big boost from diplomats and
politicians _ as when President Carter described the Soviet Union
as ``very forthcoming and cooperative'' _ which doesn't help the
word's image among defenders of the good old days.
</P>
<P>
   But forthcoming is not merely a ``common misuse of the English
language,'' as Wollam believes. For one thing, it's got history on
its side: The first recorded use is dated 1835, and forthcomingness
is found even earlier, in 1808. It didn't cross the Atlantic till
much later, though, and even today, after more than two decades of
regular use in print here, forthcoming still gets a ``Chiefly
Brit.'' tag in some dictionaries. But the membrane separating
British and American English has more holes in it every day, and it
seems unlikely that the pols and show-biz reporters so enamored of
forthcoming are hearing it as a British idiom.
</P>
<P>
   Is forthcoming an unnecessary synonym for forthright? I think
there are subtle differences, especially once we move beyond the
coded language of diplomacy. An interviewee could be forthcoming _
weeping, emoting, revealing gruesome details of past addictions and
transgressions _ while still being deceptive, intentionally or not.
Forthright connotes directness and honesty, while forthcoming
expresses more about an attitude _ the willingness to talk _ than
about the accuracy of what's said. That may mean it's a fuzzy word,
all too suitable for a culture of fuzzy communicators, but even the
fuzziness is part of its meaning.
</P>
<P>
   Another objection to forthcoming is the possibility of
confusion, since the older forthcoming, meaning ``about to
appear,'' is still in daily use. ``Her forthcoming novel is
charming,'' we could say, ``but she's not at all forthcoming
herself.'' But there aren't a lot of contexts where either meaning
would fit, and as English-usage potholes go, this one seems easily
avoidable. If obsessing about usage is your hobby _ and why
shouldn't it be? _ there are more deserving targets.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Was it a semicolon for you, too?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The new wedding night, wrote Asra Q. Nomani in Thursday's Wall
Street Journal, is more likely to be an all-night party than an
intimate revelation: With couples marrying older, living together
before the wedding, and often paying for the festivities
themselves, they want to enjoy the reception, not tiptoe off to the
bridal suite while their friends are still carousing.
</P>
<P>
   Clear enough, so far. But then Nomani sums it up this way:
``Sex, when it happens, is often an apostrophe, not an exclamation
point.''
</P>
<P>
   An apostrophe?
</P>
<P>
   It's not that the punctuation analogy is necessarily hard to
follow. For instance, a gentleman I know was quoted as saying that
after prostate surgery, sex was ``a period, not an exclamation
point.'' A period, in the nuptials story, would have implied _ you
should pardon the expression _ an anticlimactic ending to the big
night.
</P>
<P>
   Or it could have been a comma, a brief pause after which the
happy couple rejoined the wedding guests; and if the dalliance
lasted more than briefly, but remained an interlude between
partying and more partying, a semicolon would be appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   But apostrophe?
</P>
<P>
   As a punctuation mark, of course, it indicates something left
out _ the missing letters in rock 'n' roll or ne'er-do-well _ but
that meaning only works if there's no sex at all; it doesn't fit
``sex, when it happens, is often an apostrophe.''
</P>
<P>
   There's also apostrophe in the rhetorical/dramatic sense _ an
abrupt digression into exclamatory speech, as in Romeo's ``But
soft! What light through yonder window breaks? It is the east, and
Juliet is the sun.'' But however suitable this might be on
sentimental grounds, it doesn't fit the sense _ unless the author
is trying to say that the modern wedding night is all talk and no
action. At press time, Nomani hadn't returned my phone calls, but I
hope the mystery will be solved by next week. In the meantime,
hypotheses are invited, with or without proper punctuation.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Jan Freeman's e-mail address is freeman(at)globe.com; write to her
at The Boston Globe, PO Box 2378, Boston, MA 02107-2378. Please
include a hometown and phone number.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
