<HEADER>
A4292 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-COLUMN-POP-BOS &LR;      10-12 0753
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLUMN-POP-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ESCAPING FROM A `WASTELAND' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RENEE GRAHAM  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   So where are the protests? The calls for a boycott? All the
fist-shaking and finger-pointing? Where's the National Association
for the Advancement of Colored People when you really need them to
lift up their voices and scream?
</P>
<P>
   Someone, somewhere needs to make some unholy noises about this
still-nascent television season, the same one that had the NAACP
and the National Council of La Raza all in a twist during the
summer. You may remember that several such groups, as well as many
TV critics, were thoroughly upset that out of more than two dozen
new shows on the four major networks _ ABC, CBS, NBC, and Fox _
none featured a lead actor or actress of color. And most didn't
have any black, Asian, or Latino characters at all. NAACP President
Kweisi Mfume branded the fall season ``a virtual whitewash in
programming.''
</P>
<P>
   With Hollywood TV execs feeling scorched, several of them
hastily added actors of color to their shows. One of the first was
``Wasteland,'' ABC's hourlong ode to Pretty White People with
Problems. Show creator Kevin Williamson, who said his ``eyes have
been opened a little bit wider'' after irate groups even evoked the
dreaded ``R'' word, brought in Jeffrey D. Sams, a black actor, to
diversify his cast.
</P>
<P>
   And that's the problem. What with all our righteous indignation,
perhaps we failed to consider that TV types might have been doing
people of color a big fat favor with a slate of shows featuring few
black or brown faces. Now we have to endure the sight of Sams, a
smart actor who costarred on last year's far superior and quickly
canceled ``Cupid'' (also on ABC), on the absolute worst show of the
season.
</P>
<P>
   This is progress?
</P>
<P>
   So I'm calling for a protest, a boycott, or anything. Let's
rally the troops, leaflet the studios, and plead our case to Steve
Kmetko or Mary Hart. If all that tub-thumping could get a black
actor on ``Wasteland,'' then we need another mighty effort to get
him off before his career is ruined.
</P>
<P>
   Random thoughts: If Creed is the best that guitar-driven rock
has left to offer, then maybe someone should pull the plug on rock
'n' roll. Less than a decade after Nirvana kick-started a
revolution, this very photogenic Florida quartet is riding high on
some of the most shamelessly derivative and generic rock in recent
memory. They're the Backstreet Boys with instruments, 'NSync with
more tattoos. At best, their songs have all the flair of a
Soundgarden or Pearl Jam cover band. Still, their sophomore effort,
``Human Clay,'' managed to debut in the No. 1 slot on this week's
Billboard 200. Yikes.
</P>
<P>
   And speaking of sophomore efforts, what happened to Missy
``Misdemeanor'' Elliott's ``Da Real World''? After the runaway
commercial and critical success of her 1997 debut, ``Supa Dupa
Fly,'' her follow-up was one of the most anticipated of the year.
But it never caught fire and dropped out of sight like a stone.
With such a reception, the title of one of her songs, ``She's a
Bitch,'' would also be an apt description of fan loyalty.
</P>
<P>
   What in the name of Steven Patrick Morrissey is the Smiths'
``How Soon Is Now'' doing in a Nissan car commercial? Sure, we're
long past the days when jaws dropped after the Beatles'
``Revolution'' was used to sell sneakers. Now just about every
commercial employs popular music as a hook, such as the zombie-like
models in a current Gap ad singing a monotone rendition of Depeche
Mode's ``Just Can't Get Enough.'' Obviously no one is immune to
this lucrative bandwagon _ save for R.E.M., who said no to Bill
Gates when he wanted to use ``It's the End of the World As We Know
It (And I Feel Fine) to launch Windows 95. Still, there's something
particularly jarring about the Smiths, who disbanded in the 1980s,
hopping on-board. Their witty, wordy songs were so uncommercial (at
least by American standards), they became arguably the best British
band never to break big stateside. Although they've long enjoyed a
devoted cult following, in their time they never even mustered a
top 20 hit.
</P>
<P>
   Now I'm not saying artists shouldn't make as much money as
possible from their music, especially with the industry's long
history of ripping off musicians. But I can't help but feel
disheartened every time I hear Johnny Marr's trembling guitar, the
distinct intro to this naked, aching lament for love, used to
peddle a family sedan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
