<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-PATAGONIA-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATAGONIA ON HORSEBACK 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TIMOTHY LELAND  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PATAGONIA, Argentina _ The horses took us only halfway up.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the climb was on foot, up the stony face of the
escarpment. Up, up, and up to where the condors soared.
</P>
<P>
   You know you've climbed a good long way when you can look down
at a half-dozen Andean condors, hovering over a valley below, their
6-foot wing span holding them aloft in the secret swirling currents
of air.
</P>
<P>
   From the top of the butte we had just ascended, where we huddled
against the boulders to block the wind, an immense and empty
landscape lay before us, the snowcapped peaks of the Andes
glimmering in the distance.
</P>
<P>
   This was Patagonia, the wild and beautiful land of literature
and imagination.
</P>
<P>
   No towns could be seen in any direction. Not a single building,
no sign of habitation for what seemed like hundreds of miles. This
was the land we had come to observe and experience _ on horseback.
</P>
<P>
   In the mid-distance beneath us, off to the west, a thick
embroidery of cultivated trees, green against the sere brown of the
rolling landscape, was all that gave away the location of our
``estancia,'' the cattle ranch where my friend and I were staying
for a week of horseback riding, sightseeing, and fishing in one of
the world's most remote and romantic regions.
</P>
<P>
   Known as Estancia Huechhue (pronounced way-CHA-way), it lies in
the foothills of the Andes in northern Patagonia, a thousand miles
southwest of Buenos Aires. As ranches go in this part of the world,
Huechhue is a relatively small spread, covering only 36 square
miles, or some 15,000 acres. But those 36 square miles provide
plenty of land for the ranch's 900 head of Hereford to graze on.
And if you're on horseback looking for those 900 head of cattle, or
herding them from point A to point B, those 36 square miles seems
endless. Especially if you're from Boston and a game of chess is a
good physical workout.
</P>
<P>
   Not that we were displeased. My childhood friend, James Dean of
South Berwick, Maine, was seeking the same thing I was. We were
both 61; both recently retired; both looking for a novel travel
experience.
</P>
<P>
   And that's what we found.
</P>
<P>
   Argentina exports much of the best beef in the world and, to
support the industry, has many huge cattle ranches, many of which
allow paying guests to stay on the premises in considerable luxury,
just like the dude ranches in our Western states. At elegant and
expensive ranches near Buenos Aires, for example, you can play a
round of golf or a game of polo on manicured grass.
</P>
<P>
   Not at Estancia Huechhue in Patagonia. Here, unlike its North
American counterparts, there are no TV sets, no video games, no
after-dinner softball games, no Ping-Pong tournaments, no pool
tables, and no rodeos.
</P>
<P>
   Rodeos? There aren't even any radios.
</P>
<P>
   Just horses and rainbow trout. But if you like to ride the
former or catch the latter, you'll think you're in Shangri-La.
</P>
<P>
   ``We get very few guests who spend the afternoons sitting in the
sun,'' says Jane Alexander, owner of the ranch. ``The people who
come here tend to be much more active than those who prefer the
traditional dude ranches.''
</P>
<P>
   Alexander, a 42-year-old Englishwoman with shoulder-length black
hair and an explosive laugh, is a story in herself. Born and raised
in London as a member of the upper class, she married an Argentine
whose grandfather had bought the ranch in Patagonia around the turn
of the century. Shortly after their marriage in England, Jane
traveled with her new husband to see the Argentine property for the
first time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I was coming here to play for a couple of years and
then go back to London,'' she recalls, ``but it didn't work out
that way.'' In a tragic twist of fate, Jane's husband was killed in
a tractor accident shortly after they arrived, leaving the former
socialite in charge of a 15,000-acre ranch in a remote part of the
world where a foreign language was spoken and the lifestyle was
totally different. ``I never even rode horses when I was young,''
she notes.
</P>
<P>
   She does now _ every day, almost all day, either in the company
of the Argentine cowboys, known as gauchos, who work on the ranch,
or with tourists like Jim and myself who visit the ranch between
November and April, when guests are welcome.
</P>
<P>
   For those who request it, Jane and the gauchos will lay on a
full seven-day pack trip into Lanin National Park, which lies
adjacent to the ranch. During the trek, you ride through beech
forests and bamboo thickets along the shore of a green-blue lake,
up the Aquinco Valley through a forest of Monkey Puzzle trees, over
the shoulder of a nearby volcano, then drop down for a swim in some
neighboring thermal springs before returning to Huechahue.
</P>
<P>
   Although such a pack trip was tempting, Jim and I opted for day
rides, returning each night to the comfort of our twin-bedded room
in the ranch's guesthouse, where we could soak our creaking bodies
in water heated by a wood-stoked furnace outside our door.
</P>
<P>
   And our bodies did creak, notwithstanding our best efforts to
achieve comfort and support. Along with the usual assortment of
leather gloves, soft cotton socks, suntan lotion, lip balm, and
fleece jackets, I had brought my secret weapons against physical
trauma caused by prolonged activity on horseback. These included:
</P>
<P>
   --Moleskin patches (for untoward blisters).
</P>
<P>
   --A pair of black nylon long johns (to prevent chafing under
dungarees).
</P>
<P>
   --A nylon back-brace (normally worn while chopping wood in New
Hampshire).
</P>
<P>
   --And a white foam-rubber neck brace (left over from a previous
injury).
</P>
<P>
   Jim's apparel was also utilitarian, if equally unorthodox. The
first day, he showed up at the corral wearing a purple flannel
shirt from L. L. Bean, green nylon ski pants taped at the ankles to
keep from sliding up his leg, a red cotton sash around his waist
for back support (borrowed from Jane), heavy leather hiking boots,
and a black velvet riding helmet perched atop his head. He looked
like a cross between an addled English fox hunter and a street
person in Boston. He claimed that I, on the other hand, resembled a
war casualty from a local field hospital.
</P>
<P>
   No matter, we were ready to ride _ and ride we did.
</P>
<P>
   The horses of Patagonia have been bred for strength and
endurance, and they love to run. Riding in this part of the world
does not mean ambling along at a walk or an occasional trot,
admiring the views. It means pounding over the hard, rolling hills
in long-winded canters interspersed with full-throttle,
hell-for-leather galloping, when the bones and teeth of aging
bodies feel as though they may rattle and shake apart. Everywhere
we went we seemed to go at top speed, Jim and I hanging on for dear
life.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
