<HEADER>
A4298 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u t BC-TRAVEL-PATAGONIA-2ND &LR;      10-12 0795
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-PATAGONIA-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 PATAGONIA, Argentina: ... dear life.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   But after reining to a stop in one piece, how very satisfying
and exhilarating it was. The shaking-and-baking of our bones was
worth it, as, close up and personal, we saw the beautiful
Patagonian countryside flash by. Animal and bird life were
everywhere: herds of wild red deer, their white tails twitching as
they raced through the underbrush; tall, ungainly guanacos (South
American llamas), which peered at us inquisitively as we rode past;
gray rabbits constantly dashing across our path; and their larger
cousins, hares, flushed out of hiding by the two black dogs that
roamed in front of us, barking with delight.
</P>
<P>
   My memory of wildlife in Patagonia, however, will always be of
birds.
</P>
<P>
   What wildflowers are to a pack trip in Wyoming, or tropical fish
to snorkeling in Bora Bora, or whales to a sightseeing trip in Cabo
San Luca, birds are to the countryside of Patagonia.
</P>
<P>
   Surprisingly, there were numerous robins in southern Argentina,
making us feel for awhile as though we hadn't left New England
after all. But riding across the fields and meadows we saw many
other, less familiar species. Spur-winged plovers with bright red
legs rose with a clatter from the brush. Flocks of buff-necked ibis
strutted across the grassy plains, digging insects out of the earth
with their strange curved bills. Burrowing parrots, large green and
yellow birds that lived in holes they scratched in a sandy bluff,
made a tremendous clatter as we rode up.
</P>
<P>
   Ornamental trees are another hallmark of the Huechachue ranch.
As a hobby in the 1930s and '40s, Jane's late father-in-law
collected seeds and saplings from around the world and planted them
on the property. Jane would tick off the varieties that remain as
we rode out to the hills each morning: long straight lanes of
poplars, silvery-barked eucalyptus, orchards of peach, nectarine,
hazelnut, almond trees, and many others.
</P>
<P>
   On the second day of our stay, we were joined at the ranch by
six Dutch military reserve officers who belonged to a riding club
in their country _ rough and ready men in their 40s and 50s who
loved to ride during the day and drink at night, and did a lot of
both.
</P>
<P>
   They also liked good, hearty food, and they had come to the
right place for that, too.
</P>
<P>
   Jane served huge English breakfasts each day to keep us going
until lunch, which more often than not was an ``asado,'' the
traditional Argentine barbecue. Sides of beef or lamb would already
be roasting over an open fire when we dismounted for our midday
meal, and the gauchos would use their razor-sharp knives, typically
worn in a sash at the small of their backs, to cut off large hunks
for each of us to eat. A typical dinner (which in Argentina never
begins before 9), might start with an appetizer of wild hare, rich
brown meat boiled in oil and vinegar and stored in sterilized jars.
Next might come sliced venison, fresh green vegetables, baked
potatoes, avocado salad, and warm bread, all products of the ranch.
</P>
<P>
   And for dessert? When was the last time you had thick cream,
straight from the cow, poured over scoops of fresh, homemade
chocolate ice cream?
</P>
<P>
   If you're trying to lose weight, a cattle ranch in Patagonia may
not be for you.
</P>
<P>
   Every morning, following breakfast, we set out on horseback for
a different part of the estancia, helping Jane and the gauchos herd
cattle or check fencing. After five days, it was time for a more
restful diversion, and Jim and I rode to a nearby stream for
fly-fishing.
</P>
<P>
   Wading knee-deep in crystal clear water, we cast our artificial
flies in the deep glassy pools behind rocks or fallen branches.
Within an hour we had caught (and released) a half-dozen beautiful
rainbow trout that jumped out of the water when hooked, fighting
the line every inch of the way. The fishing, like the horseback
riding, is unequaled in Patagonia.
</P>
<P>
   That afternoon, refreshed and reinvigorated, we were back in the
saddle, trotting down a long dusty trail beside a beautiful river
that sparkled in the sun. Late in the day we came to the boundary
line of an Indian reservation, where the family of Domingo, one of
our favorite gaucho guides, lived.
</P>
<P>
   From the top of the hill overlooking a valley, he pointed to a
human-made rock formation, where a tribal chieftain had been buried
many years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our chiefs were always buried in a place where they could see
their tribal enemies approaching,'' Domingo said, scanning the vast
empty space in front of us. There were no enemies in sight.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, there were no friends, either.
</P>
<P>
   There, in fact, was no sign of civilization.
</P>
<P>
   That's Patagonia.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Timothy Leland is a retired vice president of the Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
