<HEADLINE>
BUENOS AIRES PULSATES WITH LIFE AND LONGING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD KINDLEBERGER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUENOS AIRES _ This Latin city on the other side of the world
seemed too far away even to think about. But visiting it turned out
to be easier than I imagined, and more interesting, too.
</P>
<P>
   A bustling metropolis of 11 million, Buenos Aires has impressive
architecture, grand boulevards, and sweeping vistas reminiscent of
Washington, D.C. Its beef and wines are world famous. Its
nightclubs showcase the tango, that steamy dance whose mournful
melodies seems to capture a nation's longing.
</P>
<P>
   Argentines will tell you there's more to see in their country
than the capital. For me, the rest will have to wait. I found
plenty to keep me busy in Buenos Aires during an eight-day visit.
</P>
<P>
   It was a steamy evening in June when I flew out of Boston.
Fifteen hours later, I woke up to winter in Buenos Aires. That
meant no snow but temperatures in the 40s and 50s. Most tourists
prefer to visit when it's warm, but the off-season has advantages.
For one, cool days make for better walking.
</P>
<P>
   The pulse of Buenos Aires is felt in its streets. Men as well as
women greet each other with a kiss on the cheek. Cafe waiters
jaywalk a tray of cafe lattes through traffic in the local version
of takeout. Dog walkers, who can make $100 a month per animal, pass
by on the sidewalk with a dozen dogs on leashes.
</P>
<P>
   The city has great parks, often beautifully landscaped and well
maintained. Resting on a bench in Jardin Botanico can conjure up a
Parisian garden or a shady square in Savannah. Monuments to heroic
events in Argentine history are everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   On the downside, streets are dirty and sidewalks crumbling. The
city has begun to offer no-smoking areas in larger restaurants, but
it has yet to push dog owners to clean up after their pets. Those
who are well off appear to be thriving, but poverty remains a huge
problem and is said to be getting worse. Politics and corruption,
great spectator sports to be sure, are the despair of many
rank-and-file Argentines.
</P>
<P>
   A visit to the downtown Plaza de Mayo gave me a glimpse of
Argentina's painful recent history. Plaza de Mayo faces the Casa
Rosaria government building where Juan and Eva Peron stood on the
balcony and waved to the crowds during pivotal moments in his
tumultuous reign.
</P>
<P>
   The Mothers of the Disappeared, wearing white kerchiefs, circle
the plaza Thursdays in a weekly march begun 22 years ago. It
commemorates the estimated 30,000 who were seized, many never to be
seen again, in the late 1970s and early '80s during the military
government's ``dirty war'' against internal critics.
</P>
<P>
   A few days later I came across a group of 100 aging men with a
separate grievance. These rightist demonstrators were still upset
at Argentina's 1982 defeat by Britain in their war over the
still-disputed Falkland Islands and the suppression of a brief 1990
insurrection by young military officers.
</P>
<P>
   Putting aside politics, I went to a Sunday soccer match at a
large stadium in the northern part of the city. Instead of the
classic 0-0 tie, it turned out to be an exciting game, won 3-2 by
the visiting team.
</P>
<P>
   But the action off the field was even more interesting. The
streets were blocked to vehicles a quarter-mile from the stadium.
When I reached the gate, with the game underway, police were in
force outside. One stood over a prisoner who knelt on the ground
with his hands cuffed behind his back. There were police on
horseback and riot police with helmets and clubs. The soccer game
was supposed to be entertainment, but the police looked as if they
were expecting a revolution.
</P>
<P>
   They had reason to be on guard, given an intensity in Argentine
fans that leads to comparisons with English soccer hooligans. The
match was supposed to be a walkover for the home team. To
everyone's surprise and the excitement of the visitors, the away
team won a big upset, beating its opponents in their home stadium
for the first time in 26 years. Maybe that explained the raucous
chanting, the obscene words and gestures exchanged by rival fans at
halftime, and the decision by police to keep the two sides
separated by a sort of demilitarized zone where no one was allowed
to sit. Or maybe it was all routine.
</P>
<P>
   In my one excursion outside the city, I took a hydrofoil from a
downtown dock across the Rio de la Plata to Uruguay. The round trip
cost $55 and took 45 minutes each way. I was hoping to have a
couple of hours to look around Montevideo, the capital, after
taking the bus there from the port of Colonia.
</P>
<P>
   That plan fizzled when the hour bus trip I had been told to
expect took 2 1/2 hours. The ride through rolling farm country was
enjoyable. But after finally arriving in Montevideo and arranging
my return trip, I had only 45 minutes to explore a city of 3
million people. I started on foot but soon switched to a cab. The
driver, a friendly fellow named Roberto who had relatives in
Trenton, N.J., whisked me past the Plaza Independencia and a blur
of stately buildings before dropping me off at the bus station with
two minutes to spare.
</P>
<P>
   If I were to do it over, I might try a package deal to
Montevideo I saw advertised on returning to Buenos Aires. The round
trip by hydrofoil, including a bus tour of the city and lunch, cost
$79. That's about the same as my boat-bus-taxi combo and would have
allowed me to see a lot more of Montevideo.
</P>
<P>
   South of downtown Buenos Aires lies the rough and colorful port
neighborhood of La Boca (Spanish for ``The Mouth''). Tourists are
warned to be wary there because of the crime. It is known as home
to some of the city's poorest residents, and the crumbling concrete
dwellings I passed, with mounds of trash and chickens pecking in
the dirt, seemed to confirm that.
</P>
<P>
   In the harbor at La Boca were rusting hulks of abandoned vessels
and some extremely foul-looking water. But less than half a mile
away, the waterfront improved dramatically. With a rebuilt quay and
benches for visitors, this was a pleasant attraction for weekend
strollers and artists painting harbor scenes from behind their
easels.
</P>
<P>
   This part of La Boca has become more commercial, with pushcart
vendors and street performers like the ones found in Harvard Square
or Faneuil Hall Marketplace. The buildings are colorfully
idiosyncratic, and bars and restaurants invite you in for a drink,
meal, or tango performance. The tango is said to have taken hold in
the brothels of La Boca early in the century when it was disdained
by polite society in Buenos Aires. Only after it became the rage in
Europe did it come back to Argentina and gain a measure of
respectability.
</P>
<P>
   On my last night I went with a group to Bar Sur on the
recommendation of an acquaintance who said it offered a taste of
the tango as enjoyed by ordinary residents. The cozy club, whose
walls are decorated with old masks and posters, is located on a
deserted street in a once-fashionable neighborhood. Instead of the
stage show and full meal offered by some of the glitzier, more
tourist-oriented establishments, it charges a $15 cover that
includes two slices of pizza.
</P>
<P>
   The two hours we were there started with a female singer belting
out ballads to the accompaniment of a piano. Then came two dancers,
a man and a woman, who tangoed with a finesse that was intricate
and acrobatic _ and very sexy. The dancing only fell flat when, as
advertised, the pair invited this writer and other members of the
audience for an on-the-spot tango lesson. My instructor quickly
moved on.
</P>
<P>
   It was an enjoyable end to my Buenos Aires sojourn. Residents
told me to return when the weather was warmer _ December or
January, for example _ and I had time to see the rest of Argentina.
Indeed, I had barely begun to know the country. I sucked mate tea,
the national drink, through a straw. The closest I came to a gaucho
was the head waiter in a funny hat at La Estancia restaurant. But I
saw enough to know I want to come back.
</P>
</TEXT>
