<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-LEAF-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAKING THE TRAIN THROUGH LEAF-PEEPING HEAVEN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KENNEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's only one problem with fall foliage drives.
</P>
<P>
   It's that last word: drives. If you've got your eyes on winding
roads and your fingers wrapped around a steering wheel, let's face
it, you're not spending much time looking at those 70-foot-tall
bouquets of orange, red, and yellow leaves. And if the leaf-peeping
traffic is bumper to bumper, so much the worse.
</P>
<P>
   But there is an alternative. You can return to the past and
leave the driving to the engineer.
</P>
<P>
   After all, it was railroads that in the middle of the last
century opened up northern New England to tourism. So what better
way to experience the quintessential aspect of northern New
England's scenery _ its fall plumage _ than by train?
</P>
<P>
   The railroads made the most dramatic regions of northern New
England, with their notches and peaks, accessible to city dwellers,
``turning the region inside out,'' writes Dona Brown in ``Inventing
New England,'' her study of 19th-century tourism here.
</P>
<P>
   This weekend, and for at least two more, there are rail
excursions into the peaks and notches of New Hampshire and the
hills and valleys of Vermont _ just as the oaks and maples are
turning their brightest. And closer to Boston, there are rail
excursions west to the Berkshires and, south of the city, along the
route of the Blackstone River and through the timeless cranberry
bogs.
</P>
<P>
   Here are some options:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CONWAY SCENIC RAILROAD &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Daily &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Valley Train in New Hampshire runs daily trough Oct. 24,
with 55-minute round trips from North Conway to Conway and 1
3/4-hour round trips from North Conway to Bartlett.
</P>
<P>
   This route follows the Mount Washington Valley aboard a restored
1898 Pullman car with wicker and rattan chairs, mahogany woodwork,
and an open observation platform. Coach fares for the Conway trip
are $8.50, and for the Bartlett trip $14.50.
</P>
<P>
   The Notch train runs daily through Oct. 15, with 5 1/2-hour
round trips between Conway and Fabyan Station. This route travels
through Crawford Notch on tracks sliced into the sides of the White
Mountains along the side of the Saco River. Coach fares are $34 for
adults.
</P>
<P>
   For information and reservations call 800-232-5251.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BLACKSTONE VALLEY EXCURSION &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Oct. 16 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Northern New England foliage may be past its peak by mid-month
but in full color in southern New England for the Blackstone Valley
excursion, a 4-hour trip along the Providence &AMP; Worcester Railroad
line.
</P>
<P>
   The Blackstone Valley is a National Heritage Corridor, and rail
line runs parallel to the river, through small villages and
farmlands, with woodlands on all sides. There will be narrators on
board pointing out the sights along the way _ many of them
associated with the beginnings of America's Industrial Revolution.
</P>
<P>
   The trip leaves Cumberland, R.I., at 10 a.m. and returns at 2
p.m. Tickets are $32 a person. For information and reservations,
call 401-724-2200.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BERKSHIRE LIMITED &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Oct. 23 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   How's this for no driving? The train leaves right from Boston's
South Station _ with stops at Back Bay, Framingham, Worcester, and
Springfield en route to Pittsfield _ on the Mystic Valley Railroad
Society's annual Berkshire Limited Fall Foliage Excursion.
</P>
<P>
   The route runs through the hilly country of Western
Massachusetts, passing through Huntington, Chester, Becket, and
Dalton, and up the Westfield River Gorge.
</P>
<P>
   This is a special Amtrak train, complete with snack bar and
restrooms, and the $65-per-person, round-trip includes lunch. It
leaves South Station at 9 a.m., arrives in Pittsfield at 1:15 p.m.,
and is scheduled to return to South Station at 6 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   For reservations and information, call 617-361-4445.
</P>
</TEXT>
