<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The Cox News Service spot news budget for Wednesday, Oct. 13,
1999.
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Photo and graphics information and editors' names can be found
at the end of this budget.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-TREATY _ WASHINGTON _ With a Senate vote scheduled for
Tuesday on the nuclear test ban treaty, President Clinton continues
talks with GOP leaders to postpone the vote, avoiding an
embarrasing defeat, while keeping his option to resubmit next year.
(Deans, Cox News Service). 30.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-POPULATION _ BEIJING _ On the day the world population
officially reached six billion, China confounded speculation
Tuesday that it might relax its one-child policy and pledged a new
``historical leap'' to further restrict its birth rate. Meeting at
the Great Hall of the People on Tiananmen Square, officials of the
world's most populous country said the next leap in birth control
would be an attempt to bring a zero growth in China's population by
the mid-21st century. Their objective is stabilize China's
population at 1.6 billion people in around 2045, by which time
India will have become the most populous nation on the globe.
(Kunstel/Albright, Cox News Service). 20.
</P>
<P>
   ANTIQUITIES _ Italian officials have asked the US for help in
halting the smuggling of looted antiquities from Italy into
America. Coming on the heels of three major raids against
antiquities dealers in Italy, the request seeks import restrictions
on a range of treasures, art and artifacts representing more than
5,000 years of history. A State Department review of the request in
Washingon Tuesday drew harsh criticism from art dealers and museum
curators, while archaeologists contended the action is needed to
halt the market-driven demand for looted treasures. (Toner, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 20.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   RAMSEY _ BOULDER, Colo. _ The JonBenet Ramsey grand jury
reconvenes today. The grand jury, which has met for more than a
year to hear evidence in the slaying nearly three years ago of the
six-year-old girl, ends its term Oct. 20. (Schneider, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   ALA-LOTTERY _ BIRMINGHAM _ Results of the Alabama lottery vote.
(Manuel, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   UGA-RACE _ Atlanta lawyer Lee Parks on Tuesday will file his
injunction against the Board of Regents, asking a federal judge in
Savannah to order UGA to cease immediately using race as a factor
in its admissions policies. (Rankin, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
20.
</P>
<P>
   FLA-ELECTRICHAIR _ A look at the chair, or 'Old Sparky,' as it's
called. Everything you wanted to know about the death penalty in
Florida. Sidebars on those who have been killed, last words, last
meals and eletrocution and the human body. (Browning, Palm Beach
Post). MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   FLA-CHAIRORIGIN _ We owe the electric chair, Florida's most
shocking piece of furniture for the past 75 years, to an elderly
New York drunk who happened to touch the terminals of an electrical
generator in Buffalo on Aug. 8, 1881. (Browning, Palm Beach Post).
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   FLA-CHAIRSHOCK _ Though the electric chair is designed to kill,
not injure, the same processes are at work whenever anyone gets an
electric shock, be it lethal or non-lethal. (Browning, Palm Beach
Post). MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   FLA-CHAIRLIST _ The list of convicts executed in Florida since
the U.S. Supreme Court restored Florida's death penalty in 1976.
(Cox News Service) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   AFL-CIO _ LOS ANGELES _ The AFL-CIO's political committee is
xpected to votes Tuesday afternoon to recommend that the labor
federation endorse Vice President Al Gore. Gore is then expected to
make a round of thank-you visits with the leaders. ON AFL-CIO
union, the Teamsters, may issue a dissenting or abstaining
statement later this afternoon. (Shepard, Cox News Service).
</P>
