<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-NOTES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICKEY'S IN A PARTY MOOD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD P. CARPENTER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   You've got to hand it to Mickey Mouse: He knows how to throw a
party that really lasts. The one now going on at Walt Disney
World's Epcot will run through Year 2000, which is the reason for
all the festivity.
</P>
<P>
   A giant version of Mickey's four-fingered hand, gripping a
116-foot-tall wand, can be found next to the Florida park's
Spaceship Earth sphere. That's appropriate, because the theme of
this salute to Y2K is ``Celebrate the Future Hand in Hand.''
</P>
<P>
   The party, which began Oct. 1, includes: &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --Tapestry of Nations. This dramatic parade features more than
120 larger-than-life, futuristic-looking puppets, 32 drummers
aboard 16 rolling percussion stages, and a lot more in a
twice-daily pageant around Epcot's World Showcase Lagoon. Why, the
puppets may even shake hands with you. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --IllumiNations 2000: Reflections on Earth. Calling this a
fireworks show is like calling the Taj Mahal a tomb: It just
doesn't do it justice. Each nightly presentation uses 2,800 shells
_ more than twice the number used in previous productions. Music
soars and a great globe of the earth spins slowly on the lagoon. A
fountain barge pumps 5,000 gallons of water a minute. A
150,000-pound ``inferno barge'' uses 37 nozzles to shoot flames
skyward. Lasers crisscross the sky. Walls of flame and a giant
torch climb 40 feet above the lagoon. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --Millennium Village. Located in the park's World Showcase
section, this 65,000-square-foot ``village'' houses hundreds of
entertainers, artisans, and storytellers, with exhibits
representing more than two dozen countries, the United Nations, and
the World Bank, proving that it's, er, a small world after all.
There are games, such as miniature golf in the Scotland exhibit,
and regional foods, too. (The village was not without controversy;
even before it opened, Arab and Muslim groups objected to some
aspects of the Israel exhibit.) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --Leave a Legacy. Guests, for a price, can leave their mark on
the park. Their photos are etched on metallic tile, then mounted on
one of 30 sculptured monoliths near Spaceship Earth. And for
collectors and traders, limited-edition souvenir pins are sold
throughout Epcot. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --Innoventions. This preview of the latest products and
technologies has been thoroughly revamped, with companies such as
Motorola, Honeywell, IBM, and AT&AMP;T joining in. You can, for
instance, see high-tech TVs, watch a computer type what a person
speaks, and participate in interactive exhibits. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --Millennium Dreamers. The extraordinary contributions of 2,000
young people from around the world will be celebrated May 8-10,
courtesy of McDonald's and the Walt Disney Co. Youngsters ages 8-15
are eligible, and those chosen will be flown to the event, along
with a parent or guardian. Nomination forms are available in
schools and several other places, including www.disney.com and
www.mcdonalds.com.
</P>
<P>
   (For more information on Walt Disney World, call 407-W-DISNEY,
visit www.disneyworld.com, or see a travel agent. And if you
haven't been to Epcot in a while, check out the reworked and
renamed Journey into Your Imagination attraction and the wild Test
Track ride.) &QL; 
 &QL; 
Travel Trivia: Walt Disney World encompasses (a) 350 acres, (b)
3,500 acres, (c) 30,500 acres, or (d) 350,000 acres. (Answer at end
of column.) &QL; 
 &QL; 
Quotable: ``Disney World has acquired by now something of the air
of a national shrine. American parents who don't take their
children there sense obscurely that they have failed in some
fundamental way, like Muslims who never made it to Mecca'' _
British journalist Simon Hoggart. &QL; 
 &QL; 
In a name: A men's room at the Animal Kingdom offers visitors a
``Whiz Quiz'' about the ``watering'' habits of elephants, rhinos,
and tapirs. Enough said. Too much, perhaps.
</P>
<P>
   Fast, in more ways than one: The new Rock 'n' Roller Coaster at
Disney-MGM Studios launches riders 0-60 m.p.h. in just 2.8 seconds
as the music of Boston's own Aerosmith blares from speakers within
the limousine-shaped cars. What's more, the coaster is one of the
popular rides that uses the new FASTPASS system during peak
seasons. Instead of waiting in line (and you know how long those
waits can sometimes be), guests have the option of inserting their
theme park admission tickets into a turnstile, which gives them a
FASTPASS and the time they should return to the ride. When that
time comes, they go to the ride's FASTPASS entrance and then, with
little or no wait, to the attraction's pre-show or boarding area. &QL; 
 &QL; 
On the menu: The entrance to the Jungle Cruise ride in the Magic
Kingdom displays an imaginative (and imaginary) lunch menu for the
crew. Among the items: fricasse of giant stag beetle, barbecued
three-toed skink, and filet of rock python. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Travel bookshelf: ``PassPorter: Walt Disney World'' (Spread the
Word Press, $19.95) by Jennifer Watson and Dave Marx is a travel
guide, trip planner, organizer, journal, and souvenir, all in one.
In addition to information on the park and advice on planning
(accompanied by worksheets), the guide contains 11 organizer
pockets. Vacationers can write their itinerary on the front of each
day's pocket and store maps, tickets, brochures, and receipts
inside. On the back of the pocket, you can write down your memories
of the day. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Big bucks for a big celebration: If you want to celebrate the
arrival of Year 2000 in style, The Walt Disney World Swan and
Dolphin hotel complex is offering a seven-night family package
featuring a stay in the two-story Presidential Suite, meals for two
adults and two children, butler service, massages, Disney World
passes, luxury transportation, and a lot more for $69,900. If
that's beyond your splurging ability, an alternative seven-day
package begins at $3,900. (For more information, call 800-227-1500
or visit www.swandolphin.com.) &QL; 
 &QL; 
Boo . . . sort of: Mickey's Not-So-Scary Halloween Party will be
held at the Magic Kingdom Oct. 28, 29, and 31. Events will include
trick-or-treating throughout the park, face painting, a costume
parade, pumpkin-carving demonstrations, and Halloween fireworks.
For prices and other information, call 407-824-4321. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Snappy slogan: Disney-MGM Studios bills itself as ``the Hollywood
that never was . . . and always will be.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Did you guess it? 30,500 acres, most of which is still unused.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Send comments and questions to Travel Tidbits, Boston Globe,
Boston, MA 02107. Send e-mail to carpen(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
