<HEADLINE>
THE UK GETS READY FOR Y2K 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY MORRIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tickets to the Millennium Dome, the centerpiece of Britain's Y2K
festivities in Greenwich, southeast London, are now on sale. The
dome, part of a nationwide program of events called the UK
Millennium Experience, is nearing completion on a promontory on the
south bank of the River Thames. It will contain spectacular
exhibits exploring a variety of aspects of life now and in the
future through 14 theme zones featuring virtual reality and other
special effects. From Jan. 1 through Dec. 31, 2000, the dome will
be open from 10 a.m. to 6 p.m. daily. The recommended length of a
visit is five hours.
</P>
<P>
   Tickets, which must be purchased in advance, are $42 for adults;
$36 for children 5-15 years of age; and $39 for seniors (60 and
over). They are available from Globaltickets of New York City by
calling 800-223-6108, Mondays through Saturdays from 9 a.m. to 8
p.m., and Sundays from noon to 7 p.m. The company says that family
tickets and tickets combining admission with round-trip travel by
river ferry from central London to the dome will be available
later. Tickets sold in the United States must first be redeemed at
Globaltickets' booking agency in the British Visitor Centre, 1
Regent St., London, close to Piccadilly Circus. Tickets can also be
purchased by credit card through the Millennium Experience Web site
at www.dome2000.co.uk.
</P>
<P>
   For more information on millennium events throughout Britain,
call the British Tourist Authority at 800-462-2748, Mondays through
Fridays between 9 a.m. and 6 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Thanksgiving ideas
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Instead of celebrating Thanksgiving at home, why not travel to
Plymouth, England? It was from this English port that the Pilgrims
set sail for the new world, and the city of Plymouth will hold its
annual American Thanksgiving Festival Nov. 24-28, complete with a
massive Stars &AMP; Stripes Turkey &AMP; Pumpkin Pie Dinner and Big Band
Dance.
</P>
<P>
   Also planned are fireworks, a Thanksgiving service in St.
Andrew's Church, a symphony concert of works of American composers,
and an American Heritage Trail. For information, call the Plymouth
Chamber of Commerce at 011-44-1752-202500, by fax at
011-44-1752-202508 or on the Web at www.plymouth-chamber.co.uk.
</P>
<P>
   Or, you might consider flying to Rome for Thanksgiving. Alitalia
is featuring a $1,099 package from Boston and New York (higher
elsewhere) that includes air fare, five nights' accommodations,
daily breakfast, Thanksgiving dinner, private Vatican Museum tour,
guided trip to Florence, transfers and taxes. Travel agents have
details or call Italiatour at 800-845-3365 or visit the Web at
www.Italiatour.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Upcoming
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Nantucket celebrates the fall with its October Harvest Oct.
15-17. During the festival 200 acres of cranberry bogs will be open
to the public. Other events range from an inn tour to a chowder
contest. For information on lodging as space is limited, call
508-228-0925 and ask about Getaway Packages.
</P>
<P>
   The Cayman Islands will celebrate Pirates Week Oct. 22-31. The
10-day event relives the days when pirates roamed the island, but
now the festival features parades, street dances, heritage
celebrations, sporting events, fireworks, and food. For information
on travel packages, call 800-346-3313 or visit the Web
atwww.caymanislands.ky.
</P>
<P>
   Key West's annual Fantasy Fest, a masking and costuming
festival, will be held Oct. 22-31. Organizers are encouraging
people to choose an era and design masks, costumes, and floats
around it _ everything from the Stone Age to the Space Age. Also
planned is a Caribbean-style Goombay Celebration. For more
information on the event, call 305-296-1817, and for lodging, call
800-LAST KEY.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Good deals
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Getting married at a Sandals Resort can be a beautiful as well
as bargain experience. The all-inclusive resorts in the Bahamas and
Jamaica are offering free flights from New York and other cities to
the resort, a free ``Weddingmoon'' package, and a 20-piece starter
set of Royal Doulton china. The offer is good now through Feb. 5
with the exception of Dec. 16-Jan. 1. For complete details, call
800-SANDALS or visit the Web at www.sandals.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Museum birthday
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   America's oldest museum, the Peabody Essex Museum in Salem,
Mass., will celebrate its 200th birthday Oct. 16-17 with an outdoor
party that will bring to life some of the colorful characters from
the museum's past. The museum will also open a major exhibition,
``Odyssey: A Journey into World Art,'' which showcases the best
works from the museum's collection. The weekend also includes a
free Family Fest Oct. 17 at 2 p.m., with games, music, and cake.
</P>
<P>
   The museum's collections include maritime art and history,
American decorative art, folk art, portraits, furniture, art from
Pacific countries, American architecture from the 17th to 19th
centuries, and one of the world's largest collections of Asian
decorative arts produced for the West. For more information, call
800-745-4054.
</P>
</TEXT>
