<HEADLINE>
GETTING WHAT THEY PAID FOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBERT JORDAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   State Farm Mutual Automobile Insurance Co. may need to buy more
insurance for itself, to cover such disasters as the one that
heavily damaged this Illinois-based company last week.
</P>
<P>
   Although State Farm saw it coming, prepared for it, and
staunchly fought against it, the insurer was still hit with more
than $1 billion in actual and punitive damages over the use of
after-market parts in auto-body repairs.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, this disaster could be deemed one of State Farm's
own doing, if the expected appeal upholds the judge's and the
jury's awards to State Farm policyholders. Both concluded State
Farm deceived policyholders about the quality of the replacement
parts it required body shops to use in repairs. The jury originally
awarded $456 million to the policyholders, or plaintiffs, in the
class-action suit, believed to be the largest ever leveled against
an insurance firm, in this case the nation's largest auto insurer.
Last week circuit Judge John Speroni increased that award, adding
$130 million in actual damages and $600 million in punitive
damages.
</P>
<P>
   State Farm, which has announced it will appeal both verdicts,
emphatically denies committing any fraud, maintaining the judge and
jury ignored the evidence it presented at trial, and that it
complied with laws and regulations in every state.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers representing the policyholders who brought the suit
claimed the parts State Farm required body shops to use were simply
not as good as original parts made for automakers. They argued
after-market or generic parts, which are based on manufacturers'
original parts but made without access to factory specifications,
were used on the repairs.
</P>
<P>
   After the jury agreed with the plaintiffs, Speroni himself ruled
that State Farm violated Illinois consumer fraud law by using
substandard parts and hiding that fact from customers. Instead, the
judge further ruled, State Farm's brochures to customers called the
parts a high-quality, low-cost alternative.
</P>
<P>
   In a 1997 memo introduced by the plaintiffs' lawyers, a State
Farm executive wrote ``We may well say it is like kind and quality,
but the bottom line is that it is not the same.'' Lawyers for State
Farm argued that such memos were taken out of context, and that
they should have been taken as evidence of the firm's efforts to
improve the quality of after-market parts. This argument apparently
did not fly with the judge or the jury.
</P>
<P>
   Although the plaintiffs sought nearly $4 billion in actual and
punitive damages, their lawyers expressed satisfaction with the
$1.19 billion award, made to those policyholders who filed claims
between July 1994 and February 1998.
</P>
<P>
   In the final analysis, the jury and judge agreed that the
insurer had failed to restore customers' cars to their preaccident
conditions. According to the verdict, an estimated 4.7 million
current and former policyholders who could have claims against
State Farm would be awarded an average of $100 each. But it was
unclear last week how many consumers would collect awards.
</P>
<P>
   Among body-shop owners, auto insurance companies, and consumers,
the debate is still raging over whether the judge and jury awards,
especially the amounts, were warranted. Insurance industry analysts
suggest these verdicts could result in an increase in both
insurance premiums and the cost of auto-body repairs if they are
not overturned.
</P>
<P>
   Some auto-body repairmen, in e-mails sent to MSNBC, said the
verdict was justified. One repairman said during his years of
repairing autos he found most after-market body replacement parts
were less than acceptable and that rust and corrosion protection is
not even close to that of original parts. He argued that if the
jury had been a panel of auto-body repairmen, the trial would have
been over in a few hours with much higher monetary awards, saving
the taxpayers time and money. In this world, he added, ``you always
get what you pay for. You want cheap, that's what you will get.''
</P>
<P>
   No doubt insurance companies other than State Farm might be at
least a bit concerned about the awards, knowing their policyholders
might suspect similar treatment and move legally in the same
direction as State Farm policyholders.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the outcome of State Farm's appeal, there was no doubt
that the total judgment against the company was a shot across the
bow of all such insurance companies that may be engaging in similar
practices.
</P>
<P>
   In sum, State Farm apparently got what it paid for: cheaper,
lesser-quality parts at lower cost. But policyholders apparently
did not get what they paid for: good as original body parts. That's
why the jury felt, and the judge even more so, that with this award
the policyholders got what was coming to them and State Farm got
what it deserved.
</P>
<P>
   (Robert A. Jordan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
