<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
6 BILLION AND COUNTING 
</HEADLINE>
 WARSH-COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID WARSH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tuesday is the day the United Nations has chosen to declare that
the human population of the Earth has reached 6 billion. To get
some idea of what this means, go to the Web site of the United
Nations Fund for Population activities (www.unfpa.org) and watch
the population clock register the rate at which new souls are being
added to our numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Or, if you like, order a copy of the 80-page State of the World
Population Report from the UN. World population is growing at the
rate of around 78 million annually, it says; a little less than the
total population of Germany is being added every year.
</P>
<P>
   Best of all, a new film, ``Six Billion and Beyond,'' by
independent filmmaker Linda Harrar, packs a great deal of
understanding into the subject. (It, too, has a Web site,
www.sixbillionandbeyond.org.)
</P>
<P>
   Filmed in six countries _ Mexico, Kenya, India, China, Italy,
and the United States _ ``Six Billion and Beyond'' was supported by
the David and Lucile Packard Foundation. It makes indelibly clear
the expectational nature of the problem. What happens next depends
on the extremely local outlook in many faraway places.
</P>
<P>
   ``Half of all those now living are under 25,'' says Harrar.
``What they decide as they reach reproductive age will determine
what the world of the next century will be like.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will have either 7 billion or 9 billion or 11 billion
people, based on the decisions that they make.''
</P>
<P>
   Those are the low, high, and median projections of global
population in 2050 by the Population Division of the UN Department
of Economic and Social Affairs.
</P>
<P>
   What do we know about the immensely complicated process summed
up in the deceptively simple phrase ``the demographic transition''?
Only the broad outlines of the process are clear.
</P>
<P>
   World population has soared chiefly because people stopped dying
as quickly. Since 1950, the death rate has been cut in half, thanks
to basic sanitation, clean drinking water, and modern health care.
Some 52 million people still die each year, or about the same
number as died in 1950. But the population is twice the size it was
then.
</P>
<P>
   As longevity has increased and development spread, fertility has
been dropping in the richer nations. In Europe, population is
shrinking, as fertility has fallen from 2.6 children per woman in
1950 to 1.4 today. In the United States and Canada, population has
more or less leveled off.
</P>
<P>
   Latin America and Asia have seen dramatic declines in fertility.
Less remarkable reductions are reported in North Africa and the
Middle East. Sub-Saharan Africa fertility is still very high by
modern standards: 5.5 children per woman today, down from 6.5 50
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   There is no magic bullet. Among the palliatives are better
health care, more education, broader job opportunities (especially
for women), and wide distribution of family planning techniques.
Trade now is generally recognized as the most efficient carrier of
these broader opportunities. Presumably those who want fewer people
and a cleaner environment generally should encourage trade and
growth.
</P>
<P>
   The big discovery in recent years has been just how great the
power of technology is to raise living standards and fend off dire
Malthusian consequences of ``overpopulation.'' Doomsday predictions
of the sort associated with Paul Erlich and the ``Club of Rome''
have gone out of style.
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't mean that overpopulation is nothing to worry about,
as some shallow optimists have concluded. Concepts such as
``carrying capacity'' and the ``ecological footprint'' of a given
population are painstakingly being worked out by ecologists,
economists, and others.
</P>
<P>
   Such considerations become especially complicated when the
propensity to global warming and the adequacy of local water
supplies are factored in. Some truly nasty surprises may lie ahead.
</P>
<P>
   The best way to proceed is cautiously _ with more research, and
heightened sensitivity to the causes and consequences of population
growth. The difference between 7 billion and 11 billion is too
important to leave to individual despair.
</P>
<P>
   (David Warsh writes about economics for the Boston Globe. His
e-mail address is warsh(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
