<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-AUCTION-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A RIVAL TO EBAY EMERGES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Half a decade ago, FairMarket Inc. founder and chief executive
Scott Randall was selling laundry detergent for Procter &AMP; Gamble. A
couple of years ago, he was selling computer parts. Today, Randall
is trying to sell everything.
</P>
<P>
   His company, based in Woburn, Mass., has emerged as a major
force in the booming Internet auction business and a serious
challenger to the dominance of auction leader eBay Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Yet you'll never purchase a set of golf clubs or Beanie Babies
from FairMarket, at least not directly. Rather than compete
directly with eBay, FairMarket works behind the scenes. The company
has won contracts to host its auctions on dozens of popular Web
sites. If you bid on merchandise on the Microsoft Network's auction
service, or offer something for sale at the Lycos or Excite search
portals, you're really using FairMarket's auction service.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think of it as a private-label eBay,'' Randall says.
</P>
<P>
   For now, FairMarket carries only around 100,000 items, far fewer
than the 3 million or so listed at eBay. But Randall is aiming for
rapid growth by weaving all of the auctions hosted by FairMarket
into a single network of wheeling and dealing.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, Boston.com is one of the FairMarket sites. If a
reader decides to auction off a set of golf clubs using the
Boston.com auction service, his item will also be available to
potential buyers on every other site that has a FairMarket auction.
So if a Microsoft Network user wants to bid on golf clubs, he'll
see the clubs listed at the Boston.com auction. In effect, it'll be
one big auction, spread across about 100 Web sites, which between
them attract 46 million visitors a month. That's almost six times
more monthly visitors than eBay attracts. (Boston.com and The
Boston Globe are both owned by The New York Times Co.)
</P>
<P>
   EBay spokesman Kevin Pursglove shrugs off the FairMarket
challenge. ``eBay users are pretty smart people,'' he said. ``We
know that they're going to keep their eyes and their ears open and
they're going to go where they can get the very best value.''
Pursglove predicts eBay's loyal users will keep the company out in
front.
</P>
<P>
   Sue Rothberg, who studies Internet auctions for Gomez Advisors
Inc. in Lincoln, thinks Pursglove's confidence is justified. ``EBay
is still the biggest and the best, period,'' she says. But she
warns that the FairMarket network could take business from other
independent auction sites.
</P>
<P>
   Randall holds an even sterner view. ``Our take on the
industry,'' he says, ``is that stand-alone sites that are
non-networked are doomed.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet that was exactly the business Randall had in mind when he
founded FairMarket in 1997 _ a stand-alone Internet auction site,
specializing in computer products.
</P>
<P>
   It was the latest career change for a self-described action
junkie. The Harvard alumnus and Harvard Business School graduate
made his mark as a brand manager for Procter &AMP; Gamble, the same
training ground that produced America Online Inc. chief executive
Steve Case.
</P>
<P>
   But somehow, peddling Dreft and Oxydol detergents began to lose
its appeal. ``Detergents are fine, but they're pretty boring,''
said Randall. ``I love a million things going on at once, nonstop
challenges . . . that's not what you get at Procter &AMP; Gamble.''
</P>
<P>
   Randall knew it was time to bail in 1994, when he got a look at
Mosaic, the first popular Internet browser. ``That's where it's
at,'' he told himself. Randall foresaw that the industries that
would grow up around the Internet would need the kind of marketing
skill he'd learned at P&AMP;G.
</P>
<P>
   His first move was to NECX Direct, of Peabody, Mass. In those
days, NECX was mainly a computer parts broker, operating an
electronic exchange on which manufacturers could bid on bulk orders
of chips and hard drives.
</P>
<P>
   But NECX founder Henry Bertolon wanted to branch out. In 1993,
he'd begun an Internet-based service for selling computer parts and
supplies. Randall believed it could be the foundation of a major
electronic retail business.
</P>
<P>
   In less than two years, Randall built the NECX on-line store
into a successful on-line enterprise. ``We were the largest Web
site in the world at the time I was running it,'' he claims.
</P>
<P>
   But when he left NECX to work for Barry Diller's Internet
Shopping Network, NECX sued, citing a non-compete agreement Randall
had signed. ``They'd sued about 30 people before, and they never
won a lawsuit,'' said Randall. ``They won this one.''
</P>
<P>
   Randall worked on Yahoo Inc.'s e-commerce business unit for a
few months, but by late 1996 he wanted to leave Silicon Valley and
return to the Bay State. The next year, he founded FairMarket in
his Beacon Hill apartment.
</P>
<P>
   Originally, the company was just another auction site, selling
computer parts, but Randall soon had a change of heart. ``I came to
the conclusion that auctions were going to be on everybody's site,
and consumers were going to go where they were already going.''
</P>
<P>
   So instead of trying to persuade Internet users to visit his
auction site, Randall decided to carry his auctions to where the
users were, striking deals with well-established sites to run
auctions for them. FairMarket gets a fee for running the auction on
its own server computers and a 1 percent cut of the selling price
of auctioned items. The Web sites that offer the auctions get a
popular new feature that can attract more traffic to their sites
and increase the prices the sites can charge to advertisers.
</P>
<P>
   It sounds like a good deal to FairMarket partners including
Charles Conn, chief executive of Ticketmaster Online-CitySearch
Inc. His company already has CityAuction, a service that runs
regional auctions targeted at communities throughout the country.
But Conn thinks FairMarket will help him maximize the number of
items for sale and the number of shoppers who might buy. ``People
want to go to the place where the most goods are, and posters want
to post where the most people are,'' Conn says.
</P>
<P>
   Gomez Advisors' Rothberg doubts that people who go to
Ticketmaster Online for concert tickets will stick around for
auctions. But if even a small percentage of visitors to FairMarket
sites participate in the auctions, that'll quickly add up to
millions of users _ enough for a very healthy business indeed.
</P>
<P>
   Randall says FairMarket itself is not for sale to some larger
entity. ``Lots of companies are interested, but it's not our
path.'' Randall's more the initial public offering type _ ``We're
going down that path right now, and talking to bankers.''
</P>
<P>
   With FairMarket's potential as a leader in e-commerce, the day
its stock goes public could be the biggest auction of them all.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
