<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPORTS-NYT-BUDGET </SLUG>
  
 Attn Sports Editors:  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sports stories from The New York Times News Service for
Wednesday, Oct. 13:
</P>
<P>
   BBN-METS-BRAVES (Atlanta) _ Mets at Atlanta, 8:12 p.m. What is
life after death like? Check out the Mets. They came to Atlanta
three weeks ago hoping to beat out the Braves for the NL East
division title and instead began a horrible slide that seemingly
cost them any role in the playoffs. But somehow they rallied and
here they are back in Atlanta, taking on the Braves in a
best-of-seven for the National League pennant. By Judy Battista.
</P>
<P>
   VECSEY-COLUMN (Atlanta) _ After being shunted to 11 p.m. time
slots in the first round of the playoffs, the Mets get a chance to
go prime time as they take on Atlanta in Game 1 of the National
League Championship Series. By George Vecsey.
</P>
<P>
   BBN-COLUMN (Atlanta) _ On Baseball on Mets-Braves. By Murray
Chass.
</P>
<P>
   BBN-BRAVES-MILLWOOD (Atlanta) _ Kevin Millwood is the least
heralded member of Atlanta's Big Four starting staff, primarily
because Greg Maddux, Tom Glavine and John Smoltz have been shutting
down the rest of the National League for so long. But right now,
Millwood might be the best pitcher Atlanta has. And he'll get the
nod in Game 2 on Wednesday afternoon. By Clifton Brown.
</P>
<P>
   BBA-YANKEES-REDSOX (Undated) _ The matchup that so many fans
wanted _ Yankees vs. Red Sox _ will take place after all. The two
teams, the proud possessors of baseball's best rivalry, have never
met in a post-season playoff series. So now they will, although
Boston will be hard-pressed to make this competitive. By Buster
Olney.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; ARATON-COLUMN (Undated) _ On the Yankees and Red Sox, who begin
their league championship series on Wednesday night. Boston won the
first World Series in this century and now, appropriately, they can
win the last one, exorcising every ghost that has accumulated
around this famously frustrated franchise. By Harvey Araton.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic on Yankee and Red Sox history.
 &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; BBA-YANKEES (Undated) _ Roger Clemens suddenly finds his quest
for a championship ring will take him back through Fenway Park; and
the Yankee outfield situation is suddenly uncertain, with Paul
O'Neill apparently sidelined for this series. By Jack Curry.
 &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BBA-REDSOX-O'LEARY (Undated) _ On Troy O'Leary, the Red Sox
outfielder who drove in seven runs with two homers in Boston's Game
5 victory over Cleveland on Monday night. By Steve Popper.
</P>
<P>
   BBA-MATCHUPS (Undated) _ Sizing up the Yankees-Red Sox series.
By Buster Olney.
</P>
<P>
   For information and repeats call the News Service at (888)
346-9867 or (212) 556-1927. And be sure to look for other sports
stories from our partners: Bloomberg News, The Boston Globe, Cox
News Service, Hearst News Service, The Arizona Republic, Kansas
City Star, Fort Worth Star-Telegram, Los Angeles Daily News, San
Francisco Chronicle and Seattle Post-Intelligencer.
</P>
