<TEXT>
<P>
   Food and dining stories from The N.Y. Times News Service for
Wednesday, Oct. 13:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FEATURES: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   WINE-YATTARNA (Nuriootpa, Australia) _ The project lasted more
than six years, and it cost at least $1 million. But it produced a
fitting white stable mate for Grange, Australia's superstar red
wine. The newcomer is called Yattarna, after an Aboriginal word
meaning ``little by little,'' and it has added new luster to the
already sterling reputation of South Australia as a world-class
producer of premium wines. (Eds: First in an En Route series.) By
R.W. Apple Jr.
</P>
<P>
   OLD-COOKBOOKS (Undated) _ Cookbooks pose an unusual problem:
Their true value can only be determined over time. I rarely refer
to cookbooks that have been published in the last couple of years.
And an informal survey of experienced home cooks, food writers,
cookbook editors and authors and bookstore owners and buyers
indicated that my experience is anything but unique. By Mark
Bittman.
</P>
<P>
   With recipes, sidebar OLD-COOKBOOKS-LIST, on runners-up.
</P>
<P>
   FULLY-COMMITTED (New York) _ ``Fully Committed,'' a one-man
play, has touched a nerve. Packed houses suggest that there are few
dishes tastier, for present-day New Yorkers, than the stew of
pretension, duplicity, avarice and cruelty bubbling under the lid
of a four-star Manhattan restaurant, and few spectacles funnier
than seeing themselves in hot, panting pursuit of a reservation.
Critic's Notebook by William Grimes.
</P>
<P>
   GRAPE-LEAVES (Undated) _ Cooking with another product of the
vine: grape leaves. By Melissa Clark. With recipes.
</P>
<P>
   GOAT-CHEESE (San Francisco) _ A new generation of goat cheeses
has inspired chefs here to create new distinctive dishes. By
Jeannette Ferrary. With recipes.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COLUMNS: &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MASTER-CHEF (New York) _ The column: How to build the perfect
sandwich: spicy grilled Cheddar. By Amy Scherber with Dorie
Greenspan.
</P>
<P>
   SIMPLE-COOKING (Undated) _ The column: Cambodianesque shrimp in
lime juice. By Mark Bittman.
</P>
<P>
   WINETALK (Undated) _ The weekly wine column: Osar, a new wine
being released in Europe now and in the U.S. this fall: an Amarone
from the Veneto region of Italy that is made with an ancient grape
called oselata. By Frank J. Prial.
</P>
<P>
   WINE-TASTING (Undated) _ A capsule wine review.
</P>
<P>
   We expect to move all Dining Section stories by early evening
with a ``d'' category code, unless otherwise indicated.
</P>
<P>
   For information and repeats call the News Service at (888)
346-9867 or (212) 556-1927. And be sure to look for other stories
from our partners: Bloomberg News, The Boston Globe, Cox News
Service, Hearst Newspapers, The Arizona Republic, Kansas City Star,
Fort Worth Star-Telegram, Los Angeles Daily News, San Francisco
Chronicle and Seattle Post-Intelligencer.
</P>
