<TEXT>
<P>
   Entertainment and culture stories from The N.Y. Times News
Service for Wednesday, Oct. 13.
</P>
<P>
   MOVIE-VIOLENCE (Washington) _ Why, despite bluster, Washington
won't crack down on controversial movies. By David E. Rosenbaum.
</P>
<P>
   ITALY-OPERA-HOUSES (Montecarlo, Italy) _ Critic's Notebook: The
little opera houses of Italy. By Bernard Holland.
</P>
<P>
   STICKLEY-STREISAND (Undated) _ The log cabin that Gustav
Stickley, American's pre-eminent proponent of the Arts and Crafts
style and one of its finest cabinetmakers, built for his family in
1911 at Craftsman Farm in Parsippany, N.J., has become a sort of
battleground between the arts and craft community and, yes, Barbra
Streisand, who plans to auction two antique corner tables designed
by Stickley. By William L. Hamilton.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; BEEFCAKE-FILM-REVIEW (Undated) _ Stephen Holden reviews
``Beefcake,'' directed by Thom Fitzgerald.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; CREMASTER(AT)-FILM-REVIEW (Undated) _ Stephen Holden reviews
``Cremaster 2,'' directed by Mathew Barney.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; FRENCH-BOOK-REVIEW (Undated) _ Richard Bernstein reviews ``French
DNA: Trouble in Purgatory,'' by Paul Rabinow (Univ. of Chicago
Press).
</P>
<P>
   PHOTOGRAPHY-TV-REVIEW (Undated) _ Caryn James reviews ``American
Photography: A Century of Images,'' on PBS.
</P>
<P>
   KINGBISCUIT-FESTIVAL (Helena, Ark.) _ The 14th annual King
Biscuit Blues Festival took place last week, and in doing so
overcame what may have been the greatest odds ever stacked against
it. By Neil Strauss.
</P>
<P>
   For information and repeats call the News Service at (888)
346-9867 or (212) 556-1927. And be sure to look for other
entertainment stories from our partners: Bloomberg News, The Boston
Globe, Cox News Service, Hearst Newspapers, The Houston Chronicle,
The Arizona Republic, Kansas City Star, Fort Worth Star-Telegram,
Los Angeles Daily News, San Francisco Chronicle and Seattle
Post-Intelligencer.
