<HEADER>
A4356 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a BC-TRANSVESTITE-SCHOOL-I     10-12 1203
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRANSVESTITE-SCHOOL-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INSIDE MADAME DURELL'S SCHOOL FOR TRANSSEXUALS  
 
</HEADLINE>
   (This quirky 1,000-word ``separate buy'' article is from THE
INDEPENDENT newspaper in London.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If unable to reach Ms.
Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``i'' international news files.)  
  
 By IMRE KARACS  
 c.1999 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The voice at the other end of the line sounds cautious. Madame
Durell gets all sorts of crank calls, from people shopping around
for false breasts or lingerie in men's sizes, or from voyeurs like
me.
</P>
<P>
   Some desperate souls will stop at nothing to take a peek inside
Madame Durell's decadent villa in Spandau.
</P>
<P>
   Credentials established, I ring the bell at the gate of the
International School of Travesty. An alsatian growls menacingly,
the front door opens, and Madame Durell stands on the threshold. He
squeezes my hand firmly.
</P>
<P>
   The place looks like the high-class brothel it is rumored to be
in the neighborhood: tasteful antique furniture at ground level and
an all-marble interior straight out of Pompeii down below. At the
far end of the pool in the basement stands a mini-jungle of plastic
palm trees, backing on to one of the establishment's many walls of
mirrors.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors will spend hours ogling their reflections, watching
their shapes, movements and mannerisms slowly transcend the
boundary of gender.
</P>
<P>
   It takes four months to turn a willing male into a passable
female, at least in outward appearance. Four months and Dm35,000
(nearly $20,000). That's how much the course in travesty costs, at
the end of which successful students receive a state-recognized
diploma from Madame Durell, a chartered travesty pedagogue.
</P>
<P>
   This is, after all, a serious educational establishment. On
Berlin's bustling variety scene, travesty is regarded as one of the
highest forms of art, and Madame Durell, who goes by the name of
Sascha Nowak-Tarnawa in his passport, as one of its greatest
exponents.
</P>
<P>
   Berlin, he says, boasts more registered travesty artists _ some
620 _ than any other city in the world. And while New York has its
transvestite school and Amsterdam a school for transsexuals, his is
the only establishment in the world dedicated to the noble art of
cross-dressing.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone understands the school's true mission. ``We have
women aged between 50 and 65 who want to learn striptease for the
benefit of their husbands,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Nowak-Tarnawa is the old-fashioned type. He does not believe
in ``using the human body _ male or female _ for entertainment,
unless it's in the cultural context.''
</P>
<P>
   And his standards are rigorous: only art of the most sublime is
to be pursued on his premises. ``We have an entrance exam. When we
find out that the applicant is just a drag queen, he has to go,''
says Mr. Nowak-Tarnawa.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, he admits the school gets all sorts. One of the
star pupils is a 74-year-old blind psychoanalyst _ happily married
_ who is here to find out what makes women click. He is only doing
the dance part of the course.
</P>
<P>
   Torsten, a 27-year-old waiter, is signed up for the full Monty.
He is unsure whether dressing up as a woman is his real calling,
but he loves playing roles, especially the role of women. Today is
Torsten's first day at Madame Durell's school. He is excited, and a
little nervous.
</P>
<P>
   We take the elevator up to Madame Durell's boudoir: yet more
marble, gilded taps, exquisite robes hanging in the wardrobe, among
them an embroidered folk costume from Mr. Nowak-Tarnawa's native
Poland.
</P>
<P>
   Torsten's first lesson is makeup. He picks out the longest false
eyelashes, applies the foundation with care, but is a little
overexuberant with the lipstick. An hour passes, and Torsten is
still not ready.
</P>
<P>
   We chat as he applies the brush strokes and plucks his eyebrows.
He worked on a cruise liner for two years, scraping the pennies
together for the course.
</P>
<P>
   He would not say it was his life's ambition to go around dressed
in women's clothes, and nor was the family terribly excited about
his further education. ``My mother was taken aback at first, but
now she is more relaxed and says: `If that's what makes you happy,
go ahead.'''
</P>
<P>
   His friends think it is a great idea. ``But I know there is a
lot of work ahead of me.'' More, maybe, than he had reckoned with.
From the makeup room, Torsten goes to the room next to the swimming
pool for a singing lesson.
</P>
<P>
   Standing ramrod straight, feet spread out next to the keyboard
in his black ballet shoes, black trousers with a white line running
down the sides and black sweater, he resembles an overgrown
penguin. Not to worry _ the posture lesson comes later.
</P>
<P>
   Julia, the Polish singing teacher, strikes a few keys. Torsten
has to sing the notes, and he does it well. He has a beautiful
baritone voice, but, alas, cannot rise to the high Cs.
</P>
<P>
   The acting class goes better. Priscilla, an actress from
California who plans to stage deaf cabaret next year in Devon,
England, devises a series of situations for her new student.
</P>
<P>
   ``You come through the door, you are a hero,'' she instructs.
Torsten enters, strutting unconvincingly. ``Let's try something
else,'' she says. ``You will now play a queen.'' Torsten obliges,
delicately guiding the imaginary crinoline through the gap of the
door, and this time the illusion works.
</P>
<P>
   Then it's on to the dance floor, with another American teacher,
Donna, in attendance. First Torsten is a chorus girl, wriggling his
hips to the theme song from ``Cabaret.'' You can tell he has done
this sort of thing before. ``He's doing well,'' whispers Priscilla.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is some Mozart, with Torsten, a head taller than his
teacher, led around the floor. It will take a while before he
masters this, but if he turns out to be good, he will get a chance
to dance Flamenco in high heels.
</P>
<P>
   Torsten has worked hard on his first day, and as a reward is
allowed to wear Madame Durell's silk dress.
</P>
<P>
   It is hard to tell four months before graduation, but he looks
promising. ``We still have to work on the style,'' says Mr.
Nowak-Tarnawa. ``But when you know who you are, it will all fall
into place.'' &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this curious 1,000-word article from THE INDEPENDENT
newspaper in London, it must be purchased from the New York Times
Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or
fax her at 732-390-4697. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please
call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
