<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991012.0153 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-12 15:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4388 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a BC-SPRINT-MCI-ALARM-ECON     10-12 1131
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPRINT-MCI-ALARM-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCI WORLDCOM TAKEOVER OF SPRINT CALLS FOR CLOSE SCRUTINY  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary Editors....and Kansas/Missouri, Miss.)   (This excellent 900-word ``separate buy'' article is from the
current (week beginning 9 Oct. 1999) Economist magazine.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada except to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If
unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at
816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into the ``f''
financial news, ``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary
news files.)  
  
 c.1999 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
 (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The $115 billion that MCI WorldCom has agreed to pay for Sprint,
a rival American long-distance telecoms firm, is a spectacular sum,
albeit in shares rather than cash.
</P>
<P>
   Yet even world-record-breaking deals no longer seem as exciting
as they once did. And all too often there is little to show that
these mergers will, in the long run, benefit shareholders or, more
important, customers.
</P>
<P>
   By these tests, it is hard to be enthusiastic about this latest
deal either. Recent big mergers in industries from banking to oil
have been driven partly by an outbreak of me-tooism and a frothy
and surprisingly uncritical stock market.
</P>
<P>
   They have also, more promisingly, been about an unrelenting
search by big firms for economies of scale. But it is in telecoms
that the action has been most frantic.
</P>
<P>
   The data revolution triggered by the Internet and the explosive
growth of mobile telephones have made previously dull-seeming
utilities appear the acme of techno-glamour.
</P>
<P>
   Since the Telecommunications Act of 1996, the telecoms map of
America has been redrawn. The Baby Bell local phone companies,
created after the breakup of AT&AMP;T in 1984, have all but ceased to
exist. In their place stand two supra-regional monsters, SBC in the
West and Bell Atlantic in the East, which have systematically
absorbed their neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   The only independent Baby Bell left is BellSouth, which entered
the bidding for Sprint with a late offer that MCI WorldCom, with
its more highly rated shares, was easily able to trump. BellSouth
may itself now be vulnerable.
</P>
<P>
   As for the new-look AT&AMP;T, having floundered in its early
attempts to enter local markets, it has bought a big chunk of the
American cable industry in order to gain direct access to
residential customers _ the vital ``last mile.''
</P>
<P>
   And then there is MCI WorldCom, which, thanks to the deal-making
of Bernie Ebbers, its boss, has gone from upstart to behemoth in a
little over two years.
</P>
<P>
   It would be easy to see the acquisition of Sprint as just
another mammoth deal, with little effect on competition. Yet to
view this deal complacently would be a mistake. In two respects it
should raise anti-competitive worries inside the Federal
Communications Commission (FCC).
</P>
<P>
   The most obvious is that, if America's second and third
long-distance operators join forces, and there is no significant
fourth firm, competition may suffer.
</P>
<P>
   Ebbers points out that the merged entity would still have a
smaller market share (just) than AT&AMP;T, that it is only a matter of
time before the two new ``mega-Bells'' are let into the
long-distance market and that new challengers such as Qwest are
popping up.
</P>
<P>
   All that is true. But it may take a few years for the newcomers
to get a national presence in long-distance _ and the scope for
tacit collusion between the big two may be worrying.
</P>
<P>
   Further ahead, the FCC should have another concern. One reason
for the wave of restructuring in American telecoms is the belief
that, to achieve customer ``stickiness'' and generate scale
economies in such areas as billing, operators need to offer a
bundle of at least four services _ long-distance, Internet, local
and wireless.
</P>
<P>
   In Europe, the same trend is visible, as a handful of firms such
as BT and Deutsche Telekom evolve into super-regional carriers.
</P>
<P>
   In America, only AT&AMP;T, with its cable strategy, and Sprint, with
its Integrated On-demand Network technology, are on the verge of
packaging together such a bundle.
</P>
<P>
   MCI WorldCom has no wireless service, the main reason for its
bid for Sprint; and SBC and Bell Atlantic have no long-distance
presence _ but, one way or another, they soon will. The question is
whether a potential five competing integrated operators should be
trimmed to only four.
</P>
<P>
   MCI WorldCom is resigned to appeasing regulators in America and
Europe by disposing of Sprint's Internet-backbone business.
</P>
<P>
   At a pinch, Ebbers might even be willing to sell Sprint's
long-distance network, if that was the price for carrying off
Sprint's mobile operation. But an ``orphaned'' long-distance
network would do little for competition.
</P>
<P>
   The FCC's chairman, Bill Kennard, is right to have put Ebbers on
notice that he can expect his deal to be skeptically scrutinized.
Ebbers is sufficiently worried to have raised the spectre of the
rapacious foreigner.
</P>
<P>
   If he is not allowed to buy Sprint, he says it will fall into
the hands of Deutsche Telekom. Yet from a competitive perspective,
the German firm would be an ideal owner for Sprint, because it has
money to spend on developing it into a more formidable operator.
</P>
<P>
   The political odds and the weight of Wall Street expectations
are, nevertheless, such that it would take a bold FCC to stop this
deal. And despite the competitive concerns it raises, the telecoms
business is changing so quickly that it is not clear that it
should.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the FCC should consider using this merger as the basis
for a less antagonistic, even if still rigorous, relationship with
the Bells.
</P>
<P>
   What is needed now is a ``fast track'' towards achieving the
opening of the local market so as to qualify the Bells for offering
long-distance service. It would involve some compromise on both
sides. But at least that would be a deal that put the customer
first. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this 900-word article, it must be purchased _ the rate
is not prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales
representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at
732-390-4697. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITORS: Please note that this article is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-12-99 1524EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991012.0154 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-12 15:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4404 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-TEEN-READERS17-COX     10-12 0861
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEEN-READERS17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    THIS WEEK, TEENS CAN READ 'FOR THE FUN OF IT'
 &HT;    480&AMP;add. Moving in (w) Washington and (l) lifestyle categories
for release Sunday, Oct. 17.
 &HT;    With TEEN-LIST sidebar
 &HT;    By ANDREW MOLLISON
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ There are all sorts of spinach-is-good-for-you
justifications for Teens Read Week, which runs from Oct. 17 to 23.
</P>
<P>
   Students who said they read for more than 11 minutes a day did
better than others on recent national tests of reading and writing
skills. As adults, readers tend to get and keep the best jobs.
</P>
<P>
   But the three celebrities recruited by librarians and
booksellers to convince teens to find time to read ``for the fun of
it'' don't tout tomes on self-improvement. When asked for their
favorite books, all invoked the pleasure principle, recommending
fiction with gripping plots:
</P>
<P>
   -- World-class figure skater Michelle Kwan liked Arthur Golden's
first novel, ``Memoirs of a Geisha.''
</P>
<P>
   -- WNBA basketball player Rebecca Lobo of the New York Liberty
liked Shel Silverstein's mysterious fable ``The Giving Tree.''
</P>
<P>
   -- NFL football player Tim Dwight of the Atlanta Falcons liked
``all'' of the Clive Cussler novels about swashbuckling adventurer
Dirk Pitt.
</P>
<P>
   ``Reluctant'' readers among teenagers present a special
challenge, said writer Diana Texier Herald, chair of a committee of
librarians who sifted through more than 1,000 new books to choose
10 with the greatest appeal to that group of teens.
</P>
<P>
   ``Keep in mind that reluctant readers aren't necessarily bad
readers,'' Herald said. ``But it's hard to pick a sure-fire winner
for someone else.''
</P>
<P>
   She said some teens who avoid recreational reading ``had to read
stuff they didn't like for school, so they don't like reading
because of that.''
</P>
<P>
   But even avid readers spend less time reading once they reach
their teens. ``In school and after school, they have so much else
going on,'' Herald said.
</P>
<P>
   Her committee of the Young Adult Library Services Association
began months ago to assemble ``top 10 quick picks'' for reluctant
teen readers.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the committee's 11 members tested their hunches on
groups of teens, usually from advisory committees at public or
school libraries. Herald's regular advisers include three dozen
boys and girls confined in a detention facility near her home in
Grand Junction, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of the kids there had never read a book before; they
were busy getting into trouble instead of reading,'' she said.
``Now, they're a captive audience.''
</P>
<P>
   Like other reluctant readers, those youngsters often lean toward
how-to books, adventure stories, short-story collections or graphic
novels, which are thick comic books. Herald said that the detained
youth don't necessarily zero in on the thinnest volumes, since
``sometimes they can only go to the library once a week.''
</P>
<P>
   Publishers submitted more than 1,000 books issued between July
1997 and December 1998. Each book was read by at least two
committee members.
</P>
<P>
   The members nominated nearly 300 books. Then, in a series of
votes, they narrowed that down to 46 fiction and 28 non-fiction
books published by 32 different publisher imprints.
</P>
<P>
   All 74 finalists, including the Top 10 list of those titles with
the most votes, are posted on a Web site
(http://www.ala.org/yalsa/booklists/99top10quick.html).
</P>
<P>
   The Top 10 for reluctant readers runs the gamut from two Star
Wars manuals to a graphic novel about a teenage single mother, and
from an inside look at the pop sensations 'N Sync to a traditional
novel about an obsessive-compulsive 11-year-old who insists on
touching a doorknob and kissing her fingers 33 times whenever she
leaves the house.
</P>
<P>
   ``If anything ties them together, it's that the authors respect
their readers as people who are almost adults, and don't see them
as children,'' Herald said. ``But reading is a personal taste. Few
people would like every one.''
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add that can stand alone as a Teen
Reads Week sidebar follows.)
</P>
<P>
   About one-fourth of the card-holders at the nation's public
libraries are between the ages of 12 and 18, said Mary Arnold, vice
president of the Young Adults Library Services Association. But
many of the teens she meets at her library in the Cuyahoga county
suburbs of Cleveland, Ohio, are working on school assignments.
</P>
<P>
   ``When teens hear that adults want them to read, they think we
mean 'Moby-Dick' or Charles Dickens,'' Arnold said. ``The whole
purpose of Teens Read Week is to get teens to read for fun again.''
</P>
<P>
   They don't even have to start with books, said Clearwater, Fla.,
librarian Jana Fine, president of the association.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could be magazines, cereal boxes, newspapers, Internet
screens,'' Fine said. ``What we know is that if you manage to get
through middle school without losing your love of reading, you'll
keep it up.''
</P>
<P>
   Details about Teens Read Week, and a variety of Top 10 lists for
various types of teen readers, are available on the Internet
(http://www.ala.org/teenread/). (cq)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
