<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEEN-READERS17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    THIS WEEK, TEENS CAN READ 'FOR THE FUN OF IT'
 &HT;    480&AMP;add. Moving in (w) Washington and (l) lifestyle categories
for release Sunday, Oct. 17.
 &HT;    With TEEN-LIST sidebar
 &HT;    By ANDREW MOLLISON
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ There are all sorts of spinach-is-good-for-you
justifications for Teens Read Week, which runs from Oct. 17 to 23.
</P>
<P>
   Students who said they read for more than 11 minutes a day did
better than others on recent national tests of reading and writing
skills. As adults, readers tend to get and keep the best jobs.
</P>
<P>
   But the three celebrities recruited by librarians and
booksellers to convince teens to find time to read ``for the fun of
it'' don't tout tomes on self-improvement. When asked for their
favorite books, all invoked the pleasure principle, recommending
fiction with gripping plots:
</P>
<P>
   -- World-class figure skater Michelle Kwan liked Arthur Golden's
first novel, ``Memoirs of a Geisha.''
</P>
<P>
   -- WNBA basketball player Rebecca Lobo of the New York Liberty
liked Shel Silverstein's mysterious fable ``The Giving Tree.''
</P>
<P>
   -- NFL football player Tim Dwight of the Atlanta Falcons liked
``all'' of the Clive Cussler novels about swashbuckling adventurer
Dirk Pitt.
</P>
<P>
   ``Reluctant'' readers among teenagers present a special
challenge, said writer Diana Texier Herald, chair of a committee of
librarians who sifted through more than 1,000 new books to choose
10 with the greatest appeal to that group of teens.
</P>
<P>
   ``Keep in mind that reluctant readers aren't necessarily bad
readers,'' Herald said. ``But it's hard to pick a sure-fire winner
for someone else.''
</P>
<P>
   She said some teens who avoid recreational reading ``had to read
stuff they didn't like for school, so they don't like reading
because of that.''
</P>
<P>
   But even avid readers spend less time reading once they reach
their teens. ``In school and after school, they have so much else
going on,'' Herald said.
</P>
<P>
   Her committee of the Young Adult Library Services Association
began months ago to assemble ``top 10 quick picks'' for reluctant
teen readers.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the committee's 11 members tested their hunches on
groups of teens, usually from advisory committees at public or
school libraries. Herald's regular advisers include three dozen
boys and girls confined in a detention facility near her home in
Grand Junction, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of the kids there had never read a book before; they
were busy getting into trouble instead of reading,'' she said.
``Now, they're a captive audience.''
</P>
<P>
   Like other reluctant readers, those youngsters often lean toward
how-to books, adventure stories, short-story collections or graphic
novels, which are thick comic books. Herald said that the detained
youth don't necessarily zero in on the thinnest volumes, since
``sometimes they can only go to the library once a week.''
</P>
<P>
   Publishers submitted more than 1,000 books issued between July
1997 and December 1998. Each book was read by at least two
committee members.
</P>
<P>
   The members nominated nearly 300 books. Then, in a series of
votes, they narrowed that down to 46 fiction and 28 non-fiction
books published by 32 different publisher imprints.
</P>
<P>
   All 74 finalists, including the Top 10 list of those titles with
the most votes, are posted on a Web site
(http://www.ala.org/yalsa/booklists/99top10quick.html).
</P>
<P>
   The Top 10 for reluctant readers runs the gamut from two Star
Wars manuals to a graphic novel about a teenage single mother, and
from an inside look at the pop sensations 'N Sync to a traditional
novel about an obsessive-compulsive 11-year-old who insists on
touching a doorknob and kissing her fingers 33 times whenever she
leaves the house.
</P>
<P>
   ``If anything ties them together, it's that the authors respect
their readers as people who are almost adults, and don't see them
as children,'' Herald said. ``But reading is a personal taste. Few
people would like every one.''
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add that can stand alone as a Teen
Reads Week sidebar follows.)
</P>
<P>
   About one-fourth of the card-holders at the nation's public
libraries are between the ages of 12 and 18, said Mary Arnold, vice
president of the Young Adults Library Services Association. But
many of the teens she meets at her library in the Cuyahoga county
suburbs of Cleveland, Ohio, are working on school assignments.
</P>
<P>
   ``When teens hear that adults want them to read, they think we
mean 'Moby-Dick' or Charles Dickens,'' Arnold said. ``The whole
purpose of Teens Read Week is to get teens to read for fun again.''
</P>
<P>
   They don't even have to start with books, said Clearwater, Fla.,
librarian Jana Fine, president of the association.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could be magazines, cereal boxes, newspapers, Internet
screens,'' Fine said. ``What we know is that if you manage to get
through middle school without losing your love of reading, you'll
keep it up.''
</P>
<P>
   Details about Teens Read Week, and a variety of Top 10 lists for
various types of teen readers, are available on the Internet
(http://www.ala.org/teenread/). (cq)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
