r e BC-TV-NOVA-REVIEW-SFCHRO     10-12 0640
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-NOVA-REVIEW-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`NOVA': DON'T BOOK THAT TIME TRAVEL VACATION JUST YET 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds.: Review of UPN's ``The Strip'' follows.)  
 By JOHN CARMAN  
 c.1999, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The celebrated physicist Stephen Hawking, appearing on ``Nova''
Tuesday, is something of a killjoy on the topic of time machines.
</P>
<P>
   ``Time travel might be possible,'' he admits. ``But if that is
the case, why haven't we been overrun by tourists from the
future?''
</P>
<P>
   To which some of us might ask, who's to say we haven't? I think
one of them even got elected governor in Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   But ``Nova'' covers all its bases in a show that looks seriously
and compellingly at the possibility of time travel.
</P>
<P>
   The late Carl Sagan, Mr. Cosmos, says on the program that
tourists from the future might have mastered invisibility. So
there.
</P>
<P>
   Other scientists, skeptics all, say they see no chance of a time
machine that can go back farther than when the machine itself was
invented. I'd explain, but I'm stupid.
</P>
<P>
   The guesswork involves a wormhole in space, much as California
Institute of Technology physicist Kip Thorne suggested to Sagan for
Sagan's book ``Contact,'' which became the Jodie Foster movie.
</P>
<P>
   That's what introduced wormholes to science fiction. The idea is
to give a speedy flight to one end of the wormhole so that, in
accordance with Einstein's theory of relativity, it's at a
different place in time than the stationary end. Then the time
traveler enters the wormhole at one place in time and exits in
another. Piece of cake.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, maybe not. Hawking, Thorne and others conclude,
perhaps wistfully, that it'll probably never happen.
</P>
<P>
   Hawking ends the program, though, with the kind of joke that
makes theoretical physicists grab their protons and double up with
laughter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't take a bet against the existence of time
machines,'' he says. ``My opponent might have seen the future and
know the answer.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
-0- &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Now for a forlorn little adventure in TV time travel. It's
called ``The Strip,'' it's on UPN and it premieres Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Let's see, two cops cruising their town in a convertible, to a
driving overlay of music. The white cop, with the dirty blond hair,
is a slob who lives on a boat. His black partner used to work in a
big northeastern city.
</P>
<P>
   And watch out for the creature named Elvis.
</P>
<P>
   For 40 points, name the show. (set ital)Ding! Ding! Ding!(end
ital) It is indeed ``The Strip,'' but our judges also will accept
``Miami Vice.''
</P>
<P>
   It's just that ``The Strip'' is a poor man's ``Miami Vice.'' A
pauper's ``Miami Vice.'' I had a feeling they squandered the whole
season's budget when they blew up a trailer home for Tuesday
night's show.
</P>
<P>
   Elvis was Don Johnson's pet alligator in ``Miami Vice.'' Here
he's Elvis Ford (Sean Patrick Flanery), and a little less brainy.
He's the slovenly one. His partner is Jesse Weir (Guy Torry). He's
the one who apparently believes that acting consists of rolling his
eyes.
</P>
<P>
   To be fair, there's plenty of eye-rolling material in ``The
Strip.''
</P>
<P>
   The two Las Vegas detectives promptly become ex-cops when Elvis
punches out their supervising lieutenant. So they take jobs as
private dicks working for the manager of Caesars Palace.
</P>
<P>
   Caesars Palace made a deal with the show's producer, Joel Silver
(``Die Hard,'' ``Lethal Weapon''). I wonder how they'll feel when
they see that the chain-smoking, pockmarked Joe Viterelli, a man
born to play mobsters, is cast as the hotel's manager.
</P>
<P>
   The show is a high-test testosterone affair with bullets,
fistfights, fast cars, fast food, babes in thongs, one babe in
bondage and the aforementioned mobile home that goes boom in the
night.
</P>
<P>
   If only ``The Strip'' could imitate that instead of someone
else's show.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
