<HEADLINE>
TEXAS FIREFIGHTING TEAM BATTLES 40-ACRE TIRE FIRE IN CALIF. 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JANE KAY  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WESTLEY, Calif. _ They've battled big blazes from the Persian
Gulf to the Gulf of Mexico, emerging victorious more than 100
times.
</P>
<P>
   Now Dwight and Randy Williams, a brother-sister team with one of
the world's great firefighting pedigrees, are face-to-face with
something they've never confronted: a smoldering 40-acre expanse of
7 million tires.
</P>
<P>
   Ignited Sept. 22 when lightning hit the former Oxford Tire
Recycling dump here, the fire could persist for a year. Williams
Fire and Hazard Control Inc., of Mauriceville, Texas, was brought
in by the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency to try to contain
the fire and quell the billows of toxic smoke that had spread
across the western San Joaquin Valley.
</P>
<P>
   ``That fire is awesome. It's beautiful,'' declared Randy
Williams, 45, who like her brother, who is 52, was attracted as a
teenager to the family business run by their father, Les.
</P>
<P>
   But, said Dwight Williams, the blaze is stealing resources,
money, life and health. ``Our job is to kill the thief,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   So far they've managed to dramatically reduce the pall of smoke
by dousing a raging oil fire fueled by melted runoff from the
tires. With a crew of two dozen they're using special foam to
suppress the flames as thousands of gallons of oil continue to melt
off the burning rubber.
</P>
<P>
   Putting out the main fire is another story.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a big job because of the resources, manpower and
length of job,'' said Randy Williams. ``But the crew would rather
be at a large gasoline or crude oil storage tank fire. It's more
thrilling to them,'' she said. ``This fire never goes away. It's
demoralizing and very taxing for our people.''
</P>
<P>
   Dwight Williams added, ``With an oil fire, you rig up for maybe
two hours and put it out in 30 minutes. For this one, you rig up
every day. You beat a piece of it back. And you do it again the
next day.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to fighting the fire, they're trying to remove as
many tires as possible from the path of the flames.
</P>
<P>
   Working close to the fire, they're using tractors with long
mechanical arms to grab tires. Meanwhile IT Group Inc. of
Monroeville, Pa., which was hired by the EPA as the master
contractor, is working farther from the flames, using excavators
and other heavy machinery to push aside big piles of tires. So far
the EPA has paid IT $1.25 million.
</P>
<P>
   Williams and IT are hoping to protect another expanse of tires
uphill from the main dump and about a quarter of its size.
</P>
<P>
   The Williamses know the bravery, the daring, the lore, the
history and the emerging technology of their trade. So far, in the
fires they've extinguished, there have been no worker injuries at
tankers, storage tanks and refineries for Texaco, Tenneco, Exxon,
Chevron, Shell and other major oil companies.
</P>
<P>
   Terry Brubaker, chief of the EPA's emergency response office in
San Francisco, said the Williamses were chosen because of their
reputation and experience.
</P>
<P>
   Dwight Williams, president and CEO, is in charge of fighting
fires. Randy Williams, vice president, directs logistics and
contract fulfillment.
</P>
<P>
   They never take vacations, said Dwight, who hasn't had more than
seven days off in a row for 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   Their father, Les, who was a legend in the firefighting
business, died of a heart attack at age 68 in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Les Williams was part of a team at Jefferson Chemical, now
Texaco Chemical, that in the early 1960s designed the first foam
made of hydrocarbons instead of animal fats.
</P>
<P>
   In 1980, Les and Dwight Williams formed Boots and Coots Fire
Protective Equipment Co. with Boots Hansen and Coots Matthews, lead
firefighters with Red Adair, the famed Houston capper of
out-of-control oil or gas well fires.
</P>
<P>
   The Williamses bought out the company and changed to the present
name in 1991. Over the years they invented and modified nozzle
systems, making it possible to apply foam with greater precision
and effectiveness.
</P>
<P>
   One of Dwight Williams' earliest jobs was on the Amazon River in
Manaus, Brazil, when he was 26.
</P>
<P>
   As a ship burned gasoline and diesel, part of the deck blew up,
blasting steel and paint in every direction. Watching Williams
stand his ground, locals started yelling, ``John Wayne. John
Wayne!'' In 1969, John Wayne dramatized the exploits of Red Adair
in the movie ``The Hellfighters.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1984, the company put out a blaze that had burned for decades
on the Hudson River at the 97-acre PJP landfill in Jersey City
across from New York. It took 48 days, 14 hours a day to extinguish
the flames.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Energy Department sent the company to assess the
possibility of fire or terrorism at the Trans-Alaska pipeline in
1986. The Defense Department sent Dwight Williams to Saudi Arabia
during the Persian Gulf War to respond to fires at refineries,
tankers or pipelines.
</P>
<P>
   During the Mississippi River floods in 1996, the company worked
for the city of St. Louis to prevent a catastrophic accident at
storage tanks threatened by rising waters. The firm's workers
vented the gas and built equipment to safely recapture it.
</P>
<P>
   In Monserrat in the West Indies, a volcano belched lava and ash
in 1998, threatening to push two large pressured liquid petroleum
gas tanks into the ocean. Dwight Williams, at times standing on 3
feet of ash, flared off 22,000 gallons of fuel and emptied the
tanks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
