<HEADLINE>
SHRIMP SIMMERED IN LIME 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By MARK BITTMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Few people I know have gone food hunting in Cambodia, so I was
curious when Deb Winson, a New York-based food stylist, came back
with an ecstatic report. ``Everything was so fresh and beautiful,
and everything was so simple,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   When I asked her to describe her favorite, dish she told me
about a great preparation for shrimp cooked in lime. The
ingredients were much as I expected: limes, sugar, salt, chilies
and garlic, all common in Southeast Asian cooking. But the
technique sounded unusual. The shrimp were not stir-fried, as you
might expect, but instead were simmered in a very pungent sauce so
that they took on strong flavor and still stayed juicy.
</P>
<P>
   For the sauce, she said, ``they started with salt, sugar and
lime, then kept tasting, adding, stirring, tasting, adding,
stirring, until they were happy with the flavor.''
</P>
<P>
   This sounded like something I could handle, so I set out to
recreate the dish. The result may not be entirely authentic, but it
is really good, a striking balance of mildly sweet and
mouth-puckeringly sour. It is also ridiculously fast, assuming you
start with peeled shrimp. If you start cooking rice before tackling
the shrimp, they will both be done 20 minutes later. (Peeling the
shrimp should take 10 minutes.)
</P>
<P>
   Be sure to heat the pan and oil sufficiently, so that the garlic
browns lightly without burning. Let the lime-and-sugar mixture cook
until it is syrupy; this won't take long, about three minutes, but
it will guarantee that the liquid coats the shrimp nicely.
</P>
<P>
   The shrimp themselves, Ms. Winson said, should be ``huge''
prawns, with their heads on if possible. There are benefits of
head-on shrimp: they might be fresh, or even alive, when you buy
them; they make for an impressive presentation, and it's fun to
suck the juices out of the heads. But I had good results with
shrimp of all sizes.
</P>
<P>
   SHRIMP IN SPICY LIME SAUCE
</P>
<P>
   Time: 20 to 30 minutes
</P>
<P>
   About { cup lime juice (3 or 4 limes)
</P>
<P>
   \ cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon salt to taste
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons neutral oil, like canola or grape seed
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon minced garlic
</P>
<P>
   { teaspoon crushed red chili flakes, or to taste
</P>
<P>
   1{ pounds peeled shrimp, or 3 pounds head-on shrimp, left
unpeeled
</P>
<P>
   Minced cilantro for garnish.
</P>
<P>
   1. In a small bowl, combine the lime juice, sugar and salt.
Place oil in a 10- or 12-inch skillet, and turn the heat to high. A
minute later, add the garlic and chili flakes and cook the garlic
until it just begins to brown. Immediately add the lime juice
mixture all at once, and cook until it reduces by half, or even
more, 3 to 5 minutes. There should be only about \ cup of liquid in
the skillet, and it should be syrupy.
</P>
<P>
   2. Add the shrimp, and cook over high heat. The shrimp will give
off liquid of their own and begin to turn pink almost immediately.
After about 2 minutes, stir contents of pan. Continue cooking,
stirring occasionally until all the shrimp are pink, about 4
minutes total. Taste, adjust seasoning, garnish with cilantro and
serve with rice.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
