<DOCNO> NYT19991012.0177 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-12 16:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4443 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d BC-WINE-TALK-NYT &LR;      10-12 0832
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINE-TALK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A MIGHTY VALPOLICELLA THAT'S A SECRET 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By FRANK J. PRIAL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   VERONA, Italy _ At a restaurant in Verona recently I was offered
a remarkable red wine, one I had never heard of before. It was
called Osar, and the restaurant owner was reluctant to talk about
it. ``Ask Sandro Boscaini at Masi,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, I did. Boscaini is president of Masi Agricola, one
of the best-known producers of Valpolicella wines. For six
generations, his family has owned the company in Gargagnago, a
20-minute drive northwest of Verona.
</P>
<P>
   At first, he was equally hesitant to talk, but finally agreed to
tell me a bit about Osar. It was, he said by way of introduction, a
wine that might just change the way the world perceives the wines
of Valpolicella. The story goes back decades.
</P>
<P>
   Valpolicella was one of the lighthearted Italian wines, along
with Bardolino and Soave, that Americans fell in love with in the
years after World War II. Valpolicella, the best of the group, and
Bardolino are red; Soave is white. To meet the demand in the late
1950s, millions of gallons of these wines were exported every year,
and inevitably quality suffered and consumers turned to other
Italian wines, notably Chianti. In recent years, local producers
have worked to restore the reputation of Valpolicella.
</P>
<P>
   Because of its northern location _ on clear days, the Alps are
quite visible _ this region is not an optimum one for growing
high-quality red grapes. So to make their best red wine, called
Amarone, Valpolicella producers have long resorted to appassimento,
the ancient practice of partly drying their best grapes before
fermentation.
</P>
<P>
   Extra-ripe grapes are spread out on bamboo panels and left in
cool lofts for three or four months. As they dry out, the grapes
lose up to a third of their weight, but their sugar and flavor
elements remain in a highly concentrated form.
</P>
<P>
   When the grapes are crushed and fermented, usually in January or
February, the resulting powerful wine can contain 16 percent
alcohol or more, compared with around 11 percent for a simple
Valpolicella.
</P>
<P>
   Still another special wine is produced by adding newly made
Valpolicella to Amarone pomace _ the pits, stems and skins left in
the fermenting vats after the wine has been drawn off. The
Valpolicella remains in contact with the pomace for about two
weeks, picking up additional color and tannins. This process is
called ripasso, because the young wine is said to have been passed
over the pomace.
</P>
<P>
   At the Masi estate, where the ripasso version of Valpolicella is
called Campo Fiorin, the Boscainis have never been satisfied with
the traditional methods.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have always wanted to make a big, red wine to compete with
the best Piemontese and Tuscan wines,'' Boscaini said, ``but we
thought we were too far north. Hence Amarone and the ripasso
wines.''
</P>
<P>
   But Boscaini and his brother, Sergio, who is Masi's chief wine
maker, had heard of a long-forgotten grape, native to the region,
that was said to have once produced a full-flavored, robust red
wine that had no need for additional processing. The grape,
oseletta, had been abandoned many years ago because it was
difficult to grow and produced only a tiny and very uneconomical
crop.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like a detective story,'' Sandro Boscaini said. ``We
found a grower who had four vines. Four vines! But we took them and
began to work with them.''
</P>
<P>
   That was 18 years ago. The Boscainis learned how to cultivate
the vines, produce good grapes, and eventually they made small
batches of wine. And then they took the experiment a step further.
</P>
<P>
   Traditional Valpolicella is made from three grapes: corvina,
rondinella and molinara. About 10 years ago, Masi began making a
wine that was mostly corvina, with some rondinella but no molinara.
Instead they added about 10 percent oseletta and a touch of a grape
called dindarella _ ``for personality,'' Boscaini said.
</P>
<P>
   The new wine, called Toar, ``showed that we could produce wines
of greater complexity and structure with fresh grapes,'' Boscaini
said. ``We didn't need ripasso or appassimento.''
</P>
<P>
   But Toar was an intermediate project for Masi. The next step was
to produce a wine made almost entirely from oseletta. That wine,
the Osar that piqued my interest, does indeed mark a revolution in
Veronese wine making. It is a rich, supple, muscular wine.
</P>
<P>
   The 1995 Osar I tasted could be characterized as more rustic
than the best Amarones. But it lacked neither complexity nor tannic
structure. Osar has about 12 percent alcohol.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, you can't go to your corner store for a sample.
Only some 5,000 bottles were made of the 1995 vintage, the first
released, and the Masi people have allowed only a few nearby
restaurants to carry it.
</P>
<P>
   The Boscainis consider Osar to be a work in progress, one they
can eventually be proud of. Let's hope that more wine lovers will
one day be able to share in their pride.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-12-99 1627EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
