<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FULLY-COMMITTED-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRITIC'S NOTEBOOK: FINALLY, A PLAY ABOUT THE DINING EXPERIENCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By WILLIAM GRIMES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ At a certain trendy restaurant on the Upper East
Side, a place where they serve Argentine cedar-roasted milk-fed
chicken, tables are very, very hard to come by. The place is fully
booked months in advance, but callers never hear the situation
described that way. They are told that the restaurant is ``fully
committed.''
</P>
<P>
   That's the name of the one-man play now at the Vineyard Theater.
My only question is, why did it take so long? In a restaurant-mad
city like New York, where virtually every aspiring actor and
playwright has waited on tables, where deals are struck over lunch
or dinner, where finagling a reservation at the latest hot spot is
a blood sport, it's astounding that fine dining has taken so long
to claim a place on the stage, not as a backdrop _ there's plenty
of eating in Chekhov and Ibsen _ but as dramatic material in its
own right.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fully Committed'' may be slight, but it has touched a nerve.
Packed houses suggest that there are few dishes tastier, for
present-day New Yorkers, than the stew of pretension, duplicity,
avarice and cruelty bubbling under the lid of a four-star Manhattan
restaurant, and few spectacles funnier than seeing themselves in
hot, panting pursuit of a reservation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fully Committed'' unfolds on a busy December day, as the
Christmas holidays approach, and a hapless, struggling actor named
Sam, played by Mark Setlock, fields an unending stream of calls
from would-be diners. Some are rude. Some are desperate. Some are
bullying. Some are clueless, like the woman from Louisville, Ky.,
who cheerfully announces, ``My husband and I are coming to New York
the weekend of January the 13th, and we are just dyin' to come eat
with y'all!'' Setlock, who once worked as a reservationist at
Bouley, runs through about 30 characters at top speed.
</P>
<P>
   All day long, the torment goes on. And it's not just the
customers. The chef, an out-of-control control freak with a
paranoid streak a mile wide, calls Sam constantly. So does the
maitre d'hotel, a supercilious, cocaine-sniffing Frenchman who
cannot bear to talk to homely female customers.
</P>
<P>
   I found ``Fully Committed'' immensely entertaining, a richly
comic affirmation of everything I've ever heard, or suspected,
about the bad behavior that good food can inspire. But it also
illuminated, almost by accident, an aspect of restaurant-going that
diners rarely think about: the intricate theater of the dining
experience.
</P>
<P>
   By now it's a commonplace to compare Manhattan restaurants to
theaters. The food tends to come in three acts. The restaurants
have set designers and lighting designers. There is a script (the
menu), and a playwright (the chef). There are reviews, of course.
And restaurants have the kind of audience that Broadway needs
desperately but can't seem to get. New York's diners, as a class,
are well informed, highly motivated and dead keen to try anything
new. The restaurant equivalent of ``Cats'' does not interest them.
They are always ready and willing to take a walk on the wild side.
</P>
<P>
   These are the obvious parallels, but Becky Mode, the author and
a former waitress and restaurant hostess, makes you see the less
obvious ones. There's something about putting a restaurant onstage,
front and center, that forces the issue.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, it captures the sheer terror and the unbelievable
chaos that lie behind each night's performance in Manhattan's
theaters of food. The place is not just fully committed, it's
overbooked to the tune of 25 diners. The Zagats have turned up, and
their reservation has been misplaced. An unfortunate accident has
taken place in one of the restrooms, so bad that the busboys have
scattered and hidden. Like a meltdown in a Soviet reactor, none of
this information reaches the public.
</P>
<P>
   By that same mysterious alchemy that produces a memorable
evening of theater, fallible human beings manage to work around the
botched deliveries, the misplaced orders, the last-minute slip-ups
and glitches, and produce perfection on a plate for 70 or 80
demanding diners. The end result is beautiful to behold. The means
resemble trench warfare.
</P>
<P>
   There are casualties along the way. The reservationist who
quakes at the thought of a call from the chef or the maitre d'hotel
does not realize it, but fear runs throughout the chain of command.
The maitre d'hotel, who looks so powerful to the reservationist,
also deals with a thousand petty annoyances and impossible demands.
He dreads the wrath of rich, spoiled customers who can take their
business elsewhere on a whim. The almighty chef, as often as not,
is a welter of neuroses and insecurities.
</P>
<P>
   There's a poignant moment, late in the play, when Sam
offhandedly tells the chef that he doesn't really care for his
orange roughy. The remark lands like a punch to the stomach. ``Do
you like my polenta?'' the chef asks, crushed. The egos are as
enormous as Macy's balloons, and they can be deflated just as
quickly.
</P>
<P>
   What chefs send out to the table every night is a peculiar
thing. It is in part a work of art, but more immediate, more
intimate than any work of art can ever be. The primal connection
between food and love adds a powerful psychological charge to the
relationship between a chef, his staff and the diners who sit,
knife and fork in hand, demanding to be satisfied.
</P>
<P>
   This is an audience with a difference. A playwright has to
satisfy a crowd. A chef and his wait staff have to fashion an
experience table by table, diner by diner. Each customer is an
audience unto himself, with the power to grant or withhold
applause.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   It's one of the fascinating paradoxes of the restaurant
experience that each table, while imagining itself the audience, is
in fact, for all the other tables, part of the show.
</P>
<P>
   There is an all-consuming, almost infantile, quality to the
egocentrism of the diner. (I'm reminded of it when I see a hungry
customer tuck his napkin in his shirt like a bib.) I think it
accounts for the neurotic behavior one sees so often in
restaurants. The customer who throws a tantrum over a bad table, or
who sends back a perfectly fine dish, is often testing the staff
the way a child tests a parent. It's not about the table, or the
dish. It's about being coddled, or accepted, or even loved.
</P>
<P>
   In some cases, it can be a vulgar display of power. There are
people who simply enjoy pushing waiters around. I well remember
eating with a normal-seeming gentleman who sent back a perfectly
prepared fillet of salmon and then turned to me, with a look of
glee on his face, and announced: ``Always send something back. It
makes a point.'' It made a point with me, all right. There are
diners who quiz the waiter on each and every ingredient in a dish,
demand about six substitutions, and send the waiter scurrying on
pointless errands throughout the meal. At a certain point, you
begin to suspect that eating well is not really the purpose of the
exercise.
</P>
<P>
   I am told that film-industry executives no longer even bother to
look at a menu. They make a point of tossing it aside, simply
instructing the waiter to have the chef prepare an egg-white omelet
with organic spinach, or mung beans, or whatever it is that
important film people eat these days.
</P>
<P>
   The message is clear: ``You think the chef is in charge here,
and I'm here to tell you that you're wrong. I'm paying, so that
makes me the producer.'' Hollywood never did go in for the auteur
theory.
</P>
<P>
   No wonder chefs run wild and managers turn to drugs. They're
stuck in an abusive, unequal relationship, frantically eager to
please an inconstant lover whose whims and demands can never be
satisfied. Inevitably, the abused becomes an abuser himself.
</P>
<P>
   It turns out that there's a world seething with intrigue and
drama behind those familiar words, ``May I put you on hold,
please?'' The caller, placated with Muzak, doodles aimlessly on a
pad. At the other end of the line, three circles of hell are
rubbing up against each other.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
