<HEADER>
A4453 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d BC-GRAPE-LEAVES-ART-2TAK     10-12 0820
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRAPE-LEAVES-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM THE VINEYARD, NATURE'S FIRST WRAP 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(editors: recipes in 2nd take)  
 (bl)  
 By MELISSA CLARK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Grape leaves are like escargots, a canned ingredient
that seems too forbidding to use fresh in a home kitchen. But in
one of those increasingly common alliances of farm and chef,
freshly picked grape leaves from vineyards are turning up both in
markets and on menus well beyond Greek and Middle Eastern
restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   Compared with grape leaves sold in jars, usually imported from
Greece, the fresh local ones have a citrusy, spicy flavor with a
surprisingly herbal bite. They are also more tender, with veins
that are skinnier and less chewy. Now is the time to try them, when
they are easiest to find, even in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Grape leaves, like the grapes themselves, have to be picked by
hand, one at a time. Although they can be harvested at any time in
the grape-growing season, most growers prefer to take them in the
fall, along with the grapes. Only the most tender, bright green
leaves are picked. The older ones will have grown too thick and
sturdy for cooking.
</P>
<P>
   From August to November, Buzzard Crest Vineyards in Penn Yan, in
the Finger Lakes region, brings its leaves on Saturdays to the
Greenmarkets at Union Square in Manhattan and at Grand Army Plaza
and Borough Hall in Brooklyn. They are never on display with the
vineyard's four varieties of grapes also for sale, though. The
leaves are stored in coolers to keep them fresh and must be
requested.
</P>
<P>
   Roman Roth of Wolffer Estate/Sagpond Vineyards on Long Island
also sells fresh grape leaves, but only to restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   The most traditional way to use grape leaves is in dolmades, the
Greek appetizer of a seasoned rice mixture wrapped into little
green bundles and braised. They can also be used to enfold any food
destined for the grill, to keep it moist and to add a subtle
flavor. But chefs are doing much more.
</P>
<P>
   Mina Newman, the chef at Layla, a Middle Eastern restaurant in
Tribeca, wraps seasoned shrimp or salmon in fresh grape leaves
before grilling. Marc Meyer of Five Points in the East Village
makes a variation on dolmades with sausage, and Matthew Kenney of
Matthew's on the Upper East Side adds figs, pine nuts and mint to
the Basmati rice in his leaves.
</P>
<P>
   David Cunningham, at the Lenox Room, also on the Upper East
Side, fills fresh grape leaves with an orzo and quail stuffing
before braising them. Scott Conant, at Chianti in midtown, chars
the leaves on the grill to garnish balsamic-glazed eel. And Scott
Campbell, at Avenue on the Upper West Side, wraps them around
halibut before roasting the fish.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Newman also dries grape leaves in the oven at low heat with
a thin coating of olive oil and a sprinkle of salt so that they
crisp up into brittle sheets that snap in the mouth like the
thinnest of potato chips. They make an attractive garnish for her
grape leaf-wrapped salmon.
</P>
<P>
   Grape leaves sold in jars have been brined, which softens and
helps preserve them. Fresh leaves have to be blanched to make them
pliable, and a light brining at the same time will also make them
last longer, a month or two in the refrigerator.
</P>
<P>
   To tenderize the leaves without blanching or brining, you can
also freeze them between sheets of parchment; they wilt when they
defrost.
</P>
<P>
   The leaves in jars are much larger than the fresh ones, up to
eight inches in diameter, and have been simmered to make them
tender. They taste of the plain brine, whereas chefs add flavorings
to their salt water: Ms. Newman uses thyme, bay leaf and garlic;
Cunningham adds retsina laced with Greek brandy, Conant a touch of
balsamic vinegar. Campbell skips brining but blanches leaves in
muscadet.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Botsacos, the chef at Molyvos in midtown, uses grape leaves
from jars because they are always available and all about the same
size. To eliminate the heavily salted taste, though, he first boils
them in lemon-spiked water, then shocks them in ice water.
</P>
<P>
   The fresh leaves have a much greener, woodsier flavor than the
kind in jars, but both work well in recipes. One key is to use the
smallest leaves, which are noticeably thinner and more tender than
the larger ones, and to snip off the central stem with kitchen
shears.
</P>
<P>
   At the Greenmarkets, Buzzard Crest sells bags of leaves,
containing about two dozen, for $4. The owner, Ken Farnan, will
fill orders with a few days' notice (315-536-9686).
</P>
<P>
   The Chef's Garden (800-289-4644), which supplies Layla, will
ship leaves for a minimum order of $50, plus shipping. The price of
100 grape leaves is $35, and the order can be filled out with
seasonal vegetables.
</P>
<P>
   (STORY ENDS HERE. RECIPES FOLLOW IN 2nd TAKE) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   FRESH GRAPE LEAVES IN HOMEMADE BRINE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from Mina Newman, Layla &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 20 minutes plus cooling
</P>
<P>
   \ cup salt
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons fresh lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   3 sprigs fresh thyme
</P>
<P>
   1 clove garlic
</P>
<P>
   1 fresh bay leaf
</P>
<P>
   \ pound fresh grape leaves. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. In a large pot filled with 2 quarts of water, combine all the
ingredients except grape leaves. Bring to a boil over high heat,
and cook for 5 minutes, stirring once or twice.
</P>
<P>
   2. Add grape leaves to pot, and cook until they are tender,
about 5 to 10 minutes. Using tongs or a slotted spoon, transfer
grape leaves to a glass jar with a tight-fitting lid.
</P>
<P>
   3. Remove brine from heat, and allow to cool for 2 hours. Pour
cooled brine over grape leaves in jars. Store in refrigerator for
up to 2 weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: about 50 leaves.
</P>
<P>
   STUFFED GRAPE LEAVES WITH LAMB AND FIGS
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from Matthew Kenney, Matthew's &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 3 hours
</P>
<P>
   8 cups chicken stock
</P>
<P>
   } cup Basmati rice
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   { pound lean ground lamb
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon chopped garlic
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon Aleppo pepper (see note)
</P>
<P>
   { teaspoon ground cumin
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   } cup diced dried figs
</P>
<P>
   { cup toasted pine nuts
</P>
<P>
   { bunch scallions, chopped
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons fresh chopped mint
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon dried mint
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons chopped parsley
</P>
<P>
   6 dozen grape leaves
</P>
<P>
   Extra virgin olive oil, for garnish
</P>
<P>
   Lemon wedges, for garnish.
</P>
<P>
   1. Bring 1{ cups chicken stock to a boil in a small saucepan.
Add rice, and reduce heat. Simmer rice, covered, until tender,
about 20 minutes. Cool.
</P>
<P>
   2. Preheat oven to 350 degrees. In large skillet, heat olive oil
over medium-high heat. Cook lamb and garlic, stirring, until lamb
is browned. Stir in Aleppo pepper, cumin, salt and black pepper,
and cook a few seconds more. Transfer to large bowl. Add rice,
figs, pine nuts, scallions, mint and parsley, and combine well.
Season with salt and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   3. To stuff leaves, place one on a work surface, shiny side
down. Place a heaping teaspoon of filling in center of leaf near
the base. Fold bottom of leaf over filling, then fold sides over
toward center. Roll toward tip of leaf. Repeat for each leaf.
</P>
<P>
   4. Bring remaining 6{ cups stock to a simmer in a saucepan. In a
9-by-13-inch pan, arrange stuffed leaves, packing them close
together, seam side down (you can make a second layer if they don't
all fit in one layer). Pour hot stock over. Cover pan with foil,
and bake until leaves are tender, about 1 hour. Let leaves cool in
cooking liquid.
</P>
<P>
   5. To serve, drizzle with olive oil and garnish with lemon for
squeezing over tops.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 6 dozen. Note: Aleppo pepper can be ordered from
Kalustyan's, (212) 685-3451.
</P>
<P>
   MERGUEZ SAUSAGE WRAPPED IN GRAPE LEAVES
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from Marc Meyer, Five Points
</P>
<P>
   Time: 1} hours  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   \ cup Basmati rice
</P>
<P>
   { cup extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   { medium onion, diced
</P>
<P>
   1 carrot, peeled and diced
</P>
<P>
   1 celery stalk, trimmed and diced
</P>
<P>
   Pinch crushed red pepper flakes
</P>
<P>
   2 cloves garlic, minced
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   7 ounces merguez sausage, casings removed
</P>
<P>
   \ cup raisins
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons pine nuts, toasted
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon chopped fresh thyme
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons ground cinnamon
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon harissa (see note)
</P>
<P>
   Grated zest of 2 lemons
</P>
<P>
   12 brined grape leaves, rinsed, stems removed
</P>
<P>
   { cup dry white wine
</P>
<P>
   1 cinnamon stick
</P>
<P>
   1 bay leaf
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons chopped flat-leaf parsley
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon fresh lemon juice.
</P>
<P>
   1. Line a bamboo steamer with cheesecloth, and add rice. Place
in a large pot with an inch of water, and steam until rice is just
tender, about 25 minutes. Remove steamer, and cool rice for 10
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   2. Meanwhile, in a large skillet, heat \ cup olive oil over
medium-high heat. Add onion, carrot, celery and pepper flakes, and
cook, stirring, until onions are tender, about 10 minutes. Add
garlic, and saute for 2 minutes. Season with salt and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   3. Preheat oven to 350 degrees. Transfer mixture to a large
bowl, and add rice, sausage, raisins, pine nuts, thyme, cinnamon,
harissa, lemon zest and salt and pepper. Mix well. Divide into 12
balls.
</P>
<P>
   4. Lay grape leaves on a work surface, shiny side down. Place
meatballs in center, and fold sides of leaves over meat. Fold up
bottom and top to enclose meat.
</P>
<P>
   5. Place stuffed leaves in a 9-inch baking dish, seam side down.
Add } cup water, remaining oil, wine, cinnamon and bay leaf, and
season well. Cover with foil, and bake until grape leaves are
tender, about 1 hour.
</P>
<P>
   6. To serve, place grape leaves in soup plates. Stir parsley and
lemon juice into liquid in pan, and season again, if necessary;
drizzle over leaves.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 appetizer servings.
</P>
<P>
   Note: Harissa is available from Kalustyan's, (212) 685-3451. &QL;
</P>
