<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOAT-CHEESE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHEVRE LEARNS SOME NEW TRICKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By JEANNETTE FERRARY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Here in the Bay Area, goat cheese is not just
goat cheese. It has colorful names like Hyku, Humboldt Fog and
Tomme Tumalo. Occasionally it masquerades as camembert and even
cheddar. And it constantly dazzles.
</P>
<P>
   This region, where goat cheese was effectively introduced to the
American palate some 20 years ago, has nurtured inventive
cheesemakers who have been experimenting with different breeds,
terrains in which to raise them, and animal feeds. This new
generation of goat cheeses has inspired chefs here to create new
distinctive dishes.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Bertolli, a firm believer that cheese is ``the soul of the
soil,'' recently tried to prove his point by gathering two dozen
people at his restaurant, Oliveto, in Oakland, for a discussion of
cheese and terroir.
</P>
<P>
   Terroir is a word French winemakers use to describe the
environment in which their grapes are grown, and it is the latest
buzz word among artisanal cheesemakers, allowing chefs to select
goat cheeses from different regions for their distinctive tastes.
</P>
<P>
   Bertolli followed the discussion with a dinner that used cheeses
from the Northern California coast, including grilled figs with
ash-tinged Humboldt Fog, fried squash blossoms stuffed with Redwood
Hill goat cheese, and pork rib chops with grilled tomatoes and
Redwood's goat camembert.
</P>
<P>
   Few ould have predicted this happy obsession 20 years ago, when
Laura Chenel of Santa Rosa, who had begun to produce little rounds
of goat cheese as she had learned in France, first presented her
cheeses to Alice Waters at Chez Panisse, the Berkeley restaurant
known for its devotion to pristine ingredients.
</P>
<P>
   To Ms. Chenel's amazement, Ms. Waters tasted and then said,
``Can you make me 60 for next week?''
</P>
<P>
   When Ms. Waters paired that cheese with baby greens, it was a
hit. ``That salad signaled quite a revolution,'' said Daphne Zepos,
a cheese authority and writer. Goat cheese became a trendy
ingredient, and artisanal cheesemaking became viable.
</P>
<P>
   Local chefs use goat cheese _ fresh or aged, soft or crumbly,
spreadable or hard _ for any course. At the famous sidewalk tables
at Enrico's, in North Beach, the favorite is smoked salmon and goat
cheese bruschetta, drizzled with cucumber jam.
</P>
<P>
   At Silks, downtown, Dante Boccuzzi makes crisp goat cheese
beignets suffused with the flavors of a pepper-rosemary marinade.
For dessert, goat cheese ice cream with a huckleberry lemon verbena
compote comes on buttery wedges of pistachio shortbread.
</P>
<P>
   Diners at Jardiniere can begin with Traci Des Jardin's parfait
of roasted beets and creamy goat cheese. Desserts include a goat's
milk sorbet served with lavender-scented strawberries.
</P>
<P>
   The cheese trolley has been restored to its former glory at
Campton Place, downtown, where Yerba Santa Alpine Chevre sits on a
silver tray alongside some of the world's best cheeses. The
flavor-dense menu of the executive chef, Laurent Manrique,
showcases asparagus with chevre and wild mushrooms and a goat
cheese tart with piquillo peppers and fried artichokes.
</P>
<P>
   At the Girl and the Fig, in the Sonoma wine country town of Glen
Ellen, the chef and owner, Sondra Bernstein, has an updated fondue
in which Juniper Grove Tomme Tumalo is mixed with sauteed
chanterelles and shiitakes and served with chunks of pear or slices
of grilled eggplant for dipping.
</P>
<P>
   And Ms. Bernstein presents her cheese course with little
descriptive cards; recent selections included Redwood Hill's goat
milk teleme and Goat's Leap Hyku.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, at Chez Panisse, where it all began, goat cheese in
the company of pancetta adorns frittatas; with an herb or two, it
is snuggled into the restaurant's ever-popular crostata, a
two-crusted pizza.
</P>
<P>
   As a condiment, a spice or the star of the dish, goat cheese
continues to find new ways of tantalizing chef and diner alike.
</P>
<P>
   GOAT CHEESE AND MUSHROOM FONDUE
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from Sondra Bernstein, The Girl and the Fig, Glen Ellen,
Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Time: 30 minutes
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   2 garlic cloves, minced
</P>
<P>
   \ pound button mushrooms, sliced
</P>
<P>
   \ chanterelle mushrooms, sliced
</P>
<P>
   \ shiitake mushrooms, sliced
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons fresh herbs, chopped (thyme, parsley, sage)
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper
</P>
<P>
   \ cup white wine
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon cornstarch
</P>
<P>
   2 cups hard goat cheese, grated.
</P>
<P>
   1. In a large saucepan, heat oil over medium heat. Add garlic,
mushrooms and herbs. Cook about 8 minutes or until mushrooms are
tender. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   2. In a stainless steel pan, combine wine and cornstarch and
bring to a simmer. Reduce heat. Add cheese and stir until smooth.
</P>
<P>
   3. Remove from heat and add mushroom mixture, stirring until
well incorporated. Serve in a fondue pot accompanied by cut-up
vegetables or fruit, grilled eggplant slices, or day-old bread, cut
in cubes.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 appetizer servings.
</P>
<P>
   GOAT CHEESE AND HONEY PHYLLO TART WITH SAUTEED SEASONAL FRUIT
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from Traci Des Jardins, Jardiniere, San Francisco
</P>
<P>
   Time: 90 minutes
</P>
<P>
   For the goat cheese filling:
</P>
<P>
   16 ounces mild goat cheese
</P>
<P>
   1 egg
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons honey
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon Grand Marnier
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   Pinch nutmeg
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons flour
</P>
<P>
   For phyllo dough:  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1 box phyllo dough
</P>
<P>
   8 ounces clarified butter
</P>
<P>
   Sugar
</P>
<P>
   For fruit garnish:  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   5 tablespoons sugar
</P>
<P>
   { cup white wine
</P>
<P>
   1 vanilla bean, split
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons butter
</P>
<P>
   1{ cups fresh fruit, peeled and seeded, cut into attractive
shapes.
</P>
<P>
   1. To make filling: Combine all ingredients, except flour, in
food processor or heavy-duty mixer. Blend well. Gradually sift in
flour, and mix until smooth. Place in refrigerator until ready to
use.
</P>
<P>
   2. To prepare dough: Place one sheet of phyllo dough on work
surface. With pastry brush, apply a coat of clarified butter.
Sprinkle with sugar. Place another sheet of phyllo on top, and
repeat, ending with a third sheet of phyllo. Brush that layer with
butter, and set stack aside. Repeat process, making a total of 6
stacks.
</P>
<P>
   3. To make fruit garnish: Combine sugar, white wine and vanilla
bean in a saucepan, and bring to a boil. Lower heat slightly and
cook until mixture has been reduced by two-thirds. Remove vanilla
bean. Melt butter in a saute pan over medium heat, and add fruit.
Cook until softened but not mushy, 8 to 12 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   4. Preheat oven to 425 degrees. Place a stack of layered phyllo
on a clean dry surface. With a sharp knife, cut 3 circles 5{ inches
in diameter, cutting through to bottom of stack. Repeat with
remaining stacks until you have 18 circles of layered dough.
</P>
<P>
   5. Spread 2 tablespoons of goat cheese mixture in center of a
circle, leaving a margin of about an inch. Place another circle on
top. Fold edges of phyllo up and over to seal all around. Bake on
cookie sheet 7 to 10 minutes or until golden brown.
</P>
<P>
   6. To serve, place fruit and some of its syrup on a plate, and
place warm tart on top.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 9 tarts.
</P>
</TEXT>
