<HEADER>
A4480 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r d BC-SECRET-BASS-SFCHRON &LR;      10-12 0840
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SECRET-BASS-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: Each week, The Chronicle offers readers the recipe
for an outstanding dish at a Bay Area restaurant, plus the chef's
secrets for making it a success. Tips and recipe follow in optional
trim.  SECRETS OF SUCCESS: Aram's Twist on Bass a Hit  
   
 By Michael Bauer  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _  The ingredients that accompany Aaron Peters' Wild
Striped Bass _ crescent potatoes, salsify and Jerusalem artichokes
_ are exciting in themselves. A delicate parsley salad, glistening
with Meyer lemon vinaigrette, rounds out this wonderful dish.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The wild bass is one of the staple dishes at Aram's, a
pan-Mediterranean restaurant tucked into an alley off Sacramento in
Presidio Heights. Located in the former home of Rosmarino, the
restaurant is now owned by Khajag and Hildy Sarkissian, former
proprietors of the Caravansary restaurants and the team that
introduced Aram sandwiches to the Bay Area.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Peters trained in much the same manner as the best
European chefs. He started working in the kitchen of Kuleto's when
he was 16 years old and then moved on to Aqua, Square One and
PlumpJack Cafe.
</P>
<P>
   At Aram's, which has a comfortable feel and a stylish decor that
reflects the affluent neighborhood, Peters crafts some creative
dishes using simple techniques and out-of-the-mainstream
ingredients. However, in the case of this fish dish, the Jerusalem
artichokes, also known as sunchokes, and the salsify, sometimes
called oyster plant because of its briny flavor, are available at
many upscale supermarkets.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Aram's, 3665 Sacramento St. (near Spruce), San Francisco;
(415) &LR;   &LR; 474-8061. Open for dinner Tuesday-Saturday, brunch
Sunday.cq &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
SECRETS OF SUCCESS
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; _  &UR; Cooking the fish. &LR;  The oil should be smoking-hot before putting
the fish in the pan; this creates a crisp, brown exterior and a
moist, flaky flesh.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Using dry heat and moist heat to cook the vegetables. &LR;  The
root vegetables are first roasted in the oven, then they're braised
in chicken stock _ a technique that enhances both taste and
texture.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Parsley salad. &LR;  The combination of parsley and lemon adds a
striking, refreshing note.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; WILD STRIPED BASS WITH MEYER LEMON, JERUSALEM ARTICHOKES &AMP; SALSIFY
</P>
<P>
   If Meyer lemons aren't available, any variety will do. And if
you can't find wild striped bass, then sea bass will work just
fine.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   The Vegetables
</P>
<P>
   1/2 pound Jerusalem artichokes, peeled and cut into
1/4-inch-thick slices
</P>
<P>
   1/2 pound Ruby Crescent or other red-skinned potatoes, cut into
3/4-inch pieces
</P>
<P>
   1/2 pound salsify, peeled and cut into 3/4-inch pieces
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   2 cups unsalted chicken stock
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon chopped fresh thyme
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons butter
</P>
<P>
   Meyer Lemon Vinaigrette
</P>
<P>
   1 Meyer lemon or other lemon
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon Champagne vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon rice wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon minced shallot
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons Dijon mustard
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   The Fish
</P>
<P>
   6 wild striped bass or sea bass fillets, about 5 ounces each
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   11/2 cups Italian parsley leaves
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; For the vegetables:  &LR; Preheat oven to 400 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Combine the Jerusalem artichokes, potatoes and salsify in a
large ovenproof skillet. Add the oil and toss to coat. Season with
salt and pepper. Roast for 15 minutes. Transfer the pan to a
stovetop burner (medium heat). Add the stock and thyme. Bring to a
boil, scraping up any browned bits. Continue to cook until the
liquid is reduced by about one third and is syrupy, about 10
minutes. Add the butter and stir until melted. Season with
additional salt and pepper if necessary. Remove from heat.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; For the Meyer lemon vinaigrette:  &LR; Zest the lemon, leaving the
zest in long threads, and reserve for the salad. Squeeze the juice
from the lemon into a small bowl. Add the Champagne vinegar, rice
vinegar, shallot and mustard. Gradually whisk in the olive oil.
Season with salt and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; For the fish:  &LR; Season the fish with a liberal amount of salt
and pepper. Heat 2 tablespoons of the oil in a large saute pan
until just smoking. Gently add half of the fish, skin side down.
Cook until the skin is brown and crispy, about 3 minutes. Using a
spatula, carefully turn the fish over and continue cooking until
just cooked through, about 3 minutes. Transfer the fish to a
platter. Keep warm.
</P>
<P>
   Repeat the process with the remaining oil and fish.
</P>
<P>
   Combine the parsley leaves and reserved lemon zest in a small
bowl. Add the vinaigrette and toss to coat.
</P>
<P>
   Divide the vegetables among serving plates. Top with the fish.
Garnish each plate with parsley salad and drizzle with any
remaining vinaigrette.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 470 calories, &LR;   &LR; 31 g protein, 21 g
carbohydrate, &LR;   &LR; 30 g fat (6 g saturated), 107 mg cholesterol, 170
mg sodium, 2 &LR;   &LR; g fiber. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
