<SLUG> BC-BESTBEANS-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: The Chronicle regularly features ``Best Way'', a
column in which the Food staff tries to establish the most reliable
way to cook many of our favorite foods. 
 
 BEST WAY: Dried Beans   By Stephen Baker  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _  Dried beans can be confounding to cook perfectly.
Should they be soaked or not? And when should you add salt?
<TEXT>
<P>
   To find out, we tried several methods of preparing black turtle
beans, looking for two things _ the best texture and the best
flavor.
</P>
<P>
   We soaked one batch overnight and one by the quick-soak method
(boiling them for 2 minutes, then letting them soak for 1 hour).
One batch was cooked without any soaking.
</P>
<P>
   We also experimented adding salt at different points _ at the
start of soaking, at the start of cooking, 30 minutes into cooking,
and at the end of cooking.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; THE BEST WAY
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; _ &UR; Texture. &LR;  Food Department staffers picked the quick-soaked beans
as having the best overall texture. The beans were smooth, without
any grainy sensation, and most beans had the skins intact.
</P>
<P>
   The skins of the beans that had soaked overnight tended to
split, letting the cooking water penetrate the beans so that they
became very soft.
</P>
<P>
   The beans that had not been soaked at all had a grainy
mouthfeel. The skins seemed cooked but the interior of the beans
was unpleasant.
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; Flavor &LR; . After picking the quick-soak method as our favorite,
we cooked quick-soaked beans in four batches, salting them four
different ways. Food staffers were surprised by the best-tasting
ones _ the beans that had been salted at the end of cooking. They
had a nice flavor throughout.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; AN APPEALING ALTERNATIVE
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  The beans that were salted 30 minutes into cooking had a better
overall appearance, with fewer split skins. These beans might work
better in a salad, whereas the beans salted at the end would work
best for soups or stews.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-12-99 1706EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991012.0187 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-12 17:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4482 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r d BC-WORKING-SFCHRON &LR;      10-12 1634
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORKING-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: Here's a plan for getting quick meals on the table in
a hurry. Now &AMP; Later is a recipe cooked on the weekend in batches _
enough to serve 12 _ and functions as dinner on the night it's
prepared; freeze the rest for two future meals. The 30-Minute
Recipe takes a half-hour or less of preparation and Fast and
Fresh.  THE WORKING COOK: Comforting One-Dish Meals Fit Fall's Cozy 
 Image 
 &HT;       
 By Tara Duggan  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SAN FRANCISCO _ &LR;  As a possible drizzly fall looms, we start to
gravitate to the foods of the hearth. Sunday afternoon is the time
to create thick, steamy vegetable soups or meat loaves with
Grandma's secret sauce. It might even be time to pull out the bread
maker.
<P>
   And what could be more homey than chicken potpie? Of course, you
can buy them ready-made any time of the year. But this week's Now &AMP;
Later recipe isn't difficult to make, and it's a whole lot better
than those frozen supermarket potpies. Made in individual portions,
these scrumptious pies have a generous filling of wild mushrooms
and boneless chicken breast in a decadent-tasting
sherry-and-shallot sauce. A flaky puff pastry crust tops each one.
</P>
<P>
   After you've completed the recipe, not only will you enjoy
potpies for dinner that night, you'll have a batch for your freezer
for that cold, rainy night when you don't feel like cooking.
</P>
<P>
   This week's Fast &AMP; Fresh recipe, Frittata with Prosciutto and
Roma Tomatoes, is a gorgeous combination of fluffy eggs, salty
prosciutto, ripe tomato and soft, creamy cheese. Looking something
like a pizza, this quick dish works great for either brunch or
dinner, accompanied by country bread and a salad.
</P>
<P>
   What makes frittatas different from omelets is that they are
open-face and partially cooked in an oven-proof skillet, then
placed in the oven to finish cooking. If you layer the topping
carefully, leaving a wide border around the edge, the eggs will
fluff up under the broiler and get golden and crusty. The melted
fontina on top smells like heaven as it comes out of the oven.
</P>
<P>
   The 30-Minute Main Course is a brothy pasta made with tiny pasta
shapes intended for soups. Swiss chard, which is sauteed with
garlic then wilted in stock, is added to this, creating a wholesome
broth.
</P>
<P>
   The flavors in this dish are straightforward. The contrast of
textures is what makes it special: Al dente pasta floating in
broth, tender wilted chard, crunchy, briny chunks of pecorino
cheese and crispy toasts. They all come together in a very
satisfying way.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; FAST &AMP; FRESH: dinner in about 20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; FRITTATA WITH PROSCIUTTO &AMP; ROMA TOMATOES
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   10 large eggs
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup grated fontina cheese
</P>
<P>
   2 ripe Roma tomatoes, sliced into very thin rounds
</P>
<P>
   4 to 6 slices prosciutto (about 1/4 pound), cut into bite-size
pieces
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Preheat the broiler before beginning preparation.
</P>
<P>
   Beat the eggs in a bowl, seasoning them with pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Prepare the other ingredients before starting to cook the eggs.
</P>
<P>
   Heat the olive oil in a nonstick oven-proof skillet over medium
heat. Pour in the eggs. As the eggs cook, lift the bottom with a
rubber spatula to prevent them from sticking and to allow the
uncooked egg to run underneath. Cook until the bottom is set and
the top still runny, about 5 to 6 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Remove the eggs from the heat. Sprinkle most of the cheese on
top, then arrange a layer of tomatoes over the cheese, leaving a
1-inch border around the outside. Sprinkle the prosciutto pieces
over the tomatoes, then top with the remaining cheese.
</P>
<P>
   Place the pan directly under the broiler until the cheese is
melted and the egg cooked through; the edges should be puffy and
golden brown. This takes about 3 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Serve with toasted country-style bread and a salad.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 395 calories, &LR;   &LR; 30 g protein, 5 g carbohydrate, &LR; 
 &LR; 29 g fat (10 g saturated), 568 mg cholesterol, 681 mg sodium, 1 &LR; 
 &LR; g fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; 30-MINUTE MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; PASTA IN BRODO WITH SWISS CHARD
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   12 slices baguette, cut thinly on an angle
</P>
<P>
   3/4 pound tiny pasta (see note)
</P>
<P>
   8 garlic cloves
</P>
<P>
   2 bunches Swiss chard
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   21/2 cups vegetable or chicken broth
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons grated pecorino or Parmesan cheese
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Before beginning preparation, preheat the oven to 400 degrees
and begin boiling a large pot of salted water for the pasta.
</P>
<P>
   Place the bread slices on a cookie sheet and toast in the oven
until browned on one side, about 5 minutes. Turn the slices and
toast the other side.
</P>
<P>
   Begin cooking the pasta. When it is al dente, drain (reserving 2
cups of the cooking water) and rinse briefly under cold tap water.
</P>
<P>
   While the pasta is cooking, put the garlic through a garlic
press; trim the stems off the chard. Stack the leaves, slice them
in half lengthwise, then slice them crosswise into thin ribbons.
</P>
<P>
   Heat the olive oil in a large heavy stock pot over medium heat.
Add the garlic and cook until it begins to release its aroma, 1 to
2 minutes. Stir in the chard and cook for 5 minutes. Add the broth
and cook until the chard is tender, about 2 to 3 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Add the cooked pasta to the stock pot, then the reserved
pasta-cooking water and heat through. There should be plenty of
liquid. Season with salt and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   To serve, portion the soup into bowls. Top with a liberal amount
of cheese and the toasts. Ladle a little broth on top to moisten
the toasts.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Note:  &LR; There are many different types of tiny pasta shapes
traditionally used in Italian brothy soup, or brodo. Look for small
1-pound boxes of pasta labeled  &LR; acini di pepe &LR;  (peppercorns),
pastina, riso,  &LR; semi di melone  &LR; (melon seeds) or orzo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 605 calories, &LR;   &LR; 19 g protein, 97 g
carbohydrate, &LR;   &LR; 15 g fat (3 g saturated), 4 mg cholesterol, 522 mg
sodium, 2 g &LR;   &LR; fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NOW &AMP; LATER: dinner this week &AMP; 2 for the freezer
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; CHICKEN POTPIE WITH WILD MUSHROOMS &AMP; SHALLOTS
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   1 pound mixed wild mushrooms, such as shiitake and oyster
mushrooms
</P>
<P>
   1 pound button mushrooms
</P>
<P>
   8 cups chicken stock or low-salt broth
</P>
<P>
   1 bay leaf
</P>
<P>
   4 sprigs fresh thyme
</P>
<P>
   11/2 pounds boneless chicken breasts (about 4 breasts)
</P>
<P>
   8 carrots, cut in medium dice
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons butter
</P>
<P>
   12 shallots, peeled
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon minced fresh thyme
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   6 tablespoons flour
</P>
<P>
   1 cup dry sherry
</P>
<P>
   2 sheets prepared puff pastry (17.3-ounce package), defrosted
</P>
<P>
   1 egg, beaten
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Have ready 12 four-inch-diameter tartlet pans (see note).
</P>
<P>
   Trim off mushroom stems and reserve. Slice the mushroom caps,
but keep the heartier mushrooms like shiitakes separate from the
lighter oyster and button mushrooms.
</P>
<P>
   Place the stock in a large pot. Add the mushroom stems, bay leaf
and thyme sprigs. Bring to a boil, then add the chicken and reduce
the heat to simmer. Cover and poach until the chicken is cooked
through, about 8 minutes. Remove the chicken with a slotted spoon
and set on a cutting board to cool. When cool, cut into medium
dice.
</P>
<P>
   Strain the stock into a smaller saucepan, discarding the
mushroom stems, thyme sprigs and bay leaf.
</P>
<P>
   Prepare a large bowl of ice water.
</P>
<P>
   Return the stock to a boil and add the carrots. Blanch until
tender, 4 to 5 minutes. Remove with a slotted spoon to the ice
water, reserving the stock. When the carrots are cool, drain and
set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Cut the shallots into eighths lengthwise, but do not cut all the
way through. You want the slices to remain attached at one end.
</P>
<P>
   Melt the butter in a large skillet over medium heat. Add the
shallots and cook until browned, stirring frequently, about 10
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Add the shiitake mushrooms, if using, and the minced thyme;
season with salt and pepper. Saute for 3 minutes, stirring
frequently. Add the button and oyster mushrooms and saute until
tender and all liquid is absorbed, about 5 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Deglaze the pan with the sherry, and cook over medium-high heat
for 2 minutes, until the liquid evaporates.
</P>
<P>
   Sprinkle the vegetables with the flour, 1 tablespoon at a time,
and stir to incorporate over very low heat.
</P>
<P>
   Add the reserved stock to the pan, scraping the bottom to remove
any stuck bits. Bring to a boil, reduce heat and simmer until there
is no raw flour taste, at least 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Add the chicken and carrots to the mushroom sauce; stir to
incorporate. If the sauce is very thick, add a bit more stock, but
be careful, the sauce will thin out when the potpies are baked.
Adjust seasoning.
</P>
<P>
   Roll out the puff pastry to extend it by about 2 inches in
length and width, making sure each sheet is large enough to cover 6
tartlet pans. Turn one tartlet pan over to use as a stencil. Using
a sharp paring knife, cut out 6 circles from each sheet.
</P>
<P>
   Ladle equal portions of filling into each tartlet pan. Place a
pastry circle on top and crimp the edges with a fork.
</P>
<P>
   Whisk the beaten egg with 2 tablespoons water. Lightly brush the
top of each pie with this egg wash.
</P>
<P>
   Bake the pies in a 375 oven until the tops are puffy and golden
brown, about 20 to 25 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Yields 12 potpies.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Note:  &LR; Foil tartlet pans are available at many supermarkets.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Freezing Note:  &LR; If you plan to freeze part of this recipe,
freeze it before baking. Wait until the filling has cooled, then
wrap the uncooked pies in freezer paper, then in foil. Defrost the
pies in the refrigerator then bake as directed above.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER POTPIE: &LR;   &LR; 395 calories, &LR;   &LR; 21 g protein, 41 g carbohydrate, &LR; 
 &LR; 15 g fat (4 g saturated), 56 mg cholesterol, 81 mg sodium, 8 g &LR; 
 &LR; fiber. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
