<SLUG> BC-CRUSH-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: The Chronicle regularly features ``Crush '99'' by
wine writers Gerald Boyd and Janet Fletcher. This column updates
wine grape harvests throughout California until crush's end around
November.   
 CRUSH '99: Final Vintage of Century Turns Frantic   By Janet Fletcher  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _  The last vintage of the century may make the
record books as the one of the fastest vintages ever.
<TEXT>
<P>
   As recently as late September, Napa Valley winemakers and
vineyard managers were twiddling their thumbs, waiting impatiently
for grapes to ripen. Then a week of 100-degree, low-humidity
weather sent grape sugars soaring. Vineyard crews scrambled to get
the grapes picked before they dehydrated, and winemakers grappled
with the nightmarish possibility of all the vineyards coming in at
once.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somebody at Mondavi described it as sitting on your hands for
a month and then the barn burns down,'' says Paul Jackson, a
vineyard manager for Honig Cellars, Grgich Hills and other Napa
Valley properties. ``Wineries went from zero to full capacity in a
week.''
</P>
<P>
   Few wineries can afford to build a facility big enough to handle
this worst-case scenario. Most years, they can count on grapes
progressing through their fermenting tanks in stages. When
everything arrives at once, there may not be enough fermenting
space; to keep wine moving from tanks into barrels, winemakers may
have to press a red wine off its skins before it has macerated as
long as they might like.
</P>
<P>
   Worse, they may have to leave ripe grapes hanging in the
vineyard because they have no place to put them. ``That's starting
to happen,'' Jackson says. ``The grapes are ready to go and the
tanks are full.'' Fortunately, irrigation can help keep the berries
hydrated until the winery has room.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have crushed as much as we can physically bring in here,''
confirms Michael Havens of Havens Wine Cellars in Yountville. ``We
worked something like 100 hours last week, getting out of here on
average at 1 a.m.. We crushed around 220 tons, better than half of
our crush.''
</P>
<P>
   The heat also produced some of the highest grape sugars in
winemakers' memories, with grapes coming in at 27 or 28 degrees
brix, instead of the more typical 23 or 24. Unless winemakers
dilute the juice with water _ a widespread if not widely admitted
practice _ such grapes could produce overly alcoholic wines,
possibly with some residual sugar. Winemakers also worry that the
grapes, while technically ripe, won't have the soft tannins and
developed flavors that come with maturity.
</P>
<P>
   On the plus side, the grapes have good acidity, says Jackson,
which is often lacking in California. And some grapes that weren't
picked during the heat wave have rehydrated in the cooler weather,
dropping a couple of degrees brix.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Havens says his grapes were showing signs of
maturity _ brown seeds and soft tannins in the skin _ before the
heat struck and should therefore make fine wine. If that's true for
others, too, this abnormal vintage could have a normal outcome.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
