<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: Each week, The San Francisco Chronicle's panel of
professional tasters tries a different product available in
supermarkets.  
 
 TASTER'S CHOICE: Kellogg's Crowned King of Toaster Pastries   By Robin Davis  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _  For a quick breakfast, many people, especially
children, turn to toaster pastries. A few minutes in the toaster,
and out pops a hot, sweet treat that can be eaten on the way to
school or work.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Today's panel tasted six frosted strawberry toaster pastries,
including three labled as low-fat. While the prices were fairly
similar, the nutritional profile differed, and not just in terms of
fat.
</P>
<P>
   Four of the pastries were fortified with vitamins and minerals.
All were high in carbohydrates, with sugar accounting for almost
half of them in all the pastries. The full-fat varieties all
contained five grams of fat per pastry, while the low-fat ranged
from two to three grams.
</P>
<P>
   Panelists chose  &UR; Kellogg's Pop-Tarts &LR;  (14.7 ounces, $2.49-$2.99
at many supermarkets) as the best. Three panelists liked the
strawberry flavor; one described it as ``best of the bunch.'' Two
others detected a bitter edge. Four would buy it; one would not.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Toastettes &LR;  from Nabisco (13 ounces, $1.69 at Andronico's) came
in second. One panelist thought the neon-pink color was ideal for
kids, but another described it as off-putting. Another taster
thought the pastry was too sweet and lacked fruit filling, but
others liked the flavor and texture. Four might buy it; one would
not.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Safeway &LR;  (11 ounces, $2.19 at Safeway) scored just four points
below Toastettes. Two panelists complained of a too-thick pastry;
others thought the pastry was bland and salty. One panelist thought
the filling had an off-flavor, but another particularly liked it.
Two might buy it; three would not.
</P>
<P>
   Fourth place went to  &UR; Auburn Farms Toast'n Jammers &LR;  (11 ounces,
$2.49 at Whole Foods), one of the low-fat pastries. Three panelists
disliked the filling, noting that it had very little strawberry
flavor (the package also does not list strawberry in the
ingredients, only apple flakes and beet juice). One panelist liked
the softer pastry and less-sweet filling, but another objected to
the royal-icinglike frosting. One would buy it; four would not.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Kellogg's Low-Fat Pop-Tarts &LR;  (14.7 ounces, $4.29-$2.59 at many
supermarkets) ranked just below Auburn Farms. All of the panelists
disliked the filling, saying it tasted fake and overly perfumed.
They also complained of metallic, bitter and salty flavors in the
dough. None would buy it.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Barbara's Nature's Choice &LR;  also was tasted but ranked too low
to rate. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Panelists were Dan Bowe, associate culinary director, Center for
Culinary Development; John P. Carroll, cookbook author; Roland
Passot, chef/owner La Folie in San Francisco and Left Bank in
Larkspur and menlo Park; Kim Severson, Chronicle staff writer; and
Kirk Webber, chef-owner, Cafe Kati, San Francisco. All products are
tasted blind. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-12-99 1709EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
