A4486 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r d BC-ANNIVERSARY-SFCHRON &LR;      10-12 4377
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANNIVERSARY-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
 20 Good Years: Five Bay Area trendsetters celebrate two decades  of
defining what we eat.   By Janet Fletcher  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _  In the trend-smitten world of wine and food, only
a few businesses have real staying power. Or so you'd think.
<TEXT>
<P>
   But this year, a surprising number of local food and wine
enterprises _ many of which have shaped the way Americans eat _ are
celebrating their 20th anniversaries. Remember when goat cheese
salad was a novelty? When vegetarian food was always brown? When
California Pinot Noir smelled like _ well, let's not go there.
</P>
<P>
   The Bay Area's celebrated dining scene owes a giant debt to some
entrepreneurs who had a good idea in 1979 and ran with it. That's
when Laura Chenel began trying to turn her goat's milk into cheese
and inadvertently launched an American cheese revolution. That's
when Michael Richmond and partners made their first Acacia Pinot
Noirs, acclaimed wines that boosted the reputation of that varietal
in California. That's when Greens opened in Fort Mason, shattering
perceptions about stodgy vegetarian food. And 20 years ago, Mary
Risley opened Tante Marie's, a professional cooking school as
ambitious as any in Paris or London. The esteemed Hayes Street
Grill dates from 1979, as do Opus One, J. Fritz and S. Anderson
wineries.
</P>
<P>
   Why did these businesses thrive when so many worthy others fell
by the wayside? To find out, we surveyed some survivors. We heard
about good decisions, bad decisions, failed partnerships, blessed
partnerships, good times and lean times, highlights and fears.
Their recollections provide a lively look back at the past 20 years
in wine and food.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; GREENS RESTAURANT
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; Then: &LR;  Motivated by the success of their Tassajara Bakery,
practitioners from San Francisco's Zen Center opened a vegetarian
restaurant in a former warehouse at Fort Mason in San Francisco in
1979.
</P>
<P>
   Working with a $300,000 budget, contractors raised the floor
two-and-a-half feet so guests could see the marina. Zen Center
carpenters used 12 types of wood on the stairs, wall paneling, bar
and Shaker-style tables. Deborah Madison, who had cooked for the
Zen Center abbot's guests and at the Tassajara retreat near Carmel,
was the obvious choice for chef. The other employees were
restaurant neophytes working to fulfill their Zen practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``We opened in a backwards way,'' recalls Annie Somerville, who
joined Greens in 1981 and has been its chef since 1985. ``Most
restaurants open for dinner; Greens opened for lunch. That was so
people who worked here could go to the meditation hall.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the early employees worked for minimum wage or for room
and board, and all their tips went back to the Zen Center. But
Greens' evolved from a not-for-profit, Buddhist-staffed business to
a for-profit business with mostly non-Buddhist employees after
1983. In the spring of that year, abbot Richard Baker resigned
under a cloud, and disillusionment swept the Zen Center. People
stopped coming to work in its businesses, says Somerville, and
Greens began hiring people from outside the fold.
</P>
<P>
   But even in the early days, when service was famously inept,
critics and customers recognized Greens as a landmark restaurant.
For the first time in most observers' memories, vegetarian food had
been given a beautiful setting and serious treatment.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Now: &LR;  Only a handful of employees have a connection to the
Zen Center, although the restaurant is still a Zen Center business.
But perhaps the bigger change for Greens has been the emergence of
so many competitors _ not just vegetarian restaurants, but
conventional restaurants with vegetarian options on the menu.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to feel threatened by other vegetarian restaurants
opening, but now I see competition as helpful,'' Somerville says.
The competitive pressure keeps employees in peak-performance mode,
she argues. ``I don't think you can let it slip.''
</P>
<P>
   The kitchen used cream and cheese liberally in the early years,
partly to compensate for lack of meat. But as tastes have changed,
so has Greens' cooking. Today it's lighter and less
dairy-dependent, more clearly focused on showcasing produce from
the Zen Center's Green Gulch Farm.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Greens serves lunch, Sunday brunch, dinner and late-night
dessert and has a take-out counter. But there's still just one
Greens, the same size as it always was.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of times, the decision to expand comes early on when
things are going great and everybody's walking through the door,''
Somerville says. ``You spend all this money, but a year later
something's different and customers aren't there and you're out a
lot of money. We're still here because we keep changing, but we do
it very slowly and conservatively.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; LAURA CHENEL CHEVRE
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Then: &LR;  In the early 1970s, Chenel was living on a small farm
in Forestville and tending a garden, fruit trees, chickens, bees
and a few goats. The idea was to be self-sufficient, she says, but
the goats captured her fancy and she began breeding them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Suddenly, I had a lot of little mouths to feed,'' she recalls,
and she began exploring the idea of making cheese so she could
afford to keep her goats.
</P>
<P>
   Chenel admits her initial cheeses were underwhelming. When
someone brought her some French chevre, she finally realized what
her goats' milk could do. In 1979, she went to France and in a few
months learned enough to come home.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly thereafter, Chenel took her new cheeses to Helen Allen,
then a cheese merchant in San Francisco. ``I know somebody who
would really like this,'' says Allen, who sent Chenel to Chez
Panisse.
</P>
<P>
   ``Alice (Waters) just flipped,'' Chenel recalls. ``She called
everybody around to taste it and placed a standing order
immediately.''
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; Now: &LR;  Chenel makes about 700,000 pounds of goat cheese a year.
It's become so mainstream that it's a staple on mass-market pizza
and pasta.
</P>
<P>
   Despite steady growth, Chenel says little else in the business
has changed. She still makes her goat cheeses the same way and has
hardly raised her prices in 20 years. In the early 1980s, Chenel
reluctantly gave up her herd to concentrate on cheesemaking, but
when she moved her bursting-at-the-seams business into the former
Stornetta Dairy in Sonoma in 1993, she had room for goats again.
She now has 450.
</P>
<P>
   ``That has added so much to my life,'' Chenel says. ``Now if I
have anything I worry about at night, it's, `Are the goats OK?' ''
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; TANTE MARIE'S
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Then: &LR;  For five years in the mid-1970s, Mary Risley taught
French cooking informally out of her San Francisco flat on
Leavenworth Street. Then she started to get calls from strangers
about enrollment procedures and fees.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd have to say, `I don't have a full-time school. You'll have
to go to Paris,''' Risley recalls. ``So I thought, `Why do people
have to go to Paris to learn fine cooking?'''
</P>
<P>
   In 1979, Risley launched Tante Marie's Cooking School in a
storefront on a residential block of Telegraph Hill. The program
was ``in the manner of the Cordon Bleu,'' says Risley, with morning
participation classes and afternoon demonstrations. She opened with
one full-time student whose formidable curriculum included French
cooking with Jeremiah Tower, Italian cooking with Carlo Middione
and Chinese cooking with Ken Hom.
</P>
<P>
   After a year, her investors encouraged her to stop the full-time
program. ``They said, `It's not going to make you money,' '' Risley
recalls. ``So I got rid of (them).''
</P>
<P>
   Her full-time school eventually did take off, especially when
Risley changed from a nine-month program to two six-month programs
a year. But her individual classes (1979 prices: $48 for six
classes) have always been well-subscribed, in the early days
primarily by non-working wives who wanted to learn how to make puff
pastry, breaded and fried Camembert and charlotte Malakoff.
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; Now: &LR;  Risley's school offers 800 classes a year (six classes:
$480), from bread baking to Shanghai-style cooking. She doesn't see
many non-working wives anymore, but neither does she see the young,
college-educated people who, 20 years ago, wanted to work in the
restaurant industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't want to work for $18,000 a year,'' Risley says.
``The educated-kids-going-into-kitchens isn't happening anymore.
They realize they can't make money.''
</P>
<P>
   Her students have changed in other ways, too. In the old days,
attendees at least knew the basic etiquette of dining. They knew
how to set a table and how much wine to put in a glass.
</P>
<P>
   No longer. Recently, the straight-talking Risley taught a
weekend class-cum-party for a dozen executives of a prominent
online business. The party favors were Harley-Davidsons.
</P>
<P>
   ``These guys were drinking $300 and $600 bottles of wine all
weekend, but when I asked, `Does anybody want to know how to open a
bottle?,' they all came running over. Because they don't know. You
ask, `Would you set the table?' and they reply, `What side does the
fork go on?' I'm not kidding. You wouldn't believe the number of
times I have to say, `Stop filling the glass up. People will think
you drink in cheap bars.'
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a whole generation of youngsters with a lot of money
who don't know that the wine glass goes over here and the bread and
butter plate there. That's what is propelling my biz now.''
</P>
<P>
   The past year brought Risley two major honors. Bon Appetit
magazine chose her as its first Cooking Teacher of the Year. And
for her considerable charitable work, Risley founded Foodrunners,
an organization that collects and distributes excess restaurant
food to shelters _ she was named the James Beard Foundation's
Humanitarian of the Year.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; ACACIA WINERY
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Then: &LR;  In 1979, Michael Richmond, a longtime employee of
Freemark Abbey, teamed up with attorney Jerry Goldstein to raise
money for a 15,000-case winery that would make Chardonnay and Pinot
Noir in the Burgundian style. To persuade potential investors that
he knew what he was doing, Richmond poured his homemade wine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oddly enough, those little homemade wines went a long way,
which surprised me,'' Richmond says. ``Homemade wine is a lot
different from running a winery.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the pair raised a little over $1 million,
purchased a half-interest in a Carneros vineyard and began making
wine in a rented facility using the methods they had seen in a
two-week tour of Burgundy.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we started Acacia, newspaper wine writers wrote about how
bad California Pinot Noir was and how California would never make
decent Pinot Noir,'' Richmond recalls. ``Our Pinot Noir label was a
knockoff of French labels because we didn't want to be associated
with California wines.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1981, the partners built a winery building and began enjoying
acclaim for their wines. But in 1986, the business almost capsized.
Plans to expand into Sauvignon Blanc and Cabernet Sauvignon ran
afoul of some of the original investors; in the ensuing turmoil,
Goldstein was forced out and the winery was sold to the Chalone
Wine Group. Richmond, who had started Acacia because he wanted to
make wine, became Chalone Wine Group's vice president of sales.
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; Now: &LR;  ``Chalone resurrected the winery, basically,'' says
Richmond, who returned to Acacia as general manager about a year
ago. Now at 45,000 cases of Pinot Noir and Chardonnay, the winery
plans to top out at 75,000 cases.
</P>
<P>
   Richmond believes that one of the biggest changes in the 20
years since Acacia's founding is the respect that California Pinot
Noirs now earn. And all those critics who used to write that the
varietal had no future here? ``It's probably been seven, eight,
maybe 10 years since I've seen anyone mention that,'' he says.
Acacia recently changed its label to one that is ``solidly
Californian,'' he points out. ``I don't really care about French
associations in our package anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; ZUNI CAFE
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Then: &LR;  With a $10,000 investment, Billy West started a
nine-table sandwich shop in San Francisco in 1979. He called it
Zuni Cafe. The restaurant had a hot plate but little else in the
way of a kitchen. Vince Calcagno, now a partner, remembers his
first meal there: swordfish cooked on a Weber grill in the back
alley.
</P>
<P>
   Calcagno, who at the time was a waiter at the new Hayes Street
Grill, became friendly with the Zuni owner; in 1981, he succumbed
to West's pleas to join the growing business.
</P>
<P>
   The early years were lean ones. Calcagno recalls serving diners
upstairs by candlelight because the upper room had no electricity.
``You couldn't see your food,'' he says, ``which might have been a
good thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Waiters made scrambled eggs with the steamer on the espresso
machine. (Don't ask about the coffee.) Despite its physical
challenges, the restaurant grew in popularity under the wildly
eclectic chef James Moore and, later, the Mediterranean-inspired
Kathi Riley. Black bean soup and guacamole with chips were menu
staples, and serapes covered the banquettes.
</P>
<P>
   In 1987, the two partners persuaded Judy Rodgers, whose cooking
they had admired at Benicia's Union Hotel, to take over the stoves.
The guacamole and black bean soup vanished and were replaced by
house-cured anchovies, the now-legendary hamburger and a much more
focused Mediterranean approach. Rodgers is now Calcagno's partner;
West died of AIDS in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Early on, the partners acquired the light-filled corner space to
the east but it took three years for them to amass enough money to
remodel it. Calcagno himself sledgehammered the floor and painted
the purple and green bathrooms. ``A lot of stuff was done like
that,'' he says. ``We had our pastry chef in a plastic bubble for a
long time, and she was such a good sport about it. But you had to
be. Everything was so homemade.''
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Now: &LR;  Zuni Cafe is a $5 million-a-year business and one of
the nation's most influential restaurants. After years of hounding
from publishers, Rodgers recently signed a contract to produce a
Zuni cookbook.
</P>
<P>
   Looking back, Calcagno says the pivotal decisions were bringing
Rodgers in as a partner and adding hard liquor in the late 1980s.
Fearful that a drinking crowd would compromise the food, the
partners had resisted. But today Zuni's lively bar is one of the
most popular places in the city for sophisticated hanging out.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
