   _  &UR; Zuni Cafe &LR; , 1658 Market St. (near Franklin), San Francisco;
(415) 552-2522. Lunch, dinner Tuesday-Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; _ On customers now: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``The good side is they're more knowledgeable (now). And they
are defimore demanding. Nobody knew what arugula was back
then; they all do now. They know that fish that isn't cooked too
much is a good thing, but in some ways they're not as much fun.
There was real excitement back then about what was happening with
food. (Now) they're always looking for the next, more fantastic
thing.''  &LR; _ &LR;   &LR; Vince Calcagno, Zuni Cafe &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ On fear of goat cheese: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``You used to put chevre on a menu and people wouldn't know what
it was. You couldn't use that word. You had to say goat cheese, and
if you said goat cheese, then they definitely didn't want it.''  &LR; _
Annie Somerville, Greens &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; rh1  &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; _On restaurant wine lists: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``In the 1970s, it wasn't a question of what kind of wine list a
restaurant had, but did the restaurant have a wine list at all?
There were only maybe 200 wineries then, and we would help each
other get our wines on the list. Now there's a level of competition
that doesn't necessarily preclude that, but we know that if one of
our wines goes on, another winery's (wine) goes off.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest change is that wine and dining go together now.
(Wine) still may not be part of American culture, but it is part of
American dining culture, and it wasn't in the '60s and 70s.''  &LR; _
Michael Richmond, Acacia Winery &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _On opening a restaurant: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``When I walk into a new restaurant now and it's a $2 million or
$4 million or $5 million (investment), my first thought is, how are
they going to pay for this? Because I know how much restaurants
make. That's why a lot of people go under, and that's one of the
biggest differences between then and now. The real investment then
was your time and energy.''  &LR; _ Vince Calcagno, &LR;   &LR; Zuni Cafe &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ On making money: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really good at spending money, so we never have a profit.
I told somebody the other day that we broke $1 million in 1998, and
he said, `How much did you profit from that?' And I said, `Profit?
I'm not in it for a profit. It's so I can eat at Zuni and
Greens.'''  &LR; _ Mary Risley, Tante Marie's Cooking School &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ On what keeps them awake at night: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``My fear is that people are getting more impressed by weird
dishes that have too many ingredients, and they are starting to
forget what simple (food) is. Look at the horrible comedians
getting $20 million for a movie. They're not even funny. They're
just crude, and that's a threat to me _ that people wouldn't
recognize quality. I worry about society in general deteriorating
and not realizing what good things are.''  &LR; _ Vince Calcagno, Zuni &LR; 
 &LR; Cafe &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``We are selling (wine) to such a rarefied portion of the
population. There are tea drinkers and Coke drinkers and Snapple
drinkers, but there's not a broad base of wine drinkers.
Advertising money is shaping the taste of Americans. It's the
Kendall-Jacksons and the Gallos that are going to save our industry
because they're going to put money into national advertising.''  &LR; _
Michael Richmond, Acacia Winery &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; MARY RISLEY'S FRESH FIG &AMP; PLUM TART
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   Crust
</P>
<P>
   1 cup flour
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup butter, cut in 1-inch pieces
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/8 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon water mixed with a few drops vanilla
</P>
<P>
   Filling
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup unpeeled almonds
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 egg
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons butter
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons raspberry or cherry eau-de-vie (framboise or kirsch)
</P>
<P>
   Topping
</P>
<P>
   1 pound unpeeled figs, halved
</P>
<P>
   1 pound dark plums, halved
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup red currant jelly
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon framboise or kirsch
</P>
<P>
   &UR; To make the crust:  &LR; Place the flour, butter, sugar and salt in
a food processor. Process until the butter is the size of oatmeal
flakes. With the machine running, pour in the water mixture.
Process until the dough comes together in a ball.
</P>
<P>
   Press this mixture into a 9-inch tart pan, preferably with a
removable bottom. Refrigerate until chilled.
</P>
<P>
   Bake in a preheated 375 degrees oven until lightly browned, 10
to 12 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Cool on a rack.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; To make the filling:  &LR; Preheat oven to 375 degrees. Process the
almonds and sugar in a food processor until the almonds are finely
ground. Add the egg, butter and eau-de-vie. Process 1 minute.
</P>
<P>
   Spread the almond mixture in the cooled pastry shell. Arrange
the figs and plums cut sides up, in alternating concentric circles,
over the almond mixture. The almond mixture should be completely
covered with fruit. Bake for 30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Combine the jelly and framboise or kirsch in a small saucepan
and melt over low heat.
</P>
<P>
   Unmold the tart, if possible, onto a pretty plate. Using a
pastry brush, lightly coat the figs and plums with the melted
jelly.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 530 calories, &LR;   &LR; 6 g protein, 70 g carbohydrate, &LR; 
 &LR; 27 g fat (14 g saturated), 92 mg cholesterol, 240 mg sodium, 5 &LR;   &LR; g
fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
ZUNI CAFE'S CHOCOLATE POT DE CREME
</P>
<P>
   This rich dessert has been served at Zuni since the early 1980s,
well before the restaurant's famous hamburger, roast chicken or
gateau Victoire made the menu. The chocolate version is the most
requested flavor.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   6 ounces bittersweet chocolate, chopped
</P>
<P>
   11/2 cups heavy cream
</P>
<P>
   11/2 cups milk
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   8 egg yolks
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 300 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Melt the chocolate with 1/2 cup of the cream in a 2-quart
saucepan or in a bowl over simmering water. Remove from heat.
</P>
<P>
   Combine the remaining 1 cup cream, the milk and sugar in a
saucepan and warm until the sugar dissolves.
</P>
<P>
   Whisk the yolks in a bowl, then slowly stir in the warm cream
mixture. Pour the resulting custard mixture through a strainer into
the melted chocolate and stir to combine.
</P>
<P>
   Pour the mixture into 6 custard cups and place them at least an
inch apart in a baking pan. Add enough hot water to the pan to
reach just under the lip of the cups. Bake until the custards are
just set at the edges, about 45 minutes. They will continue to cook
after you remove them from the oven, and the chocolate will harden
as it cools. Take care not to overcook; this custard is best when
slightly soft. Loosely cover and refrigerate.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 500 calories, &LR;   &LR; 9 g protein, 29 g carbohydrate, &LR; 
 &LR; 41 g fat (23 g saturated), 371 mg cholesterol, 65 mg sodium, 1 &LR;   &LR; g
fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; JOSA'S CHICKEN MOLE VERDE
</P>
<P>
   Josefina Perez is an Acacia Winery employee who occasionally
cooks Mexican food for the staff. Michael Richmond recommends
Acacia's Chardonnay or Pinot Noir with this dish.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   2 whole chickens
</P>
<P>
   Chicken stock or water to cover
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup corn oil
</P>
<P>
   4 slices firm-textured white bread
</P>
<P>
   5 (6-inch) corn tortillas
</P>
<P>
   Dry ingredients
</P>
<P>
   4 ounces (about 3/4 cup) sesame seeds
</P>
<P>
   6 ounces (about 1 cup) raisins
</P>
<P>
   1 tablet (3.1 ounces) Ibarra Mexican chocolate, broken into
chunks
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup pumpkin seeds
</P>
<P>
   10 to 12 whole almonds
</P>
<P>
   1 cinnamon stick
</P>
<P>
   15 whole cloves
</P>
<P>
   15 whole black peppercorns
</P>
<P>
   Fresh Ingredients
</P>
<P>
   2 pounds tomatillos, husked
</P>
<P>
   2 pounds spinach, stemmed
</P>
<P>
   1 bunch Swiss chard, stems and ribs removed
</P>
<P>
   1 bunch cilantro, stemmed
</P>
<P>
   1 head romaine lettuce, cored and chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 bunch green onions, trimmed and sliced
</P>
<P>
   5 garlic cloves
</P>
<P>
   3 shallots
</P>
<P>
   1/4 to 1/2 pound serrano chiles, stemmed and seeded, if desired
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Put the chickens in a large pot with stock or water to cover.
Bring to a simmer, skimming. Adjust heat to maintain a gentle
simmer and cook for 2 hours. Remove the chickens and let cool, then
cut into serving pieces or pull the meat off the bones in large
bite-size chunks. Reserve the stock.
</P>
<P>
   Heat a little of the corn oil in a large skillet over moderately
high heat. Fry the bread slices on both sides until browned, then
fry the tortillas until crisp, adding more oil as needed. Drain on
paper towels.
</P>
<P>
   Toast the sesame seeds in a dry skillet until lightly colored.
</P>
<P>
   In a blender, working in batches if necessary, blend the sesame
seeds, raisins, chocolate, pumpkin seeds and almonds to a paste,
thinning with a small amount of the reserved chicken stock (about
1/2 cup).
</P>
<P>
   Grind the cinnamon, cloves and peppercorns in a spice grinder
until finely ground. Add to the paste and blend well.
</P>
<P>
   Transfer the spice paste to a large frying pan and simmer,
stirring, constantly, for 15 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   In a blender (working in batches), blend all the fresh
ingredients to a puree, thinning with a small amount of the
reserved chicken stock (about 1/2 cup). Add to the cooked spice
paste and simmer for 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Add the cooked chicken to the sauce, season with salt and pepper
and heat through.
</P>
<P>
   Serve with rice.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 10.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 600 calories, &LR;   &LR; 43 g protein, 50 g
carbohydrate, &LR;   &LR; 27 g fat (6 g saturated), 94 mg cholesterol, 247 mg
sodium, 9 g &LR;   &LR; fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
GREEN GULCH YELLOW FINN POTATO CAKES
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   2 pounds large Yellow Finn or Yukon Gold potatoes
</P>
<P>
   11/2 teaspoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   11/2 cups thinly sliced leeks (white part only)
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   1 egg
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons creme fraiche + 1/2 cup for garnish
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup grated Asiago, Gruyere or fontina cheese
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   Vegetable oil for cooking the cakes
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Boil the potatoes in their skins until they're slightly
underdone, about 20 minutes. Drain, saving 1/2 cup of the cooking
water, and let cool. Peel the potatoes, then grate on the largest
holes of a grater or in a food processor.
</P>
<P>
   Heat the olive oil in a skillet; add the leeks, season with salt
and pepper and saute until leeks are tender, about 5 minutes,
adding a little reserved potato-cooking water to keep them from
sticking. Toss with the grated potatoes and season with salt and
pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Combine the egg and 3 tablespoons creme fraiche in a small bowl;
beat until blended. Add to the potato mixture and mix well. Add the
cheese and flour and mix again.
</P>
<P>
   Form the mixture into cakes 3 to 4 inches in diameter and about
1/2 inch thick. Cook in a lightly oiled skillet or on a griddle
over medium heat until the cakes are golden on both sides, 4 to 5
minutes per side. Keep each batch of cakes warm in a low oven while
you make the rest.
</P>
<P>
   Serve hot, with a dollop of creme fraiche.
</P>
<P>
   Yields 12 to 15 cakes; serves 4.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER CAKE: &LR;   &LR; 89 calories, &LR;   &LR; 3 g protein, 11 g carbohydrate, 4 g &LR; 
 &LR; fat (2 g saturated), 23 mg cholesterol, 58 mg sodium, 0 fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; PROVENCAL REVERIE
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from ``American Country Cheese,'' by Laura Chenel and
Linda Siegfried (Addison Wesley, 1989).
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   1 cup fruity olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 large head garlic, cloves peeled and slivered
</P>
<P>
   1 large bay leaf
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup fresh thyme leaves
</P>
<P>
   Generous grind black pepper
</P>
<P>
   8 ounces fresh goat cheese, thinly sliced
</P>
<P>
   Sliced baguette
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Combine the oil, garlic and bay leaf in a saute pan and simmer
over low heat for about 15 minutes. Do not let the garlic brown.
Add the thyme and black pepper. Heat 1 to 2 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Arrange the cheese on a serving plate. Pour the warm garlic
mixture over the cheese and serve with warmed or toasted baguette
slices.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4 to 6.
</P>
<P>
   &QR; }h.f &UR; WH(8
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
