<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-12 17:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4490 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d BC-WINE-YATTARNA-ART-3TA     10-12 0880
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINE-YATTARNA-ART-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GROOMING A CHARDONNAY FOR STARDOM 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By R.W. APPLE Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NURIOOTPA, Australia _ The project lasted for more than six
years, and it cost at least $1 million. But it produced a fitting
white stable mate for Grange, Australia's superstar red wine, which
was once described by the English wine writer Hugh Johnson as the
New World's only real first growth. The newcomer is called
Yattarna, after an Aboriginal word meaning ``little by little.''
</P>
<P>
   The first vintage, 1995, released last year, caused a sensation.
It won all four categories for which it was eligible at the Sydney
Wine Show, the first wine ever to do so. People camped out
overnight at the cellar door of Penfolds, which makes it, for the
right to buy a single bottle. The second vintage, in the view of
Australian critics, is even better.
</P>
<P>
   Yattarna has added new luster to the already sterling reputation
of South Australia as a world-class producer of premium wines _ a
reputation that has been established in little more than two dozen
years.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the planet's great wines emerge from cobwebby Old World
wineries or sleek California setups. Not Grange and Yattarna. They
are produced at a gigantic, highly mechanized facility here in the
Barossa Valley, a remote, largely unspoiled stretch of countryside
45 miles northeast of Adelaide.
</P>
<P>
   With wine tanks the size of silos, miles of tubing and more than
a dozen low-lying buildings, the Penfolds operation looks more like
an oil refinery than a winery.
</P>
<P>
   One bunker-like, air-conditioned concrete structure, covering
five acres, has a capacity of 80,000 300-liter hogsheads. All of
the upper-end Penfolds red wines, including Grange, are aged in
this building, by far the largest of its kind in the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``No lovely mystical winery here,'' said Peter Gago, a member of
Duval's wine-making team, as he drove us around the place. ``Here
it's all production, all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   The Barossa, settled by Scottish and German immigrants in the
1830s and 1840s, has seen a surge of winemaking success in recent
years, and not just at Penfolds. The family-owned Henschke Cellars,
just up the road from Nuriootpa, produces a shiraz called Hill of
Grace that in many years rivals Grange; on one restaurant wine list
in Adelaide, the 1980 Hill of Grace was $215, slightly more than
the 1980 Grange, at $200.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Grange, Hill of Grace is made each year from grapes from
the same vineyard; that makes it more vulnerable to the vagaries of
the weather. But when the viticultural gods smile, as they did in
1991 and 1994, Stephen Henschke, whose family has been growing
grapes in the Barossa for five generations, turns them into
voluptuous wines that age a bit more quickly than the slow-maturing
Granges.
</P>
<P>
   As in California, tiny vineyards have also caused a stir, not
only with peppery shiraz but also with Rhone-style blends of
shiraz, aromatic mourvedre and fruity grenache. At a utilitarian
little winery set against the swell of gentle green hills, Charles
Melton, a ringer for the Marlboro cowboy, produces an opulent,
much-esteemed blend called Nine Popes (the name is based on a shaky
translation of Chateauneuf-du-Pape).
</P>
<P>
   He is often credited with single-handedly reviving the grenache
grape in Australia. Using the fruit from thick, gnarled, ancient
bush vines, some planted before the American Civil War, Turkey Flat
turns out luscious Grenache Noire and award-winning shiraz.
</P>
<P>
   These and other top Barossa wines, including Glaetzer, Elderton,
Mountadam and St. Hallett Old Block, are making their way to the
United States, often in tiny quantities. The Australian Wine Bureau
(212-351-6585 or www.wineaustralia.com), can help track them down.
</P>
<P>
   Nine Popes turns up occasionally on the wine lists of American
restaurants, including the highly original one that Stephen Beckta,
a young Canadian sommelier, has assembled at Cafe Boulud in
Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it is giant Southcorp, which owns Penfolds, that sets the
standard. It thinks big. It exports more top-end red and white
table wines (excluding bulk wines, champagne and fortified wines)
than any other company in the world _ a total of 5.5 million cases
in 1998, including 2.5 million cases to Britain, where it is a
major supermarket presence, and 1.5 million to the United States.
The figures have roughly doubled in the last five years, and more
than 40 percent of the company's sales are now abroad.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of those sales, of course, are modestly priced wines of
the kind that earned Australia a reputation for ``sunshine in a
bottle.'' But while churning out millions of cases of everyday
drink, Southcorp also manages to lavish a lot of attention on 7,000
to 12,000 cases a year of Grange and fewer than 2,000 cases of
Yattarna. It is an unusual combination.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could sell 10, 20 times that many if we had them,'' said
David Combe, the former politician and diplomat who heads
Southcorp's export operations. ``But the winemakers decide how much
to produce, not the accountants or the salesmen.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
