<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991012.0197 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-12 17:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4492 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d BC-WINE-YATTARNA-ART-2ND     10-12 0922
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINE-YATTARNA-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NURIOOTPA, Australia: the salesmen.''  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   John Duval, the resolutely self-effacing chief winemaker at
Penfolds, who led the search for ``the white Grange,'' as the new
wine came to be called, sees Yattarna as a work in progress; hence
the name. At the moment, it is 100 percent chardonnay, but he does
not exclude the possibility that small amounts of other grapes
might be included in the future; most years, up to 15 percent
cabernet sauvignon is added to the shiraz (the Australian name for
syrah) from which Grange is made.
</P>
<P>
   Also still to be answered is the important question of aging:
will Yattarna mature gracefully, gaining depth and authority after
six, seven, even 10 years, or will it nose dive after two or three,
the way many American and Australian chardonnays have a disturbing
habit of doing?
</P>
<P>
   Yattarna has been built to last, in a balanced style, creamy but
not over oaky, with a luscious, lingering finish and a nice nip of
citrus at the end. But neither Duval nor his bosses at Southcorp
can be sure yet.
</P>
<P>
   There are those who decry the hype surrounding Yattarna, and
especially the high prices it has commanded from the outset _ at
least $80 on retailers' shelves, when it can be found, much more at
auction. Leeuwin Estate's Art Series chardonnay, from Western
Australia, and Petaluma's Tiers chardonnay, another new
super-premium, both have their champions.
</P>
<P>
   Len Evans, the dean of the Australian wine world, sees the
emergence of Yattarna and Tiers, in particular, as evidence that
Australia, like California, is sorting out which grapes grow best
in which region.
</P>
<P>
   The Adelaide Hills, he thinks, are ideal for chardonnay. The
grapes that go into Tiers come from that area, just east of
Adelaide, the South Australian capital, as do 90 percent of those
in the 1996 Yattarna; the other 10 percent come from Tumbarumba in
the far-off Snowy Mountains, near Canberra. In Australia's
punishing summer heat, hills and mountains offer islands of the
relatively cool weather chardonnay grapes like best.
</P>
<P>
   ``Up until now,'' Evans said, ``our chardonnays have been all
head and shoulders, like Picasso's bull. They start fast, then fade
fast, with no continuity and no finish. These new wines are a new
departure, an evolution in style. They have more intensity, better
structure and an enduring concentration of flavor. I think of them
as mini-Montrachets.''
</P>
<P>
   Grange was created by Max Schubert, a winemaking legend who died
in 1994. His portrait hangs to this day in a kind of shrine at
Penfolds, surrounded by locked wood-and-glass cases containing one
bottle of each Grange vintage.
</P>
<P>
   Looking up at it one evening not long ago, Duval, his successor,
took note of the crags and creases in the beaky face and said,
``There's a story for every one.''
</P>
<P>
   Deeply impressed by the first growths of Bordeaux, Schubert
emulated many French practices, including the use of new oak for
aging, in attempting to create an Australian counterpart. Lacking
sufficient cabernet sauvignon when he began, in 1951, he used
mostly shiraz grapes, and shiraz still predominates. At first, most
of the grapes came from the original Penfolds vineyard at Magill,
then on the outskirts of Adelaide.
</P>
<P>
   After five years, Schubert submitted the results to company
higher-ups. They hated it, and ordered him to cease production. But
he continued in secret, and eventually the brass relented. He
concluded that he had shown the wine too soon, before it had aged
enough to ``come together,'' as wine people say; even today, it
takes at least 10 years for a bottle of Grange to mature and 20 or
so for it to reach its peak.
</P>
<P>
   Today, there is a kind of Grangeomania among wine collectors,
who value it for its tastes of ``raspberries, strawberries,
violets, truffles and old boots,'' in Evans' exuberant description.
Auction prices have reached $300 and more for great vintages like
1976, 1986 and 1990. The 1990 was named Wine of the Year in 1995 by
The Wine Spectator, the first time a wine from anywhere other than
France or California had been so honored.
</P>
<P>
   Possibly the richest, most concentrated wine on earth, it is
still made mostly from the fruit of low-yielding old vines, grown
with the least possible irrigation. Today, only a few of the
grapes, and only in occasional years, come from Magill, which has
been almost completely swallowed up by Adelaide's suburban sprawl.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the fruit used in Grange comes from the Penfolds-owned
Kalimna vineyard, about three miles northwest of Nuriootpa. That,
said Gago, ``is where most of the oomph in the wine comes from.''
But important lots of grapes also come from a select group of
contract growers, to whom Penfolds pays cash bonuses for
outstanding quality, in the Barossa as well as other viticultural
regions in South Australia like McClaren Vale and the Clare Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Almost all comes from old vines, some of them 100 years old.
</P>
<P>
   Unhindered by the restrictive geographical appellations used in
France, Italy and increasingly in the United States, Penfolds could
use grapes grown anywhere in Australia in Grange. In practice, it
doesn't do so.
</P>
<P>
   Forsaking the taste of individual terroirs, or localities, that
the French prize so highly, Penfolds seeks a consistent ``house
style.''
</P>
<P>
   But each batch of grapes has to earn its way into the Grange
blend each year. Each is vinified separately, then tasted by Duval
and his colleagues until they reach a consensus on what to use.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-12-99 1717EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991012.0198 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-12 17:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4494 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d BC-WINE-YATTARNA-ART-3RD     10-12 0811
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINE-YATTARNA-ART-3RDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NURIOOTPA, Australia: to use.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Of 60-odd outside growers, only nine or 10 see their produce
chosen each year. If relatively little fruit makes the cut, Grange
production that year is reduced.
</P>
<P>
   The fruit that misses goes into one of the other premium
Penfolds reds. The company makes a lot of them _ pure cabernets
like Bin 707, a powerful, layered wine that competes with
Australia's best; pure shirazes like Kalimna Bin 28, which has won
almost as many prizes here and abroad as Grange, and several
blends, including St. Henri, which is aged not in new, small
barrels but in huge, 45-year-old casks, and Bin 389, which Gago
described as ``the poor man's Grange.'' It's the one he and his
colleagues buy for their cellars.
</P>
<P>
   Red wines have always carried the Penfolds flag abroad. Almost a
decade ago, Ross Wilson, who then headed Southcorp, shared some of
the best with associates during a visit to Hong Kong. But when it
came to white wine, they drank Montrachet, the great white
Burgundy.
</P>
<P>
   ``After a while,'' Combe recalled, ``he asked, `Why can't we
make something like that?' Then he gave the boys an open
checkbook.''
</P>
<P>
   Basically, Duval and his colleagues set out to use the Grange
methodology _ assembling a wine from the best fruit available,
grown in cool climates all across Australia. At first, they
considered using riesling or semillon grapes, which have for
decades made some of Australia's best and longest-lived wines,
quite different from what they produce in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   But it is chardonnay that has the international reputation,
Duval said, so it was chardonnay that quickly became the focus of
the ``white Grange'' search (though an experimental wine released
in 1994 contained 10 percent sauvignon blanc). The process was
semipublic, with wine writers and others invited to taste trial
blendings.
</P>
<P>
   And it had the full support of Southcorp managers, unlike
Schubert's original quest.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1995 we decided we had to draw a line in the sand and
release the first Yattarna,'' Duval said. ``We had teased people
long enough. We had concluded that the Adelaide Hills, with their
low yields, were going to give us most of what we wanted, which is
flavor, length and intensity.''
</P>
<P>
   Fruit trees and vines had always grown on the middle slopes of
the Adelaide Hills, but chardonnay has been planted there only for
the last decade. As the vines mature, so should the wine improve,
little by little.
</P>
<P>
   Happiest Hunting In South Australia
</P>
<P>
   Any hungry wine lover who turns up in South Australia will find
lots of good things to eat and agreeable places in which to eat
them.
</P>
<P>
   The Australian Gourmet Traveller, the country's leading food
magazine, chose the Grange Restaurant, in the Adelaide Hilton
(Victoria Square; 011-61-8-8237-0698), as its restaurant of the
year in 1998. The Malaysian Chinese chef, Cheong Liew, started
blending European techniques with Asian ingredients 25 years ago,
before anyone had thought of the word ``fusion.''
</P>
<P>
   By now, his is a cuisine of infinite refinement, a parade of
sweet, spicy, salty, smoky, sour and garlicky flavors. Liew
innovates fearlessly, using marjoram and chili, for instance, to
flavor his fish beignets.
</P>
<P>
   Penfolds serves solid, classic food at its Magill Estate
Restaurant (78 Penfolds Road, Magill, 011-61-8-8301-5551), a
handsome glass box overlooking the city from the lower slopes of
the Adelaide Hills. The all-Penfolds wine list is stuffed with
older vintages and offers both Yattarna and Grange by the glass.
</P>
<P>
   Petaluma has the Bridgewater Mill (Mount Barker Road,
Bridgewater, 011-61-8-8339-3422), a leafy spot 35 minutes southeast
of town, open only for lunch, Thursday through Monday. The fine
Vietnamese chef, Le Thu Thai, er, bowled us over with his herby hot
and sour snapper soup with prawn dumplings.
</P>
<P>
   For the truly obsessive, there is no beating the Universal Wine
Bar (285 Rundle Street, Adelaide, 011-61-8-8232-5000), patterned
after Willi's Wine Bar in Paris. Order a steak frites, or the
smoked and lightly grilled salmon, a revelation. Then attack the
comprehensive, more than fairly priced wine list.
</P>
<P>
   If you fancy a pinot noir, for example, you will find not only
South Australia's best but also medal winners from the Melbourne
region and famous names from around the world.
</P>
<P>
   Maggie Beer, one of the most famous names in Australian food,
has reentered the restaurant business with Charlick's Feed Store
(Ebenezer Place, Adelaide, 011-61-8-8223-7566), a big, breezy spot
downtown that features wonderfully briny, deep-shelled oysters from
nearby Cowell Bay and the remarkably plump, moist chickens raised
by her daughter Saskia in the Barossa. An oversize sheet lists more
than 150 wines, all but three or four of them Australian, including
big names and small, some absurdly cheap. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
