<HEADER>
A4502 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-FRENCH-BOOK-REVIEW-NY     10-12 1150
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRENCH-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`FRENCH DNA': BIOTECHNOLOGY MEETS FRENCH PRIDE AND FEARS 
</HEADLINE>
   (editors: publication notes at end of review)  
 (bl)  
 By RICHARD BERNSTEIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The dust jacket of this new book by Paul Rabinow asks an
outrageous question: ``Is there such a thing as `French DNA?''' The
answer, of course, is no, if by French DNA one means some
genetically unique and precious substance that makes the French
biologically different from others. But Rabinow's answer is a sort
of symbolic yes, and that is what gives his book, ``French DNA:
Trouble in Purgatory,'' its scandalous flavor.
</P>
<P>
   Rabinow, a professor of anthropology at the University of
California at Berkeley, tells the story of the collapse of an
agreement between a French institute and an American company to
collaborate on genetic research. The reason for the collapse was
the French government's refusal to allow the American company
access to the most valuable asset of the French institute,
thousands of samples of genetic material collected from French
families that had volunteered in the service of medical advance.
The DNA in question wasn't deemed to be biologically unique, but it
was seen as part of the French patrimony, and therefore requiring
protection from crass commercial exploitation by hegemonic America.
</P>
<P>
   There are elements of defensive French nationalism in this that
are reminiscent of the battle to banish English words from the
language of Moliere. But Rabinow has a far more complex and subtle
interpretation. His book makes clear that a French ethical and
historical unease over manipulating the very constituent
ingredients of life played at least as important a role in the
failed collaboration, as did France's continuing worries about
American domination. In acting as they did, the French were
expressing a belief that DNA, cells, genes, body parts in general
are indistinguishable from the human person and therefore sacred,
inappropriate for profit-making activity.
</P>
<P>
   Rabinow's telling of this story is brilliant but also unkempt,
penetrating and impenetrable at the same time. The narrative is
frequently disjointed, with interpretive passages alternating with
background summaries and what seem to be almost raw field notes.
Rabinow is too interested in the social meaning of things to bother
much with explanations of the science involved, and he makes
references to such things as polymerase chain reactions as if we
all know what they are. Most important, perhaps, Rabinow's writing
is turgid and stilted, or so it will surely seem to people
unaccustomed to the language and the in-group conceptual devices of
the American Anthropological Association.
</P>
<P>
   The bare bones of Rabinow's story are these: By 1994 France's
leading genetics laboratory, the Center for the Study of Human
Polymorphism, known by the French acronym CEPH, had struck a deal
with a start-up American company, Millennium Pharmaceuticals, to
collaborate in finding the gene that causes diabetes and then to
profit from the therapeutic application of that discovery. The
laboratory's main contribution was to have been its bank of genetic
samples collected from the families of French diabetics. Before the
agreement went ahead, the French government in early 1994 put a
stop to it, with one official making the remark about French DNA
that gave Rabinow his title.
</P>
<P>
   Rabinow dispenses with those bare bones in a quick introduction
and then, in Chapter 1, plunges into ultra-high concept, the deep
and difficult-to-grasp meaning of things. Borrowing concepts from
Weber, Foucault, Hannah Arendt, Aristotle, Italian philosopher
Giorgio Agamben and several others, Rabinow sets up a kind of
theoretical framework.
</P>
<P>
   The main idea here threatens to become lost in a fog of
highfalutin lingo, but occasionally it emerges sufficiently into
the clear to be understood by mere mortals. It is in essence that
biotechnology, especially the ability to alter life forms, has
changed the rules of the ethical game, destroying old definitions
of life itself without creating new ones.
</P>
<P>
   ```Life' is problematic today because new understandings and new
technologies that are involved in giving it a form are producing
results that escape the philosophical self-understanding provided
by both the classical world and the Christian tradition,'' Rabinow
writes in one of the clearer statements he makes in this section.
This has produced an anxiety in certain quarters that he likens to
the emergence of the idea of Purgatory in Christian theology seven
centuries ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the moral and moralistic discursive productions surrounding
key sectors of the life sciences, purgatorial themes and tropes
retain (or, better, once again attain) a certain actuality,'' he
writes. In other words, we don't know whether we are heading for a
kind of heaven on earth or for an eventual ethical hell.
</P>
<P>
   The most interesting parts of ``French DNA'' are Rabinow's
concrete and lucid explanations of this French unease over the
practices that have emerged in recent decades: the collection of
blood, organ transplants, in-vitro fertilization and genetic
research. The French, concerned about equality of care and holding
to the notion, as Rabinow puts it, that ``the body is the person''
and is therefore sacred, have been uncomfortable with
biotechnology, and even more uncomfortable with the commercial
exploitation of it. Expressing his frustration with this attitude,
which he saw as obstructionist and outmoded, the president of the
laboratory, Daniel Cohen, presented Rabinow with a different view:
``Why make the natura as it now stands sacred?''
</P>
<P>
   In Rabinow's view, it isn't sacred; yet what he calls the French
``sanctification of the genome'' lay behind the political
opposition to the CEPH-Millennium deal. Other factors played roles
as well, and Rabinow covers them. One was a conflict between two
leading figures within the laboratory itself, with one of them
manipulating French ethical concerns.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was the good old-fashioned French sensitivity to
American power. When the French press discovered the
CEPH-Millennium agreement, it presented it as the pathetic giveaway
of an important part of the noble French patrimony. It is here that
the idea of ``French DNA'' entered the picture.
</P>
<P>
   Rabinow has combined a rich set of themes and observations with
a deep grasp of the French to create this portrait of France
struggling with the technologically new, trying to achieve a moral
balance among curing disease, making money and upholding the sacred
value of life. It is too bad that he chose to tell this very modern
tale from within a closed professional world that keeps the rest of
us on the outside looking in.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `FRENCH DNA: Trouble in Purgatory'
</P>
<P>
   By Paul Rabinow
</P>
<P>
   201 pages. University of Chicago Press. $25.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
