<TEXT>
<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The New York Times Photo Service has moved
the following photos to compliment coverage of the military coup in
Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) SIACHEN GLACIER, in the western Himalayas -- Oct. 12,
1999 -- PAKISTAN-ARMY-3, 10-12 -- Pakistani soldiers on patrol in
the high peaks of the western Himalayas in this photo taken earlier
this year. Pakistan, like India, has some 3,000 soldiers fighting
in a border war here that is now 15 years old. Prime Minister Nawaz
Sharif of Pakistan was ousted in a military coup on Tuesday after
sacking the country's powerful army chief. Sharif's ouster sparked
expressions of concern from around the world, not least in
neighboring India where officials said the armed forces were on a
state of ``full alert.'' (Pakistani Military/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) WAGHA, Pakistan -- Oct. 12, 1999 -- PAKISTAN-ARMY-2,
10-12 -- A Pakistani Ranger stands guard at border crossing between
India and Pakistan in this 1997 file photo. Prime Minister Nawaz
Sharif of Pakistan was ousted in a military coup on Tuesday after
sacking the country's powerful army chief. Sharif's ouster sparked
expressions of concern from around the world, not least in
neighboring India where officials said the armed forces were on a
state of ``full alert.'' (John Giannini/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) ISLAMABAD, Pakistan -- Oct. 12, 1999 -- PAKISTAN-ARMY,
10-12 -- Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif of Pakistan in the foyer of
his official residence in this 1997 file photo. Sharif was ousted
in a military coup on Tuesday after sacking the country's powerful
army chief. A senior police official said troops had told Sharif
not to leave his Islamabad residence and police at his home had
been disarmed. (John Giannini/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   If you have any questions, please call 212-556-4204 or
888-603-1036.
</P>
