A4506 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-MOSQUITONETS13-COX     10-12 0341
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOSQUITONETS13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    PESTICIDE-SOAKED MOSQUITO NETS FOR AFRICAN CHILDREN
 &HT;    By JEFF NESMITH
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The World Health Organization on Tuesday launched a
five-year campaign to protect at least 60 million African children
from malaria with bed nets soaked with pesticide.
</P>
<P>
   The mosquito-borne illness is the largest killer of children in
Africa, causing an estimated 700,000 childhood deaths annually.
</P>
<P>
   Officials attending a multilateral malaria conference this week
in Dar es Salaam, Tanzania, said recent studies show that children
who sleep under nets that have been impregnated with pyrethroids, a
common pesticide, are 50 percent less likely to get malaria.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is scandalous that 700,000 African children died last year
from malaria when a $4 bed net could have saved them,'' said David
Alnwick, chief of health for UNICEF.
</P>
<P>
   WHO officials said that by working with African governments to
eliminate tariffs on bed nets and insecticides and using
mass-marketing strategies, they believe they can bring cost of nets
down $2 each, an amount within the reach of most African families.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign, to be called ``Roll Back Malaria,'' will also
solicit individual donations for families who cannot afford to buy
the nets.
</P>
<P>
   Nils Daulaire, head of the private Global Health Council, said
that in addition to saving the lives of children, the bed net
campaign will cut down on the overall ``pool of infected
individuals'' and probably reduce the number of cases of the
disease among adults.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is probably the leading strategy for saving children's
lives in Africa,'' Daulaire said. ``Even among children who have
the disease and don't die of malaria, the infection leaves them
weakened and less able to deal with other diseases.''
</P>
<P>
   Individuals who are interested in making contributions to help
purchase nets can get information by sending an e-mail to
rdm(at)who.int.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
