<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-$ADV19-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN SHOPPING IS SERIOUS
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Tuesday, Oct. 19)  
(nk) 
 By SUSAN SWARTZ   
 Santa Rosa (Calif.) Press Democrat   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   We're on the prowl for pants. We fan through the store, move
through the racks. Dressy, sporty, tailored, trendy, drawstring,
pleated? What are those with the button front? Sailor? Geez,
parachute pants. So '80s.
</P>
<P>
   Are those flares? I remember flares. Possibly invented by Cher.
All the London models wore them. You need platforms if you're going
to wear flares. I don't know why, but I remember that you do.
</P>
<P>
   We are shopping, one mother and two adult daughters, of similar
tastes with a few strong exceptions and different fashion memories,
equally outspoken and pledged to not let anyone buy something she
will regret later. This is strategic shopping. We are not here to
browse but to buy. We have a list.
</P>
<P>
   We move fast, choosing, rejecting, sympathizing, admonishing,
cajoling, commenting, standing back and frowning, creating a force
field that no clerk can penetrate. We have done this before.
</P>
<P>
   Is every single pair of pants in this store made out of spandex?
Do you think these pouf out funny on the side? Does stretch
stretch? Stretch doesn't work on everyone. No, I'm not saying you.
They look good on you. Get the black.
</P>
<P>
   Because black goes with everything. And black is slimming. No,
I'm not saying you're fat. I think they'll loosen up. No, I'm not
saying they're tight.
</P>
<P>
   What do you wear under stretch pants? Thong underwear? Not in
this life.
</P>
<P>
   Stretch pants can't last. There are no pockets.
</P>
<P>
   Try some jeans, at least. You never outgrow your need for jeans.
</P>
<P>
   We are looking for a basic sweater. An easy pullover. An
uncommitted turtleneck. Something between a cowl and a mock.
Classic. Katherine Hepburnish. Not too long. Not too short. Three
quarter sleeves? What's wrong with pushing them up the old way?
</P>
<P>
   Minor distraction over at the T-shirt sale table. You can do
pink. I look sick in pink. Here's a yellow, but you've enough
yellow.
</P>
<P>
   Wouldn't you love to need a sweater like this in your life? It's
as heavy as a rug. This is not a California sweater. If you did a
lot of winter sailing in the North Atlantic you could wear that
sweater. Avoid temptation. Not even with jeans?
</P>
<P>
   I like the vest, but don't you already have something like that?
And what's with the hood?
</P>
<P>
   That's a good color with your eyes but short sleeve season is
definitely over.
</P>
<P>
   Do I wear this out or in? Button or unbutton? Do I really want
this shirt? Tell me why I need this. If I color my hair can I wear
this? Do I need to color my hair?
</P>
<P>
   We are seriously seeking shoes. Black ones. Hip looking ones,
but not too extreme. Something to wear with pants to the office.
Maybe a skirt.
</P>
<P>
   Do you ever wear skirts? No, but I could start, and if I did
could I wear these shoes? Sure, with tights. I don't wear tights.
OK, socks. Thick or thin?
</P>
<P>
   You could walk unaided up the sheer side of a mountain in those
shoes.
</P>
<P>
   You may have noticed that I don't do ladylike shoes.
</P>
<P>
   Try the platforms. I remember platforms. They have an attitude
and they might make you taller than your boss.
</P>
<P>
   What are those? They look so sad next to the big, tall shoes.
Like slippers, like something you wear after foot surgery. You
could never wear them with the pants. They're not worthy.
</P>
<P>
   It is the end of the day, the worst time to get lost in
shoeland. The clerks are rummy. There is nothing left in size 8. We
are hungry and tired, giddy with inappropriate shoe longings. We
break down just looking at a pair of peds. Put the shoes on hold,
come back tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   What do you think of this purse?
</P>
<P>
   That purse doesn't fit your body. We don't have the strength for
purses. Purses aren't on the list. We'll go eat now.
</P>
<P>
   (The Press Democrat in Santa Rosa, Calif., is part of the New
York Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
