<HEADER>
A4508 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      10-12 0831
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UP AND DOWN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARIANNE MEANS  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Revived by the official embrace of the AFL-CIO,
Vice President Al Gore and the rickety roller-coaster that is his
campaign have suddenly picked up momentum and are climbing upward.
</P>
<P>
   But with Bill Bradley closing in on him, there will be many
hair-raising dips ahead before the ride is over.
</P>
<P>
   My money is still on Gore to win the nomination. He's the more
experienced, articulate, consistent and disciplined of the two.
Thus far he has not proved that he is the better campaigner, but as
vice president he is being judged by a tougher standard than voters
have yet applied to the lesser-known Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   Gore won the AFL-CIO endorsement the old-fashioned way. He
earned it. The official union sign of approval, which will come on
Wednesday, was crucial to shatter a growing public perception that
his campaign was foundering. A delay in the labor federation's
endorsement past the early primaries would have announced to the
world that the unions feared Gore was a sinking ship.
</P>
<P>
   As the familiar political and sports maxim goes, when the going
gets tough, the tough get going. Gore campaigned hard for the
endorsement, relying not just on old favors and old friends but on
a great deal of arm-twisting and private pressure from President
Clinton as well.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley campaigned to stave off the endorsement. But his
pro-labor record is not as strong as Gore's. Furthermore, union
leaders feared neutrality might encourage a long and bloody
Democratic primary fight, which nobody wanted. All Bradley had was
a sense of political momentum, and it was not enough.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley still trails Gore by 12 percentage points among
Democrats nationally in a recent USA Today-CNN-Gallup Poll. Yet in
the past month Gore dropped 12 points while Bradley gained 9 points
nationally. And in New Hampshire, which holds the first primary,
Bradley has pulled even with Gore, as he has in some other northern
states.
</P>
<P>
   Gore is wisely re-inventing his campaign with a new theme: Stay
and fight. He contrasts his own dogged support of the Democratic
Party and the battered Clinton presidency to Bradley's decision to
quit the Senate in 1996 in the gloomy days after the new Republican
majority took over Congress. It's a trumped-up issue, but
potentially effective nonetheless. Quitters are not voter
favorites.
</P>
<P>
   Moving his campaign headquarters to Tennessee, a silly stunt on
the surface, seems to be providing a psychological boost by
physically distancing the campaign from the White House and
Washington. If Gore cannot shake the public's Clinton fatigue, at
least he can say its source is miles away.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's best idea, however, is to challenge Bradley to a series
of debates, a truly masterful stroke that poses real problems for
Bradley. If Bradley declines to debate, he looks scared, an
outsider who has forgotten what he used to know. If he does debate,
he is likely to look like chopped liver when Gore is finished with
him.
</P>
<P>
   Shades of Hubert Humphrey, the Minnesota orator who drove the
segregationist South from the 1948 Democratic convention. Except
for the gab-gifted President Clinton, the vice president is the
most formidable public policy debater currently on the national
stage.
</P>
<P>
   Gore knows every national and international issue down to the
commas and semicolons. His memory for detail is astonishing. The
verbal axing he gave Ross Perot during their 1993 debate over the
North American Free Trade Agreement finished Perot as a serious
political figure.
</P>
<P>
   A debate could also put to rest the myth that Bradley is
charming plastic while Gore is dull wooden. During his Senate
years, Bradley had a reputation for being one of the most boring
legislators on Capitol Hill. He was a great cerebral yawn. If he
has perked up since then, now's the time to demonstrate it. But
frankly I don't believe in personality transplants.
</P>
<P>
   The debate idea reverses expectations, bringing Gore down to the
challenger's level and Bradley up to the incumbent's level.
Normally this would not be a good move for the incumbent. But Gore
loses nothing here, except some elitist baggage.
</P>
<P>
   He cannot shake an establishment image entirely, particularly
after the AFL-CIO endorsement. But he must superimpose on it a
picture of the human Al Gore, the hard-working public servant. To
that end, he has wisely dumped the lectern and vice presidential
seal that used to distance him from his audiences. He speaks now
more informally, as just another candidate.
</P>
<P>
   This is good stuff _ cosmetics, but important cosmetics. Yet in
the end the voters will respond to Gore's policy message and the
way it contrasts with Bradley's message.
</P>
<P>
   The question a voter asks is always the same: What have you done
for me lately and what will you do for me now?
</P>
<P>
   (Marianne Means can be reached by e-mail at
means(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
