<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-12 17:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4513 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d BC-OLD-COOKBOOKS-ART-2TA     10-12 1264
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLD-COOKBOOKS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SHELF OF TREASURES, ALWAYS FRESH 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: recipes in 2nd take; With OLD-COOKBOOKS-OLD)  
 (ART ADV: Photo (NYT1) is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By MARK BITTMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Cookbooks pose an unusual problem: their true value can be
determined only over time. No quick read-through can distinguish
the great from the merely good. No reviewer is going to cook every
single recipe to see if they all work. Instead, a cookbook is a lot
like other pieces of kitchen equipment: it needs to be used for
months, maybe years, before you know whether it really makes it _
that it truly is, as the blurb always says, indispensable.
</P>
<P>
   What a pity that it takes so long. By the time a good cookbook
proves that it is in fact great, it has probably been relegated to
the back shelves of the bookstore and replaced on the display
tables by this year's models, mostly mediocre to poor.
</P>
<P>
   Without doubt one of the best ways to search for cookbooks is to
reach into the past. I rarely refer to cookbooks that have been
published in the last couple of years, turning instead to those I
have come to know and trust; perhaps one book joins the list each
year. And an informal survey of experienced home cooks, food
writers, cookbook editors and authors, and bookstore owners and
buyers indicated that my experience is anything but unique.
</P>
<P>
   What was surprising, however, was that the same titles kept
coming up in those conversations. And gratifyingly, many were the
same as those on the list I'd rather not live without. This list is
incomplete and personal, of course, but the books share qualities
that make them enduring.
</P>
<P>
   These books are all meant to live in the kitchen, not on a
coffee table. They're comprehensive, with wide perspectives that
give a rich sense of the areas of cooking they cover.
</P>
<P>
   They contain information not readily available elsewhere, and
sometimes they are the only game in town. Each has a personality
and a life that makes it readable.
</P>
<P>
   And finally, the recipes work. A friend insists that if a
cookbook gives you 5 good new recipes, it's a success. Perhaps, but
how do you find those 5 if the 200 others are failures?
</P>
<P>
   Most of these books are in print, though some are more widely
available than others. The hard-to-find specimen often turns up on
line; among the better sources are www2.alibris.com, Amazon.com and
Bookfinder.com. Kitchen Arts and Letters, 1435 Lexington Ave., New
York 10128 (near 93rd Street), (212) 876-5550, is also a good bet.
</P>
<P>
   A BOOK OF MIDDLE EASTERN FOOD by Claudia Roden (Vintage Books,
1974; $16). Ms. Roden's most recent book, THE BOOK OF JEWISH FOOD
(Knopf, 1996), was an instant classic. But this volume, first
published in 1968, covers a broader, more important topic. I love
it for its flavors, its accessibility and its warmth. Ms. Roden
grew up as a Jew in Egypt, and she has a pleasantly unusual
perspective on the region's cuisine. More important, she has a
brilliant palate, sound judgment and a near-perfect recipe-writing
technique. Organized traditionally, by food groups, the book
includes 50 pages of mezze (appetizers) and salads, nearly a dozen
kibbeh (ground meat dishes), a survey of unusual beverages and
yogurt dishes and much more _ it's not just an introduction to
Middle Eastern food but a true guidebook. Few 30-year-old books
feel as current, not only in language but also in ingredients and
method. And passages like this one have made the book a favorite of
cooks who like to read: ``Every year, a type of migrating quail
flies over Alexandria. Hundreds of the small birds fall, exhausted,
on the dunes of the beaches of Agama, to be caught in large nets
and collected in baskets. They are marinated in a rich sauce
flavored with cumin and coriander, and grilled on the beaches over
numerous little fires.'' This is followed by a simple, irresistible
recipe for the marinade.
</P>
<P>
   MASTER RECIPES by Stephen Schmidt (Clear Light, second edition,
1998; $29.95). Schmidt, a New Yorker who teaches cooking and
occasionally writes for cooking magazines, practically perfected
the recipe-and-variation cookbook format. In 1989, the first
edition of this book met with critical but not commercial success
and fell out of print. Fortunately, there is a new edition, with
some updating. Schmidt's instructions are deliberate and clear, and
there are delightful common-sense surprises throughout. But the key
to this book is that it teaches cooking, and does so correctly.
This leads to some unusual recipe titles, like ``Braised Beef Stew
Meat (or Lamb Stew Meat, or Beef Pot Roast or Round Steak),'' but
they get the message across. The long, painstakingly detailed
recipes _ the one for beef stew runs more than 1,500 words _ can be
followed by a novice. And the variations (that recipe has 11) are
sensible and easy to follow.
</P>
<P>
   CHARMAINE SOLOMON'S ENCYCLOPEDIA OF ASIAN FOOD (Periplus
Editions, 1996; $39.95). This book, the newest on my list, filled a
desperately empty hole: it's the closest thing to an Asian
Larousse, and sorely needed. Ms. Solomon, who lives in Australia,
gives nearly equal weight to the cooking of two dozen countries,
including Indonesia, the Philippines, Sri Lanka and others that are
rarely mentioned elsewhere. There is no Asian technique or
ingredient I could think of that this book did not define
adequately, and there are 500 good recipes and dozens of beautiful,
detailed color illustrations (unfortunately grouped in the back).
If you just want to know the difference between palm sugar and
jaggery and the uses for each, this is the place. More important,
if you want seven distinctive and authentic variations on curry
paste, they are here, too.
</P>
<P>
   DESSERTS by Nancy Silverton (Harper &AMP; Row, 1986; out of print).
You'll have to search for this gem, but it's worth the effort. Ms.
Silverton, who is a co-owner of Campanile restaurant and La Brea
bakery in Los Angeles, was a leading light among pastry chefs in
the 1980s, but her dessert book was designed for the long run. It
is the first dessert book I turn to when trying something out of my
repertory. The recipes range from simple (spiced pecans) to
challenging (raspberry caramel napoleon). They have never failed
me, and most are impressive enough to be served at a four-star
restaurant. Yet the directions are clear enough to be followed by
any moderately experienced, patient home cook. The 20-page basics
section (``Trade Secrets'') sets the stage nicely.
</P>
<P>
   CLASSIC INDIAN COOKING by Julie Sahni (William Morrow, 1980;
$26.) A treasure, comparable in its accessibility and style to
Marcella Hazan's ``Classic Italian Cookbook.'' With it and a few
unusual ingredients, you will be able to prepare quite probably the
best Indian food you've ever eaten _ even if you are a novice cook.
In the first 95 pages, Ms. Sahni, a teacher and writer who lives in
Brooklyn, offers a succinct, purposeful introduction including
directions for making ghee (Indian-style clarified butter), cheese
and yogurt; detailed descriptions of every spice mentioned in the
book, and descriptions of basic techniques. This section by itself
it is worth the price of the book. Better still, it is followed by
400 pages of fantastic recipes. It's been 15 years since I cooked
my way through this book, yet it remains one of my most vivid
kitchen memories. I envy anyone who has yet to experience the joy
of discovery that it brings.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   FRENCH COOKING IN TEN MINUTES Edouard de Pomiane (North Point
Press, $10). A quirky choice, I'll admit. But this slim, witty
volume _ first published in 1930 and subtitled ``Adapting to the
Rhythm of Modern Life'' _ is a cult classic. The wicked quick
recipes (rarely taking as little as 10 minutes, but close) work,
especially for cooks with a little experience. And there's a
hilarious preface entitled ``Some Indispensable Concepts for
Understanding This Beautiful Book.'' These concepts, in fact, can
be revelations. De Pomiane suggests that the first thing you do
when you enter the kitchen is set a pot of water to boil: ``What's
it for? I don't know, but it's bound to be good for something.''
This is true, and a real time saver in many instances. As for
recipes, the author offers many soups, mostly based on bouillon
cubes (I'd suggest canned stock) or water; fish; bean dishes
(including a credible choucroute garnie); salads, and meats _ in
short, what you eat for dinner. There is some cheating here (some
recipes call for cooked potatoes, for example), but the spirit is
honest and the result valuable.
</P>
<P>
   CHICKPEAS IN GINGER SAUCE
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from Julie Sahni
</P>
<P>
   Time: 40 minutes
</P>
<P>
   4 cups cooked or canned chickpeas, with 1 cup of their liquid
</P>
<P>
   \ cup neutral oil, like canola
</P>
<P>
   2 cups chopped onion
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons minced ginger
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons minced garlic
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons ground coriander
</P>
<P>
   { teaspoon ground cardamom
</P>
<P>
   { teaspoon mango powder, or 1{ teaspoons lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   \ teaspoon cayenne
</P>
<P>
   \ teaspoon black pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 medium tomato, chopped
</P>
<P>
   Salt to taste
</P>
<P>
   1 medium onion, thinly sliced
</P>
<P>
   1 green chili, seeded, stemmed and shredded.
</P>
<P>
   1. Drain chickpeas, reserving liquid. Put oil in large skillet,
and turn heat to medium high. Add chopped onions; cook 5 minutes,
or until they turn light brown, stirring occasionally. Add ginger
and garlic, reduce heat to medium and cook 2 minutes, stirring.
</P>
<P>
   2. Add coriander, cardamom, mango powder (but not lemon juice),
cayenne and black pepper. Stir; then add tomato. Cook until tomato
becomes saucy and begins to separate from the oil, about 5 minutes.
Add the reserved chickpea liquid, the lemon juice if you are using
it, salt and { cup water.
</P>
<P>
   3. Cover, and turn heat to low; simmer about 10 minutes, or
until mixture is thickened. Add chickpeas, cover and cook 10
minutes longer. Taste, and adjust seasoning. Serve, passing sliced
onion and chili at the table.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings.
</P>
<P>
   POPPY SEED-ORANGE COOKIES
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from Nancy Silverton
</P>
<P>
   Time: 40 minutes, plus 1 hour's refrigeration
</P>
<P>
   2 sticks unsalted butter
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons grated or finely chopped orange zest (from about 3
oranges)
</P>
<P>
   { cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 egg yolk
</P>
<P>
   { teaspoon vanilla extract
</P>
<P>
   2 cups minus 2 tablespoons flour
</P>
<P>
   \ cup poppy seeds.
</P>
<P>
   1. Use an electric mixer to cream butter with orange zest until
it whitens and holds soft peaks, 3 to 5 minutes. Beat in sugar
until well blended.
</P>
<P>
   2. Whisk together egg yolk and vanilla, and beat in, scraping
down sides of bowl as necessary. Add flour and poppy seeds, mixing
only enough to combine. Wrap dough in plastic wrap, and chill 30
minutes, or until firm.
</P>
<P>
   3. Divide dough into 4 sections; work with one section at a
time, keeping the remainder refrigerated. On a lightly floured
surface, form each section into a solid log about 1{ inches thick.
Place on a cookie sheet, and put in the freezer at least 30
minutes, or until firm enough to slice. Repeat. (The dough may be
wrapped and frozen for as long as 3 months; it slices most easily
while frozen.)
</P>
<P>
   4. Preheat oven to 325 degrees. Using a sharp knife, slice logs
into ]-inch rounds; place them 1 inch apart on nonstick baking
sheets. Bake 12 to 15 minutes, or until firm and evenly browned.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: about 6 dozen.
</P>
<P>
   QUAIL MARINADE
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from Claudia Roden
</P>
<P>
   Time: 10 minutes
</P>
<P>
   5 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   Salt to taste
</P>
<P>
   Pinch cayenne
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon ground cumin
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon ground coriander
</P>
<P>
   1 onion, peeled and minced
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons finely chopped parsley.
</P>
<P>
   In a small bowl, combine all ingredients. Rub the mixture into 4
quail (or 2 Cornish hens or 1 chicken) and marinate at least 1 hour
before grilling. (Birds can marinate as long as 24 hours in the
refrigerator.)
</P>
<P>
   Yield: About { cup marinade.
</P>
</TEXT>
