<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-12 17:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4515 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d BC-OLD-COOKBOOKS-LIST-NY     10-12 0399
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLD-COOKBOOKS-LIST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORTH BUILDING A NEW BOOKCASE
</HEADLINE>
  With OLD-COOKBOOKS 
 (nk) 
 By MARK BITTMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are some other great cookbooks from the past, in no way of
the second rank but described more briefly here for reasons of
space.
</P>
<P>
   BISTRO COOKING by Patricia Wells (Workman, 1989; $13.95). This
American in Paris assembled 200 of her favorite recipes, culled
from years of reviewing restaurants in France. The selection is
authentic, quirky and wonderful.
</P>
<P>
   COUSCOUS AND OTHER GOOD FOODS FROM MOROCCO by Paula Wolfert
(HarperCollins, 1973; $18). This cookbook, Ms. Wolfert's first,
opened new worlds for American cooks, like those that followed.
Many recipes are challenging, but almost all are splendid.
</P>
<P>
   THE FINE ART OF ITALIAN COOKING by Giuliano Bugialli (Random
House, 1977; $27.50). The single most useful cookbook about Italian
food in print. Detailed and serious, it can vault your
understanding and execution to another level.
</P>
<P>
   ITALIAN FOOD and FRENCH PROVINCIAL COOKING by Elizabeth David
(Penguin U.S.A., 1999; $13.95 and $14.95). These books, just
reissued in this country, spell out the basics of home cooking in
the city and the country.
</P>
<P>
   JANE GRIGSON'S VEGETABLE BOOK (Penguin Books, 1998; $18.95). I
wish there were an American equivalent to this A-to-Z guide to the
most common vegetables in Britain. But it is well worth deciphering
terms like ``custard marrow'' (pattypan squash) and grappling with
measurements for the wonderful prose and recipes.
</P>
<P>
   THE OLD WORLD KITCHEN by Elisabeth Luard (Bantam, 1986; out of
print). The best at describing ``the cuisine of the necessary'' in
European peasant life. Filled with hard-to-find gems like socca and
duck with cucumbers.
</P>
<P>
   SIMPLE FRENCH FOOD by Richard Olney (Macmillan, 1974; $15.95). A
favorite of old-school cooks; very French and not always simple,
but always correct and valuable.
</P>
<P>
   THE THOUSAND RECIPE CHINESE COOKBOOK by Gloria Bley Miller
(Simon &AMP; Schuster, 1984; $21). Almost 35 years old, but still the
best guide to Chinese cooking for those with little or no
experience.
</P>
<P>
   UNCOMMON FRUITS AND VEGETABLES: A COMMONSENSE GUIDE by Elizabeth
Schneider (Morrow, 1986; $28). This is newly back in print, and
hallelujah. It covers dozens of exotics, like gooseberry, cherimoya
and yuca, as well as some more common fruits and veggies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
