<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Wednesday, Oct. 13, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(lh) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the temperature soared past 90 degrees in portions
of the central Plains as breezes from the southwest directed
unseasonably hot air into the region. On Wednesday, brisk winds
from the north behind a departing cold front will import much
colder air from Canada southward into the area. Very chilly air
will also pour into the upper Midwest and northeastern Plains with
afternoon readings holding in the 40s in many locations.
</P>
<P>
   Showers and thunderstorms will stretch from the central Gulf
Coast to the Carolinas Wednesday as moist air from the Atlantic
Ocean and Gulf of Mexico intercepts a stationary front draped
across the region. South of the front, partial sunshine and humid
conditions will persist in Florida with afternoon readings near 90
degrees. Isolated thunderstorms are also possible.
</P>
<P>
   Dry weather will cover the Northeast and northern Middle
Atlantic states as high pressure slides off the coast. The day will
begin with ample sunshine, though clouds and breezes from the
southwest will increase during the afternoon ahead of an
approaching cold front. As the front undercuts and lifts
increasingly humid air ahead of it, a broken line of showers and
spotty thunderstorms will sweep east through the Great Lakes. Any
showers that form will be brief.
</P>
<P>
   A moist flow of air from the Pacific Ocean will spark scattered
showers across northern Washington and the Bitterroot mountains.
The remainder of the West will be dry with considerable sunshine.
California will stay quite hot as afternoon readings exceed 100
degrees across the deserts.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Forecasting Woes
</P>
<P>
   Weather balloons and commercial aircraft recorded winds as high
as 140 miles per hour at altitudes near 30,000 feet over central
Canada and the upper Midwest Tuesday morning. These jet stream
winds blew almost directly from west to east. Such fast, ``zonal''
winds are the basis for the forecasting rhyme ``Fast flow,
weatherman's woe.'' The woe comes from the difficulty in timing the
arrival and departure of precipitation associated with streaking
disturbances because the timing by computer guidance is often too
slow. Fast-moving disturbances will race over the northern tier
states Wednesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
