<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-12 17:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4520 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-TWAIN-VS-MCGWIRE-NYTR     10-12 0722
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TWAIN-VS-MCGWIRE-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAC SWINGS WEAK LITERARY BAT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mo.)   (bl)  
 By LOWELL COHN   
 The Press Democrat, Santa Rosa, Calif.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Roll over, Mark Twain, because Mark McGwire is on the scene.
</P>
<P>
   Let me explain. I was in St. Louis over the weekend to cover the
49ers-Rams game. I arrived late Saturday afternoon, rented a car
and started driving to my hotel. Right away, I ran into trouble.
</P>
<P>
   According to the map, I was supposed to be following the Mark
Twain Expressway toward downtown. But the road signs didn't say
anything about Mark Twain. The signs said Mark McGwire Expressway.
This was puzzling to an out-of-towner.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, I realized the freeway name had been changed from
Twain to McGwire. The change took place, I later learned, last
spring when Missouri Gov. Mel Carnahan encouraged the Legislature
to dump Twain for McGwire. As I made my way downtown, I wondered
how I felt about the guy who wrote ``Tom Sawyer'' getting the
heave-ho for the guy who hit 70 dingers.
</P>
<P>
   In a way, it was a frivolous question. I mean, it was only a
stretch of highway, for heaven's sake _ not a museum or a monument.
And it was an ugly piece of asphalt at that. Still, questions of
value were at issue, questions we're asking as the millennium draws
to a close and we take stock of ourselves as a nation: What really
matters to us? And who are our heroes?
</P>
<P>
   Don't get me wrong. I love sports and have made my living
writing about them for more than 20 years. I believe sports are
important to America. I also think McGwire is a good man. I've
known him since he came up with the A's in 1986, and he was always
polite and civilized, even when he was frustrated by injuries.
</P>
<P>
   But Missouri was wrong to honor McGwire where it formerly
honored Twain. McGwire is a regular guy who did an extraordinary
thing. He smacked a bunch of home runs. Good for him.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Twain is a national treasure. He is our Shakespeare, and
that is not something to be taken lightly or to be compared with a
ballplayer. He wrote ``Huckleberry Finn,'' the best novel in our
entire literature, a humane, clever, touching book, written in the
dialect of ordinary people.
</P>
<P>
   And of course, Twain invented Huck, the most important character
in American fiction. Excuse me a moment for sounding literary, but
because Twain lived, we talk and write and think the way we do.
Without him, there might not have been a writer like Ernest
Hemingway or a character like Holden Caulfield.
</P>
<P>
   OK, enough of that. To use a few sports terms, we are talking
superstar here, we are talking all-time great, we are talking Hall
of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   Most of all, we're talking someone whose impact has endured from
generation to generation _ Twain was born in 1835, McGwire in 1963.
Some day, a better home-run hitter will come along and break
McGwire's records, and then he'll become a distant memory or an
asterisk in the record book. Twain never will be distant or an
asterisk, and he'll always be as modern as this minute.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not the only one who feels that way. Brian Bartow, who's in
charge of public relations for the Cardinals, told me McGwire was
embarrassed by the whole freeway thing and considered it ``corny.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Mark wasn't too excited about it,'' Bartow said. ``Just
because he hit 70 home runs, why put his name there? He thought the
governor should have been worrying about other things.''
</P>
<P>
   All of which shows McGwire is no Pudd'nhead.
</P>
<P>
   You may be surprised by a letter that ran in Sunday's St. Louis
Post-Dispatch. Under the headline ``Time to Trade McGwire,'' Ryan
Corley of Washington, Mo., wrote: ``I know the great achievements
of Mark McGwire, but what about the team's success? It seems no one
cares if we win or lose as long as McGwire hits a homer. Well, my
opinion is to trade McGwire.''
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, not everyone in Missouri is wild about Big Mac. So
here's what I want to know. If the Cardinals ever trade him, what
happens to the expressway? Maybe Carnahan should change its name to
the Kurt Warner Freeway. Mark Twain may be a little above the
governor's head.
</P>
<P>
   (Lowell Cohn writes for The Press Democrat, Santa Rosa, Calif.,
which is a member of The New York Times Regional Newspaper Group.
This article was distributed by The New York Times News Service.) &QR; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-12-99 1749EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
