<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-12 17:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4522 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-PHOTOGRAPHY-TV-REVIEW     10-12 0888
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PHOTOGRAPHY-TV-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM A BROWNIE BOX SNAPSHOT TO AN IMPRINT ON THE AMERICAN
CONSCIOUSNESS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Okla.)  (Editors.: Production notes are at end of review. Time and channel
are for New York area. Check local listings.) 
(DW) 
 By CARYN JAMES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In 1900, conveniently on schedule for this centennial survey, a
revolution in photography took place: the small Brownie box camera
went on sale for $1, affordable enough for everyone to start taking
snapshots. ``American Photography: A Century of Images'' juxtaposes
that crucial fact with videotape taken this year. In a church hall
in Oklahoma City, people who have survived a tornado sift through
hundreds of photographs recovered from the storm and laid out on
long tables. They are searching for those irreplaceable objects now
taken for granted as part of every family's history.
</P>
<P>
   As it traces the role of photography in American life, the
program gives a vivid sense of how frozen images have helped shape
what the country thinks about issues from child labor to racism,
from Lewis Hine's pictures of small children at work in mills to
Gordon Parks' heart-wrenching 1940s image of a smiling black girl
hugging a life-size white doll.
</P>
<P>
   But this wide-ranging program is also intellectually glib and
works better as a sleek visual survey (American Photography 101)
than as thoughtful analysis. It is so intent on demonstrating the
centrality of the still image that it wears blinders to the equally
important role of moving images. Willfully playing down movies and
television, ``American Photography'' comes to seem facile rather
than convincing.
</P>
<P>
   The three-hour program (a lot to take in one gulp) is organized
chronologically and divided into many small sections, creating a
swift but jittery tone. The documentary makes room for Alfred
Steiglitz's shimmering images that turned photography into art but
is less interested in esthetics than in social change.
</P>
<P>
   That approach works best, and ``American Photography'' becomes
most gripping, when it examines the context that produced some
famous photographs. Rayna Green, a curator at the Smithsonian
Institution and one of the many articulate on-screen experts,
explains how Edward Curtis created his iconic images of American
Indians during the century's early decades. He dragged around a
trunk of costumes and props, sometimes replacing an Indian's
everyday suit with beads and a feathered headdress.
</P>
<P>
   During World War I no pictures of dead or maimed bodies could be
published in newspapers or magazines, with censorship supporting
the war. Those grisly images of soldiers with parts of their faces
shot off were finally printed in the 1930s as propaganda against
American entry into the next World War.
</P>
<P>
   As it zooms through the century, the program acknowledges how
taking a photograph makes an event seem real. The assumption that
the camera doesn't lie was fiercely exploited by advertising. Among
the most amusing photographs here are those of Babe Ruth in ads for
underwear, breakfast cereal, even anchovy paste.
</P>
<P>
   There is so much thought and style scattered through ``American
Photography'' that it is a shame the program is self-defeating in
its boosterism about its subject. Showing the well-known
photographs of destitute farmers taken for the Farm Security
Administration by Dorothea Lange, Walker Evans and others, the
narrator says, ``Today when we think of the Depression, we see
these faces.'' Well, some people do. Others see panhandlers on Wall
Street, among many possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   Such overstatement is typical. Even granting that the program
has chosen to focus on still photography, the argument about the
primacy of the frozen image has to be made rather than blithely
asserted. Yet there is no mention here of the newsreels shown in
movie theaters, a crucial instrument in shaping American thought
from the Depression on.
</P>
<P>
   It is true, as the program says, that certain searing images
have gained their power through repeated viewings: the 3-year-old
John F. Kennedy Jr. saluting at his father's funeral, and a
napalmed Vietnamese girl running naked toward the camera, howling
in pain. But the program ignores the fact that most people first
saw the Kennedy salute on live television. It is content to let a
former editor from The Associated Press say that still pictures
``had a much greater impact'' on American thought about the war in
Vietnam than television did, without beginning to define the
differences.
</P>
<P>
   Harris Yulin, an otherwise talented actor, reads the narration
in a stereotypical PBS drone. At least its many quick glimpses at
subjects makes the uneven ``American Photography'' easy to dip in
and out of. You can stay put for the compelling sections on war
photography and take a break during the talk with Stewart Brand,
the wacky creator of The Whole Earth Catalog, the best evidence
that a smaller range and greater depth might have helped here.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `AMERICAN PHOTOGRAPHY: A Century of Images'
</P>
<P>
   8 p.m. ET Wednesday on PBS
</P>
<P>
   John Schott, executive producer; Ellen Hovde and Muffie Meyer,
producer/directors; Ronald H. Blumer, writer; Blumer and Sharon
Sachs, co-producers. A production of KTCA/Twin Cities Public
Television in association with Middlemarch Films.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-12-99 1750EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991012.0219 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-12 17:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4529 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-CREMASTER-FILM-REVIEW     10-12 0872
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CREMASTER-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`CREMASTER 2': AN EPIC AVANT-GARDE WESTERN
</HEADLINE>
   (lh) 
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   With ``Cremaster 2,'' the fourth installment of his projected
cycle of five experimental films, Matthew Barney proves beyond a
doubt that he is not a cinematic dabbler tossing around ideas that
might just as readily be elaborated in performance art or in a
video installation. Larger in scale, darker in tone, and much more
lavishly produced than the previous installments, ``Cremaster 2,''
is an epic avant-garde western built around classic themes but
laced with an intricate (and often whimsical) symbolic framework.
</P>
<P>
   You could drive yourself crazy chasing down the symbolic clues
that the film drops and that lend ``Cremaster 2'' its own integral
form while also connecting it to the cycle's broader themes. But to
obsess too much about the internal mechanics of a work whose
connections seem intuitive (and often very loose) would be to
overlook its purely cinematic power. Visually and emotionally,
``Cremaster 2'' unfolds as a disturbing, enigmatic dream that has
its own forceful rhythms and moods and a haunting musical
soundtrack that ranges from fragments of folk songs (sung by Patty
Griffin) to the Mormon Tabernacle Choir.
</P>
<P>
   As the camera sweeps across the Columbia Ice Field in Alberta,
Canada, or contemplates the dazzlingly white Bonneville Salt Flats
in Utah, ``Cremaster 2'' conveys a surreal desolation and grandeur
that the music underscores. These wide-open spaces are filmed with
a breathtaking beauty and with a compelling feel for the emotional
weight that the sky and landscape exert on individuals. And as the
film depicts various rituals enacted in these open spaces, it
creates a palpable tension between a sense of freedom and one of
emptiness and constriction.
</P>
<P>
   The rites Barney has devised include synchronized equestrian
maneuvers executed by American cowboys and the Canadian mounted
police, the taming of a Brahma bull, and an imaginary flashback to
the 1893 Columbia International Exposition in Chicago where the
legendary escape artist Harry Houdini appeared. In the
hallucinatory world of ``Cremaster 2'' the exposition has been
relocated to the Columbia Ice Field, and Houdini impersonated by
Norman Mailer. A good part of the film incorporates elements from
Mailer's masterpiece ``The Executioner's Song,'' with Barney
portraying its protagonist, Gary Gilmore, who committed two murders
in July 1976 while on parole and was sentenced to death by a Utah
firing squad in 1977.
</P>
<P>
   Utah being the Beehive State, the film includes scenes of
swarming bees along with shots of interiors that have a
honeycomblike design. Near the end of the film an ominous,
wasp-waisted ``queen bee'' (a hallucinatory version of Gilmore's
paternal grandmother), dressed in black Victorian finery,
approaches Houdini at the exposition. The woman is also a variation
on the Hungarian opera diva memorably portrayed by Ursula Andress
in ``Cremaster 5.''
</P>
<P>
   As for bees, nature's pollinators also connect to the cycle's
broader interest in fertility and sexual transfiguration. In
earlier installments Barney appears in various satyr guises. A
running theme of the cycle, exemplified by a race-car sequence on
the Isle of Man and gymnastic feats performed by Barney, is the
male compulsion to master difficult physical challenges. Since
``cremaster'' is the name of the muscle that raises or lowers a
man's testicles in response to temperature, the whole cycle could
be seen as a meditation on the driving forces of masculinity.
</P>
<P>
   But it is Gilmore's story and his family history, evoked
symbolically, that give ``Cremaster 2'' a solidity and emotional
depth that are missing in the earlier, more playful installments.
One especially gripping scene portrays the shooting of an auto
mechanic in a deserted gas station. The murder is viewed as the
climax of an elaborate macho ritual of car fetishism _ the checking
of oil and tires, inspection under the body _ in a surreal space
dominated by automotive advertisements.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the completed ``Cremaster'' series coheres as a kind of
cinematic ``Ring'' cycle remains to be seen. ``Cremaster 2'' is so
much deeper and more resonant than the other installments that
right now it's hard to see how they can work together visually.
(Theoretically, ``Cremaster 2'' is the second film in the cycle,
whose parts have been filmed out of order; 4, 1, and 5 preceded.)
Much will depend on the final installment, ``Cremaster 3,'' whose
intended location is the Chrysler Building and whose premiere is to
be at the Solomon R. Guggenheim Museum sometime in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `CREMASTER 2'
</P>
<P>
   Written and directed by Matthew Barney; director of photography,
Peter Strietmann; music by Jonathan Bepler; production designer,
Matthew D. Ryle; produced by Barbara Gladstone and Barney; released
by Glacier Field.
</P>
<P>
   With: Norman Mailer (Harry Houdini), Matthew Barney (Gary
Gilmore), Anonymous (Baby Fay La Foe), Lauren Pine (Bessie
Gilmore), Scott Ewalt (Frank Gilmore), Patty Griffin (Nicole Baker)
and Michael Thomson (Max Jensen).
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 79 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   This film is not rated.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-12-99 1752EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991012.0220 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-12 17:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4535 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a BC-TEXASATLARGE-CHAPMAN-     10-12 0601
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXASATLARGE-CHAPMAN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROPE A CHICKEN, WIN A PRIZE AT WATT MATTHEWS COWBOY DAYS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ART CHAPMAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There was nothing that legendary rancher Watt Matthews admired
more than a good cowhand _ someone with a strong back, a willing
hand and dead solid accuracy with a
</P>
<P>
   He would love this year's Watt Matthews Cowboy Days in Albany in
Central Texas. It will feature the first ``Texas National Chicken
Roping,'' an event designed to test the quickness and tenacity of
both roper and poultry.
</P>
<P>
   Matthews died in 1997, and the folks in Albany _ near his
beloved Lambshead Ranch in Shackelford County _ quickly established
a celebration in his honor. This year's event takes place Saturday
and Sunday and features _ along with the chicken roping _ a Western
photography symposium, a cowboy breakfast on the courthouse lawn, a
melodrama inside the courthouse and a Don Edwards concert.
</P>
<P>
   There will also be a ranch rodeo, chuckwagon dinner and western
swing dance.
</P>
<P>
   But the chicken roping is clearly the premier event.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a new event, and we're pleased to present to the state of
Texas the first National Chicken Roping,'' said Bob Echols, event
chairman. ``There will be three divisions: junior, women's and
men's.''
</P>
<P>
   The chicken roping is a team event. A header and a heeler go to
work, on foot, as soon as the Dominique chicken is turned loose in
a 20-foot by 30-foot pen.
</P>
<P>
   The ropers have 90 seconds to toss a rope of soft material
around the chicken's neck, and then another around its legs.
</P>
<P>
   The ropes, 10-feet-long, were specially made for the event by
Classic Rope Co. in Granbury.
</P>
<P>
   ``They might start making them commercially,'' Echols said.
``This thing could catch on.''
</P>
<P>
   For those who feel sorry for the chickens, Echols promises that
judges will ensure there is no chicken abuse, no yanking or
jerking. No plucking. In fact, a lot of people in Albany doubt that
many chickens will be caught.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're a little smaller target than a calf and a little
quicker,'' said Lea Clayton with the Albany Chamber of Commerce.
``They have a really fast reaction time.''
</P>
<P>
   Ropers will pay $5 a team for a chance at the chickens. The
winners will get a few caps and roping gear as trophies.
</P>
<P>
   The chickens, the entire flock of 21, will be auctioned off
after the roping.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think we're going to have a good turnout,'' Echols said.
</P>
<P>
   Also part of the Watt Matthews Cowboy Days is the annual Spanish
Gourd Award, given to individuals who exemplify Matthews' love of
the land and livestock.
</P>
<P>
   This year's recipient is former Gov. Dolph Briscoe Jr.
</P>
<P>
   Briscoe served in the Legislature from 1949 to 1957. He was
governor from 1973 to 1979.
</P>
<P>
   Briscoe's primary contributions to the ranching industry were
co-sponsorship and passage of the Farm-To-Market Road Program in
1949 and leadership in the screwworm eradication program in the
early 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   The Farm-To-Market Road Program helped bring rural Texas ``out
of the mud,'' Briscoe has often said. The screwworm eradication
program saved ranchers millions of dollars in livestock losses.
Cattlemen viewed the program as the most significant health advance
in the Texas livestock industry.
</P>
<P>
   For more information on the Watt Matthews Cowboy Days, contact
the Albany Chamber of Commerce at (915) 762-2525.
</P>
<P>
   (Art Chapman writes a weekly column on things Texan. You can
call him at (817) 390-7422, or e-mail: artc(at)star-telegram.com.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
