   BRADLEY-CALIF _LOS ANGELES _ With 435 Democratic delegates,
California is the top prize in the Democratic nomination
sweepstakes between former New Jersey senator Bill Bradley and Vice
President Gore. But no where is the deck stacked more heavily
against Bradley than in California. The entire state Democratic
Party, from Gov. Gray Davis on down, is allied with Gore.
Disenchantment with Gore because of President Clinton's troubles,
Bradley's primary draw in other parts of the country, isn't an
issue in California, where Gore has visited 60 times since 1992 and
dozens more as a member of Congress. Bradley is hoping to attract
independents and support from California's exploding high-tech
crowd, but these voters will do him no good in California's open
primary, where only registered Democrats count toward delegate
selection. (Foskett, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
