<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-12 17:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4541 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-BEEFCAKE-FILM-REVIEW-     10-12 0762
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEEFCAKE-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BEEFCAKE:' TAN AND PUMPED UP, LIVING CAMPILY EVER AFTER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Production notes appear at end of review.) 
(DW) 
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Of the many pop ditties that float like wisps of pink ice cream
through ``Beefcake,'' Thom Fitzgerald's campy strawberry milkshake
of a film saluting the dream world of '50s male physique
photography, none captures that ethos more perfectly than ``Mr.
Sandman.'' In this giddy cinematic swirl of vintage photos and film
clips of young men flexing their muscles, interspersed with
fictional, satirically shaded vignettes set in 1950s Los Angeles,
the Chordettes' cooing plea to ``make him the cutest that I've ever
seen'' distills the strained faux-naif attitudes behind those
pictures.
</P>
<P>
   Back in that fabulous decade, Calvin Klein was just a wee lad,
Mark Wahlberg a twinkle in his father's eye and the display of the
male body as a pinup limited largely to ads featuring a
bare-chested Charles Atlas promising to turn 97-pound weaklings
into swaggering he-men through a principle called ``dynamic
tension.'' But as Fitzgerald's film amusingly documents, a
submerged, dissembling homoerotic culture of male pinup literature
was also in its infancy. Years before gay men had even adopted the
term ``gay,'' admirers of the pumped and chiseled male body were
discreetly snapping up copies of Physique Pictorial, a magazine
produced in Los Angeles by Bob Mizer.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the young men Mizer photographed were amateurs
``discovered'' in random locations like bus stations. Mizer also
established the Athletic Model Guild, a photo agency that amassed
hundreds of thousands of physique photos. Some of his models lived
with him and his mother, who assisted her son and who designed the
young men's ``posing pouches.'' To avoid prosecution for obscenity,
Mizer promoted his models as clean-cut embodiments of good health
and physical fitness.
</P>
<P>
   What Fitzgerald has created in ``Beefcake'' is a heady,
impressionistic mixture of biography, fantasy and social history in
which it isn't always clear which is which. One strand of the movie
follows the starry-eyed Neil O'Hara (Josh Peace plays Neil, who is
campily named after a character in ``Valley of the Dolls''), who
travels from Nova Scotia to Los Angeles and ends up living with
Mizer (Daniel MacIvor) and other young men in a group situation
that suggests a low-rent version of Hugh Hefner and his bunnies. In
these scenes the movie delights in parodying vintage Southern
California hipsterese with its pretentious ``Daddy-o's,'' ``hep
cats'' and other quaint terms.
</P>
<P>
   We also meet several of Mizer's real-life former physique models
who are now in their 50s and 60s, as well as the fitness guru Jack
LaLanne. Even today these men strain to uphold a 50s-style
all-American image. The former Andy Warhol ``superstar'' Joe
D'Allesandro also appears as himself today and as a teen-ager in an
eight-millimeter nude film made by Mizer.
</P>
<P>
   The movie's biggest problem is that MacIvor's portrayal of Mizer
as a repressed, photography-obsessed milquetoast who displays no
apparent sexual interest in his models doesn't square with scenes
late in the movie that recreate Mizer's actual trial for operating
a prostitution ring using those models. The production notes for
``Beefcake'' say the trial transcript used in the film was
discovered as the movie was nearing completion and incorporated
almost as an afterthought. This results in a glaring discrepancy
between the giddy, campy celebration that ``Beefcake'' begins as
and the darker material unearthed late in its production.
</P>
<P>
   Despite this contradiction, ``Beefcake,'' which opens Wednesday
at the Film Forum, offers a fascinating double-edged portrait of
1950s Los Angeles. In the shadows of this wholesome sun-drenched
pre-Beach Boys world of giddy optimism and cheer _ a strawberry
milkshake world, if ever there was one _ worms were turning.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `BEEFCAKE'
</P>
<P>
   Written and directed by Thom Fitzgerald; director of
photography, Thomas M. Harting; edited by Susan Shanks and Michael
Weir; music by John Roby; production designer, D'Arcy Poultney;
produced by Shandi Mitchell and Fitzgerald; released by Strand
Films. At the Film Forum in Manhattan. Running time: 93 minutes.
This film is not rated.
</P>
<P>
   With: Daviel MacIvor (Bob Mizer), Josh Peace (Neil O'Hara) and
Carroll Godsman (zer), with Jack LaLanne, Russ Warner, Dave
Martin, Jim Lassiter, Joe Leitel, Joe D'Allesandro and Valentine
Hooven (themselves).
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-12-99 1758EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991012.0225 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-12 18:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4542 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-STICKLEY-STREISAND-2T     10-12 0828
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STICKLEY-STREISAND-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TUG-OF-WAR   ON FURNITURE THAT BARBRA STREISAND IS SELLING AT
CHRISTIE'S  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla., Vt. Calif., N.J.)   By WILLIAM L. HAMILTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The log cabin that Gustav Stickley, America's pre-eminent
proponent of the Arts and Crafts style and one of its finest
cabinetmakers, built for his family in 1911 at Craftsman Farm in
Parsippany, N.J., was meant to embody his vision of the power of
the Arts and Crafts ideal, down to the last piece of plain oak
furniture that spoke of the virtue of the simple life. As
Stickley's own magazine, The Craftsman, described it that year it
was to be ``a rudimentary sheltering of domestic life, a place of
safety where love and friendship could be shut in and foe and
danger shut out.''
</P>
<P>
   Things have not been simple, or safe, for a long time. In 1987
developers made an unsuccessful stab at the last 26 acres of the
farm, which originally had 653 acres. The town bought the property
in a grass-roots move to preserve it.
</P>
<P>
   It is now a National Historic Landmark and a museum operated by
the Craftsman Farm Foundation, a nonprofit organization, since
1989. It has become an unlikely battleground between the Arts and
Crafts community and Barbra Streisand.
</P>
<P>
   The foundation has been trying to return Stickley's furnishings
to the house for 10 years, including a pair of glass-fronted
cabinets Stickley designed specifically for the corners of his
dining room.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Streisand now owns the cabinets, which she intends to sell
as part of her collection of American Arts and Crafts furniture at
Christie's New York on Nov. 29. The 106 lots are estimated to bring
a total of $2 million to $3 million. She purchased the cabinets at
Christie's in 1989 for $68,200.
</P>
<P>
   The foundation has made repeated appeals to Ms. Streisand for a
donation of the cabinets or terms for a private sale since then,
said Tommy McPherson, the foundation's executive director. But Ms.
Streisand's publicist, Dick Guttman, denied that that she or her
adviser on Arts and Crafts had ever been approached by the
foundation.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not one person I've talked to who can sympathize with
her as to why she hasn't donated the cabinets or given the farm the
chance to raise the money and buy them from her,'' said Tim
Gleason, a New York dealer who said he had helped the foundation
with requests to Ms. Streisand's production company, Barwood Films
Ltd.
</P>
<P>
   The foundation, he said, has been ``snubbed by one of the
wealthier collectors'' in the Arts and Crafts community.
</P>
<P>
   Guttman insisted on Friday that ``this is the very first she's
heard of it.'' He added, ``This has never been presented to her.''
</P>
<P>
   McPherson responded that the foundation had been approaching Ms.
Streisand through her representatives since she bought the cabinets
10 years ago and had received consistent negative responses.
</P>
<P>
   McPherson said that even requests for measurements, which with
the farm hoped to at least reproduce the cabinets for its dining
room in lieu of the originals, were ignored.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know who these people thought they were talking to,''
Guttman said on Monday, replying to McPherson's assertion, ``but it
wasn't an authority. The one person through whom all of this would
funnel has no recollection of any of this.'' He was speaking of Ms.
Streisand's Arts and Crafts adviser.
</P>
<P>
   Now that the cabinets are available publicly, estimated by
Christie's at $40,000 to $60,000 apiece, a price experts said
seemed unrealistically low given the importance of their provenance
_ from the farm, not the star.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those pieces should go back to the farm,'' said David Rudd, a
dealer in Syracuse. Rudd once owned Stickley's house there. ``They
started at the farm,'' he said. ``That collection is important
historically, for this period.''
</P>
<P>
   Others think it is nobody's business but Ms. Streisand's.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've sold things to Barbra, and she's always been decent to
deal with,'' said David Rago, an Arts and Crafts dealer who is also
on the Craftsman Farm Foundation's board of advisers, and was
married at the farm. ``Naturally I would have liked to see the
cabinets donated, but if the farm is surprised they weren't, it was
out of ignorance. She's free to do what she wants with her pieces.
It's very easy to spend someone else's money.''
</P>
<P>
   In reaction to the sale, the foundation began a fund-raising
appeal, hoping to raise at least $75,000 to bring the cabinets
back.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would have been delighted to buy them outright; it's a bit
of a tragedy to have to bid for them in an open market,'' McPherson
said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Streisand's collection, which was created largely in the
1980s, consists of furniture, lamps, pottery, metalwork and
textiles by artists including the potter William Grueby, the
coppersmith Dirk van Erp and Frank Lloyd Wright. It formed the
contents of Ms. Streisand's Beverly Hills house, which was sold
this year.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Several items from her collection, including the cabinets, were
offered for sale to other, more prestigious institutions recently,
including the Metropolitan Museum of Art, said one dealer with
knowledge of the offer, before the collection was consigned to
Christie's.
</P>
<P>
   Given the layers of advisers who can hermetically seal a
celebrity from public contact, the foundation had been concerned
that its requests were not getting through to the star.
</P>
<P>
   But Gleason said that Nancy McClelland, international head of
20th-century decorative arts at Christie's, who is working with Ms.
Streisand on the sale, had had talks with her about the disposition
of the cabinets and their possible donation or sale to the farm.
Gleason said he had spoken with Ms. McClelland about the
discussions, but Ms. McClelland denied that she had had the
conversations with Ms. Streisand.
</P>
<P>
   The Craftsman Farm Foundation has cause to be nervous about
going to auction now. After its peak in the late 1980s and a slump
in the early '90s, the Arts and Crafts market has been
exceptionally strong during the last 12 to 18 months, in part
because of the appearance of vigorous new high-end collectors like
Rudy Ciccarello, a Florida businessman who paid $275,000 for a
Stickley cupboard on Saturday at a country auction house in
Williston, Vt.
</P>
<P>
   The Craftsman Farm Foundation and the Arts and Crafts community
might wish for an 11th-hour intervention from Ms. Streisand, in
withdrawing the cabinets from the sale, but the cabinets are also
stars.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Nancy doesn't get those cabinets in the sale, it's
considerably weaker,'' Gleason said of Ms. McClelland at
Christie's. ``Those cabinets and the sideboard are her marquee.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Streisand paid a $362,000 for a Stickley sideboard in 1988,
which remains a record for a piece of Arts and Crafts furniture.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to raising money, the Craftsman Farm Foundation
hopes that publicizing its interest will dissuade its own community
from bidding against it. But at least one important collector, who
asked not to be identified, said he thought the farm should be
prepared to pay the market's price and ``not be a prima donna.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite their provenance, he agreed with several dealers that
the cabinets' condition and esthetic forms were unexceptional and
that an institution's expectation of collectors to ``lay hands
off'' at an auction was setting a bad precedent.
</P>
<P>
   Despite what Guttman described as an ``disturbing,
unprofessional'' telephone message from the farm threatening
negative publicity, McPherson expressed concern about any
impression that the foundation was playing the bully.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're genuinely pleased to have a chance to bid on them,'' he
said of the cabinets. ``Obviously there could have been a lot of
other scenarios, but Barbra Streisand is making a decision about
her money, and we don't intend to be in the crying game about it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
