<HEADLINE>
RICKY MARTIN REHEARSING IN THE LAKELAND CENTER 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By BILL DEAN   
 The Ledger, Lakeland, Fla. 
  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAKELAND, Fla. _ Latin superstar Ricky Martin has been ``Livin'
La Vida Loca'' for months in the United States _ but will he do so
in Lakeland?
</P>
<P>
   The singer has booked The Lakeland Center's arena for a week's
worth of rehearsals before starting a national tour at the Miami
Arena on Oct. 20.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, tour personnel unloaded some of an expected 19 to 20
tractor-trailers at the Lakeland Center's arena for the private
rehearsals, which local officials described as technical rehearsals
to fine-tune sound and lighting.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've been rehearsing this show in Los Angeles at the Forum
since late September,'' said Allen Johnson, executive director of
The Lakeland Center.
</P>
<P>
   Martin joins a growing list of performers who have rehearsed at
The Lakeland Center, including Sheryl Crow in March, Phil Collins
in 1997 and U2 in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   AmeriSuites, the on-site hotel at The Lakeland Center, received
hundreds of phone calls and many visits from people wanting to know
if the singer was staying there, said Joanie Thresher, director of
sales and marketing at AmeriSuites.
</P>
<P>
   The reason? Martin is a bona fide pop-music phenomenon, a
27-year-old singer whose current album, ``Ricky Martin,'' has sold
more than 5 million copies in five months.
</P>
<P>
   Born in Puerto Rico and beginning his career in the teen-aged
group Menudo, Martin also is credited with spearheading Latin pop
music interest in the United States, where Latin acts such as
Jennifer Lopez and Mana also sell millions of albums.
</P>
<P>
   While AmeriSuites has booked a lot of rooms for Martin's road
crew through Sunday, the singer himself is not staying there,
Thresher said. Johnson of The Lakeland Center said he had no idea
where Martin was staying.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand he's coming in and out of town,'' Johnson said.
``I heard he has media commitments that will mean he's in and
out.''
</P>
<P>
   The closest Martin's tour will play to Lakeland is a sold-out
date at Tampa's Ice Palace on Oct. 22 _ one of only 16 North
American cities on the tour.
</P>
<P>
   (The Ledger in Lakeland, Fla. &UR; ,  &LR; is part of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
