<SLUG> BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JEERS FOR NO CHEERS - SUNDAY  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
(ATTN: Ohio)  By DAVID GRIMES   
 Sarasota (Fla.) Herald-Tribune   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Although I'm well aware that sports fans can go ``overboard'' in
support of their teams, up to and including killing each other, I
think the Northern Ohio Girls Soccer League has taken the
``sportsmanship'' thing a little too far.
</P>
<P>
   According to an Associated Press story, league president Al
Soper declared a recent Sunday ``Silent Sunday,'' a day when all
coaches and parents were forbidden from cheering.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want kids to be able to learn and to be able to think and
play without constant yelling,'' Soper said. After refereeing a
boys soccer tournament earlier this year, Soper said he ``needed
earplugs.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The crowd was so loud, kids couldn't hear the whistle, talk to
each other, develop combinations or anything,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The conventional wisdom, of course, is that parents have lost
(assuming they ever had it to begin with) perspective of what youth
sports are all about. We've all read the ugly stories of
hyper-stimulated dads (and the occasional mom) assaulting his kid's
coach or the umpire or even a player on the other team.
</P>
<P>
   I think we can all agree that abusive behavior has no place in
youth sports.
</P>
<P>
   But cheering?
</P>
<P>
   I have no experience with youth-soccer moms and dads, but I do
know a thing or two about Little League parents, and I rather
expect the two groups have much in common.
</P>
<P>
   One thing I've learned is: The younger the kids, the crazier the
parents.
</P>
<P>
   It's the parents of the 5-, 6- and 7-year-olds who should be
given sedatives before being allowing into the bleachers.
</P>
<P>
   Out on the field, you've got a bunch of 60-pound kids wearing
uniforms so big that a moderate breeze would cause them to take
flight. Their gloves, some of them costing more than $100, are the
size of manhole covers and are almost too heavy for some of the
smaller players to lift.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, the kids protect these expensive gloves by keeping
them out of contact with the ball as much as possible. At this
stage, it is not uncommon for a ball batted say, 6 inches, to
result in a home run. Indeed, if the rules were not so restrictive,
the batter could probably score several home runs on the same
6-inch hit as the fielders furiously whip the ball around to
wherever a person with a glove might not be standing.
</P>
<P>
   If you are a fan of slapstick comedy, it is great entertainment.
However, if you think your son or daughter has major-league
potential and is being held back from his (your?) dream by
incompetent coaching and a bad call at the plate in a 23-2 game,
then you tend to derive little, if any, amusement from these
proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, most (not all) of these parents drift off to other
things (apocalypse preparation, unsolved conspiracies), much to the
relief of their stressed-out kids who learned only one thing from
their Little-League experience: They never want to play organized
baseball again.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of us stick around to wince, shake our heads in
disbelief and, more than anything else, cheer. We yell lots of
stuff, too, but of course we do it in a helpful, supportive,
affirming sort of way.
</P>
<P>
   For example, if our child lets the ball dribble between his
legs, allowing the winning run to score, we yell, ``Bad hop!''
</P>
<P>
   If our child is pitching and wings the ball over the backstop
into the parking lot and through the windshield of one of our cars,
we helpfully advise that he ``bring it down a little.''
</P>
<P>
   The sun is the culprit for high, fly balls that drop at our
child's feet. The wind is responsible for the opposing player's
blast that clears the fence by 50 feet. Monday games, of course,
are impossible to win as they come too soon after the weekend and
Friday games are also sure losers because the weekend's on
everyone's mind.
</P>
<P>
   It's a long season and if we weren't allowed to cheer we'd be
left with nothing to do but hang around the concession stand,
screaming at the person running it for forgetting the hot-dog buns
and running out of cups.
</P>
<P>
   We're rather tightly wound, we Little-League parents, but we
mean well. We really do.
</P>
<P>
   (The Sarasota (Fla.) Herald-Tribune is part of the New York
Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
