<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-12 18:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4550 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-ITALY-OPERA-HOUSES-NY     10-12 1275
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ITALY-OPERA-HOUSES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LONGING FOR SPACES THAT ARE LESS GRAND AND MORE OPERA  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By BERNARD HOLLAND   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LUCCA, Italy _ One reaches up to turn the latch at 14 Via
Carmignani in the nearby hillside town of Montecarlo. It was a door
meant to be opened by men on horseback. From the street, one sees
one more among a row of private houses. But beyond this particular
door is a lobby, complete with bar and box office, and beyond it
the Teatro di Assicurati.
</P>
<P>
   Though presently not used as such, this space, ringed by a
two-tiered horseshoe of boxes, has been the opera house of
Montecarlo since 1795. Now, the orchestra pit beneath the stage is
blocked, and plush red seats have replaced the noisy wooden chairs
of the orchestra stalls. Seating capacity: 196.
</P>
<P>
   On the street, an out-of-date poster offers jazz concerts. A
poster framed on the lobby wall advertises an 1861 performance of
``Lucia di Lammermoor,'' Donizetti's memorable bel canto tragedy,
currently running at the Metropolitan Opera in New York.
</P>
<P>
   There is a distance between the two events, and not just in
years or geography. Montecarlo's ``Lucia'' played to a house whose
orchestra section seated 50 patrons. Met performances, even those
not sold out, still accommodate at least 3,500 more patrons. The
music and the voice parts were probably similar, made more so by
the Met's return to a version presumably closer to the composer's
original wishes. Yet by virtue of place, these become two very
different operas.
</P>
<P>
   Montecarlo and the Met represent extremes: the too little versus
the too big. The Assicurati's cut-down orchestra certainly had a
limiting effect on Donizetti's melodrama, which, on the other hand,
threatens to disappear altogether within the vast spaces of Lincoln
Center. But there are messages coming from both sides about opera
and its intentions. They are perhaps better addressed in another
Tuscan opera house, the Teatro del Giglio here in the city of
Lucca.
</P>
<P>
   The Giglio has been a theater since the late 17th century but
took its current form at the urging of Napoleon's sister, Elisa
Baciocchi, named by her conquering brother as ruler of the city,
and then by her successor, Maria-Luisa of the Parma Bourbons, Queen
of Lucca. The new Giglio was inaugurated in 1819. A more recent and
egalitarian renovation (Communism, at least in its Italian form,
has been a big political force in Tuscany) removed the highest of
four tiers of boxes to create an open gallery. Once seating 600,
the theater now holds a few hundred more.
</P>
<P>
   Gilbert Duprez, who sang in the first ``Lucia'' in Naples in
1835, had stood on the stage of the Giglio four years earlier and
introduced Italy not only to Rossini's ``William Tell'' but to the
first high C sung from the chest. With this opening shot, the
light, airy, flexible tenor tone on which so much of bel canto was
based, was doomed. Opera houses were finding bigger voices like
this one. More people would be reached, bigger houses built to put
them in, more tickets sold. Without the brilliance and carrying
power that Duprez was advertising (Rossini dismissed the sound as
the death throes of a chicken), the Met would not exist.
</P>
<P>
   Today's Teatro del Giglio put on ``La Sonnambula'' last month.
When we think of Bellini's opera now, it is its connection to the
charismatic singers capable of soaring above an opera's creaking
plot and out to an audience of thousands. Lately the Amina of
choice has been Joan Sutherland or Maria Callas. They put the
grandness in grand opera.
</P>
<P>
   At the Met performance I heard, Andrea Rost and Frank Lopardo
sang Lucia and Edgardo. Both are good big-house singers, and both
spent much of the afternoon aiming their voices outward for maximum
coverage. Though indifferent in other ways, the Giglio production
offered heroines of a different kind.
</P>
<P>
   On opening night, Patrizia Ciofi was the more sophisticated
Amina: a finished singer with a voice that could command a somewhat
bigger theater than this. Paola Cigna the next evening was softer,
sweeter and technically good enough. Neither is a grand opera
voice, and I doubt that they will make the rounds of New York,
London, Chicago and the like. Yet Ms. Cigna's size was an endearing
fit for the space it was in. We have rightly thrilled to Ms.
Sutherland's elegant declamation and Ms. Callas' fire, but here was
opera as conversation.
</P>
<P>
   The Giglio, when correctly used, creates intimate social
intercourse. Alone on the stage of this theater, one can speak in a
normal voice with people at the very top of the gallery. One of the
troubling things about these ``Sonnambula'' performances was how
little most performers took account of the space they were
occupying. In two casts on successive evenings, one Elvino and both
Lisas shouted. The rest, with their varying degrees of vocal
subtlety, understood a little better that they did not have to.
</P>
<P>
   One had the sinking feeling that Italy, with perhaps more
intimate opera spaces per square mile than any country in the
world, may be forgetting how to use them. Some of these singers
would have sung a lot louder had they been able to.
</P>
<P>
   Young Italians, or singers from anywhere, might look to another
tiny opera house on another nearby hilltop town in Tuscany: Barga.
With a history roughly parallel to Montecarlo's but brought to life
by the English family of Peter Hunt, Barga's Teatro dei Differenti,
seating under 300, has been a modern working theater for over 30
years. A renovation lasting an unlikely 16 years (Barga's Mayor,
throwing up his hands and rolling his eyes: ``Italy is always
Italy.'') ended last year, and now the theater gleams, at least
inside. The new facade, conforming to government guidelines, is
sadly ugly and out of place.
</P>
<P>
   There is the same inviting smallness, and acoustics perhaps
better than the Assicurati's. The early seasons of the Festival
Opera Barga were remarkable. Attracting foreign students and young
professionals, offering the coaching and direction of people like
the late Italo Tajo and Lorenzo Malfatti, now head of Lucca's
summer academy for Americans, the Opera Theater of Lucca, and
bringing in conductors like the young Sir John Eliot Gardiner, the
Differenti has staged Stravinsky's ``Rake's Progress,'' Handel's
``Agrippina,'' Milhaud's ``Pauvre Matelot,'' Schoenberg's ``P
Lunaire'' and a raft of out-of-the-way pieces by Cimarosa, Cavalli,
Satie, Falla and Zandonai.
</P>
<P>
   Both theaters were originally built and owned by consortiums of
important families in the two towns. Both were for periods of time
closed as potential hotbeds of sedition. Malfatti remembers having
to telephone each family before Barga performances to see if their
boxes were available for ticket buyers. The theaters now belong to
the local governments, Montecarlo's having just barely been saved
from demolition for a proposed car park.
</P>
<P>
   Big opera houses coincide roughly with architecture's tendencies
toward gigantism at the end of the last century. The Met's size
reflects its dependence on paying customers. Great opera comes out
of these spaces but often at a price. We have more or less stopped
dreaming of a Piccolo Met, but there is that chance that the New
York City Opera might find itself a small and embracing Broadway
theater and offer us alternatives. Recordings and television are
promising places for smaller voices in grand-opera repertory.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise there are the theaters of Lucca, Pisa, Mantua, Livorno
and the like. The singers, the orchestras and the productions may
be less than we are used to, but a flavor of rightness pervades
them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
