<HEADLINE>
GROCERY STORE REWARDS PLANS RAISE PRIVACY ISSUES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MATT BEER  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Melissa Hernandez, a San Francisco housewife,
would gladly trade her driver's license number, Social Security
number and information about her buying habits for bargains on
whole chicken breasts and 2 percent milk.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got nothing to hide,'' said Hernandez, loading her
late-model Honda with bags of groceries outside a Safeway here.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it saves me a few bucks, why not?'' Hernandez said of her
Safeway Club card.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Gov. Davis signed a new law that answers Hernandez's
question.
</P>
<P>
   Introduced by state Sen. Jackie Speier, a Democrat of Daly City,
Calif., the bill restricts the kinds of information grocery stores
in the state can solicit in exchange for letting customers use the
various reward or loyalty programs like Safeway's.
</P>
<P>
   In these programs, stores give customers a card that's
electronically read at the cash register. After each trip to the
store, a customer's purchases are logged to create a constantly
updating database of what consumers are buying. Customers using
these cards at the registers are rewarded with discounts on some
grocery items.
</P>
<P>
   The Food Marketing Institute, a Washington, D.C.-based trade
association, estimates that 60 percent of retail grocery stores
will offer some form of data-gathering reward program by the end of
the year.
</P>
<P>
   Speier's bill puts the first legal restraints on these popular
programs. Stores are prohibited from asking for Social Security or
driver's license numbers. Additionally, stores are prohibited from
selling or sharing the names or addresses of customers.
</P>
<P>
   These mandates, the lawmaker said, prevent stores from profiling
individual buyers, then trading that personal data with others,
including national suppliers and marketers.
</P>
<P>
   ``One's personal information is like gold,'' said Speier. ``It
gets collected and sold to all kinds of organizations. It's a major
problem if you're at all concerned about privacy.''
</P>
<P>
   Large supermarket chains say the legislation simply enforces the
privacy policies the stores have been following on a voluntary
basis.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were already in compliance,'' said Judy Decker, spokeswoman
for Lucky Stores Inc. of San Leandro, Calif., which owns and
operates 500 supermarkets in California. ``From the time we've
first offered the awards card two years ago, we had no intention of
selling the information.''
</P>
<P>
   This policy is echoed at the Pleasanton, Calif.-based Safeway
Corp. supermarket chain, which has 1,656 stores in the United
States and Canada and which has been credited with starting the
first loyalty program a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not sell any personally identifying information to
anyone _ don't plan to, and we never will do it,'' said Safeway
spokeswoman Deborah Lambert. ``That's been our policy since we
launched the program two years ago. We don't even store information
by a consumer's name,'' added Lambert. ``We store the information
by product.''
</P>
<P>
   Speier said the law is aimed at future abuses. ``We're going to
make sure these stores stay away from any abuses,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Privacy advocates applaud the legislation, but believe it
doesn't go far enough to curb potential abuses.
</P>
<P>
   Tara Lemmey, president of Electronic Frontier Foundation, a San
Francisco-based privacy advocacy group, said, ``It's good to see
some kind of legislative awareness of the importance of data
privacy.''
</P>
<P>
   But Lemmey said the bill, which prohibits the distribution of a
grocery customer's name and address, needs to encompass more
consumer information. ``A company shouldn't be able to disclose
anything without a customer's consent,'' she said. ``It shouldn't
be limited to just the names and addresses.''
</P>
<P>
   Marketers who make their livelihood by harvesting consumer data
say the law is an unnecessary intrusion into the bargains many
supermarket customers are willing to cash in on.
</P>
<P>
   ``The consumer is choosing to participate in the program,'' said
Chet Dalzell, spokesman for the Direct Marketing Association, a New
York-based industry trade group representing some 4,600 member
companies. ``As long as the stores disclose what the data is being
used for, there should be no restrictions on that arrangement.''
</P>
<P>
   That is exactly how Hernandez feels about her Safeway Club card.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as they aren't selling it to some sleazy porn outfit
for whatever, I'm OK with what they do with my information,'' she
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-12-99 1806EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
