<DOCNO> NYT19991012.0231 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-12 18:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4553 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l BC-EXOTICLIMOS-TEX     10-12 0870
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EXOTICLIMOS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S A STRETCH, BUT EXOTIC LIMO BUSINESS IS A GAS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DICK J. REAVIS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ When prom season comes next spring, the 200 or so
limousine companies in Dallas-Fort Worth will be busy _ and the
owners of two of them will be worried. Brad Goodbread of Truly
Texas Limousine is one of the concerned operators. Some of his
clients hire limousines for proms in Dallas, where he has to keep
an eye out _ so he won't be ticketed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been told that they've got two people in Dallas who
enforce the regulations, mainly during prom season. They hang out
at the hotels, watching to catch somebody,'' he says. So far,
Goodbread has been lucky. ``I guess I just haven't been caught.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem that Goodbread has with Dallas is that the city
seems to be run by car snobs: It won't grant permits for limos that
are made from ``stretched'' pickup trucks.
</P>
<P>
   Chapter 10A of the Dallas City Code is clear on the subject:
``... a limousine,'' it says, ``is a luxury sedan.'' In addition to
forbidding the drivers of pickup limousines to originate a trip in
Dallas, the ordinance forbids the reboarding of a passenger who has
disboarded, to attend a prom, to use a restroom, to get married _
or for any other reason.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dallas thinks that a limousine has to be a Cadillac or a
Lincoln,'' groans Tom Doherty, owner of Three-D Custom of Everman,
a company that builds pickup, Humvee and SUV limos, the so-called
exotics of the trade.
</P>
<P>
   Passengers prefer exotic limousines, Doherty and their owners
say, mainly for reasons of caprice and curiosity. ``In Fort Worth,
it's the cowboy appeal, something about the Old West,'' says Rodney
Rasberry, whose 341/2-foot Ford F-350 went into service this week
under the name Western Luxury Limousine.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're pretty useful when you've got eight passengers with
luggage,'' says Goodbread, who operates a 31-foot Chevy C-3500.
``They also come in handy for tailgate parties at Cowboys games.''
</P>
<P>
   Only two companies operate pickup limousines out of bases in
Fort Worth and Arlington, and the only Humvee limo in the Metroplex
has recently been sold to a Florida operator. But Doherty, who
built all three vehicles, is sure that his business would triple _
if Dallas would just loosen up.
</P>
<P>
   Fort Worth and Dallas/Fort Worth Airport issue permits to
limousines, just as Dallas does, and authorities in those two
jurisdictions haven't banned the exotics. ``I don't see any reason
to exclude them if there's a demand for the service _ and there is
_ and as long as there's no safety problem,'' says Robert Bergeron,
who administers D/FW's program for permits.
</P>
<P>
   Doherty built his first stretch pickup in 1989, and soon limo
companies from across the nation were ordering them. He no longer
keeps count, but he estimates that he has stretched about 150
pickups, adding 22 to 176 inches to the length of each.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, Doherty got his first call for a stretch version of the
Humvee, the Jeep-like military vehicle that is now the Army
standard. ``It was the thing at the time. Arnold Schwarzenegger and
Sylvester Stallone were driving civilian models of the Humvee, and
everybody wanted one,'' Doherty says. His first Humvees were sent
to a client in Atlanta. Now his shop is producing its 25th stretch
model.
</P>
<P>
   Stretch pickup limousines are roomy and comfortable, but the
Humvees, even with amenities like televisions and wet bars, and
with the alteration that is unique to Doherty's shop _ lowering the
vehicle's transmission hump from 17 to 4 inches _ are a bit
cramped. ``There's not much head room,'' Doherty acknowledges.
</P>
<P>
   One of the reasons that limo operators like pickup and Humvee
models, however, is eminently practical. ``Those we build have
diesel engines, and limos spend a lot of time sitting, with the air
conditioning running. The diesel engines don't heat up at idle like
gasoline engines do,'' Doherty says.
</P>
<P>
   Stretched Humvees and pickups are not cheap. Sticker prices run
about $90,000 for new Hummers, and the work of Doherty's shop adds
$50,000 to $100,000 to their price as limousines. Comparative
figures for the pickups are a purchase price of about $30,000, plus
$40,000 to $60,000 for conversion to limos.
</P>
<P>
   Purchasers cry all the way to the bank, Doherty says: Hourly
rates for Humvee rentals run from about $200 to $350, and those for
pickups from about $100 to $200; standard rates for sedan limos run
from $75 to about $100 per hour.
</P>
<P>
   The Dallas restriction against the exotics hasn't brought in any
revenue from fines, partly because operators have learned to be on
guard. On the other hand, the fee for renewing a limousine permit
in Dallas is a hefty $500 per year. Perhaps because permit fees
promise to be a more reliable source of income than fines for the
municipal department that oversees the city's taxi and limo
affairs, Dallas officials say that they are now considering
proposals to repeal the city's sedan-only rule. But until a change
is made, the operators of cowboy Cadillac limos will have to keep
their eyes peeled.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
