<HEADER>
A4555 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-FILM-REVIEW-ROMANCE-H     10-12 0867
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-ROMANCE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`ROMANCE' ISN'T ROMANTIC 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By AMY BIANCOLLI  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's hard to say a bad word about a film like ``Romance''
without sounding prudish, anti-intellectual or both. When it comes
to critical booby traps, you can't do better (or worse) than an
explicit French movie about the sexual exploits of a bored young
woman. Praise it and prove your mettle. Pan it and look like a
dunce.
</P>
<P>
   Enter the dunce.
</P>
<P>
   ``Romance'' is _ despite its topic and its start-to-finish,
up-close-and-personal, look-ma-bare-organs graphic sex _ about as
titillating as a visit to the gynecologist. In fact, it is a visit
to the gynecologist; at one point, the film's continually humping
protagonist equates male-female intercourse with monthly checkups
at her Ob/Gyn's. Yell if this sounds sexy to you.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, none of ``Romance'' is sexy. None of it's romantic _
please note ironic title. And not much of it's compelling, although
Yorgos Arvanitis' cool photography and writer-director Catherine
Breillat's virgin-whore color scheme are both artfully done. Those
who wear white have pathetic, stilted or nonexistent sex lives.
Those who wear red are ooh-la-la. And those who wear black are _
but that would give away the ending (and it's a weird one).
</P>
<P>
   When we first meet Marie (Caroline Ducey) and her wan model
boyfriend, Paul (Sagamore Stevenin), we know they aren't having sex
because they wear nothing but crisp white clothing. Paul and Marie
sleep in the same bed, but he became indifferent to the sex act
months ago and wishes Marie would just quit whining about it. ``It
doesn't interest me,'' he says, his face the picture of ennui.
</P>
<P>
   She, for her part, is in love with her lump of a boyfriend and
refuses to walk out. Her alternative solution is to sleep around,
which she does, bringing her pale disinterest to one dull coupling
after another. One stud, played by porn star Rocco Siffredi,
listens blankly while Marie blathers on about inadequate male
endowments. Another guy pays her for oral sex, then rapes her on a
staircase.
</P>
<P>
   Much nicer _ a true prince among men, actually _ is Robert, a
red-shirted Don Juan (Francois Berleand) who gags Marie, ties her
up, sparks her appetite for S&AMP;M and boasts of having slept with
10,000 women (one of whom an inept subtitle identifies as the late
``Grace Delly''). Robert is scum, but he's scum with heart: When he
binds Marie a little too painfully, he apologizes and caresses her
head with tenderness.
</P>
<P>
   Such is Breillat's idea of a human moment _ a dominating
lothario who strokes the hair out of the heroine's eyes. The rest
of the film is flat, affectless, in love with its own detachment
and lacking any compelling narrative or character; Ducey's face
tears up on occasion, but most of the time it's as dolefully
inexpressive as her bored interior monologues (``I hollow myself:
that's my purity''). And nowhere is she less expressive than in
coitus, when her eyes assume the glazed disassociation of someone
having a root canal.
</P>
<P>
   Excuse us for asking, but isn't sex supposed to be _ oh, what's
that word _ fun? The sex acts in ``Romance'' are so head-to-toe
graphic that they've sparked comparisons to pornography (albeit
gabby pornography), but it isn't the movie's genitalia, or its
venereal candor, that offends; it's the portrayal of intercourse as
an emotional dead zone. Like David Cronenberg's ``Crash,''
``Romance'' scoffs at monogamous union but finds little reward in
its alternative. Simply put, it makes sex dull.
</P>
<P>
   None of which is particularly liberating. For a film that's been
promoted as a frank ode to female desire, Breillat's work neither
conjures the thick mists of true physical longing nor makes much of
a case for womanhood. Marie goes from being dressed in white and
fed up with the shortcomings of the common male to being dressed in
red and being even more fed up with the shortcomings of the common
male.
</P>
<P>
   Except for Robert, who understands Marie's vague, twin longings
for submission and control, every man in ``Romance'' is just
another target for blandly articulate male-bashing. According to
Breillat's world schema, men are bored with sex, bad at sex,
obsessed with sex, disgusted with sex, ill-equipped for sex and
determined to have sex with everything that moves. They are
faithless, self-involved louts who want only to seduce and conquer.
</P>
<P>
   This is feminism? No, it isn't _ and neither is a dream sequence
in which Marie fantasizes about a brothel where men couple with
faceless groins. In the slightly less-tedious ``36 Fillette,'' the
only other Breillat film to be released stateside, a sexually
budding 14-year-old flippantly observes that men would like nothing
more than to remove women's heads from the rest of their bodies.
Separate their minds from their nether parts, so they can have sex
without their brains getting in the way.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, Breillat thought enough of this conceit to base an
entire movie on it. The result is ``Romance,'' a film that reduces
sex to its mechanical components and reduces those who have it _
men as well as women _ to cheerless automatons.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
