<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-12 18:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4557 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-AFLCIO13-COX     10-12 0779
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AFLCIO13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GORE'S AFL-CIO ENDORSEMENT UNLIKELY TO BE UNANIMOUS
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Vice President Al Gore appeared to escape a major
political embarrassment Tuesday as AFL-CIO officials privately
pushed the 68-union federation closer to endorsing Gore over an
increasingly popular Bill Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, arriving here Tuesday afternoon for last-minute
negotiations with labor leaders at their hotel, planned to visit
the AFL-CIO convention Wednesday morning to accept the labor
endorsement following a formal vote of the federation's 700
delegates.
</P>
<P>
   But the anticipated floor vote, on the final day of the
gathering, would be a mere formality. The key vote to recommend
Gore to the convention delegates was to be taken late Tuesday by
the AFL-CIO's political committee.
</P>
<P>
   Following weeks of intensive lobbying by Gore and Bradley,
AFL-CIO President John Sweeney appeared to have lined up the
necessary support on the political committee to secure the
endorsement for Gore. But the private vote of the panel, which
includes representatives from more than two dozen unions, was
unlikely to be unanimous.
</P>
<P>
   James Hoffa, president of the International Brotherhood of
Teamsters, which is represented on the political committee,
announced that the Teamsters would vote against endorsing Gore
because his 1.4 million-member union is not ready to endorse a
presidential candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is the feeling of our members that they need more time to
see the candidates in action, and we, as a union, need more time to
advance our agenda through the electoral process,'' Hoffa's
statement said.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the week, Teamsters officials had indicated that the
union might simply abstain when the political committee met to vote
on an endorsement.
</P>
<P>
   The United Auto Workers also indicated they would either abstain
or vote against endorsing a presidential candidate at this time.
</P>
<P>
   To avoid embarrassing Sweeney because of the Teamsters'
opposition to a Gore endorsement, Hoffa's statement added that ``in
the end, the labor movement can count on the Teamsters Union to do
the right thing for America's working families.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoffa, who seven months ago took over the union his legendary
father and namesake once headed, also avoided any public
appearances off the convention floor because ``he does not want to
be perceived as being in a power struggle with Mr. Sweeney,'' said
Teamsters spokesman Chip Roth.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the Teamsters' current opposition to an endorsement of
Gore, Roth said one of the more positive developments of the
convention is that ``we have established a dialogue with the Gore
campaign at the highest levels.''
</P>
<P>
   Sweeney, at the urging of President Clinton, pushed for the
endorsement of Gore this week, the earliest ever by the AFL-CIO,
because of Texas Gov. George W. Bush's rising popularity, according
to Steve Rosenthal, the AFL-CIO's political director.
</P>
<P>
   The only other time the labor federation endorsed a presidential
candidate during the primaries was in 1983 when it backed Walter
Mondale against a strong challenge from Gary Hart.
</P>
<P>
   ``The danger of not doing something now (for Gore) is that
George W. Bush will get elected,'' said Rosenthal.
</P>
<P>
   The expected endorsement of Gore marks the beginning of a $40
million campaign by the AFL-CIO to mobilize political support for
their preferred candidates in the 2000 general election.
</P>
<P>
   Its timing also helps Gore avoid a major setback as he tries to
restart his campaign from a new headquarters in Nashville amid new
polling data showing Bradley continuing to cut into his lead.
</P>
<P>
   The new Nashville headquarters caused some embarrassment for the
Gore campaign Tuesday when it was disclosed by The New York Daily
News that some of the wiring at the building had been done by
nonunion workers.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee AFL-CIO President John Neeley assured his fellow union
members that the mistake was made because of ``the rush'' with
which Gore's campaign sought to move the headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   A CNN/Gallup/USA Today poll completed Sunday shows Gore with a
12-point lead over Bradley, down from 33 points from last month.
</P>
<P>
   Gore now has the backing of only 51 percent of Democrats
compared to 63 percent in September, according to the poll.
Bradley's support has grown from 30 percent in last month to 39
percent now.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gore needs all the help he can get,'' William Schneider, CNN's
chief political analyst, said Tuesday at the Los Angeles Convention
Center. ``This endorsement couldn't come at a better time for
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
