<HEADLINE>
SHOWTIME FILM ON MAPPLETHORPE; `TODAY' RECORDS; JETS MONDAY NIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ohio)   (bl)  
 By BILL CARTER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Another Artist, Another Exhibit
</P>
<P>
   Showtime will be making a movie based on the political brawl
over an art exhibition accused of being obscene.
</P>
<P>
   No, not  &UR; that &LR;  one. The Showtime film, which will probably begin
shooting in November, will be based on the exhibit of art by Robert
Mapplethorpe that aroused such passions in Cincinnati in 1990 that
the director of the Contemporary Arts Center there, Dennis Barrie,
was actually put on trial and charged with pandering obscenity. (He
was acquitted.)
</P>
<P>
   But Jerry Offsay, president for programming at the Showtime
networks, acknowledged Tuesday that the uproar over the
``Sensation'' exhibition at the Brooklyn Museum of Art, which has
pitted New York Mayor Rudolph Giuliani against much of the art
world as well as free-speech advocates, is ``a very lucky accident
of timing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The controversy over the Brooklyn exhibit was not a factor at
all in our deciding to make this movie,'' Offsay said Tuesday,
``because we've had this project in development since 1994.'' It
only got announced this week, he said, because the final piece fell
into place: James Woods agreed to star in the film as Barrie.
</P>
<P>
   Offsay added that before the mayor's challenge to ``Sensation''
made headlines, the network had already reached an agreement with
the director Frank Pierson, and Woods had already read the script.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he conceded that having the furor over ``Sensation''
erupt just as Showtime decided to do the film was the kind of
development that often helps television movies get attention. He
equated it with Showtime's decision last year to a do a version of
``Inherit the Wind'' just as the debate over the teaching of
evolution in Kansas schools became national news.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a project here that was eight years old,'' Offsay said.
``And in meetings when you have a project like this, some creative
executive always asks a question like, `What's the relevance of a
story this old?' But hot-button issues like this tend to be
timeless. History does repeat itself.''
</P>
<P>
   The film will look at the position Barrie found himself in
Cincinnati when the exhibition of Mapplethorpe's photographs, which
have images like men in sadomasochistic poses and children with
genitals exposed, was attacked by religious and political leaders
in Cincinnati and stirred debate in Washington over public
financing for the arts. Offsay said the film would deal with the
trial and also with how the incident roiled Barrie's private life.
</P>
<P>
   ``His family was involved,'' Offsay said. ``They were vilified
at Little League games. There's a lot of human drama, as well.''
</P>
<P>
   The reason the project took so long to get started, Offsay said,
was simply that Showtime could never get an acceptable script
written. Once it was, by Ilene Chakin, Showtime and the film's
producer, Michael Manheim, sought a director.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Pierson, who won an Emmy for the HBO film ``Citizen
Cohn,'' was a first choice. ``Frank asked one question,'' Offsay
said. ``He wanted to know if we would allow him to show in the film
the seven images from the exhibit that were at the center of the
trial.''
</P>
<P>
   Offsay said that Woods eventually asked the same question, and
that he told them both that Showtime could hardly be doing a film
about about the issue of censorship and leave out those images.
Pierson will use the actual art in the movie, Offsay said, although
he insisted that the film would still have to be able to receive an
R rating.
</P>
<P>
   As for when the film will make it to television, Offsay said it
would most likely be in May or June, just about the time that a
Senate race between Mayor Giuliani and Hillary Rodham Clinton is
expected to be heating up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I'm going to be more concerned about the Emmy race,''
Offsay said.
</P>
<P>
   Records for `Today'
</P>
<P>
   The success of NBC's ``Today'' reached the kind of perfectly
round milestone last week that the network could not resist crowing
about.
</P>
<P>
   As of last week ``Today'' had been in first place in the morning
ratings for 200 consecutive weeks. That's the longest period of
dominance for one program since competition among morning news
programs began in 1975.
</P>
<P>
   But ``Today'' had already had the record back at week 199, and
all the way back to week 88.
</P>
<P>
   Still, 200 weeks is a noteworthy number. The streak began the
week of Dec. 11, 1995. That was not a week of any major event on
the program, like the addition of a new host. But that was the week
that Jeff Zucker, who had produced the program earlier and went off
to work on a prime-time magazine program, returned to ``Today'' as
the executive producer.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the program's hosts _ like Katie Couric and Matt Lauer,
and in the past, Bryant Gumbel _ acknowledge Zucker's essential
role in building ``Today's'' unchallenged leadership.
</P>
<P>
   Because of his importance, there was one small detraction from
NBC's elation in the timing of the 200-week announcement. Zucker
told his staff his week that he was taking a leave of absence from
``Today'' starting this week to have surgery for what he called a
pre-cancerous condition.
</P>
<P>
   Zucker, who is 35, previously suffered from colon cancer and was
treated through surgery and with chemotherapy. A spokeswoman for
the program said he was extremely optimistic and expects to rejoin
``Today'' in four to six weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The Return of the Jets
</P>
<P>
   One indication that the New York Jets were back as one of the
elite teams of the National Football League was their return this
season as one of the most featured teams on ``Monday Night
Football.''
</P>
<P>
   ABC may regret that if the Jets don't start doing better this
season. This week, the Jets' first Monday night game drew one of
the smallest ratings for that show in years: under a 10 rating,
according to preliminary national figures. (Each rating point
represents just over 1 million homes.)
</P>
<P>
   Certainly the game was affected by the division in the sports
audience; many viewers were drawn to Game 5 of the Indians-Red Sox
baseball playoff series. But the football game also appears to have
lost to the entertainment lineup on CBS, which drew an 11 rating
from 9 to 11 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest winner on the night was CBS's comedy ``Everybody
Loves Raymond,'' which continues to build into the biggest hit on
that network. It had a 12.1 rating.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
