<HEADLINE>
SUPREME COURT AFFIRMS NICHOLS' CONVICTION AND LIFE SENTENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK HELM  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Supreme Court on Tuesday rejected the appeal of
Terry Nichols, convicted in the 1995 Oklahoma City bombing that
killed 168 people and injured hundreds more. The action let stand
his conviction and life sentence.
</P>
<P>
   In his appeal, Nichols, 44, argued that his federal conviction
for conspiring to use weapons of mass destruction should be
overturned because he never intended to hurt anyone.
</P>
<P>
   In December 1997, Nichols was found guilty in a federal trial of
involuntary manslaughter and conspiracy because of his role in the
April 19, 1995, bombing of the Alfred P. Murrah Federal Building.
Nichols was sentenced to life in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, in June of that year, co-conspirator Timothy McVeigh
was convicted of first-degree murder in connection with the bombing
and later sentenced to death.
</P>
<P>
   In appealing Nichols' sentence, his lawyer, Michael Tigar,
argued that ``the government's evidence failed to prove that Mr.
Nichols was aware that Mr. McVeigh intended to kill.''
</P>
<P>
   Tigar also argued that Nichols' sentence was invalid because his
trial judge used overly harsh sentencing guidelines. The lawyer
contended that because the judge used guidelines designed for
first-degree murder instead of involuntary manslaughter _ the crime
for which Nichols was convicted _ his sentenced should be
overturned.
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton administration lawyers contended that Nichols'
intent would be relevant only if he had been sentenced to death.
The administration also said judges have discretion on which
guidelines to follow.
</P>
<P>
   In February the 10th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals agreed with
that reasoning and upheld Nichols' life sentence. On Tuesday the
Supreme Court let that ruling stand.
</P>
<P>
   An argument similar to Tigar's was used successfully by
co-conspirator Michael Fortier to get his 12-year prison sentence
overturned in June.
</P>
<P>
   The 10th circuit court, in throwing out his sentence, ruled that
federal guidelines for involuntary manslaughter, not first-degree
murder, should have been used. Fortier had pleaded guilty to having
advance knowledge of the bombing. Despite the appellate ruling, a
U.S. District Court earlier this month gave Fortier same 12-year
sentence.
</P>
<P>
   Nichols is expected to go on trial again late next year or in
early 2001 in an Oklahoma court on state murder charges.
Prosecutors are seeking the death penalty in that case.
</P>
<P>
   Also on Tuesday, the high court:
</P>
<P>
   _ Upheld a Maine program that subsidizes children attending
private, nonreligious schools while refusing to spend state money
for those who go to religious schools.
</P>
<P>
   _ Refused to let Pennsylvania exempt religious publications from
a state sales tax.
</P>
<P>
   _ Agreed to decide whether former Associate Attorney General
Webster Hubbell's guilty plea on a misdemeanor tax charge will
stand. The court will try to clarify whether prosecutors can use
documents against defendants who are required to produce them under
a limited grant of legal immunity. Hubbell, a friend of President
Clinton, said his immunity deal with Independent Counsel Kenneth
Starr should have precluded Starr from using the tax documents.
</P>
<P>
   _ Agreed to hear a challenge by ranching and farming groups to
the Clinton administration's regulation of livestock grazing on
millions of acres of federal land throughout the West. The court
voted to study the appeal, which says the administration's 1995
rules violate a 65-year-old law and threaten the livelihood of tens
of thousands of ranchers.
</P>
<P>
   (Mark Helm can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address mark(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-12-99 1844EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
