<HEADER>
A4583 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-ST.-FRANCIS-OPERA-$AD     10-12 0998
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ST.-FRANCIS-OPERA-$ADV17-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MESSIAEN'S EXCURSION INTO RAPTUROUS OPERA  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, OCT. 17) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By PAUL GRIFFITHS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As it becomes clear that Gerard Mortier will be replaced as
director of the Salzburg Festival when his contract expires in
2001, a new release of Olivier Messiaen's lone, immense opera ``St.
Francois d'Assise,'' recorded in performance at the festival, is
especially timely. The production of this opera was the main event
of Mortier's first Salzburg season, in 1992, and in many ways it
was a declaration of intent.
</P>
<P>
   New music, as much as old, was now to benefit from the
festival's resources and prestige. More comprehensively, new stage
directors were to change the look of the festival: ``St. Francois''
brought Peter Sellars to Salzburg for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   The new release (Deutsche Grammophon 445 176-2; four CDs),
recorded at a revival last year, leaves out the wonders and
conundrums of Sellars' staging, but it will serve as a magnificent
reminder of the musical achievements of Mortier's decade at
Salzburg.
</P>
<P>
   And after all, the sound is what matters here. Messiaen was a
master of sound, and he often said that his aim was to astonish, to
shock the listener with wonderful and unexpected sonorities and so
give an intimation of the bliss experienced by souls in Paradise.
In none of his works did he astonish so much, or on so many levels,
as in ``St. Francois.''
</P>
<P>
   The work requires a huge orchestra and chorus, a baritone of
immense authority and stamina in the title role, and a soprano with
the voice of an angel. Until now, anyone wanting to hear ``St.
Francois has had to get to one of its inevitably rare performances
or rely on two recordings: one from the partly defective premiere
production, of 1983; the other an obscure Belgian account conducted
by Kent Nagano.
</P>
<P>
   The new set has faults of its own (some of them because
Salzburg's Felsenreitschule, a large auditorium carved into a
mountainside, is by no means an ideal place in which to record),
but through them all, with total certainty, the work gleams and
radiates.
</P>
<P>
   Messiaen sometimes achieved his bewilderments by simple means,
writing melodies that seem rudimentary as they unfold but that
because of the special scales he used, prove puzzlingly difficult
to recall accurately. Plainchant was his model, but what was there
communal and prayerful becomes in his music, and especially in
``St. Francois,'' emphatic individual declamation.
</P>
<P>
   Each of the characters has his own voice (there is no female
role except that of the Angel, who is addressed as male) and his
own repertory of phrases. Like saints in a medieval polyptych, they
carry with them their identifying emblems, which include, in
Messiaen's powerfully expressive world, not only particular melodic
traits but also identifying emotions: the raging self-pity of the
Leper, whom Francis cures; the immature fearfulness of Brother Leo,
one of Francis' companion monks; the overwhelming conviction and
sense of purpose of Francis himself.
</P>
<P>
   Partly because these emotions are contained in melodic symbols _
almost signals _ rather than allowed to interweave and develop, but
also partly because of the almost uniformly slow pace of the
singing, there is no question of realistic representation.
</P>
<P>
   The opening scene, in which Francis uses Leo's fear as a
teaching point, is a little liturgy of verses and refrains.
Francis' questing certainty and Leo's anxious doubt are conveyed in
alternation, presented rather than represented. If there is little
dramatic tension among the characters, each of whom exists within
his own frame, there is great drama just in their appearance.
Invested in their separate musics, they address us from inside a
magnificently rich, resonant and strange world: that of Messiaen's
orchestra.
</P>
<P>
   In this department, Messiaen's search for astonishment took him
way beyond the elemental chantings of the soloists. Perhaps the
most extraordinary thing about ``St. Francois'' is how the vocal
melodies, unaccompanied or given halos of string tone, fit into the
vastly more complex orchestral score.
</P>
<P>
   Often the orchestral image will come from the song or call of a
bird, amplified to sound through a great body of wind and
percussion instruments. The scene that principally concerns the
Leper _ the third of the opera's eight, roughly half-hour scenes _
uses almost no bird songs, as if the leper had shut out the voices
of nature; yet here, too, the score has its awesome moments: low
brass pacings suggestive of Wagner's music for the dragon Fafner,
swirling mixtures of wordless voices with dabs of string and
percussion tone.
</P>
<P>
   The orchestral performance in the new recording, by the Halle
Orchestra under the direction of Nagano, is strong and often
thrilling. Nagano has known this score since it was being written,
and through his command of tempo and sonority he makes it sound out
full and clear.
</P>
<P>
   One hears Messiaen's exultant embrace of all kinds of chords,
timbres and textures: an embrace so contrary to the confinement and
reduction that other composers have recently felt necessary to
express the spiritual life.
</P>
<P>
   Excellent, too, are the soloists. In the title role, Jose van
Dam is superb, conveying the saint's grand calm and benevolence but
intimating the nagging feeling of insufficiency that keeps him on
his path.
</P>
<P>
   Dawn Upshaw yields purity as the Angel, and Chris Merritt
supplies the embattled anger of the Leper thoroughly in his
singing, avoiding expressionist exaggeration.
</P>
<P>
   Van Dam, who has been Francis in every complete performance of
the work so far, has announced that he will not take on this
colossal part again, which adds further value to the recording. Of
course, the piece will go on: the Lincoln Center Festival is
reportedly exploring the possibility of staging a production in New
York. But now there is a permanent record of Messiaen's vision in
all its splendor.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
