<DOCNO> NYT19991012.0246 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-12 18:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4589 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-AMERICAN-BALLET-ART-2     10-12 0778
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMERICAN-BALLET-ART-2TAKES-$ADV17-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLD-TIME RIVALS MAKE A DATE TO GO DANCING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Mich.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, OCT. 17)  
 (af)  
 By CHRISTOPHER REARDON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   More than most dance companies, American Ballet Theater prides
itself on its versatility. And rightly so. Last spring it presented
``Giselle'' and other Old World heirlooms.
</P>
<P>
   For the fall season, which opens on Tuesday and runs for two
weeks at City Center, the troupe will flaunt its progressive side,
taking on the macabre expressionism of Agnes de Mille, the wry
populism of Twyla Tharp and the quicksilver partnering of Nacho
Duato.
</P>
<P>
   As disparate as these dances are, however, one piece in the
program stands out as a real stretch: Martha Graham's ``Diversion
of Angels.''
</P>
<P>
   Such a union of classical and modern might have been thought
treasonous when the piece was first seen in 1948. Back then, ballet
was lofty and lithe, a passport to the heavens.
</P>
<P>
   Graham's work was its antithesis, an earthbound art that bared
the human soul. Her signature move, an abdominal contraction and
release that starts deep in the pelvis, would have made a naif like
Giselle blush with shame.
</P>
<P>
   Even now, with choreographers shuttli and forth between
classical and contemporary troupes, adding Graham to Ballet
Theater's repertory is a rare and risky endeavor. Only three other
ballet companies have performed her work, and never in New York,
where her troupe is based.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's an expression in England about taking coals to
Newcastle,'' said Wayne Eagling, artistic director of the Dutch
National Ballet, which will stage its fifth piece by Graham next
month. ``It's like a company bringing Balanchine to New York; it
better be bloody good.''
</P>
<P>
   Some purists are aghast at the notion that dancers with no prior
training in the Graham technique could, after six weeks of
rehearsals, do her work justice. Others wonder why Ballet Theater's
Ashley Tuttle, a paragon of classical form, would bother with
Graham's barefoot modernism. But the most common refrain is simply,
``What took so long?''
</P>
<P>
   Ballet Theater has been a crucible of crossover ballet at least
since 1976, when it asked Ms. Tharp, who was known for setting
dances to songs by Petula Clark and the Beach Boys, to make a piece
for Mikhail Baryshnikov. The result was ``Push Comes to Shove,'' a
public sensation that breached the wall between ballet and modern
dance for good. (The company will perform it, minus Baryshnikov, at
City Center.)
</P>
<P>
   There was talk of adding Graham to the repertory a dozen years
ago. She and her rehearsal director, Peggy Lyman, even came and
taught a class. But the project stalled with Baryshnikov's
departure as artistic director in 1989, Graham's death two years
later and financial crises at both companies. (Ballet Theater paid
off the last of its $5 million debt in 1998, while the Graham
troupe retired its $2 million debt earlier this year.)
</P>
<P>
   Kevin McKenzie, Ballet Theater's artistic director since 1992,
eventually resumed the conversation with Ron Protas, his
counterpart at the Graham studio.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt it was important for the company to do a Graham piece,
and do it well, because she's such an influential figure,''
McKenzie said. ``You're going to get it watered down, three times
removed, from some present-day choreographer anyway. So why not go
to the source?''
</P>
<P>
   Protas was game. At the time, he was laying the groundwork for
the new Martha Graham Trust, which licenses her work to dance
companies and schools. The goal, he said, is to keep her work alive
and help it reach a broader audience. To that end, he struck a deal
that allows Ballet Theater to perform ``Diversion of Angels,''
McKenzie's first choice, at a cost of $55,000 for the first year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Angels'' was an anomaly for Graham. Sprightly and tender, it
came just after three of her darkest works: ``Cave of the Heart,''
``Night Journey'' and ``Errand Into the Maze.'' Instead of Medea,
Jocasta and Ariadne, the tragic heroines of those glosses on Greek
myth, it presents three couples happily in love.
</P>
<P>
   To Graham, who created the piece during her brief marriage to
Erick Hawkins and never performed in it, the couples represented
different shades of devotion. The two lovers dressed in white
should appear ``mature and balanced,'' Protas told the dancers
after watching a rehearsal earlier this month. The red couple
should be erotic, he added, the yellow one playful and elusive.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The dancing, to an ebullient score by Norman Dello Joio, is
arguably lighter and more linear than anything else in Graham's
oeuvre. But it's no cakewalk.
</P>
<P>
   ``You cannot hide behind a narrative or a story or a dramatic
portrayal,'' said Peter Sparling, a former Graham dancer whose
modern-dance troupe in Ann Arbor, Mich., recently performed
``Angels.'' ``It's essential, lyrical Graham. The technique is laid
bare.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of her dancers once dubbed the piece ``Perversion of
Angles,'' a sobriquet that seems even more apt at Ballet Theater.
Four weeks into rehearsals, the dancers had the basic structure
down. But the women were still struggling to throw themselves into
radical tilts without falling off balance and learning to leap
without letting their center of gravity ride too high.
</P>
<P>
   The men, wearing knee pads and ballet slippers that will have to
be gone by opening night, grimaced as they plunged to the floor and
tried to spiral right back up.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the purest modern &UR; - &LR; dance technique there is,'' said
Keith Roberts, a principal dancer who has created roles with Ms.
Tharp, James Kudelka and Lar Lubovitch. ( Roberts will also dance
in Lubovitch's newest work, ``Meadow.'') ``It's like asking a
modern dancer to do `Sleeping Beauty.'''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, the effort is not unprecedented. Many notable Graham
dancers (including Graham herself) mastered her technique after
years of classical training.
</P>
<P>
   Rudolf Nureyev, who was jeered during his clumsy debut with the
Graham company in 1984, eventually became an important interpreter
of her work. And last year the Colorado Ballet scored a hit with
its production of ``Appalachian Spring'' (1944), after six solid
weeks of rehearsal.
</P>
<P>
   Takako Asakawa, a Graham protege who is teaching them the piece,
said she had hoped to start off with a few weeks of classes. But
the troupe's busy schedule made that impossible. So after showing
them a 1976 video of ``Angels,'' with herself as the red girl, she
dived right in, demonstrating each of the roles herself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our best way of bringing it to life is through imitation,''
said Roberts, who dances as the red boy. ``We may not fully grasp
what's going on, but if we can imitate it until we get it into our
body, then we can start understanding the feeling of it. It's kind
of a backward approach, but it's all we can do in the time we
have.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the more striking images in rehearsal was that of Ms.
Tuttle, her feet wreathed in adhesive tape, laying a string of
altered arabesques across the floor. Every few steps she stopped,
lifted herself up on point with a visceral contraction and then
surged ahead.
</P>
<P>
   McKenzie had initially pegged her as the yellow girl, an
effervescent role that seemed to suit her persona. ``My natural
movement quality is to be more upright, more flighty, more like
Giselle,'' she said. But Ms. Asakawa, sensing an untapped
potential, shrewdly recast her as the red girl.
</P>
<P>
   On the whole, Ms. Asakawa said, she has found Ballet Theater's
dancers more receptive to Graham than their peers at the Paris
Opera Ballet, where she restaged ``Temptations of the Moon'' (1986)
a few years ago. But with two weeks to go, she was still
dissatisfied with their timing and spacing, and she thought their
transitions were rough.
</P>
<P>
   Again and again she instructed them to flex their feet, molded
their torsos with her hands and shared emotional insights into the
roles. In a dance studio, it was pretty much business as usual.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're not going to look like people who have studied Graham
technique for 12 years,'' Protas said. ``But I think they will have
mastered it to a degree that's acceptable and dramatic.''
</P>
<P>
   Then he offered an anecdote that, if true, appears to call the
entire enterprise into question.
</P>
<P>
   ``Martha's disciples have much more rigidity about her work than
she did,'' he said. ``One time she told Misha, `Darling, this
contraction and release thing: it's so overrated.' Of course, it's
the whole basis of her work.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
