DO PANAMA HATS REALLY COME FROM PANAMA? (For use by NYTimes News
Service clients) 
By ROGERS CADENHEAD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q:.MDNM/ I was told that Panama hats aren't from the country of
Panama. Is this true?
</P>
<P>
   _ M.H., Arlington, Texas
</P>
<P>
   A:.MDNM/ Panama straw hats are actually from Ecuador. The most
widely accepted explanation for the misplaced name is that the hats
were originally exported from Panama, according to Fino Fino, a hat
retailer in Menlo Park, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   ``Workers on the Panama Canal found them to be durable headwear
and comfortable under the tropical sun,'' states the Fino Fino Web
site. Another early wearer, President Teddy Roosevelt, helped to
popularize Panamas in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Fino Fino takes its name from the Montecristi fino, a hand-woven
Panama hat still made in Ecuador that ranges in price from $250 to
$10,000. All of the retailer's Panama buyers are inducted into the
Peninsula Panama Hat Society, which meets every June.
</P>
<P>
   ``The continued existence of the Ecuadorian weavers of the
Montecristis is dependent on the demand for this quality of hat,''
according to Fino Fino. For more information, visit the company Web
site at www.finofino.com or call (650) 321-8720.
</P>
<P>
   Q:.MDNM/ How can I contact Meryl Streep?
</P>
<P>
   _ Mrs. G.A.W., Northborough, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A:.MDNM/ Write to her in care of Creative Artists Agency, 9830
Wilshire Blvd., Beverly Hills, CA 90212.
</P>
<P>
   Streep, 50, is starring next in ``Music of the Heart'' with
Gloria Estefan and Angela Bassett. In the film, which premieres
Oct. 29, Streep plays a Harlem violin teacher whose students earn
an opportunity to perform at Carnegie Hall.
</P>
<P>
   Off screen, Streep is active with Mothers &AMP; Others for a Livable
Planet, a not-for-profit group she co-founded in 1989 with several
neighbors in Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   The 30,000-member group, which has a Web site at
www.mothers.org, promotes organic food, opposes genetically
engineered ingredients and is involved in other environmental
consumer issues.
</P>
<P>
   Q:.MDNM/ Who are the voices of the Budweiser frogs and lizards?
</P>
<P>
   _ B.J., Anderson, Tenn.
</P>
<P>
   A:.MDNM/ The lizards are voiced by Daniel Mastrogiorgio (Frank)
and Paul Christie (Louie), frogs by Tom Woodard (Bud), Ronnie
Brooks (Weis) and Brian Steckler (Er), and the ferret by Bob
Morrow, according to Robert Dougherty, publisher of an unofficial
Budweiser Lizards Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Dougherty's Lizards site is published at
geocities.com/SouthBeach/Cove/3141/budlizards.html. There's also an
official site for the commercials at www.budweiser.com/lizards.
</P>
<P>
   (Rogers Cadenhead writes a trivia column for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. To ask a question, write in care of the
Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, TX 76101, or e-mail him at
trivia(at)prefect.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on
the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
