<HEADER>
A4593 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-INTERNET-CAMPUS-COX     10-12 0835
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-CAMPUS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Electronic Campus a joint effort of colleges in 16 states
 &HT;    By Ernest Holsendolph
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Brandy McCorkle had a problem. She needed one more
course to graduate, but the course she needed on the Mississippi
State campus conflicted with her job. She was stymied.
</P>
<P>
   Stacia Washer, a full-time hospital worker in Quality, Ky., and
a busy mother, desperately needed to find time to study toward a
degree _ but how to fit it in an already demanding schedule?
</P>
<P>
   Both of these women found refuge in one of the newest and
fastest growing sources of higher education, the Electronic Campus.
It is a fast-growing so-called distance learning program, where
students in 16 states take college courses by way of the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The Electronic Campus, not to be confused with the new Georgia
GLOBE program, started just two years ago with 104 courses and has
now mushroomed into one of the biggest ``campuses'' in the
Southeast.
</P>
<P>
   At last count, the Electronic Campus comprised more than 2,000
courses, with more than 20,000 students enrolled, many of them in
their choice of 65 degree programs. All level of degrees are
offered, and the Electronic Campus is now connected to the Georgia
Galileo library system, providing vast new sources of reference
readings to the students on the far-flung campus.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best thing about this program is that we are not a flea
market, we are a mall, an educational mall,'' said Mark Musick,
president of the Southern Regional Education Board, which started
and now governs the Electronic Campus.
</P>
<P>
   Since it was envisioned in 1996, the Web-based campus has been
governed by the participating colleges that offer courses. It is
coordinated by the SREB.
</P>
<P>
   The colleges maintain records of enrolled students, keep track
of their progress and decide what credits are given for the work.
</P>
<P>
   The SREB acts as the switchboard for the courses, and as dean
assuring that the courses are of the right caliber. The board,
through Musick and his team, puts together support services like
the Galileo addition.
</P>
<P>
   And so McCorkle got Mississippi State credit for her course, and
Washer can work through Western Kentucky, the school she would
attend if she had the time to do so.
</P>
<P>
   As with everything on the Internet, its glory is the always the
connection, giving students and schools a new flexibility.
</P>
<P>
   Musick said Clayton College &AMP; State University and Southern
Polytechnic have been among the busiest and most creative partners
in the Electronic Campus. Clayton's former president, Richard
Skinner, was named this year to organize a new program of
electronic education to bolster Georgians' opportunity to benefit
from distance learning.
</P>
<P>
   The point of the state's program, GLOBE or Global Learning
On-line for Business and Education, is to get more Georgians to
take college courses and to strengthen the state's pool of workers
in information technology and develop other skills for business
growth.
</P>
<P>
   The Electronic Campus has no such focus but instead stretches
broadly to provide a range of courses, emphasizing regional
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
   I wondered how the colleges, normally so competitive, agreed to
such a cooperative program.
</P>
<P>
   ``The governors of the 16 states decided three years ago that we
needed this 'educational free trade zone' to suit students needs
and strengthen the system for the region,'' Musick said.
</P>
<P>
   He pointed out that though schools are competitive, on the
higher levels and in research endeavors, cooperation has always
been a hallmark of secondary education. This has led to a kind of
educational ``common market'' approach to electronic or distance
learning.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is certainly a sense of cooperation as we build this
program,'' said Bruce N. Chaloux, Electronic Campus director.
</P>
<P>
   The range of offerings is large, from simple courses with
reading lists and study guides to others that are interactive Web
sites, with give and take between teachers and even among students.
</P>
<P>
   The Electronic Campus can be viewed at the following site:
www.sreb.org.
</P>
<P>
   Clayton State's Web offerings range from Accounting 101 to
periodontics and AIDS management to courses in writing and music
appreciation. To view the courses and enrollment information at
Clayton State, see the following site: distancelearning
</P>
<P>
   .clayton.edu/srec/
</P>
<P>
   Some futurists have predicted that the growth of distance
learning could spell the end of higher education as we know it, and
provide an escape from the rigidity and expense of old-fashioned
education using bricks and mortar.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Chaloux sees it another way. ``Youngsters will still go to
college,'' he said, ``but the ways they learn will change and there
will be newer options and approaches that will enhance their
learning opportunities.''
</P>
<P>
   Ernest Holsendolph writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
