<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLU13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    New drug arrives in time for flu season
 &HT;    By Kevin Lamb
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Early indications suggest the flu season will
arrive sooner and hit harder this winter than in normal years. On
the bright side, though, doctors will be able to battle influenza
with a newly approved prescription drug.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always speculation as to whether the numbers are going to
be high,'' says Greg Rozelle, director of the personal health
division for the Combined Health District of Montgomery County,
Ohio. ``But there's a little bit of a difference in the vaccine
this year. When the strains change, more people tend to get sick.''
</P>
<P>
   Public health officials are predicting flu to strike four weeks
earlier than usual because of a strain that infected people on
Alaskan cruise ships the past two summers.
</P>
<P>
   Rozelle has seen no cases confirmed with laboratory tests so far
this season.
</P>
<P>
   It's not too soon for people to get their vaccines, Rozelle
says. They're becoming available at county health departments,
senior centers, clinics, doctor's offices and many drugstores and
supermarkets will offer them. Medicare covers flu shots for its
elderly and disabled beneficiaries, who are the people most in need
of receiving them.
</P>
<P>
   ``People over 65, people with chronic medical risks and health
care workers dealing with people at risk should be vaccinated every
year,'' Rozelle says. ``It's especially important for diabetics and
people with chronic heart, kidney or respiratory problems.
Influenza can lead to serious complications including pneumonia,
and every year a few deaths are attributed to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Flu is blamed for 20,000 deaths a year in the United States,
with as many as 50 million contracting the virus. Its most common
symptoms are sudden high fever, headache and upper respiratory
problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you've got the flu, it knocks you off your feet,'' Rozelle
says. ``You're not going to be coming in to work sniffling to the
boss, `Man, I'm sick.' You're going to be home in bed.''
</P>
<P>
   There is no such thing as stomach or intestinal flu, Rozelle
says, although other viruses cause diarrhea and abdominal pain.
</P>
<P>
   It's important to recognize flu symptoms early because the new
drug, Relenza, can diminish the effects of both A and B types of
influenza if treatment begins within the first two days of
symptoms. The drug is inhaled through the mouth.
</P>
<P>
   The flu strains that this year's vaccination inoculates against
are A/Beijing, A/Sydney and B/Yamanashi, Rozelle says. Those are
the killed viruses used in the vaccines.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's based on a bit of scientific guesswork,'' Rozelle says.
``They take a look at what's happening in other parts of the world.
But they're usually pretty close.''
</P>
<P>
   People with confirmed food allergies to eggs should not receive
flu shots because eggs are used in manufacturing the vaccine,
Rozelle says.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Lamb writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
E-mail: kevinlamb(AT)coxohio.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
