<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-STRIP-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    UPN's `Miami Vice' of the desert lacks charismatic leads,
originality
 &HT;    By Kevin D. Thompson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   All buddy cop films look the same. There's a black cop and a
white cop. The white cop is usually the seen-it-all veteran. He
squints a lot, which makes him look cooler than he really is. The
black cop is the jive-talking, designer clothes-wearing sidekick.
He fires the cliched one-liners between car crashes and big-budget
explosions.
</P>
<P>
   If all buddy cop movies are frustratingly formulaic, the same
can be said about buddy cop TV shows. That brings us to ``The
Strip,'' UPN's by-the-numbers cop series that tries too hard to be
the millennium's new ``Miami Vice.'' But chances are ``The Strip,''
executive produced by Joel Silver (''The Matrix,'' ``Lethal
Weapon''), won't be around long enough to ring in the new century.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Strip'' is the kind of show you can watch with the volume
down and still know what's going on. Crockett and Tubbs have
nothing to fear. The always squinting Elvis Ford (Sean Patrick
Flanery) and the jive-talking Jesse Weir (Guy Torry) are loose
cannon Las Vegas cops. That means they duke it out with bad guys in
moving trucks, hang on the back of speeding limos and dis Kevin
Bacon between those scenes when they're not duking it out with bad
guys in moving trucks and hanging on the back of speeding limos.
</P>
<P>
   But Elvis and Jesse turn in their badges. Well, to be more
accurate, they toss them off a roof, after they're made the
scapegoats for a botched FBI investigation. They're immediately
hired by a big-shot casino tycoon (Joe Viterelli) to, you know, do
the jobs the cops can't _ or won't. First up: find a wealthy
client's kidnapped wife.
</P>
<P>
   Since there's nothing new or interesting to see, the series'
success rides on its stars. Unfortunately, both Flanery and Torry
look and act like third-rate TV stars. As Elvis, Flanery clearly
went to the Luke Perry School of Acting. He has the same
disheveled, I-don't-care-how-I-look-because-I'm-still-cool
attitude. Torry is mildly amusing, but he's no Eddie Murphy or
Chris Tucker.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Strip'' certainly moves fast. But it's going nowhere.
</P>
<P>
   THE STRIP
</P>
<P>
   Today: 9 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: A by-the-numbers cop series that tries too hard to
be the new ``Miami Vice.''
</P>
<P>
   Kevin D. Thompson writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm
Beach, Fla. E-mail: kevinthompson(AT)pbpost.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
