<SLUG> BC-TV-CENTURYOFIMAGES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PBS PHOTOGRAPHY DOCUMENTARY ACTS TOO MUCH LIKE THE TOURIST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``American Photography: A Century of Images,'' the three-part
documentary beginning Wednesday night on PBS, begins with
devastating images: scenes of the havoc wreaked by tornadoes this
spring in Oklahoma and Kansas. But it's not the destruction that's
affecting; it's the photos.
</P>
<P>
   Snapshots, really. Hundreds, maybe thousands of them, neatly
laid out on tables in a community center. They were ripped out of
their homes by the tornadoes, recovered miles away, and now lie
waiting for their owners to reclaim them. They're mixed in a
confusing assortment, and people wander through the center, trying
to find their memories amid the mass.
</P>
<P>
   Within moments, ``American Photography'' has implanted itself in
your brain: What if this happened to you? What if your photos,
documenting your family, your vacations, your celebrations,
suddenly vanished? The opening scene is a great device for
illustrating the importance of photography.
</P>
<P>
   It's also a great analogy for what's right and wrong with
``American Photography.'' Because out of hundreds of possibilities,
the series has uncovered some beautiful, striking examples of
photography as art and journalism _ and let dozens of others get
lost.
</P>
<P>
   Each of the series' episodes, averaging a little more than 50
minutes apiece, focuses on an era. The first part, ``The Developing
Image,'' centers on the first third of the century, when
visionaries such as Alfred Stieglitz and Paul Strand helped
photography evolve as art. (The former used darkroom manipulation,
the latter worked creatively with the camera itself.) The first
episode also addresses photography's role in bringing home the
horrors of World War I, and Teddy Roosevelt's astute understanding
of how the camera can help construct a politician's image.
</P>
<P>
   The second episode, ``The Photographic Age,'' is about the
middle third of the century, with the growth of newspaper wire
services, the beginnings of the pinup, and the worldwide impact
that photos gave catastrophes such as the Hindenburg disaster and
Pearl Harbor. The third part, ``Photography Transformed,'' takes us
into the modern (and sometimes digitally altered) age. It rehashes
the oft-discussed way that President Kennedy knew how to take
advantage of the camera while President Nixon seemed defeated by
it, and offers glimpses of Vietnam, which one interview subject
calls the only ``uncensored'' war.
</P>
<P>
   ``American Photography'' rushes through these subjects with the
speed and brutality of a ``paparazzo's'' motor-driven camera. It's
a frustrating bit of must-see public TV _ must-see for what it
contains, frustrating for what it's missing. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The most famous images are here, and you'd be disappointed if
they weren't: the raising of the U.S. flag on Iwo Jima, Jack Ruby
shooting Lee Harvey Oswald, the ``whole Earth'' photo of the late
'60s, Buzz Aldrin setting foot on the moon, a student wailing over
a dead body at Kent State. Images you might not be familiar with _
photos of a World War I soldier's face blown into a half-moon by an
explosion, of Depression-era families enduring the Dust Bowl, of
atrocities of the pre-civil-rights era _ add depth to the series.
</P>
<P>
   But crunching 100 years into 160 minutes makes for some glaring
omissions. It's odd that a TV series would ignore the contributions
of television and movies, which are forms of photography; movies
began as a series of still photos, each slightly different from the
last, that became moving images when run together. (Maybe it's
because TV is ignored that the TV camera here insists on zooming in
on the still photos, telling you what to look at instead of letting
you decide for yourself.)
</P>
<P>
   The series' third episode is the most problematic, because it
gives lip service at best to photography's impact on pop culture.
Earlier episodes glance at the influence of ``Life'' and ``National
Geographic''; why does the last ignore ``Playboy'' (a cultural
phenomenon, like it or not) and ``Rolling Stone,'' which has
perhaps the best photography of many photo-obsessed magazines.
Where are the contributions that photography made to album covers,
movie posters and even television _ what would Farrah Fawcett have
been without her famous pinup photo?
</P>
<P>
   And although the series name-drops Andy Warhol and Robert
Rauschenberg, it never even mentions such luminaries as Annie
Leibovitz, Richard Avedon, Robert Mapplethorpe and Herb Ritts _ and
these are just the tip of a late-20th century iceberg. How can you
do a series about photos and not mention Leibovitz, perhaps the
pre-eminent celebrity photographer since the '60s?
</P>
<P>
   If anything, ``American Photography'' should have been longer;
this fascinating subject could easily have justified a
decade-by-decade, 10-episode series. It's like traveling to a
foreign land and taking pictures only of the landmarks. What you
see will make you ooh and aah. But there's a bigger picture out
there, and though this is a worthy series, it leaves that picture
underdeveloped.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
