<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-GAYS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RULING AGAINST BAN ON GAYS IN MILITARY RILES BRITISH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ In a nation that clings fiercely to its traditions,
there was gnashing of teeth when a European court in France told
the British military that its ban against homosexuals was illegal.
</P>
<P>
   The Daily Telegraph, the voice of conservative Britain,
responded by devoting half of its letters page to the subject under
the headline, ``Devastating effects of open homosexuality in the
Forces.''
</P>
<P>
   But those who cherish tradition here will have to get used to
the idea of the Strasbourg-based European Court of Human Rights
having growing influence over their way of life. The ruling that
forced the British government to suspend the ban against
homosexuals in the military, and that may force it to scrap it for
good, is only one of many that will probably challenge and
fundamentally change longstanding British institutions.
</P>
<P>
   Under a law passed last year by the British Parliament, the
European Convention on Human Rights will be incorporated into
British law in October 2000. It requires the British government to
make its domestic laws compatible with the convention and judgments
by the Strasbourg court based on the document. It will also
obligate British judges to interpret human rights according to the
convention, which has sided more often with individual rights than
with institutional ones.
</P>
<P>
   The British military is just the first of many institutions here
that will feel the results. The new law will:
</P>
<P>
   --End immunity for government agencies and open the door to
negligence suits against the police and social service agencies.
</P>
<P>
   --End or severely curtail the practice of Britain's intelligence
agencies of routinely blocking publication of critical books and
newspaper articles.
</P>
<P>
   --Expose the lucrative tabloid newspaper industry to huge
judgments for invasion of privacy, something it is used to doing
with impunity.
</P>
<P>
   Ben Emmerson, a lawyer who represented two of the four
homosexuals who won their case challenging the ban on gays in the
military, said the Human Rights Act that becomes law next year is
``the most significant legal reform ever in the history of the
United Kingdom.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not going to be piecemeal. It's going to affect every
single decision, from planning to crime, to family law, to
immigration,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Pavlos Eleftheriadis, a law lecturer at the London School of
Economics, agreed that the change wrought by the new focus on human
rights will reverberate through British society. But he said that
while traditionalists have tended to criticize the convention as
usurping British sovereignty, the European law can be used to
preserve tradition as often as to challenge it.
</P>
<P>
   The European convention provides Britons with legal protections
not specifically mentioned in British law.
</P>
<P>
   ``There isn't a right to privacy in English law,'' Eleftheriadis
said. But privacy is a concept with considerable case law in the
European court. Eleftheriadis said it has been used imaginatively
in environmental cases in which plaintiffs have argued successfully
against property development on the grounds it would result in the
loss of their home, and consequently their privacy.
</P>
<P>
   Eleftheriadis noted that the United States and most European
countries have constitutions, while English legal tradition rests
in common law. Laws are made by Parliament, and no court here can
challenge them.
</P>
<P>
   Although the European court cannot strike down British laws, it
can, as it did in the military case, declare that they are
incompatible with the Convention on Human Rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``Strictly speaking, the Strasbourg decisions are not binding,
but in practice they are always respected,'' Eleftheriadis said.
``When they lose in Strasbourg, the British always comply.''
</P>
<P>
   Although it has never happened, and no country seems eager to be
a test case, any signatory to the convention that ignores the
Strasbourg court faces expulsion from the Council of Europe, where
membership is mandatory for all countries in the European Union.
</P>
<P>
   Civil liberties advocates say the new emphasis on human rights
will bring British law more into line with other European
countries. In maintaining its ban against gays, the British
military was swimming against the tide of Europe. The Netherlands
lifted its ban in 1972, Denmark in 1979. Italy has a ban that is
not enforced, while Germany does not have a ban.
</P>
<P>
   Britain not only has a ban, but rigorously enforced it. About
1,000 gay men and women have been thrown out of the military in
recent years. In response to last week's decision, George
Robertson, the minister of defense, ordered a halt to proceedings
against about 60 people in one of his last acts before becoming
general secretary of NATO.
</P>
<P>
   The Ministry of Defense has always opposed allowing gays to
serve in the military, calling it an ``unwelcome social
experiment'' that would weaken morale and cause havoc.
</P>
<P>
   But Duncan Lustig-Prean, 40, a former naval lieutenant commander
and one of the four who fought their discharges in the European
court, said he received support and sympathy from his naval
colleagues, not hostility, when it became clear the Royal Navy was
going to dismiss him.
</P>
<P>
   British courts had backed the military. The European court,
however, ruled that the ban was illegal because the process used to
investigate claims against gay servicemen and women violated their
right to privacy. The court said the British military's view that
having homosexuals in the military would create trouble was
``founded solely upon the negative attitudes of heterosexual
personnel toward those of homosexual orientation.''
</P>
<P>
   Cary James, editor of The Pink Paper, a newspaper of the gay
community, said the court's ruling would have repercussions for
other employers.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a domino effect,'' he said. ``Once the military
falls, the rest can. This could be the driving force for equal
rights for everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Gay activists such as James have turned their attention to
abolishing Section 28, a clause in the 1988 Local Government Act
that prohibits ``the intentional promotion of homosexuality'' by
local authorities and ``the teaching of homosexuality as a pretend
family relationship'' in schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the military case, the judges said homosexuality is
innate,'' James said. That, he said, means any law in Britain that
excludes people based on their sexual orientation would violate the
European Convention on Human Rights.
</P>
<P>
   While some view the Strasbourg court as another example of
European institutions ruining British traditions, others have
sought to use it to safeguard tradition.
</P>
<P>
   Four independent schools that want to continue doling out
corporal punishment went to the court to challenge a ban against
caning that took effect Sept. 1. Those who want to ban professional
soccer matches on Sunday afternoons have also taken a case to the
court, arguing that the games interfere with their ability to
worship. Landowners want the Strasbourg court to strike down a
British law that gives Britons a statutory right to roam over 4
million acres of privately owned land in England and Wales.
</P>
<P>
   ``The convention is neither left-wing nor right-wing,''
Eleftheriadis said. ``It is the perfect compromise because you
retain parliamentary supremacy, but you create a system of checks
and balances.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-12-99 1926EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
