<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-12 19:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4631 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-LOMAX-DELTA-BLUES-$AD     10-12 0665
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOMAX-DELTA-BLUES-$ADV17-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVELATIONS FROM A DELTA JOURNEY  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, OCT. 17) 
</HEADLINE>
  (af) 
 Tony Scherman is the author, most recently, of ``Backbeat: Earl
Palmer's Story.''  
 By TONY SCHERMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In 1941 and 1942, the folklorist Alan Lomax visited the
Mississippi Delta to document its African-American folk music. One
of his major objectives was to record the Delta's most famous
cultural product, the blues.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mississippi the Blues Lineage'' (Rounder 11661-1825), whose
contents Lomax selected before a stroke incapacitated him several
years ago, represents his early-'40s Delta blues fieldwork. It's
part of the ambitious ``Alan Lomax Collection,'' whose eventual 140
or more CDs will embrace Lomax's 50-plus-years of worldwide song
collecting.
</P>
<P>
   Lomax didn't record the greatest of the Delta blues singers; by
1941, Robert Johnson was three years dead. But Eddie (Son) House,
who gives four performances here, was Johnson's teacher, and
McKinley Morganfield, who gives two, was Johnson's disciple, later
to become world famous as Muddy Waters.
</P>
<P>
   The album includes several other good bluesmen _ David
(Honeyboy) Edwards, still performing today at 84, and the otherwise
unrecorded William Brown of Memphis _ but to hear these journeymen
and then House and Waters is to grasp the difference between
competence and mastery.
</P>
<P>
   Not long after these sessions, Muddy Waters left for Chicago,
where he pioneered the electric blues band and died in 1983, full
of years and renown. On his too-brief appearance here (an album's
worth of Waters' Lomax songs, ``The Complete Plantation
Recordings,'' is available on MCA), he plays bottleneck guitar with
a nimbleness and speed he rarely displayed later on.
</P>
<P>
   Vocally, he is recognizably himself, though without the gravitas
of later years. The up-tempo ``I Be Bound to Write You'' is a
version of Waters' early signature tune, ``I Be's Troubled'' (in
Chicago it became ``I Can't Be Satisfied''). ``You Gonna Miss Me
When I'm Gone,'' a slow shuffle, sounds like Robert Johnson's
``Come on in My Kitchen,'' but without Johnson's edge of panic.
Even in his mid-20s, Muddy Waters has a reassuring solidity.
</P>
<P>
   The revelation to most listeners will be Son House, whom blues
fans know either as a stiff-fingered old man past his prime (he was
rediscovered in 1965) or from a half-dozen abysmally recorded 78s
made in 1930. When Lomax found House, the singer was 39 and at the
top of his form.
</P>
<P>
   While the voices of most Delta bluesmen have a liquid pliancy
(except Charley Patton's, which sounds like a buzz saw), House's
rings like burnished iron. Although the dominant emotion in his
songs is anguish, it sounds somehow involuntary, wrenched from
inside. House's three solo performances are worth the price of the
CD (and there's more to come: eventually, an entire CD of House's
1941-42 recordings).
</P>
<P>
   But the track that makes this album indispensible is the last
one, ``Walking Blues,'' featuring House singing and whaling away on
rhythm guitar; Willie Brown on lead guitar (not the William Brown
mentioned above but the legendary musician invoked by Robert
Johnson _ ``tell my friendboy Willie Brown'' _ in Johnson's
``Crossroads Blues''); Fiddlin' Joe Martin playing lickety-split
mandolin runs and yelling encouragement, and Leroy Williams on
harmonica.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of all my times with the blues, this was the best one,'' Lomax
wrote later, ``better than Leadbelly, better than Josh White, Sonny
Terry, and all the rest of them.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Walking Blues'' swaggers infectiously, an unamplified portent
of the electric blues that would rock postwar America. But postwar
America was light years away from the feudal cotton kingdom into
which Alan Lomax of Washington came barreling, armed with a
recording machine, immense curiosity and the instinct that led him
unerringly _ as it had before and would again _ to several of the
most splendid American performers of the century.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-12-99 1941EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991012.0271 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-12 19:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4632 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-ATLANTA-AIRPORT-ART-2     10-12 0883
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATLANTA-AIRPORT-ART-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARTSFIELD ATLANTA: IS WORLD'S BUSIEST AIRPORT ALSO THE BEST? 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (DUPLICATION WARNING: also sent in category code `t.')  
 (bl)  
 By EDWIN McDOWELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ As a Marine Corps pilot in the 1970s, Michael Quiello
learned to appreciate the teamwork necessary to take off from or
land a plane safely on a rolling, pitching aircraft carrier. In his
subsequent 19 years as a pilot for Delta Air Lines, Quiello, who is
now Delta's system manager for international operations, has been
equally impressed by the teamwork necessary to make an airport hum.
And in his opinion, no large airport functions as smoothly as
Hartsfield Atlanta International.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the best airport in the world,'' said Quiello, who has
flown in and out of such highly regarded airports as Charles de
Gaulle in Paris, Schiphol in Amsterdam and Changi in Singapore.
</P>
<P>
   With 73.5 million passengers last year, Hartsfield is now,
incontestably, the world's busiest airport, pushing the perennial
front-runner, Chicago O'Hare, to second place. But is Quiello being
objective when he says it's the best? After all, his employer,
Delta, has its main hub here and, together with its regional
subsidiary, Atlantic Southeast Airlines, accounts for almost 80
percent of the passengers.
</P>
<P>
   His praise for this onetime raceway, though, is echoed by other
pilots. ``There are taxiways all over the place, it's easy for
passengers to get around in, and they planned it very well,'' said
Larry Coy, a longtime pilot for Continental Airlines, which has its
main hubs at Houston and Newark, N.J. ``It's just a great
airport.''
</P>
<P>
   It is far from perfect, for with its phenomenal growth have come
flight delays, parking shortages and clogged traffic. But while
some cities, like New York, have been glacially slow in providing
airport rail links, Atlanta has a quick rail route from downtown.
</P>
<P>
   Hartsfield, then, may offer a shining example of how an airport
can become a giant and help transform a city into a global
crossroads. Yet it also provides a cautionary tale about the
downside of the boom in air travel. And as more and more people
take to the skies, Atlanta and other cities have little choice but
to make do with existing airports, for the cost of building new
ones is increasingly prohibitive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Overall, it's a good airport,'' said Henrietta Aswad, owner of
the Global Journeys travel agency in Atlanta. ``But there are never
enough parking spaces. They don't have enough spots where you can
pick up or drop off passengers. And getting into the airport from
the main highway is a nightmare.''
</P>
<P>
   Hartsfield's general manager, Benjamin DeCosta, said: ``We're
No. 1 in passengers, and we intend to stay No. 1. But we're also
the most delayed airport in the U.S., with an average of eight-plus
minutes a flight. We're committed to changing that.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   That will not be easy, even for DeCosta, a determined Brooklyn,
N.Y.-born lawyer who was general manager of Newark International
Airport and Teterboro Airport in New Jersey until he was recruited
last year by Mayor Bill Campbell of Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The main reason for the delays is that when Hartsfield's last
master plan was drawn up, in the 1970s, it envisioned a maximum of
65 million passengers a year, said John Boatright, a vice president
at Delta (which has been a continuous Hartsfield tenant since
1934). The current master plan, not yet formally adopted, forecasts
121 million passengers a year by 2015.
</P>
<P>
   Unless something is done well before then, aviation specialists
say, delays could average a half-hour or more and at peak times
departing planes could be backed up as far as the eye can see. The
airport's growth, after all, remains rapid. So far this year,
Hartsfield has handled almost 3.4 million more passengers than
O'Hare. For the first time ever, it also leads all U.S. airports in
takeoffs and landings, its 295,000 so far this year more than
10,000 higher than O'Hare and more than 27,500 ahead of Dallas/Fort
Worth.
</P>
<P>
   Traffic will get worse, too, because in spite of predictions
that Atlanta would slide backward after its 1996 Olympics high, the
city has become more of a destination, less of a stopover.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Ten years ago, 70 percent of Hartsfield passengers connected to
other flights, DeCosta said. That is down to about 55 percent,
thanks in part to the city's growth as a business center. In
addition, though international passengers, especially from Europe
and Latin America, account for fewer than 6 percent of the
Hartsfield total, they have been growing about 20 percent a year
for several years.
</P>
<P>
   Hartsfield has been able to accommodate as many passengers as it
does in part because of what Joe Leonard, chief executive of the
airline AirTran Holdings Inc. (which also has its hub here), said
are its skilled air traffic controllers, control tower operators
and ``an airport whose superb design has stood the test of time.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   That design consists of a terminal building and six concourses
flanked by four east-west runways _ the direction of the prevailing
winds in the region. Taxiways are wide enough for two jumbo jets to
pass on their way to or from any of the 143 domestic or 24
international gates. And the airspace over Atlanta is not as
congested as it is over New York and other urban areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even with only four runways here, compared with seven at
O'Hare and Dallas,'' said assistant general manager James Stogner,
``Hartsfield can get people and planes in and out more efficiently
than any airport in the world. We were a hub before that word was
ever used for an airport. Delta pioneered bringing a tremendous
number of people into a central station and sending them out
again.''
</P>
<P>
   What is now the airport was an abandoned auto racetrack until
the city of Atlanta bought the site in the 1920s and turned it into
Hartsfield International. Hartsfield owes its current stature to a
blessing in disguise _ the economic downturn in the 1970s, which
cut air travel and thus the need to expand quickly to accommodate
more passengers.
</P>
<P>
   ``That gave us some breathing room,'' said Stogner, who has
served under eight of the airport's nine general managers. ``So we
went back and refined our research, this time with substantial
input from the airlines.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of that input came from Eastern Airlines as well as Delta.
Eastern, which shut down in the 1990s, had the first continuous
passenger service from Atlanta to New York, in 1930, and the first
international flight out of Atlanta, to Montreal in 1956.
</P>
<P>
   From atop a hill at the southern edge of the airport, it is
possible to see what Quiello described as the airport's daily
``coming together like a symphony orchestra.'' As waves of planes
land and take off on adjoining runways below, Thomas Nissalke, the
airport's aviation simulation manager, said: ``In good weather, we
can simultaneously depart 94 planes an hour and can land 90 an
hour. No other airport can handle as many airplanes in an hour on a
four-runway system.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   To prepare for those 121 million passengers expected by 2015,
some city officials would like to build a second airport _ a
project that would face many hurdles. Meantime, Hartsfield is going
to build another runway _ but the one on the drawing boards is
already outmoded for today's jets. That is because it was planned
as a runway for commuter planes, and when environmental and legal
clearances for the project were approved, in 1994, most commuter
aircraft were prop planes, not jets.
</P>
<P>
   Though DeCosta and others hope to extend the runway, some
property owners who would be displaced in nearby College Park are
opposed.
</P>
<P>
   For passengers, Hartsfield's strengths are its relative
convenience and, despite the long distances involved, the relative
ease of getting from here to there. But arriving by car can be
numbing _ cars clog the approach roads at peak times, and even the
31,000 parking spaces can sometimes all seem to be occupied.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Hartsfield moves masses of people more efficiently than
most. It is one of the few U.S. airports with a mass-transit rail
station inside the terminal, transporting about 8,000 people to the
airport each day and connecting the airport and downtown in about
20 minutes for $1.50. Nine trains make a 3.5-mile loop underground,
stopping at 13 stations.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Hartsfield maintains a squad of volunteer hosts in red shirts or
blouses who help passengers throughout the airport and a bicycle
patrol trained to answer questions. DeCosta is a stickler for
passenger satisfaction and a clean, orderly airport. He personally
inspects men's rooms and picks up litter, and each month he
alternates with his deputies in the terminal's atrium fielding
passengers' questions.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   With an annual payroll of $1.9 billion, the airport, which is
owned and operated by the city of Atlanta, brings in nearly $15
billion a year to the local and regional economy. About 43,000
people are employed by the airport, its suppliers and
concessionaires. ``The support the city gives is excellent,'' said
Leonard of AirTran. ``They and the officials at the airport do a
nice job of investing in facilities and keeping them up.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Still, the relationship is not always smooth. In April 1998,
Campbell dismissed Angela Gittens, the independent-minded general
manager, and replaced her with DeCosta. Also independent-minded, if
more circumspect than his predecessor, DeCosta says he has more
authority here than he had in Newark.
</P>
<P>
   Among the examples he cited were a recent meeting with Sen. Max
Cleland, D-Ga., to brief him on expansion plans _ plans that are
forecast to cost $5.4 billion in the next decade.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike many others in Atlanta's Department of Aviation, DeCosta
contends that a second airport is unnecessary. He favors a master
plan proposal that Hartsfield buy the property to expand the
projected fifth runway, add and expand terminals and add many more
parking spaces.
</P>
<P>
   He also suspects that a change in technology, specifically
planes capable of vertical landings and takeoffs, will help make a
second airport unnecessary.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, there is the matter of cost. ``A new airport is very
expensive,'' he added, ``so you would have to identify who would
pay off the bonds. That would have to be an airline with deep
pockets, and so far I don't know of any volunteers.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
