u f BC-COKE-ENJOY-COX     10-12 0514
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-ENJOY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Coca-Cola: 'Always' ready for a change
 &HT;    By Henry Unger
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ ``Always'' may not be forever at Coca-Cola.
</P>
<P>
   After nearly a 7-year-run, the company's ``Always Coca-Cola''
campaign may give way to a new ``Enjoy Coca-Cola Classic'' theme
that could debut around Jan. 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a number of initiatives in the works for brand
Coca-Cola that you will see early next year in the marketplace, but
we're not going to comment on speculation,'' company spokesman Bob
Bertini said Tuesday. He was referring to trade publication reports
about the expected change.
</P>
<P>
   ``With all elements of our marketing mix, we're constantly
looking to enhance and strengthen our connection with consumers,''
Bertini said.
</P>
<P>
   While Coke Classic is still, by far, the most popular soft drink
in America, its 20.6 percent market share remained the same last
year by growing at the industry's overall rate of 3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, some non-cola brands have surged in popularity.
Case sales for Sprite, for example, which Coca-Cola Co. sells,
jumped 9 percent last year, and Pepsi's Mountain Dew rocketed 9.9
percent, according to Beverage Digest. That trend has continued so
far this year.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, industry experts have been predicting for months
that the Atlanta-based beverage giant would rejuvenate its flagship
Classic brand with new and more heavily financed advertising and
marketing campaigns. During the first six months of this year, the
company spent about $58 million on U.S. media ads for Coke Classic,
according to Competitive Media Reporting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Next year, we're going to see a major push behind Coke
Classic,'' said John Sicher, editor and publisher of Beverage
Digest. ``Coca-Cola is the name on the door and the biggest brand,
and its strong growth is critical to the company.``
</P>
<P>
   Sicher said Coke bottlers have told him they've been instructed
to replace the ``Always'' red disk design with new ``Enjoy''
graphics on various Classic promotional and display items. The
graphics are expected to show the neck of the contour bottle with
the cap popped off and soda fizzing out, Beverage Digest reported.
The words ``Coca-Cola'' are in very large letters, while
``classic'' is in lower-case small type.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, the publication said, there will be a new tagline
for point-of-sale promotional materials: ``Enjoy All That's
Inside.''
</P>
<P>
   Some industry analysts speculated Tuesday that the company might
still find a way to use the word ``Always'' in a less prominent
position in its marketing because of the equity that has been built
up in the word.
</P>
<P>
   Others, however, expect the company to make a clean break with
the past.
</P>
<P>
   The company currently is using a number of advertising agencies
for Classic, including Edge Creative and Wieden &AMP; Kennedy. It
developed the ``Always'' campaign with Creative Artists Agency.
</P>
<P>
   Henry Unger writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
