<HEADER>
A4638 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-DUPONT-Y2K-NYT &LR;      10-12 0953
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DUPONT-Y2K-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEADING A Y2K TEAM, AS TIME RUNS SHORT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ark., Del.)  (mk) 
 By BARNABY J. FEDER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WILMINGTON, Del. _ Cinda Hallman suspects that she helped to
create the Year 2000 computer problem. As a young systems analyst
fresh out of Southern Arkansas University, she joined Conoco Inc.
in 1966 and wrote software for processing gasoline taxes that did
not look ahead to the need to handle dates starting in the year
2000.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Hallman, now a senior vice president at DuPont Co., the
chemical giant that owned Conoco from 1981 until spinning it off
last August, assumes that the tax program is still in use and
probably had to be repaired recently to avoid malfunctioning.
</P>
<P>
   If so, she has more than made up for that small contribution to
the global computer mess that has come to be known as Y2K. As chief
information officer of DuPont in 1995, she sounded the Y2K alarm in
the top reaches of management. She then created an organization
that mapped DuPont's vulnerability to the problem and developed
performance benchmarks to hold managers' feet to the fire when
their groups lagged behind.
</P>
<P>
   ``I figured it was going to cost $350 million to $400 million,
and that's how it is turning out,'' Ms. Hallman said at DuPont's
headquarters here. ``People have been surprised.''
</P>
<P>
   DuPont's war on computer malfunction is just a variation of the
management challenge that faces all global companies. The land
mines lie not just in DuPont's own systems and electronic machinery
but also in possible disruptions among the 4,800 companies most
critical to its supply chain, in the operations of its 2,700 major
customers and in outside services it depends on, like
telecommunications, air-traffic control and customs.
</P>
<P>
   Although the individual fixes tend to be simple, the sheer
number of variables and the complexity of all the links have led
some experts to call Year 2000 the greatest management challenge
since World War II. DuPont's repair budget is bigger than most but
hardly exceptional; AT&AMP;T expects to spend more than $700 million
and Citigroup, $950 million.
</P>
<P>
   Year 2000 is an opportunity to update some systems, of course,
but the main driver is fear: There will be hell to pay if computers
choking on Year 2000 dates lead to business disasters. ``Unlike
other information-technology projects, this one is much more
visible to the public and to boards of directors _ and being late
isn't an option,'' said Harris Miller, president of the Information
Technology Association of America, a trade association for the
computer industry. ``Managers' heads are on the chopping block in a
much more visible way than usual.''
</P>
<P>
   At DuPont, some managers have already been found wanting. The
company took at least four people off special Year 2000
contingency-planning assignments after they proved too slow in
meeting their targets.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first half of '98 was a high-anxiety period of
organizing,'' said Paul Couvillion, a former nylon plant manager
who was appointed by Ms. Hallman to oversee Year 2000 work.
Couvillion had to make sure that goals and timetables were set for
hundreds of Year 2000 operations, from repairs of individual
computer programs to overall readiness of major divisions. He also
established a system of green, yellow and red ratings for progress
reports.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the problem was scale: H. Dale Martin, who had surveyed
150 separate DuPont manufacturing plants in helping to set up a
global environmental program in the early 1990s, discovered that he
had to investigate nearly 2,100 DuPont addresses in laying the
groundwork for monitoring Year 2000 readiness by site. And hundreds
of those addresses turned out to be either duplicate designations
for the same place or abandoned locations that had not been excised
from company records.
</P>
<P>
   Another problem was that Year 2000 concerns were initially given
short shrift in some divisions. When senior managers were too busy
to have ``gotten it on their radar,'' Ms. Hallman said, she put it
there for them. Last year, for example, she saw that one of
DuPont's major businesses _ she declines to say which one _ had
fallen behind its schedule for repairing the software that
processes orders and manages product shipments.
</P>
<P>
   Time was running out, and Ms. Hallman invited herself to the
office of the corporate vice president in charge of the business to
tell him so. Pointing out the red marks that he had been ignoring
in the reports, she told him bluntly ``to put someone of a Gen.
Patton nature on it.''
</P>
<P>
   He did, and the unit caught up, she said. ``Now, every time he
sees me, he wants to tell me how well they are doing,'' she added.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Hallman, a tall Arkansas native who began making
money-management decisions for her family as a 15-year-old after
her father died, came to the Year 2000 project with plenty of
credibility within DuPont. She achieved wide recognition in
information-technology management circles for sharply cutting
DuPont's expenses while modernizing its systems. She also won
praise in trade publications for negotiating a novel three-way,
10-year alliance with Andersen Consulting and Computer Sciences
Corp. in 1996 that shifted 3,200 DuPont employees to the two
vendors.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Hallman was promoted to global vice president in 1997 and,
last year, to senior vice president, overseeing an array of
activities in addition to information technology, including
purchasing, engineering, human resources and accounting. The year
2000 will be a lift for other careers at DuPont, too, she predicts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tech people won't be able to say they learned much,'' she
said. ``But some managers will have stood out as leaders.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
