<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORK-MY-BRIEFCASE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE OVERSTUFFED BRIEFCASE: FEW HAVE TIME TO OPEN IT 
</HEADLINE>
  (Life's Work: This column about the intersection of jobs and
personal lives appears every other week. Lisa Belkin's e-mail
address is belkin(at)nytimes.com.) 
(DW) 
 By LISA BELKIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The constant, scolding ache in my right shoulder, I
am somewhat relieved to report, is not a new symptom of age, nor is
it anything that will require surgery. It's my shoulder bag.
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, it's the sleek, sexy laptop computer I carry in
that bag, a laptop I chose because it weighs so little _ only 2.9
pounds. That doesn't count the spare battery, which weighs nearly a
pound but gives me four extra hours of mobile work time. It doesn't
count the A/C charger that I take along when I travel, just in case
I use up those four extra hours. Or the notes (file folders, steno
pads, documents) that are the raw material for what eventually goes
on the computer screen.
</P>
<P>
   I weighed it all the other day. My lightweight laptop, with its
case and its baggage, means I'm lugging an extra 13 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   I'm hardly the only one carrying the weight of the work on her
shoulder. Any morning, on any train platform, dozens of bags make
mine look underfed. Waiting for the 7:29 to Grand Central the other
day, Lisa Chung sagged under a bulging leather case that held two
laptops _ not just her Thinkpad but also her Portege _ plus her
office pumps plus a doorstop-size book she was reading for an
after-hours leadership seminar. She guessed the combined weight to
be ``about 10 pounds?'' On the moon, maybe. My relative sense of
weight is based on the 20-pound barbells at the gym (I don't use
them, but I put them back onto the rack occasionally), and this was
much heavier.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's my exercise for the day,'' she said with a shrug. ``That,
and running for the train.''
</P>
<P>
   The question is not how much are we carrying, but why are we
carrying it. The simplest answer is that we have more work to do.
So much more that we can't do it during the confines of a
traditional workday, so we have to do it at home and on the way
home. On the way back to work again. The corollary to this is that
we've shaped our world so that we can work anywhere _ which also
means we have no excuse not to work everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   But then why are so many people with overstuffed briefcases not
actually working? Look at them. They're reading the newspaper or
napping or chatting on cell phones. For a two-hour flight to
Indianapolis last week, I packed the laptop and a 500-page
deposition I was reading as research for an article, but I never
got around to glancing at the document or starting up the machine.
I did, however, manage to plow through the stack of thick, glossy
magazines I bought before I boarded.
</P>
<P>
   Psychiatrists have theories about us. Work, says Dr. Alan
Manevitz, who drags his own briefcase to New York-Presbyterian
Hospital every day, has become our ``transitional object,''
something we cart around because it makes us feel secure. Like my
8-year-old son, who would happily cart his Pokemon collection back
and forth to school, even though his teacher forbids him to take it
out of his backpack.
</P>
<P>
   Back on my train platform, a few feet from where Lisa Chung was
bench-pressing her laptops, Hartley Konnett was Exhibit A of this
hypothesis, having a cigarette before his trip to the trading
floor. At his feet was his briefcase, which he says ``goes under my
desk, where it sits all day, until I carry it back home, where it
sits all night.'' He's tried to leave the thing at work, he says,
but ``you come into the office without it and you feel naked;
people actually comment.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. David Yamins, who never leaves his office at Maimonides
Medical Center without packing prescription pads, journal articles
and his computer, and who spends his daily commute listening to
tapes of psychiatry residents and their patients, says this need to
work isn't necessarily a bad thing. ``We're getting an awful lot
done,'' he says. ``What's wrong with that?''
</P>
<P>
   I'm not so sure. I recall my grandmother and the five-hour
flight we took together when I was 13. An avid reader, who was
still taking courses in subjects like Chinese history in her 80s,
she didn't open a book or even plan her itinerary. Instead, we
talked. On train rides, she looked out the window. My grandmother
knew how to sit and watch. Now my generation has improved the world
so much we don't remember how. As an experiment, I rode the train
empty-handed this week, save for my wallet. I lasted 12 minutes.
Then I gave in and began to scribble a to-do list on the flap of my
checkbook.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
