<HEADLINE>
STOCKS IN BROAD RETREAT 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By KENNETH N. GILPIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Stock prices staged a broad, sharp retreat Tuesday,
pulled down by rising interest rates, political instability in
Pakistan and the prospect that third-quarter corporate earnings may
not live up to expectations.
</P>
<P>
   Interest rates rose in reaction to a surge in crude oil prices.
Late in the day, the yield on the 30-year Treasury bond stood at
6.22 percent, its highest level in nearly two years.
</P>
<P>
   Concern about rising rates was exacerbated by an announcement
from Raytheon Co. that sales and earnings would not be up to
expectations for the balance of this year and in 2000. Word of a
possible military coup in Pakistan, a development that could
heighten tension with India, became an additional source of
instability.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are still stuck squarely in a trading range, but it looks
like the market may be adjusting to the downside again,'' said
Michael Clark, head of U.S. stock trading at Credit Suisse First
Boston. ``It will be tough to get positive momentum back until many
of the issues that are confronting the market are resolved.''
</P>
<P>
   At the close, the Dow Jones industrial average was down 231.12
points, or 2.2 percent, to 10,417.06, its biggest decline in more
than four months. Of the thirty stocks that make up the blue chip
index, only two, Chevron and International Paper, managed to rise
in price. Hewlett-Packard, American Express and IBM all fell by
more than three points.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index lost 22.17, or 1.7
percent, to 1,313.04.
</P>
<P>
   Raytheon, the biggest loser among S&AMP;P 500 stocks, did not trade
for much of the day. The stock suffered its worst one-day decline
in nearly two decades once it finally did open for trading, and
closed at 24 1/4, down 18 3/4.
</P>
<P>
   The NASDAQ composite index, which set a record on Monday, fell
43.52, or 1.5 percent, to 2,872.43. And the Russell 2000 index of
small company stocks dropped 5.51 or 1.3 percent, to 424.68.
</P>
<P>
   At 772 million shares, trading volume on the New York Stock
Exchange was fairly light. But losing stocks outnumbered those that
rose in price by a margin of five to two.
</P>
<P>
   On the NASDAQ stock market, 992 million shares changed hands.
</P>
<P>
   Additional questions about the market's near-term direction
surfaced after the close Tuesday, when technology bellwether Intel
released an earnings report that fell a bit short of expectations.
During regular trading, Intel was one of a small number of stocks
that moved higher on the day, closing at 76 11/ 16 , up 3/16. But
the stock was down as much as 5 in after-hours trading.
</P>
<P>
   ``Technology has been solid, but with this announcement from
Intel we will have to see if that sector stays okay,'' Clark said.
</P>
<P>
   A number of brokerage houses, including PaineWebber Group and
Donaldson Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette, posted results that were better than
expected. Weyerhaeuser, the nation's third-largest forestry
company, said its third-quarter net more than doubled from the same
period a year ago. And after the market closed, Motorola, another
big technology firm, reported earnings that were squarely in line
with forecasts.
</P>
<P>
   In what was generally a bad day for financial service company
stocks, Donaldson Lufkin Jenrette rose 2 3/16, to 42 1/2.
</P>
<P>
   Weyerhaeuser led a strong performance by paper and forest
products company stocks, gaining 1 1/16, to 60 1/2. But Motorola
fell 1 11/16, to 94 15/16.
</P>
<P>
   The rise in crude oil prices helped to boost oil stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Royal Dutch Petroleum gained 5/8, to 58. Chevron was up 1 1/8 to
88. And BP Amoco rose 7/8, to 54.
</P>
<P>
   The rise in interest rates hammered big Internet stocks. America
Online fell 7 1/16, to 114. Yahoo! fell for a second day, dropping
7 1/2, to 173 7/8. And eBay lost 5, to 144 3/4.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Federal Reserve Board has to be happy to see some air come
out of the market,'' said David Mead, chief investment officer at
Harris Bank in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Mead said stocks could correct a bit more from here, and that
over the near term bonds seem a better investment.
</P>
<P>
   However, he said that so many stocks have been beaten so far off
their 52-week highs that he is beginning to make some selective
purchases.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-12-99 1951EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
