<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-12 19:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4649 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-ANTIQUITIES-COX     10-12 0729
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANTIQUITIES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Italy asks U.S. to ban trade in antiquities
 &HT;    By Mike Toner
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Italy, concerned that American markets for ancient
Roman, Greek and Etruscan artifacts are spurring the destruction of
its cultural heritage, has asked the United States for help in
halting international traffic in its archaeological treasures.
</P>
<P>
   The request, coming on the heels of a crackdown on artifact
smuggling operations by Italy's national police, seeks import
restrictions on a wide range of art and artifacts spanning more
than 5,000 years.
</P>
<P>
   A State Department review of the request Tuesday triggered angry
objections from U.S. art dealers who contend that such a sweeping
embargo is both unnecessary and unenforceable. Archaeologists say
it is needed to help halt a ``furious tide of looting to supply
antiquities for the international art market.''
</P>
<P>
   Italy is the first industrialized country to seek such
protection under the U.S. Cultural Property Protection Act since it
was passed 15 years ago. The sheer size of the market in Italian
antiquities _ with imports estimated in the range of $50 million a
year _ is also making the request the most controversial.
</P>
<P>
   The controversy is heightened by the last week's introduction of
legislation _ proposed by Sens. Daniel Patrick Moynihan and Charles
Schumer (both D-N.Y.) and supported by art dealers _ that would add
new, and some say potentially crippling, limitations to the act.
</P>
<P>
   As proposed by Italy, the import ban would apply to statuary,
sculptures, ceramics, glass, frescoes and other objects from the
5th millennium B.C. to the 5th century A.D.
</P>
<P>
   ``Few countries in the world can claim an archaeological
heritage as rich as Italy's,'' said Boston University archaeologist
Ricardo Elia, representing the 30,000 members of the Archeological
Institute of America in support of the import restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   ``But despite strong legislation and strenuous efforts, it
remains plagued by archaeological site looting and other forms of
art theft. And sadly, the United States has long been a major
market for antiquities coming from Italy,'' Elia told the U.S.
Cultural Property Advisory Committee, which is expected to
recommend a course of action to the State Department this year.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike some countries, where looting goes largely unchecked,
Italy has moved aggressively to stamp out the looting and smuggling
inside its own borders.
</P>
<P>
   Between 1993 and 1997, Italian police seized more than 120,000
artifacts from clandestine excavations by Italian tomboroli, or
tomb robbers. Late last year, they broke up a Sicilian smuggling
ring and confiscated 10,000 illicit antiquities worth an estimated
$30 million. Another raid in March netted 11,000 objects.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Italian authorities say the looting continues. Only
last month, thieves backed up a truck to the Emperor Hadrian's
second century B.C. villa outside Rome and made off with a
3-foot-high pink marble column weighing hundreds of pounds.
</P>
<P>
   The daring theft prompted Gen. Roberto Conforti, the head of
Italy's art theft squad, to note that with 40 million visitors
expected in Rome for next year's millennium jubilee, the country is
in danger of becoming a ``help-yourself service'' for artifact
thieves. ``If every tourist takes home a souvenir of the Eternal
City, there will not be much of it left,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Italy had forbidden the export of any of its art and antiquities
for more than 60 years, but without cooperation from countries
where such goods are sold, it has been difficult to recover objects
after they leave the country. In one of the rare exceptions, U.S.
courts this year ordered the return of a $1.2 million gold bowl
that had been smuggled out of Italy and purchased by New York
financier Michael Steinhardt.
</P>
<P>
   But U.S. art dealers say any blanket ban on the importation of
Italian antiquities only in the United States would not solve the
problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``More needs to be done to stop theft and looting at the
source,'' said Rena Moulopoulis, an attorney for Sotheby's in New
York. ``Italy needs more domestic deterrents to this activity, like
stiffer penalties and prompt prosecution.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike Toner writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
