u s BC-HKN-THRASHERS13-COX     10-12 0517
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-THRASHERS13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Home not too sweet for Thrashers
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ They play in a $213 million arena considered far ahead
of the industry curve. They practice in a $2.3 million facility
that has as many television sets as it does Lifecycles. In many
cases, they live in country-club homes that allow them to golf
during down time.
</P>
<P>
   Nice.
</P>
<P>
   Bu three home games before sellout crowds, the Thrashers
are looking forward to _ airplane food.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's time we got out of Dodge,'' said coach Curt
Fraser, whose team opens a three-game trip Thursday against the New
York Islanders in Uniondale, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know when I played,'' Fraser said, ``it always seemed like
when you got on the road things happened a little easier for
everybody. You're more relaxed. You're not squeezing splinters out
of the wood on your sticks. We've been tight here at home.''
</P>
<P>
   The Thrashers managed a 5-5 tie with Buffalo Saturday after
losing to New Jersey 4-1 and Detroit 7-1. The Islanders will be a
nice departure from the trio of Stanley Cup contenders, but the
players appear to be looking forward mostly to a change of scenery.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you play in a different environment, you have to stick
together a little more,'' defenseman Chris Tamer said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes,'' center Mike Stapleton said, ``when you're at home
you're trying to impress everybody (in the stands), especially
being in a new city. On the road you don't feel like you have to
put the show on. It's a simple game. Maybe that's what we need.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will also give us a chance to get to know each other
better,'' Stapleton said, ``When you're on the road is when you
spend most of your time together, and that's when you become a
team.''
</P>
<P>
   The trip is illogical _ north to the Islanders, back to Atlanta,
south to Tampa Bay on Saturday, then north again to the New York
Rangers on Sunday. But as center Ray Ferraro said, ``There won't be
any distractions, because there won't be any time for them on this
ridiculous schedule. Play, fly, practice, play, fly, play.''
</P>
<P>
   The trip is the first for the Thrashers since they made their
final roster cuts. Since then, players have been getting settled
into new homes and making arrangements for family members who came
to town during the opening homestand. Players will tell you that
the distractions are no excuse for the poor defensive play to open
the season, but they won't be present during this trip.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always found that when you get into different
surroundings, you gel more as a team,'' team captain Kelly
Buchberger said.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Edmonton, we could have 18-day road trips sometimes, and
you had to get along,'' he said. ``It builds team chemistry. That's
especially important with this team because we're all new players.
When you're away from home, you talk hockey more because you're not
with your family. Everything is hockey.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Schultz writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
