<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-12 19:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4651 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k BC-FRIEDMAN-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      10-12 0757
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRIEDMAN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: BUSH'S BIG CHANCE  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By THOMAS L. FRIEDMAN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Now that George W. Bush is defining himself on domestic policy
by trashing his own party's congressmen, maybe it's time for him to
define himself on foreign policy by trashing Pat Buchanan.
</P>
<P>
   ``George W. should welcome Buchanan leaving the party _ indeed,
he should see it as an opportunity,'' says Bill Kristol, editor of
the conservative Weekly Standard, who, with his colleague Robert
Kagan of the Carnegie Endowment, is mounting a campaign against
Republican isolationism. ``It is the only way we are going to
restore Republican internationalism.''
</P>
<P>
   Kristol has a point. The Republican Party has lost its way on
foreign policy since the end of the Cold War. Try a little test:
Say the words ``Trent Lott'' and ``foreign policy,'' and see what
images or ideas pop into your head. Anything? The International
House of Pancakes, perhaps? Beef Wellington? Nothing? OK, now
substitute ``Dennis Hastert.'' Nada? Zippo? Well, it's not
surprising. They have no ideas _ only politics, and it doesn't stop
at the water's edge.
</P>
<P>
   Without the threat of a morally vile and strategically lethal
enemy _ the Soviet Union _ the Republican Party has drifted toward
a sort of know-nothing, ``drive-by'' foreign policy. Its members
drive by the White House, shout some putdown of President Clinton,
demand more money for a missile shield and drive on. Their only
interest is defeating the president, not defining a policy.
</P>
<P>
   Why? Because on one end the GOP is pulled by Buchananite
isolationists. Buchanan's brown-shirted view of America is that
it's just like Germany or France _ a nation shaped not by an idea,
but by a territory and by who was born here and who not. ``So
Buchanan is all in favor of fighting Indians and Mexicans to
conquer this continent,'' says Kristol, ``but he turns against any
war abroad that might involve defending American principles and
ideals _ not just soil. He doesn't want to export our ideals,
because, deep down, he doesn't value our ideals. He is a
European-style conservative. He looks to blood and soil as our
identifying characteristic, not the Declaration of Independence and
the Constitution.''
</P>
<P>
   At the other end of the GOP are the realists. They have a world
view: The world is a jungle, there are no norms, and the only thing
that matters is that potential foes be balanced and contained. When
the USSR existed, Republican realism appeared to have a real moral
content, since it was about balancing and containing communism,
argues Kristol.
</P>
<P>
   ``But,'' he says, ``in a world where America is the overwhelming
superpower, and there is no Soviet threat, or any other immediate
threat to contain, Republican realism can slide into Buchanan-like
isolationism.''
</P>
<P>
   It leaves a GOP that on foreign policy seems as if it's against
everything _ from Kosovo to arms control to foreign aid. And that
brings us back to Buchanan, who is still deciding whether to run
for president as a Republican or from the Reform Party.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Republican establishment view is, `Don't pick a fight with
Buchanan, so we don't alienate his voters,''' says Kristol. ``That
is wrong. The party should encourage him to leave. This is not
about who Pat Buchanan is _ we know who he is _ it's about who
George W. Bush and the Republican Party are. Do they stand for
American ideals and global leadership in foreign policy, or are
they just a tent to raise money and accumulate votes?''
</P>
<P>
   It's understandable that the Republican leadership doesn't want
to pick a fight with Buchanan, but, on the other hand, notes Kagan,
``They aren't even saying, `We must not have these views in the
party.' Because the truth is their own foreign-policy views _
except for John McCain and a few others _ are not really that far
from Buchanan's.''
</P>
<P>
   George W.'s biggest foreign-policy proposal has been for a
commission to review U.S. troop deployments abroad, suggesting
there were too many. Not exactly ``the vision thing.''
</P>
<P>
   It would be tempting to say that this is politics and Bush
should just triangulate his way to election. ``But you need to lay
the groundwork during the campaign for how you are going to
govern,'' says Kristol. ``If, as a presidential candidate, you
don't take on the most extreme isolationist in your party, then as
a president you are going to find it very difficult to lead a
Congress, already tilting isolationist, toward any kind of serious
engagement abroad.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
