<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-12 19:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4652 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-SPY-SATELLITE-PHOTOS-     10-12 0671
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPY-SATELLITE-PHOTOS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIANT LEAP FOR PRIVATE INDUSTRY: SPIES IN SPACE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Colo., South Africa)  (ART ADV: Photo NYT19 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By WILLIAM J. BROAD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   People passing through 14th and Constitution in Washington on
Sept. 30 had no idea that the world's first private spy camera was
orbiting 400 miles overhead. But the spacecraft snapped a picture
of the intersection in resolution sharp enough to show their cars,
as well as surrounding buildings, monuments and city bustle.
</P>
<P>
   Inaugurating a new commercial era, Space Imaging Inc., the
private company in Thornton, Colo., that built the spacecraft, made
the photograph public Tuesday. It is the world's first commercial
image from space whose sharpness rivals those of military spies in
the sky.
</P>
<P>
   The release caps many years of planning, delay and debate. The
emerging spy satellite industry holds promise for geographers,
urban planners and others, but it also poses knotty security and
privacy questions.
</P>
<P>
   Among other uses, the industry is expected to aid detection of
states trying to set off underground nuclear explosions in secret,
augmenting global sensors that can detect rumbles from clandestine
blasts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one of the most significant developments in the history
of the space age,'' said John E. Pike, head of space policy at the
Federation of American Scientists, a private group in Washington.
``It was revolutionary when it was available to the nuclear powers,
and one expects it to have similar potential now that it is
commercial.''
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration gave the go-ahead in 1994 for such
private space cameras. Space Imaging launched the first successful
satellite of the class on Sept. 24, after a similar effort failed
in April. Three other companies have announced plans to put similar
craft in orbit by the end of next year, and experts say that
perhaps a dozen or so may fly in the next decade.
</P>
<P>
   The new wave of commercial space cameras can see objects as
small as a few feet wide _ down to one meter _ and thus show cars,
homes, roads, boats, trees, buildings, pipelines, bridges, convoys,
tanks, jets and missiles _ but not individual people. The image
released Tuesday shows the Washington Monument, part of the White
House ellipse and buildings like the Department of Commerce and the
American History Museum of the Smithsonian Institution.
</P>
<P>
   The company said it was taking orders, but no images would be
sold until late this year. The Pentagon is expected to be a main
customer.
</P>
<P>
   Mark E. Brender, a Space Imaging spokesman, said prices would
range from $30 to $600 per square mile. He added that the minimum
order, at least for now, would be $1,000.
</P>
<P>
   Brender said the satellite was being run through calibration
tests, including photographing painted lines on a runway in Texas
that are exactly one meter wide ``so we can see precisely how
accurate the sensors are.''
</P>
<P>
   Eastman Kodak, a top contractor for military spy satellites,
built the camera and telescope system, whose main mirror is 27
inches wide.
</P>
<P>
   Space Imaging is a private company owned by the Lockheed Martin
Corp., which makes many of the military's spy satellites, and
E-Systems Inc., a unit of Raytheon that provides many of their
communication links. International investors include Mitsubishi and
Hyundai.
</P>
<P>
   An illustration of how spy satellites can expose plans for
secret explosions came in 1977 when South Africa was preparing to
detonate a nuclear device beneath the Kalihari desert. As Seymour
M. Hersh recounted the episode in ``The Samson Option'' (Random
House, 1991), an American spy satellite found signs of preparation
for an underground test.
</P>
<P>
   Alerted to the activity, President Jimmy Carter helped lead a
quiet campaign of international protest. South Africa, facing the
loss of diplomatic relations, scrapped the planned detonation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-12-99 1957EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
