<DOCNO> NYT19991012.0287 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-12 20:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4654 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-MENTALLY-ILL-VOTE-ART     10-12 1118
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MENTALLY-ILL-VOTE-ART-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VOTER PROJECT AIMS TO CREATE NATIONAL CONSTITUENCY OF THE MENTALLY
ILL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Va., Fla., Calif., Ga., Texas, Ore., N.Y.)  (ART ADV: Photos (NYT12,13) are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By ERICA GOODE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   On the morning of the 1996 presidential election, Sharon Denny
drove to the local polling place, an elementary school in her
Houston neighborhood. On the way, she gave herself a pep talk.
``This is so important,'' she told herself. ``And it makes such a
difference to our country. You have got to go vote.''
</P>
<P>
   But standing in line for the voting booth, Ms. Denny grew
anxious. What if she got inside and did not know what to do? What
if she punched the wrong holes? She broke into a cold sweat, she
recalls, and she remembers thinking, ``This is why they don't want
people with mental illness to vote, because what if I get up there
and I really want to vote for Bill Clinton and I don't, I end up
voting for Dole?''
</P>
<P>
   Defeated, Ms. Denny, who has suffered from manic-depression for
35 years, returned home, her ballot uncast, as it has been in every
election since she first registered to vote 15 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   But in next year's presidential election, Ms. Denny, 51, knows
that she will make it to the front of the line, and that she will
finally vote for the candidates and initiatives that she believes
in.
</P>
<P>
   She is certain of this because in August she joined the Mental
Health Voter Empowerment Project, an effort to create a nationwide
constituency of people with mental illness by locating potential
voters _ whether in hospitals, at advocacy events, in housing
projects, clinics or support groups _ registering them, educating
them about mental health issues and making sure they get to the
polls on Election Day 2000.
</P>
<P>
   It remains to be seen whether such an effort will be embraced by
politicians, especially in a climate where they must respond to
highly publicized incidents of violence involving mental illness,
like the death of Kendra Webdale, who was pushed off a New York
subway platform by a man suffering from schizophrenia.
</P>
<P>
   Complicating the issue further, many politicians have only
recently become aware of mental health as a political issue: a few
even believe, mistakenly, that the mentally ill cannot vote.
</P>
<P>
   A volunteer from the project will call to remind Ms. Denny to
vote, accompany her to the polling place and help her in the voting
booth, if necessary. Ms. Denny will arrive fully informed about the
candidates, and in particular about their stands on topics of
concern to the mentally ill, like equal health insurance coverage
for psychiatric illnesses, HMO reform, involuntary commitment and
financing for mental health programs and services.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 44 million Americans meet the diagnosis criteria
for some form of mental disorder, according to the National
Institute of Mental Health, and 5.6 million of those live with a
serious mental illness, like schizophrenia or manic depression.
</P>
<P>
   In theory, such numbers could represent a powerful voting bloc,
one any political candidate might feel obliged to court. But people
with severe mental illness, who often subsist on disability
benefits and may spend years bouncing from psychiatric hospitals to
jails to the streets, have been ignored by politicians because they
offered neither money nor votes.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Steele, who started the voter empowerment project in New
York City in 1994, said that the idea came to him after hearing a
speech by New York Gov. Mario Cuomo. In the speech, Steele
recalled, Cuomo said that his signing of a mental health bill was
``a good and compassionate thing,'' but that it was not smart
politics, because the mentally ill did not vote.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next four years, Steele, a veteran of 35 years spent in
state hospitals with a diagnosis of schizophrenia, registered an
estimated 28,000 New York City voters. And 15,000 of those newly
registered voters, he and his staff of volunteers learned through
their tracking efforts, cast their votes in the November 1998
election.
</P>
<P>
   Now the Mental Health Association of New York State, backed by a
federal grant and financing from a pharmaceutical company, is
expanding Steele's project throughout the state, and the Mental
Health Association of Houston and Harris County has launched its
own version of the program. The National Mental Health Association,
which has its headquarters in Alexandria, Va., will hold regional
training sessions for the project beginning this fall in Orlando,
Los Angeles and Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd like to have our issues be part of the 2000 debate,''
said Joseph Glazer, president of the New York association, ``and
the only way to get our issues to that level is to have a strong
base of registered voters and a sufficient voice so that the mental
health consumer community has to be listened to.''
</P>
<P>
   Steele compared the fight for political visibility to earlier
struggles by women and African-Americans: ``This is a civil rights
movement, like those that preceded it. Every one of those movements
began with access to the vote. Until we, the mental health
consumers, are seen as a constituency of consequence, we will not
close the holes in the mental health system.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Voter registration drives are nothing new, and many
organizations, at one time or another, have tried to increase
political participation among the disenfranchised, including people
with mental illness, by registering new voters.
</P>
<P>
   But such drives often are limited in effectiveness, the
organizers of the voter empowerment project contend, because they
rarely address the obstacles _ transportation, education, fear _
that prevent the newly registered from actually getting to the
polls or into the voting booth. Nor is the typical voter drive
conceived as part of a larger political strategy, one that in this
instance aspires to imitate influential interest groups like the
Christian Coalition, the gay rights movement or the environmental
lobby.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think that you're going to see mental health become a
single issue that's going to determine an election,'' said Clarence
Sundram, a human rights consultant in Albany and former director of
the New York State Commission on Quality Care. ``I don't think it's
going to have the hot-button effect like abortion has. But I think
the political organizing and advocacy that consumers do can and
does have an effect on laws that affect the lives of people with
mental illness.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   For a variety of reasons, consumer leaders argue, the emergence
of a national ``mental health'' constituency is more possible today
than at any time previously. While the stigma that accompanies a
diagnosis of mental illness persists, Americans as a whole are
better informed about the difficulties that confront those who
suffer from depression, manic-depression and other illnesses, in
part as the result of public figures ``coming out'' about their own
experiences.
</P>
<P>
   Most recently, Tipper Gore, the wife of Vice President Al Gore,
revealed that she received treatment for clinical depression after
their son, Albert, nearly died after being hit by a car in 1989 at
age 6. Activism on Capitol Hill by groups like the National
Alliance for the Mentally Ill, an organization of family members
and some consumers, has also helped raise awareness of mental
health issues.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the voices of consumers themselves have been
growing steadily stronger. What began in the early 1970s as an
``anti-psychiatry'' campaign by mental health system ``survivors,''
dedicated to exposing abuses in psychiatric hospitals and other
treatment institutions, has matured into a broader-based advocacy
movement, encompassing a range of viewpoints unified by a
commitment to improving the mental health system.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``In the early days a lot of people felt the need to free people
from psychiatry,'' said Joseph Rogers, executive director of the
National Mental Health Consumers Self-Help Clearinghouse, which in
August sponsored the National Summit of Mental Health Consumers and
Survivors, a meeting that drew 450 consumer leaders to Portland,
Ore. ``Now we still definitely have folks who feel that way, but
we've grown to include people who have had positive experiences as
well as negative experiences.'' Rogers said.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In many states, consumers have become part of the mental health
system itself, offering their perspective in a variety of official
capacities and running self-help services, like drop-in clinics,
and housing and employment programs.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In a 1996 survey of state mental health commissioners, Dr. Jean
Campbell of the University of Missouri School of Medicine found
that 91 percent reported that mental health consumers served on
state advisory boards; 85 percent said that consumers took an
active role in developing their state's mental health services.
``We're broadening and pushing the mental health system and making
it a better place,'' said Sally Zinman, executive director of the
California Network of Mental Health Clients.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Yet there remain barriers to turning local activism into a
national political presence, not the least of which is a lack of
wealthy donors, of the type who nurture the coffers of many
special-interest groups.
</P>
<P>
   The voter empowerment project, for example, is eligible for
federal grants and financing by corporations because of the Mental
Health Association's nonprofit status. But that status also
obligates the project to remain nonpartisan in its drive to
register voters. And while some organizations have given up their
nonprofit status in order to push a political agenda, most mental
health groups cannot afford to follow suit.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   At a recent training session for the project, held in
Binghamton, N.Y., the leaders of more than a dozen consumer groups
and mental health organizations learned how to find unregistered
voters _ events that offer food are a sure-fire draw, they were
told _ how to establish a confidential database with voters' names,
phone numbers and addresses, how to teach new voters about the
electoral process and how to organize events like candidates'
nights.
</P>
<P>
   But they were also instructed in educating people about mental
health issues while avoiding endorsement of particular candidates.
An educational pamphlet, for example, might inform project members
that a certain politician had referred to the mentally ill as
``mentally deficient,'' they were told, but the pamphlet could not
recommend voting against the candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Such constraints lead some to view the voter empowerment project
as a rather tepid political endeavor. ``It's Political Action
101,'' Rogers said. ``When you're actually supporting candidates,
that's real political action. My hope is that after that, people
will take the next step, which is to get really involved in
directly trying to affect policy.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Still, project organizers believe that the voters they register
``get it,'' and will use their ballots to support candidates with a
good record on mental health issues. And they hope that politicians
will eventually get the message, viewing them as a constituency to
be wooed.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Whether political candidates will want the votes of people with
mental illness is another matter. Rep. Jerrold Nadler, D-N.Y., who
has attended candidate events held by the empowerment project, said
he thinks an organized group of voters with mental illness would be
treated like any other voting bloc. ``Any constituency that has any
size and sticks together and votes together is one that people are
going to be interested in,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But lawmakers are under pressure from other directions, as well:
Constituents who react every time there is a widely publicized
incidence of violence involving mental illness.
</P>
<P>
   ``For every Tipper Gore, you have news coverage of some deranged
person committing a horrible act,'' Sundram said. ``Those things
reinforce negative stereotypes of people with mental illness.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet in virtually every such instance, consumer advocates
contend, violence can be traced to a lack of adequate services and
treatment. The mentally ill, studies have shown, are no more
violent than other groups, except when alcohol or drug abuse is
involved.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the stigma that clings to mental illness is not so
easily combatted. And it is a discomfort so powerful that it often
infects even those who themselves are ill.
</P>
<P>
   Many people who have been treated for mental illness believe,
incorrectly, that they cannot vote because they have been
hospitalized, or that they will lose their disability benefits if
they register. Only adult citizens who have been convicted of a
felony or declared mentally incompetent are ineligible to vote.
``I've been mentally ill for most of my life, and I didn't really
feel I had the right to vote,'' said Peter Lasher, a 44-year old
New York man who has been hospitalized repeatedly for
manic-depression.
</P>
<P>
   Lasher did not register to vote until four years ago, when he
was persuaded to do so by the voter empowerment project.
</P>
<P>
   He has now voted in several elections, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But he remains nervous about the process and is afraid of the
voting machines. He cast an absentee ballot in 1996 and said he
would do so again in the next presidential election _ once he
decides who to vote for. ``I sort of like Gore,'' he said, ``and I
like Tippy _ she's very pro-mental health.''
</P>
<P>
   Chris Lehane, a spokesman for the Gore presidential campaign,
said the campaign would welcome a chance to hear the empowerment
group's suggestions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The right to vote is obviously something that is very, very
important,'' he said, ``and we would do everything we can to
encourage those who are eligible to vote.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
