<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-12 20:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4659 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-SAME-OLD-SONG-FILM-2T     10-12 0853
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAME-OLD-SONG-FILM-2TAKES-$ADV17-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIS `SAME OLD SONG' IS, FOR HIM, ANYTHING BUT  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, OCT. 17) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By ALAN RIDING   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ White-haired, straight-backed, good humored, Alain
Resnais seemed quite amused by the idea that it took him 35 years
to have his first genuine box office hit.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, at 77, he could well afford to display nonchalance,
what with his place in the history of modern cinema having long
been assured by his remarkable early films ``Hiroshima Mon Amour''
and ``Last Year at Marienbad.'' Even so, the success of this
Frenchman's latest movie, ``On Connait La Chanson,'' or ``Same Old
Song,'' surprised him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always refuse to talk numbers,'' he said, chuckling as he
prepared to contradict himself, ``but my films usually sell about
300,000 tickets. I did not expect this film to sell 2.6 million in
France alone. I had warned the producer that it would not be easy
to export, but it also did well in Germany, Italy, Japan. Now let's
see what happens in the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of the charm of ``Same Old Song,'' which opened in New York
on Friday, derives from the way its six main characters lip-synch
popular French songs. They do not stop and break into song as they
might in a musical; rather, the songs flow from the action, the
lyrics arising out of normal conversation or of a character's
thinking aloud. The songs, which many French moviegoers know by
heart, nonetheless add a dimension of passion or poignancy or
absurdity.
</P>
<P>
   But will it be the same to understand the songs through
subtitles?
</P>
<P>
   ``My idea, my hope, is that it is not necessary to know the
songs beforehand in order to enjoy the movie,'' Resnais said.
``There is not one song in the film that does not have genuine
musical quality, so they're not there just because they were
hits.''
</P>
<P>
   The narrative tradition of La Chanson Francaise helps. Thus,
while Resnais and his screenwriters, Agnes Jaoui and Jean-Pierre
Bacri, did not build the movie's story line around the songs, they
had no trouble finding 36 songs or excerpts that fitted the twists
and turns of their plot.
</P>
<P>
   Among familiar voices heard are those of Maurice Chevalier,
Edith Piaf, Leo Ferre, Gilbert Becaud, Serge Gainsbourg, Eddy
Mitchell, Johnny Halliday and Julien Clerc.
</P>
<P>
   The idea is clever but not original, Resnais hurries to remind,
because he took his inspiration from the English writer Dennis
Potter, who used the same technique in ``The Singing Detective''
and ``Lipstick on Your Collar,'' both originally made for
television. His challenge, Resnais said, was to borrow without
copying.
</P>
<P>
   So, while Potter, who died in 1994, usually used entire songs,
Resnais rarely does. And the mood of ``Same Old Song'' is decidedly
lighter than much of Potter's work.
</P>
<P>
   ``Potter was extremely pessimistic,'' Resnais said. ``His are
films of a man who has suffered a great deal, who creates
characters who are paranoid. The songs are in total contrast with
the situations in the film. We tried to have the song always come
from inside the head of the character, to reflect the moment.''
</P>
<P>
   Resnais's story itself has the complexity of a soap opera. Odile
(Sabine Azema), who is married to dull Claude (Pierre Arditi), is
eager to buy an apartment being promoted by a real estate agency
headed by the smoothie Marc (Lambert Wilson). Odile's scholarly
sister, Camille (Ms. Jaoui), falls for Marc just as Marc's elderly
employee, Simon (Andre Dussollier), falls for Camille.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Odile's old flame, Nicolas ( Bacri), who has
reappeared in Paris, has Simon showing him apartments to rent.
</P>
<P>
   No one, however, is quite as he or she wants to be seen. Camille
triumphantly completes her doctoral thesis and then slumps into
depression. Simon pretends to be writing radio plays until he is
exposed as a lowly real estate agent. Nicolas puts on the airs of a
business executive while working as a chauffeur. Claude seems to be
a devoted _ and obedient _ husband but in fact has a mistress.
Odile behaves heartlessly, then is gripped by remorse. Only Marc
the cad remains true to himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never plan to leave a precise message,'' Resnais said over
coffee near the Paris Opera's Palais Garnier. ``Usually, I meet a
writer and say, `We have a producer; would you like to try to make
a film together?' The writer says yes or no, we meet, we look for
topics, they develop. In this case, some ideas came out about
appearances, about people who are very different the more you know
them, about the way you imagine them and the way they are. But
there was never the idea of, `Let's make a film about ... '''
</P>
<P>
   In that sense, Resnais is a very un-French director: he does not
write his own movies, he always works with a screenwriter, he does
not consider himself an auteur and he demands that the opening
credits of his films do (italics)not(end italics) include that all
too contagious formula: ``A Film by Alain Resnais.'' A French
dictionary of movie directors even posed the question: ``Does Alain
Resnais really exist?''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``The actors and writer are equally auteurs of a film,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Resnais is modest, but there is also reason for his modesty: he
never intended to become a director. Rather, he began his career in
the mid-1940s as a film editor working for the influential producer
Pierre Braumberger. And it was Braumberger who pushed him into
making short documentaries about the visual arts, notably ``Van
Gogh,'' Picasso's ``Guernica'' and ``Gauguin.''
</P>
<P>
   His 32-minute documentary about Auschwitz, ``Nuit et
Brouillard,'' reached a broader audience in 1956, but it was not
until two years later that he made his first feature film,
``Hiroshima Mon Amour,'' again at the insistence of producers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They wanted to make a film about the atomic bomb, mainly
because they had some yen they couldn't take out of Japan,'' he
recalled. He began working with the French documentary filmmaker
ChrisMarker. ``But we decided we had nothing to add to the two
existing documentaries, one English, one Japanese,'' Resnais said.
``They asked if I'd like to work with Francoise Sagan. I said fine,
but she was never approached. I then mentioned Marguerite Duras,
and she heard about it and contacted me. I happened to remark that,
while we were having tea, planes carrying A-bombs were flying
around the clock. Perhaps that would be one way of looking at the
film, with the bomb in the background.''
</P>
<P>
   From this conversation, Duras developed a script that dwelled on
a Japanese man and a French woman meeting in Hiroshima, both
carrying the scars of World War II, the woman because she had been
punished as a collaborator for having an affair with a German
soldier during the occupation, the man because of the A-bomb that
ended the war in Japan. The film was widely acclaimed as a
masterpiece.
</P>
<P>
   With his next film, ``Last Year at Marienbad,'' (1961) the
backing of a producer led Resnais to the novelist Alain
Robbe-Grillet and resulted in one of the most mysterious, and
discussed, movies of the 1960s, an unsettling dreamlike tale of a
man meeting a woman with whom he may _ or may not _ have had an
affair the previous year at a spa in Marienbad.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Resnais has generally followed the same routine: a
producer comes up with some money, he finds a writer, an idea for
an original screenplay is thrashed out and eventually a film is
made. In 1993 with ``Smoking/No Smoking,'' he broke the pattern by
turning Alan Ayckbourn's six-part play, ``Intimate Exchanges,''
into two movies.
</P>
<P>
   But the actor-writers invited to adapt the play, Ms. Jaoui and
Bacri, then became Resnais's writing team for ``Same Old Song'' (in
the meantime, they wrote and acted in ``Un Air de Famille''). Their
only condition was that they should also appear in Resnais's film.
</P>
<P>
   Resnais said he always took time to cast his films, but on this
occasion he took three actors _ Ms. Azema, Arditi and Dussolier _
with whom he had frequently worked before, along with the two
screenwriters and Wilson. They all then formed what is known
affectionately as the ``Resnais family,'' the close-knit team that
makes the film.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before shooting, he organizes individual work sessions with
each actor at his home during which a very precise agreement is
reached on the psychology of the character and the situations,''
Ms. Jaoui said.
</P>
<P>
   When it came to making ``Same Old Song,'' Wilson said the
biggest challenge was to avoid showing that he was going from
talking to lip-synching.
</P>
<P>
   ``As soon as you hear the music, it is hard to resist the
beat,'' he recalled. ``Ignoring the beat, even for something as
simple as lighting a cigarette, is much harder than I thought it
would be.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, two years after the movie's release in France, Resnais's
attention has now turned to his next movie, but as so often _ he
has only made 14 feature films in 40 years _ things are moving
slowly. And with Ms. Jaoui and Bacri busy on their own projects, he
has still to find a writer with whom he wants to work.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want someone who has written for theater,'' he said. ``I am
looking for a particular sound, the sound of someone who knows how
to manipulate words. Jaoui and Bacri can do that. But Agnes Jaoui
is now making her own film. She no longer needs a director. I
suspect that if I asked them, they'd say, `We'll make it
ourselves.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-12-99 2007EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
