<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UGA-RACE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Motion filed to bar UGA use of race
 &HT;    By Bill Rankin and Doug Cumming
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ White female plaintiffs want a judge to order the
University of Georgia to halt immediately the consideration of race
in admissions decisions.
</P>
<P>
   In a motion filed Tuesday, the women asked U.S. District Judge
B. Avant Edenfield of Savannah to issue an injunction against UGA.
If Edenfield agrees, the order would affect admissions decisions
for next year's freshman class.
</P>
<P>
   The motion is part of lawsuits that have been filed by four
women denied admission to UGA this school year. Their suit contends
UGA unconstitutionally discriminated against them by providing
preferences to male and African-American applicants.
</P>
<P>
   The motion asked Edenfeld to hold a hearing this month on an
injunction.
</P>
<P>
   On Sept. 30, UGA President Michael Adams said race would remain
a factor in evaluating some high school seniors who apply to UGA.
The university wants to be fair, accessible and representative of
the state's population, Adams said, explaining his reasons to
engage in a legal battle.
</P>
<P>
   Adams stands by that position, UGA spokesman Tom Jackson said
Tuesday. ``How we admit and why we think it is important is well
known,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The vast majority of admitted students, including most of the
blacks accepted as freshmen, will be accepted solely on academics,
Jackson said.
</P>
<P>
   For a relatively small percentage of applicants, admissions
officials employ the Total Student Index. The index is a list of
several factors, including the minority status of an applicant,
that give added weight to the student's academic standing.
</P>
<P>
   An injunction would not be relevant until March, when Total
Student Index decisions are made, Jackson said.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta lawyer Lee Parks, who represents the plaintiffs, noted
Tuesday that Edenfield gave UGA ``a clear indication on the
constitutional problems with the program. . . . It's important to
have this heard quickly so it doesn't affect another class.''
</P>
<P>
   Parks was referring to a ruling Edenfield issued in July in
which he said, ``UGA cannot constitutionally justify the
affirmative use of race in its admissions decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   In his motion, Parks said UGA is making admissions decisions
that ``overtly'' use race as a factor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Such racial quota systems and other racial favoritism is
unconstitutional,'' the motion said. ``(UGA's) present admissions
policy affords nonwhite applicants a huge preference.''
</P>
<P>
   Admissions decisions for the next school year are being made and
students are being notified on a ``rolling basis,'' the motion
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Accordingly, a need for immediate relief is present,'' it
said.
</P>
<P>
   UGA no longer uses gender in its admissions process. But Parks
asked Edenfeld to issue an order prohibiting its further use as
well. Otherwise, UGA will be free to return to its old ways, Parks
said.
</P>
<P>
   The state Attorney General's Office apparently is gearing up for
the legal battle. Last week, it hired as special assistant
attorneys general Mark Cohen, former Gov. Zell Miller's chief
counsel, and Mike Kaufman, both of the firm Troutman Sanders, and
Rodney Strong, the former director of the city of Atlanta's
minority business program.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Rankin and Doug Cumming write for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
