<HEADER>
A4671 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-INMATE-EXECUTION-COX     10-12 0399
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INMATE-EXECUTION-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Appeal of Georgia death-row decision declined
 &HT;    By Bill Rankin
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The U.S. Supreme Court let stand Georgia's refusal to
provide lawyers for death-row inmates who challenge their sentences
through civil lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the high court, without comment, declined to
consider the case of Exzavious Gibson. In 1996, Gibson became the
first prisoner in the modern history of the death penalty to be
denied a court-appointed lawyer in a habeas corpus lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Habeas lawsuits attack the constitutionality of sentences and
convictions after direct appeals are exhausted.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia is the only state in the country that does not provide
lawyers for death-row prisoners during this process. In February, a
deeply divided Georgia Supreme Court, by a 4-3 vote, ruled that
prisoners have ``no state or federal constitutional right to an
appointed lawyer'' in habeas proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   Gibson is now represented by lawyers from the Atlanta firm King
&AMP; Spalding. The American Bar Association, NAACP Legal Defense Fund
and the Southern Center for Human Rights filed briefs in support of
his U.S. Supreme Court petition.
</P>
<P>
   A transcript of Gibson's habeas hearing indicated he had little
idea of what was going on.
</P>
<P>
   Described as being borderline mentally retarded, Gibson told the
judge he did not know how to plead during a hearing that did not
require a plea. He offered no evidence.
</P>
<P>
   The hearing was ``one of the most unfair and one-sided
evidentiary hearings imaginable,'' Gibson's new lawyers, Joseph
Bankoff and Courtland Reichman, told the high court. ``The outcome
of this case, and those that are accumulating in its wake, is
shocking.''
</P>
<P>
   Since 1976, more than half _ 113 of 221 _ of Georgia's capital
cases affirmed by the state Supreme Court have been overturned
during habeas corpus review, the Southern Center for Human Rights
said in its brief to the high court.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is doubtful that the harmful errors in any of these cases
would have been detected and proven in the absence of counsel,''
the center's director, Stephen Bright, said.
</P>
<P>
   Gibson was convicted in 1990 of killing Douglas Coley, an
Eastman, Ga., grocer.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Rankin writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-12-99 2015EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
