<DOCNO> NYT19991012.0298 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-12 20:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4672 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-UNESCO-ELECTION-NYT &LR;      10-12 0841
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UNESCO-ELECTION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS UNESCO HOLDS JOB INTERVIEWS FOR TOP POST , 11 APPLY  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Romania, Sri Lanka, Australia, Saudia Arabia, Senegal,
Spain, Great Britain, Egypt, Japan, Trinidad and Tobago, The
Philippines, Hungary, France)   By ALAN RIDING   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ In a cautious move toward greater openness, UNESCO's
executive board will hold job interviews on Wednesday for the post
of the organization's director general.
</P>
<P>
   No less unusual, all 11 candidates have been campaigning
publicly, creating the impression that for the first time
personality and ideas may be as important as back-room political
deals.
</P>
<P>
   Political maneuvering has of course not stopped, with some
countries and regions openly backing candidates and rumors flying
of ``checkbook'' lobbying by at least two governments. But the
quality of the contenders may become more relevant than in past
years when the 58-nation board votes in secret next week to pick a
successor to Federico Mayor Zaragoza of Spain.
</P>
<P>
   The single candidate to be presented to UNESCO's 186-nation
general conference on Nov. 12 must win a majority.
</P>
<P>
   Diplomats said that although vote pledges were usually made only
for the first vote, it is possible that no winner will emerge from
the first four votes, on successive days, starting Monday. If that
happens, a runoff will be held between the two front-runners on
Oct. 22.
</P>
<P>
   What is at stake is a six-year term to run a 2,326-member staff,
a $544 million annual budget and a mandate as broad as the
Paris-based organization's full name: the United Nations Education,
Scientific and Cultural Organization.
</P>
<P>
   But the new director general will also take over a UNESCO still
plagued by bureaucracy, inefficiency and nepotism and widely viewed
as urgently needing an overhaul.
</P>
<P>
   Western diplomats say UNESCO today is nonetheless a far cry from
the left-leaning talk shop that the United States and Britain
abandoned in frustration in 1985. Britain rejoined in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, with Amadou Mahtar M'Bow of Senegal as director
general, UNESCO became particularly identified with promotion of a
so-called new world information order, which was aimed at breaking
a perceived monopoly of Western news organizations and which
Western governments viewed as an attempt at global censorship.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor, who has served two terms and is not seeking re-election,
immediately dropped that campaign and made some administrative
changes during his first term. But he has been increasingly
criticized in recent years, within the organization and among many
member governments, accused of being a tireless self-promoter and
of hiring friends and allies.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he'd left after one term, he'd have been hailed as an
excellent director general,'' one Western diplomat said.
</P>
<P>
   Ten months ago, eager to find a new director general more
answerable to UNESCO's members, the executive board instituted new
rules for picking a successor.
</P>
<P>
   Notably, candidates had to register before Sept. 10 _ in the
past, they could be nominated during the voting process _ and each
had to write a 2,000-word essay with his or her vision of the job
and submit to a 30-minute interview.
</P>
<P>
   The new rules brought some openness to the election process,
even though UNESCO's constitution still says candidates should be
nominated ``in confidence.'' As a result, apart from the customary
lobbying of UNESCO board members, the candidates have been giving
interviews _ and have set up their own Web sites _ with a view to
raising their public profiles.
</P>
<P>
   Ismail Serageldin, an Egyptian intellectual who is a vice
president of the World Bank, likes to describe himself as the
candidate of ``civic society'' and, as such, has been most active
in mobilizing outside support, with 43 Nobel Prize winners
endorsing his candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, Ghazi Algosaibi, Saudi Arabia's ambassador to
London, has the Arab League's backing. Coming from a country with a
monarchical form of government, he has been eager to portray
himself as a poet and liberal.
</P>
<P>
   Japan's ambassador to Paris, Koichiro Matsuura, starts with the
advantage that Japan is the largest contributor to UNESCO's budget,
to which he adds the promise of an efficient administration of
UNESCO. Gareth Evans, until recently Australia's foreign minister,
is a late candidate who is thought to enjoy considerable European
support. Neither Matsuura nor Evans is fluent in French, which may
be a liability.
</P>
<P>
   The next director general is widely expected to be one of those
four men, although seven other candidates will also have a chance
to make their pitch on Wednesday: Senake Bandaranaike, Sri Lanka's
ambassador to France; Ion Caramitru, Romania's culture minister;
Lawrence Carrington, a diplomat from Trinidad and Tobago; Daniel
Janicot, a French diplomat, currently UNESCO's deputy director
general; Rosario Manalo, the Philippines' deputy foreign minister;
Makaminan Makagiansar, Indonesia's delegate to UNESCO, and Pal
Pataki, a Hungarian diplomat.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
