<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-12 20:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4679 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-BRADLEY-CALIF-COX     10-12 0727
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRADLEY-CALIF-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bradley concentrates on California high-tech sector,
independents
 &HT;    By Ken Foskett
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Before unveiling his health care plan here two
weeks ago, Democrat Bill Bradley warmed up his crowd with some
basketball humor.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles Lakers coach Phil Jackson, a New York Knick
teammate, hadn't come West to make the Lakers NBA champions,
Bradley deadpanned. ``He came here because he is part of my
southern California presidential strategy.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley, back in California to raise money this week, needs all
the help he can get. With 434 delegates to the Democratic
nominating convention, the most in the country, California is the
Big Kahuna of the 2000 sweepstakes.
</P>
<P>
   But no where does Bradley's outsider campaign for president face
bigger obstacles, the latest hurdle being the expected AFL-CIO
endorsement of Vice President Al Gore today .
</P>
<P>
   Though unions are sagging elsewhere, California's 1.5 million
union members accounted for 29 percent of the state electorate in
1998, compared to 22 percent nationally.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley is also pushing up against the full weight of the state
Democratic Party, which was energized in 1998 with the landslide
victory of Gov. Gray Davis.
</P>
<P>
   Virtually every state or federal elected Democratic office
holder, from Davis on down, has endorsed Gore. The enthusiasm for
Gore, who made his 60th trip here as vice president this week,
extends to local activists, as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``To many of us, Bradley is an unknown quantity,'' says Elton
Hall, president of the Conejo Valley Democratic Club near Los
Angeles. ``With Gore you've heard speech after speech....People are
tired of dog and pony shows. They want to see substance and Gore
has really laid out his positions.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley also isn't benefiting from voter disaffection with
President Clinton, one of his primary appeals elsewhere. Clinton
and Gore are both popular in California.
</P>
<P>
   ``The economy is booming,'' says Keith Umemoto, a former
chairman of the state party's Asian &AMP; Pacific Islander caucus.
``Why sever that?''
</P>
<P>
   To counter the disadvantage he faces among Democratic loyalists,
Bradley has centered his California campaign around an appeal to
workers in the booming technology sector. He is using the Internet
to enlist ``thousands'' who follow the campaign through e-mail,
according to state director Gale Kaufman.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know that it is a lot to overcome,'' said Kaufman of Gore's
edge. ``My hope is we get a lot of people ... who have not been
working on campaigns before. That's where the energy comes from,
and there is no monopoly on that.''
</P>
<P>
   The strategy appears to have paid off in fund-raising. In the
first half of 1999, Bradley raised $2 million in California,
compared to Gore's $2.2 million. Bradley's donors include Hollywood
celebrities Dustin Hoffman and Michael Douglas.
</P>
<P>
   The dynamics of California's open primary on March 7, however,
both help and hurt Bradley. Only registered Democratic voters count
toward picking convention delegates. If Bradley captures
independents or even Republicans in the primary, they won't help
him win delegates.
</P>
<P>
   But delegates are allocated proportionally.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a no-loser for Bradley,'' says Bob Mulholland an
advisor to the state party. ``You can leave the state a distant
second and still head to the convention with 100 delegates.''
</P>
<P>
   With its ethnically diverse electorate, California has become
the epitome of interest-group politics. Ethnic minorities now
outnumber whites in California, according to the latest estimates,
and California's Latino voters -- 14 percent of the electorate --
are generating new political energy.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has aggressively courted Latinos and has the endorsement of
Lt. Gov. Cruz Bustamante. Gore has also been courting
African-Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Alice Huffman, a national party member, arranged for Gore to
meet about 70 African-American leaders last month. Bradley taught
at Stanford University after he left the Senate in 1997. He has
made two major campaign trips here. And he hopes strong showings in
Iowa and New Hampshire will give him momentum in California and
other early primary states.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Foskett writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
