<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-12 20:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4685 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-BLUE-BAUER-COX     10-12 0365
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLUE-BAUER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bauer taps Atlantan to chair his campaign
 &HT;    By Mark Sherman
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Republican presidential candidate Gary Bauer on
Tuesday named Atlanta businessman Ronald Blue his new national
campaign chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Blue replaces Charles Jarvis, who left Bauer's campaign amid
concernthat Bauer was spending too much time behind closed doors
with a young, single woman.
</P>
<P>
   Blue has known Bauer for 15 years through their work on
conservative family values issues. He said he examined Jarvis'
concerns and found them without merit. ``Several of us . . . sat
down and looked at the facts and said this is all smoke, there's no
fire there at all,'' Blue said in a telephone interview.
</P>
<P>
   Jarvis, now an adviser to GOP candidate Steve Forbes, never
publicly accused Bauer of having an affair, which Bauer in any case
denied. His aides feared the tumult would damage his campaign among
the religious conservatives whose support he is seeking.
</P>
<P>
   Blue said his experience as a financial planner and investment
manager did not prepare him for politics. ``As a businessman,
things run with structure and organization and have processes in
place,'' he said. ``Political campaigns, in my experience so far,
seem to run from crisis to crisis. Things tend to get distorted.''
</P>
<P>
   Blue, 57, said he will serve in an advisory capacity and will
remain with his business, Ronald Blue and Co., in Atlanta. Bauer's
campaign is his first involvement in national politics.
</P>
<P>
   Blue had been serving as Bauer's finance chairman. ``The thing
that has pleased me is Gary's ability to raise money, especially
from small donors,'' Blue said.
</P>
<P>
   While paying homage to the fund-raising powerhouse of George W.
Bush's campaign, Blue said Bauer has enough money to remain in the
game. ``You never know what's going to happen in politics,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Blue is on the board of the Family Research Council, the family
values group Bauer led until he decided to run for president.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Sherman writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
