<DOCNO> NYT19991012.0306 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-12 20:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4686 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      10-12 0771
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS  COLUMN : RESPECT IS NOT A BASEBALL ISSUE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By GEORGE VECSEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ They were caught in an apparently fatal tail spin only
three weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   They were shunted by Major League Baseball to the late, late
show to satisfy an arriviste franchise out west.
</P>
<P>
   They have been denigrated by their manager as not among the
brightest of humankind.
</P>
<P>
   Now the Bizarre If Not Amazing Mets have returned to where the
craziness all began.
</P>
<P>
   Last evening they were due to play the Braves in the first game
of the National League championship series with a gathering
rainstorm threatening to disrupt matters.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets were back in Turner Field, insisting that they are not
the same becalmed outfit that lost three straight to the Braves
here, then three straight in Philadelphia, then two of three to the
Braves in New York. Some of the Mets have acted as if those numbers
were invented. They actually happened.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets did not get respect from baseball, which put its first
two games on at 11 p.m., beyond the reach of younger fans. It is
all well and good for Commissioner Bud Selig to say they
``agonized'' over the decision. The fact is, they did it.
</P>
<P>
   For all that, baseball lucks out again, with East Coast teams,
four storied franchises with great angles no matter who wins.
Atlanta-Boston? There are old curmudgeons up in Boston who haven't
gone to a game since the Braves left town. They would go out and
cheer Chipper Jones as if he were Bob Elliott reincarnated.
</P>
<P>
   As for the Mets, so much has happened to them since their slump
that it almost seems like another age. The manager has had his mood
swings _ often within seconds of each other _ from fatalistic to
antagonistic to grandiose. The players have failed in the clutch
and performed in the clutch. Still, the Mets are with us.
</P>
<P>
   Did the Braves' superiority have any carryover in this series?
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, I hope none of that comes into play,'' Bobby
Valentine said last night. ``But it's probably some factor there
that you have to factor in. I heard Joe Torre said, `You're
supposed to rip up what happened in the past once you get to these
playoffs.' I like that statement a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   There was also the baseball fact of life that good pitching
stops good hitting, as proven by the way Pedro Martinez of Boston
shut down the slugging Indians when he materialized in the middle
of another slugfest in the deciding American League game Monday
night.
</P>
<P>
   At the risk of sounding like McGuire in the movie, ``The
Graduate,'' who pompously intoned that the future lay in plastics,
one could solemnly state that the future of any given playoff
series lies in pitching. The high level of
Maddux-Millwood-Glavine-Smoltz could shut down a hot streak in a
hurry.
</P>
<P>
   There has been a great deal of talk generated by Valentine, who
has had it both ways, saying the Braves do not respect the Mets,
then noting that the Braves have no need to respect the Mets.
</P>
<P>
   This is essentially silly business because ``respect'' is really
something out of the contact sports, the kind of thing Pat Riley or
Bill Parcells would tell their troops to inspire them to throw
their bodies around.
</P>
<P>
   Respect is really not a baseball concept. There could be all
kinds of respect, but when a Martinez starts bending his pitches
around the sharp corners of a strike zone, what's respect got to do
with it?
</P>
<P>
   The players are all in the same union, and it shows. The hang
around the batting cage and chat with each other _ and why not?
They could be changing sides, voluntarily, in the next year or two,
so why antagonize a future teammate or a current lodge member?
</P>
<P>
   Just a glimpse of the batting cage before last Saturday's game
between the Yankees and Texas showed a dozen Hispanic players from
both sides chatting among themselves. When the game began, the
players would do their best to beat each other, but there was no
missing the pride and respect ball players generally have for each
other.
</P>
<P>
   Valentine's acerbic comments may reflect the tensions he
generates. Other players and managers tend to get huffy when he is
mentioned, so he broadens it into a general condition.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a joke, a joke, the lack-of-respect angle,'' Bobby Cox,
the Braves' manager, said Monday. ``I don't know where that came
from. They've got our respect. They have a lot of good players on
that team and they're good guys. I like them.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mets have survived their low moments. Here they are, with a
chance to win back some of the perceived loss of respect, external
or internal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
