<SLUG> BC-HARVARD-SETTLEMENT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARVARD TO PAY MILLIONS IN WORKER SETTLEMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE E. LEWIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMBRIDGE, Mass. _ Harvard University has agreed to pay millions
of dollars in back pay and benefits to 300 to 500 employees who
were misclassified as casual workers.
</P>
<P>
   The university also will offer a significant number of workers
from the group both full-time employment and monetary compensation.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement, announced Tuesday by Harvard and the 3,600-member
Harvard Union of Clerical &AMP; Technical Workers, comes two months
after the university publicly acknowledged misclassifying the
workers, despite a union contract requiring that after three months
on the job casual employees must be reclassified as full-time. That
contract, as well as a longstanding university policy, defines a
casual employee as anyone who works less than 17.5 hours a week.
</P>
<P>
   Anne Taylor, general counsel and vice president of Harvard, said
the total payout would be ``in the millions, but exactly how much
no one knows at this time . . . This is a creative solution, a fair
solution, and an imaginative solution.''
</P>
<P>
   Union president Adrienne Landau said she was ``encouraged'' by
Harvard's willingness to fix the problem. ``We were able to be our
usual tenacious, but highly civil, selves because the university
recognized that this was an important issue,'' she said, ``and it
knew this agreement was the right thing to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Union director Bill Jaeger, who helped draft the agreement,
described the measure as ``an approximation'' of the benefits and
pay workers have lost since 1995. He acknowledged that while a
handful of workers had been on the casual or contingent list
longer, a compromise was reached to cover four years because a
majority of the workers had been denied the benefits of full-time
employment within that period. Jaeger added that the university had
some concerns about the challenge of recreating old pay and
compensation records.
</P>
<P>
   ``In many cases, the rate of pay for these workers was not
regulated. So, they received substandard pay,'' said Jaeger. ``They
were also shut out of a comprehensive benefits package.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreement, compensation will be based on a formula
that assesses the number of hours a casual employee worked, as well
as length of service, dating back the four years when, Jaeger said,
the bulk of the violations occurred. Jaeger said compensation would
vary from a lump sum of about $250 to a maximum of $12,000 that
will paid to workers over three years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, we tried to push (the time period) back as far as
possible to make this right for as many people as possible,''
Jaeger added. ``So this was a compromise. To my mind, it was a good
and fair compromise.''
</P>
<P>
   The issue of misclassification of temporary or casual workers
has been pushed to the forefront in recent years by high-tech
workers and by professional employees who claim they were kept on
projects for years, without benefits or job security.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, a federal study found that 29 percent of some 1.3
million temporary employees had been at the same job for a year or
longer, up from 25 percent of 1.1 million temporary workers in
1995. Such workers, often described as perma-temps, have been the
focus of a number of highly publicized lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am very proud of this (agreement),'' said Taylor. ``There
certainly has been activity in the legal world surrounding this
issue, but (Harvard) is one of the first employers to say, `We're
going to belly up to the bar and address it.' ''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
