u s BC-BBA-MATCHUPS-NYT &LR;      10-12 1337
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MATCHUPS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICAN LEAGUE MATCHUPS _ REDSOX VS. YANKEES 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; YANKEES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   PITCHING:
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees rested for three days after sweeping the Texas
Rangers in the division series, giving Manager Joe Torre plenty of
time to line up his rotation. Orlando Hernandez goes in Game 1, and
whether he is 64 or 24, Hernandez will be a challenge for the
Boston hitters: El Duque has demonstrated a penchant for big games,
having generated an 0.41 earned run average in his first three
postseason starts. David Cone pitches in Game 2 and is scheduled to
throw Game 6 _ both of which are to be played in Yankee Stadium _
and though he was inconsistent in the last months of the regular
season, he was always good at home. His ERA of 1.90 in Yankee
Stadium was the best home mark in the American League this season.
Roger Clemens will throw Game 3 _ and Game 7, if necessary, with
Andy Pettitte in Game 4. Mariano Rivera, the closer, hasn't allowed
a run since July 21. The Yankees' biggest concern now is the
effectiveness of those five pitchers (Mike Stanton, Allen Watson,
Ramiro Mendoza, Hideki Irabu and Cone) who did not work in the
first round. Stanton and Mendoza, in particular, are more effective
with regular game action. Stanton hasn't pitched since Oct. 2,
Mendoza since Oct. 1.
</P>
<P>
   OFFENSE:
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees had an efficient attack in the division series
against Texas, scoring 14 runs in three games, and again they
showed the patience that is the foundation of their offense,
forcing the Texas starters to go deep into pitch counts and tire in
the middle innings. That strategy won't be as effective against the
Red Sox, except when Pedro Martinez pitches, because the Boston
manager, Jimy Williams, is quick to call on his relievers when Bret
Saberhagen and Ramon Martinez pitch. Paul O'Neill is going to try
to play in spite of his broken rib, but he really doesn't feel as
if it affects his swing as much as it does his defense. Chuck
Knoblauch, Derek Jeter, Darryl Strawberry and Bernie Williams all
are swinging the bat well, and Ricky Ledee seems poised for a
breakout. Joe Girardi, who would be the starting catcher in four of
the seven games, batted .367 with runners in scoring position, and
something always seems to be happening when he's hitting: He's the
most likely Yankee to drop a sacrifice bunt and to attempt a
hit-and-run.
</P>
<P>
   DEFENSE:
</P>
<P>
   O'Neill's status will have a significant impact on the Yankees'
defense. If his injury forces him to the bench, then Torre will
play either Ledee or Shane Spencer in right field, and while
Spencer might have more experience in right than Ledee, neither is
as good as O'Neill. Right field in Fenway Park might be the most
difficult outfield position in all of baseball, with its low,
curving fence from right field to right-center, and its huge
expanse. Bernie Williams played terrifically in center in the
division series, Chuck Knoblauch's throwing problems were no
problem, and the Rangers never had enough runners to try to exploit
the inability of the Yankees' starters to hold potential
base-stealers.
</P>
<P>
   ON THE BASES:
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees did not attempt a single stolen base in the series
against Texas, a reflection of Ivan Rodriguez's throwing ability,
as well as the Yankees' passiveness in base-stealing situations.
Joe Torre, the Yankees' manager, almost uniformly sends runners
from first, or first and second, when the count is 3 balls and 1
strike or 3-2 with less than two outs, and he does like to
hit-and-run with Girardi and Scott Brosius.
</P>
<P>
   X-FACTOR:
</P>
<P>
   O'Neill took batting practice Tuesday under the scrutiny of
about 20 cameramen and 100 reporters. Every move he makes will be
examined, dissected, and if his injury appears to cause him any
distress and affect his swing, his base-running or his defense, the
Red Sox surely will look to take advantage.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; RED SOX &LR;
</P>
<P>
   PITCHING:
</P>
<P>
   Boston essentially has two separate staffs _ Pedro Martinez, and
the rest. When Martinez pitches, a reliever or two might be
required for the last few outs; when Martinez doesn't pitch,
everybody is available, and Manager Jimy Williams has shown a
willingness to use anybody at any time. Williams went to his
bullpen 16 times in the five-game series against the Cleveland
Indians. His bullpen might be void of stars, but it is deep and
versatile, and the relievers are all accustomed to pitching in any
situation. Derek Lowe throws a hard, sinking fastball and generated
3.17 groundballs for every fly ball, an extraordinary ratio. Rich
Garces was 5-1 with a 1.55 earned run average in 30 appearances in
the regular season, throwing fastballs and breaking balls. Rheal
Cormier is left-handed _ the only left-hander in the Boston bullpen
_ and this year, he held left-handed hitting opponents to a .198
batting average; Williams figures to save him for Paul O'Neill,
Bernie Williams and Tino Martinez in the late innings. Bryce Florie
throws sinkers, Tom Gordon fastballs and curves and Pat Rapp will
try to spot his pitches. Ramon Martinez, the Game 2 starter, is
recovering from shoulder surgery, and from one start to the next,
the Red Sox aren't sure if he'll have his good fastball and
command.
</P>
<P>
   OFFENSE:
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox do not really hit for a high average, as do the
Texas Rangers. They don't have the power of the Indians, the
Seattle Mariners or the Yankees. They had the fewest stolen bases
of any team in the league, and their average of 3.70 pitches per
plate appearance is mediocre for a contending team. They drew more
than 100 fewer walks than the Yankees. Nomar Garciaparra, their
shortstop, might be the only name from their lineup vaguely
recognizable to casual fans who will be watching. But they are a
dangerous team, their confidence apparent in the production they
generated and the swings they took against the Indians. Jason
Varitek, the catcher, is aggressive and confident at the plate, and
John Valentin smashed three home runs in two games against the
Indians. Mike Stanley is always dangerous, and Troy O'Leary broke
out of a slump with two home runs and seven RBIs in Game 5 against
Cleveland, after the Indians intentionally walked Garciaparra twice
to get to him.
</P>
<P>
   DEFENSE:
</P>
<P>
   Garciaparra is among the best shortstops in baseball, and
Varitek is _ to use a scout's phrase _ empathetic with pitchers,
which is to say that he will draw the best out of his battery
mates. The rest of the Boston infield is poor, the second baseman
Jose Offerman weak at turning double plays, Valentin's range at
third greatly reduced by injuries and Mike Stanley adept at digging
balls out of the dirt at first but rangeless. The Boston outfield
is strong, with O'Leary comfortable playing the Green Monster in
Fenway Park, Darren Lewis capable of covering lots of ground in
center and Trot Nixon solid in right field. Opposing teams have had
success running against Pedro Martinez, swiping 21 bases in 31
attempts.
</P>
<P>
   ON THE BASES:
</P>
<P>
   Most of the Red Sox movement on the bases comes with hit-and-run
plays, and when runners are on the move with full counts. They had
the fewest steals in the league, with Jose Offerman (18 steals) and
Garciaparra (14) responsible for about half of those.
</P>
<P>
   X-FACTOR:
</P>
<P>
   On paper, the Red Sox have no chance. The Yankees' pitchers are
rested, in line, their offense is more potent, they are rich with
postseason experience, and in the late innings, they have
baseball's best reliever, Mariano Rivera, who can enter in the
eighth and finish a game. But there's something strange about this
Red Sox team, some mystical weirdness following them. They are
playing hard, playing well, and they are not afraid of the Yankees,
having won eight of 12 games from them during the regular season.
If you believe in The Curse of the Bambino, then you might believe
that because the Red Sox won the first World Series of the century,
they are destined to win the last.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-12-99 2029EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991012.0310 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-12 20:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4690 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-DISCO-MUSIC-2TAKES-$A     10-12 1244
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DISCO-MUSIC-2TAKES-$ADV17-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISCO LIVES! ACTUALLY, IT NEVER DIED  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, OCT. 17) 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Please note subslug for SATURDAY-NIGHT-FEVER)  
(spelling of Trammps cq) 
(af) 
 By JON PARELES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When the staged version of ``Saturday Night Fever'' opens on
Thursday at the Minskoff Theater, it should, by rights, look as
quaint as the 1950s of ``Grease'' did in the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   ``Saturday Night Fever,'' the movie released in 1977, marked the
apogee of disco, a lucrative moment in pop that quickly generated a
backlash, a record-business crash and a widespread repudiation.
Twenty years is the usual nostalgia gap, the time it takes for fond
memory to replace the embarrassment of succumbing to a long-gone
trend; hence the Broadway-bound ``Saturday Night Fever,'' despite
negative reviews of its London production.
</P>
<P>
   But while there's plenty of nostalgia attached to disco, the
music doesn't seem distant. In all but name, the disco era never
ended. Only the haircuts are obsolete.
</P>
<P>
   Dance music, disco's current alias, still fills clubs from here
to Tokyo, and the disco beat, that steady thump that disk jockeys
call four-on-the-floor, is still the music's common denominator,
unsubtle but supremely effective. Disco songs from the late 1970s
are all over movie soundtracks, period or not. And beyond its
persistence as dance music, disco has stayed current in more
stealthy ways.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly everything that was initially reviled in disco _ its
monotonous rhythm, its gimmicky sounds, its disposability, its
superficiality, its emphasis on physical function over literary
meaning, its notion of music as pure dumb fun, not to mention its
gay undercurrents _ has become entrenched in the pop mainstream,
from the Backstreet Boys to Mary J. Blige to Ricky Martin to Beck.
Disco, once mocked for being shallow and synthetic, has turned into
roots.
</P>
<P>
   Officially, disco rose fast and burned out faster. The music had
been percolating since the mid-1970s at gay men's parties and
clubs, where disk jockeys sought out uptempo soul songs that pulled
people onto the dance floor. They favored a more basic beat than
the crafty, jumpy rhythms of great early-1970s funk, and they
appreciated singers who were melodramatic to the point of
campiness; they also liked instrumental passages and interludes of
pure rhythm that they could stretch out (using two copies on two
turntables) to keep people moving.
</P>
<P>
   As disco taste grew focused, producers working out of basement
studios and selling albums from the trunks of their cars started
catering to the new niche. Major labels followed, pushing songs
onto the radio and up from the gay underground. The disco beat
became premeditated rather than fortuitous: four-on-the-floor,
saved from tedium by syncopated bass lines and sparks from Latin
percussion. But it was also cosmopolitan, embracing European
electronics, funk rhythm guitar, big-band arrangements and carnival
beats.
</P>
<P>
   Before long, disco became glamorous. It was the music of the jet
set, cordoned off behind velvet ropes for the fashion elite in New
York clubs like Studio 54, yet as accessible as a record store or a
radio for those who wanted to fantasize.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it generated an angry reaction from some of the people
outside the ropes: blue-jeaned rock fans who wanted to see their
music as natural, authentic and handmade.
</P>
<P>
   Long after ``Pet Sounds'' and ``Sgt. Pepper's Lonely Hearts Club
Band'' staked out the recording studio as a place to create
illusions, most rock still hid the artifices of recording and tried
to make songs sound like bigger, better versions of concert
performances. But disco, as its name declared, made the recording
paramount.
</P>
<P>
   The music had to sound good from the turntable, not the stage
(where most disco performers ended up singing along with their
taped studio tracks). It was made to be canned, and no one
pretended otherwise. Rock had spent a decade insisting it was art,
not an act, and then disco called its bluff.
</P>
<P>
   Disco challenged rock's star system, which counted on fans'
loyalty for the length of a performer's career. Dancers were
attached only to the song and the beat, listening to the invisible
voice hired to front the band but not curious about its past or
future.
</P>
<P>
   Disco had haphazard effects on careers. Except for a handful of
performers like Donna Summer, who managed to escape facelessness,
disco was a world of one-hit wonders, while true fans learned to
follow producers like Giorgio Moroder or Nile Rodgers or Gamble and
Huff. With the right beat and the right song, disco offered a way
for minorities and pop outcasts _ blacks, Hispanics, gays, older
singers, fat singers _ to be heard, however briefly, in the
mainstream.
</P>
<P>
   Disco revived the fortunes of vocal groups like the Trammps and
the Manhattans, but it sandbagged the best 1970s funk bands like
the Meters, whose music was compulsively danceable but not
rudimentary enough for disco use. It was one of rock's periodic
simplifications, a dark ages for rhythm even as more fans decided
that they should be dancing. It took some time before dance-music
producers figured out how to rebuild some of what had been thrown
away.
</P>
<P>
   Disco was denounced as formulaic, mechanical, contrived,
forgettable: all true, but all irrelevant as lights flashed and
mirror-balls rotated. Actually, there was plenty of variety in
disco, which made hits out of songs as diverse as the Cameroonian
funk of Manu Dibango's ``Soul Makossa,'' Thelma Houston's
gospel-charged ``Don't Leave Me This Way,'' the ditsy pop novelty
of A Taste of Honey's ``Boogie Oogie Oogie,'' the orchestrated soul
of the O'Jays' ``Use ta Be My Girl'' and the severe minimalism of
Kraftwerk's ``Trans-Europe Express.''
</P>
<P>
   Even after disco became a fixed commercial genre, some bands,
like Chic and Dr. Buzzard's Original Savannah Band, still tried to
slip ideas and ironies onto the dance floor.
</P>
<P>
   With groups like the Village People dispensing gay-culture
double entendres, disco represented an unspoken detente between
straight and gay styles: don't ask, don't tell, just dance. The
love story in the ``Saturday Night Fever'' movie gave disco a
heterosexual face and insisted that, yes, straight men could dance
to it.
</P>
<P>
   With the reassuring, white-suited images of John Travolta and
the three Brothers Gibb, the ``Saturday Night Fever'' soundtrack
album _ part Bee Gees, part best-of-disco compilation _ became the
all-time best-selling album until Michael Jackson's ``Thriller''
came along in 1982. Rock stars like David Bowie and the Rolling
Stones were already putting on the disco thump like a new polyester
shirt.
</P>
<P>
   But as disco radio stations appeared and the recording business
jumped on the disco bandwagon, listeners outsmarted merchants. They
realized that most disco songs were about as durable as the
one-night stands that started on the dance floor, and that it was
more sensible (and cheaper) to keep up with the latest songs on the
radio, or in the clubs, than to collect them.
</P>
<P>
   Record companies saw sales plummet from 726.2 million albums,
singles and tapes in 1978 to 575.6 million in 1982; the Grammy
Award category for Best Disco Recording lasted exactly one year
(won by Gloria Gaynor's ``I Will Survive'') before it was quietly
terminated. Diehard rockers thought they had won the war of style,
and cued up ``Stairway to Heaven'' one more time.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Little did they know. Disco had shown people a good time again,
free of rock's earnestness. It was a return to utilitarian music,
doing its job with as little pretension as a pop-up toaster, and it
was a harbinger of pop's increasing specialization. Punk, which
arose around the same time, acquired the monopoly on rock's noisy,
rebellious impulses, but disco grabbed the franchise for physical
pleasures and party fun, not something the pop audience wanted to
renounce.
</P>
<P>
   While mid-1970s disco hits now conjure a pre-AIDS age of
hedonism, explaining their popularity as soundtrack tunes, the 4/4
thump has survived as a pop mating signal.
</P>
<P>
   Disco had also suggested, at its best moments, a zone of
dance-floor democracy where class, race and sexual preference
didn't matter (though youth and beauty did). It was a plastic
utopia, but it was still a nice place to visit, and dancers and
listeners still did.
</P>
<P>
   Through the 1980s, the primitive synthesizers and drum machines
that had been embraced by disco producers grew more complex and
flexible, allowing the music to grow ever more mechanized and less
realistic, an excursion into a sonic neverland.
</P>
<P>
   Styles jelled and acquired their own names with accelerating
specialist snobbery: electro, hi-N.R.G., Latin freestyle, house,
techno. Even industrial rock, brandishing punk attitude and
dystopian science-fiction concepts, was steady-thumping canned
music for use on the dance floor.
</P>
<P>
   Punk-era rockers like Blondie and Talking Heads allowed
themselves to use four-on-the-floor after the declared death of
disco; performers in all sorts of genres let their songs reappear
as remixes with a steady dance beat. Through her rise in the 1980s,
Madonna never tagged herself as disco, but her music bubbled out of
clubs to reach the pop charts, and her appreciative scanning of gay
culture (leading to her appropriation of rituals like voguing) made
her the disco queen of the decade.
</P>
<P>
   The disk jockeys' judgment that music could, and should, still
be manipulated after it was recorded _ in dance-floor segues and
overlays and in extended, rhythm-happy remixes _ was not about to
be forgotten. It surfaced quickly at the block parties in the South
Bronx where hip-hop was being born.
</P>
<P>
   Disk jockeys toyed with funk records and current disco hits; the
bass line for Chic's ``Good Times'' resurfaced on the first hit rap
record, the Sugar Hill Gang's ``Rapper's Delight'' in 1979. With
disco and hip-hop, the seeming permanence of recordings was
thoroughly destabilized; there would always be the possibility of
another version, another mix.
</P>
<P>
   Because it existed primarily as canned music, disco easily
anticipated the music-video era. Nearly every band that wants a hit
now has to can itself for music video _ in the process,
lip-synching over its prerecorded music track like a disco diva
doing a ``track date'' appearance. What seemed artificial as the
1970s ended has become unremarkable, just the way things are done.
</P>
<P>
   Handmade rock hasn't disappeared by any means. Onstage, at
least, it's still a way of life for punk, hard-rock, country and
rap-metal bands. But in the 1990s it has to compete with music that
uses disco methods: blunt repetition, synthetic sounds, mechanized
rhythms, puppet singers.
</P>
<P>
   Rock bands don't necessarily rule out any of those methods in
the studio; after all, they all own drum machines, too. The disk
jockey's attitude toward sonic information has prevailed, as both
working bands and lone producer-arranger-songwriters agree that
what comes through the speakers is the only thing that matters, and
that anything in the archives of recorded sound is fair game. That
attitude prevailed by way of hip-hop, not disco, but the result is
the same.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, hip-hop has regularly plundered disco for material;
Wyclef Jean even went back to ``Saturday Night Fever'' to remake
the Bee Gees' ``Stayin' Alive'' as ``We Trying to Stay Alive.''
</P>
<P>
   Where hip-hop insists on ``keepin' it real'' _ despite its
studio-manipulated soundscapes and stylized rhymes _ disco's legacy
is a happy suspension of reality. Voices, lyrics and pop structures
tethered 1970s disco to everyday life. But in clubs, disk jockeys
increasingly stripped away those signposts, narrowing the music
down to the beat, the hook, the texture, working for direct
physiological and psychological effect.
</P>
<P>
   Current electronica acts like the Chemical Brothers and disk
jockey-programmers like Paul Oakenfold put together songs only to
splinter them when they perform; they make a chord pulsate and
expand until it fills a club, then cue a drum-machine salvo to make
dancers shout almost by reflex. The music is canned and repetitive,
but it ignores permanence or repeatability; it's about immediate
experience, about getting lost in the euphoric present.
</P>
<P>
   It's a primal approach to music, one that has nothing to do with
reflection or judgment or posterity. Despite its tackiness and its
cliches, its crassness and its silliness, disco in the 1970s was
reaching for something that rock, with its increasing
self-consciousness, had almost given up. Jungle boogying and booty
shaking and loving to love, disco chanted inane mantras.
</P>
<P>
   But it restored pop's connection to direct physical release with
a beat so elementary that anyone could feel it. By reminding the
pop audience that it could simply enjoy the sensations of the
moment, disco made its own moment last far longer than anyone could
have guessed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
