<HEADLINE>
ONLINE COMPANIES TRY TO DEVELOP POLITICAL E-CLOUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN RICHMAN and MICHAEL PAULSON  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Internet companies have taken Wall Street by storm,
and now they're trying to do the same in the nation's capital.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the biggest names in Internet commerce and services _
including Seattle's Amazon.com _ have lined up behind the effort.
America Online, eBay, Excite &LR; Home and Yahoo! are among the other
companies joining forces as NetCoalition.com.
</P>
<P>
   Their mission: influence decisions affecting companies whose
business is purely Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Uppermost on the current agenda: Keep cyberspace free of taxes
and regulation; stop legislation that could curb growth.
</P>
<P>
   Their lobbying aims to cut a distinctly different swath in
high-tech political opinion making in Washington. That's partly
because the companies don't think the efforts of big, broad-based
firms like Microsoft necessarily represent their views.
</P>
<P>
   But the companies themselves also don't fit the profile of
industrial clout in the nation's capital. Internet executives are
often twentysomethings. And the companies they run may be small,
start-up enterprises that have yet to show a dime of profit _ not a
prescription for getting attention in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The effort got off the ground in July, and in recent weeks
Amazon government affairs counsel David Gabrieli and the lobbyist
for NetCoalition.com have been meeting with members of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goal is to become part of the process in D.C., to bring
the pure-play Internet perspective to D.C., and to act as a
resource to Congress and the executive branch,'' said Gabrieli, who
represents Amazon.com, the world's largest Internet retailer and
one of the e-commerce companies that hasn't yet turned a profit.
</P>
<P>
   Congressional staff members said the Internet industry needs to
court members of Congress from its home states, who are its natural
advocates, as well as members of key committees, such as Commerce,
that regulate issues of importance to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very positive step,'' said Tony Williams, chief of
staff for Sen. Slade Gorton, R-Wash., who has championed Microsoft
in Congress. ``These high-tech companies don't think about
government and politics because they're busy starting their
businesses, but at some point they realize government is having an
impact, and they need to get engaged.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the top officials of Internet companies don't even know
their own members of Congress, let alone the myriad elected
officials who have a voice in enacting laws that can affect the
companies, Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   ``As you grow, you get bigger and you run into regulations and
people who don't understand your issues,'' he said. ``We want them
to keep growing, but they need to have a relationship with us so we
understand what impacts them.''
</P>
<P>
   The companies have approached Rep. Adam Smith, D-Wash., who has
been active in the debate over how to regulate the export of
encrypted software, which is technology that allows secure
transmission of e-mail and financial transactions.
</P>
<P>
   ``All industries want to get their voices heard on the (Capitol)
Hill, so this is not surprising, but we think it's great,'' said
Ali Weise, Smith's spokeswoman. ``Technology is now so pervasive in
our lives that every committee in Congress deals with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Congress is paying increasing attention to the Internet. More
than 75 pieces of legislation now pending would regulate the
Internet in some way, and there's increasing talk about taxing
electronic commerce. Before any decisions are made, the companies
want Congress to recognize their chief executives as the experts in
electronic commerce.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, some of the lobbying is being done by the
companies' chief executives and other top officers, who fly to
Washington periodically to visit lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're the ones on the front line in making the Internet
work,'' said Elizabeth Wang, general counsel for Internet
advertising company DoubleClick Inc. of New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our overall mission is that Congress turn to us before bills
are passed,'' added Todd Krizelman, co-chief executive of
theglobe.com, a New York company that lets Internet users set up
free Web pages.
</P>
<P>
   ``As the Internet has grown so rapidly and affected so many
different industries, the government needs to understand how these
changes are going to impact the economy and evaluate when and when
not to be involved.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of NetCoalition's CEOs don't fit the traditional image of a
lobbyist, or even of a chief executive officer. Theglobe's co-CEOs,
for example, are both in their mid-20s.
</P>
<P>
   Members are selling a product some members of Congress aren't
familiar with. Executives from NetCoalition said some lawmakers
have rarely been online and have only a vague understanding of what
Internet companies do or how legislation might affect them.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, lawmakers are used to being courted by large, rich
corporations, not small, high-growth _ and often money-losing _
start-ups. Stephan Paternot, the other co-chief executive of
theglobe, said the NetCoalition's influence in Washington shouldn't
be measured by traditional yardsticks like profit. In this new
industry, growth rate, brand recognition and ability to attract Web
users are what's important, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are the companies that are already being responsibly run,
and we want to make sure some shop out in the middle of nowhere
doesn't come out and taint what we do,'' Paternot said.
</P>
<P>
   The companies also want to distinguish themselves from
broad-based technology giants like Microsoft Corp. and AT&AMP;T Corp.,
which, although well-known to lawmakers, may not represent the
interests of companies whose fortunes are tied solely to the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   NetCoalition says it worries that Congress' new-found interest
in cyberspace could spawn laws that will limit or slow the growth
of the Internet. Technology behemoths _ with heavy stakes in other
businesses such as software or telecommunications _ could survive
that, but companies like those in NetCoalition couldn't, said Tim
Stevens, a corporate counsel for Inktomi Corp. The success of these
companies rides on the Internet alone _ and its explosive growth.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, adjusting to the pace of Washington's bureaucracy has
been ``like putting on the parking brake after going 75 miles an
hour,'' said Brian O'Shaughnessy, a former policy director at the
Internet Alliance who is now senior manager for corporate
communications at Network Solutions Inc.
</P>
<P>
   None of the companies has spent much money on the new lobbying
venture. They committed funding for only one year, though they
expect it to last longer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will commit for as long as it takes,'' said Amazon's
Gabrieli.
</P>
<P>
   NetCoalition rents office space from Wiley, Rein &AMP; Fielding, a
blue-chip lobbying firm in Washington, D.C., that will help
represent the group. The group has a single employee, Daniel Ebert,
who says he now functions as its coordinator but in the future will
also lobby.
</P>
<P>
   The nine member companies each have one vote on important issues
and will decide together whether to add other companies. No one
company is leading the group, which Gabrieli said meets about twice
a month by conference call.
</P>
<P>
   The growth of electronic commerce has spurred talk in Congress
of taxes and consumer protections _ even as both political parties
present themselves as friends of the industry.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the Internet bills introduced so far have been referred
to committees and stayed there. Of those that have passed, most
seek to protect consumers: for example, setting a standard for
electronic signatures used to identify online credit card users and
the authors of e-mail, and establishing civil penalties for misuse
of online information such as real estate listings or stock quotes.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the companies in NetCoal-ition are less than 5 years
old. Besides DoubleClick and theglobe, the smaller Internet
companies in NetCoalition are Inktomi Corp. and Lycos Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Though getting involved in government is generally not part of a
start-up business' culture, Krizelman said the Justice Department's
lawsuit against Microsoft has been ``a great lesson'' for the
industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``It taught us `better approach Washington pre-emptively, rather
than wait until there is a problem,''' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft nearly doubled its spending on lobbying, to $1.2
million, in the last six months of 1997 compared to the prior
half-year. That spending boost coincided with the Justice
Department's reopening its antitrust investigation, in October
1997.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft execs, from Chairman Bill Gates on down, have
repeatedly acknowledged their naivete in the ways of Washington,
and have tried to make up for lost time with a flood of spending.
</P>
<P>
   ``In retrospect, we probably got big enough three or four years
ago to get involved in issues related to communications, (and) we
should have stepped up our activities there a bit sooner,'' Gates
said in March 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Other Internet lobbying organizations
</P>
<P>
   Hands Off the Internet _ Advocates unregulated approach to
Internet access and freedom from Internet taxes.
</P>
<P>
   www.handsoffthe.net
</P>
<P>
   Internet Alliance _ Promotes and develops online and Internet
services.
</P>
<P>
   www.internetalliance.org
</P>
<P>
   OpenNet Coalition _ Advocates open access to broadband cable
systems.
</P>
<P>
   www.opennetcoalition.org
</P>
<P>
   ProComp _ Promotes fair competition in the Internet arena,
including enforcement of antitrust laws.
</P>
<P>
   www.procompetition.org.
</P>
<P>
   TechNet _ A Silicon Valley political action committee.
</P>
<P>
   www.technetwork.org.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
