<TEXT>
<P>
   The Seattle Post-Intelligencer plans to move the following for
clients of the NYTimes News Service for editions of Wednesday, Oct.
13, and thereafter. If you have any questions, please call Bob
Schenet at (206) 448-8035.
</P>
<P>
   WTO-NADER (Washington) _ In a lengthy critique that is likely to
form the basis for much of the protest in Seattle next month,
consumer activist Ralph Nader Wednesday will release a study of the
World Trade Organization alleging that the body is undermining
environmental and public health laws around the world. The
book-length report analyzes five years of WTO rulings and finds
that the organization, meeting in secret, has decided against every
public health, safety and environmental regulation it has ever
considered.
</P>
<P>
   By Michael Paulson. (Story will move in the ``f'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-LOBBY (Washington) _ Internet companies that have won
respect on Wall Street are trying to do the same in Washington.
Amazon.com Inc., America Online Inc., eBay Inc., ExciteHome, Yahoo
Inc. and several lesser-known companies have formed
NetCoalition.com, a lobbying group determined to influence
decisions affecting companies whose business is purely Internet.
</P>
<P>
   By Dan Richman and Michael Paulson. (Story has moved in the
``f'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   ARMY-LEWIS (Undated) _ The Army will undergo a fundamental
transformation to make America's land forces more responsive to
short-notice crises and smaller-scale conflicts, such as the war
over Kosovo, that have increasingly occupied the American military
in the 1990s. The transformation will take years but will begin
immediately with the conversion of two combat brigades at Ft.
Lewis, Wash., into more flexible, faster-moving units. (Summary
from wires).
</P>
<P>
   By Ed Offley. (Story will move in the ``a'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   GORE-ENVIRONMENT (Seattle) _ If any presidential candidate
expect to be embraced by the environmental movement, it would be Al
Gore. But when the vice president arrives in Seattle Wednesday to
kick off his state campaign with a $1,000-a-plate dinner,
environmental leaders are likely to greet him not with open arms,
but with detailed demands. Environmentalists have not abandoned
Gore. But their pressuring of the vice president points out not
only some problems in the Gore campaign, but also how the
environmental movement and its political clout have shifted.
</P>
<P>
   By Joel Connelly. (Story will move in the ``p'' category.)
