<HEADLINE>
MERCKER NAMED STARTER AGAINST YANKEES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ By now, Red Sox fans have given up trying to guess
Jimy Williams's next move, and the manager flummoxed them again
Tuesday by naming Kent Mercker as Boston's starter in Wednesday
night's opening game against the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   But the real surprise came when Mercker explained why he pitched
so dismally Sunday night against the Indians in Boston, lasting
only 1 2/3 innings and giving up two runs on three hits.
</P>
<P>
   Mercker has had sore ribs for the last month, but the lefthander
said Tuesday, ``My ribs didn't bother me. That was my problem. I'd
had 13 days off, and this probably sounds funny, but I felt too
good out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Mercker first injured his ribs when he and third baseman Wilton
Veras collided while chasing a popup Sept. 6 in Seattle, and
Mercker tweaked the injury while reaching for a high hopper off the
bat of the White Sox' Mike Caruso later that month. He missed a
start against Baltimore during the last series of the regular
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``You put all the things together _ the rest, the not feeling
pain, the adrenaline, the situation _ and I was just out there
trying to throw as hard as Pedro (Martinez),'' said Mercker. ``And
so I fell behind batters and didn't pitch the way I am capable of
pitching.''
</P>
<P>
   With his staff beleaguered after a tough five-game series
against the hard-hitting Indians, Williams seemingly had three
choices for the opener: Pat Rapp, Tim Wakefield, or Mercker. With
the Yankees apparently a bit more vulnerable to lefthanded starters
(19-14 on the season, though 13-5 in Yankee Stadium), Williams
chose the lefty, even on two days rest.
</P>
<P>
   The short rest, Mercker believes, ``will be good for me because
I'm not going to be feeling like Superman out there. I'll be able
to stay within myself and make better pitches.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We just felt he was the right one to start this particular
game,'' said Williams. ``His command maybe wasn't what he liked it
to have been in that game (Sunday) and maybe it will be better and
he'll get (ahead) of hitters better.''
</P>
<P>
   Mercker conceded that he was getting the start by default, ``but
I'm looking forward to it,'' he said. ``This is a chance that not
many people get, and I'm looking forward to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Mercker spots his fastball and has a good changeup, but his best
weapon, as with so many of these Red Sox, is that so many outsiders
expect so little from him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a source of motivation to try and prove everybody
wrong,'' said Mercker, repeating the Red Sox' 1999 mantra. ``It's
obvious we're an underdog, but we were an underdog against
Cleveland, too.''
</P>
</TEXT>
