<HEADER>
A4697 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBA-REDSOX-O'LEARY-NY     10-12 0781
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-O'LEARY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE DANGERS OF UNDERESTIMATING BOSTON  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By STEVE POPPER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Nomar Garciaparra was intentionally walked the first time
on Monday night, Troy O'Leary took no offense and found no great
revenge when he blasted a grand slam to put the Boston Red Sox in
front of the Cleveland Indians.
</P>
<P>
   After the Indians once again issued an intentional pass to
Garciaparra in the seventh inning, O'Leary responded to the slight
with a three-run homer to help the Red Sox reach the American
League Championship series against the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   O'Leary said Tuesday that he not only understood Cleveland's
strategy, but would probably have done the same thing if he were an
opposing manager.
</P>
<P>
   O'Leary may be selling himself short, the same way Manager Mike
Hargrove of Cleveland did. His Indians, meanwhile, feel they have
been slighted by the news media and the fans across the nation.
</P>
<P>
   While most see the Red Sox as little more than a speed bump on
the way to the Yankees' 25th World Series title, the players
chuckle a little bit at the notion. They are more than happy to
play the part of the lightly regarded underdogs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been written off by everybody,'' O'Leary said.
``Obviously, you guys have been wrong. We don't have the big-name
guys. We've just got a lot of guys with a lot of heart that know
how to play the game, know what it takes to win, know their job. We
all kind of clicked together and when you bring that all together,
it turns out to be a very good baseball team.''
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox happily count off the names of the Yankees'
All-Stars, while humbly acknowledging that Pedro Martinez and
Garciaparra are perhaps the only players anyone outside of Fenway
Park might recognize.
</P>
<P>
   This season O'Leary led Boston in home runs with 28, and he
drove in 103 runs, more than anyone on the team other than
Garciaparra. The Red Sox did win 8 of 12 from the Yankees this
season, with O'Leary hitting a pair of homers.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, O'Leary was 1 for 16 in the post-season against the
Indians and he did not have a home run in the divisional series
this season until the decisive game. But in two pitches he proved
that there is more to the Boston lineup than Garciaparra. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   O'Leary might epitomize the image that is reflected in players
like Damon Buford, Brian Daubach and Mike Stanley: lesser-known or
more well-traveled than their Yankee counterparts.
</P>
<P>
   O'Leary was acquired by the Red Sox on April 14, 1995, on
waivers from Milwaukee, having got a small taste of the majors in
each of the two previous seasons. A month later, he was a starter,
a role he has not relinquished.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are just a bunch of guys in here that believe in
themselves,'' Stanley said. ``We don't get involved in who's
favored. Nobody picked this team higher than fourth, nobody picked
us to beat Cleveland. It's a cliche, but we're just taking it one
game at a time.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees would not bite for such talk. Andy Pettitte,
scheduled to pitch Game 4, said: ``There's a danger, definitely, in
looking at them as a one-man team with Garciaparra, because you've
got another big league hitter coming up behind that guy. I think
O'Leary's gotten a lot of respect this year for the year that he's
had. I don't think you hear a lot about Stanley. I've always
thought he was a good hitter. You don't hear a lot about Jose
Offerman and he can swing the bat pretty good. Jason Varitek
obviously has some power. They've got a good lineup.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Butch Huskey, who came to the Red Sox in a trade from Seattle in
midseason, is well aware of the aura that surrounds the Yankees,
having seen it during his time across town with the Mets.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're the same players over there that just get a little
more TV exposure,'' Huskey said. ``Why couldn't Troy O'Leary be an
All-Star? When you put him on a baseball field with those guys over
there, he's going to go out there and compete.''
</P>
<P>
   Inside the locker room, the Red Sox still enjoy jabbing at the
notion that the season was lost when Mo Vaughn left to join the
Angels. By surviving a wild-card race with Oakland and Toronto, and
then pulling off the divisional series after spotting Cleveland a
2-0 lead, the Red Sox continue to enjoy the perception that nobody
else believes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Really, nobody has given us any credit, but as you saw from
the Cleveland series, we've done OK,'' O'Leary said. ``We wouldn't
be here if we weren't for real.'' Huskey added: ``Why should we
think of ourselves as underdogs? If you go out there and execute
and do the little things that you're supposed to do, after nine
innings you may find yourself ahead of the big dogs.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
