<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Another day of waiting in Ramsey case
 &HT;    By Craig Schneider
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOULDER, Colo. _ A long day of high expectations for the
JonBenet Ramsey grand jury ended Tuesday with a jury taking no
action and deciding to meet again today.
</P>
<P>
   Only a week remains in the jury's term as speculation continues
to mount that a decision is imminent in the 3-year-old murder
mystery. With no word emerging from the meeting held in secret by
the grand jury, Boulder County District Attorney spokeswoman
Suzanne Laurion said she assumed, ``They are still immersed in
casework.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday offered slim pickings for more than 100 news people
waiting outside the Boulder Justice Center, anticipating a feeding
frenzy on the story that has rarely strayed from headlines or news
shows.
</P>
<P>
   Observers continued to speculate that the grand jury has begun
deliberating the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone assumes they are deliberating,'' said Craig
Silverman, a former Boulder deputy district attorney who has
watched the case closely. ``They could be deciding whether to see
additional witnesses. They may be studying John and Patsy Ramsey's
video (discussion with authorities).''
</P>
<P>
   If the grand jury is deliberating, Silverman noted, such
deliberations rarely last more than two days in Boulder. Despite
Tuesday's lack of action, the grand jury of eight women and four
men appears to be speeding to a conclusion. The panel began sitting
in September 1998.
</P>
<P>
   JonBenet Ramsey was found strangled and beaten in a basement
room of her family's home in Boulder the day after Christmas of
1996. Her father discovered her body that afternoon about seven
hours after his wife said she had found a ransom note demanding
$118,000 for the girl's safe return.
</P>
<P>
   Police have said JonBenet's parents, John and Patsy Ramsey,
remain under an ``umbrella of suspicion.'' The Ramseys have
steadfastly maintained their innocence. They have since moved to
the Atlanta area with their 12-year-old son, Burke.
</P>
<P>
   Boulder County District Attorney Alex Hunter met over the
weekend with Dr. Henry Lee, the noted forensic expert who helped
undermine evidence in the O.J. Simpson case.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have a tough case,'' said Lee of the prosecution. ``Any
case needs a lot of information. Alex Hunter and the police have
done tons of work, but there is no major, major evidence.''
</P>
<P>
   The media frenzy outside the courthouse drew curious onlookers.
``It looks like OJ,'' said Hope Colcord, 79.
</P>
<P>
   Craig Schneider writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
