<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Huff waived as Falcons seek LB help
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Falcons linebacker Keith Brooking has told some
members of the organization he plans to play Sunday against the
Rams.
</P>
<P>
   That's bravado. In reality, it's unclear when he'll return from
a partially torn medial collateral right knee ligament, but
Brooking has been told he'll be out two to six weeks.
</P>
<P>
   He'll be missed right away, because his speed would come in
handy against a 4-0 St. Louis team that frequently uses running
back Marshall Faulk as a receiver.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons (1-4) waived defensive tackle Ben Huff on Tuesday to
clear a roster spot at linebacker. Lamont Green, an undrafted
rookie from Florida State cut at the end of the preseason, is
likely to be activated from the practice squad.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons aren't likely to sign a free agent or acquire a
player through a trade.
</P>
<P>
   Brooking, the team's first-round draft choice in 1998 from
Georgia Tech, became a starter on the weak side after the Falcons
waived '98 leading tackler Cornelius Bennett in February. Brooking
and free safety Eugene Robinson are tied for the team lead with 39
tackles, trailing only strong safety Marty Carter, who has 58.
</P>
<P>
   The injury occurred in the second half of Sunday's 20-17 victory
in New Orleans, where fullback Bob Christian's season ended last
Dec. 13 when he tore ligaments in his right knee.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was wrapping up (Saints running back) Ricky Williams and my
foot was planted, when I think (Saints left tackle) Willie Roaf
landed on my leg,'' Brooking said. ``My foot didn't give, but my
leg did.''
</P>
<P>
   Brooking tore the same ligament as a freshman at Tech and missed
about eight weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a lot worse,'' he said. ``(Monday) my leg was stiff,
but by (Tuesday), I already had a lot of my range of motion back.''
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons won't know until later in the week whether middle
linebacker Jessie Tuggle can play. He aggravated a strained left
patella tendon against the Saints, missing most of the second half.
</P>
<P>
   Ruffin Hamilton replaced Brooking, but backup strong-side
linebacker Craig Sauer, who's quicker, might start on the weak
side.
</P>
<P>
   Rookie Jeff Kelly is the likely candidate to start if Tuggle
can't play.
</P>
<P>
   Matt Winkeljohn writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
