<HEADER>
A4700 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-BASEBALL-MARKETPLACE-     10-12 0875
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BASEBALL-MARKETPLACE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET PLACE: RATING WORLD SERIES CHAMPS FOR WINNING EFFECT ON
STOCKS 
</HEADLINE>
 
(Attn: Ga., Wis., Mass.)  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By FLOYD NORRIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Given the fervor created by the success of New York's
two baseball teams this year, you might think that America's former
national pastime (baseball) has a chance to eclipse its current
national pastime (trading stocks).
</P>
<P>
   This column will examine the history of the interplay between
the two. To wit: What, if anything, does success for New York's
baseball players have to say about the likely success for those who
play stocks?
</P>
<P>
   The historical answers are clear. The New York Yankees are good
for stocks, but the Boston Red Sox are better. The Atlanta Braves
are also good, but a New York Mets appearance in the World Series
would be a bad omen. Previous Subway Series have been followed by
subpar market performances.
</P>
<P>
   Those conclusions are based on the completely unreasonable
assumption that what happens to the stock market in the year after
a World Series is somehow influenced by which teams played in the
Series. To study the effect, the performance of the Dow Jones
industrial average was checked from the end of each October to the
end of the following October. The figures were analyzed for the
year after each World Series, beginning with the first one in 1903,
but excluding the two years when no World Series was played. The
average annual gain was 7.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The market has done much better in years after the Yankees
appeared in the World Series. The average during those 35 years was
a gain of 10.5 percent, compared with an average rise of just 5.6
percent when Yankees fans were presumably depressed by the failure
of their team to win the pennant. In other words, the market does
nearly twice as well after the Yankees win a pennant than it does
after their defeats. (The figures include the Dow's rise of 21.2
percent from the end of last October through Tuesday.)
</P>
<P>
   Boston has been in the series nine times, leading to an average
gain of 12.9 percent, far better than the Yankee figure. After the
five Series that it won _ the last in 1918, to be sure _ the gain
averaged a very impressive 15.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets have been in the World Series three times, and those
three years were not among the best for stocks, to say the least.
In the 12 months after the ``Miracle Mets'' Series championship of
1969, the Dow fell 11.7 percent as the great 1950s-1960s bull
market began to crumble.
</P>
<P>
   The next Mets World Series appearance, in 1973, boded even
worse. The 1973-74 bear market was on by then, and in the next
year, the Dow fell 30.4 percent, for its worse showing in four
decades.
</P>
<P>
   The last Mets appearance, a victory over the Red Sox in 1986,
produced the best performance, with the Dow rising 6.2 percent from
October to October. But that period ended with the 1987 stock
market crash.
</P>
<P>
   Contrast that sorry record to the performance of the Atlanta
Braves, a team that has appeared in four World Series in the 1990s,
winning one. The average gain for the Dow in the aftermath of those
appearances was 17.4 percent, with the best showing, a rise of 26.8
percent, coming after the Braves won in 1995. (If one includes the
four previous series for the peripatetic Braves, two each in Boston
and Milwaukee, the average performance falls to 12.9 percent.)
</P>
<P>
   There has never been a Yankees-Mets Subway Series. But there
have been 13 Subway Series, seven against the Brooklyn Dodgers and
six against the New York Giants, with the Yankees winning 10 of
them.
</P>
<P>
   More important for this purpose, the average performance of the
Dow in the year after a Subway Series has been a gain of only 6.0
percent. By contrast, the average has risen 13.2 percent a year in
the year after a Yankees World Series appearance against teams not
from New York.
</P>
<P>
   While it has historically been a good stock market omen for the
Yankees to get into the World Series, it has been an even better
one for them to lose. The average gain for the Dow after the 11
Yankees losses was 12.9 percent. The average gain after the 24
Yankees' wins was 9.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees have an outstanding performance record even though
the team was not in any World Series during the first 13 years of
the current bull market, which began in 1982. Its appearances in
1996 and 1998 helped, but much of the record can be traced to the
fact that the Yankees were a superior team when stocks went crazy
in the 1920s, but that the team then missed the World Series for
three years from 1929-31, thus avoiding the worst years of stock
market collapse.
</P>
<P>
   If you've come this far, perhaps you'd like to know what would
happen if the World Series were abolished, freeing stock market
players from such distractions. History says it would be great. The
average performance for the Dow after the two years there was no
series _ in 1904 when the New York Giants refused to play the
Boston Pilgrims, and after a labor dispute wiped out the 1994
series _ was a gain of 27.3 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-12-99 2038EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
