<HEADER>
A4702 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BBA-ALCS-ADVANCE-COX     10-12 0520
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ALCS-ADVANCE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ALCS: Memories fuel matchup
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It defies all odds. Someone in Yankee Stadium tonight
cannot recite chapter and verse of the Bucky Dent story. ``I don't
remember that,'' Orlando Hernandez said. ``They only have
two-channel television in Cuba.''
</P>
<P>
   Dent hit a home run in a one-game playoff to keep Boston from
reaching the postseason in 1978, and the Yankees went on to win the
World Series.
</P>
<P>
   No ALCS ever has been like this one. The New York Yankees and
Boston Red Sox, owners of baseball's meanest rivalry, meet for the
first time in the postseason, summoning nearly a century of bad
blood, busted hopes and spilled beer.
</P>
<P>
   ``You are asking me for too much now,'' Hernandez said.
</P>
<P>
   But the asking has only started.
</P>
<P>
   El Duque gets the ball for Game 1, facing ex-Brave Kent Mercker
and a Red Sox team that beat the Yankees like no other this season.
This series is the most significant Yankee-Red Sox meeting at
Yankee Stadium since 1949, when Boston hit town in the season's
last weekend with a one-game lead and two games to play _ and lost
the pennant.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the first time in history, this will happen,'' New York's
David Cone said. ``This is the first time the Yankees and the Red
Sox can get together in an LCS. Without the wild card, it wouldn't
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This,'' Mercker said, ``is why you play baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Joe Torre, who growing up in Brooklyn was steeped in New
York rivalries, is jacked up about this one. His Yankees lost eight
times in 12 tries against the Red Sox and then watched Boston work
the impossible comeback against Cleveland. Even without what went
before, these games would tantalize his club.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that even if (the Yankees) don't know the ancient
history that has these two clubs involved,'' Torre said, ``I think
they have seen Bucky Dent's home run more so on that scoreboard
than they want to, especially with my bench coach (Don Zimmer)
being the manager of the Red Sox at the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``But there is no question,'' Torre said, ``that you feel that
this is going to be something special.''
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox made the Bronx, running on fumes from Monday night
and their third consecutive victory over Cleveland. Boston has not
been to an ALCS since 1990, when it was swept by Oakland. Suddenly,
with the improved health of Pedro Martinez's back and the drama of
returning from an 0-2 deficit to win the AL Division Series, the
Sox look like a gathering force.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just have to keep going and hope you keep flying to
different cities,'' said Williams, whose team was 3-2 at Yankee
Stadium this season.''
</P>
<P>
   Troy O'Leary won't hit two homers every night, just as Martinez
won't be coming out of the bullpen. But what happened in the LDS is
that quite unexpectedly, the most amusing two teams in the league
wound up here.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's dynamite,'' Torre said. ``It really is.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Stinson writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
