<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-12 20:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4703 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-TRANSPOSED-MUSIC-3TAK     10-12 1009
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRANSPOSED-MUSIC-3TAKES-$ADV17-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAILORING ARIAS TO SUIT THE VAGARIES OF THE VOICES  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, OCT. 17) 
</HEADLINE>
  (af) 
 Will Crutchfield is a conductor specializing in 19th-century
opera.  
 By WILL CRUTCHFIELD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Transposition is in the news at the Metropolitan
Opera. Sir Charles Mackerras just concluded a series of
performances of ``Lucia di Lammermoor'' with three large chunks of
the score restored to the higher keys in which the composer
originally wrote them.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time Placido Domingo has been reprising two of his
most celebrated roles, the tragic clown of ``Pagliacci'' and the
tormented Moor of ``Otello,'' with adjustments in the other
direction to accommodate the autumnal range of his tenor voice.
Both circumstances are being discussed extensively _ even heatedly
_ and both are being a bit misunderstood as often as not.
</P>
<P>
   ``Transposition'' in music refers to the collective lowering or
raising of a group of notes, a process that leaves the essential
musical message intact. Yes, they sound different; but a tune that
starts on E is the same tune if you start it on D, as long as you
move all the other notes down by the same distance.
</P>
<P>
   Any piece of music can be transposed, but in professional
practice, it is almost exclusively a vocal issue. An oboe is an
oboe, and what is well written for oboe in one key need never be
moved to another. What is well written for piano or violin may,
indeed, suffer considerably if it is moved, because the mechanics
of execution (just where the violinist shifts from one string to
another, for instance, or which notes are easily accessible to the
pianist's thumb) are so particular that a passage that is
satisfyingly brilliant in one key can become dauntingly awkward in
another.
</P>
<P>
   But singing is a different matter. One soprano, one baritone, is
not like another. Each voice is a unique instrument, and though
there is enough correspondence to allow a great deal of music to
pass from artist to artist unaltered, there has also been a lot of
tailoring as music has been committed to paper.
</P>
<P>
   Whether by rewriting individual lines to add or subtract notes
at the end of the range or by transposing entire pieces, it has
always been necessary to organize a fit between the voices one
wants and the music one wants them to sing.
</P>
<P>
   Such things happen a thousand times a day in the world of
popular song, and no one is concerned; even musicians who are
prepared to take Gershwin's ``Who Cares?'' quite seriously as a
piece of skillful composition (and they should) do not care what
its ``original key'' might have been. The same is largely true in
the world of classical lieder, though pianists know that sometimes
the singer's convenience can add hours to their practice schedule.
</P>
<P>
   But in opera, it's news. The reasons range from a sportive
interest in competitive statistics (how high can Dame Joan
Sutherland still sing this season?), through sensitivity to the
color of a particular key (we tend to think that D major sounds
``military'' and D flat sounds ``warm''), to concern for the
long-range harmonic relationships between one key and another that
were _ sometimes _ important to the way composers conceived their
music over the span of an opera.
</P>
<P>
   Each of these aspects has its complications. The earlier we look
in operatic history, the simpler the answers, for two reasons.
Until, say, Mozart's time or a little after, operas were composed
for specific singers and, if revived at all, recomposed for the new
ones.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the orchestrally accompanied musical units (arias and,
eventually, ensembles) were linked by the keyboard-accompanied
dialogue we call ``recitative,'' whose harmonic structure was
intentionally loose, having no purpose but to prepare the key of
the next piece.
</P>
<P>
   Recitative is infinitely adjustable to accommodate whatever that
next key might be. So Handel transposed his arias all over the map,
a step, a third or a fourth above or below their original keys as
the situation might require, expertly rewriting the instrumental
parts to avoid awkwardness in the orchestra. (If the composer was
not around, the presiding maestro of any operatic season stepped in
to do this job.)
</P>
<P>
   Both these situations changed, and that is the reason we have an
issue today. At more or less the same time, composers moved toward
a more continuous musical texture, reducing and eventually
eliminating the arbitrary nature of the ``linking'' material; and
they began thinking in terms of a coherent artwork that would pass
more or less unaltered from one theater to another.
</P>
<P>
   So singers had to become more adaptable. Then, too, a further
complication was gradually introduced: the exploitation of extreme
vocal notes for their particular character and impact. All the
notes of an aria by Vivaldi or Bach make sense if you play them on
the violin; the same is not true of Verdi, because some notes are
there for a more purely vocal impact.
</P>
<P>
   These changes did not happen in a flash. Different composers
attempted different degrees of continuity and coordination. And
even when those were at their maximum, it remained a matter not of
principle but of the musical particulars of the moment whether a
certain transposition was easy or difficult, justifiable or
questionable, noticeable or hidden.
</P>
<P>
   What is certain is that in all generations before our own,
transposition was practiced a lot more frequently than it is in our
museum-oriented opera houses. The less we do it, the more we talk
about it: just now, the Internet is buzzing with debate over
``Lucia'' and Domingo. But any Met season 50 or 100 years ago
involved far more transposition and far less consternation.
</P>
<P>
   A few examples. We think of the conductor Arturo Toscanini as a
purist, but even at the end of his operatic career, and even in the
shrinelike environment of the Salzburg Festival, he made
transpositions to accommodate his singers in both ``Fidelio'' and
``The Magic Flute.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The latter opera illustrates one frequent cause for
transposition: the Queen of the Night is written for an
extraordinarily high soprano voice, and the voices that are both
sufficiently high and appropriately dramatic are rare. The Queen's
``vengeance'' aria is composed in D minor. Dame Joan was criticized
for singing it in C minor the one time she performed the role, in
the early 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   Toscanini was not criticized, as far as I know, for letting his
Queen do the same in the 1930s. At the Met in 1901, Marcella
Sembrich lowered it farther (to B minor), apparently without
raising eyebrows. Nowadays we tend to prefer slighter voices and
the original key; different compromises for different times.
</P>
<P>
   This is only the tip of the iceberg. The beloved Rosa Ponselle
made extensive transpositions in ``Aida,'' ``Il Trovatore,''
``Norma,'' ``La Traviata'' and much else. The baritone aria in
``Faust,'' the tenor arias in ``La Boheme'' and ``Il Trovatore,''
and the bass arias in ``The Barber of Seville'' have probably been
heard as often in transpositions as in their original keys.
</P>
<P>
   It has always been understood that transposition could become a
problem, and in earlier times, composers and singers freely
adjusted vocal lines within the original key to solve problems
without transposing, when that was the more practical solution.
That still happens at the drop of a hat when a new composition is
being prepared, but it has fallen out of favor in familiar operas,
probably because so many listeners have memorized them from
recordings that the adjustments would be too easily commented on,
and singers are shy about revealing their limitations.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the limitations exist, and it is silly to suppose that
adaptation to them should or could be forbidden. Tenors are
especially prone to need it; we all love the sound of a good
tenor's high range, but the fact is that many fine tenors have the
right sound without having the last few notes their higher
colleagues command.
</P>
<P>
   Tito Schipa, also at the Met, transposed a good deal more of
``Manon'' than Domingo is transposing of ``Otello.'' And yes, it
meant that his co-star had to adjust to some passages lower than
she might have wished. ``Of course it was a little difficult,''
Bidu Sayao, the Manon of one Saturday broadcast that has been
preserved, told me many decades later, ``but he was such an artist
that it was worth the effort.'' Good attitude.
</P>
<P>
   As for the composer's intentions: what is lacking in many
discussions is an appreciation of how flexible and contingent these
were. It is wonderful to see the long-range harmonic structure of
an opera composer who worked that way, but this is not the same as
thinking that the opera is ruined if the structure is modified on
occasion.
</P>
<P>
   Mozart did work that way, but it did not stop him from
transposing afterward when he needed to. Verdi, as far as the
evidence suggests, did not work that way, though he did seem to
care about the local color of individual keys; yet he, too,
willingly transposed all his life.
</P>
<P>
   The case of Verdi is complicated, and this is relevant to the
current ``Otello'' fracas. It's true that he once called for a
contractual right to forbid transposition in his scores, but only
as part of a general program of asserting control over rights,
royalties, cuts and casting that he pursued in the middle of his
career to assure the success of his operas and his (then
unprecedented) right to veto their production when he deemed
success unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   He was dealing with a situation in which Amelia in ``Simon
Boccanegra'' might substitute a Donizetti aria for ``Come in
quest'ora bruna'' (this happened), so his verbal pronouncements on
the matter have to be seen as exaggerations in that context.
</P>
<P>
   But practice was another matter. In ``Rigoletto,'' Verdi
composed Gilda's ``Caro nome'' in F and transposed it himself
before finishing the score. He made a midpiece modulation from G to
F in ``I Lombardi'' specifically to give the soprano high As
instead of Bs, ``because that note is particularly effective'' in
the particular singer's voice. He transposed a high-C showpiece
from the original St. Petersburg ``Forza del Destino'' to B flat
precisely because, as he put it, ``nobody will be able to sing what
was written for Tamberlik.''
</P>
<P>
   Violetta's duet with Germont in ``La Traviata'' went from E to E
flat because for the second production of the opera he had a
lower-voiced baritone; Verdi referred to his revision of this scene
as ``some tranpositions and adaptations for the new cast,'' though
in fact he also made other improvements: the reason he had the
second version published in place of the first.
</P>
<P>
   Even his oft-quoted letter objecting to the transposition of
``Celeste Aida'' is followed by one saying, in effect, ``OK, give
the permission, but let's not let this become a habit.'' (Verdi
also approved, advised and practiced copious local rewriting for
the sake of vocal comfort, up to and including his last opera,
``Falstaff.'')
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   And Verdi's predecessors did all this even more than he. In the
case of Donizetti and ``Lucia,'' it is probably exaggerated to call
the current Met production a different ``version'' of the score. A
different approach, yes, because Sir Charles has rethought the
embellishments from the ground up. He has also restored many cuts;
but so did the team that performed the opera with Edita Gruberova a
few seasons back.
</P>
<P>
   Still, ``Lucia'' at the Met, even at its most transposed and
altered, has always been closer to the composer's original than,
say, ``Giulio Cesare'' or ``The Tales of Hoffmann'' have been.
</P>
<P>
   As for the keys: since the Lucia arias have traditionally been
sung in lower keys and very high notes have been added at their
conclusions, it has been easy for many to assume that the high
notes are the reason for the transpositions. But history does not
bear this out; the Lucia arias were being sung (and published) in
the familiar transpositions within a decade of the opera's
premiere, long before the ultrahigh added notes became standard.
</P>
<P>
   The evidentiary record, for those who enjoy poring through it,
is clear that as late as the turn of the expiring century, more
Lucias sang the role without high E flats than with. And yet they
were singing in the lower keys. It is much more a matter of the
usual reason for transposition: general vocal ``fit'' between
singer and music.
</P>
<P>
   The gradual fossilization of certain ``standard'' interpolations
_ in this opera and in many others _ was a phenomenon of the
post-World War I period, as the few surviving operas from the age
of improvisation were equipped for life in an operatic environment
no longer hospitable to improvisation.
</P>
<P>
   So everybody should lighten up. Wagner was the most continuous
and least transposable of opera composers (and he sensibly avoided
unusual high notes, probably in part for that reason); yet even
Wagner accepted transpositions for the abandoned first production
of ``Tristan,'' and certain transpositions have functioned well
enough in his scores. Helen Traubel always sang Brunnhilde's Battle
Cry in B flat, not B. At Bayreuth itself, Senta's Ballade was
transposed upward for the young voice of Anja Silja (just as the
little aria of Mozart's Masetto is usually transposed up for the
youngish baritones who sing the part).
</P>
<P>
   It's all a matter of practicality, not principle. If the
transition can be made with some harmonic elegance, and if the
musical loss is either negligible or, at worst, small enough to be
outweighed by the performance it makes possible, then _ no big
deal. If it can't be, then one decides, OK, that singer can't do
that role.
</P>
<P>
   The ``overall harmonic conception'' is important to the
composer's inspiration if it is _ and sometimes it is. But as the
composers themselves knew, that takes its place among many other
priorities when it comes down to what happens on the individual
night, and sometimes it can yield.
</P>
<P>
   As for Domingo, meanwhile: if Verdi had not opened up his
autograph score and scratched out some key signatures, ``Otello''
itself would be with ``Lucia'' and ``Norma'' on the list of operas
that changed between manuscript and publication. The quartet in Act
II, where Desdemona asks her husband's pardon and Iago finagles the
famous handkerchief from his wife, was originally composed in B.
Verdi moved it to B flat during rehearsals, and though we have no
correspondence on the matter, the reason could hardly be more
obvious: as written, the piece required two sustained high Bs, a
note Otello is otherwise required to touch only briefly.
</P>
<P>
   It is easy to surmise, from what we know of Francesco Tamagno,
that these were difficult for the original singer of Otello,
especially given the lyrical context of the lines in question.
</P>
<P>
   If Tamagno had needed the other transpositions that are being
used at the Met, would Verdi have provided them? Or would he have
made local adjustments in the vocal part to render them
unnecessary? Or would he have said, ``All right, too much, let's
get another singer''? We can't know.
</P>
<P>
   If he were around right now, and ``get another singer'' meant
forgoing the services of a beloved artist who had much to offer, in
a role whose distinguished exponents are painfully rare _ well, I
don't think there's a lot of doubt here.
</P>
<P>
   The important thing to remember is that what happens on a given
evening cannot really ``damage'' a musical score. It is still
there, and nothing prevents its being performed unaltered another
day. The moment an Otello of comparable caliber arrives who is
comfortable with the original keys (as our current one was from
1976 until now), those keys will be right there waiting for him.
Meanwhile, rest easy, Maestro Domingo; the ghost of Verdi is on
your side.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
