<SLUG> BC-BBA-ALCS-NOTES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ALCS NOTEBOOK: O'Neill probably will playBy Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   New York _ If Paul O'Neill can get out of bed this morning,
expect him to be in right field tonight.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Yankee still has a broken rib, but he expects to
play in Game 1 of the ALCS, barring a flare-up after a full workout
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before, it was like I don't want to do to much. I might tear
something,'' he said. ``It's not that. (The pain) is going to be
there. It is there when I wake up in the morning. It is there when
I go to bed at night. It is something you can get in the game and
forget about. Hopefully, that is the case.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Neill was first injured in the next-to-last game of the
regular season, when he crashed into a wall at Tampa Bay's
Tropicana Field and suffered a non-displaced fracture of the 10th
rib on his right side. He went 2-for-8 in the first two games of
the AL Division Series against Texas before being held out of Game
3.
</P>
<P>
   His Monday workout came after three days of inactivity.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll see (this) morning, and we'll try to push it right up
against the deadline as far as announcing the roster,'' manager Joe
Torre said.
</P>
<P>
   ALCS rosters must be submitted at 10 a.m. today.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a big part of our team,'' shortstop Derek Jeter said.
``You want to have all your guns when you're going into a series
like this.''
</P>
<P>
   Merck works
</P>
<P>
   Former Brave Kent Mercker draws the first postseason start of
his career in Game 1, as well as his first October work since 1995
in Atlanta. With Boston's rotation knotted up, how did manager Jimy
Williams make this call?
</P>
<P>
   ``Managerial decision,'' Williams said. And that's all he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox' biggest decision might have been to knock
knuckle-baller Tim Wakefield off the ALCS roster, along with
reliever John Wasdin. The Red Sox added right-handers Pat Rapp and
Bryce Florie.
</P>
<P>
   Mercker started Game 3 of the AL Division Series, gave up a pair
of runs, never got out of the second inning, and Boston won by 17
runs. Even though that was four days ago, Mercker sensed he was the
logical choice to work tonight, because Pedro Martinez, Ramon
Martinez and Bret Saberhagen had thrown substantially more than he
had.
</P>
<P>
   ``So, I guess I was getting to start by default,'' said Mercker,
who allowed three runs in 12 innings of postseason relief with the
Braves. ``I think Jimy is doing it out of necessity, that there's
no one else that can pitch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's got confidence in me, but I am going to take
advantage of it. This is a chance not many people get, and I am
looking forward to it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees are not. With O'Neill and Tino Martinez batting
left-handed in the middle of the lineup, they went 19-14 against
left-handers this season and did not have to face one in the Texas
LDS.
</P>
<P>
   Wakefield done
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox will keep an 11-man pitching staff for the series,
but it will not include Wakefield, a veteran of three postseason
teams in Pittsburgh and Boston and who served the Red Sox as a
starter, middle reliever and closer at various times of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tough decisions,'' Williams said, ``but (you) have to make
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Stinson writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
