<SLUG> BC-MALARIA-WHO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW MALARIA PROGRAM TO USE TREATED BEDDING NETS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KAREN HSU
 &HT;    c.1999 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   The World Health Organization plans to announce Wednesday an
ambitious new program to fight malaria among children in Third
World countries by distributing special mosquito-net bedding dipped
in insecticide.
</P>
<P>
   As part of a WHO initiative called Roll Back Malaria that
started last year, project manager Dr. David Nabarro said WHO wants
to help provide 60 million African families with these
insecticide-treated mosquito nets over the next five years.
</P>
<P>
   Fewer than 2 million African households are estimated to have
bed nets, and the number of households actually using them properly
is much lower, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Malaria, spread through mosquito bites between dusk and dawn,
kills 1.1 million people worldwide each year, and about 1 million
of them are in Africa. One of every four childhood deaths in Africa
is from malaria, resulting in 700,000 children in Africa, most of
them under five years old.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, studies showed that insecticide-treated nets
could reduce malaria deaths by 25 percent. The nets were dipped in
synthetic pyrethroids, a substance derived from a plant common in
East Africa that has a long safety history and is
environmentally-friendly. The insecticide creates an invisible
chemical wall that keeps the bugs away.
</P>
<P>
   Although it is not the only solution, treated nets are a cheap
and immediate solution to combatting the increase of malaria, said
Dr. Dyann Wirth, director of the Harvard Malaria Initiative. ``Nets
alone are really not effective,'' said Wirth. ``It is clear that we
have the technology and it can have a huge effect now on child
deaths with malaria,'' said Nils Daulaire, president and chief
executive of Global Health Council, a membership alliance of
improving health worldwide. ``Nobody leaves from the hospital
anymore without a child car seat in the US, but that doesn't make
more than a five percent difference in our child death rate. With
malaria, no mother in Africa should leave the hospital without a
bednet.''
</P>
<P>
   Between 1991 and 1996, Vietnam launched a new anti-malaria
treatment drug and distributed insecticide-treated bednets on a
massive scale, and was able to reduce the malaria incidence by more
than 95 percent, said Dr. Kamini Mendis, a WHO malaria specialist
in Geneva. Mendis said that a trial of only treated bednets in the
southern part of Sri Lanka resulted in reducing the number of
malaria infections by 80 percent over 18 months.
</P>
<P>
   Malaria control experts meeting this week at a conference in Dar
es Salaam, Tanzania, are discussing strategies to increase the
availability of bednets, working with manufacturers to bring down
the cost, and promoting the need to regularly re-treat the bednets
every six months with the safe insecticide.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will reduce the reliance of DDT,'' said Nabarro.
</P>
<P>
   The World Bank, one of the core partners of the Roll Back
Malaria initiative, is supporting loan financing to countries to
begin to provide bednets, working with the bednet producers, and
trying to reduce the tax and tariffs of the bednets. In some
countries, bednets are still categorized as a luxury or
higher-tariff good, not a public-health good, such as
pharmaceuticals, said Julie McLaughlin, health specialist for the
World Bank. In some places, a net could cost $20, although Nabarro
said he hopes that they can eventually get the cost down to $3.50
for a net.
</P>
<P>
   The United Kingdom's Department for International Development,
the British equivalent of the US Agency for International
Development has already pledged $70 million for the bednet project.
</P>
<P>
   But one main problem will be distribution, said Dr. Peter Winch,
a specialist in behavior change interventions in tropical disease
control at the Johns Hopkins School of Hygiene and Public Health.
</P>
<P>
   ``The time people need nets and anti-malaria drug treatments the
most is in the rainy season, but that is also when people don't
have the money because the harvests haven't come in yet, and roads
are impassable because of the rain,'' Winch said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
