<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-12 20:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4708 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-HEALTH-CARE-NYT &LR;      10-12 0833
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEALTH-CARE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON ORDERS CAMPAIGN TO ENROLL CHILDREN IN U.S. HEALTH INSURANCE
PLAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ROBERT PEAR and ROBIN TONER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton directed federal officials
Tuesday to visit America's schools and enroll children in a health
insurance program that he said had fallen far short of his original
goal of providing coverage to 5 million youngsters.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is simply inexcusable that we're sitting here, and have
been, with the money for two years to provide health insurance to 5
million kids, and 80 percent of them are still uninsured,'' Clinton
said at the annual meeting of the American Academy of Pediatrics.
</P>
<P>
   Census Bureau data show that the number of children without
health insurance has increased by 15.6 percent since Clinton took
office, to 11.1 million last year from 9.6 million in 1993. The
number of uninsured children rose by 330,000 in 1998 alone, despite
an exceptionally strong economy and billions of dollars of new
federal money made available to pay for children's health
insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Congress created the new program, the Children's Health
Insurance Program, in 1997. It provided $24 billion over five years
and a total of $39 billion over 10 years, but states have used less
than 25 percent of the money made available so far.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we're going to bring health care coverage to more children,
we have to start with where the children are _ in the schools,''
Clinton said Tuesday. He instructed officials from the Departments
of Education, Agriculture and Health and Human Services to find
eligible children in the schools and sign them up in the new
program.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said schools would disseminate information on health
insurance along with the forms used to apply for school lunch
subsidies. ``Millions of parents who fill out their school lunch
forms now will have a chance to learn about these health
programs,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the president said, ``thousands of Americorps and
Vista volunteers who deal directly with low-income families every
day'' will be trained to enroll children in Medicaid and in the new
program.
</P>
<P>
   But children are not the only ones without insurance. A new
study shows that 20 percent of all uninsured people are offered
health insurance by employers, but choose not to take it. Most of
those people cite cost as the reason, saying premiums are too high.
</P>
<P>
   The study was issued Tuesday by a research organization, the
Center for Studying Health System Change. Peter Cunningham, a
co-author of the study, said: ``If all uninsured people with access
to employer-sponsored health plans were to enroll in those plans,
that would do more to reduce the number of uninsured than any of
the incremental expansions of coverage that have been passed or
proposed in recent years.''
</P>
<P>
   Seven business, consumer and medical groups said Tuesday that
they would work together to investigate ways of providing coverage
to the uninsured. The groups include Families USA, a consumer group
that supported Clinton's proposal for universal insurance coverage
in 1993-94, and the Health Insurance Association of America, which
helped kill the Clinton plan with television advertisements
featuring ``Harry and Louise.''
</P>
<P>
   Ronald Pollack, executive director of Families USA, and Charles
Kahn III, president of the insurance association, said Tuesday that
they wanted to force candidates to address the problems of the
uninsured in next year's elections.
</P>
<P>
   These groups will offer proposals to help the uninsured at a
conference in January. Detailed proposals will also be offered by
the other participants: the American Hospital Association, the
American Medical Association, the American Nurses Association, the
Service Employees International Union and the Chamber of Commerce
of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   A poll commissioned by Families USA and the Health Insurance
Association of America indicates that two-thirds of Americans would
be willing to pay $50 a year in additional taxes to insure that all
Americans had health coverage. The poll, conducted by Celinda Lake
and William McInturff, also suggests that at least half of all
adults would be more likely to vote for a presidential candidate if
the candidate talked about expanding access to health care.
</P>
<P>
   The poll found that the number of Americans touched directly or
indirectly by a lack of health insurance was much larger than
commonly assumed. Twelve percent of people ages 18 to 64 said they
were currently uninsured. Seventeen percent said they had coverage
now but had been uninsured at some time in the last three years.
And 43 percent said they had been insured for three straight years,
but knew someone who had been uninsured in those years.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are large numbers of people who drift in and out of
coverage,'' McInturff said.
</P>
<P>
   The survey, based on telephone interviews with 800 adults from
Sept. 29 to Oct. 4, had a margin of sampling error of 3 to 4
percentage points.
</P>
</TEXT>
