<SLUG> BC-AUSTRIA-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VOTE TALLY   IN AUSTRIA   PUTS FAR RIGHT   IN 2ND PLACE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Israel)   By DONALD G. McNEIL Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   VIENNA &UR; , Austria &LR;  _ With 250,000 absentee ballots finally
counted, the results of Austria's Oct. 3 elections were declared
official Tuesday, with the far-right Freedom Party holding onto
second place by a mere 415 votes.
</P>
<P>
   That appeared to give the party, led by Joerg Haider, a good
chance of being in whatever government is eventually formed.
Haider's bitterest opponents have openly called him a Nazi _ for
his anti-immigration stance, for once referring favorably to Third
Reich employment policy and for praising a war-veterans' group that
included some concentration camp guards.
</P>
<P>
   Israel's foreign minister, David Levy, was quoted on Vienna
radio stations Tuesday as having told Israeli army radio that he
would cut off relations with Austria if Haider gets a government
role.
</P>
<P>
   The Austrian government reacted angrily, issuing a communique
saying Levy's comments were ``totally unjustified.''
</P>
<P>
   Many moderate Austrians are angered by what they consider an
overreaction by the world outside and the suggestion that Nazism
has any place in current Austrian politics.
</P>
<P>
   A tiny vote gap between second and third place and the counting
of absentee ballots was important because the leader of the
third-place Austrian People's Party promised in mid-campaign that
if his party came in behind Haider's, he would drop out of the
``grand coalition of reds and blacks'' that has controlled Austrian
politics for 13 years.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night, his party appeared to be keeping that promise,
saying after a meeting of the party leadership that it would go
into opposition.
</P>
<P>
   But the chief of the conservative business- and church-oriented
party, Wolfgang Schuessel, couched the announcement in careful
phrasing, saying his party leaders had voted to ``put the switches
in motion to move into opposition.'' Journalists and others
covering the late-evening announcement said the sentence gave him
an out and that he might still form the ``grand coalition'' if
talks with the governing Social Democrats _ the reds _ proved
fruitful.
</P>
<P>
   Schuessel has said the coalition should not form again until it
works out disagreements on budget cuts, employers' payments to the
government benefits pool and military policy.
</P>
<P>
   After reading the official tally, Interior Minister Karl
Schloegl, a Social Democrat, said the People's Party ``will not
lose face if they negotiate with the Social Democrats.''
</P>
<P>
   A politics professor from the University of Vienna, Anton
Pelinka, analyzing the results for Austrian television, suggested
that all coalition talks would fail because the parties are so far
apart and at nearly equal strength. He predicted that talks would
drag on until Christmas and that new elections would be called.
</P>
<P>
   Schuessel's party, known as ``the blacks,'' fell 415 votes short
of Haider's ``blues'' party, but each got 26.9 percent of the 4.6
million votes cast and each will have 52 seats in Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   The Social Democrats ended up with 33.2 percent of the vote.
Although it is still the dominant party, its percentage of the vote
has fallen year after year, while Haider's has grown. The Freedom
Party had only 5 percent of the vote when Haider took it over in
1986.
</P>
<P>
   On the other side of the political spectrum, the Green Party has
doubled the percentage of its vote since 1995. Tuesday, after the
absentee ballots were counted, it had picked up a 14th
parliamentary seat and will be able, in egalitarian fashion, to
seat seven men and seven women.
</P>
<P>
   Haider has said he is willing to negotiate a coalition
government with virtually anyone. Speaking at a news conference
Tuesday in Klagenfurt, in his home province of Carinthia, he said
the vote showed that the red-black coalition was dead with the
voters.
</P>
<P>
   Haider's success in winning 27 percent of the vote has created
Austria's biggest foreign relations crisis since 1986. It was
revealed then that Kurt Waldheim, a former U.N. secretary general
who had been elected Austria's president, had lied about his German
army service in World War II, in a unit implicated in atrocities.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the leader of Austria's strong Roman Catholic Church,
Cardinal Christoph Schoenborn, toured the Yad Vashem Holocaust
memorial in Jerusalem and reminded Israelis that nearly 75 percent
of voters had not selected Haider.
</P>
<P>
   Even though frustration with the dominance and bickering of the
red-black coalition is widespread, weekend opinion polls indicated
that between 54 and 59 percent of Austrians wanted it to continue
in power.
</P>
<P>
   Besides a ban on immigration into Austria, Haider favors a 23
percent flat tax, wants every mother who is an Austrian citizen to
get a $400 check each month and opposes the social security cuts
the government reluctantly made to qualify for the euro, the
European currency.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
