<SLUG> BC-RAYTHEON-WOES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAYTHEON STOCK DROPS ON WARNING OF LOWER SALES, PROFITS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROSS KERBER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Raytheon Co. stock dropped 44 percent Tuesday after it warned
that sales and profits will be far below expectations this year and
next.
</P>
<P>
   After trading was halted most of the day while the company
discussed its problems with analysts and reporters, the stock fell
18 3/4 to close at 24 1/4. In July, the stock hit a high of
74-15/16.
</P>
<P>
   Raytheon also said it plans to eliminate about 2,380 jobs,
including 140 from its Lexington, Mass., headquarters and 200
elsewhere in Massachusetts and New Hampshire. The layoffs are in
addition to the thousands of positions the company has shed in
recent years.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Burnham, Raytheon's chief executive, said the company's
condition ``fills me with anger, embarrassment and guilt.'' He said
he hoped the company's candor about its difficulties would help
Raytheon ``re-establish credibility'' with investors.
</P>
<P>
   Among its immediate woes, Raytheon said it expects no new orders
this year for its Patriot ground-to-air missile and said it will
have to write off other munitions inventories.
</P>
<P>
   Burnham also tried to address bigger questions surrounding the
company, which has released a stream of warnings about its outlook
in recent months. In general, Burnham said, the company has moved
too quickly to integrate defense units it acquired from Texas
Instruments Inc. and Hughes Electronics Corp. two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``In retrospect, we tried to do too much too fast, given the
size of the task, our state of readiness, and the depth and
maturity of the management team,'' Burnham said.
</P>
<P>
   Burnham also backed off his much-vaunted goal of growing revenue
by 6 to 8 percent a year and profits by 10 to 12 percent a year,
and set more modest expectations for 1999 and 2000. In addition,
Burnham said the company would take pretax charges of $638 million
this year, up from a charge of as much as $450 million the company
said last month that it planned to take during its third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The company's update was aimed at investors worried by
Raytheon's statements last month, and Burnham pledged the company
would continue to grow 1 or 2 percent faster than the overall
defense market.
</P>
<P>
   But the update calmed few shareholders, who among other things
were spooked by Raytheon's forecast that profit margins will
probably fall from 15 percent to 12 percent next year at Raytheon
Systems Co., the defense contracting unit that accounts for
three-quarters of Raytheon's total revenue.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't get much uglier,'' said Bill Fiala, an analyst at
Edward Jones in St. Louis. ``What makes this so serious is that the
problems that were disclosed today were in areas that are the bread
and butter of Raytheon.
</P>
<P>
   ``US defense contracts are what make Raytheon tick and dropping
the ball in that area is a serious issue,'' Fiala said.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Nisbet, an analyst at JSA Research in Newport, R.I., said
he was troubled by continual shifts in guidance Raytheon has given.
``The credibility has gone to near-zero, and its going to be a long
time before it is back,'' said Nisbet. He compared Raytheon's
problems to those at Lockheed Martin Corp., whose stock has also
fallen this year after it issues earnings warnings.
</P>
<P>
   Of the job cuts announced Tuesday, Raytheon said it would cut
the bulk of positions _ 1,850 _ from plants in California, New
York, and Texas. About 150 positions will come from its Engineers &AMP;
Constructors unit, mainly in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Raytheon had previously indicated it would cut jobs at its
headquarters. Of the other 200 layoffs pending in Massachusetts and
New Hampshire, Raytheon spokesman David Polk said the company
couldn't be more specific about the locations of positions to be
cut. The company also wasn't able to say how many positions were
new cuts and how many related to previous layoff efforts under way
since last year.
</P>
<P>
   The company still has made no decision about the fate of a
microelectronics plant in Quincy, which employs about 450 and for
which the company is considering a sale or closure, Polk said.
</P>
<P>
   In all Raytheon will spend $92 million on severance packages,
and another $55 million for facility closures, none of which will
occur in New England.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking for several hours on their conference call Tuesday,
Burnham and chief financial officer Frank Caine ran through a
litany of issues facing Raytheon, the country's third-largest
defense contractor.
</P>
<P>
   Of great concern to investors is the success of Raytheon's
Patriot missile, which it markets heavily to countries like Greece,
Taiwan, and South Korea in packages worth around $1 billion and up.
Raytheon had hinted it was close to another major deal, but said it
expects no major Patriot orders before next year.
</P>
<P>
   Also, increased competition from Russian and French suppliers
means it expects slimmer profit margins on Patriot than it once
expected, Burnham said.
</P>
<P>
   Raytheon said the single largest portion of the charge it will
take, $320 million, relates to various operating shortcomings at
Raytheon Systems Co. and at Raytheon Engineers &AMP; Constructors,
which builds power plants and other big infrastructure projects.
</P>
<P>
   Much of that amount, $105 million, relates to two military
programs the company said it couldn't identify pending further
negotiations with the Pentagon. In addition, Raytheon said it will
have to write off certain inventories of its AMRAM and Sparrow
air-to-air missiles.
</P>
<P>
   Raytheon also said $25 million of the charge relates to work in
a joint venture with Boeing Co. for business jets. On work for that
contract, ``Our performance has not been good and created a $25
million embarrassment/overrun for us,'' Caine said.
</P>
<P>
   Raytheon said it now estimates 1999 revenue of about $20
billion, about $600 million less than previously forecast, and that
revenue in 2000 won't grow by more than 3 percent, down from its
earlier growth estimate of 6 to 8 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The company now estimates it will earn $2.70 to $2.80 per share
before charges, compared with analyst estimates of about $3.56 per
share. For next year Raytheon estimates earnings of $2.10 to $2.25,
compared to Wall Street estimates of about $3.91 per share.
</P>
<P>
   Also, revenue suffered because the company couldn't hire enough
software engineers, Burnham said, falling 1,000 short of its goal
of hiring 6,000 workers with such skills this year.
</P>
<P>
   Raytheon also said about $35 million in charges relate to
Raytheon's involvement in the troubled Iridium satellite-phone
network, led by Motorola Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Raytheon had planned to detail its bad news at analyst
conferences scheduled for Wednesday, but the company scrubbed those
meetings and moved up its schedule because of an article published
in The Wall Street Journal Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Citing unidentified sources, the story said the company had been
criticized by Pentagon procurement officials for lagging work on
contracts including those for the Tomahawk cruise missile, RC-135
aircraft and Javelin shoulder-fired missile.
</P>
<P>
   Burnham and Caine denied the central elements of that article,
however, saying work on all three programs is proceeding on or
ahead of schedule. A Pentagon spokesman said the agency retains its
confidence in the company, and a Navy spokeswoman for the Tomahawk
program said work is proceeding on schedule and under budget.
Officials for the other programs couldn't be reached to comment
late Tuesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
