u l BC-FASHION-CHANEL-COX     10-12 0550
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FASHION-CHANEL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lagerfeld gives Chanel wearability
 &HT;    By Robert Janjigian
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Among fashion insiders, when a collection is described
as ``commercial,'' it is tantamount to saying a designer has taken
a rest from pushing the edge of the style envelope. In other words,
there's something wearable lurking in there.
</P>
<P>
   At Chanel, Karl Lagerfeld managed to create a spring-summer
collection that incorporated many of the directional concepts seen
on other runways, while making them palatable for the women who
actually buy and wear high-ticket, high-fashion clothing. It was a
collection of great depth and diversity.
</P>
<P>
   He employed snakeskin, but made the material his own by dyeing
it in colors and applying a little sparkle to the surface. There
was leather and there was lace. Colors were brilliant, and included
melons, yellows, pinks, orange and lavender, as well as basic black
and white.
</P>
<P>
   Lagerfeld used denim, but not in an overwhelming way. The
designer handled the fabric as another texture, rather than making
it an excuse to bring street looks to the fore.
</P>
<P>
   Layering also played a big part in the Chanel show look, but
with new twists. There was something for the minimalist, as in
sleek two-piece day dresses with a simple geometric Courreges-style
look, as well as the maximalist _ puffy satin party dresses. These
followed the trend toward shorter cocktail lengths for evening, but
were upbeat and sassy.
</P>
<P>
   With tweedy suits, Chanel's bread-and-butter, Lagerfeld updated
them by including a soft, contrasting scarf hem.
</P>
<P>
   Big, bold abstract floral printed silks, which included double-C
logos, were soft and ruffled and cut into sensible dresses and
skirts. Long dresses, all in black, made an elegant statement from
the house where little black dresses originated.
</P>
<P>
   Lagerfeld hasn't given up his quest for giving Chanel a singular
presence, a signature identity in a competitive fashion arena where
everybody's clamoring to create an identifiable look. Most
designers resort to sticking their name or initials onto as many
things as possible. Lagerfeld has gone beyond that.
</P>
<P>
   While many models indeed had jeweled double-C logos tattooed on
their upper arms or across their chests (a temporary measure that
was hopefully for the runway only), you didn't leave the
presentation thinking you'd witnessed a Chanel logo fest, or that
you couldn't go out of the house wearing anything unless your name
started with ``C.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Lagerfeld turned his full attention toward the quilted
surfaces associated with Chanel handbags. He chose a more pillowy
version of the grid quilting, applying it to a large number of
ensembles, such as the waistband of pleated skirts. Quilted vests
and asymmetrically wrapped bustiers were a refined step away from
fencing or bulletproof protective garb. The gauntlet-style gloves,
which were made of quilted leather, prompted one onlooker to
comment, ``Hey, those would make great grill mitts for next
summer's barbecues.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the message of the quilting was clear and its
application clever.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Janjigian writes for The Palm Beach Daily News, Palm
Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
