<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UNION-GORE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFL-CIO EXPECTED TO ENDORSE GORE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KRANISH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Vice President Al Gore, who has endured weeks of
bad political news and ever-tightening polls, Tuesday hailed the
all-but-certain endorsement of AFL-CIO as a campaign turning point
that will provide thousands of key organizers and millions of
dollars in financial support.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a lift for the campaign. This puts us in a strong
position to win the nomination,'' Donna Brazile, who was promoted
to be Gore's campaign manager in the recent shake-up, said in an
interview here Tuesday. ``In 1992,labor provided one quarter of the
delegates to the Democratic convention, so this is important.''
</P>
<P>
   AFL-CIO political director Steve Rosenthal said the endorsement,
which is to be made official Wednesday, will provide Gore with an
unspecified amount of money _ he called it ``gazillions'' _ as well
as invaluable support from organizers who can turn an election in
key states such as Iowa, California and New York.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the optimistic words, the AFL-CIO endorsement hardly
assures Gore a victory over his lone rival for the nomination,
former New Jersey Senator Bill Bradley. Some unions are likely to
go their own way, endorsing Bradley or perhaps the Republican
nominee. And union members don't always take the suggestion of the
party leadership. Still, the AFL-CIO remains one of the most
important political and financial players in Democratic politics.
</P>
<P>
   Gore can use all the help he can get. In the most recent round
of bad news for Gore, a CNN-USA poll found that Gore leads Bradley
by 51 percent to 39 percent among likely Democratic primary voters.
By comparison, the same poll taken last month found Gore ahead by
63 percent to 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The poll was significant because Bradley's strength until
recently has been concentrated in the few early primary and caucus
states where he has campaigned heavily. The poll indicated that the
burst of positive publicity that Bradley has received in the past
few weeks has translated into national support.
</P>
<P>
   Rosenthal acknowledged that the union membership and support
might be less important in some early states such as New Hampshire,
Delaware and South Carolina. But he said it could be a decisive
factor in many other states, particularly the large bloc that votes
next March 7.
</P>
<P>
   ``We firmly believe that Al Gore can win the nomination and the
White House and we think he is a much better candidate than the
media depicts,'' Rosenthal said.
</P>
<P>
   The endorsement has been all but certain for days. Sweeney said
in an interview last week that the only question was when the
endorsement would come. Tuesday night, any remaining doubt was
expected to be erased when the AFL-CIO's political committee met to
vote on a recommendation. Union officials said there was no doubt
that Gore would get the nod, although Teamsters president James
Hoffa continued to try to urge other union leaders to delay an
endorsement.
</P>
<P>
   Gore declined to speak publicly about the endorsement until it
becomes official Wednesday, but he said through his spokesmen that
he expected it to be a turning point in the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is really the first primary of the Democratic campaign,''
Gore spokesman Chris Lehane said at the Los Angeles convention
center, where the AFL-CIO convention is being held _ and which is
also the site of next year's Democratic national convention. Lehane
said that the endorsement was ``good groundwork'' for winning the
nomination at the convention center next year.
</P>
<P>
   Gore arrived in Los Angeles Tuesday and promptly began visiting
the hotels of union presidents, thanking them for support.
</P>
<P>
   While Bradley had little hope of snaring the AFL-CIO
endorsement, the former senator did hope to delay it for several
months. Bradley spent considerable time courting the Teamsters,
siding with the union in their request to block Mexican trucks with
imported goods from crossing the US border until more inspectors
are hired. While Bradley helped write the North American Free Trade
Act (NAFTA), he hoped his support of the delay of the
truck-crossing measure would translate into union support. Gore,
also a NAFTA backer, has also said he is reviewing the truck issue.
</P>
<P>
   But Gore, as the incumbent vice president, has used the
advantages of his office to court labor, and President Clinton has
worked hard on Gore's behalf, promising to implement pro-labor
policies and meeting last Thursday in New York City with Hoffa.
</P>
<P>
   While union membership has been declining, it is still important
politically. The AFL-CIO believes that labor played a major role in
the election of Democratic governors in Iowa and California in
1988, which are important states in the presidential campaign as
well. Still, labor strength varies greatly from state to state.
Lehane said, for example, that union members make up 20 percent of
likely Democratic voters in New Hampshire, 28 percent in New York,
36 percent in California and 38 percent in Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Rosenthal said that as soon as the endorsement is announced, the
AFL-CIO will begin conducting state-by-state meetings aimed at
organizing the Gore vote. The labor leaders will work closely with
the Gore campaign and state organizations to register voters,
especially minorities, and launch get-out-the-vote drives.
</P>
<P>
   Rosenthal vowed to run a positive campaign on Gore's behalf,
noting that Bradley has ``served himself very well over the last
few months in establishing strong ties to labor. We intend to run a
very positive campaign about Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley was invited to speak to the convention, and he had hoped
to appear here if the AFL-CIO decided to delay the endorsement. But
even though Bradley is slated to be in the Los Angeles area for
fund-raising, he is not expected to show up at the convention
because Gore is getting the endorsement.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley campaign officials could not be reached for comment
Tuesday night on the endorsement.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's win with labor did not come without a glitch.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee AFL-CIO President Jim Neeley, attending the
convention, made excuses for the vice president, whose campaign
hired a non-union contractor last week to do the initial wiring of
his new Nashville, Tenn., headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   Modern Electrical Contracting had 30 phone and computer lines
installed for Gore by last Friday, when the New York Daily News
first reported the contract. They were pulled from the job Friday
night.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-12-99 2058EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
