<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-12 20:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4725 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-FENDI-TAKEOVER-NYT &LR;      10-12 0820
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FENDI-TAKEOVER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRENCH-ITALIAN ALLIANCE TAKES CONTROLLING STAKE IN FENDI 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By JOHN TAGLIABUE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME _ The world's biggest luxury-goods company, LVMH Moet
Hennessy Louis Vuitton of France, forged an unusual alliance
Tuesday with the Italian fashion house Prada to take control of
Fendi SpA, ending a months-long battle for the Rome-based design
house known for its trendy Baguette bags, chic sunglasses and furs
by the designer Karl Lagerfeld.
</P>
<P>
   Under an agreement announced Tuesday, LVMH and Prada paid an
undisclosed amount for a 51 percent stake. Advisers said privately
that the two buyers paid about $520 million, which values the
company around $1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The sale hands control of Fendi to Bernard Arnault, the chairman
of LVMH, and the Prada chairman, Patrizio Bertelli, but leaves the
general management, styling and promotion in the hands of the five
Fendi sisters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fendi today is maybe like Gucci or Prada five years ago; we
want to give this name the full potential,'' Arnault said. ``It is
a very, very hot brand.''
</P>
<P>
   As if to inject a note of continuity, the announcement said that
the Fendis, LVMH and Prada would ``count even in future on the
valuable collaboration of Karl Lagerfeld,'' Fendi's ready-to-wear
designer since 1965.
</P>
<P>
   The prominent mention of Lagerfeld lent credence to reports here
that the five sisters, who each own 20 percent of Fendi, had relied
on Lagerfeld's judgment in deciding upon a new majority owner.
</P>
<P>
   News of the deal was the latest in a series of corporate
shake-ups in the world of luxury goods, which is undergoing rapid
consolidation. That a Frenchman could step in and buy control of
one of Italy's hottest fashion houses was thought by analysts to
have been made possible by the alliance with Prada and Bertelli,
its acquisitive owner.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, Arnault of LVMH fought a bitter takeover
battle for another star of the Italian design world, Gucci. In the
midst of that battle, Bertelli emerged as an ally, when he agreed
to sell a 9.5 percent stake in Gucci that he had amassed to LVMH.
But Gucci's chairman, Domenico De Sole, thwarted the hostile bid by
LVMH when he sold a stake in Gucci to a white knight, Francois
Pinault, a French billionaire and owner of the department-store
chain Pinault-Printemps-Redoute.
</P>
<P>
   In seeking Fendi, Arnault and De Sole fought again. Though
Fendi's sales have been booming _ thanks largely to its Baguette
bags, a sought-after item since their introduction in the fall of
1997, and Lagerfeld's acclaimed ready-to-wear collection _ the
company is poorly managed and lacks the capital to finance global
expansion.
</P>
<P>
   Arnault, in an interview, said that ``on the side of Prada, they
will bring production and creativity in Italy,'' while LVMH would
``bring the international network of shops.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the deal, Prada and LVMH are obligated to acquire any of
the 49 percent of Fendi that the sisters should decide to sell in
the future. Arnault said LVMH and Prada held a common view on
quality and image, and on where the market is going.''
</P>
<P>
   For Gucci, which made $3 billion when it sold a 45 percent stake
to Pinault, the Fendi decision was the second setback in recent
days. On Friday, Gucci reported hitches in its plans to acquire
from Pinault the company that controls the Yves Saint Laurent
brand, Sanofi Beaute, apparently over difficulties with Pierre
Berge, the partner of Yves Saint Laurent and the company's chief
executive. But Gucci says it expects to settle that deal within
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   De Sole evidently backed away from Fendi when the bidding with
Arnault pushed the price that Fendi was asking beyond what he was
thought Gucci should pay.
</P>
<P>
   Fendi says it expects revenue from direct sales and licensed
products to total $330 million this year, up from $321 million in
1998. But De Sole saw the revenue figures as considerably lower.
</P>
<P>
   What appears to have tipped the scales in favor of the
LVMH-Prada link, beyond price, was the concession to Fendi's
creative control of the company. Anna Fendi, one of the sisters and
the mother of Silvia Venturini, the designer of the Baguette bag,
told an Italian news agency, Radiocor, that, ``we will keep Fendi,
even if there will be a merger.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Prada and LVMH have been spending freely in recent months
to fatten their portfolios of luxury-goods companies.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, LVMH paid roughly $800 million to acquire the
Swiss maker of luxury watches, Tag Heuer AG, and took a controlling
share in a San Francisco cosmetics company, Benefit Cosmetics.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, LVMH acquired a controlling share of a British
high-quality shirtmaker, Thomas Pink. Prada, for its part,
announced this summer that it was acquiring controlling stakes in
two privately owned fashion houses, Jil Sander of Germany, and
Helmut Lang, an Austrian design house now based in New York.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
