<HEADLINE>
DILEMMAS OF A SINGLE MAYOR
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``a'' national news file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Jason Nastke &LR; , 20-year-old mayor of Valatie, N.Y. (population
1,500), is interviewed in the latest issue of Seventeen magazine.
His remarks on leisure activities might be instructive for San
Francisco's bachelor mayor:
</P>
<P>
   Q: ``What do you do in your free time?''
</P>
<P>
   A: ``What I love most is dating! I get so many dates because of
who I am. People are intimidated by me, but I tell them, `Hey, I'm
just Jason!' ''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; JOHN HURT'S ACTING LESSONS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The British actor  &UR; John Hurt &LR;  shares some unusually frank
appraisals of fellow actors in the latest issue of Madison
magazine:
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; Robert De Niro &LR;  is ``brilliant in comedy because he stops
worrying.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Hurt has never known ``a performance of  &UR; Brando &LR; 's that was
anything other than a gift to the audience. It's never been just
for himself.''
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Ralph Fiennes &LR; , who was in a London production of ``Ivanov,''
made some ``fundamental'' errors. ``He chose to play passion loud.
The danger of that is the minute you play passion loud, it's
tantamount to being aggressive. You put the audience at arm's
length.''
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Anthony Hopkins &LR;  is ``an intriguing actor, &LR; '' but ``a strange
creature. He feels that if he isn't shaking his head, he's not
getting his passion across. ... If you shake your head and shout,
it can give the impression that you don't understand. ... That's
when it becomes what is called ham.''
</P>
<P>
   On the difference between movies and the theater, Hurt said,
``Theater presents something. In cinema you let people into the
world you're weaving. That's the glory of film. It's immensely
private. You get to create a reality and invite the audience to see
things that they don't normally see.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ANCHORMAN SPEAKS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   A letter from the Cultural Institutions Group, a New York
consortium of museums and arts groups, protesting Mayor  &UR; Rudolph &LR; 
 &UR; Giuliani &LR; 's threats to the Brooklyn Museum over its ``Sensations''
show went unsigned by a third of the group's members. One major
abstainer was Carnegie Hall, whose representative told the New York
Times: ``The only statement we can make is that we have no
statement to make.''
</P>
<P>
   Not so board member  &UR; Peter Jennings &LR; . Although Jennings, the
ABC-TV anchorman, said he was unable to attend the meeting in which
a vote was taken, he stepped beyond the traditional journalist's
neutrality on the issue. ``It's a mistake for Carnegie Hall, a
leading cultural institution, to remain mute,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ An appeal for blood donors by German Health Minister  &UR; Andrea &LR; 
 &UR; Fischer &LR;  elicited a response from  &UR; Count Dracula &LR; , says a note from
Chemical and Engineering News forwarded by  &UR; Peter Linde &LR; . The
count, whose full name is Ottomar Rudolphe Vlad Dracul Prince
Kretzulesco, is the last link of the Dracul family, &LR;  and lives in a
castle near Berlin.
</P>
<P>
   He led an August campaign for blood, &LR;  and attended vampire movie
screenings intended to attract donors.
</P>
<P>
   _ Science fiction editor, actor and writer &UR; Forrest J. Ackerman &LR; ,
81, who was  &UR; Ed Wood &LR; 's agent and coined the term ``sci-fi,'' got
his start in the genre with his first published story, in The San
Francisco Chronicle in 1929. In Ackerman's story, ``A Trip to
Mars,'' a copy of The Chronicle saved the world from destruction.
Personals returns the favor by mentioning he'll be at Booksmith on
Haight Street on October 15  &LR; at 7 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   _ Variety reports that Sen.  &UR; John McCain &LR; , R-Ariz., a
presidential candidate, has sold movie rights to his book, ``Faith
of My Fathers,'' to USA Films, which is run by  &UR; Barry &LR; 
 &UR; Diller &LR; . Buyer and seller are refusing to discuss dollar amounts.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``I love bed. I (was) ... in bed for seven years, and then got
up and went around the world. Of course, in those days there were
more servants to bring you the food and things. But it was nice,
wasn't it? Just went to bed for seven years.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Actor Robert Morley, from Studs Turkel's new book, ``The
Spectator: Talk About Movies and Plays With Those Who Make Them''
(New Press; $26.95).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
