<DOCNO> NYT19991012.0339 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-12 21:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4728 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-HANCOCK-EXECUTIVE-BOS     10-12 0902
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HANCOCK-EXECUTIVE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOHN HANCOCK PRESIDENT TO BECOME CHIEF EXECUTIVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNNLEY BROWNING  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ In a swift reshuffle on the eve of its metamorphosis
into a Wall Street-listed player, John Hancock Mutual Life
Insurance Co. said Tuesday that its president, David F.
D'Alessandro, would succeed Stephen L. Brown as chief executive
next June.
</P>
<P>
   The change, approved by Hancock's board, is designed to reassure
investors about management issues before the Boston-based insurer
sells around $2 billion in stock to the public in early 2000, in a
highly anticipated initial public offering.
</P>
<P>
   D'Alessandro, Hancock's president and chief operations officer,
had long been pegged for the top job. But with company policy not
requiring Brown, 62, to retire for another two years,
D'Alessandro's ascension to the main post will come sooner than
expected.
</P>
<P>
   The change will bring the insurance industry's most unorthodox,
flamboyant, and outspoken player to the helm of a once-staid
company in the midst of major change.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted things to be clear before the IPO and the
roadshow,'' D'Alessandro said in a brief interview, referring to
presentations that Hancock will make to investors around the
country before selling stock. Brown will remain chairman of Hancock
and play a more active role in overseeing its mutual fund
operations.
</P>
<P>
   Hancock officials said it was Brown's idea to step down on June
1 after eight years in the top job. ``It is very important for our
policyholders, our future investors, and Wall Street to know who
will be at the management helm of our company, what role they will
play,'' Brown said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   D'Alessandro, 48, is the youngest chief executive ever in
Hancock's 137-year history. A journalism and public relations major
at Utica College who took one semester of mathematics and never
went to business school, he is a far cry from the typical,
gray-suited insurance executive. A marketing specialist famed for
his flashy ties, he joined Hancock in 1984 as a spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Atypical for a hidebound industry, his activities have gone
beyond traditional insurance. D'Alessandro is best known in Boston
as the man who revived the flagging Boston Marathon. And earlier
this year he became a vocal critic of the International Olympic
Committee and its corruption scandal _ despite Hancock's status as
a major Olympics sponsor.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, the low-profile Brown, a trained actuary who spent
his entire career at Hancock after graduating from Middlebury
College in 1958, joined the company when he was 21 and rose slowly
through the ranks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ultimately, the company is going to demand to be run
differently,'' D'Alessandro said in a brief interview. ``This
company is going to be driven by shareholder value, which is an
entirely different concept from focusing on just earnings and
surplus growth.'' The latter is a measure of wealth particular to
the insurance business.
</P>
<P>
   Hancock is a mutual insurer, meaning it is formally owned by its
policyholders. Like many of its competitors, it no longer regards
that centuries-old form of ownership as practical in the modern
financial services world, and will instead become a publicly traded
company, with shares listed on the New York Stock Exchange.
Eligible policyholders will trade their ownership ``rights'' for
cash, stock, or souped-up policies.?
</P>
<P>
   But the IPO, which could be the industry's largest ever, is not
just designed to raise extra cash to pay shareholders. Hancock
wants stock in order to finance acquisitions and to attract and
retain top talent.
</P>
<P>
   Hancock, one of the insurance industry's most profitable
companies, sells various forms of insurance, including life,
long-term care and annuities, and mutual funds, which are sold
through through third-party channels.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're going to see Hancock recognize its role more actively
as a manufacturer, rather than as a distributor, of products,''
D'Alessandro said, referring to plans to expand Hancock's presence
in the investment management business.
</P>
<P>
   While Hancock cannot make acquisitions for two years after the
public offering, some industry analysts see it merging with another
company.
</P>
<P>
   ``They say they're not interested in a bank, but when you look
at their operations, there are natural synergies to be gained in
being with a broader financial services company,'' said Michael
Cowan, an industry analyst at A M Best, a ratings firm.
</P>
<P>
   Under Brown, the nation's sixth-largest mutual insurer doubled
its assets under management to $124.4 billion and grew net income
by 140 percent to $627 million last year.
</P>
<P>
   D'Alessandro is credited with revamping Hancock's career sales
ranks and launching successful advertising campaigns. As president,
he is in charge of insurance and retail investments, technology,
personnel, marketing, and financial operations.
</P>
<P>
   As chief executive, D'Alessandro will also oversee Hancock's
investment operations, institutional pension business, and
corporate strategy. Hancock said D'Alessandro now oversees
Hancock's investment and pension sector. Brown remains on Hancock's
important policy-making committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ultimately, the personality of the chief executive says a lot
about the personality of the company,'' Cowan said. ``With Dave,
you're going to see some real action.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-12-99 2104EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
