<DOCNO> NYT19991012.0341 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-12 21:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4731 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-SCHOOLS-VIOLENCE(TRIM     10-12 1229
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOLS-VIOLENCE(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONSULTANT ON PREVENTING SCHOOL VIOLENCE IS KEEPING BUSY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)   (bl)  
 By SCOTT COLLINS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WESTLAKE VILLAGE, Calif. _ These are busy days for Ronald
Stephens, an expert on school violence.
</P>
<P>
   A stack of 20 as-yet-unanswered phone messages bellows like an
accordion from Stephens' open briefcase. His well-thumbed date book
is jammed with appointments in a tiny scrawl. He started the week
leading a seminar in New Mexico; now he is about to fly to Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm in deep trouble,'' he jokes, when asked how his wife copes
with his long absences from home (about a third of his time since
January).
</P>
<P>
   As horrible as the nation's spate of school shootings has been
for students, parents and administrators, it has been a boon for
Stephens, head of the National School Safety Center in this
wealthy, bucolic Los Angeles suburb just east of Malibu.
</P>
<P>
   He has become one of the nation's most widely quoted authorities
on school violence. In May, a month after the shootings at
Columbine High School in Littleton, Colo., Stephens appeared on
television 25 times. His writings on school safety have been
published in a number of newspapers and magazines, from USA Today
to the Journal of the American Medical Association. He crisscrosses
the country, giving workshops on school violence, training
administrators to watch for volatile youngsters and inspecting
their schools for security and evaluating their evacuation plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tragedy at Columbine High School has underscored how much
work remains to be done,'' says Stephens, a trim, graying man of
52.
</P>
<P>
   Schools, Stephens hastens to say, remain relatively safe. One of
his favorite statistics, which he often uses in conversations, is
that young people are 99 times more likely to be shot and killed on
the street or at home than in school _ a figure that may bring cold
comfort to worried parents.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he belies his own nonchalance by counseling principals
and teachers to be prepared for anything. He seems to be trying to
find a middle ground _ reassuring parents that schools are safe but
making sure that administrators are ready for violence when it
happens.
</P>
<P>
   ``I divide administrators into two camps,'' Stephens said.
``Those who've faced a crisis, and those who are about to.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   At a recent workshop in Westlake Village, Stephens invited
Pasadena Police Chief Jarado Blue to deliver a rough-and-ready talk
to 37 administrators and school board members who traveled from as
far away as Georgia to get pointers on dealing with violence in
schools. Blue quickly disposed of any remaining complacency in the
room when he referred to the participants in the workshop as ``soft
targets'' _ that is, sitting ducks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Make sure you don't evacuate into an area where a sniper could
shoot,'' he warned.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Unlike some of his colleagues, Stephens focuses on how to
prevent school violence rather than investigating its root causes.
In preparing his workshops and booklets, Stephens borrows freely
from school districts whose policies he admires. His approach is
mainly prescriptive: administrators should engage in random locker
checks, review the students' use of the Internet at school and
strictly limit visits by outsiders.
</P>
<P>
   He encourages schools to develop detailed crisis plans, and he
gives workshop participants quizzes to help them evaluate their
districts' readiness. Arguing that careful preparation can stem a
catastrophe, he notes that eight different SWAT teams responded to
the Columbine shootings, which made coordination difficult.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps surprisingly, Stephens is not a big fan of metal
detectors and closed-circuit cameras, which he believes can create
a false sense of security. ``There's not a high-tech strategy
around that can predict whether a youngster will commit an act of
violence,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Many officials, who say they are besieged by would-be safety
experts after every school shooting, have come to trust Stephens as
a consistent and moderating influence.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think he's probably the most knowledgeable person involved
with school safety,'' says Bob Moore, superintendent of the
Independent School District in Amarillo, Texas, which paid Stephens
$2,000 last July to talk with school officials.
</P>
<P>
   After his district had a nonfatal shooting in 1991, Moore said,
``We had all these safety consultants coming out of the walls _
they're all trying to sell you something, and a lot of them don't
know what they're talking about.''
</P>
<P>
   Others are less enthusiastic about Stephens' work. Some critics
are skeptical of his self-scoring checklists, which are supposed to
evaluate problem students and a school's potential for violence.
One such test asks officials, ``Has there been a recent emergence
of an underground student newspaper?''
</P>
<P>
   ``It sounds like Big Brother, doesn't it?'' scoffs Kevin Dwyer,
president of the National Association of School Psychologists in
Bethesda, Md. Dwyer believes such lists often encourage snap
judgments based on weak evidence. ``I think it gets us into this
whole area of `profiling' that we're worried about'' in the society
at large, he added.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Stephens is a Vietnam War veteran who was a social-studies
teacher and school administrator before becoming an education
professor at Pepperdine University in Malibu. In 1984, President
Ronald Reagan created the National School Safety Center, with
support from the Education and Justice departments, and the center
was affiliated with Pepperdine. Stephens was chosen to run the
center in 1985.
</P>
<P>
   He is still sorting out some of the hot-button issues
surrounding school violence. When asked his position on gun
control, he said: ``This is a hard topic for me. I feel like
criminals are going to get handguns anyway. I'm still not convinced
that we have to take handguns away from every responsible
citizen.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Nor has Stephens escaped political controversy. Pepperdine is
perhaps best-known for once offering a job at its law school to
Kenneth Starr, the independent counsel whose investigation of the
Monica Lewinsky scandal led to President Clinton's impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, when the center failed to win a renewable $1 million
federal grant, Stephens, according to a published report, accused
Clinton appointees of rejecting the application because of Starr's
investigation. Education officials denied the charge, and Stephens
now says a reporter misconstrued his position.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, the loss of funds has hurt the center, and its annual
budget has plummeted to $250,000 from $1.2 million, requiring
Stephens to lay off half of his eight-member staff. (In the 1980s,
the center had about 30 employees.)
</P>
<P>
   Stephens said he planned to make up for the shortfall through
corporate sponsors and fund raising, as well as through fees from
workshops and booklets.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the setback, Stephens said he was more committed than
ever to spreading his message of school safety. That is partly
because of the headlines that every parent has now grown to dread.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're dealing with more challenging circumstances now
than ever before,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
