u s BC-BBA-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT     10-12 0837
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: THE RED SOX COULD HIJACK THE SUBWAY SERIES  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By HARVEY ARATON    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Over the weekend, the Boston Red Sox beat up on the Cleveland
pitching staff badly enough to outscore the New York area's two
professional football teams combined, 44-9. Now if the Red Sox can
out-hit the Yankees, if they can come up with someone other than
Pedro Martinez to pitch, they just might find themselves with the
chance to ruin two baseball teams in the town that has tormented
them most.
</P>
<P>
   For a franchise that has managed to simultaneously be storied
yet sad, this is the opportunity of the century, the Great American
Century, which happens to acknowledge, that's right, Boston, as its
first official World Series winner in 1903. Now that the 1999 Red
Sox have rid the playoffs of an Indians' logo that is so
insensitive to Native Americans, and with the Mets teaming with
destiny to obstruct the irritating tomahawk-choppers in Atlanta, it
could mean that the baseball gods are trying to settle old debts
before turning the page.
</P>
<P>
   Afford the Red Sox last ups, one finalat a rousing finish
to a century of pain. Give them a shot at denying the hated Yankees
their 25th World Series trophy and the greatest .250 average
baseball will ever know. Then bring on the Mets, and let the Red
Sox square things for the most humiliating experience of all.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is to see who gets to the Series,'' Darryl Strawberry
said. ``It's been a long time for them.''
</P>
<P>
   It's been since 1918 since the Red Sox won the Series, but they
never suffered as when they were last there, in 1986. No one in the
current Red Sox lineup could vouch for this, like the Yankee who
will start Game 3 of a American League Championship Series that
begins Wednesday night. Roger Clemens wasn't up Tuesday for
dwelling on past failure. Strawberry, however, sounded happy to
report that he's sure Clemens ``looks over at me in here and is
thinking, `He's wearing the ring I should be wearing.'''
</P>
<P>
   An out away in Game 6, the one a young Clemens started, no one
on, and some of the Mets' biggest stars already back in a clubhouse
resigned to defeat, uniforms off. Then a base hit. Then another.
And another, and soon, a wild pitch, and the tying run was crossing
the plate.
</P>
<P>
   Someone, as Strawberry recalled Tuesday, in the Mets' clubhouse
said: ``Let's put our clothes back on.''
</P>
<P>
   After being undressed by the Yankees for decades, here come the
Red Sox, the underdog Red Sox, the little engine that could hijack
New York's Subway Series. Here they come for more major league
misery or, if you believe they are armed with the magic of
Martinez, poised to get the last 100-year laugh.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez one-hit the Yankees several weeks ago at Yankee
Stadium, good reason to believe they weren't celebrating the
collapse of the Cleveland staff Monday night. If the Red Sox can
manage a split of the first two games in New York, if the series
somehow goes seven, the Yankees battle cry will be: Gimme an Uh and
an Oh.
</P>
<P>
   ``For all the physical things that Pedro brings to the table,
he's got that psychological edge because of what he's accomplished
this year,'' said Joe Torre, the Yankee manager, who gets points
for taking the dramatic license to match Clemens against Martinez
Saturday at Fenway Park in Game 3.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe this is nit-picking, but what, exactly, were Martinez and
the Red Sox waiting for Monday night, once Martinez had resolved to
withstand the pain in his back and pitch? Obviously, they were
hoping to get by without him, so he could go three times against
the Yankees. Given the way the rest of the Red Sox pitch and how
the Indians hit, it was a never-say-die script Harrison Ford should
read. Somehow it worked out. The Curse of the Bambino was lifted,
the way it was in Game 5 of the league championship series in 1986,
when the Angels were an out away from taking out the Red Sox in
five.
</P>
<P>
   Then it reappeared, disguised as a ground ball between Bill
Buckner's legs.
</P>
<P>
   Is it possible, at the turn of the Millennium, that could be
gone for good?
</P>
<P>
   ``No matter what teams are left after this, you're going to have
a great end of the baseball season,'' said Jim Leyritz, the
Yankees' spare part who passed briefly through Boston doing the
journeyman's shuffle the last few years. ``You couldn't have
written a better script.''
</P>
<P>
   Not unless you live west of the Eastern time zone. Honey, we've
shrunk the majors. Sorry, Los Angeles. Too bad, Arizona. How's
that, Bud Selig? This is what the baseball gods have to say about
New Yorkers being made to stay up until 2 a.m. last week to watch
the Mets. When the clock strikes midnight now, we will be
conditioned, alert, waiting for something weird.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the Red Sox win the Series, they might shut down Boston
for a few days,'' said John Valentin. ``And maybe the President
will come to Boston instead of us going to the president.''
</P>
<P>
   It would be the very least they could ask.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
