<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TREATY-DEBATE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE CONSERVATIVES REJECT PLAN TO POSTPONE VOTE ON TEST BAN
TREATY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT14 is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(sw) 
 By ERIC SCHMITT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Senate conservatives on Tuesday rejected a
compromise by the Republican and Democratic leaders to postpone
action on a treaty banning underground nuclear testing, imperiling
the fate of the accord.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Both leaders said they would resume talks on Wednesday to find
wording acceptable to all senators, acknowledging that the treaty
lacks the two-thirds majority to pass. The issue now, they added,
is whether the Senate defeats the pact or finds a face-saving way
to withdraw it from consideration.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The setback illustrates the tricky political position
confronting the Senate majority leader, Trent Lott. He is juggling
the demands of 55 diverse Republicans, many of whom want to delay a
treaty vote to avoid a diplomatic embarrassment and others who want
to kill the pact regardless of the international repercussions. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Lott took a step toward averting a vote when he
signaled that he would accept assurances from Senate Democrats that
they would not seek action on the treaty until President Clinton
leaves office. Republicans had insisted that Clinton make that
pledge, but he has refused.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``If we can be guaranteed that it would be set aside and not
come up in this Congress, then we could accept that,'' Lott told
reporters after a spirited luncheon with other Senate Republicans.
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic leader, Tom Daschle, answered Lott's call, saying
in a letter that he would support Clinton's request to postpone the
vote and agreed not to reschedule the treaty, absent ``unforeseen
changes in the international situation.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After Republicans balked, Daschle changed the phrase to
``extraordinary circumstances,'' as defined by the two leaders.
Democrats insisted on that provision in the event Pakistan or
India, for example, resumed nuclear weapons tests.
</P>
<P>
   But the wording drew strong opposition from Republican
hard-liners like Sens. Jon Kyl of Arizona and Jesse Helms of North
Carolina, who complained that Democrats would use the ``loophole''
to seize on the slightest global disturbance and wield the treaty
as a campaign issue next year.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The objections killed a proposed exchange on the Senate floor
between Lott and Daschle that would have defused the political and
procedural brhip that has engulfed the treaty since Lott
surprised Democrats two weeks ago by answering their demand to
bring it up with a no-notice vote.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Under the proposed agreement, the Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty
would be sent back to the Foreign Relations Committee for further
hearings.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Tuesday's setback, a growing number of Democrats and
Republicans seemed eager to postpone the vote. Sens. John Warner,
R-Va., Republican, and Daniel Patrick Moynihan, D-N.Y., released a
letter today to their two leaders, endorsing efforts to delay
Senate action on the treaty until the next Congress convenes in
2001.
</P>
<P>
   About a dozen senators have signed the letter so far.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine Albright telephoned half a dozen
moderate Republicans on Tuesday, urging them to consider the
diplomatic consequences.
</P>
<P>
   Treaty supporters have warned that the Senate's defeat of the
accord would send a dangerous signal to emerging nuclear nations
like India and Pakistan that it was acceptable to continue testing.
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, amid reports of a military coup in Pakistan, Lott
scoffed at those concerns and said the unrest in Pakistan would not
have any bearing on the Senate's action.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Why should it have any bearing on this debate? Lott said.
``What we're talking about in this treaty is the national security
of our own country. Nothing we do here will have any affect on the
government in Pakistan.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The behind-the-scenes maneuvering overshadowed the Senate's
second day of debate on the treaty itself. Critics and supporters
mostly read from prepared statements, speaking to a largely empty
chamber.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Democrats expressed astonishment that Republicans would insist
on voting on a pact that the president requested withdrawn for
national security reasons.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The opponents of the treaty have won, for now,'' said Sen.
Joseph Lieberman, D-Conn. ``Why push for this vote if the president
of the United States has asked for delay because of his fears? This
isn't politics. This goes to the heart of our security.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But critics argued the pact would permanently bind the United
States' ability to test while rogue nations, and perhaps even China
and Russia, cheated and conducted nuclear explosions that eroded
America's atomic deterrent.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The treaty is based on noble, idealistic goals, but it fails
the hard-reality test,'' said Sen. Jim Bunning, R-Ky. ``The U.S.
usually lives up to the agreements it signs. But there is no
guarantee that other nations would follow the letter of the law.''
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   To put the treaty into effect, ratification by 44 nations
believed to have a nuclear capacity is needed. Only 26 countries,
including Britain and France, have done so. China, which has not
ratified the pact and is taking its lead from the United States, on
Tuesday urged the Senate to approve the treaty.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-12-99 2110EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
