<DOCNO> NYT19991012.0344 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-12 21:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4736 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBA-PEDRO-BOS &LR;      10-12 1437
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-PEDRO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A HIGHER LEVEL, EVEN FOR PEDRO MARTINEZ 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A few months ago he was simply being called
baseball's ``dominant pitcher.'' In recent weeks, however, his name
had often been preceded by the words ``shoo-in Cy Young Award
winner.'' But Monday night in Cleveland, Pedro Martinez reached an
even higher level.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez now has a rare athletic aura encircling him. He now has
a mystique about him.
</P>
<P>
   He had popped a few Advil into his mouth Monday night and, two
days after not being able to throw a baseball 40 feet because of a
strained back muscle, he had held baseball's best-hitting team
hitless for six innings. Martinez did not have his fastball, but he
had his heart. And that was enough to lead the Red Sox to a 12-8
victory in the deciding Game 5 of their American League Division
Series against the Indians. It was a rare moment in Boston's
storied baseball history.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel good,'' the Mystique Man said in the Yankee Stadium
clubhouse Tuesday. ``I am sure I can work through it. And now I
have more days to rest, I should be OK.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, he will have four days rest when he takes the mound
Saturday amid what may be the most electric atmosphere inside
Fenway Park in years: Martinez pitching Game 3 of the AL
Championship Series for the Red Sox against Roger Clemens for the
Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   Pedro vs. Roger? It may sound like an enticing personal duel to
Boston fans, but not to Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not facing Roger,'' he said. ``Roger is not the one
hitting against me. I'm facing the New York Yankees. That's who I'm
worried about, not Roger. Roger doesn't hit. Roger has to worry
about my teammates, Nomar (Garciaparra), the (Troy) O'Learys, those
guys.''
</P>
<P>
   And then the Mystique Man offered this coup de grace: ``Roger?
Roger is just a pitcher out there.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A significant part of the Martinez mystique is pride. As
pitching coach Joe Kerrigan, teammate Mike Stanley, and other Red
Sox said in the happy mayhem following Monday night's win in
Cleveland, Martinez doesn't just want to be in that situation, he
craves it.
</P>
<P>
   No one knows this better than older brother Ramon Martinez, who
was so worried when Pedro walked to the mound in the fourth inning,
sore back and all, then was so proud after his little brother had
pulled off his marvel of marvels.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he came into the game, I knew he wasn't 100 percent,''
said Ramon. ``I was so nervous.''
</P>
<P>
   When Pedro got through that fourth inning, Ramon rushed over to
his brother.
</P>
<P>
   ``I asked him how he feel, and he said he felt fine,'' recalled
Ramon. ``Pedro say, `Everything under control.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Then Ramon asked his little brother how the other part of him
felt _ his emotions, his mind _ when two days earlier he could not
throw a baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I ask Pedro how he feel,'' said Ramon, ``and Pedro say,
`Nervous. But everything's under control.' ''
</P>
<P>
   After every inning _ the fourth, fifth, sixth, seventh, and
eighth _ Ramon would go over to Pedro.
</P>
<P>
   The question from big brother was always the same: ``Pedro, how
do you feel?''
</P>
<P>
   And despite the little brother's assurances, Ramon could not
relax.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was so nervous,'' he said. ``I was in the dugout, but every
time Pedro throw the ball, I was ready to run out to the mound. And
when he come back to the dugout, I'd ask him again.''
</P>
<P>
   Ramon acknowledged that at least part of the reason he kept
asking the same question was simply to say something, to say
anything to relieve the twin pressures of the Red Sox absolutely
needing to win the game and his brother risking an aggravation of
his back injury. But, really, Ramon never had to ask Pedro a thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know my brother, I know him so well,'' said Ramon. ``I could
see in his eyes. I look in Pedro's eyes and I see the fire. I could
see from his eyes he was fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Ramon had seen the fire as early as Sunday night, when no one
else knew that Pedro would be ready to pitch Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I ask him after the (fourth) game and Pedro tell me, `I'm
going to be there,' '' said Ramon. ``And I told Pedro that all of
us were going to be there for him. He was happy to hear that. And
that was it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Yankees manager Joe Torre agrees that Martinez has the Mystique:
``There is no question that aside from all the physical things that
Pedro brings to the table, he has got that psychological edge of
what he has accomplished this year. There is no question. We will
go out there and hopefully be able to match him.''
</P>
<P>
   Torre will hope to match Martinez on Saturday by sending out
Clemens, which ``will be a lot of fun,'' said the manager.
``Obviously, what Roger has meant to that organization and that
ballpark for a number of years and, of course, what Pedro has done
this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of all, what Martinez did Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   In the second inning, Martinez went over to Kerrigan and manager
Jimy Williams ``and he just wanted to assure us he was OK,'' said
Kerrigan. ``I was as surprised as anybody else. We had formulated
our game plan before the game, and all we were thinking was maybe
Pedro could give us an inning at the end of the game.''
</P>
<P>
   By the third inning, though, the score was 8-8, and Martinez had
seen enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just wanted to settle the game down,'' said Kerrigan. ``We
just wanted to bring some normalcy to the game. It was looking like
one of those backyard softball games.''
</P>
<P>
   Kerrigan was amazed by what he saw. Instead of Martinez giving
his all for an inning or two, said the pitching coach, ``I saw him
getting looser and then he got stronger as he went on.''
</P>
<P>
   And each inning, when Martinez stepped out of the dugout, said
the pitching coach, ``I was watching Pedro when he got back to the
mound and watched him throw his warmup pitches and I was looking
for any stiffness. I was just watching for him tightening up.''
</P>
<P>
   Kerrigan was expecting Martinez to throw maybe 40 pitches.
Instead, the ace went out inning after inning, six of them in all,
throwing a total of 97 pitches. Kerrigan could only marvel at what
he saw.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's Pedro,'' he said. ``That's the legend of Pedro.''
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, in the outfield at Fenway Park, Martinez could toss
the ball only a few times before having to call it quits.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's when I thought Pedro had no chance of pitching,'' said
Kerrigan. ``No chance. He and I threw only four or five balls, only
at a distance of 40 or 50 feet, and Pedro told me, `No, I can't do
it.' ''
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, in the gloom and mist and drizzle of late afternoon
in Fenway, Martinez was encouraged by being able to toss the ball _
tossing it only moderately, mind you _ for all of eight minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``But Pedro was still a little fatigued depite playing catch in
the outfield for only eight minutes,'' said Kerrigan. ``That was on
my mind. The fatigue.''
</P>
<P>
   Early Tuesday morning, in the mayhem of the Red Sox clubhouse in
Cleveland, as Kerrigan looked on as Pedro and Ramon Martinez hooked
arms and danced to a salsa beat, the pitching coach was nearly
speechless when asked to put Martinez's performance into context.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know . . . geez,'' said Kerrigan. ``It was one of the
most heroic, gutsy performance you've ever seen. I mean, Pedro was
so alive. I mean, Pedro brought so much life to our bench. I mean,
he'd come in between innings and he was nothing but a chatterbox,
bringing our offensive people along with him. He was real loose, he
was chattering away, he was having fun out there. He loves that
situation. He lives for it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Martinez said he had never before felt what he felt when the Red
Sox carried him off the Jacobs Field mound on their shoulders.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just a great, great feeling,'' he said. ``It was my
first time I experienced something like that and, you know, you
pretty much have to live it to understand it.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez is hoping to keep the feeling going. It's all about
winning, whether in this historic Red Sox-Yankees rivalry or any
other series.
</P>
<P>
   ``My rivalry is really against any team,'' said Martinez.
``That's my personal rivalry. I'm going to feel about the Yankees
the way I feel about any team. I don't have anything against any
team; I don't have anything against Roger. I respect Roger just as
Roger has to respect our team.''
</P>
<P>
   So, concluded Martinez, ``I'm just going to go out there and
play the way I know how to play and forget about the fact that Babe
Ruth was traded in 19 . . . I guess, 18? Or sold. Or whatever. And
just go out there and play my game.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
