<HEADER>
A4742 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-CONGRESS-BUDGET-NYT &LR;      10-12 0812
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON PAPER, BUDGET BALANCES WITHOUT RAID ON SOCIAL SECURITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By TIM WEINER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Something symbolically enormous may have happened
Tuesday: the Congressional Budget Office announced that the
government may have balanced the budget in fiscal 1999 without
spending Social Security money.
</P>
<P>
   If so, it would be the first time that has happened since 1960,
when Dwight Eisenhower was president, gentlemen sported felt
fedoras and women wore fox stoles.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans, who have struggled to find a way to balance the
2000 budget without spending Social Security money, jumped on the
budget office's estimate as evidence of their fiscal discipline.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even with all the emergency spending we had in '99, we did not
spend Social Security dollars,'' said the House majority leader,
Dick Armey, R-Texas. ``This is, like, the first time, and we really
stepped over the line now.''
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton and the Republicans in Congress are locked in
a political struggle over whether the spending bills that Congress
writes and the president signs will once again dip into the Social
Security surplus. Both parties have portrayed themselves as
protectors of the retirement funds.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's announcement may make those arguments more politically
potent than ever. But budget experts continue to point out that the
arguments are over such relatively small figures that they have
almost no impact on the economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've reached the promised land, at least temporarily,'' said
Robert D. Reischauer, director of the budget office from 1989 to
1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fiscally, it's irrelevant,'' he said. ``But it's
psychologically and symbolically very important. If any budget
expert told you in 1997 that we would have balanced the budget by
1999, this person would have been committed'' to an asylum.
</P>
<P>
   The budget office said the government's general revenues showed
a $1 billion surplus for fiscal 1999, which ended Sept. 30. It
cautioned that the figures were preliminary. They may be off by as
much as $3 billion, so the promised land may be a mirage.
</P>
<P>
   Surplus Social Security funds have functioned as money under the
mattress for Congress for four decades. When general government
revenues to run federal agencies run out, Congress taps into the
retirement funds. Almost all outside experts say that spending
Social Security surpluses has had no effect on its benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans have been vowing almost daily never again to spend
the money. Speaker J. Dennis Hastert again promised Tuesday never
to ``return to the days when Democrats raided Social Security.''
</P>
<P>
   The struggle, which both sides have represented as a fight to
``save Social Security,'' has driven the Republicans to employ tens
of billions of dollars in accounting devices, which even some in
their own party are calling gimmicks and tricks, to make their
spending bills appear to keep that promise.
</P>
<P>
   Though both parties rushed to claim credit for Tuesday's
supposed surplus, the new numbers calculated by the budget office
show that everyone in Washington underestimated the force that may
have balanced the budget: unexpectedly high tax revenues generated
by a rip-roaring economy.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, most people believed that Congress had spent at
least $21 billion and as much as $37 billion in Social Security
funds in the fiscal 1999 spending bills.
</P>
<P>
   But as the tax money rolled into the federal counting house this
spring and summer, that number dwindled. Tuesday, on paper, it
disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   The report that the budget may be balanced ``is probably worth a
good headline, but beyond that it is not clear what it will
portend,'' said Dan Crippen, director of the budget office since
1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether we are on one side or another of the line by a billion
is not as important as the economic growth that caused us to arrive
at the line,'' Crippen said.
</P>
<P>
   And Gene Sperling, director of the National Economic Council,
credited the White House for ``an enormous fiscal achievement that
seemed unimaginable when President Clinton took office.''
</P>
<P>
   Reischauer, a veteran of past budget battles, demurred.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is every likelihood that we will fall from grace in the
current fiscal year unless saved again by the power of the economy
to generate unexpected revenues,'' he said ``And woe be to those
who are blamed for a fall from grace.''
</P>
<P>
   The new budget office figures show about $125 billion in excess
Social Security funds for fiscal 1999, above and beyond the
projected $1 billion surplus in general government revenues.
</P>
<P>
   If Congress really has the will to keep its hands off the Social
Security surpluses for the next 10 years, about $2 trillion of
those revenues will accrue, says the budget office.
</P>
<P>
   Left untouched, they would halve the federal debt of more than
$3.6 trillion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
