<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-12 21:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4743 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBA-SOX-RIVALRY-2TAKE     10-12 1102
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-SOX-RIVALRY-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO TEAMS JOINED BY HISTORY 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   And so, destiny brings them together again in the final October
of the 1900s, 21 years after Bucky Bleeping Dent's wedge shot found
the screen above The Wall.
</P>
<P>
   They have been intertwined, the Red Sox and Yankees, since they
came down to the final day in 1904 (they were the Pilgrims and
Highlanders then) and Happy Jack Chesbro uncorked a wild pitch to
give Boston the pennant.
</P>
<P>
   When the Sox opened Fenway Park in 1912, they played New York.
When Yankee Stadium opened in 1923, Boston was the visitor. Babe
Ruth hit his first home run against the Yankees. Lou Gehrig hit his
first against the Red Sox. Ted Williams played his first game in
Yankee Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   When Roger Maris hit his 61st homer in 1961, Boston's Tracy
Stallard served it up. When Joe Cronin broke his leg and ended his
career, he did it at Yankee Stadium. When Williams spat at the
Fenway fans in 1956, he'd just been booed for muffing Mickey
Mantle's fly ball. When Billy Martin and Reggie Jackson nearly came
to blows in the dugout, it happened at Fenway.
</P>
<P>
   They are Sparta and Athens, these two, the Bronx and the Fens,
pinstripes and carmine hose, World Series rings _ and the Curse of
the Bambino.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox and Yankees are the ``lyric bandbox'' and the House That
Ruth Built, the Splendid Splinter and the Yankee Clipper, Curt
Gowdy and Mel Allen. They are Joe McCarthy pinch-hitting for Ellis
Kinder, Cy Young pitching a no-hitter at 41, Martin and Jimmy
Piersall fighting in the runway, Bill Lee calling the Yankees
``brownshirts,'' Thurman Munson slamming into Carlton Fisk at the
plate, the Boston Massacre, Yaz popping up to third, and Boggsie in
pinstripes, riding a victory horse in the Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox and Yankees are World Series tickets sold in New York
and torn up in Boston, SOLD OUT signs for the big weekends and a
showdown atmosphere even in May. ``It's like the World Series every
day,'' Fisk once said.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox-Yankee rivalry is the stuff of obsession _ at least
on the Boston side. When Tom Yawkey bought the Red Sox in 1933, he
said his only reason was to beat the Yankees. It took him 13 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess we never not talk about the Yankees,'' Fisk once
conceded. `` `What did the Yankees do?' You hear that from the
first spring training game on.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Yankees aren't consumed by what's happening 240 miles
north, it may be because there usually has been relatively little
to be consumed with. Since the day Sox owner Harry Frazee (a New
Yorker, of course) sold them Babe Ruth in 1920, the Yankees have
won 35 pennants and 24 world championships. The Red Sox have won
four and none.
</P>
<P>
   With rare exceptions, whenever the two clubs have gone head to
head _ at the trading table or on the diamond _ the Yankees have
prevailed. Boston sent four Hall of Famers to New York. New York
sent back a few hundred grand and Danny Cater. The Red Sox lost the
1949 pennant to the Yankees on the final day. The Red Sox lost the
1978 pennant to the Yankees on the day after the final day.
</P>
<P>
   The rivalry has been lopsided in New York's favor ever since the
cash-strapped Frazee sold Ruth for $100,000 and a $300,000 loan to
pay off his note on Fenway Park.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're going to be sore as hell at me for what I'm going to
tell you,'' Frazee told Sox manager Ed Barrow.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're going to sell the Big Fellow,'' Barrow guessed. ``I
expected it, Harry. But let me tell you this _ you're going to ruin
yourself and the Red Sox in Boston for a long time to come.''
</P>
<P>
   Thus began the ``Rape of the Red Sox,'' a four-year flesh
auction that sent the core of the ballclub _ pitchers Waite Hoyt,
Joe Bush, Sam Jones, George Pipgras, and Herb Pennock, catcher
Wally Schang, shortstop Everett Scott and third baseman Joe Dugan
to New York for cash and nobodies.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees, who hadn't won a thing until they suited up Ruth,
claimed six pennants and three World Series in the next eight
years. The Red Sox, who had won three Series in four years,
finished last in eight of the next 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``All Frazee wanted was the money,'' said a bitter Harry Hooper,
whom Frazee traded to the White Sox. ``He was short of cash and he
sold the whole team down the river to keep his dirty nose above
water.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees always had the money, which came pouring out of
owner Jacob Ruppert's brewery. But they've also had the knack of
stiffing the Red Sox at both ends of the bargain. In 1923, Boston
traded Pipgras to New York for a backup catcher and cash. Pipgras
went 93-64 in nine seasons for the Yankees, won 24 games in 1928
and was 3-0 in three World Series. After the Red Sox bought him
back a decade later for $100,000, Pipgras went 9-9 in three seasons
and disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   Always, the cosmic joke has been on the Red Sox. They ship a
castoff to New York, he becomes a god. Pitcher Wilcy Moore was 4-10
when Boston sent him back to New York in the middle of the 1932
season. Moore ended up winning the decisive game of the World
Series.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox traded first baseman Babe Dahlgren to the Yankees for
cash. Dahlgren took over for Lou Gehrig and played in the 1939
World Series. Ray Scarborough was 1-5 when Boston sold him to New
York in the middle of the 1952 season. He went 5-1 for New York and
pitched in the Series.
</P>
<P>
   It took the Red Sox nearly two decades to recover from losing
Ruth and the rest. What brought them even, finally, was Yawkey's
cash and Pearl Harbor. When the war was over, the two ballclubs
were nearly back level _ and baseball's most enduring rivalry
developed in earnest.
</P>
<P>
   The 1948 and 1949 seasons set the tone for the passion, the
anxiety, the drama _ and in Boston, the disappointment. (In 1946,
when the Red Sox won their first pennant since 1918, the Yankees
finished 17 games back.)
</P>
<P>
   In 1948, the Red Sox eliminated New York in the next-to-last
game of the season and ended up losing the pennant playoff to
Cleveland when Joe McCarthy bypassed 18-game winner Jack Kramer for
journeyman Denny Galehouse because the wind was blowing toward The
Wall.
</P>
<P>
   In 1949, the Yankees won by beating Boston twice at the Stadium
on the final weekend. For Bostonians, the tease and the torment
began then. After falling 8 1/2 games back in June after Joe
DiMaggio swept them in Fenway all by himself (and got a standing O
from Bostonians), the Sox (who had five .300 hitters) went 59-19
over the second half of the season and climbed into first place
with five games to play.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
