<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-12 21:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4744 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NJ-GUN-CONTROL-ART-(T     10-12 1279
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-GUN-CONTROL-ART-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
N.J. GOVERNOR SIGNS TRIGGER-LOCK GUN LAW 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Colo., Texas, Conn., Ill., Mich., Minn., Kan., Neb.,
Calif.)  (ART ADV: Photo NYT20 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By DAVID KOCIENIEWSKI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. _ Calling it a major step to prevent gun violence,
Gov. Christie Whitman on Tuesday signed into law a measure that
will make New Jersey the fourth state in the nation to prohibit the
sale of any new handgun unless it is accompanied by a trigger lock.
</P>
<P>
   The trigger lock bill, which had the support of some gun groups,
was approved only after legislative leaders blocked a far more
sweeping proposal to enact the nation's first mandate for what are
called smart guns, firearms equipped with an electronic device to
prevent anyone but an owner from firing.
</P>
<P>
   As the first state to enact an assault weapon ban in 1990, New
Jersey was considered promising territory by many proponents of
smart guns, who have been advocating their proposal in Trenton, the
state capital, since 1998. In the aftermath of the Columbine High
School shootings in Colorado, which left 15 dead, public opinion
polls indicated that as many as 80 percent of state voters wanted
stricter gun control and that even a majority of gun owners favored
smart guns.
</P>
<P>
   But Republican legislative leaders and Whitman ultimately turned
away from the bill after a furious lobbying campaign by gun owners
and concerns that the legislation was ahead of the technology
currently available. The speaker of the state Assembly, Jack
Collins, a Republican, said he did not allow the measure to come up
for a vote because, he said, no reliable smart gun would be on the
market for years, so the law would have been a de facto gun ban.
</P>
<P>
   Gun control advocates said they had hoped the legislation would
spur firearms manufacturers to improve smart-gun technology, in the
same way that Congress passed auto safety laws compelling car
manufacturers to speed the development and deployment of air bags.
In the end, however, the gun control forces called the trigger lock
bill only a marginal improvement and said it illustrates that even
at a time when shootings in schools and elsewhere have made gun
violence a national concern, any tightening of gun control remains
a difficult political proposition.
</P>
<P>
   ``On one hand, it's a step in the right direction,'' said Joe
Sudbay, an analyst for Handgun Control Inc., an advocacy group
based in Washington. ``But in New Jersey and a lot of other places,
the gun lobby is still effective, even when its wishes go against
the overwhelming majority of the public.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey's trigger lock law comes at a time when gun control
efforts have met with mixed results in Congress and other states.
The U.S. Senate, reacting to the public outcry after the Columbine
shootings in April, passed an assortment of proposals including the
requiring of background checks for handgun sales at gun shows. That
proposal is now stalled in conference committee with the House of
Representatives, and the House majority whip, Tom Delay, R-Texas,
this week warned against efforts to strengthen it, declaring that
``this House is a pro-gun House.''
</P>
<P>
   In state legislatures, gun control advocates have had more
success in recent years, but have still been limited to incremental
steps. Connecticut passed a law and Illinois enacted legislation
which requires that parents safeguard their firearms from minors by
using trigger locks or locking gun cases. And advocates for gun
rights have temporarily scaled back their push for laws broadening
the right to carry concealed weapons in states like Michigan,
Minnesota, Kansas and Nebraska.
</P>
<P>
   The most sweeping gun restrictions adopted in recent years were
in California, where candidates who supported gun control won the
governor's race and several key legislative elections in 1998, and
the state passed a package of bills outlawing assault weapons and
so-called Saturday night specials, mandating trigger locks and
limiting the sale of handguns to one per month.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey's smart gun bill, sponsored by the Senate minority
leader, Richard Codey, a Democrat, and Sen. Joseph Palaia, a
Republican, appeared to gain crucial momentum after the Columbine
shootings. It cleared Law and Public Safety Committee and the
Senate president, Donald DiFrancesco, a Republican who plans to run
for governor in 2001, said at the time he would allow it to the
floor for a vote by the full Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Gun rights groups used their extensive network of shooting clubs
and gun dealers to rally opposition to the bill. They offered
telephone banks and campaign volunteers to legislators who opposed
the smart gun proposal and sponsored a bill to loosen restrictions
on carrying concealed weapons. One of the state's most prominent
proponents of gun rights even publicly threatened to open what he
said was a secret file of complaints against DiFrancesco from
former law clients because he dared defy the gun lobby.
</P>
<P>
   By June, Collins, whose district in rural Salem County is
considered far more supportive of gun rights than other regions of
the state, said he was not inclined to let the Assembly vote on the
smart-gun proposal. So DiFrancesco instead pushed through a version
of the bill that would require smart gun technology on all guns
sold in the state without setting a date when the requirement would
take effect.
</P>
<P>
   Rich Miller, director of the Coalition of New Jersey Sportsmen,
a hunting group, said his group did not publicly oppose trigger
locks, but that it was still so adamantly against smart-gun
legislation that he was determined to exact his revenge on
DiFrancesco.
</P>
<P>
   ``After the Assembly races this fall, my goal in life is to
prevent Donny DiFrancesco from becoming the next governor,'' Miller
said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey Democrats hope to regain the momentum on the issue by
making gun control a major part of their campaign in the state's 80
Assembly races this fall, according to Julie Roginsky, the campaign
director for Assembly Democrats.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   But Collins, who is also expected to seek the Republican
nomination for governor in 2001 and is likely to receive the
backing of gun rights advocates and other conservative groups, said
he believed the trigger lock law and the $1 million research grant
for smart-gun technology would strike voters as a sensible,
forward-looking approach to the problem.
</P>
<P>
   Some gun owners' groups said they would be providing intensive
campaign support to candidates who have ardently defended gun
rights. The New Jersey Association of Rifle and Pistol Clubs, which
opposed both the proposals on smart guns and trigger locks, said it
would provide telephone banks and volunteers for at least five
Assembly candidates who opposed smart guns and supported a recent
bill to loosen restrictions on carrying a concealed weapon,
according to Nancy Ross, a spokeswoman for the group.
</P>
<P>
   When the Legislature begins its new session in January, Ms. Ross
said, the group expects to fight a new attempt to revive the
smart-gun initiative.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trigger locks, smart guns, they're all just gimmicks by
politicians trying to look like they're doing something by
demonizing law-abiding gun owners without addressing the problem of
criminals who use guns,'' Ms. Ross said. ``I'm sure it will
resurrect it's ugly head again. Then we'll reach out to legislators
all over again.''
</P>
</TEXT>
