<SLUG> BC-BBN-NLCS-NOTES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Weiss' heroics help put him on starting roster for NLCS
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Walt Weiss got his first start of the 1999 postseason
Tuesday after making quite an impression in the division series.
</P>
<P>
   His play on a grounder up the middle helped rescue the Braves
from a bases-loaded, no-out situation in the 10th inning of Game 3.
He also entered Game 4 in the fifth inning after a Jose Hernandez
error.
</P>
<P>
   After hitting only .148 in August while recovering from a
quadriceps injury, Weiss bounced back to hit .261 (6-for-23) in
September and October.
</P>
<P>
   ``He did play down the stretch in a few ball games and looked
good,'' Cox said. ``He looked good in Houston when he came in, and
Don (Baylor) has him swinging a lot better right now. He's a great
defensive shortstop, and I thought I'd go that way for tonight's
game anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez, the every-day shortstop since the Braves acquired him
from the Cubs on July 31, struggled offensively to end the season,
hitting only .236 (17-for-72) the last month. He was 1-for-11 in
the division series.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't say anything about it,'' Hernandez said. ``He's the
skipper, he does the lineup. Whenever they need me, I'll be there.
I hope I can be in the lineup tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez said he was surprised not to see his name in the
lineup, given how well he has hit Mosato Yoshii. He's 5-for-7
against him in his career with a double, home run and two RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   Cat on the mend
</P>
<P>
   Andres Galarraga had a CT scan on his lower back Tuesday morning
and was given the go-ahead to take the next step in his workouts as
he continues his rehabilitation from lymphoma with an eye toward
returning next season.
</P>
<P>
   Galarraga's test results will be sent to his specialist in
Chicago for a second look, but Galarraga was told by Braves team
orthopedist Dr. Joe Chandler on Tuesday that the bone in his lower
back, which had been stricken with cancer, was getting stronger.
Galarraga has been walking on the treadmill and doing some
stair-climbing. Now he can jog and lift light weights.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said the bone is much better, no question,'' Galarraga
said. ``I don't think I'll be able to swing (a bat) and lift the
heavy stuff until December, but it's good news. This will give me
some time to go step by step and be ready for spring training.''
</P>
<P>
   Galarraga threw out the ceremonial first pitch before the start
of Game 1.
</P>
<P>
   Sticking with nine pitchers
</P>
<P>
   Cox decided to keep the Braves roster for the NLCS as is, with
nine pitchers and three catchers, despite the scare the Braves got
in Game 3 of the division series when they nearly ran out of
pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We always carried three guys that could catch,'' Cox said.
``Eddie (Perez) does have a little bit of a bad knee. . . .But nine
pitchers is a little dangerous, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Perez has been playing the last half of the season with torn
cartilage in his left knee.
</P>
<P>
   One player who was happy at the prospects was Greg Maddux, who
enjoys getting called on to pitch in relief. He faced one batter in
the division series, walking Craig Biggio on a checked swing that
appeared to be strike three.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly on time
</P>
<P>
   For all the rain Turner Field took Tuesday afternoon and early
evening, Game 1 of the NLCS was only three minutes late starting,
at 8:15 p.m. It was originally scheduled for 8:12 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves did get some home field advantage with the weather
because it was only drizzling when they were taking their batting
practice Tuesday afternoon. It rained hard on the Mets, causing the
Braves grounds crew to clear the field to put the tarp down. The
Mets moved to the indoor batting cages.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll Rogers writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
