<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRADLEY-COLUMN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    It's not `war,' it's baseball
 &HT;    By Mark Bradley
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Everywhere you turn, a phony war breaks out. The Mets
are miffed because the Braves don't respect them. The Mets are
miffed because Chipper Jones had the audacity to hit a slew of home
runs against them. The Mets are miffed. . . . well, because it's
1999 and everybody's miffed about something.
</P>
<P>
   The bemused Braves look on and wonder: What is it with those
guys? With Bobby Valentine speaking of ghosts? With Valentine
saying Chipper can't have another series like the one in September?
What did we do to that team besides beat it like a drum?
</P>
<P>
   This is how that trash-talking Bobby Cox fanned the flames
before Game 1: ``They've got a class ballclub. . . . There are some
guys in the league you wouldn't want on your team, but I can't say
that about any of their guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Talk about gall.
</P>
<P>
   This is how it is when you face a team based in New York. You
get not just the team but the tabloids. You speak a simple
declarative sentence _ C. Jones to the Mets' fans: ``I told them to
go on home and put on their Yankee stuff'' _ and it becomes a
headline three inches high. ``Let The War Begin'' declared the
frothing New York Post on Tuesday. Which seemed, you know, a tad
overblown.
</P>
<P>
   Because this isn't war.
</P>
<P>
   This the National League Championship Series.
</P>
<P>
   This is where the Braves are every October.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, we got a bit giddy around here in '91 and '92, when
this postseason business was new. But that was then. Now we treat
the NLCS as an autumnal rite, which also makes New Yorkers crazy.
</P>
<P>
   Since tickets for Games 3, 4 and 5 are prized commodities in
Gotham, New Yorkers can't grasp why Game 1 didn't sell out here.
The first question asked of both Cox and Valentine in their pregame
briefings Tuesday regarded tickets sold, or the lack thereof.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seems like a pretty big series to me,'' said Valentine,
grinning that infernal grin.
</P>
<P>
   Said the questioner: ``After some of the things the Braves had
to say about your fans, do you think that says anything? At least
your fans show up.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, now. The Mets drew 2.7 million this season. The Braves
drew 3.2 million. On the last Friday night of the regular season,
the crowd at Turner Field was 38,413. The throng at Shea Stadium
that night was 29,528. The Braves, it should be noted, had clinched
the NL East five days earlier. The Mets were still embroiled in the
wild-card chase. What does that say about showing up?
</P>
<P>
   Give Valentine credit. He made the salient point: ``Our fans
were great the last two weeks of the season. They were there in
force. They were very supportive. But then again, they haven't had
the opportunity in 10 years. (Eleven, actually.) Just about
everybody in this community (meaning Atlanta) probably has seen a
playoff game in the last 10 years. A little different.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes. Tuesday's was the 44th postseason game this city has staged
this decade. The Mets have played host to two _ last weekend. It's
more than a little different. The sight of empty seats at Turner
Field in October doesn't mean that people don't care about this
team. They do. But here there's an October every year. And here, it
might also be said, there are no tabloids to stoke the phony war.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Bradley writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
