<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-12 21:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4750 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-JORDAN-VISIT-ART-NYTR     10-12 0750
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JORDAN-VISIT-ART-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VISIT FROM MICHAEL JORDAN SURPRISES STUDENTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036.) 
(lh) 
 By GARETH McGRATH   
 Wilmington (N.C.) Morning Star   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BURGAW, N.C. _ The tall, well-dressed man strode confidently
Tuesday morning down the corridors of Pender High School.
</P>
<P>
   As a former high school player in a neighboring county, the man
with one of the most famous faces in the world was no stranger to
Pender County schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``I dreaded coming up here because you always knew it was going
to be a challenge, but it was a great atmosphere,'' Michael Jordan
said, recalling when his team from Laney High School in Wilmington
traveled to the old Pender High School, now Burgaw Middle School.
</P>
<P>
   But on Tuesday, Jordan took on another challenge, seeking to
brighten the lives of about three dozen high school students whose
families had lost everything to the extensive flooding caused by
Hurricane Floyd.
</P>
<P>
   The swing through Pender County marked a rare public appearance
for Jordan in Southeastern North Carolina. The visit included
touring areas hit hard by flooding and a stop at a Salvation Army
disaster relief center.
</P>
<P>
   Also on Tuesday, Jordan and his wife Juanita made a $250,000
contribution to the North Carolina governor's hurricane relief
fund.
</P>
<P>
   ``Figured if I had to visit anywhere in North Carolina, it
better be close to home,'' he said, noting he has many relatives in
Pender County. ``I mean, when I was growing up here in Wilmington,
we thought it might happen, but it never did. Now it has.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday he talked from the heart to the roughly 35 students who
had no idea why they were summoned from their classes for a special
meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just want to tell them that sometimes God gives us
tests, deals you bad cards now and again,'' Jordan said as he
waited in a side office to be introduced. ``It's how you respond
that matters. All you can try and do is grow and get stronger from
it.''
</P>
<P>
   The superstar took care that his appearance not become a media
scene.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't want a circus,'' said Estee Portnoy of Falk
Associates Management Enterprises, the Washington, D.C.-based
agency that manages Jordan's business affairs. ``He wanted it to be
personal, focused on the kids.''
</P>
<P>
   At about 10:30 a.m. the three dozen students found themselves
facing Principal Dorothy Dempsey after having been summoned to the
home economics classroom.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought we were all in trouble or something,'' sophomore
Steve Easley said afterward.
</P>
<P>
   After being told a special guest wanted to see them, Michael
Jordan sauntered in grinning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh my God, it really is Michael Jordan,'' said one student as
Jordan began laughing.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan deftly answered questions about his cars, if he brought
the students any sneakers, and how cartoon character Elmer Fudd,
his costar in the movie Space Jam and recent MCI commercials, was
doing.
</P>
<P>
   The atmosphere changed when a student asked Jordan how he had
overcome the death of his father James Jordan, who was murdered in
1993 at the age of 56.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan, 36, said although the loss was devastating, on
reflection he felt lucky to have spent so much time with him and to
have had such a good role model.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had my father for 30 years,'' he said. ``Some kids don't
have their father that long. I felt fortunate to have had him that
long, to have the chance to spend time with him, for him to teach
me how to make right decisions. That was the positive that came out
of that.''
</P>
<P>
   After signing all the hall passes used to call the students to
the meeting, and an odd towel, T-shirt, picture, notebook and
envelope, Jordan climbed into the driver's seat of a Range Rover
for the short drive to the Salvation Army center in Burgaw.
</P>
<P>
   There, adults looked wide-eyed in amazement as Jordan wheeled a
shopping cart full of underwear and Gatorade into the former
pharmacy building.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where do these go?'' he nonchalantly asked a volunteer as she
stood open-mouthed, not believing what she was seeing.
</P>
<P>
   Salvation Army supervisor Ray Dalrymple said when he was told
Monday someone important was stopping by, he wasn't excited because
he thought it would be another politician.
</P>
<P>
   ``But he's Mike!'' he said. ``He's bigger than any politician.''
</P>
<P>
   (The Morning Star in Wilmington, N.C., is part of the New York
Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
