<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-12 21:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4752 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-ALA-LOTTERY13-COX     10-12 1212
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALA-LOTTERY13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Early results indicate Alabama votes down lottery; Mayor slot
may need runoff
 &HT;    By Marlon Manuel and Peter Mantius
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTGOMERY, Ala. _ Gov. Don Siegelman's effort to establish a
lottery for education in Alabama appeared headed for defeat
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   With 44 percent of the state's 2,627 precincts reporting, the
``no'' votes led 56 percent to 44 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of my church-going customers said they voted no,'' said
Emilo Davis, owner of the downtown GroSouth plant and feed store,
where the lottery vote dominated conversation.
</P>
<P>
   Lottery supporters predicted a turn-around before all the votes
were counted, but Rebecca Paul, CEO of the Georgia Lottery, was
among those who acknowledged that Siegelman may have to try again
in November 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a presidential election year, you've got a much better
chance of passing that constitutional amendment,'' Paul said.
</P>
<P>
   Voters streamed to polls statewide to cast ballots on the
constitutional amendment that would make Alabama the sixth state in
the Deep South with a lottery behind Florida, Kentucky, Virginia,
Louisiana and Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   In another major vote in Alabama on Tuesday, interim Mayor
William Bell, the hand-picked successor of Birmingham's first black
chief executive, led 13 challengers but a runoff appeared possible.
</P>
<P>
   With 2 percent of the city's precincts reporting, Bell had 34
percent of the vote, well short of the 50 percent needed to avoid a
runoff. City Councilman Bernard Kincaid was second with 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In the statewide lottery vote, early forecasts indicated turnout
would exceed the 57 percent that voted in last November's
gubernatorial race. Siegelman was elected overwhelmingly then on
the promise of delivering a lottery that would fund HOPE
scholarships like those awarded in Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   A self-described ``farm boy,'' Davis said he plays lotteries in
Georgia and Florida. He has hopes of a state-funded scholarship for
his son, Emilo Jr., and voted for a state lottery.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems like the well-to-do people are against it,'' said
Davis, whose red brick store stands three blocks from the Capitol
and next door to the banquet building where lottery advocates
gathered Tuesday night. ``It seems like for the poor people, it's a
way for them to grow up to better things.''
</P>
<P>
   With scores of churches opposing the amendment, the choice in
many areas of the state was depicted as God vs. the governor.
</P>
<P>
   On Madison Avenue, a few blocks from the cold, marble steps of
the Capitol, a billboard with a white background loomed over
traffic. ``Lottery?'' the billboard asked. in bold, black letters.
The answer came in red letters: ``W.W.J.D. What would Jesus Do.?''
</P>
<P>
   Both sides got considerable help from Georgians. Former Georgia
Gov. Zell Miller stumped for the lottery alongside Siegelman.
</P>
<P>
   ``We support them,'' said Wyck Knox, chairman of the Georgia
Lottery. ``Their goals and ours are the same: better education. So
we're not competitors in the bigger sense.''
</P>
<P>
   Emmett Henderson, executive director of the Georgia Council on
Moral and Civic Concerns, was among those helping Christian
conservatives leading the fight against the plan.
</P>
<P>
   Henderson said it's been difficult for lottery opponents to
mount an effective campaign. ``When you have a sitting governor
saying that anybody who doesn't support the lottery should be
ashamed of themselves, it's tough.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't understand the gambling craze that has gripped this
country,'' he said. ``For state government to be in that business
is wrong. ''
</P>
<P>
   The largest Christian group in the state _ the Alabama Baptist
Convention, part of the Southern Baptist Convention _ ferociously
opposed the amendment and donated tens of thousands of dollars to
anti-lottery groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``We voted no,'' said Faye Lipham as she and her husband walked
out of the brick city gymnasium in Lanett, a town near the Georgia
border. ``I'm a Christian and I don't believe in bringing anything
like that here. I've never known gambling to help schools.'' A
Democrat, Lipham voted for evangelical Christian Fob James in last
fall's gubernatorial election carried by Siegelman. Also in Lanett,
Elizabeth Yerta said droves of people pretended to be morally
anxious about the lottery, but still play the games in Georgia and
Florida.
</P>
<P>
   ``A person who's got religion has religion 24 hours a day,''
Yerta said. ``Those who are righteous are righteous when it's
convenient.''
</P>
<P>
   Florida opened the Deep South to lotteries when it began started
games in 1988. Critics later complained revenue generated by the
Florida lottery didn't supplement the education budget, but rather
became the primary source of funding.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, Georgia voters narrowly approved a constitutional
amendment that permitted a lottery. At the time, Miller, as a new
governor, offered HOPE scholarships, merit awards for students who
attended state colleges.
</P>
<P>
   Next fall in South Carolina, where Jim Hodges also rode the
promise of an education lottery to the governor's mansion, voters
will decide whether to start a lottery there.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last decade, Alabama polls consistently showed lottery
support at 60 percent. But a barrage of ads on both sides depressed
support to 49 percent in a poll taken Thursday by the Alabama
Education Association, which favors the lottery. However,
opposition remained stable at 35 percent but the number of
undecided voters rose to 15 percent _ an indication that voters had
wearied of lottery polls.
</P>
<P>
   Former Georgia officials _ including Miller, two of his former
press aides, his 1994 campaign manager and his one-time pollster _
boosted lottery advocates in Alabama. Miller's former press
secretary helped run Siegelman's gubernatorial campaign and acted
as the primary spokesman for the Alabama referendum.
</P>
<P>
   In Montgomery, federal government employee Steve McCarver said
he voted for the lottery because of the Legislature's reluctance to
raise taxes for anything, including education. But he was put off
by the visible opposition of organized religion, which openly
contributed to political action committees that opposed Siegelman's
lottery proposal.
</P>
<P>
   ``They should have their tax-exempt status yanked,'' McCarver
said. ``That's partisan politics. ``That should stay in church.
Once it travels out of church, it's politics.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Capitol Heights Community Center, a precinct dominated by
elderly retirees, Leon Anderson, 60, and his wife, Doris, both
voted yes despite their church and minister preaching against the
referendum.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't have to buy a ticket,'' said Leon Anderson, retired
from the state Department of Transportation.
</P>
<P>
   Said Doris Anderson, a retired accountant for the state
Department of Education, ``I just wanted to keep the money in our
state.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson thought of his two grandchildren, ages 10 and 14, who
live in Alabama. More than likely, they'll go to college in state.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this wasn't for education, I wouldn't have voted for it,''
he said. ``This is a voluntary tax.''
</P>
<P>
   Marlon Manuel and Peter Mantius write for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
