<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-12 21:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4758 &Cx1f; tth-z
r p BC-GORE-ENVIRONMENT-SPI &LR;      10-12 1178
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-ENVIRONMENT-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ENVIRONMENTALISTS MAKING DEMANDS OF GORE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOEL CONNELLY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ If any presidential candidate could be expected to be
warmly embraced by the environmental movement, it would be Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   But when the vice president arrives in Seattle Wednesday to kick
off his state campaign with a $1,000-a-plate dinner in Seattle,
environmental leaders are likely to greet him not with open arms,
but with detailed demands.
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalists are pressing Gore _ and the Clinton
administration _ for everything from rescue tugs at the Strait of
Juan de Fuca to including the removal of Snake River dams as an
option in salmon recovery plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gore's challenge is to reassert his historic leadership
position on the environment, which has been tarnished by seven
years of defending oft-compromised positions,'' said Bill Arthur,
director of the Sierra Club's Northwest office.
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalists have not abandoned Gore, author of ``Earth in
the Balance.'' But their pressuring the vice president points out
not only some problems in the Gore campaign, but also how the
environmental movement and its political clout have shifted.
</P>
<P>
   A quarter-century ago, environmentalism in the Northwest was a
bipartisan cause. Republican Govs. Dan Evans in Washington and Tom
McCall in Oregon fought to create a Hells Canyon National
Recreation Area on the Snake River. Evans and GOP Rep. Joel
Pritchard were instrumental in the fight for an Alpine Lakes
Wilderness Area.
</P>
<P>
   But the environmental lobby has turned away from Republicans in
recent years, arguing that the party of Theodore Roosevelt has
turned away from them. The Sierra Club has endorsed Democrats in
the past four presidential elections. Environmental groups serve as
off-season employers for Democratic campaign consultants and
pollsters.
</P>
<P>
   Although Republican presidential hopeful Sen. John McCain is
playing up his conservation credentials, the battle for the hearts
and minds of organized environmentalists is between Gore and former
Sen. Bill Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   One small environmental group, Friends of the Earth, has already
endorsed Bradley, who is actively courting West Coast
environmentalists.
</P>
<P>
   Part of Gore's problems stem from the tempestuous relationship
the Clinton administration has had with environmental
organizations.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton has been willing to compromise conservation
programs in order to achieve other goals. He signed a controversial
timber rider that allowed some logging of old growth. He signed a
Kosovo emergency funding bill last May that included a rider that
cleared the way for a controversial gold mine in Okanogan County.
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton also opposed Republican congressional efforts to
roll back environmental laws. The proclamation of a 1.7
million-acre Escalante-Grand Staircase National Monument in Utah's
canyonlands helped Clinton become the first Democrat since Harry
Truman to carry Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   The rescue tug issue has been a particular headache for Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Last Friday, a bevy of top conservationists met with U.S.
Transportation Secretary Rodney Slater in Everett. They urged
Slater to find a way to put a tug at Neah Bay, and to demand that
the administration order escorts for laden oil tankers in the
Strait of Juan de Fuca west of Port Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``We suggested the vice president's visit this week would be a
good time to announce any resolution of this issue,'' said Kathy
Fletcher, executive director of People for Puget Sound.
</P>
<P>
   (Transportation interests argue that a system is already in
place where tugs will come to the aid of stricken vessels, and that
additional requirements would hurt Puget Sound ports by burdening
shippers with unnecessary costs.)
</P>
<P>
   (``The industry has voluntarily implemented the state of the art
International Tug of Opportunity System in which more than 100 tugs
that travel the waters of Puget Sound and British Columbia can be
immediately called upon in emergency situations,'' said Jim Keough
of Sea-Land Services.)
</P>
<P>
   Gore, during a Seattle visit last year, said the Clinton
administration had a process under way for ``resolving'' the tug
escort issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although the process will not be completed in a matter of
hours, I assure you it will be completed before the rough seas of
winter drive up the risk factors again,'' Gore said in an
interview.
</P>
<P>
   Many environmentalists had hoped the issue would have been
resolved long before now.
</P>
<P>
   Are the environmentalists worth the price they are demanding?
Their clout is a matter of dispute.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1996 and 1998 elections, a trio of Washington House
Republicans _ Randy Tate, Rick White and Linda Smith _ appeared on
the League of Conservation Voters national ``Dirty Dozen'' list of
alleged enemies of the environment in Congress. All lost.
</P>
<P>
   But now, ``All of the polls I've seen show the environment at
the moment a non-player in the presidential race,'' said Denis
Hayes, president of the Bullitt Foundation and a director of the
League of Conservation Voters.
</P>
<P>
   Environmental groups plan a major effort, keyed to Earth Day
2000, to raise the profile of such issues as clean air and urban
sprawl. Earth Day comes in April, just after key primaries that
will decide the GOP and Democratic nominations.
</P>
<P>
   They have well-heeled allies. Media mogul Ted Turner is putting
millions of dollars into such causes as the League of Conservation
Voters education fund. Seattle philanthropist Paul Brainerd has
committed $1 million a year over three years to make the
environment a more important political issue. Brainerd hosted Gore
at a Democratic fund-raiser last year.
</P>
<P>
   But cautionary notes are coming from some senior Democrats. One
of them, former Rep. Al Swift, represented a northwest Washington
House district that included a big green constituency as well as
resource and farming towns.
</P>
<P>
   ``They (environmentalists) could drive Gore beyond the pale,
even in our state,'' Swift said. ``You can be zealous to the point
of being blind to practicality. The Christian right has done it to
the Republicans.''
</P>
<P>
   Environmental issues have played well in the West Coast states
of Washington, Oregon and California _ all of which have Democratic
governors. In the Mountain West, however, even the Clinton
administration's limited environmentalism has cost the party
dearly. Democrats have lost five governorships since the
Clinton-Gore administration took office.
</P>
<P>
   Former Idaho Gov. Cecil Andrus, who has helped preserve millions
of acres of public land, warns that Gore is already far too closely
identified with unyielding greens.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Al Gore has to take a major share of blame for the
decrease of Democrats in statehouses and congressional seats in the
(Mountain) West,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Sierra Club's Arthur disagrees. ``Here are opportunities for
the vice president to stand up and say he is working to preserve
environmental laws,'' he said. ``I believe it plays well across the
country.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
