<HEADLINE>
HIGH COURT TO HEAR STARR'S APPEAL IN HUBBELL CASE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Maine, Ariz., Ga., Va., Pa., Texas)  (bl) 
 By LINDA GREENHOUSE   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Whatever unfinished business remains in the office
of Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr, that business now includes a
new Supreme Court case. The justices Tuesday agreed to hear Starr's
appeal in a case growing out of his prosecution of Webster Hubbell,
the former Justice Department official and law partner of Hillary
Rodham Clinton, on a charge of tax evasion.
</P>
<P>
   Hubbell pleaded guilty in June to the charge, a misdemeanor, as
well as to an unrelated felony charge, receiving probation for both
with no fine and no jail time. The tax plea was conditional; the
indictment would be dismissed entirely unless Starr could persuade
the Supreme Court to overturn a federal appeals court decision that
had sharply limited his ability to build a case on financial
records that Hubbell had produced under a grant of immunity.
</P>
<P>
   Starr told the justices in his brief that the appeals court had
``made it infeasible to bring Hubbell to trial'' under its
restrictive interpretation of the federal immunity statute in the
context of a subpoena requiring the production of documents that
turn out to be incriminating. Although neither side has much left
at stake in the case, the Supreme Court probably accepted the
appeal to examine an immunity question that could recur in ordinary
federal prosecutions.
</P>
<P>
   The precise legal question in the case is whether, in order to
be able to use the documents despite an earlier grant of immunity,
the prosecution has to show it already knew with ``reasonable
particularity'' that the incriminating documents existed when it
issued the subpoena. Hubbell had turned over some 13,000 pages of
his business records, and Starr has conceded that he would not be
able to show that when an Arkansas grand jury issued a subpoena for
this material, he knew that it would contain evidence that Hubbell
had failed to pay taxes and penalties of more than $850,000.
</P>
<P>
   A federal district judge who threw out the case last year
denounced the independent counsel's tactics as ``a quintessential
fishing expedition.'' The U.S. Court of Appeals for the District of
Columbia Circuit then vacated that ruling, giving Starr another
chance to use the tax records but setting the standard that he says
is impossible to meet.
</P>
<P>
   As the appeals court interpreted the Supreme Court's precedents,
the Fifth Amendment's protection against compelled
self-incrimination applies to producing personal papers as well as
to giving testimony, on the theory that providing documents of
which a prosecutor is unaware is itself a form of testimony that
serves to validate the papers' existence and authenticity. Only
when the existence and possession of the documents is a ``foregone
conclusion,'' the appeals court said, is there no testimony
involved.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, United States vs. Hubbell, No. 99-166, Hubbell
refused to produce his records without a grant of immunity, which
Starr gave him. In defending the indictment he later obtained,
Starr is arguing that the grant of immunity did not extend to the
purely physical act of producing documents that Hubbell had created
voluntarily, long before they were sought.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
