</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-RDP-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 WASHINGTON: were sought.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   On a busy day at the court, these were some of the justices'
other actions.
</P>
<P>
   Parochial School Tuition
</P>
<P>
   For a second week, the court declined to address the question of
government support for religious school tuition. Without comment,
the justices turned down a pair of cases from Maine, where a state
law gives school districts the option of not building their own
high school, but instead paying tuition for parents to send their
children to nearby public or private schools.
</P>
<P>
   Two groups of parents with children in Roman Catholic high
schools sued to require the state to pay parochial school tuition
as well. An earlier version of the law had made no distinction
between religious and secular schools, but in 1981, the state
attorney general issued a formal opinion declaring that under
Supreme Court precedent, the government could not provide a direct
subsidy for religious school tuition. The legislature then amended
the law.
</P>
<P>
   In their respective lawsuits, one filed in state court and the
other in federal court, the groups of parents argued that while
there was no right to have the state pay for private school
tuition, once such a program was established, the state was obliged
to support, on a neutral basis that did not discriminate against
religion, the private choices that individual parents made.
</P>
<P>
   The Maine Supreme Judicial Court rejected this argument in
Bagley vs. Raymond School Department, No. 99-163, as did the 1st
U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals, in Boston, in Strout vs. Albanese,
No. 99-254.
</P>
<P>
   Neither these cases nor a tuition tax credit case from Arizona
the justices turned down last week directly presented the Court
with a pure school voucher case of the sort now working through the
courts in Ohio and Florida, under which parents receive public
money for tuition at the school of their choice. The justices have
evidently decided to wait for more legal developments.
</P>
<P>
   Right to Counsel
</P>
<P>
   Also without comment, the court refused to hear a death penalty
appeal from Georgia that raised the question of whether the
Constitution requires a state to provide competent counsel for an
inmate challenging his death sentence in a state petition for a
writ of habeas corpus.
</P>
<P>
   The inmate in this case, Exzavious Gibson, did not have a
lawyer, and repeatedly told the judge that ``I don't know what to
plead.''
</P>
<P>
   While there is a right to counsel at trial, the Supreme Court
has not extended that right to post-conviction proceedings like
habeas corpus.
</P>
<P>
   The court's last pronouncement on the issue, in a 1991 case from
Virginia, was, however, somewhat equivocal. While the court ruled
by a 5-4 vote that there was no right to post-conviction counsel,
the fifth vote was provided by Justice Anthony M. Kennedy, who
noted that the issue had not been presented in its starkest form
because there had not been an inmate in Virginia who had not
managed to find some legal representation on a habeas corpus
petition.
</P>
<P>
   Groups including the American Bar Association and the NAACP
Legal Defense and Educational Fund Inc., had hoped to use this
case, Gibson vs. Head, No. 99-77, to persuade the court to
re-examine the issue, in light of recent developments including the
elimination by Congress of federal money for state resource centers
that used to provide lawyers for habeas corpus representation. Many
of those centers have closed, the bar association told the court.
</P>
<P>
   Bible Tax
</P>
<P>
   The court turned down an appeal by the state of Pennsylvania of
a decision barring the state from giving a sales tax exemption for
Bibles and religious publications sold by religious groups. The
Pennsylvania Supreme Court ruled earlier this year that the
selective exemption violated the constitutional separation between
church and state. The case was Pennsylvania vs. Newman, No. 99-154.
</P>
<P>
   Luggage Search
</P>
<P>
   Accepting an appeal from the federal public defender's office in
San Antonio, the court agreed to decide whether a law-enforcement
officer, looking for drugs, who squeezes or otherwise manipulates
the luggage carried by bus passengers is conducting a ``search'' in
the constitutional sense, requiring a warrant or probable cause.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, Bond vs. United States, No. 98-9349, a border
patrol agent entered a Greyhound bus at a checkpoint in Sierra
Blanca, Texas, and walked down the aisle, feeling the luggage in
the overhead bins. The agent felt a brick-like object in a canvas
bag located over the seat of a passenger, Steven Bond, who
identified the bag as his and permitted the officer to open it. It
contained methamphetamine.
</P>
<P>
   While the 5th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals, in New Orleans,
ruled that the event was not a ``search,'' on the ground that a bus
passenger does not have a ``reasonable expectation of privacy'' in
carry-on luggage, other courts have reached the opposite
conclusion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
