<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-12 21:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4773 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-HOLLEY-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      10-12 0959
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLLEY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRUTH BE TOLD, SOX ARE A BUNCH OF CLOWNS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ They will not even be the best story in the
neighborhood when they play Wednesday night. You could take the
nearby No. 4 Express and find someone with a tale more intriguing
than any told by the Red Sox. You could walk a couple blocks to the
Bronx County Building and find people with more compelling things
to say. You could find better comedians among the kids who attend
P.S. 156.
</P>
<P>
   But that has never been how the Sox advertised themselves. They
are not in the American League Championship Series because they are
more interesting or talented than anyone else. They will be playing
the first game of a best-of-seven series at Yankee Stadium because
they know what to expect from each other.
</P>
<P>
   You ask how they got to this point. Here's your answer:
</P>
<P>
   They are a bunch of clowns.
</P>
<P>
   Repeat: The Sox, described by many as grim-faced,
grease-under-their-fingernails baseball warriors, are truly a bunch
of baseball clowns. That is their  It is why they keep
hanging around when everyone else expects them to go home. If they
go home, they wouldn't have as much fun teasing people as they do
now. So they stay. And tease each other.
</P>
<P>
   No, they will not be the best story in the Bronx, but they just
may have more fun than anyone else in the area. That certainly is
not a job requirement. You can be dour and still help your team
win. But the performance of this Sox team matches the personalities
of the players. That is, these guys are unusual. They can be
serious and tell you why they believe they can win the World
Series. Then they can find some weakness of yours and talk about
you to your face.
</P>
<P>
   ``The worst is probably Darren Lewis,'' Sox outfielder Butch
Huskey said Tuesday. ``He always has something to say about
somebody. But we all got him back (Monday) night.''
</P>
<P>
   After the Sox beat the Indians, 12-8, Monday night to advance to
the ALCS, Lewis stood at the front of the team bus and gave a
speech. Before he finished, he was reminded of his mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did you see the game?'' Huskey said. ``Did you see the way he
was running the bases out there?''
</P>
<P>
   On a long fly to center, Lewis neglected to tag up and go from
second to third. In the same inning, still on second, Lewis decided
he could simply stroll to third base when a teammate drew a walk _
even though there was no one on first. He zoned out. After
realizing what he had done, he tried to scramble back to second. He
would have been picked off if Indians catcher Sandy Alomar hadn't
thrown the ball into center field. He eventually made it to third.
The hard way.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis heard about that from his teammates. And what about the
speech?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd rather keep that to ourselves,'' left fielder Troy O'Leary
said with a grin. But Lewis tried to clarify.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have our own little Def Comedy Jam going sometimes,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   He was reminded that there is often some choice language in the
performances.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah,'' he said, ``sometimes we have some of that, too.''
</P>
<P>
   This is how they entertain themselves during the season. Some of
their jokes rank as pure family humor. You have to know the quirks
of the person to fully appreciate the putdown.
</P>
<P>
   If more people knew this side of the Sox, there would be yet
another reason to buy into their underdog, Everyman persona. You
know people who are just like these guys.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm telling you,'' Lewis said, ``there isn't one prima donna
in this room. Not one. The term that everybody is using these days
is ``old school.' You hear that a lot on ESPN, but that's us. We
are old school baseball players.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have people who care about their contracts or how
many square feet they have in their houses. We just play the game.
Nobody is trying to be pretty. Nobody wants to have their own
dance. In the modern era of pro sports, that's a compliment.''
</P>
<P>
   And don't forget that other part, the part about being clowns.
</P>
<P>
   For example, if you walked into the Sox clubhouse and asked,
``Where is the Shop-a-Holic?'' someone would quickly tell you when
they last saw Pat Rapp.
</P>
<P>
   ``We call him that because he always seems to be walking around
with a Dillard's bag,'' Lewis said of the pitcher. ``We were all in
the clubhouse in Cleveland and Jeff Frye _ who likes to poke fun _
saw Rapp walk by with a bag. He said, ``What are you doing now,
buying Christmas ornaments?' ''
</P>
<P>
   That exchange went on just before Game 5, when most people
probably expected the Sox to be in war mode. They can be serious
when necessary. Their point is that it isn't always necessary.
</P>
<P>
   One of the group's favorite targets is the media. Tuesday, Mike
Stanley was asked when the team was ``written off.'' Stanley
replied that he didn't know ``if we have ever been written on.''
Later, Huskey was asked about the alleged curse that has kept
Boston from winning a World Series since 1918.
</P>
<P>
   ``Curse?'' Huskey said. ``If you believe that, you believe in
those psychic people talking on the phone. And from what I
understand about Bill Buckner, he shouldn't have even been in the
game he was hurting so bad. Why put a guy in that position?''
</P>
<P>
   Just before it was time to clear the clubhouse, Bret Saberhagen
told a story that was symbolic of the Sox.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you have a 6-foot-7-inch guy going against a 5-4 guy and
the 5-4 guy believes he can take you out, he's the guy you should
be afraid of,'' he said. ``We're guys who really believe we can
win.''
</P>
<P>
   At least you would know what to expect from the 5-4 Sox. They
would box with you for a while. Afterward, they would stand among
themselves and tell a few jokes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
