<SLUG> BC-FBN-BENGALS13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bengals reflect on positives of first win
 &HT;    By Marty Williams
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CINCINNATI _ Carl Pickens' expressionless face was buried in a
magazine and he responded in a disinterested monotone to questions
about the two touchdowns he scored in Cleveland on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   But when a writer asked him about his blocking, the 29-year-old
receiver became much more loquacious.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was sweet, wasn't it,'' he smiled while describing the
hit that allowed tailback Corey Dillon to break off a 38-yard gain
that led to the  first touchdown in the 18-17 victory over
the Browns. ``People don't bring it up very often, but I take a lot
of pride in my blocking.''
</P>
<P>
   Pickens holds Bengals career records for touchdown catches (59)
and receptions (492) and is third in yardage (6,307), but he can
also do the grunt work.
</P>
<P>
   ``My job on that play was to secure the back side in case Corey
decided to cut it back,'' Pickens said in describing his role on
Dillon's big run. ``You always want to get your assignment done
because you never know when things are going to break down.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of Pickens' persistence, a play that started as a
meltdown didn't become one of those breakdowns.
</P>
<P>
   Dillon was supposed to run to his right, but the hole never
opened. He cut back to the left, circled behind Pickens' block and
motored to the 1-yard line.
</P>
<P>
   On the next snap, Dillon was thrown for a 4-yard loss, but then
rookie quarterback Akili Smith froze the Cleveland secondary with a
play fake and found Pickens uncovered in the back of the end zone.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first TD pass of Smith's career and the first of the
season for Pickens, who missed all of training camp in a contract
dispute.
</P>
<P>
   Later, Smith and Pickens teamed up for the game-winner with five
seconds left, the receiver going high above cornerback Ryan O'Neal
on one of his patented fade routes.
</P>
<P>
   Pickens and Jeff Blake made the fade a staple in their personal
arsenal, but it wasn't their exclusive property.
</P>
<P>
   ``I also worked the fade with Boomer Esiason, David Klingler,
Donald Hollas, Neil O'Donnell _ a bunch of quarterbacks,'' Pickens
said. ``I can't remember for sure, but I think I even caught one
from Hootie and the Blowfish.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bengals head into Sunday's home game against Pittsburgh with
a 1-4 record. And despite the confidence boost provided by Smith,
which is expected to contribute to the first sellout of the season,
Pickens is well aware that winning a game by one point in the final
seconds against a winless expansion team is not convincing evidence
of a turnaround.
</P>
<P>
   ``We won a game, which we desperately need to do,'' he said.
``Now we've got to take the positives that came out of that game
and build on them. At the same time, we've got to take the
negatives and learn from them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to remember how good we felt when we walked off the
field. We have to believe that we can do that every week and we
have to work hard enough to make it happen.'' CONTACT Marty
Williams at 225-2252 or e-mail marty_williamscoxohio.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The DAYTON NEWSPAPERS INC., DAYTON, OHIO
</P>
<P>
   AP-NY-10-12-99 1916EDT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
