<P>
   (NYT15) HELENA, Ark. -- Oct. 12, 1999 -- KINGBISCUIT-FESTIVAL,
10-12 --Lucky Lopez Evans of Madison, Wis. playing on a Helena,
Ark., street. This former plantation town in eastern Arkansas is
home to the King Biscuit Blues Festival. It has now grown to become
the largest free blues gathering in the South and an extraordinary
opportunity for fans of the music to see a living tradition
reconnect with its roots. (Rollin A. Riggs/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) WASHINGTON -- Oct. 12, 1999 -- TREATY-DEBATE, 10-12 --
Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, center, speaks to reporters on
Tuesday about the debate over the Comprehensive Test Bean Treaty on
Tuesday. Hopelessly outnumbered Senate supporters of a global ban
on nuclear testing moved closer to a deal with Republican leaders
on Tuesday for a face-saving postponement of a planned vote. Lott,
R-Miss., tentatively agreed to the arrangement but was working out
details with other GOP foes of the treaty, those involved in the
process said. (Paul Hosefros/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) HOUSTON -- Oct. 12, 1999 -- MENTALLY-ILL-VOTE-2, 10-12
-- Betsy Schwartz and David Clark of the Mental Health Voter
Empowerment Project registering people to vote during a picnic.
looking over voter registration manual at picnic. The project is
tgrying to create a nationwide constituency of people with mental
illness by locating potential voters and registering them,
educating them about mental health issues, and making sure they get
to the polls on election day. (Sam C. Pierson Jr./New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) NEW YORK -- Oct. 12, 1999 -- MENTALLY-ILL-VOTE, 10-12 --
Peter Lasher, 44, who has been hospitalized repeatedly for manic
depression, registered to vote four years ago, when he was
persuaded to do so by the voter empowerment project. In theory,
patients suffering from mental disabilities represent a powerful
voting block. But people with severe mental illness, who often
subsist on disability benefits and may spend years bouncing from
psychiatric hospitals to jails to the streets, have been ignored by
politicians because they offered neither money nor votes. (Chang W.
Lee/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) SEATTLE -- Oct. 12, 1999 -- WTO-SEATTLE, 10-12 -- Sandra
Yee, Mooly Lord and Roy Chan of the group Ruckus of the University
of Washington voice their opinion about the World Trade
Organization's leader Michael Moore, who is speaking at the
University later Tuesday. It is increasingly clear that the largest
free-trade meeting ever held in this country has also become a
giant protest magnet for a broad array of environmental, labor and
other groups that say the trade body is a handmaid to corporate
interests whose authority should be sharply curtailed. (Scott
Eklund/Seattle Post-Intelligencer Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) NEW YORK -- Oct. 12, 1999 - BBA-YANKEES-3, 10-12 -- New
York Yankees right fielder Paul O'Neill walks past manager Joe
Torre (6) and coach Don Zimmer behind the batting cage at Yankee
Stadium on Tuesday. O'Neill will play with a slightly fractured rib
in the American League Championship Series against the Boston Red
Sox on Wednesday, O'Neill said following Tuesday's practice. ``As
of now I'm playing unless I wake up tomorrow and today's activity
has set it back, and I don't think it will,'' said O'Neill. (Bill
Greene/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
