Tuesday. The Red Sox face the New York Yankees at the stadium on
Wednesday in Game 1 of the American League Championship Series.
(Bill Greene/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) NEW YORK -- Oct. 12, 1999 -- LEVINE-HARRY-POTTER, 10-12
-- Arthur A. Levine is editorial director of Arthur A. Levine
Books, an imprint of Scholastic Inc., which has published three
best-selling children's books about a junior wizard, Harry Potter.
Scholastic paid more than $100,000 for the first manuscript by an
author who was then unknown - a lavish bet on a children's book.
``It's a scary thing when you keep bidding and the stakes get
higher and higher,'' writes Levine. (Marilynn K. Yee/New York Times
Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) ATLANTA -- Oct. 12, 1999 -- ATLANTA-AIRPORT-2, 10-12 --
With 73.5 million passengers last year, Hartsfield is now the
world's busiest airport. ``We're No.1 in passengers, and we intend
to stay No.1,'' says Benjamin R. DeCosta, Hartsfield Airport's
general manager. ``But we're also the most delayed airport in the
U.S., with an average of eight-plus minutes a flight. We're
committed to changing that.'' (Alan S. Weiner/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) ATLANTA -- Oct. 12, 1999 -- ATLANTA-AIRPORT-1, 10-12 --
With 73.5 million passengers last year, Hartsfield is now,
incontestably, the world's busiest airport, pushing the perennial
front-runner, Chicago O'Hare, to second place. It is far from
perfect, however, for with its phenomenal growth have come flight
delays, parking shortages and clogged traffic. (Alan S. Weiner/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) TRENTON, N.J. -- Oct. 12, 1999 -- NJ-GUN-CONTROL, 10-12
-- Gov. Christine Todd Whitman, right, is surrounded by legislators
on Tuesday after signing a new law that makes New Jersey the fourth
state in the nation to prohibit the sale of new handguns unless it
is accompanied by a trigger lock. Standing from left are
Assemblymen Alfred Steele, Tom Smith, and Guy Talarice. (Laura
Pedrick/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) UNDATED -- Oct. 12, 1999 -- SPY-SATELLITE-PHOTOS-B&AMP;W,
10-12 -- Inaugurating a new commercial era, Space Imaging Inc., a
private company based in Thornton, Colo., made this photo public on
Tuesday which shows the White House. The image, taken from space,
was cropped from a wider image. Photos at this resolution are the
world's first being made available from a commercial satellite
whose sharpness rivals those of military spies in the sky. (Space
Imaging/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) PITTSBURGH, Pa. -- Oct. 12, 1999 -- SLEEP-WORKPLACE,
10-12 -- Philippe Truche, a senior consultant at Deloitte
Consulting, takes a break in the company's nap room last Thursday.
Falling asleep on the job may be a cardinal taboo of the workplace,
but a smattering of companies around the country are defying common
wisdom and actually encouraging the practice. They are discovering
that it increases morale and productivity. (Gary Tramontina/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) BOSTON -- Oct. 12, 1999 -- OBIT-CHAMBERLAIN, 10-12 --
Bill Russell, right, laughs as he and long time rival Wilt
Chamberlain relive old times on a stage in front of a back drop of
a mural depicting them in action in this May 26, 1999 file photo at
the Fleet Center. Chamberlain, one of the most dominant players in
the history of basketball and the only one to score 100 points in
an NBA game, died Tuesday at 63. (Jim Davis/Boston Globe Photo)
LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) NEW YORK -- Oct. 12, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., OCT. 17 --
AMERICAN-BALLET, 10-12 -- Yan Chen and Keith Roberts of American
Ballet Theater rehearsing Martha Graham's ``Diversion of Angels.''
``It's like asking a modern dancer to do 'Sleeping Beauty,' ``
Roberts says. (Jeffery A. Salter/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) HELENA, Ark. -- Oct. 12, 1999 -- KINGBISCUIT-FESTIVAL,
10-12 --Lucky Lopez Evans of Madison, Wis. playing on a Helena,
Ark., street. This former plantation town in eastern Arkansas is
home to the King Biscuit Blues Festival. It has now grown to become
the largest free blues gathering in the South and an extraordinary
opportunity for fans of the music to see a living tradition
reconnect with its roots. (Rollin A. Riggs/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) WASHINGTON -- Oct. 12, 1999 -- TREATY-DEBATE, 10-12 --
Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, center, speaks to reporters on
Tuesday about the debate over the Comprehensive Test Bean Treaty on
Tuesday. Hopelessly outnumbered Senate supporters of a global ban
on nuclear testing moved closer to a deal with Republican leaders
on Tuesday for a face-saving postponement of a planned vote. Lott,
R-Miss., tentatively agreed to the arrangement but was working out
details with other GOP foes of the treaty, those involved in the
process said. (Paul Hosefros/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) HOUSTON -- Oct. 12, 1999 -- MENTALLY-ILL-VOTE-2, 10-12
-- Betsy Schwartz and David Clark of the Mental Health Voter
Empowerment Project registering people to vote during a picnic.
looking over voter registration manual at picnic. The project is
tgrying to create a nationwide constituency of people with mental
illness by locating potential voters and registering them,
educating them about mental health issues, and making sure they get
to the polls on election day. (Sam C. Pierson Jr./New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) NEW YORK -- Oct. 12, 1999 -- MENTALLY-ILL-VOTE, 10-12 --
Peter Lasher, 44, who has been hospitalized repeatedly for manic
depression, registered to vote four years ago, when he was
persuaded to do so by the voter empowerment project. In theory,
patients suffering from mental disabilities represent a powerful
voting block. But people with severe mental illness, who often
subsist on disability benefits and may spend years bouncing from
psychiatric hospitals to jails to the streets, have been ignored by
politicians because they offered neither money nor votes. (Chang W.
Lee/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) SEATTLE -- Oct. 12, 1999 -- WTO-SEATTLE, 10-12 -- Sandra
Yee, Mooly Lord and Roy Chan of the group Ruckus of the University
of Washington voice their opinion about the World Trade
Organization's leader Michael Moore, who is speaking at the
University later Tuesday. It is increasingly clear that the largest
free-trade meeting ever held in this country has also become a
giant protest magnet for a broad array of environmental, labor and
other groups that say the trade body is a handmaid to corporate
interests whose authority should be sharply curtailed. (Scott
Eklund/Seattle Post-Intelligencer Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) NEW YORK -- Oct. 12, 1999 - BBA-YANKEES-3, 10-12 -- New
York Yankees right fielder Paul O'Neill walks past manager Joe
Torre (6) and coach Don Zimmer behind the batting cage at Yankee
Stadium on Tuesday. O'Neill will play with a slightly fractured rib
in the American League Championship Series against the Boston Red
Sox on Wednesday, O'Neill said following Tuesday's practice. ``As
of now I'm playing unless I wake up tomorrow and today's activity
has set it back, and I don't think it will,'' said O'Neill. (Bill
Greene/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) NEW YORK -- Oct. 12, 1999 -- BBA-YANKEES-2, 10-12 -- New
York Yankees pitcher Orlando ``El Duque'' Hernandez warms up during
practice at Yankee Stadium on Tuesday. Hernandez will face the
Boston Red Sox on Wednesday in the first game of the American
League Championship Series. (Bill Greene/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) COKER, Ala. -- Oct. 12, 1999 -- PUMPKINS-FLOATER, 10-12
-- Keante Dubose, 4, from the Gingerbread Children's Center in
Northport, Ala., looks at his find during an outing to the Red
Rooster Farm on Tuesday. Several children ranging in age from
pre-school to second grade picked their own pumpkins on Tuesday in
plenty of time for Halloween festivities. (Neil Brake/Tuscaloosa
News)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) ARLINGTON, Texas -- Oct. 12, 1999 -- BBA-YANKEES, 10-12
-- New York Yankees pitcher Roger Clemens enjoys a champagne bath
from his teammates after defeating the Texas Rangers last Saturday.
Clemens' quest for a championship ring will take him back through
Fenway Park as the Yanks face the Boston Red Sox, Clemens' old
team, on Wednesday in the first game of the American League
Championship Series. (Chang W. Lee/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) SIACHEN GLACIER, in the western Himalayas -- Oct. 12,
1999 -- PAKISTAN-ARMY-3, 10-12 -- Pakistani soldiers on patrol in
the high peaks of the western Himalayas in this photo taken earlier
this year. Pakistan, like India, has some 3,000 soldiers fighting
in a border war here that is now 15 years old. Prime Minister Nawaz
Sharif of Pakistan was ousted in a military coup on Tuesday after
sacking the country's powerful army chief. Sharif's ouster sparked
expressions of concern from around the world, not least in
neighboring India where officials said the armed forces were on a
state of ``full alert.'' (Pakistani Military/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) WAGHA, Pakistan -- Oct. 12, 1999 -- PAKISTAN-ARMY-2,
10-12 -- A Pakistani Ranger stands guard at border crossing between
India and Pakistan in this 1997 file photo. Prime Minister Nawaz
Sharif of Pakistan was ousted in a military coup on Tuesday after
sacking the country's powerful army chief. Sharif's ouster sparked
expressions of concern from around the world, not least in
neighboring India where officials said the armed forces were on a
state of ``full alert.'' (John Giannini/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) ISLAMABAD, Pakistan -- Oct. 12, 1999 -- PAKISTAN-ARMY,
10-12 -- Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif of Pakistan in the foyer of
his official residence in this 1997 file photo. Sharif was ousted
in a military coup on Tuesday after sacking the country's powerful
army chief. A senior police official said troops had told Sharif
not to leave his Islamabad residence and police at his home had
been disarmed. (John Giannini/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) NEW YORK -- Oct. 12, 1999 -- GRAPE-LEAVES, 10-12 -- Mina
Newman, the chef at Layla, a Middle Eastern restaurant in TriBeCa,
wraps seasoned shrimp in fresh grape leaves before grilling to
create this dish. In one of those increasingly common alliances of
farm and chef, freshly picked grape leaves from vineyards are
turning up both in markets and on menus. (Michael Rogol/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) SAN FRANCISCO -- Oct. 12, 1999 -- GOAT-CHEESE, 10-12 --
Dante Boccuzzi makes crisp goat cheese beignets at Silks. As a
condiment, a spice or the star of the dish, goat cheese continues
to find new ways to tantalize chef and diner alike. (Peter
DaSilva/New York Times Photos)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) UNDATED -- Oct. 12, 1999 -- OLD-COOKBOOKS, 10-12 -- Good
cookbooks, like these, give information not readily available
elsewhere and have distinct personalities that make them readable.
(Michael Rogol/New York Times Photo)
</P>
