<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-12 21:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4781 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-CONGRESS-BANKS-NYT &LR;      10-12 1030
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-BANKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BILL TO OVERHAUL FINANCIAL SYSTEM FACES VETO 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By STEPHEN LABATON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As Congress moved closer Tuesday to completing
legislation that would overhaul the nation's financial system, the
Clinton administration denounced a new Republican measure
introduced by three top lawmakers and said it would be vetoed by
the president.
</P>
<P>
   Both the House and Senate have already adopted competing
versions of legislation this year that would tear down the
Depression-era barriers that have restricted banks, securities
firms and insurance companies from expanding into each other's
businesses. Efforts at reconciling the two bills had stalled.
</P>
<P>
   But Tuesday the logjam was broken when three senior Republicans
said they had reached a compromise on most aspects of the
legislation, including measures that would offer some privacy
protections to consumers and some regulatory relief to smaller
banks, and said their agreement had moved Congress considerably
closer to completing their work on a final bill. A House-Senate
conference committee is scheduled to begin its final work on the
measure Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``This guarantees that we will pass a bill and it will now be up
to the president to decide whether he will sign it,'' said Sen.
Phil Gramm, R-Texas, who heads the Senate Banking Committee. Gramm
joined two House committee chairmen, James Leach and Thomas Bliley
Jr., in announcing the new measure.
</P>
<P>
   Leach, R-Iowa, heads the House Banking Committee, while Bliley,
R-Va., is chairman of the House Commerce Committee. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials quickly tried to pour cold water on the
proposal. The officials said the Republican compromise was a giant
step backward and would be rejected by the White House because it
failed to safeguard community lending or protect the privacy rights
of consumers.
</P>
<P>
   They also said there was little hope that the parts of the
legislation objectionable to the White House would be significantly
changed before a vote by a House-Senate conference committee soon,
and that Tuesday's announcement could thus doom prospects of
financial services legislation during the 106th Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the bill were presented to the president in its current
form, the president would veto the bill,'' Treasury Secretary
Lawrence Summers said. ``The administration is disappointed by the
recommendations on the Financial Modernization bill put forth by
Chairmen Gramm, Leach and Bliley on Tuesday. A flawed process risks
producing flawed legislation. In important respects, the chairmen's
proposal abandons the bipartisan consensus that the House
legislation achieved.''
</P>
<P>
   Summers and other administration officials Tuesday criticized
the legislation for failing to provide privacy protections for
consumers and for heavily diluting the Community Reinvestment Act.
That 1977 law encourages banks and savings associations to make
loans to minorities, farmers, inner-city residents and others who
have historically been denied access to credit.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican compromise also left open a long-standing dispute
between the Treasury Department and the Federal Reserve about which
would have regulatory primacy over many of the nation's banks.
</P>
<P>
   Hoping to broker a deal to resolve the issue, Gramm and Leach,
who supports the administration's position on the regulatory issue,
managed to get Summers and Alan Greenspan, chairman of the Fed, to
reopen their negotiations concerning the issue Tuesday morning. The
two sides made progress but by the end of the day were still far
apart.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, the House of Representatives and the Senate
passed competing versions of legislation that would repeal the
Glass-Steagall Act of 1933. The Clinton administration has
expressed a strong preference for the House version, sponsored by
Leach, and had threatened to veto the Senate version, sponsored by
Gramm.
</P>
<P>
   The measure announced Tuesday continues to favor the Federal
Reserve as a top regulatory agency.
</P>
<P>
   But Leach said that the provision was ``only a place holder,''
that would be reconsidered during the mark-up later this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless there is more deference to the Treasury, we all
recognize that we will be inviting a veto,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   While some Democrats and the Clinton administration criticized
the proposed legislation for weakening provisions of the law that
encourage lending to minorities and the poor, other Democrats said
it represented an important move for Gramm.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over all, Phil Gramm has begun to take a step in the right
direction, but he still has a few more to go before this bill can
become a law,'' said Sen. Charles Schumer, D-N.Y. ``It's now quite
clear that the banking bill will be made or broken on the Community
Reinvestment Act.''
</P>
<P>
   Other Democrats said that the privacy and regulatory issues
remained significant concerns as well.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican measure eliminates Gramm's proposal to exempt
more than 4,000 smaller banks and savings associations from the
requirements of the Community Reinvestment Act. In its place, the
new measure loosens the act's requirements on many more smaller
institutions by replacing annual reviews of their lending records
with reviews once every five years.
</P>
<P>
   The measure also adopts a provision from the House bill that
limits banks and other financial companies from sharing customer
information with marketers and other third parties. But
administration officials said that the new measure also contains
new definitions that significantly weaken that provision.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation also does not prevent affiliates of the same
corporation from sharing customer information. So, for example, an
insurer would be able to give confidential customer information to
a bank if the two companies are affiliated.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation's privacy provisions raise concerns among
liberal and conservative groups. An alliance of critics, including
Ralph Nader, the consumer advocate; Phyllis Schlafly of the Eagle
Forum; Nadine Strossen of the American Civil Liberties Union; Sen.
Richard Shelby, R- Ala., and Rep. Ed Markey, D-Mass., will hold a
news conference on Wednesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
