A4782 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-BROADCASTERS-HALLOFFA     10-12 0262
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BROADCASTERS-HALLOFFAME-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ohio Hall of Fame to induce Donahue, Kirk
 &HT;    By Bob Batz
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Two former Dayton broadcasters _ Phil Donahue and
Steve Kirk _ will be inducted into the Ohio Radio-TV Broadcasters
Hall of Fame in Akron on Nov. 7.
</P>
<P>
   Donahue started his radio career in Dayton in 1959 in the news
department at WHIO-AM (1290). Later, after a stint as host of the
popular Conversation Piece show on the station, he moved to
television.
</P>
<P>
   At its peak of popularity, The Phil Donahue Show reached as many
as 25 million households each week. The program, which earned
Donahue the prestigious Lifetime Achievement Award for Daytime
Television from the American Academy of Television Arts and
Sciences, went off the air in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Kirk, who started his 37-year radio career as a $235-a-month
morning-show host at a station in Bellaire, Ohio, made his Dayton
debut on WING-AM (1410) in 1966.
</P>
<P>
   During his 25 years at WING, Kirk _ who also worked at radio
stations in Cincinnati and Columbus _ was known for his sense of
humor and willingness to make personal appearances. He retired in
1998.
</P>
<P>
   Carl Day, a news anchor-reporter at Dayton's WDTN-TV, Channel 2,
is already a member of the Ohio-Radio -TV Broadcasters Hall of
Fame.
</P>
<P>
   Kirk is thrilled by the honor. ``Just think,'' he said Tuesday
from his home in Ponce Inlet, Fla. ``Me and Phil Donahue in the
Hall of Fame. I never thought it was possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
