<SLUG> BC-CORRECTIONS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TIMES CORRECTIONS FOR WEDNESDAY, OCTOBER 13
</HEADLINE>
 Eds.: These corrections will appear in The New York Times on
Wednesday. Days and dates refer to the original article's
transmission by the New York Times News Service, and may need to be
adjusted by NYT clients.)  
(gc) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BC-GERMANY-GRAVES-NYT (moved on Monday, Oct. 4)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Monday, Oct. 4,
about the desecration of a Jewish cemetery in Berlin misstated the
burial site of Leo Baeck, a prominent rabbi. It is in London, not
Berlin.
</P>
<P>
   BC-ALTMAN-PROFILE-NYT (moved on Sunday, Sept. 12)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Sunday, Sept. 12,
about the investment banker Roger C. Altman and his role as adviser
to CBS in its merger with Viacom misstated the background of Robert
A. Altman, for whom the investment banker is occasionally mistaken.
Robert Altman was formerly the president of First American
Bankshares, a company controlled by the Bank of Credit and Commerce
International. He was not the chairman of the Bank of Credit and
Commerce.
</P>
<P>
   BC-UKRAINE-ALUMINUM-NYT (moved on Sunday, Aug. 22)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Sunday, Aug. 22,
about efforts by the Trans-World Group to expand its aluminum
operations in Ukraine referred incorrectly to the formation and
ownership of the company. It was founded by two brothers, David and
Simon Reuben. Lev and Mikhail Cherny, two brothers from Uzbekistan,
had no involvement in the company's formation. While Lev Cherny is
a joint venture partner, Mikhail Cherny has no connection with the
company. The article also misstated the date of Trans-World Group's
founding. It was in 1977, not the late 1980's.
</P>
</TEXT>
