<HEADER>
A4789 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-FOREIGN-BRIEFS-NYT &LR;      10-12 0799
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOREIGN-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA: ZHIRINOVSKY TO TRY AGAIN
</P>
<P>
   The Russian nationalist Vladimir Zhirinovsky said he might form
a new party to get back on the ballot for the December
parliamentary election. The Central Election Commission
disqualified Zhirinovsky's Liberal Democratic Party from the vote,
saying senior officials had failed to declare all of their
property. Zhirinvosky said he might submit a new list of
candidates, forge a new bloc or perhaps even create a new party.
</P>
<P>
   NORTHERN IRELAND: MANDELSON ON THE JOB
</P>
<P>
   Peter Mandelson spent his first full day as Northern Ireland
secretary meeting in Belfast with the leaders of the Ulster
Unionists, the largest Protestant party, and Sinn Fein, the
political wing of the IRA. Mandelson, Prime Minister Tony Blair's
closest confidant who is returning to government 10 months after
being forced out in a financial scandal, was accompanied by Mo
Mowlam, his predecessor.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN: FARMERS STRIKE BACK
</P>
<P>
   Farmers in Plymouth blocked French trucks from bringing produce
into England to protest France's refusal to comply with the
European Union's Aug. 1 decision to lift the ban on imports of
British beef. France says its own food safety experts doubt the
European Commission's finding that British beef is fully free of
the mad cow disease that prompted the 1996 ban.
</P>
<P>
   IRELAND: 6 TIED TO IRA ARMS
</P>
<P>
   The police arrested six people in three counties in connection
with what they said was an operation to smuggle arms from the
United States to the Irish Republican Army. The IRA is in the third
year of a cease-fire and says it has not sanctioned the import of
any weapons.
</P>
<P>
   ITALY: ANDREOTTI DENIES MAFIA MEETING
</P>
<P>
   Acquitted last month of charges he conspired with the Mafia in a
1979 murder, former Prime Minister Giulio Andreotti, 80, dismissed
a Palermo prosecutor's claim that in 1987 he met and kissed
Salvatore (The Beast) Riina, a convicted Mafia boss. ``If I as
prime minister really went to a home of a person under house arrest
to meet with a man known to be a Mafia chief on the run,''
Andreotti told the jurors, ``then this court should not only
condemn me but lock me up in a psychiatric prison.''
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   PERU: REBELS END JAIL PROTEST
</P>
<P>
   Fifty imprisoned Marxist guerrillas ended a three-week hunger
strike in a high-security prison in the Andean city of Arequipa
without winning concessions from authorities to improve prison
conditions. It was the most aggressive public action by the
pro-Cuban Tupac Amaru Revolutionary Movement since its guerrillas
took hundreds of hostages in a raid on the Japanese ambassador's
residence three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   BRAZIL: TROOPS GUARD ENERGY SITE
</P>
<P>
   Maneuvers by some 2,500 state military policemen have begun in
the area of a hydroelectric power complex that is the focal point
of a dispute between the central government and the state of Minas
Gerais. The governor opposes the sale of government-owned energy
companies to private interests.
</P>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   INDIA: GANDHI STILL PARTY LEADER
</P>
<P>
   The Congress Party president, Sonia Gandhi, was unanimously
chosen to lead the party in Parliament, despite the party's searing
defeat in national elections. She did not say, however, whether she
will name herself or someone else to serve as day-to-day leader of
the opposition on the floor of the lower house. Ms. Gandhi, who
will be making her debut in Parliament, accepted responsibility for
the party's defeat.
</P>
<P>
   KAZAKHSTAN: NEW PREMIER PICKED
</P>
<P>
   A former foreign minister known in the West as an economic
reformer, Kasymhomart Tokayev, has been named the new prime
minister. He takes over at a time when citizens remain poor despite
the country's vast oil and gas resources. Ultimate power in the
Central Asian nation lies with the autocratic president, Nursultan
Nazarbayev.
</P>
<P>
   MIDDLE EAST
</P>
<P>
   YEMEN: QAT BANNED FROM SKIES
</P>
<P>
   The national airline has banned the chewing of qat on its
flights, an official newspaper reported. The step is the latest in
a national campaign against the mild stimulant, a bitter leaf that
is widely chewed by rich and poor alike in Yemen.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA
</P>
<P>
   NIGERIA: ABACHA SON TIED TO MURDER
</P>
<P>
   A Nigerian official says a son of the former military ruler,
Gen. Sani Abacha, is to be charged with murder, BBC News reported.
Mohammed Abacha is to appear in court this week. President Olusegun
Obasanjo confirmed last week that Mohammed Abacha had been detained
for what he called heinous crimes. He gave no details, but reports
say they include the killing of Kudirat Abiola, a wife of the late
opposition leader, Moshood Abiola. She died when her car was
ambushed in Lagos in 1996.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
