</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-REDSOX-TICKETS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FANS IN SEARCH OF TICKETS COME UP EMPTY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARCELLA BOMBARDIERI  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Anthony D'Antonio, 39, of Danvers, Mass., took the day
off from work to stake out the ticket office at Fenway Park
Tuesday. He commandeered a folding chair and settled in on the
sidewalk.
</P>
<P>
   D'Antonio pledged to wait all day to buy a ticket for the
playoff series against the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   There was one problem: No tickets were for sale.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe they'll feel sorry for me,'' said the car salesman.
``I'm telling you they will sell tickets. It's just one of those
waiting games.''
</P>
<P>
   Red Sox fans are accustomed to maintaining hope in the face of
constant heartbreak. And Tuesday, Red Sox management has to contend
with the angry beast it created.
</P>
<P>
   Not one single, lonely ticket changed hands at the box office at
Fenway Tuesday. All post-season tickets had been sold by telephone
by Oct. 2, according to a team spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't matter.
</P>
<P>
   A few insistent fans promised to sit and wait all day at Fenway,
in the belief that the same loyal faith that the Red Sox rewarded
with their improbable victory against the Cleveland Indians might
be rewarded again with a showering of tickets from the gods of
baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday morning, about 200 fans, a team spokesman estimated,
waited in line outside Fenway for tickets that didn't exist. Some
had camped out all night, only to be turned away by police around
9:30 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Tickets, of course, are still available to those who can pay a
steep price. By Tuesday afternoon, bidding on the online auction
site eBay (www.ebay.com) had soared to $4,000 for four box seats
for game three on Saturday, the first Red Sox home game of the
American League Championship Series and the prized Roger
Clemens-Pedro Martinez pitching matchup. Another pair of tickets
sold for $950.
</P>
<P>
   Those who could not afford to pay such inflated prices were
outside Fenway Park with nothing do but wait, hope and _ in some
cases _ vent.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like a chess game with them,'' said 47-year-old Richard
Frost as he stood in the stairway outside the ticket office. Frost
intended to maintain his vigil for at least an hour or two. ``I'm
here, and now it's their move. They've got tickets. They sell 'em
when they want to sell 'em.''
</P>
<P>
   Like many, Frost angrily accused the Red Sox of ignoring the
average fan.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they want to make friends with the neighbors around here
and get on good terms with us, why don't they sell the tickets to
us?'' Frost said. ``They're playing hardball.''
</P>
<P>
   But Richard Bresciani, Red Sox vice president of public affairs,
defended the practice of selling tickets over the phone.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the best and fairest way to accommodate our fans,''
he said. ``Otherwise you're going to have people mobbing our ticket
office, and it doesn't give a fair chance to our fans in New
Hampshire and Maine. They are Red Sox fans, too.''
</P>
<P>
   The team has sold thousands upon thousands of tickets to
individual fans, Bresciani said, filling up all of the aged
ballpark's 33,800 seats. About 65 percent of tickets go to season
ticket holders, Bresciani added, while others are reserved for
corporate sponsors and the other Major League teams.
</P>
<P>
   The face value for the playoff tickets is $35 for bleacher
seats, $50 for the grandstands and $65 for box seats, Bresciani
said.
</P>
<P>
   But the law of supply and demand meant that those who had
tickets could sell them for a lot more.
</P>
<P>
   Ticket brokers were asking for $1,500 to $2,000 for lower box
seats and $500 for grandstand seats, according to Jamie Moore, a
concierge at the Four Seasons Hotel. He fielded dozens of call
through the day from out-of-towners looking for a room and a set of
tickets, but many balked at the ticket prices Moore told them
brokers were seeking.
</P>
<P>
   ``The powerbrokers will pay anything to impress a client,''
Moore said. ``But if the real people have any sense they're going
to wait a few days until everyone gets a feel for the market.''
</P>
<P>
   While Red Sox fever has swept Boston, ticket brokers say they
still have a tough time purchasing tickets and then reselling them
for a profit. Some had no tickets to offer at all; others had only
a handful because they refused to buy from season ticket holders
for hundreds or thousands of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not getting involved in it. I'm fed up. It's ridiculous,''
fumed Tony, a broker who goes by ``The Ticket Guy,'' but refused to
give his last name. ``Go to a bar, watch the game on a nice
big-screen TV, and have a nice dinner, and don't pay anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Though some fans say they will take his advice, others are still
willing to open up their wallets. Michael Conlon, a security
company executive from Winthrop, Mass., who walked away from Fenway
disappointed Tuesday, said he would shell out a few hundred bucks
for a ticket. After all, he spent $750 a piece for tickets to the
All-Star Game played at Fenway this summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll get in here somehow,'' Conlon said, pointing to the
ballpark. ``The whole thing is historic. Being a baseball fan for
30 years, this is an amazing event. ''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
