<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DELL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Samsung, Dell sign deal on screens
 &HT;    By Jerry Mahoney
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Seeking to avoid future shortages of screens
that have slowed sales of notebook computers this year, Dell
Computer Corp. has signed a five-year, $8.5 billion agreement with
Samsung Electronics Ltd. for millions of displays beginning next
year.
</P>
<P>
   Dell also said Tuesday it will invest $200 million in Samsung
bonds, providing the world's leading maker of LCD screens with
additional capital to expand its capacity.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe that these agreements make us a preferred partner
of Samsung's and will provide us with a massive stream of LCDs
based on leading-edge display technology,'' Dell Chief Executive
Michael Dell said in a news release.
</P>
<P>
   The shortage of liquid-crystal display screens stems from the
economic crisis that swept over most of Asia beginning in early
1998. Companies in Japan and South Korea, which supply more than 90
percent of screens, cut spending on new plants by 35 percent, said
Ross Young, president of DisplaySearch, an Austin company that
monitors the industry.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Dell and other PC makers have experienced heightened
demand for notebook computers, and their customers were forced to
wait weeks for some models. DisplaySearch forecasts that LCD
companies will supply only 86 percent of the 16.3 million projected
demand this year for thin-film transistor screens.
</P>
<P>
   Those high-quality displays, often referred to by the initials
TFT, have a transistor for each of the thousands of tiny elements
that control the illumination.
</P>
<P>
   ``The outlook for the TFT-LCD market can't be better,'' said
Shim Yong Jae, an electronics analyst at SG Securities Co.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dell's investment reconfirms the industry trend, which will
benefit leading LCD suppliers such as Samsung.''
</P>
<P>
   Young said Asian LCD makers increased their investments in their
plants by 40 percent this year, but production won't significantly
increase until late in 2000. DisplaySearch expects there will be an
oversupply by the second quarter of 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Dell spokesman T.R. Reid said the contract with Samsung commits
the company to buying a much higher number of LCDs than Dell buys
now. ``We have very robust growth forecasts for our notebooks.''
</P>
<P>
   Dell's revenue from notebook sales grew 49 percent in the second
quarter, more than twice the rate of the PC industry. As part of
its more aggressive pursuit of consumer business, Dell recently
began offering notebooks in blue and gray casings.
</P>
<P>
   Dell doesn't provide details of its agreements with contractors.
But Young of DisplaySearch estimates Samsung will supply about 60
percent of Dell's notebook LCDs this year. Samsung, which has a
memory-chip plant in Austin, also supplies Dell with memory,
monitors and CD-ROM drives.
</P>
<P>
   The convertible Samsung bonds, which have a maturity of 39
months, yield annual interest of 5 percent. Dell can exchange the
bonds into common shares or depositary receipts at $216.22 per
share _ a 28 percent premium to Tuesday's closing price.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, Apple Computer Inc. agreed to invest $100
million in Samsung for a guaranteed supply of LCDs.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Mahoney writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas. Bloomberg News contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
