<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-12 21:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4793 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-OBIT-CHAMBERLAIN-ART-     10-12 0964
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-CHAMBERLAIN-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILT CHAMBERLAIN, BASKETBALL SUPERSTAR, DIES AT 63 
</HEADLINE>
  (See related column, CHAMBERLAIN-ANDERSON) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphics clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(sw) 
 By FRANK LITSKY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Wilt Chamberlain, whose size, strength and intimidation made him
probably the most dominant player in basketball history, was found
dead on Tuesday in his home in the Bel-Air section of Los Angeles.
He was 63.
</P>
<P>
   According to John Black, a spokesman for the Los Angeles Lakers,
Chamberlain's last team, the authorities were called to the home
shortly after noon Pacific time and found the body. Jim Wells, a
Fire Department spokesman, said there were indications that
Chamberlain had suffered a heart attack.
</P>
<P>
   Chamberlain was hospitalized in 1992 because of an irregular
heart beat, and his agent and friend, Sy Goldberg, said Chamberlain
was on medication. He had always stayed in good physical condition
and recently ran in the Honolulu Marathon.
</P>
<P>
   At 7- feet 1 inch and 275 pounds, Chamberlain was an awesome
offensive force, and while he scored many points with gentle
finger-roll shots, he also became the game's first monster dunker.
Before he came along, basketball had such big centers as
6-foot-10-inch George Mikan and 7-foot Bob Kurland. But Chamberlain
was bigger and stronger, with a more fearsome inside game, so
dominant that the National Basketball Association widened the
free-throw lane to force him farther from the basket.
</P>
<P>
   He started an era of dominant centers that included Bill Russell
of the Boston Celtics, his antagonist in so many playoff and
championship series, and continued with the 7-foot-2-inch Kareem
Abdul-Jabbar, and today with the 7-1, 315-pound Shaquille O'Neal of
the Lakers. They, like Chamberlain, were dominant not just because
of their height, but because they combined strength with agility
and the ability to play above the rim. Indeed, the title of
Chamberlain's 1991 autobiography reflected his legacy _ ``A View
From Above.''
</P>
<P>
   He was so spectacular that he had two nicknames _ ``Wilt the
Stilt,'' which he disliked, and ``The Big Dipper.''
</P>
<P>
   In 14 seasons in the NBA, starting in 1959 wiadelphia and
ending in 1973 with the Lakers, he played 1,045 regular-season and
160 playoff games. He scored 31,419 points, the NBA career record
until Abdul-Jabbar broke it, and grabbed 23,924 rebounds, still the
league record. He averaged 30.1 points and 22 rebounds a game.
</P>
<P>
   His teams reached the playoffs 13 times, but only two won
championships _ the Philadelphia 76ers in 1967 and the Lakers in
1972. Four of his teams lost in playoff finals and six others in
conference finals. In three of those championship finals, Russell
and the Celtics won the seventh and final game by 1 or 2 points.
</P>
<P>
   His most famous game came on March 2, 1962, when Philadelphia,
then known as the Warriors, played the New York Knicks in Hershey,
Pa. Helped by giddy teammates, he scored 100 points, still the
one-game record. What made it more stunning was that Chamberlain,
one of the poorest free-throw shooters the sport had known, sank 28
of 32 that night.
</P>
<P>
   He led the league in scoring seven consecutive seasons (1960-66)
and in rebounding 11 times in 14 seasons. He was voted the league's
most valuable player as a rookie in 1960 and again in 1966, 1967
and 1968.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've lost a giant of a man in every sense of the word,'' the
National Basketball commissioner, David Stern, said in a statement
on Tuesday. ``The shadow of accomplishment he cast over our game is
unlikely ever to be matched.''
</P>
<P>
   Leonard Koppett, the basketball historian, called Chamberlain
``clearly the most dominating player who ever played basketball,
maybe not the best, but the most dominant.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill Russell was probably the most influential player,''
Koppett said, ``but one on one, Wilt overwhelmed him like anybody
else. There has been nothing like Wilt since.''
</P>
<P>
   Chamberlain seemed almost irritated over the fuss made over his
100-point game at the expense of other accomplishments.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was hot that night,'' he said. ``They were feeding me and it
was just one game.''
</P>
<P>
   The NBA records he liked best were his season records of 50.4
points a game in the 1961-62 season, 48.5 minutes a game the same
season and 27.2 rebounds a game in 1960-61. He also holds the
single-game record for rebounds, 55, set against Boston in 1960.
Russell used to joke that he ``saw every one of those 55
rebounds.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I give Kareem full credit for breaking my all-time scoring
record,'' Chamberlain said in an interview in 1994. ``It's a record
of longevity, not a flash in the pan. The important records are the
ones that take an athlete many games or years to amass. Anyone can
have a great game, but having 1,000 good games has more
significance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those records were more than having one lucky night. When I
was at Kansas, Walt Wesley was averaging 4 points a game, but one
night as a pro, for the Cincinnati Royals, he scored 50-something
points. Kareem was in the 50s only once in his career, so does Walt
Wesley equal Kareem? I saw Bo Jackson run 94 and 97 yards for
touchdowns in one game, and no one else ever did that, but does
that mean he's better than Jim Brown or O.J. Simpson or Walter
Payton?
</P>
<P>
   ``There are more records to shoot at now, and records become a
bigger deal. Some records are manufactured out of thin air. When I
was playing, who knew of double doubles and triple doubles? They
had no significance, no meaning. I had triple doubles every night,
and they didn't even keep track of blocked shots then.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Records aside, Chamberlain is forever linked with Russell. It
was Chamberlain, the extrovert, against Russell, the introvert;
Chamberlain, the bull, against Russell, the smoothie. As Jeremy
Larner wrote in Life magazine in 1967:
</P>
<P>
   ``Wilt has played the role of offended nobility, self-conscious
up and down and off the court, consumed by aristocratic agonies
whenever any agent, force, power, referee or teammate queers the
act. In contrast to Russell, who with his grim visage and tense,
spare physique, never makes a move that isn't purposive,
Chamberlain blossoms with excessive gestures and dysfunctional
contortions, sitting up atop himself almost apologetically as he
powers for point after point.''
</P>
<P>
   Their rivalry through the 1960s and '70s captivated fans and
helped build the NBA into the attraction it is today.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Chamberlain powered for point after point only when
his team owner and coach wanted that. Part of his greatness was
that he could do almost anything needed.
</P>
<P>
   When he started playing pro basketball, the 24-second clock
(under the rule that requires a team to shoot within 24 seconds of
gaining possession) had been introduced only five years earlier.
The public was fascinated by scorers. So when Chamberlain entered
the NBA, Eddie Gottlieb, who owned the Philadelphia Warriors,
wanted to maximize that appeal. If others could score 30 points a
game, Gotlieb wanted Chamberlain to score 40 or 50 or more.
</P>
<P>
   Chamberlain obliged, but once he had averaged 50 points a game
for an entire season, the thrill was gone. The team wanted him to
pass more, and he soon became the league leader in assists. The
team wanted him to play defense more, and he became even more of a
terror. Whatever the team needed, he did it, and better than almost
anyone else.
</P>
<P>
   Wilton Norman Chamberlain was born on Aug. 21, 1936, in
Philadelphia. He didn't begin playing basketball until he was in
the seventh grade. He grew 4 inches in three months when he was 15,
and was 6-11 when he entered Overbrook High School in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   After leading Overbrook to three public school championships and
two all-city titles, Chamberlain became one of the most recruited
plyers ever with over 200 colleges interested.
</P>
<P>
   He chose the University of Kansas and Coach Phog Allen, now in
the Hall of Fame. In his first game against the Kansas varsity _
freshmen weren't allowed to compete against other teams then _ he
scored 50 points before a packed Allen Fieldhouse crowd of more
than 15,000.
</P>
<P>
   As a sophomore, he led the 1957 Jayhawks to the National
Collegiate Athletic Association tournament finals, where Kansas
lost to unbeaten North Carolina in triple overtime.
</P>
<P>
   Disgusted by being smothered by zone defenses, Chamberlain left
Kansas after his junior year and joined the Harlem Globetrotters.
</P>
<P>
   Chamberlain, extremely agile for his size, ran cross-country in
high school and was an outstanding high jumper and shot-putter at
Kansas. His passion besides basketball was volleyball, and wanted
to try to qualify for the Olympic volleyball team but was unable to
because professionals were not eligible for the Games then.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
