<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARMY-LEWIS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARMY PLANS MAJOR OVERHAUL TO ALLOW FASTER RESPONSE  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ED OFFLEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Army will undergo its most significant overhaul in decades,
aimed at allowing it to respond far more quickly to to short-term
crises worldwide, the Army's senior leaders announced Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The transformation will begin immediately with two brigades at
Fort Lewis south of Seattle, and eventually extend to the entire
Army.
</P>
<P>
   The changes are aimed at getting combat units in place in days,
not the weeks or even months that have been the rule in recent
years. And fewer support units will be needed.
</P>
<P>
   Army Chief of Staff Gen. Eric Shinseki discussed the broad
outlines of the plan yesterday at a meeting of defense industry and
service officials in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   Many details were unavailable yesterday, including whether the
reorganization will involve fewer or more troops than the two Fort
Lewis brigades currently have, or the overall cost to redesign them
into what one official called a ``lethal medium'' force.
</P>
<P>
   The plan calls for the Fort Lewis brigades to be converted
within 12 months. They will abandon the heavy equipment such as
tanks and infantry fighting vehicles the Army has used for decades
in favor of lighter ``wheeled'' equipment that can be rushed to the
battlefield more quickly.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement came just five months after the Army was unable
to deploy an Apache attack helicopter force from Italy to Macedonia
in time to play a role in the NATO strikes against Serbia. And a
decade ago, it took several months for the Army to move each of its
heavy divisions from the United States to Saudi Arabia in Operation
Desert Shield.
</P>
<P>
   ``We intend to transform the Army, all components, into a
standard design ... that allow(s) us to put a combat-capable
brigade anywhere in the world in 96 hours once we have received
`execute liftoff,' a division on the ground in five days,''
Shinseki told the Association of the U.S. Army Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The plan also envisions using advanced computer networks and
secure communications to significantly reduce the number of support
troops and the amount of logistical supplies that will be sent into
battle zones aboard the Air Force's new C-17 airlift fleet.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is big,'' said John Grady, communications director for
the Army association, when asked about the plan. ``This can really
be a revolution in the way soldiers can fight wars.'' Grady called
the plan ``one of biggest changes to the Army in the last 50
years.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Norm Dicks, D-Wash., said Fort Lewis will become ``the
vanguard of our new military strategy of fast-deployable troops''
under the plan.
</P>
<P>
   For decades, the Army has organized its combat forces as
``heavy'' or ``light'' divisions and brigades, with the heavy units
organized around battalions of 70-ton M1A1 Abrams tanks or M2
Bradley infantry fighting vehicles and artillery units. Light units
consist of foot soldiers trained for basic infantry operations,
using non-armored ``Humvee'' vehicles or troop-carrying helicopters
to maneuver on the battlefield.
</P>
<P>
   But heavy units are too bulky to deploy to overseas emergencies
rapidly, and light units lack the protective vehicles and firepower
that can enable them to protect themselves in sustained combat.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are absolutely excited about this opportunity,'' said I
Corps spokeswoman Lt. Col. Melanie Reeder at Fort Lewis. ``It is a
great initiative.''
</P>
<P>
   Shinseki said he picked the base because its ``infrastructure,
maneuver space and gunnery ranges will accommodate such a
transformation.'' I Corps commander Lt. Gen. James T. Hill will
preside over the restructuring of the two brigades.
</P>
<P>
   Fort Lewis currently has both a heavy and a light brigade. The
3rd Brigade, 2nd Infantry Division is an armored unit with 3,700
soldiers including two tank battalions and one mechanized infantry
battalion. The 1st Brigade, 25th Infantry Division, is a light
infantry unit with 2,600 soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   Both units, beginning with the 3rd Brigade, will begin
conversion into a new combat identity centered on an as-yet
undefined ``wheeled'' combat vehicle that provides armored
protection and cannon firepower for troops but is 50-70 percent
lighter and easier to fly to distant battlefields, Shinseki said.
</P>
<P>
   The Army has no such vehicle in its inventory, but the Marine
Corps has fielded a light armored vehicle for the past decade.
Officials said they did not konw if the Army intends to buy that
version or press for a different version.
</P>
<P>
   Shinseki told the Washington audience he does not intend to take
years to develop the new combat vehicle. ``It is our intent to have
an initial set of prototype vehicles beginning to arrive at Fort
Lewis this fiscal year,'' the general said.
</P>
<P>
   At a later news conference with Army Secretary Louis Caldera,
Shinseki said it was too early to spell out what kinds of
equipment, including armor, will be done away with. ``Everything's
on the table,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question he posed to industry is, `What can you provide
off the shelf fairly quickly that meets our requirements for
protection, mobility and lethality?''' explained a senior Army
official, speaking on grounds of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   Army officials were adamant that the initiative is not an
experiment or technology test. ``These are operational units that
will be deployed,'' the senior official said.
</P>
<P>
   Material from The Associated Press was used in this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
