<HEADER>
A4796 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-ARMY-RESTRUCTURE-ART-     10-12 1012
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARMY-RESTRUCTURE-ART-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARMY IS RESTRUCTURING WITH BRIGADES FOR RAPID RESPONSE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Wash.)  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By STEVEN LEE MYERS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As a first step in what could ultimately be the
most significant restructuring of the Army's combat divisions since
the Vietnam War, the Army on Tuesday announced that it would create
two new lighter, more mobile brigades able to deploy anywhere in
the world within 96 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Responding to criticism that the Army had moved slowly to adjust
to the post-Cold War crises most likely to confront the nation, the
Army chief of staff, Gen. Eric Shinseki, outlined what he said
would be ``a major transformation'' of the Army over the next
decade, beginning with the new brigades.
</P>
<P>
   Shinseki said the Army would reduce the large support units that
accompany combat brigades when they deploy. He also said the Army
would reconsider the weapons systems it buys, paying greater
attention to those that are lighter but still lethal.
</P>
<P>
   With advances in technology and tactics, he added, the heavy
weapons now at the heart of the Army's structure, like the the
Abrams M1-A1 tank, could become obsolete. They would be replaced by
wheeled vehicles that could be moved overseas in greater numbers
more quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything is on the table,'' Shinseki said.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's announcement was a significant reversal for the Army,
which only last year considered but then rejected changes in the
structure of its forces. The issue was revived this year after the
NATO air war against Yugoslavia, when the Army took more than a
month to deploy a squadron of Apache helicopters to Albania.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the changing world in which we live today, we've got to be
able to get to the fight faster,'' said Army Secretary Louis
Caldera on Tuesday. Caldera appeared with Shinseki before the
Association of the U.S. Army, a booster organization, here in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Many details of the proposal remain unresolved, including the
exact size and shape of the new brigades, which will be based at
Fort Lewis, Wash. Shinseki and other Army officials said those
details would be ironed out in the weeks ahead as the service
prepares its budget for the next fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
   Although he stopped short of realigning the Army's 10 combat
divisions, as some experts have called for, Shinseki said the
Army's distinction between ``heavy'' armored divisions and
``light'' infantry or airborne divisions would soon disappear.
</P>
<P>
   ``If technology provides the answers we think, then what we have
traditionally described as light and heavy will begin to merge,''
the general said. ``I think you will see the entire transformation
will go toward capabilities that give those divisional formations
the lethality that the heavy forces have and the agility of the
lighter forces.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Of all the armed services, the Army probably has arguably had
the most difficult time transforming itself to reflect the
unpredictable world in the post-Cold War era. To its critics, the
Army has moved too slowly to change a force that, although smaller,
still looks much as it did when the United States was prepared to
slug it out with the Warsaw Pact on the plains of Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Krepinevich, the executive director of the Center for
Strategic and Budgetary Assessments, in Washington, said Tuesday's
announcements showed the Army understood the challenges it faces.
</P>
<P>
   But he said the changes stopped short of addressing the real
problem, which he said is the ability to put large forces into
combat in remote areas without the support bases it has relied upon
in past conflicts. In the Persian Gulf war, the United States had
six months to build up a force in Saudi Arabia before driving Iraqi
troops out of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sounds like the Army is talking the talk, but it is taking
baby steps on the walk,'' Krepinevich said.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The two new brigades are designed to be ``medium'' forces _
lighter than the heavy armored units but still operating with
armored vehicles, unlike infantry or airborne units. They are
expected to have about 3,000 soldiers each and will be converted
from existing units now at Fort Lewis: the 3rd Brigade of the 2nd
Infantry Division and the 1st Brigade of the 25th Infantry
Division.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Rather than having 70-ton Abrams tanks, the brigades will be
equipped with lighter armored vehicles, no more than 20 tons each.
To speed the creation of the units, Shinseki said, the Army will
buy existing vehicles now available, such as those used by the
Marine Corps.
</P>
<P>
   While the Army has considered creating medium divisions in the
past, it has not significantly altered the structure of its
division since 1965, when it created the light airborne divisions.
</P>
<P>
   Shinseki said the brigades would serve as a model in the years
ahead for restructuring the rest of the Army, which now has six
heavy and four light divisions, along the lines of the plan he
outlined Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   With the Army being called on to send troops across the globe,
he said that all divisions would have to become more mobile, able
to travel aboard cargo aircraft like the C-17, which carry only a
tank at a time.
</P>
<P>
   The Army's goal, he said, will be to deploy a full division with
15,000 soldiers within five days, and five divisions within a
month. ``That is a stretch from our current capability,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Shinseki said that to accomplish that the Army had to reconsider
the weapons that it has designed for the future, shifting attention
to those that are more mobile.
</P>
<P>
   Although he did not specify any in particular, Army officials
have said that one of the Army's biggest programs _ the $11.5
billion effort to build a self-propelled howitzer called the
Crusader _ could be dramatically scaled back or cut altogether.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
