<SLUG> BC-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VALENTIN TAKES IT ALL IN STRIDE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ He knows how it works. Once upon a time, he was the
Flavor of the Month, the way Wilton Veras was not long ago.
</P>
<P>
   But it doesn't take much to go from Flavor of the Month to
Resident Poison Pill. Have one season perceived to be far below
your established standard (even if, on closer examination, it isn't
really so bad), then have another year in which you play hurt and
really do play poorly, and management introduces a fresh young face
into your spot and your own fans register a 10 on the Boo-O-Meter
when you're introduced prior to the first home game of the
playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   That's got to hurt, no?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's actually very easy to take,'' maintains John Valentin,
one of the many Red Sox heroes during the epic weekend dispatch of
the Indians in the American League Division Series. ``Because it's
baseball. Everybody wants to see the old guy out and the new guy
in.''
</P>
<P>
   In this case, ``everybody'' really did mean just about everybody
except the one man whose opinion really mattered. Jimy Williams
wasn't about to turn third base over to the young whippersnapper
when the playoffs came, not when he had at his disposal a man who
had played in big games and done great things and who wasn't quite
ready to pick up that first Social Security check.
</P>
<P>
   Nope, Valentin had a key ally in Williams. Fans and, yes, media
(we know who we are) were quite prepared to bail on Valentin, whose
ailing knee had rendered him almost useless at times during the
long, long season. We might have been more sympathetic were it not
for the generally exemplary play of young Veras, who knocked out
key hits during the team's September surge and who played third
base as if to the manor born. It was very tempting to say, ``Hey,
let the kid play.''
</P>
<P>
   And the kid might have come up big, too, as Valentin is happy to
acknowledge.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a young player with a lot of talent,'' Valentin says.
``He's got a chance to be a good player some day.''
</P>
<P>
   Some day. But not now. These are money games. Veteran cool is
more reliable than youthful exuberance. John Valentin may still be
hurting. He may have a lot less mobility than the kid. He may never
be the player he was in 1995, when he both scored and knocked in
100-plus runs from the No. 2 spot in the order. But this past
weekend he demonstrated what veteran class is and why we should all
be very careful what we wish for, as he bashed three home runs and
two doubles and knocked in 12 runs during those three glorious Red
Sox triumphs over Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, it was gratifying for me,'' he says. ``But the big
thing is what it meant to the team to be able to come from 0-2
against a great team like the Indians.''
</P>
<P>
   Valentin accepts any praise he gets with wry amusement. He has
sampled the capriciousness of modern American baseball life, and it
has left its scars on his psyche. Not many players of his stature
came from so far back in the pack. A walk-on at Seton Hall who
batted ninth? A .216 hitter in Double A? These are not the normal
items found on the resume of an accomplished major leaguer. He is
justifiably proud of his accomplishments.
</P>
<P>
   He still looks into the mirror and sees a shortstop. Is that so
bad? He's not stupid. He knows how good Nomar Garciaparra is. But
he had always defined himself as a shortstop, and when he was
moved, to second base and later to third, he chose to believe it
was because he was capable of helping the team at either of these
alien positions, not because he was a poor shortstop.
</P>
<P>
   He wasn't that bad a second baseman, and he often plays a very
nice third base (but please, John, do get those throws up). He is a
gamer. He feels unappreciated by the public, however, even though
he won't come out and say it. It is, for some reason, very chic to
be a John Valentin basher.
</P>
<P>
   Forget this year, OK? Consider the 1998 season, when he led the
team in runs and knocked out his customary 40 doubles. That's not
bad. But if you were to ask the first 100 Red Sox fans you meet if
he had a good or bad offensive year, about 90 would shout, ``Bad!''
</P>
<P>
   So he has developed a necessarily thick skin. The way he figures
it, let the fans and the press say what they want. All he can do is
show up and hope the manager writes his name on the lineup card. As
long as he has respect inside the locker room and in the
all-important manager's office, he can survive.
</P>
<P>
   He thought speculation that Williams might bypass him in favor
of the kid was ludicrous, and he has been proven correct. He knew a
veteran manager wanted a veteran presence in the lineup, and now he
has the satisfaction of having turned in a great clutch performance
when his team needed it most.
</P>
<P>
   And when the day really does come that Veras elbows him out of
the lineup?
</P>
<P>
   ``The Red Sox are no different than anyone else,'' he says
``Changes are made. I'm sure when that time comes here I'll have no
trouble getting someone else to accept my services.''
</P>
<P>
   Romantic? No. Eminently pragmatic? Yes. He's a veteran. This is
what they're all about.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
