<DOCNO> NYT19991012.0392 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-12 22:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4801 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-BANKS-NYT &LR;      10-12 1190
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-BANKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LITTLE KNOWN POWER BROKER IN YELTSIN'S CIRCLE EMERGES IN BANKING
SCANDAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also RUSSIA-BANKS-RESIGN) 
(DW) 
 By CELESTINE BOHLEN and NEELA BANERJEE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ The money laundering scandal at the Bank of New York,
at first dismissed by Russian bankers and politicians as an
overblown sensation manufactured in America, has now made its way
into the middle of Russia's own highly charged political scene.
</P>
<P>
   In the process, a new figure has emerged from the shadows,
touted by one side in a bitter power struggle here as the latest
Rasputin figure to hold sway in the Kremlin. His name is Alexander
Mamut, 39, a lawyer and banker who by his own admission is a friend
and adviser to the inner circle around President Boris Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
   In the space of a week, the soft-spoken and boyish-looking Mamut
has gone from being a little-known financier to being labeled as
the Kremlin's latest all-purpose power-broker, whom the Russian
media has linked to a corporation charged with operating an illegal
money transfer business through the Bank of New York.
</P>
<P>
   The most graphic allegations were broadcast Sunday night in a
television program that linked Mamut to Sobinbank, a Moscow bank
recently raided by the police as part of the investigation here
into several Bank of New York accounts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sobinbank is just one unit of the laundering system,'' said
the reporter for the popular ``Itogi'' program.
</P>
<P>
   ``Its founder is Alexander Mamut,'' the reporter went on. ``He
is a man of marked individuality in every respect. He is well
acquainted with people from the president's close circle.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview this week in the boardroom of MDM Bank, also
mentioned in the Itogi report, Mamut, who two months ago was made
chairman of the MDM supervisory board, denied any knowledge of the
illegal money transfers.
</P>
<P>
   But he does not deny that he has Kremlin connections.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really am acquainted with these people,'' he said when asked
if he knew Tatyana Dyachenko, one of Yeltsin's daughters, and
several top Kremlin administration officials. ``And this
acquaintance has been used to incriminate me.''
</P>
<P>
   Mamut's career is typical of many young and aggressive
entrepreneurs who emerged in the early 1990s. He came from a
well-respected Moscow family and was educated at prestigious
universities along with several top bankers.
</P>
<P>
   Mamut went into law and parlayed that into the banking business,
opening his own bank, the Corporation for Project Financing, which
he describes as a small asset-management company.
</P>
<P>
   How his banking career developed, and how it landed him in the
center of an investigation, is still an open question.
</P>
<P>
   In a series of recent reports in publications and TV stations
that are now firmly in the anti-Yeltsin camp, Mamut has been
painted as the mastermind behind schemes to take billions out of
Russia, acting under cover provided by his political connections.
Some of the most virulent charges against him have appeared on a
Web site, gazeta.ru, that specializes in investigative reporting,
with a anti-Kremlin slant.
</P>
<P>
   While still chairman of his first bank, now all but legally
bankrupt after Russia's financial crash in August 1998, he went on
to become a member of the board of Sobinbank in an arrangement that
he says came about because of shared clients. He left Sobinbank
last August, when he joined MDM, which had enjoyed a reputation as
a well-managed privately held bank until it too was tarred by its
business relationship with Sobinbank and Flamingo Bank, another
bank raided recently by Russian police.
</P>
<P>
   Mamut is not the first Kremlin adviser to be labeled as the link
between the family, the name for the tight circle that revolves
around Ms. Dyachenko, the president's younger daughter and closest
confidante, and a group of favored Russian businesses. Before him
there was Roman Abramovich, the major shareholder of the Russian
oil company Sibneft, and before him, Boris Berezovsky, a Russian
financier with outsized political ambitions.
</P>
<P>
   These have become magnets for all sorts of allegations.
Depending on which newspaper or magazine is recounting them, the
charges range from staging secret takeovers of major Russian
companies to acting as the asset managers for the family's
holdings.
</P>
<P>
   Some reports are true, according to people who have been
involved in deals involving family-connected businesses.
</P>
<P>
   But according to Mamut, the sources of the charges against him
are part of a ``merciless information war'' he says has been
whipped up by Media-MOST, an information empire now allied with
Yeltsin's opponents. ``One of the methods of this power struggle is
to discredit the existing power, by discrediting and slinging mud
at specific people who are close to power,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then there is a second line of attack,'' he said, ``which is
the Bank of New York scandal. If you can tie the Bank of New York,
in the highly nervous situation that exists abroad and here in
connection with the discrediting of certain people, then you have a
shocking version of the scandal.''
</P>
<P>
   By his own account, Mamut was introduced into the Kremlin circle
in the 1995 or 1996. He said he got to know Valentin Yumashev
before Yumashev, who began his career as a journalist, became
Yeltsin's chief of staff, and that he met Abramovich and Berezovsky
when the Corporation for Project Financing handled the ruble
accounts for Sibneft, in which Berezovsky also reportedly has
shares.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Mamut has become an unofficial unpaid adviser to
Alexander Voloshin, now chief-of-staff, whom he says he meets with
once a month to discuss banking and legal issues. But mostly, he
describes his Kremlin relations as friendship rather business.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are typical friendly relations,'' he said, describing how
he was one of several dozen people, including Ms. Dyachenko, who
filled up an Aeroflot flight late last year to go skiing in
Austria. ``I don't want to describe them in detail or fully because
the context created around me and around these relations is quite
tendentious.''
</P>
<P>
   According to one political consultant familiar with the way the
Kremlin works, Mamut is being too modest. His role is described as
a crucial bridge between the Kremlin and Russia's business and
political elite, all the more useful because it is not official.
Nor, he said, can it be denied that such connections are useful to
building private business networks.
</P>
<P>
   ``When someone like Mamut meets with you, and tells you to do
something, you do it, because you know who stands behind him,''
said the consultant, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   But in a city now stricken with pre-election fever, it is
increasingly difficult to separate myth from reality. ``In the two
years I worked in the Kremlin, I never heard of or saw Mamut,''
said Aleksei Volin, a former Kremlin media strategist who now heads
a government news agency. ``I'm already used to the papers every
few months trotting out yet another person whom they say runs the
Kremlin or is close to the family. I think it is terribly
exaggerated.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
