<HEADLINE>
SOME IDEAS ON FIRST-BALL TOSSERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It is as if the hardball god decided to save the best
for last and ring out the century in ultimate theatrical fashion.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning Wednesday night at Yankee Stadium, the Red Sox and
Yankees _ rivals of biblical proportion _ will play as many as
seven games for the right to represent the American League in the
final World Series of the 1900s.
</P>
<P>
   Red Sox-Yankees. It's up there with Harvard-Yale, Coke-Pepsi,
Kennedy-Nixon, Army-Navy, Macy's-Gimbel's, and Ford-Chrysler.
</P>
<P>
   Officials of both teams no doubt are scurrying to secure
potential first-game-ball tossers for this cataclysmic, apocalyptic
series. Helen Hunter, the widow of ex-Yankee great Catfish Hunter,
does the honors Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Here are some unsolicited suggestions for the next six games:
</P>
<P>
   --Ted Williams _ It's a shame Joe DiMaggio didn't live to see
this series. It would have been wonderful to see the two greatest
living ballplayers, bookend stars of the game's signature
franchises, standing on the mound together for a game of catch. The
Great DiMaggio is gone, but Ted is working on 91 days' rest since
his All-Star appearance at Fenway.
</P>
<P>
   --Julia Ruth Stevens _ The Babe's daughter claims he wished no
ill on the Boston franchise when Harry Frazee sold him to New York
(``Daddy would never have done that!''). She has allegiances to
both the Yankees and Red Sox. Give her the damn ball.
</P>
<P>
   --Max Frazee _ The great-grandson of the man who sold Ruth to
the Yankees in 1919, Max is an artist who specializes in depictions
of serial killers. He was living in TriBeca when the Sox last made
it to the World Series against the Mets in 1986. The Sox honored
him when they attempted to lift some alleged curse at Fenway six
years ago. Mighty Max should be found for a first-ball toss.
</P>
<P>
   --Don Zimmer _ Get over it, Sox fans. Zim takes too much heat
for what happened in 1978. OK, maybe he could have used Bill Lee
instead of Bobby Sprowl against the Yanks, but he didn't throw the
meatball to Bucky Dent. He's wearing pinstripes now and some Sox
fans took it as an omen when Zim took a foul ball off the noggin in
Game 1 of the Division Series against Texas. Only Zim could come
back and say, ``110,000 ears in this ballpark, and that line drive
had to find mine.''
</P>
<P>
   --Stephen King _ He deserves it. It's been a tough year for the
horror man/Sox season ticket-holder. He cursed Boston's bullpen
when he wrote, ``The Girl Who Loved Tom Gordon,'' then suffered
serious injuries when he was struck by a van while walking on a
road in Maine. He proved his mettle in 1978 when he was a college
professor and canceled classes after the playoff game.
</P>
<P>
   --Mike Torrez _ Last seen running in the corridors of Shea
Stadium screaming, ``I'm off the hook,'' after Bill Buckner's
error, it's time for Torrez to reappear. He pitched for both the
Sox and Yankees and in 1989 flew to Delray Beach, Fla., and tossed
another meatball to help Dent christen the Little Fenway Park at
his baseball school.
</P>
<P>
   --Roger Clemens _ Whoops. Never mind. He's going to throw some
unceremonial first pitches Saturday in Game 3 in Boston. And he'd
better bring those headphones he used to tune out Butch Hobson. Sox
fans hooted the Rocket at the All-Star Game in July. Beating a
Yankee Clemens at Fenway in the playoffs would be better than sex
or chocolate.
</P>
<P>
   --Bill Parcells _ Believe it or not, even though he is a Jersey
Guy, the Tuna is a Sox fan. He could inspire a lot of emotion in
either ballpark, especially Fenway.
</P>
<P>
   --Sparky Lyle _ Pitched for both teams. Did little in Boston.
Won a Cy Young with the '77 Yankees. Maybe Danny Cater could join
him for a double first-ball toss.
</P>
<P>
   --Wade Boggs _ He could ride his horse to the mound, flash his
Yankee championship ring, and tell us how much he hates Boston.
</P>
<P>
   --Helen Robinson _ Has been at the Fenway switchboard since
1941. Power behind the throne. Guardian at the gate. Friend of Ted.
Fifty-eight years of ``Red Sox'' deserves a first ball, don't you
think?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
