<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LVMH IN DEAL WITH PRADA TO TAKE CONTROL OF FENDI
</P>
<P>
   The luxury-goods company LVMH-Moet Hennessy Louis Vuitton of
France has forged an unusual alliance with the Italian fashion
house Prada to take control of Fendi, ending a months-long battle
for the Rome design house. Under the agreement, LVMH and Prada paid
an undisclosed amount for a 51 percent stake. Advisers said that
the two buyers paid about $520 million, which values the company
around $1 billion. The sale hands control of Fendi to Bernard
Arnault, the chairman of LVMH, and the Prada chairman, Patrizio
Bertelli, but leaves the general management in the hands of the
five Fendi sisters.
</P>
<P>
   THE SERIES SCORECARD FOR STOCKS
</P>
<P>
   In the fervor created by the success of New York's two baseball
teams this year, it is worth examining the history of the interplay
between World Series teams and stocks. The historical answers are
clear. The New York Yankees are good for stocks, but the Boston Red
Sox are better. The Atlanta Braves are also good, but a New York
Mets appearance in the World Series would be a bad omen.
</P>
<P>
   FRENCH BANK PAYS $4 MILLION TO U.S.
</P>
<P>
   Credit Lyonnais has paid $4 million to the U.S. government to
avoid criminal charges stemming from its role in backing the
Italian financier Giancarlo Parretti's takeover of
Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer.
</P>
<P>
   GM DENOUNCED OVER DEALER PLAN
</P>
<P>
   The president of the National Automobile Dealers Association
bitterly criticized General Motors for its plan to buy 5 percent to
10 percent of its dealerships and operate them itself. He hinted
that dealers might try to use their political influence to stop GM.
</P>
<P>
   STOCKS DROP AS DOW FALLS 2.17 PERCENT
</P>
<P>
   Stock prices retreated. The Dow Jones industrial average fell
231.12 points, or 2.17 percent, to 10,417.06. The Standard &AMP; Poor's
500-stock index lost 22.17 points, or 1.66 percent, to 1,313.04.
The Nasdaq composite index, fell 43.52 points, or 1.5 percent, to
2,872.43.
</P>
<P>
   SECURITIES FIRMS POST SOLID GAINS
</P>
<P>
   Merrill Lynch, Paine Webber and Donaldson, Lufkin and Jenrette
reported better-than-expected third-quarter earnings, reflecting a
strong rebound from a disastrous quarter last year but a decline
from a strong first half. Investors reacted favorably, pushing
shares of Donaldson, Lufkin up $2.1875 a share, to $42.50.
Merrill's shares were down 75 cents, to $67, and Paine Webber
slipped 68.75 cents, to $35.
</P>
<P>
   PHILIP MORRIS ADMITS SMOKING RISKS
</P>
<P>
   Philip Morris is acknowledging that scientific evidence shows
that smoking causes lung cancer and other deadly diseases after
decades of disputing the findings of the United States Surgeon
General and other authorities.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL AGENTS FACE ONLINE RIVALRY
</P>
<P>
   After a fitful start, the online travel marketplace is finding
firm footing as people become adept at using the Internet and as
personal computers achieve greater household penetration. That
could mean trouble for travel agents.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
