u s BC-SOX-WILLIAMS-BOS &LR;      10-12 0737
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOX-WILLIAMS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TED WILLIAMS HAS A SPLENDID OPINION OF THIS TEAM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ He is the greatest living ballplayer, perhaps the
best hitter of all time, and certainly the signature player in the
99-year history of the Boston Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   No one suffered more at the hands of the New York Yankees than
Ted Williams, who played for the Sox from 1939-60 and watched the
Yankees go to the World Series 16 times (winning 12) while he went
once.
</P>
<P>
   Like much of New England, the godfather of Red Sox Nation is
beginning to wonder whether this might be the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't bet against the Red Sox right now,'' Williams said
Tuesday from his home in Hernando, Fla. ``I just think this might
be the year of all years the way things are developing. Yes, sir.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole world is watching the Red Sox. I tell you what, here
I am, an old guy, and I can't wait to see 'em go. Baseball has just
got everybody hooked right by the throat right now.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, 81, threw out the first ball at the All-Star Game at
Fenway Park this summer and was in Boston on Monday. He had to
return to Florida Monday night, but caught part of the Sox-Indians
game on television. He's fired up at the prospect of a seven-game
series between the Sox and Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   ``That'll be a monumental thing, I'll tell you,'' he said. ``The
Red Sox deserve a hell of a lot of credit. Their manager and
general manager have worked together like two peas in a pod and I
just don't think we've ever had a better 1-2 combination. That
manager has had a hell of a year. I've been on his bandwagon all
the time. He is a great baseball man. I'm not related to him, but
it doesn't sound bad to me.''
</P>
<P>
   When Williams and Joe DiMaggio were the biggest names in
baseball, the Red Sox and Yankees engaged in one of the best
pennant races in history, a battle that was chronicled in David
Halberstam's ``Summer of '49'' The Sox went to New York for the
final two games of the season, needing only one victory to win the
pennant. Boston lost both games.
</P>
<P>
   ``In '49 we had a hell of a team, but so did they,'' said
Williams. ``Those are still games that a lot of people keep talking
about.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can only tell you every time we played the Yankees, they
were tough. They always seemed to have a lot of guys. They'd get a
new guy in the lineup and the guy would be outstanding or a Hall of
Famer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember when I saw Yogi Berra walk up to home plate for the
first time at Fenway Park. They said, `Now catching for the New
York Yankees, Yogi Berra.' And I saw him walking up there and I
thought, `Who are they trying to (expletive) with this guy?' And he
goes down as one of the greatest catchers. That was the Yankees for
you.''
</P>
<P>
   He hasn't seen a lot of the '99 Sox, but likes what he's seen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know any of 'em coming in,'' said Williams. ``Then I
get a chance to see 'em and I say, `Hey this guy is a pretty good
player.' We've had a couple of players that snuck away, but we've
come up with some great pitchers.''
</P>
<P>
   Nomar Garciaparra is a particular Williams favorite. The AL
batting champ made a visit to Hernando last spring and talked
hitting with the Splinter. Williams had a sore elbow (hit by a
pitch) when he hit only .200 in the 1946 World Series. He
appreciates what Garciaparra (sore wrist after being hit by a
pitch) is doing under trying conditions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how Nomar is doing it,'' said Williams. ``He
wants to play so damn bad and he's so damn good. He's just
tremendous. And that little guy at third base (John Valentin), I
like. He's good. I love him.''
</P>
<P>
   Like the rest of the hardball world, he is impressed by Pedro
Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's certainly a nice guy,'' said Williams. ``I talked to him
at the All-Star Game. I'd never seen him pitch, but as I walked in
there and saw him throw a couple of balls, I thought, `Boy, can
this guy throw the ball.' ''
</P>
<P>
   What about it, Ted? Could you have hit Pedro?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if I could have hit him or not,'' the Kid said
humbly. ``If I faced him I wouldn't try to pull him until I had a
chance. Like with any tough pitcher, one thing any good hitter has
got to do is don't help him! But he is so close all the time with a
tough pitch.''
</P>
<P>
   Don't be fooled. He could have hit Pedro. And he could hit any
Yankee they throw out there.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
