u f BC-RAYTHEON-EARNINGS-NYT     10-12 0796
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAYTHEON-EARNINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAYTHEON FURTHER REDUCES FORECAST OF PROFIT, AND SHARES FALL 43
PERCENT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass., Calif.)   (af)  
 By AMY HARMON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Less than a month after warning investors that earnings would be
lower than expected, Raytheon Co. reduced its forecasts again
Tuesday, sending its shares plunging 43 percent after a delayed
opening on the New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   The military contractor, which is based in Lexington, Mass.,
said sales would grow 3 percent this year and next, half its
earlier forecast. It also said that profit margins at its Raytheon
Systems Corp. unit, which accounts for about three-quarters of its
revenue, would be about 12 percent instead of the expected 15
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel P. Burnham, Raytheon's chairman and chief executive,
cited delayed orders and tougher competition abroad for the
setback. He also said that Raytheon's aggressive acquisition
strategy might have stretched the company's management team beyond
its limits.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been a shift in environment for every senior manager
in the company,'' Burnham said, ``and as a result their sense of
history has been distorted. When these companies were brought
together, they were restructured around products. That created an
opportunity to lose perspective on what was going on.''
</P>
<P>
   Raytheon said it now expects this year's profit to range from
$2.70 to $2.80 a share, excluding special charges, compared with
analysts' previous forecasts of $3.56 a share. Earnings, with
pretax charges of $638 million for restructuring and project
problems this year, will be between $1.40 and $1.50 a share.
</P>
<P>
   Profit in 2000 will be $2.10 to $2.25 a share, it said, down
from estimates of $3.91, and Raytheon will take pretax charges next
year of $30 million to eliminate about 2,000 jobs, close plants and
write down investments.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, the company had profit from operations of $1.14
billion, or $3.34 a share, on sales of $19.5 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Several Wall Street analysts who participated in a conference
call with Raytheon executives Tuesday afternoon were less than
sympathetic to the company's explanations.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are shocked,'' said Cai von Rumohr, an analyst with
S.G. Cowen &AMP; Co. ``The estimate has come down a huge amount, and
it's very hard sitting on the outside to sort out how much of this
is lack of control.''
</P>
<P>
   Raytheon's troubles are particularly worrisome because the
company had been widely viewed as one of the best-managed concerns
in the armaments industry.
</P>
<P>
   Burnham, who has a reputation as a cost-cutter, took the helm
last December, and the company's Tomahawk cruise missiles played a
leading role in the war in the Balkans this summer. In July,
Raytheon's class B stock price touched a 52-week high of $76.5625.
</P>
<P>
   But after an intense period of mergers and of comparatively easy
cost-cutting through consolidation, aerospace companies are facing
a more and more volatile business environment, with fewer places to
hide the reality of sagging profits.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me this is disappointing but not unexpected,'' said Jon
Kutler, president of Quarterdeck Investment Partners, an aerospace
mergers-and-acquisitions company based in Los Angeles. ``When you
take away the benefits of consolidation, this is really the nature
of the rough-and-tumble business.''
</P>
<P>
   The class B shares of Raytheon fell to $24.25 Tuesday, dropping
$18.75 late in the day, after the delayed opening.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've got a real credibility problem,'' said Charles
Gabriel, senior vice president at Prudential Securities. ``They
need to regain confidence from management that these are not
permanent problems. But frankly, I think people are going to take
another look at the stock,'' he added, ``and think of it as a
buying opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   Raytheon has been cutting its expenses and had 11,300 jobs and
said it expected to cut 15,400 positions by the end of the year,
which would leave its total work force at 115,000. The company also
said it had reduced plant space by 4.5 million square feet.
</P>
<P>
   Raytheon has suffered because such customers as Egypt and Taiwan
have delayed purchases of the Patriot missile. The sale to Taiwan,
for example, may not be booked until 2001, the company said during
the conference call.
</P>
<P>
   Competing systems will hurt sales of the Patriot missile, it
added, citing Russia and France as countries whose munitions makers
were becoming more active in the markets Raytheon serves.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Burnham emphasized that the company's core programs were
on track. He denied a report that the Tomahawk missiles and several
other fixed-price contracts with the Pentagon were running over
cost. A Pentagon spokesman told reporters that Raytheon is not
considered ``a troubled contractor.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
