<HEADER>
A4815 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBC-GATECH-RECEIVERS-     10-12 0515
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-GATECH-RECEIVERS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Campbell a second deep threat
 &HT;    By J.C. Clemons
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ His fractured jaw has been wired for about four weeks.
But when Kelly Campbell saw that the North Carolina secondary was
lined up close and daring Georgia Tech to throw long, he couldn't
keep his mouth shut.
</P>
<P>
   Through clenched teeth, the receiver went to the sideline and
pleaded with offensive coordinator Ralph Friedgen and receivers
coach Stan Hixon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told the coaches, `We need to go deep on these boys and get
into the end zone,' '' Campbell said. ``(North Carolina) wanted to
play man-press (coverage), so I said, `Let's go deep.'''
</P>
<P>
   Friedgen and Hixon listened, and soon the Tar Heels were burned.
Tech was on its way to a 31-24 overtime win Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've gained a lot of respect for Kelly Campbell,'' head coach
George O'Leary said of the sophomore from Mays High whose jaw was
fractured when he was slugged in the Florida State loss Sept. 11.
``He puts the (defensive) focus on the whole field and not just on
Dez (White)'s side.''
</P>
<P>
   Campbell leads Tech with 26 catches for 473 yards and four
touchdowns. White has 19 for 477 and three touchdowns, and backup
flanker Kerry Watkins has 11 for 173 yards and three scores.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell, who says he was timed in 4.29 seconds in the 40-yard
dash in high school, torched the Tar Heels on a 47-yard scoring
pass in the second quarter. He ran a hitch-and-go pattern up the
right sideline and caught the toss from quarterback Joe Hamilton
that helped move Tech within 13-7.
</P>
<P>
   On Tech's first play of the second half, Campbell again got
behind the secondary and hauled in a 59-yard pass that helped put
Tech ahead 14-13. He wasn't finished. On the tying drive, Campbell
caught passes of 32 and 35 yards to set up Luke Manget's field
goal. In all, he had seven catches for 203 yards. It was no
coincidence Campbell's performance came the week after White
scorched Maryland for 215 yards on five catches.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been fortunate that Kelly has been coming on,'' Hixon
said. ``It's been a blessing to our offense because we were
throwing to Dez so much, on third downs (opponents) were sending
the safety over to his side.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now they can't double(-team) but one of them. But which one?
The Florida State game was a coming out for Kelly, and Saturday
showed it wasn't a fluke. Kelly can flat-out run past people.''
</P>
<P>
   White credits Hixon, in his fifth season coaching the receivers,
for developing him, Campbell and Watkins. ``He really pushes in
practice,'' White said. ``And there is a healthy competition going
on between all of us.''
</P>
<P>
   As long as defenses continue to dare the Jackets to go deep,
that competition should pay dividends on Saturdays.
</P>
<P>
   ``We invite the man-press coverage,'' Hixon said. ``We're
thinking touchdown. Press us with no deep help _ please. That's the
attitude we have.''
</P>
<P>
   J.C. Clemons writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
