<HEADLINE>
PAKISTANI CITIZENS SHOW UP FOR COUP-IN-PROGRESS 
</HEADLINE>
  (With PAKISTAN-COUP and related stories.) 
(mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ISLAMABAD, Pakistan _ Late-model cars lined the road leading to
Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif's official residence, as citizens,
hearing that a military coup was in progress, drove in to watch.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are truckloads of soldiers here,'' one woman reported
smilingly into her mobile phone. ``Why don't you come and see for
yourself?''
</P>
<P>
   Some who gathered here clearly were more riveted, for Tuesday at
least, by the spectacle of Sharif's overthrow than the political
consequences.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not concerned with what happens to the prime minister or
who comes next,'' said a housewife who gave her name as Asma. ``We
had dinner and a friend phoned my husband about all this. So we
thought we should watch it and we came here.''
</P>
<P>
   A 14-year-old girl called Samina pulled her mother by the hand
toward a wireless set with a long antenna being used by one of the
soldiers. ``What a strange phone!'' she said to the man in uniform.
He gently asked her girl to step back.
</P>
<P>
   The troops did not push the onlookers away but prevented them
from crossing a certain point. They were harsher, though, to the
swarm of reporters who were staking out the place where Sharif was
being held in ``protective custody.''
</P>
<P>
   Several Sharif supporters also arrived at the scene but stood
silently. They were soon surrounded by a group of people who began
shouting pro-military slogans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why not hail the army? What's wrong with it?'' asked one of
the men who cheered the military, Qadeer Ahmed. ``What has this
government done for us? Have they given us jobs?''
</P>
<P>
   However, a doctor who gave his name as Iftikhar Ali disagreed,
calling the military takeover a blow to democracy. ``How long will
the army continue to destroy civilian governments?'' he asked.
</P>
</TEXT>
