<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-12 22:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4824 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKN-KRIKORIAN-COLUMN-     10-12 1233
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KRIKORIAN-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO HIDING WILT'S GREATNESS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOUG KRIKORIAN  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   They tell me Wilt Chamberlain is dead.
</P>
<P>
   But I know he isn't.
</P>
<P>
   Immortals live forever.
</P>
<P>
   And I figured this would be Wilt Chamberlain's destiny since,
after all, this was a man who performed such superhuman
accomplishments as scoring 100 points in a single NBA game,
averaging 50.4 points in a season and establishing so many other
similarly celestial marks that will remain unchallenged into
posterity.
</P>
<P>
   Across the American athletic landscape of the 20th century, no
figure dominated his sport with the statistical thoroughness that
Wilton Norman Chamberlain did when he was stuffing basketballs,
grabbing rebounds and blocking shots during his 14 seasons of
distinction in the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   And I'm not sure there ever has been an athlete who inspired as
much awe off the arena of play as on it as the 7-1, 275-pound
Chamberlain, who spent almost his entire existence having to endure
the oohs and aahs and stares of the autograph-seeking masses.
</P>
<P>
   ``How can I hide?'' Wilt Chamberlain once complained to me. ``I
can't go anywhere _ the gas station, the grocery store,
restaurants, the doctor's office _ without people coming up and
bothering me. But I've learned to live with it.''
</P>
<P>
   He came out of Overbrook High in Philadelphia in 1955 as the
most publicized prep basketball player in the history of this
country, and it's a badly kept secret that he received an immense
sum to attend the University of Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure any player in the NBA was making more money than
I was at Kansas,'' he once admitted to me.
</P>
<P>
   He would play two seasons for the Jayhawks, but would leave
school after his team was beaten by North Carolina in triple
overtime in the NCAA title game in 1958.
</P>
<P>
   He would tour a year with the Harlem Globetrotters, and then
would begin his mythic stay in the NBA in 1959 when he joined the
Philadelphia Warriors, who would shift to San Francisco in 1962.
</P>
<P>
   He would return to Philadelphia a couple of years later, and
soon the 76ers would become such an NBA power that they dethroned
the mighty Boston Celtics in 1967 during a record-breaking, 68-win
season.
</P>
<P>
   He was a complex, sensitive man given to severe mood swings when
he was a player, lapsing into a boorish silence one day and then
becoming a fun-loving chatterbox the next.
</P>
<P>
   He could be rude and uncaring, but he also could be kind and
giving as he was one evening when he gave the San Pedro
restaurateur, Lou Trani, his NBA Rookie of the Year trophy.
</P>
<P>
   He was particularly defensive about the constant media criticism
he received about his teams always finishing behind the Celtics and
their nonpareil center, Bill Russell.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing could incite Chamberlain's anger more than this subject.
</P>
<P>
   ``Put Bob Cousy, Bill Sharman, Sam Jones, K.C. Jones, Tommy
Heinsohn, Frank Ramsey and John Havlicek on my teams and let
Russell have the guys I had to play with,'' Chamberlain often said.
``Then I would have been the one sipping the champagne at the end
of every season.''
</P>
<P>
   For 21 years, from 1968 until 1989 when we had a serious falling
out, Wilt Chamberlain probably was my closest pal in athletics, a
person I had dinner with countless times.
</P>
<P>
   I covered him during his seasons with the Lakers as a young
reporter for the Los Angeles Herald Examiner, meeting him for the
first time on a team flight to Philadelphia when he recruited me to
be the fourth member of a card game called hearts. The other
participants were Elgin Baylor and Jerry West.
</P>
<P>
   We didn't exactly strike up an immediate friendship, especially
after I led off a subsequent story describing Chamberlain's work
thusly: ``Wilt Chamberlain was the tallest spectator at the Forum
last night.''
</P>
<P>
   Chamberlain's first year in Los Angeles was an eventful one,
with his season-long feud with the Lakers' coach, Bill van Breda
Kolff, being one of the highlights.
</P>
<P>
   It would be a disappointing ending for Chamberlain, who would be
kept humiliatingly on the bench by van Breda Kolff in the closing
minutes of Game 7 against the Celtics and his eternal nemesis,
Russell, playing his final contest.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers would lose that championship match by a point, and
Chamberlain never forgave van Breda Kolff for the slight.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd have won that game had van Bred Kolff put me back in,''
insisted Chamberlain. ``Van Breda Kolff got our team beat just to
get back at me.''
</P>
<P>
   Van Breda Kolff soon would be fired by the then Laker owner,
Jack Kent Cooke, but it would be four more seasons before
Chamberlain would win his second NBA title.
</P>
<P>
   The 1971-72 Lakers are considered by sporting pundits as one of
the great teams in NBA history they won a record 33 straight that
still stands and it was
</P>
<P>
   Chamberlain's rebounding and shot-blocking that were the vital
factors.
</P>
<P>
   It came out later in a highly fictionalized autobiography that
Wilt Chamberlain was a lady killer with thousands of conquests, but
the Chamberlain I knew was not particularly smooth with the
opposite sex, and I never saw him besieged by females.
</P>
<P>
   There were several occasions when the Lakers were on the road,
and Chamberlain and I would have dinner together on off days.
</P>
<P>
   He was given to hyperbolic rhetoric, and there was nothing that
Uncle Wiltie, that was the sobriquet I gave him, couldn't do better
than anyone else score points, grab rebounds, lift weights, fight,
high jump, run, score on women, play volleyball, etc.
</P>
<P>
   He lived alone in his Bel Air mansion that he had built in the
early 1970s, and was a physical fitness fanatic who exercised
almost every day of his life.
</P>
<P>
   He remained an active bachelor throughout his 63 years who
savored traveling around the world, and he never came close to
getting married.
</P>
<P>
   ``I figure there is something wrong with an institution in which
more than 50 percent who try it get divorced,'' he once told me
during an interview I did with him for Inside Sports Magazine.
``And out of the other 50 percent, I'm willing to bet 40 percent of
those people want to get divorced. The odds just aren't good.''
</P>
<P>
   I think of Wilt Chamberlain, and I can recall chauffeuring him
around in a rental car in Atlanta and remembering the reaction of a
startled cabbie at a stop light when he saw Chamberlain.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is that you Wilt?'' the cabbie asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, it's Bill Russell,'' cracked Wilt.
</P>
<P>
   I think of Wilt Chamberlain, and think of all the telephone
conversations we had about Kareem Abdul-Jabbar and how he got so
mad at me for detailing the contents from one of them in a column
for which he never forgave me.
</P>
<P>
   I think of Wilt Chamberlain, and I can recall the evening he
scored 66 points against the Phoenix Suns and the evening he
grabbed 44 rebounds against Russell's Celtics and the evening he
blocked 23 shots against the San Francisco Warriors and that
magical evening when he led the Lakers to their first world
championship in Los Angeles with a stirring performance against the
New York Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't get any better than this,'' he would say to me in a
rare display of emotion later in the Forum press lounge.
</P>
<P>
   I think of Wilt Chamberlain, and I can remember all the sorrows
and laughs and dazzling feats dispensed by a man who literally was
a giant of this nation's athletics.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-12-99 2224EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991012.0405 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-12 22:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4826 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-PAKISTAN-REAX-1STLD-W     10-12 1003
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PAKISTAN-REAX-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITE HOUSE FEARS FURTHER DESTABILIZATION IN PAKISTAN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS to change spelling of Musharraf's first name in 7th graf,
from Pervez to Pervaiz.)  (With PAKISTAN-COUP, PAKISTAN-MUSHARRAF, PAKISTAN-SCENE) 
(mk) 
 By JANE PERLEZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Clinton administration urged the Pakistani
military to restore democratic government as quickly as possible,
but at the same time officials acknowledged that Prime Minister
Nawaz Sharif's rule had been increasingly corrupt and autocratic.
</P>
<P>
   The overthrow of Sharif was the latest in a series of turbulent
events on the subcontinent that have left the administration
fearful that Islamic militancy will strengthen in Pakistan, a poor
and heavily populated country that last year tested nuclear
weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials said they did not believe that the
control of Pakistan's nuclear capability was significantly affected
by the military takeover. Under Sharif, the Pakistani army managed
the nuclear sites and devices and maintained final authority over
them, they said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The military has custodial control over nuclear weapons,'' a
senior administration official said. ``We have been assured by
Pakistani civilian authorities in the past that they have control
over their release. How this is playing out with the military
government we will have to see. We see this as a political crisis,
not one concerning the control or use of nuclear weapons.''
</P>
<P>
   The overall picture of Pakistan slipping toward chaos as it
faced a hostile neighbor, India, which also tested nuclear weapons
last year, helped make the subcontinent one of the most precarious
regions, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last thing we need is a chaotic Pakistan where you have
democracy put on the back shelf, the economy in a shambles and we
get a Talibanization of Pakistan,'' said a senior U.S. official.
Islamic fundamentalism has become more prevalent in the Pakistani
army since the military was cut off from U.S. government assistance
in the early 1990s, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The administration said that after a televised address Tuesday
night by Gen. Pervaiz Musharraf, proclaiming army rule, it remained
unclear what steps he would take next.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to see the earliest possible restoration of democracy
in Pakistan. We hope Gen. Musharraf will set forth clear plans for
the restoration of a civilian government in Pakistan,'' the State
Department spokesman, James Rubin, said.
</P>
<P>
   It was possible, officials said, that Musharraf might follow the
pattern of the last two military takeovers in Pakistan and appoint
a government of civilian technocrats to run the country.
</P>
<P>
   Rumors of a possible coup in Pakistan had been surfacing since
Sharif, under pressure in July from President Clinton, urged
Musharraf to withdraw his forces from the Indian-held side of
Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
   The withdrawal of the forces from beyond Pakistan's side of the
cease-fire line in the disputed Himalayan territory of Kashmir has
been cited by the White House as one of Clinton's foreign policy
successes this year.
</P>
<P>
   But the retreat of the army was unpopular on the streets of
Pakistan and in the military. Sharif reacted by cracking down on
opposition parties, the courts and the press, as well as
downgrading the status of the president.
</P>
<P>
   In September, Shahbaz Sharif, the brother of the prime minister,
came to Washington to meet with administration officials to follow
up on the July meeting. In the process, he warned of the worsening
domestic crisis, a senior administration official said.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after, opposition leaders began to tell American officials
the same things. The State Department then issued a public
statement warning Pakistan not to undertake any
``extraconstitutional'' measures.
</P>
<P>
   At about the same time, the Pakistani chief of intelligence, Lt.
Gen. Mohammed Ziauddin, visited Washington in late September and
warned the CIA director, George Tenet, and others that tensions
between Sharif and Musharraf were coming to a head, an official
said.
</P>
<P>
   The imminence of a coup appeared to abate slightly when Sharif
formally extended Musharraf's tenure into 2001, but revived again,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, the administration warned Sharif against
continuing his ``undermining of democracy.''
</P>
<P>
   Musharraf became the second chief of the army to be dismissed by
the prime minister within a year, a situation that the army
interpreted as a threat to its traditional role.
</P>
<P>
   The prime minister handpicked Musharraf, a commando-trained,
headstrong officer with less education than his predecessor, Gen.
Jehangir Karamat, who was fired last October after making
unfavorable public comments about the prime minister's style of
leadership.
</P>
<P>
   The United States cut military aid to the Pakistani army in the
early 1990s after President Bush could no longer certify to
Congress that Pakistan was not in possession of nuclear devices.
</P>
<P>
   Traditionally, the Pakistani army has been a stabilizing
influence but has become more vulnerable to Islamic influences in
recent years. This was especially so as the tradition of
better-educated men joining the military faded, experts said.
</P>
<P>
   In the last year, as the economy has weakened, army officers
have collected electric bill payments and completed other menial
tasks to try and keep the country running, said Michael Krepon, the
president of the Henry L. Stimson Center, which studies arms
control issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``The army does not want to run the country but the army wants
to be the main repository of power,'' Krepon said.
</P>
<P>
   But there were increasing possibilities of the army's
fracturing, Krepon said. ``There are eight or nine core commanders
in Pakistan. The army has one of two choices: They could rally
behind a guy who is a loose cannon like Musharraf or they could
divide,'' Krepon said.
</P>
<P>
   If the army divided, then the question of command and control
over the nuclear devices would come to the fore, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
