<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-12 22:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4830 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-FRENCH-BANK-MGM-FRAUD     10-12 0860
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRENCH-BANK-MGM-FRAUD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CREDIT LYONNAIS PAYS $4 MILLION FINE TO AVOID CHARGES IN MGM CASE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By ANDREW POLLACK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The French bank Credit Lyonnais has paid $4
million to the U.S. government to avoid criminal charges stemming
from its role in backing the Italian financier Giancarlo Parretti's
takeover of Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer, the Justice Department said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The settlement was announced at the same time that federal
prosecutors here unsealed a 94-page indictment against Parretti and
his former partner, Florio Fiorini, accusing them of numerous
instances of fraud.
</P>
<P>
   It was because of the indictment that Parretti, who has been a
fugitive from sentencing in another case for nearly three years,
was arrested Monday in Orvieto, Italy. Fiorini was arrested Tuesday
outside Rome and both men are being held for extradition to the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, Credit Lyonnais had maintained in legal proceedings
that it had been swindled by Parretti and Fiorini, who took over
MGM in 1990 and were then accused of nearly driving the studio to
financial ruin, forcing the bank to absorb losses of as much as $2
billion.
</P>
<P>
   But in the settlement, the bank admitted that it had not
exercised adequate oversight, that there was ``substantial
evidence'' that at least one former bank official engaged in
intentional wrongdoing, and that three bank officials accepted
bribes from Parretti and Fiorini. According to the indictment of
the two men, bank officers were given shares in a company,
vacations to Bora-Bora, flights on Parretti's Gulfstream IV and art
work.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bank always said they were victimized, their employees
were cheated or deceived,'' Jeffrey B. Isaacs, the assistant U.S.
attorney in charge of the case, said Tuesday. ``When we looked at
some of the transactions, it didn't really make sense.''
</P>
<P>
   Credit Lyonnais said in the settlement that it ``regrets and
accepts responsibility for any consequences in the United States
that this conduct and lack of supervision may have caused.'' The
bank's lawyers at White &AMP; Case, a New York law firm, did not
comment.
</P>
<P>
   The settlement states that criminal charges were not being
brought because Credit Lyonnais was cooperating with the
investigation and because the bank had spent $2 billion to bail out
MGM and reimburse shareholders and creditors of the studio and of
the Pathe Communications Corp., another company Parretti had
controlled.
</P>
<P>
   The settlement was reached in June and the payment made then,
but was kept secret so as not to tip off Parretti, 57, and Fiorini,
58. Similarly, the indictment of the two men was returned by a
federal grand jury last November, but kept under seal while
documents were prepared to secure the arrest and extradition of the
two men.
</P>
<P>
   The extradition requests are being hand-carried to Italy this
week, although it could take up to a year to determine if the two
men will be brought to the United States for trial, prosecutors
said.
</P>
<P>
   The indictment charges Parretti and Fiorini with securities
fraud, conspiracy, filing false reports with the Securities and
Exchange Commission, falsifying corporate records of Pathe and MGM,
and making false statements to auditors. The indictment charges
Parretti alone with international money laundering and tax evasion.
</P>
<P>
   The investigation by the Federal Bureau of Investigation and the
Internal Revenue Service took several years and used evidence from
10 countries. It stands to provide the most complete account of the
actions by Parretti and Fiorini to get control of Cannon Group _ a
publicly traded independent film producer that was renamed Pathe
Communications _ and subsequently of MGM, which Parretti bought for
$1.3 billion from the billionaire Kirk Kerkorian, who eventually
bought it back from Credit Lyonnais. Parretti and Fiorini are
accused of falsely claiming that there was sufficient equity in the
MGM acquisition deal so that MGM and Pathe could maintain normal
operations. But, the indictment states that there was virtually no
equity, that the two men had secretly pledged Pathe and MGM assets
to Credit Lyonnais and that more than $1.1 billion of the money to
buy MGM came from secret loans by the bank.
</P>
<P>
   The indictment also says that Parretti engaged in a scheme to
loot MGM by diverting more than $15 million in corporate funds and
the European rights to MGM's ``roaring lion'' logo to an Italian
company he and his wife controlled.
</P>
<P>
   Another charge is that Pathe sold movie theaters it owned in
Britain and the Netherlands at an inflated price to a shell company
secretly controlled by Parretti and Fiorini. This improved Pathe's
financial condition and helped the Dutch subsidiary of Credit
Lyonnais deceive Dutch banking regulators by shifting bad debt to
what appeared to be a new borrower.
</P>
<P>
   Parretti is involved in numerous legal entanglements. In October
1996, he was convicted in a Delaware court of perjury and tampering
with evidence in a civil lawsuit brought against him by Credit
Lyonnais. But in January 1997, he fled the United States and was a
fugitive until his arrest Monday. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
