<HEADLINE>
CHIP PRICES CAUSES DROP IN INTEL'S THIRD-QUARTER EARNINGS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Calif., N.Y.)   (af)  
 By LAWRENCE M. FISHER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The Intel Corp. posted third-quarter earnings
Tuesday that fell a few cents short of analysts' estimates because
of falling prices for microprocessors and narrower profit margins.
</P>
<P>
   But Intel executives said that sales growth had been on target
in the period.
</P>
<P>
   For the quarter ended Sept. 25, net income for Intel fell 6.4
percent, to $1.46 billion, or 42 cents a diluted share, compared
with $1.56 billion, or 44 cents a share, in the period a year
earlier. Revenue rose 9 percent, to $7.33 billion from $6.73
billion.
</P>
<P>
   The results reflect one-time charges of $333 million for
purchased research and development, $121 million of amortization of
goodwill and other costs related to acquisitions. For the first
time, Intel broke out the goodwill _ the difference between the
price paid for a company and the value of its assets _ which was
previously included in the cost of sales.
</P>
<P>
   Without the one-time charges, Intel earned $1.9 billion, or 55
cents a diluted share, up 20.3 percent from $1.58 billion, or 45
cents a share, in the quarter a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts attributed the results to falling prices for chips,
delays in new products and supply constraints caused by the
earthquake in Taiwan last month.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts had expected Intel to earn 57 cents a share, according
to First Call/Thomson Financial, which tracks company earnings. The
so-called whisper number was 60 cents, according to
Earningswhispers.com.
</P>
<P>
   First Call had advised analysts not to include the goodwill in
their estimates, but some did so anyway, leading to some confusion
over whether Intel missed estimates by 2 cents or more.
</P>
<P>
   ``From my reference point, they missed the number by 4 cents,
not 2, but that's less important than the outlook, which at this
point is extremely guarded,'' said Drew Peck, an analyst with SG
Cowen. He said he thought Intel was being intentionally vague about
its prospects for the fourth quarter because it still does not know
the extent of the effect of the Taiwan earthquake on PC shipments.
``They may be the first major casualty of Taiwan,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Before Intel reported its results, its shares rose 18.75 cents,
to $76.6875. In after-hours trading, they fell as low as $71.
</P>
<P>
   In July, when Intel reported its second-quarter results, Intel
executives predicted that gross margins would be up in the third
quarter. They fell instead, which Andy D. Bryant, Intel's chief
financial officer, attributed to lower average selling prices, a
reduction in the value of existing inventory, and an increase in
start-up costs associated with new products. ``We underestimated
the effect of the delay in manufacturing on 0.18 micron,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Intel's fastest Pentium III processors are currently
manufactured in a process under which each circuit is 0.25 micron
in width; going to 0.18 micron will help reduce processor sizes,
allowing more chips per wafer, which reduces cost, while also
allowing the production of faster chips.
</P>
<P>
   Competition at the high end of its product line heated up for
Intel during the quarter as Advanced Micro Devices Inc. introduced
its Athlon chip at speeds up to 700 megahertz. The fastest Pentium
III currently available is 600 MHz.
</P>
<P>
   Since Advanced Micro also has yet to move to 0.18 micron, with
its inherent speed advantage, it could continue to maintain the
highest speed processor on the market. IBM and Compaq Computer have
both introduced PCs using the Athlon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that at the high end of Intel's product line, the
execution has not been as good as it could be, and as it should
be,'' said Mark Edelstone, an analyst with Morgan Stanley Dean
Witter. The net result, he said, has been to reduce the proportion
of higher-end, higher-profit products in Intel's revenue mix, which
pushed down total sales and profit margins, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Intel said it expected revenue for the fourth quarter to rise
from the third quarter and that gross profit margin should increase
as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``We remain on track for a seasonally strong second half,'' Paul
Otellini executive vice president and general manager of Intel's
architecture business group, said in a conference call with
analysts. ``At this point we believe our supply of materials from
Taiwan is not affected, and our customers have not asked us to do
anything different as a result of the quake,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   During the quarter, Intel acquired four companies: the Dialogic
Corp., Level One Communications, Softcom Microsystems Inc. and the
Netboost Corp. These deals were valued at more than $3 billion
combined and were intended to strengthen Intel's networking and
communications product offerings. Intel also introduced Intel
Online Services Inc., which will operate corporate computer systems
over the World Wide Web. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
