<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AFLCIO-CONVENTION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNION LEADERS SEE GRIM NEWS IN LABOR STUDY 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By STEVEN GREENHOUSE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ After years of blithely ignoring the decline of
organized labor, the AFL-CIO is force-feeding union leaders a heavy
dose of bad news _ that job growth is fastest in industries where
unions are weakest while job losses are greatest in industries
where unions are strongest.
</P>
<P>
   The news came in a study commissioned by the AFL-CIO as a
wake-up call to union leaders across the nation to organize or see
the labor movement continue its decades-long decline.
</P>
<P>
   The study, which was made public last week and is being
discussed at the AFL-CIO convention here this week, also shows that
the fastest-growing metropolitan areas, like Atlanta, Dallas,
Houston, Miami and Phoenix, tended to have the lowest percentage of
workers in unions. And the slowest-growing metropolitan areas,
including Chicago and New York, which has 13 percent of the
nation's union members, tended to have the highest percentage of
workers in unions.
</P>
<P>
   ``In overall terms, the economy is moving against us,'' said
David Chu, the labor federation's director of strategic research
and the official who was in charge of the study.
</P>
<P>
   For decades, following the lead of its 68 member unions, the
American Federation of Labor and Congress of Industrial
Organizations took little interest in organizing. But distressed
about labor's declining numbers and clout, AFL-CIO president John
Sweeney has made it take a more forceful role, goading and cajoling
the member unions to get more serious about organizing.
</P>
<P>
   Sweeney has said he is worried that as the percentage of workers
in unions has plunged to 13.9 percent today, from 35 percent four
decades ago, labor's bargaining clout has atrophied, making it
easier for employers to hold down wages not just for unionized
workers, but for nonunion ones too.
</P>
<P>
   The study found that between 1984 and 1997, the 30
fastest-growing sectors of the economy, including hotels,
child-care, finance, retail trade and airlines, added 26 million
new jobs, but only one in 20 of workers in those industries joined
unions.
</P>
<P>
   The study also showed that in eight industries with the greatest
job loss, including steel and auto, four-fifths of the 2.1 million
jobs lost belonged to union members. Those jobs were often lost
because of competition from imports and because managers moved
operations overseas to take advantage of lower-cost labor.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're somewhat a victim of our own success,'' Chu said.
``Heavily organized industries have high wages and benefits.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite Sweeney's calls for more organizing, only a few unions _
most notably the Service Employees International Union and the
Hotel Employees and Restaurant Employees Union _ have aggressively
increased their spending on organizing.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the communication workers' union has begun an
uphill fight to organize workers at Microsoft and IBM, while the
auto workers' union is stepping up efforts to organize auto parts
plants. And with the apparel industry continuing to shed jobs
because of imports, the Union of Needletrades, Industrial and
Textile Employees is making a big push to unionize the industrial
laundry industry, having organized 9,000 laundry workers last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a major growth industry, and it can't move off shore,''
said Bruce Raynor, secretary-treasurer of the needletrades union.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-12-99 2240EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991012.0410 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-12 22:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4842 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-AFLCIO-GORE-NYT &LR;      10-12 1191
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AFLCIO-GORE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE CAMP PLANS TO ENLIST LABOR AND BLACKS TO COMBAT BRADLEY 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Having all but won the endorsement of one of the
most active armies of foot soldiers in politics, Vice President Al
Gore's campaign is relying on organized labor's grass-roots support
in crucial states like Iowa, New York and California to beat back
the candidacy of former Sen. Bill Bradley in the Democratic
presidential primaries.
</P>
<P>
   Campaign officials say they then hope that in the South they can
win the votes of blacks, who make up 40 percent of the Democratic
electorate there, and go on with little trouble to claim the
nomination.
</P>
<P>
   This double-barreled approach is the big-picture strategy of the
Gore campaign to win the nomination.
</P>
<P>
   The Gore campaign views the labor endorsement as the first
primary because the AFL-CIO, which is meeting here this week, is
expected to send 80 committed delegates to the Democratic National
Convention in August. That is nearly as many as Iowa and New
Hampshire combined and would bring Gore's total committed
delegates, including mayors, governors and members of Congress, to
more than 500 of the 1,000 or so he will need to win the
nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley lags far behind in the delegate count, and officials
said it was this ``electability'' factor that seemed persuasive in
getting the unions to endorse and endorse now, rather than wait.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there is no guarantee that things will work as
planned. The endorsement, which is expected Wednesday, does not
guarantee that the rank and file will enlist, and it will be up to
Gore to inspire them. And while the Gore camp is plotting its nuts
and bolts strategy, Bradley is closing the gap in the polls,
largely by capturing the national imagination in a way that Gore
has yet to do. The latest CNN/Time poll over the weekend put
Bradley within 12 points of the vice president. Six weeks ago the
same poll had them 33 points apart.
</P>
<P>
   But the anticipated Gore endorsement provides the structure for
labor to swing into high gear in places where it has recently
proved its muscle, particularly in saving the candidacies of Gov.
Gray Davis in California and Gov. Tom Vilsack in Iowa. Labor also
has a huge constituency in New York, one of the states where
Bradley, a former star basketball player for the New York Knicks,
has an edge in the polls. The Gore camp expects labor to help turn
the tide there.
</P>
<P>
   The Gore campaign is starting to express some confidence that it
is winning over important Democratic constituents. The only area
where Gore strategists see Bradley firmly ahead is among male
sports fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bradley needs to stop us big time in some component of the
Democratic family, and I don't see where that is,'' said Gore
campaign chairman Tony Coelho. .
</P>
<P>
   The states where labor is strong are also the states that figure
early in the political calendar. Iowa, scheduled to vote Jan. 31,
is first. It is a strong labor state where Gore is ahead. New
Hampshire, where Bradley leads, comes next. Labor has less
influence there, and while the Gore campaign is making an intense
effort to win, the state is not crucial to its success. On March 7
come the big states with important labor strongholds _ California,
Ohio and New York. If organized labor turns out for Gore, he could
virtually sew up the nomination.
</P>
<P>
   But Gore faces a wild card in California, where independents and
Republicans can cross over and vote in the Democratic primary. This
could allow Bradley to win the popular vote, even if the Democratic
delegates still go to Gore. The effect of such an unusual turn of
events would be to give Bradley a psychological advantage that he
could use to slow a Gore roll at a critical juncture.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the expected labor endorsement will not be unanimous.
The teamsters and the United Auto Workers plan to vote against
endorsing Gore. The unions are upset with Gore's embrace of free
trade, and although it differs little from Bradley's, they hope
that by withholding their support, they can extract concessions
from the Clinton administration.
</P>
<P>
   If Gore does not wrap up the nomination after California, the
campaign moves South, where Gore is relying on black voters to
sweep him to victory. Gore has a strong following among blacks for
two reasons: President Clinton is a hero in the black community,
and so is Gore's late father, former Sen. Albert Gore Sr. of
Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   And it is not lost on black voters that Gore has appointed a
black woman, Donna Brazile, as his campaign manager, the first ever
in a presidential election.
</P>
<P>
   The Gore camp believes it has been helped by Bradley's effort to
court homosexuals by supporting the reopening of the Civil Rights
Act to add protections for gay men and women. Prominent blacks are
alarmed by this, saying it would give conservatives in Congress a
chance to roll back hard-fought rights for all, and Gore operatives
are trying to feed those fears.
</P>
<P>
   But how can Gore rely so heavily on labor if the federation's
endorsement was in doubt as recently as last week? His aides, and
union officials, say Gore ran into problems chiefly because he had
not properly courted the leaders. They said, for instance, that
although the vice president's office was working regularly with
unions on labor issues, his staff did not make a political
connection between the issues and Gore's candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gore wasn't calling on the leaders,'' said Gerry Shea, a
senior assistant to AFL-CIO president John Sweeney. ``He assumed it
had been done through the issues people.'' Gore tried to make up
for his inattentiveness by meeting with several leaders here
Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Gore knows he needs to work the AFL-CIO members better than he
worked the leaders. His first test comes later Wednesday, when he
flies to Seattle to meet with aerospace workers.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond sending Gore into union shops, his campaign is relying on
the telephone banks and organization drives that characterized
labor's commitment in the 1998 Congressional elections. The AFL-CIO
diverted the $35 million it had spent in 1996 on television
advertisements and put it instead into local organizing.
</P>
<P>
   AFL-CIO political director Steve Rosenthal said the federation
planned to organize a Gore tree by identifying a Gore supporter in
each union in each state, then in each affiliate, at each work site
and on each shift. He said organizers believe that this
worker-to-worker contact is the best way to get reliable
information to members. In 1998, he said, 76 percent of union
members who received union literature voted for the endorsed
candidate.
</P>
<P>
   But one problem that may emerge for Gore is that the AFL-CIO
intends to focus its efforts on contrasting Gore with the
Republican front-runner, Texas Gov. George W. Bush, not with
Bradley. Rosenthal said this stance would test the theory that the
union could mobilize for Gore without going negative on Bradley. As
another political operative said of avoiding squabbles in
primaries: ``Don't bury the body too deep; you may need to dig it
up again.''  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
