<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-MILLWOOD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ATLANTA'S KEVIN MILLWOOD IS READY FOR GAME 2  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Kevin Millwood has been better in the post-season than
he was during the regular season for the Braves.
</P>
<P>
   After tossing a one-hitter in a complete game against the
Houston Astros in the division series last week, Millwood is hoping
for a similar performance against the Mets on Wednesday night in
Game 2 of the National League Championship Series.
</P>
<P>
   On a staff that includes three former Cy Young Award winners,
Millwood emerged as Atlanta's most consistent pitcher this year
with an 18-7 mark and a 2.68 earned run average. In two starts
against the Mets this season, Millwood is 1-0 with a 1.20 er..
</P>
<P>
   Is Millwood confident he can beat the Mets in Game 2?
</P>
<P>
   ``I've pitched against these guys a couple of times this year,
and I've had some pretty good success,'' the 24-year-old
right-hander from North Carolina said. ``I'm going to do what I've
done in those other two games. Until they make me change, I'm going
to stick with my same game plan.''
</P>
<P>
   Darryl Hamilton and John Olerud were the only two Mets who
managed more than two hits against Millwood this season. Edgardo
Alfonzo was 1 for 14. Mike Piazza was 2 for 16.
</P>
<P>
   While Atlanta's other three starters have been around longer and
have won Cy Young Awards, Greg Maddux, Tom Glavine and John Smoltz
have all had periods when they struggled this year, either because
of injury or inconsistency. But Millwood, who reached the majors in
1997 and was 17-8 for the Braves last year, never had an extended
period of difficulty, and many believe that he is now Atlanta's
ace.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest thing for me this year has been consistency,''
Millwood said. `I haven't mixed in those bad starts between two or
three good ones. I've learned just by sitting back and watching
other guys do it.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the whole season, I guess I would be the most consistent
right now,'' said Millwood, who will oppose the Mets' Kenny Rogers.
``That makes me feel good when people say that. It's nice to be
noticed. I'm not one to go out and beg for a lot of press, but it's
always nice when people say those things about you, when you're on
a staff like this one.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people have considered me to be the so-called ace,
but I don't see it that way. We don't really have an ace on this
staff. We've had three or four guys that would be considered an ace
on just about any other staff. And we're lucky enough to have them
all on this team.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked which Met has given him the most trouble this year,
Millwood singled out Olerud, who was 3 for 11.
</P>
<P>
   ``He sits back with a short swing, and he can hit a line drive
anywhere,'' Millwood said. ``He can hit a home run anywhere. You
try to keep him off balance, but it seems every swing he takes,
he's got good balance and he's hitting the ball hard somewhere. You
want to try to stay away from a guy like that in crucial
situations.''
</P>
<P>
   Against the Astros last week, and in one of the most dominant
pitching performances of the post-season, Millwood seldom
encountered crucial situations. He doesn't expect to top that
performance against the Mets. But if he pitches nearly that well,
it will probably be good enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't possibly try to throw a one-hitter again,'' Millwood
said. ``That's kind of insane. I'm going to pitch the same way I've
pitched all year and try to win. If I give up 10 hits and we win,
that's still a good start. This time of year, I don't think it's
how effective you are; it's whether you win or lose.''
</P>
<P>
   This season, Millwood has done a lot more winning than losing.
He sees no reason the post-season should be any different.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure I'll probably get a little nervous,'' Millwood said.
``But you guys will never know.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
