<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-12 22:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4845 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-ISRAEL-CUBANS-ART-NYT     10-12 1092
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-CUBANS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE EVER-SO-QUIET EXODUS: ISRAELI CUBANS' STORY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By DEBORAH SONTAG    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ASHKELON, Israel _ In their temporary apartment here, Zeida
Quintero and Irolando Carpio watched Tuesday, for the hundredth
time, a videotape of their marathon going-away party in Cuba. He
smoked a hand-rolled cigar, she sipped a bittersweet Cuban coffee.
Outside their window, the sea sparklede palms swayed, so
evocative of home.
</P>
<P>
   But the comparison stopped there. Husband and wife, both
dry-eyed, enjoyed the salsa music and taped memories, but evinced
little nostalgia for what they left behind. And they evinced it in
remarkably fluent Hebrew.
</P>
<P>
   It has been a year since their extended family of nine left
Cuba. But until Monday, Ms. Quintero and Carpio _ and 400 other
Cuban immigrants _ were an Israeli state secret. Few knew that
Cubans have been trickling into Ben-Gurion Airport in Tel Aviv
since 1995, from Havana by way of Paris. Few knew that they have
been living in the immigration center here, among Ethiopians,
Chechens and Yemenis, in other centers and in their own new homes.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli censors banned those few who did learn of the Cubans'
existence from publishing or broadcasting the information. No one
ever mentioned the Cubans' presence on the floor of the Israeli
Parliament. But on Sunday, the government lifted the ban after The
Sunday Telegraph in London disclosed the hidden immigration
program.
</P>
<P>
   Secrecy was a major component of a highly unusual deal that the
Jewish Agency for Israel struck with Fidel Castro, the Cuban
leader, using the Canadians as intermediaries. In an agreement
signed in 1994, Castro, whose country has no formal diplomatic
relations with Israel, agreed to grant exit to any member of Cuba's
dwindling Jewish population who wanted to move to Israel. His only
condition was that the program maintain the lowest possible
profile, both in Cuba and Israel.
</P>
<P>
   In keeping with that agreement, Jewish Agency officials declined
to confirm Tuesday even the existence of the Cubans in Israel,
despite the censors' lifting of restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   But the Cuban immigrants themselves went out of their way to
take advantage of the press disclosures.
</P>
<P>
   Now that their situation could be openly discussed, they said,
they could make public a demand. They wanted, as Carpio put it,
``to be treated like Ethiopians'' in terms of Israeli aid to
immigrants. They wanted Israel to recognize that they had forfeited
all their possessions _ ``down to the drinking glasses,'' Carpio
said _ to the Cuban government. They had arrived with nothing but a
few battered suitcases and 48 pounds of clothes per family. They
want to receive an ``immigration basket'' of money and services,
they said, just like the Ethiopians and, to a less generous extent,
the Russians.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, they're complaining,'' commented Avraham Burg, the
Speaker of the Parliament. ``That means they've really become
Israelis.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Quintero is not complaining, especially not after the
Immigration Minister, Yuli Tamir, proposed late Tuesday that the
Cubans get the help they are asking for.
</P>
<P>
   Fingering her Star of David necklace, Ms. Quintero said she felt
embarrassed that Israel's first glimpse of the Cuban community
showed not their appreciation but their pent-up frustrations. She
also regretted that Israelis might have got what she called a false
impression that most of the Cubans see Israel as a way station to
Miami or New York.
</P>
<P>
   Television cameras could not help but focus Tuesday on one Cuban
immigrant, Ester Mechulam, since she greeted them at the gate to
the center. ``Brooklyn, Brooklyn,'' she was saying. ``I dream of
Brooklyn.''
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, Ms. Quintero said she and her husband considered
themselves ``die-hard Zionist Jews,'' even though, like everyone
else, they left primarily because the opportunity presented itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have well-established family in New York, in New Jersey,''
she said. ``We don't want to join them. We want them to join us
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Israeli experts believe that 1,300 Jews remain in Cuba. Fifteen
more Cubans are expected to arrive next week _ assuming Castro does
not freeze the program because it has gone public _ and 200 have
completed the paperwork to leave. Over the last four years, 10
immigrants have chosen to return to Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   The small Jewish community in Santa Clara, Cuba, had dwindled to
eight families, including Ms. Quintero's. Now there are just seven.
The old synagogue houses a government museum, an ode to the
revolution that makes no mention of the building's history.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Quintero said she originally came from a town in Matanzas
Province where everyone was Jewish. Inside their homes, they held
Jewish weddings and celebrated Passover. Outside, like everyone
else in Cuba, they practiced no religion. Neither did they ever
encounter anti-Semitism, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Once Castro began easing restrictions on religious activities,
the Jewish families in Santa Clara began holding community-wide
Sabbath dinners, rotating from one home to the next. International
Jewish organizations sent ``guides'' to teach them prayers and
rituals, Ms. Quintero said.
</P>
<P>
   No posters or fliers or radio commercials told the Jews of Cuba
that they were free to leave for Israel. The information traveled
by word of mouth, ``from Jew to Jew,'' said Edwin Sanchez Perez,
24, who came from Havana and wears a gold hoop earring in each ear.
</P>
<P>
   ``For one and a half years I awaited a visa,'' he said. ``Here
in Israel I don't go to synagogue. It's not my thing. But in Cuba,
during that year and a half, if I hadn't gone to synagogue I
wouldn't have been allowed to leave. Not that the Cuban government
cared. It was the Jewish community leaders who gave the thumbs up
or thumbs down.''
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to the Israeli Tourism Ministry, Ms. Quintero
requested brochures. Somehow, they gave her family the wrong
impression.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought Israel was purely religious,'' said her husband,
Carpio. ``Also that it was very poor. Then we got here and saw that
it was a tremendous economic superpower.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a miracle,'' he said. ``In the desert, they grow here
mangos sweeter than tropical Cuba's.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
