<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Learning pet-food business, creating new products are
priorities, CEO says
 &HT;    By Tim Tresslar
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CINCINNATI _ The Procter &AMP; Gamble Co. wants to grow sales by
sharing existing technology throughout the company to create new
products, P&AMP;G's top executive told shareholders Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   As part of this, researchers are brainstorming new products _
everything from dog shampoos to pharmaceutical products to help
aging pets' joints _ to augment the Iams Co.'s pet food line,
executives said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just ideas,'' said Durk Jager, president, chairman and chief
executive of P&AMP;G. ``But all of them are possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Jager made his comments during the company's annual meeting
Tuesday in Cincinnati. The consumer-products giant purchased
Vandalia, Ohio-based Iams in August for $2.3 billion, P&AMP;G's largest
acquisition ever. The acquisition became effective Sept. 1.
</P>
<P>
   While researchers have discussed new products, Iams' immediate
task has been to help P&AMP;G executives learn the pet food business,
Iams spokesman Bryan Brown said. Executives also are concentrating
largely on growing Iams' international market share, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The clear focus is on nutrition and that's where we're placing
the priority,'' Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   According to industry estimates, Iams controls about 27 percent
of the global premium pet food market, second only to
Colgate-Palmolive Co.'s Hill's Pet Nutrition, which controls about
33 percent. Ralston Purina has about 15 percent, while other
manufacturers share the remaining 25 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Despite industry speculation that P&AMP;G will expand Iams'
distribution beyond veterinarian offices and pet stores to
mass-market retailers, Iams' short-term focus remains on
distributing the company's products through traditional channels,
Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   Iams Chairman and Chief Executive Clayton Mathile and new Iams
President Jeff Ansell just completed a 30-day international tour in
which Mathile introduced Ansell to employees and distributors,
Brown said. The pair still have some North American locations to
visit, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Mathile, who walked onto the Aronoff Center for the Arts stage
with Gunnar, a 9-year-old golden retriever, to address
shareholders, promised P&AMP;G executives a smooth transition.
</P>
<P>
   Brown said he was unsure how much longer Mathile will stay with
the company he grew from a small organization to an $800 million
international organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really Clay's call to set that timetable,'' Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   Jager told shareholders the company plans to focus more on
e-commerce, citing reflect.com, the company's new Web site.
</P>
<P>
   P&AMP;G reported $38 billion in sales for 1999, Jager said. The
company's earnings will reflect the benefits of its reorganizations
within three years, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Tresslar writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
