<P>
   &UR; BLACKGOO &LR;  _ Growing grapes may seem a bucolic way to make a
living or spend retirement but then you probably haven't heard
about Black Goo. Unlike the Phylloxera root louse and Pierce's
Disease, this scourge has not made the headlines but it is raising
as much fear in some fields as the black plague once did in cities.
Also called Vine Decline, the disease is tied to several types of
fungi and the spores seem to be everywhere _ in the air, soil and
water. Even more alarming, the spores have shown up in rootstock
from commercial nurseries and some of the 60 acres used for
grapevine research and propagation at the University of California
at Davis, the nation's leading viticulture center. By Peter Sinton
