<SLUG> BC-MGM-BLACK-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MGM'S GAINS SURPRISE WALL STREET
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DAVE McNARY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Long-struggling Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer offered a
sunny outlook after posting its first profitable quarter in three
years, well above Wall Street's expectations.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a tremendous milestone for the new MGM,'' proclaimed
Alex Yemenidjian, installed as chairman and chief executive officer
by owner Kirk Kerkorian in April. ``We have set the stage for
sustained improvement with further revenue enhancements and
diversification planned for the long term.''
</P>
<P>
   MGM executives, in a conference call with analysts and reporters
Tuesday, disclosed plans to double the number of films it will
release over the next few years until it's producing 10 to 15
annually. Yemenidjian said he will soon announce TV deals, which
could create MGM-branded cable and satellite channels, with the
goal of taking advantage of the massive MGM library of 5,000 movie
titles.
</P>
<P>
   MGM also said it plans an extensive release schedule of titles
in the burgeoning DVD format with 70 by year's end and another 130
next year.
</P>
<P>
   The studio's third-quarter earnings rose to $10.3 million, or 7
cents a share, compared with a loss of $40.3 million, or 61 cents a
share, in the 1998 period and far ahead of analysts' consensus
forecast of a loss of 19 cents a share. Revenue rose 15.3 percent
to $299.3 million, and cash flow totalled $40.2 million compared
with negative cash flow of $11.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   MGM said the improved results stemmed from cost-cutting moves
that will save $40 million annually, better-than-expected box
office from its three movies (``Stigmata,'' ``The Thomas Crown
Affair'' and ``Tea With Mussolini'') and revenue gains from its TV
division, including sales of ``The Outer Limits'' and
``Poltergeist: The Legacy'' to the Sci-Fi Channel.
</P>
<P>
   The executives also termed initial ratings for MGM's ``National
Enquirer'' series have been ``encouraging.'' Industry trackers
expect MGM to produce strong results next month from ``The World Is
Not Enough,'' the 19th James Bond film, while ``Flawless,'' a
Robert DeNiro drama-comedy due Nov. 24, may have potential.
</P>
<P>
   For the first nine months of 1999, MGM lost $546.1 million with
most of that from charges for restructuring and cost-cutting. ``We
recognize that it's incumbent for us to prove that quarterly
profits are a habit, not an aberration,'' Yemenidjian said.
</P>
<P>
   MGM's stock edged up 6.25 cents to $22.1875 after touching a
1999 high of $24 earlier in the session. The stock, which had been
held down by short sellers, gained 48 percent last week after MGM
canceled a $750 million external stock offering due to the
depressed price and substituted a $720 million internal offering.
</P>
<P>
   Yemenidjian said the funds from the offering would be used to
finance an ``aggressive but disciplined'' growth strategy.
Kerkorian, who owns 90 percent of MGM, has pledged to buy any
shares not bought by other investors.
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
