<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GROW-GROW </SLUG>
 A BUSINESS _ SF CHRON  
 GROW A BUSINESS/PETER SINTON  &HT;     Welfare-to-Work Grads Also Bring Tax Benefits 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
 &LR;   &LR; Q: I have a small business and am interested in hiring an
entry-level employee from a welfare-to-work program but wonder how
well graduates of such training courses do and how long they stay
at their new jobs.
<P>
   &QL; 
A: There's some new evidence of how well these new workers do that
you might find encouraging. San Francisco Works, the
welfare-to-work training program sponsored by the United Way of the
Bay Area, Committee on Jobs and the SF Chamber of Commerce, has
just released a survey that shows the great majority of businesses
that hired its graduates are happy.
</P>
<P>
   Since March 1998, SFWorks has graduated 219 former welfare
recipients from its job skills training program, placed 156 (or 71
percent) in jobs and reports that 133 still hold their jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday, SFWorks released the results of a survey conducted
for it this past summer by BTW Consultants. It shows:
</P>
<P>
   _83 percent of the 45 businesses that responded said they were
either very satisfied or satisfied with the program. None was
dissatisfied.
</P>
<P>
   _93 percent of the respondents said they would refer other
businesses to SFWorks and many already have.
</P>
<P>
   _70 percent of SFWorks graduates who were hired performed
satisfactorily and 76 percent of business respondents said they are
interested in hiring more graduates.
</P>
<P>
   _35 percent of businesses said recruiting SFWorks graduates cost
less than recruiting other entry-level employees, 27 percent said
it cost about the same and 19 percent said it cost more.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Gustavson, an owner of San Francisco Reservations, said he
is pleased with the program. One SFWorks graduate left after a
short time but another has been with the company for more than a
year and continues to do well at the hotel reservation call center.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the social benefits and satisfaction of helping
individuals make the transition from public assistance to work,
Gustavson notes that there are some nifty tax benefits. He said
businesses that participate in the program can deduct up to half of
salaries from their federal business tax bills.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; For more information on SFWorks, call (415) 217-5181 or visit &LR; 
 &UR; the Web site www.sfworks.org. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Search Engine Search
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Q: I have had a Web site for the past three years and would like to
be accessible through more search engines. How do I go about
offering my information to these search engines and how do I
contact them?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
A: Getting known in the right Internet circles isn't so easy, as
you have no doubt found out.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Kent, the Colorado co-author of ``Poor Richard's Internet
Marketing and Promotions'' (Top Floor Publishing, $29.95), suggests
using a good software program or one of the many Web-based
submission services.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is that there are more than 1,500 search sites (also
called engines) where people can find information about other Web
sites.
</P>
<P>
   With a few of the most popular ones, like Yahoo (www.yahoo.com/
info/suggest), Kent said real people actually check all submissions
so you can't automatically list your own URL (universal resource
locator). But you can automatically list your site on most search
engines using either online resources or software programs.
</P>
<P>
   One of the benefits of running software programs on your
computer is that you can submit to search sites as many times as
you want without incurring additional charges. You also can submit
multiple URLs.
</P>
<P>
   Kent likes Tucows (www.tucows.com) which stands for The Ultimate
Collection Of Winsock Software. He also mentioned the highly rated
AdWeb software which for as little as $60 lets you automatically
submit your site to 1,500 search engines.
</P>
<P>
   Online submission services include Submit It!
(www.submitit.com), and Register-It! (www.register-it.com) and
WorldSubmit (www.worldsubmit.com).
</P>
<P>
   The latter service lets users automatically submit their
profiles to 1,550 search sites one time for $49 or six different
times for $90. Kent and other experts recommend resubmitting your
Web site frequently since search engines often clear out their
files. This can drive up the costs of using online submission
services and if you have a new profile you want to submit, like for
a new product, you also will have to pay additional listing fees.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Send small-business questions to entrepreneurs &LR; sfgate.com, or to
Peter Sinton, Grow a Business column, 901 Mission St., San
Francisco, CA 94103.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
