<HEADER>
A4853 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-CLINTON-TREATY13a-1ST     10-12 0730
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-TREATY13a-1STLEDE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    WITH DEAL ELUSIVE, TEST BAN TREATY FACES FATAL VOTE
 &HT;    Corrects Smith party designation in graf 16.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Shadowed by a military coup in the world's newest
nuclear power, President Clinton and his Democratic allies sought
in vain Tuesday for a deal that would prevent Senate rejection of
an international ban on testing atomic weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Republicans vowed to kill the test ban treaty outright on
Wednesday unless its backers pledge in writing to abandon the
accord until after Clinton leaves office.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is something that the White House does not feel
comfortable
</P>
<P>
   with,'' responded White House spokesman Joe Lockhart. ``I think
it sends the message that, no matter what happens in the world, we
have given up our leadership position in nonproliferation.''
</P>
<P>
   As Lockhart spoke at the White House, military officials in
Islamabad announced that they had overthrown the democratically
elected government of Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif, who was
reportedly placed under house arrest.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's coup in Pakistan, which joined the nuclear club 17
months ago, provided an ominous backdrop to several hours of Senate
debate over the fate of the test ban treaty.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do we want to be voting down the treaty on the day that
there's a coup in Pakistan?'' asked Sen. Joseph Biden, D-Del., the
ranking Democrat on the Senate Foreign Relations Committee. ``This
is high-stakes poker here.''
</P>
<P>
   But with the treaty about 20 votes short of the support needed
for ratification in the Senate, the body's Republican leadership
made it clear that one way or another, the treaty would be laid to
rest on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's when all the sand drains out of this glass,'' said John
Czwartacki, press spokesman for Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott,
R-Miss.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm perfectly comfortable having a vote,'' Lott told
reporters. ``This treaty is fatally flawed.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton became the first national leader to sign the
Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty, which would outlaw test explosions
of nuclear bombs, in 1996. The next year he sent the treaty to the
Senate, asking that it be ratified.
</P>
<P>
   The pact has been signed by 154 nations, but will not take
effect unless the United States and 43 other nuclear-capable
countries ratify it. So far, roughly half of them have done so.
</P>
<P>
   A ratification vote in the Senate had been expected as early as
Tuesday, but it was put off and scheduled for Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Ratification requires a two-thirds majority vote in the
100-member Senate, but fewer than 50 Senators are thought to favor
it.
</P>
<P>
   The treaty is opposed chiefly by Republicans, who contend it
would hamstring U.S. weapons development efforts, undermine the
American nuclear deterrent, and would be susceptible to cheating by
rogue states with nuclear ambitions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not in the best interest of our nation to ratify this
treaty,'' said Sen. Tim Hutchinson, R-Ark.
</P>
<P>
   ``The world would be a more unstable ... not a more stable
place,'' said Sen. Bob Smith, I-N.H., ``if this treaty were to be
ratified.''
</P>
<P>
   With the treaty facing certain defeat, disheartened Democrats
pleaded with Republicans to defer a vote on the accord, in the hope
of keeping it alive for possible ratification next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The opponents of the treaty have won, for now, so why push for
a vote?'' asked Sen. Joseph Lieberman, D-Conn. ``Can't we find a
way to avoid just good old-fashioned gridlock?''
</P>
<P>
   Members of both parties were trying to agree on a way to put off
the vote. As of late Tuesday, though, no deal had been struck,
according to Lott's spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are several drafts going back and forth,'' said
Czwartacki. ``The key is finding the airtight language that
guarantees it (the treaty) not come up in this Congress. ... hat's
what's proving elusive.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats had proposed language that would allow the treaty to
be revived in the current Congress if there were extenuating
circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a hole big enough to drive a truck through,'' objected
Czwartacki.
</P>
<P>
   A number of the treaty's foes opposed any such deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had plenty of time to study the treaty,'' Smith said.
``We're here to vote, that's what we're here for.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
