<HEADER>
A4854 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-COLLEGES-WEB-TOURS-NY     10-12 0634
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLLEGES-WEB-TOURS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONLINE PRESENTATIONS BOOM AS COLLEGES COMPETE FOR THE TOP
STUDENTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By NICK GOLDIN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Colleges and universities are racing to provide applicants with
virtual tours of their campuses, setting up online presentations
that mirror actual campus visits.
</P>
<P>
   More than 800 colleges, compared with about 200 just two years
ago, now maintain Web sites that let prospective students view
slide shows, roll video clips of college life and glimpse
picturesque quadrangles captured live by cameras strategically
placed on campus.
</P>
<P>
   By doing so, they are also acknowledging that a strong presence
on the Internet is vital to winning the hearts of the most
qualified students.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors to Princeton University's site, for example, see video
and audio snippets that simulate the real tour. One of the most
ambitious sites, for Washington State University in Pullman, allows
computer users to navigate an interactive map, view live shots of
the campus, browse a photo library of campus scenes and watch video
presentations on topics like financial aid, career services and
fraternity and sorority life.
</P>
<P>
   Cornell University maintains a virtual slide show and a live
view of the campus center.
</P>
<P>
   Virtual tours are becoming the first step for many students in
narrowing the list of possible destinations, though admissions
officers doubt they will replace the traditional visit, which can
include a tour, an overnight stay in a dormitory, a sample lecture
and discussions with current students.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're trying to do is continue a student's interest in
the institution with the ultimate goal of getting them to visit,''
said Brian Davis, the associate director of undergraduate
admissions at the University of California at Los Angeles. The UCLA
Web site provides a 360-degree panorama of campus scenes.
</P>
<P>
   High school students say that online presentations help them
work through the college selection process, providing information
on everything from school traditions to meal plans. It is
especially useful for those who cannot easily or economically visit
the campus, or to refresh prospective students' memories after they
return home from sometimes numbing multiple visits.
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Raiffe, a Miami senior who was in New York last month
for a round of campus tours, conceded that while nothing beat a
personal visit for getting the feel of a school, ``what they showed
me wasn't that much more than I could have gotten from the Net.''
He plans to turn to the Internet this fall for information on the
remaining colleges on his list.
</P>
<P>
   But Molly Darnieder, the director of campus information and
visitor relations at Cornell, believes that Web sites leave a void.
``The little nuances about each school that you can't pick up from
a Web site can be really important,'' Ms. Darnieder said.
</P>
<P>
   Students are using these online research tools the way they once
used paper guides and school rankings, said Chris Carson, the
president of campustours.com, a site with almost a thousand links
to multimedia presentations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The venerable printed view book that all of us received when
we applied to college is slowly going out of style,'' Carson said.
</P>
<P>
   Some admissions officials caution that virtual tours are not
always representative of what an institution has to offer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Students might lose sight of the fact that these are marketing
tools, and schools will show them what the schools want,'' said Bob
Laird, the director of undergraduate admissions at the University
of California at Berkeley.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors to Berkeley's Web site, Laird joked, will not hear,
``We'd like to show you our poorest faculty lecturers.''
</P>
<P>
   Then again, visitors would not hear that on an actual campus
tour, either.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
