<SLUG> BC-OHIO-NAACP-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Friday's Freedom Fund Banquet to mark NAACP's 90-year legacy
 &HT;    By Angela Townsend
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ More than 1,100 people will gather Friday at the
Dayton Convention Center to celebrate the legacy of the National
Association for the Advancement of Colored People, ``90 Years of
Making Democracy Work.''
</P>
<P>
   That is the theme of the 48th annual Freedom Fund Banquet, held
by the Dayton chapter of the NAACP.
</P>
<P>
   Patricia Russell-McCloud, an attorney who heads her own
Atlanta-based motivational speaker training firm, is the scheduled
keynote speaker. Russell-McCloud is a former senior managing
attorney for the Federal Communication Commission and past national
president of The Links Inc., a black women's volunteer service
organization.
</P>
<P>
   The banquet is much more than people gathering for a meal and to
hear a dynamic speaker, said Dayton chapter president Jessie
Gooding.
   ``We want to let the community know that we're celebrating 90
years of history. And I think that (the Dayton chapter) has made a
great contribution to that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   While the national NAACP has spent much energy this year
strengthening national leadership and bolstering membership in its
2,200 local chapters across the country, the 84-year-old Dayton
chapter continues to focus on discrimination and employment issues
closer to home and the criminal justice system, Gooding said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still in business. We're still continuing to work to
improve conditions of race relations, and economic status for
minorities,'' Gooding said.
</P>
<P>
   The Freedom Fund banquet is the NAACP Dayton chapter's major
fund-raiser. Proceeds help cover operational expenses and
scholarships.
</P>
<P>
   Angela Townsend writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
