<HEADER>
A4856 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-CROSSWORLDS-CROSSWORL     10-12 0693
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CROSSWORLDS-CROSSWORLDS </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 CrossWorlds' Controversial CEO to Quit Post  &HT;     By Tom Stein 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
 &LR;   &LR; Katrina Garnett, the founder of CrossWorlds Software who posed
seductively in a slinky, low-cut cocktail dress for a national
advertising campaign, has learned a hard lesson. Namely, sex
doesn't sell software _ especially software that costs about
$850,000 a pop.
<P>
   Garnett, 37, resigned yesterday as CrossWorlds chief executive
and president. She was replaced by Alfred Amoroso, 49, who last
served as general manager of IBM's Asia Pacific Global Services,
where he managed 25,000 employees.
</P>
<P>
   Garnett will become chairman, a new position, at the Burlingame
company, which employs 210.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts believe she voluntarily removed herself from the
company's day-to-day operations but that the decision might have
been hastened by concerned board members and investors, who have
watched nervously as CrossWorlds burned through about $60 million
since Garnett founded it in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The company also announced yesterday that it has raised an
additional $25 million in financing. Investors include Soros
Private Equity Partners, SAP AG, Venrock Associates _ where
Garnett's husband Terry Garnett is a partner _ as well as the
Garnett family trust.
</P>
<P>
   David Dobrin, an analyst at software advisory firm Benchmarking
Partners, speculates that the new round of financing may have come
with the stipulation that Garnett become less involved in the
company.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I was a venture capitalist investing millions, I wouldn't
want to see Katrina blow it all with a single magazine ad featuring
herself in a little black dress,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   CrossWorlds competes in the so-called enterprise application
integration (EAI) market. It makes the stuff that allows companies
to connect their disparate software systems. For example, a
customer can use the CrossWorlds product to link its financial
management system from SAP with its sales-force automation system
from Siebel.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of 1998, the company had only about 30 customers and
sales of $9.5 million. CrossWorlds competes against the likes of
Tibco Software, New Era of Networks and TSI International, firms
that are beginning to turn a profit and seem to have more traction
in the market.
</P>
<P>
   The EAI market reached $450 million in 1998 and is growing at
roughly 50 percent a year, according to AMR Research.
</P>
<P>
   Dobrin said CrossWorlds has a strong product but that potential
customers have stayed clear because it is overly complex. ``While
other EAI companies are just putting in the pipes, CrossWorlds is
trying to build the entire house and everything that comes with
it,'' he said. ``People don't want all those high-end features.''
The average CrossWorlds sale is about $850,000, on the high end of
the market.
</P>
<P>
   He added that there was a perception in the software industry
that Garnett was spending too much time marketing her company and
speaking with journalists rather than going out and actually
selling the product.
</P>
<P>
   The Australian-born Garnett last appeared on the cover of
Forbes' May 31 issue clad in a high-collared black vinyl jacket and
clutching a red arrow, snapped in two. &UR;  &LR; The magazine profiled the
company's struggle to survive the ``slings and arrows'' that
followed its high-profile, controversial ad campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Other analysts noted that Garnett, who declined to comment for
this article, gave birth to her third child earlier this year and
has been noticeably absent from the office ever since.
</P>
<P>
   A CrossWorlds spokesman acknowledged that ``family was a
contributing factor'' in Garnett's decision.
</P>
<P>
   Her resignation as CEO of CrossWorlds may pave the way for an
initial public offering later this year or early next year. ``I
think the board realized they needed a leader who had a more stable
appearance who would be more impressive to Wall Street,'' said
Kimberly Knickle, an analyst with AMR Research.
</P>
<P>
   Amoroso, who is traveling in Japan, could not be reached for
comment. He is expected to take the helm at CrossWorlds in early
November.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
