<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OHLALA-OHLALA </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Breadmaker Rises Up to Swallow Oh-La-La Coffee Chain  &HT;     By Carol Emert 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
San Francisco's struggling Oh-La-La coffee chain has been purchased
by Bay Bread of South San Francisco.
<P>
   Bay Bread co-owner Pascal Rigo said yesterday that his company
bought the assets of Oh-La-La in a bankruptcy-related sale on
September 27 for slightly less than $500,000.
</P>
<P>
   Oh-La-La, one of San Francisco's first coffee-bar chains, has
had a bumpy past. The company, which currently operates nine cafes
in San Francisco, had been run since December 1996 by Good Food
Fast of Redondo Beach (Los Angeles County), which now is in the
process of liquidating. Oh-La-La's prior owner was Java Centrale of
Sacramento, which purchased Oh-La-La in 1995 in a
bankruptcy-related auction. Java Centrale is now defunct, as well.
</P>
<P>
   Rigo, a native of France, said he intends to differentiate
Oh-La-La from the rest of the coffee-bar pack by returning to its
Gallic roots. It will serve large madeleines instead of muffins,
brioche with gravlax, and small sandwiches with salad. Both coffee
and food will be organic.
</P>
<P>
   Rigo, whose company is primarily a wholesaler of organic breads
and pastries, said he intends to remodel the stores and add
``hearth'' ovens so customers can see the bread baking. Bay Bread
currently operates in-store bakeries with such ovens for
Andronico's, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Rigo plans to sell goods made by Bay Bread in the Oh-La-La
stores. Bay Bread operates a grain mill in Utah, a large bakery in
South San Francisco and a commissary and retail outlet,
Boulangerie, on Pine Street in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Rigo said the success of Boulangerie has whetted the company's
appetite to undertake more retail.
</P>
<P>
   Bay Bread's sales this year, excluding Oh-La-La, are expected to
hit $12 million, Rigo said. Oh-La-La's sales came in at $3 million
last year. Rigo said he hopes to boost them to $4.5 million in
2000.
</P>
<P>
   The chain was founded in 1982 by Philippe Laik, a Frenchman who
intended to take his concept nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   European-style coffee bars were just beginning to catch on at
the time, and the market was wide open. Starbucks was a small
Seattle company still owned by Jerry Baldwin, now the chairman of
Peet's Coffee and Tea of Emeryville, and Pasqua _ a San Francisco
coffee-bar chain recently purchased by Starbucks _ wasn't founded
until the following year.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, when the company was at its peak with about 25
locations and $5.5 million in annual sales, its then-chief
executive Howard Berkowitz told The Chronicle that he intended to
expand to 53 company-operated stores, 1,100 franchise stores and
$100 million in sales by 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Oh-La-La opened a couple of stores in New York and Los Angeles
but never became a major player.
</P>
<P>
   It filed for bankruptcy-court protection for the first time in
November 1994, at which time it had assets of $2.1 million and
liabilities of $6.1 million. Java Centrale bought it the following
year.
</P>
<P>
   The French concept could succeed if it is implemented well and
store locations are good ones, said Andrew Barish, a retail analyst
with Banc Boston Robertson Stephens.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will probably require a higher-end demographic and a little
higher education levels to be able to appreciate some of the French
items,'' Barish said.
</P>
<P>
   Bay Bread currently is in merger discussions with a large French
bakery, Rigo said. An announcement is expected in a few weeks. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
