u a BC-CANCER-NEWTEST-COX     10-12 0832
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANCER-NEWTEST-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Technology test in breast cancer fight announced
 &HT;    By Sanjay Bhatt
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ An experimental treatment for breast
cancer that uses microwaves to zap tumors could make today's gold
standard of cancer treatment _ surgery, radiation and drugs _ look
as primitive as poking holes in the skull to relieve headaches.
</P>
<P>
   Columbia Hospital's Center for Breast Care in West Palm Beach
announced Tuesday it is recruiting up to 10 women to take part in
the nation's first test of a new technology that pinpoints
microwaves to kill breast cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Applying technology used in the Gulf War to jam enemy radar and
home in on missiles, doctors will heat breast tissue with
microwaves, the same energy used to cook TV dinners.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been known that heat kills tumors,'' said Kurt O'Neill, a
spokesman for Celsion Corp., the Columbia, Md., company licensed to
market the technology. ``The problem in the past has been getting
heat to the tumor only _ and not healthy cells.''
</P>
<P>
   The Phase 1 trial also will be conducted at Harbor UCLA Medical
Center in Torrance, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers are looking for women who are already planning a
mastectomy. At the end of the trial, doctors must remove the breast
to determine whether the tumor is dead and the surrounding breast
tissue is unaffected.
</P>
<P>
   If the trial succeeds, however, microwave treatment would
eliminate the need for painful and disfiguring breast surgery, said
Dr. Robert Gardner, medical director at Columbia's breast center.
He said he is looking for ``10 angels'' to volunteer for the tests.
</P>
<P>
   Women facing a mastectomy and diagnosed with a single invasive
breast tumor 3 centimeters or less in diameter are eligible.
</P>
<P>
   Subjects would be paid $75 at each visit to cover travel and
other expenses, and would not be charged for any medical costs.
</P>
<P>
   While welcoming any treatment that avoids surgery, the American
Cancer Society refused to label Celsion's treatment a breakthrough.
``There are many things that look very promising in animals that
fail to be successful in humans,'' said Debbie Saslow, the
society's director of breast and cervical cancer.
</P>
<P>
   And even if successful, it could be many years before the
treatment is available to all, Saslow said. Assuming its trials and
federal permits proceed smoothly, Celsion said it hopes to market
the system in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, scientists could not kill cancerous cells without
harming healthy ones, limiting the use of microwaves to skin
tumors.
</P>
<P>
   The treatment, invented by the Massachusetts Institute of
Technology, focuses microwaves in a way never tried before. It
takes advantage of a basic law of physics: When two waves get
perfectly in sync, their energies combine, becoming stronger.
</P>
<P>
   The treatment also is being used in a trial at Montefiore
Hospital in New York to unblock prostate glands in men.
</P>
<P>
   In animal trials last year at Massachusetts General Hospital in
Boston and at Oxford University in England, Celsion's treatment
system killed breast tumors in more than 90 percent of cases,
Gardner said.
</P>
<P>
   Some animals had side effects of skin redness and a few
developed blisters, but no damage to surrounding tissue and nothing
approaching the harsh side effects, such as extreme fatigue and
nausea, of chemotherapy.
</P>
<P>
   Plans to hold the clinical trial at Mass General fell through.
Gardner learned about it from colleagues there and asked Celsion to
send him information. O'Neill said a member of Celsion's medical
advisory board thought highly of Gardner, leading it to consider
his proposal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want people who are very enthused ... and very respected,''
O'Neill said.
</P>
<P>
   Gardner was enthusiastic at a news conference Tuesday. ``This
has never been done before,'' he said. ``This has the potential to
replace surgery and be a phenomenal breakthrough.''
</P>
<P>
   Avoiding surgery could save lives: Gardner estimated as many as
one-fourth of women who undergo a mastectomy die in spite of, or
possibly as a result of, the aggressive treatment.
</P>
<P>
   More than 176,000 Americans, nearly all of them women, will be
diagnosed with breast cancer this year and 43,700 will die, the
Cancer Society estimates.
</P>
<P>
   Avoiding two months of radiation therapy would mean fewer
patients left with swollen or hard breasts, Gardner said.
</P>
<P>
   And it could save money too: Surgery, radiation treatments and
hospital stays cost about $20,000, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Mindy Parsons, a Boynton Beach woman who survived the removal of
both her breasts in 1996, said it would be fantastic if she could
have avoided surgery.
</P>
<P>
   ``The physical pain can be dealt with, but it causes emotional
scars that last indefinitely,'' Parsons said. ``Losing a breast is
very much (losing) a part of being a woman.''
</P>
<P>
   Sanjay Bhatt writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla. E-mail: sanjaybhatt(AT)pbpost.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
