<HEADER>
A4860 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-FBC-UCLANOTES-LADN     10-12 0499
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLANOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAGNIFICENT SEVEN GET IT DONE FOR BRUINS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ They haven't mended a tattered national
reputation. They don't deserve a nickname, and they aren't being
compared to counterparts at Florida State or Penn State. But UCLA's
defensive line and linebackers _ the ``front seven'' in football
lingo _ are quietly becoming an immovable force.
</P>
<P>
   Three weeks ago, the Bruins pressured Stanford's quarterbacks
and held tailback Kerry Carter to 31 yards. Then they dominated
Arizona's State's offensive line and contained Oregon tailback
Reuben Droughns. (The Ducks had just one touchdown drive longer
than 44 yards.) In each game, UCLA's breakdowns originated in the
secondary, with poor coverage and missed tackles. The front seven
has done its job.
</P>
<P>
   Junior end Kenyon Coleman is rapidly becoming one of the best in
the Pacific-10 _ so good the Bruins are worried he'll bolt for the
NFL. Tackles Ken Kocher and Pete Holland are making plays they
didn't make a year ago. Reserves Santi Hall, Anthony Fletcher and
Sean Phillips contribute consistently. Linebacker Robert Thomas is
a rising star.
</P>
<P>
   Maturity and experience are partly responsible for the
improvement: Fletcher, Kocher and Thomas were true freshmen last
year. But coach Bob Toledo credits first-year assistants John
Pearce (ends) and Jethro Franklin (tackles) for much of the
progress.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, it wasn't unusual to see the linemen resting on one
knee, listening to former coach Terry Tumey explain nuances and
schemes. This year, there's less talk and more action. Franklin and
Pearce have implemented a grueling practice regimen designed to
toughen the players mentally and physically.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see them after practice, and they look like they've been in
a war,'' Toledo said. ``They're dirty and sweaty. They're working.
They aren't taking any Sno-Cone breaks.''
</P>
<P>
   The practices are sometimes tougher than the games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see myself last year and this year, and I'm a totally
different player,'' Kocher said. ``A lot of it is (Franklin's)
coaching. He's making us work hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Need some lift?: Bruins kicker Chris Griffith leads the Pac-10
with 1.67 field goals per game and is third in accuracy (10 of 13).
But he had two field goals blocked by Oregon.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to do a better job protecting,'' Toledo said, ``and
he's got to get the ball up a little quicker.''
</P>
<P>
   Big Bear leg: One of Cal's best players is junior Nick Harris,
who averages 46.9 yards per punt (fourth in the nation) and has
dropped six punts inside the opponent's 20 this season.
</P>
<P>
   For a team that struggles moving the ball _ Cal is last in the
league in offense _ Harris' leg provides a boost in field position.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a big part of our defensive game plan,'' Bears coach Tom
Holmoe said. ``There are many times we'll punt at the 35 and he'll
put it inside the 10. He's fantastic.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
