<SLUG> BC-WEISEL-WEISEL </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Growth Spurt Propels Weisel Partners Into Top S.F.
Investment  Bank 
 &HT;     By Sam Zuckerman  
 c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Thomas Weisel Partners, a startup that didn't exist a year ago, is
poised to become San Francisco's largest independent investment
bank.
<P>
   Since opening for business in January, the firm has completed 51
public or private stock offerings and six merger deals, worth a
total of more than $13.5 billion. Weisel Partners recorded $80
million in revenue for the six months ended in September and
expects to post revenue of $150 million for the full year.
</P>
<P>
   That performance will put Weisel Partners in first place among
local independent investment banks when Hambrecht &AMP; Quist Group,
currently the largest, completes its recently announced sale to New
York's Chase Manhattan Corp. in several months.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last three years, the city's big three independent
firms - H&AMP;Q, Robertson Stephens and Montgomery Securities, now
known as Banc of America Securities - all sold out to traditional
banks.
</P>
<P>
   So far this year, Weisel Partners is in 21st place among
investment banks nationwide in public stock offerings, behind
Robertson Stephens, Banc of America and H&AMP;Q, but ahead of Volpe
Brown Whelan, San Francisco's second-ranking independent investment
bank.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Weisel, 58, the onetime one-time  &LR; bicycle-racing champion
who founded Weisel Partners, was Montgomery's chief executive when
the  &LR; North Carolina's NationsBank, now Bank of America, bought the
firm in 1997. He quit a year ago after following  &LR; a dispute with
bank executives over control of Montgomery, bringing dozens of
employees of his old firm to his new venture.
</P>
<P>
   During the last nine months, Weisel Partners has built its
headquarters at the foot of Montgomery Street, grown to 66 partners
and 384 total employees, and opened offices in New York, Boston and
London.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to raising capital and providing merger advice, the
firm is a stock broker for institutional clients and manager of a
private investment fund that is approaching $1 billion in assets.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts described Weisel Partners' blazing start as phenomenal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's difficult to believe they're only 9 nine  &LR; months old.
They have a record older and larger firms would envy,'' said
Michael Flanagan, an independent securities industry analyst based
in the Philadelphia area.
</P>
<P>
   Flanagan said he was especially impressed by Weisel Partners'
ability to win the coveted lead-manager assignment in six stock
offerings during the third quarter, including the $50 million IPO
of VitaminShoppe.com, an online supplier of nutritional
supplements, earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   The lead managers in stock offerings oversee the sales process
and collect higher fees than firms that serve as co-managers.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Flanagan warned, Weisel Partners will have to work hard
to maintain its entrepreneurial edge as it settles into the middle
ranks of U.S. investment banks.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be a mid-sized investment bank is not the ideal niche for
an independent company,'' he said. ``Loss of nimbleness is a
concern.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Weisel said his firm's fast start has been due
to its focus on fast-growing areas of the economy, such as
Internet-based commerce and electronic information services aimed
at businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Capital-raising activity ``has been concentrated in areas where
we've built up our competence, where people are going to make money
over the next 10 years,`` Weisel said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Weisel said, the sale of so many firms, including
Montgomery, put lots of top-caliber on the job market. On Monday,
for example, the firm announced it had hired Bill Shutzer, former
president of the boutique investment bank Furman Selz, as senior
partner in its New York office.
</P>
<P>
   Weisel Partners officials said the firm will keep its sharp
focus and rein in growth once it reaches about 500 employees.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
