<SLUG> BC-INTEL-INTEL </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Intel Earnings Fall Short of Expectations  &HT;     By Henry Norr 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
For the second consecutive quarter, Intel's financial results have
fallen slightly below Wall Street's inflated expectations.
<P>
   The chip-making giant reported net income of $1.9 billion (55
cents per share) for its fiscal third quarter, excluding the costs
of several recent acquisitions. Those figures represented increases
of 21 and 22 percent, respectively, from the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
   Revenue for the quarter ended September 25 was $7.3 billion, up
9 percent from last year's third-quarter total of $6.7 billion.
</P>
<P>
   By most standards, that sounds like healthy growth, but Wall
Street had expected better. Analysts surveyed by First Call
/Thomson Financial had predicted net income of 57 cents a share,
and the ``whisper numbers'' _ unofficial predictions offered to
major clients and often leaked on the Internet _ were 59, 60 or
even 61 cents.
</P>
<P>
   In recent days, Intel's stock had climbed in anticipation of a
strong report, closing yesterday, before the announcement, at
$76.69. Once the official numbers were released, the stock plunged
$5.69 in after-hours trading.
</P>
<P>
   But analyst Mark Edelstone of Morgan Stanley Dean Witter said he
didn't expect the sell-off to continue for long. ``I think we've
already seen most of the reaction, and quite frankly, it's an
overreaction,'' he said. ``People tend to shoot first and ask
questions later, but as they get their questions answered, they'll
think better about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Intel's revenues actually were up slightly more than expected,
Chief Financial Officer Andy Bryant said in a post-announcement
conference call; the problem was that its gross profit margin,
which had been expected to rise, dipped slightly, from 59.4 to 58.7
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant and Paul Otellini, executive vice president and general
manager of the Intel architecture business group, offered several
explanations for that decline. First, the company's Celeron chip
continued to gain ground at the low end of the PC market, where
margins tend to be smaller than in the high-performance segment.
</P>
<P>
   Conversely, sales of high-end, high-margin chips were somewhat
below expectations, the execs acknowledged, mainly because the
transition to a new production process, in which chip features
measure only .18 micron compared with .25 micron in the previous
process, has taken slightly longer than expected. That transition
also has involved some extra costs, they said.
</P>
<P>
   Intel, however, now is shipping the new chips to PC-makers, who
are expected to announce desktop models, servers and notebooks
including them on October 25.
</P>
<P>
   The actual costs of producing chips in the new process are lower
than expected, Intel said. For the third quarter, that forced the
company to reduce the value of its existing inventory, which
further cut into earnings.
</P>
<P>
   But for the fourth quarter and beyond, the lower-than-expected
costs of the new production process should bolster Intel's
fortunes. Bryant and Otellini forecast ``strong seasonal demand''
for all products in the traditionally strong fourth quarter, and
they predicted that gross margins would climb by ``a couple of
points.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The bad news is just a one-time hit,'' Morgan Stanley's
Edelstone said. ``The good news is that going forward, the whole
cost structure will be lower. And what investors care about is the
outlook, not what's in the rearview mirror.''
</P>
<P>
   Separately, Intel announced plans to collaborate with Nokia, the
Finnish company that has recently risen to No.1 in the cellular
phone manufacturing market, to build television set-top boxes that
combine features of the Internet with broadcast TV. The new set-top
box will run on an Intel chip, probably a Celeron. The first fruits
of the new alliance are slated to reach the market in the second
half of next year, Intel said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
