<SLUG> BC-BLACKGOOBOX-BLACKGOOBOX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRAPEVINE ENEMIES 
 &HT;     BY PETER SINTON
</HEADLINE>
 _ SF CHRON   &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; There seem to be almost as many grapevine diseases and pests as
grape varieties. Here is a sampling of some of the nastiest,
according to University of California at Davis plant pathologist
Doug Gubler:
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; Powdery mildew  &LR; _ The fungus colonizes leaves, fruit and green
stems thus depriving the plant of moisture and nutrients. Without
use of fungicides, the disease would devastate much of the
California crop.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; Phylloxera root louse  &LR; _ This microscopic insect has infected about
a quarter of grape vines planted in clay coastal soils and has
required replacement with resistant rootstocks. Vines planted in
the sandy Central Valley don't seem susceptible to the louse, which
slowly consumes the roots and causes death.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; Eutypa Dieback  &LR; _ This fungal disease, formerly called Dead Arm,
attacks pruning wounds. It invades the vascular tissue, creating
cankers that clog water-conducting vessels and could affect half of
California's grape acreage. New materials are being tested to treat
pruning wounds.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; Pierce's Disease  &LR; _ Just as mosquitoes deliver malaria to humans, a
little insect known as the sharpshooter infects grape vines with
the bacterium Xylella fastidiosa when they probe the leaves. The
plants try to wall off the bacteria and end up choking off their
own water and nutrient supply. As a sign of the severity of the
disease, especially in Riverside County's Temecula Valley, the
University of California appointed an emergency task force last
week to tackle the disease. It also afflicts other plants from
almond trees to Oleander bushes planted along freeway median
strips. There is no effective control.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; Botrytis or bunch rot  &LR; _ This fungal disease causes rot when it is
especially wet during bloom or at harvest. It affects about
three-quarters of California vineyards, but leaf removal and
fungicides can be used to treat it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; Viruses  &LR; _ Fanleaf and Leafroll viruses have been a leading cause
of premature vine death, but UC Davis ensures that new vines sold
by commercial nurseries are free of these diseases.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; Vine Decline (Black Goo)  &LR; _ Several species of Phaeoacromonium and
Cylindrocarpon fungi cause this disease or contribute to it. The
fungi cause clogging of the water- and nutrient-bearing tissue,
stunting growth or even killing the plant. No effective treatment.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-12-99 2253EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991012.0430 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-12 22:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4864 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-BLACKGOO-BLACKGOO_SFC     10-12 1655
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLACKGOO-BLACKGOO </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Spread of Unstoppable Fungi Creates Rift in Wine Country  &HT;     By Peter Sinton 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
A fearsome fungus nicknamed ``Black Goo'' is spreading through the
wine country, destroying vineyards and relationships.
<P>
   Also called Vine Decline, the disease is linked to several types
of fungi and the spores seem to be everywhere _ in the air, soil
and water. Even more alarming, the spores have shown up in
rootstock from commercial nurseries and some of the 60 acres used
for grapevine research and propagation at the University of
California at Davis, the nation's leading viticulture center.
</P>
<P>
   The disease, whose cause is not clearly understood, is creating
a rift in the normally genteel North Coast wine region. Growers who
have it blame the nurseries for selling them infected rootstock.
Some nurseries blame the growers, saying the disease only afflicts
plants that haven't been tended properly.
</P>
<P>
   There's not even a consensus on the severity of the problem.
Some growers and consultants say the nurseries and even UC Davis
are trying to hush it up to avoid lawsuits, panic and falling land
prices. They charge that UC Davis was slow to divulge a decade ago
that its favored AXR-1 rootstock was susceptible to Phylloxera, and
that history is repeating itself.
</P>
<P>
   Vines infected by the Black Goo fungi Phaeoacremonium and
Cylindrocarpon can appear normal for months or years. When the
fungi start growing, however, they can kill the vines or just make
them sickly underachievers.
</P>
<P>
   The symptoms are many and varied: stunted growth, dark gummy
ooze (black goo) instead of clear sap inside the wood, grooved and
asymmetrical trunks, graft unions that fail to callus over, leaves
that prematurely turn yellow.
</P>
<P>
   Many big nurseries, growers and scientists say the fungi in
question have been around for decades. But for years, the disease
was undiagnosed. Now, it seems to be spreading more rapidly as
growers rip out vines infected with the widespread Phylloxera root
louse and replant them with new vines that may be infected with the
fungus.
</P>
<P>
   Lynn Dondero, a Sonoma dermatologist who planted 16 acres
outside Santa Rosa with vines purchased from Sonoma Grapevines in
May 1997, is one of the victims of Black Goo. He has watched his
Pinot Noir and other varieties sicken and exhibit the classic signs
of Black Goo disease _ slow growth, stunted vines and dark
splotches on cross-sectioned wood.
</P>
<P>
   Dondero tore out some vines and sent them to laboratories for
analysis, and some of the cultures turned up positive for
Phaeoacremonium and Cylindrocarpon. In late August, Dondero sued
Sonoma Grapevines, charging that the well-known nursery
misrepresented its products and sold him vines that it knew were
diseased.
</P>
<P>
   This month, Sonoma Grapevines countersued Dondero for slander.
``He is claiming we knowingly sent out diseased material,'' said
President Rich Kunde. ``I consider that a personal attack. If we
were lying to all our customers, we wouldn't be in business for 28
years.''
</P>
<P>
   Some major growers, nurseries and scientists argue that the
Black Goo scare is being fomented by growers who are trying to get
others to pay for their mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   They contend that Vine Decline, as they prefer to call it, only
becomes a serious problem if vines are already weak or stressed
because they have been handled, planted, fed or watered improperly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's like disease in humans,'' said Kunde. ``We're
exposed to lots of things every day, but when you get run down or
stressed, you can get the flu and the person next to you doesn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Sonoma Grapevines chief viticulturist Chris Lindelof said
customers return less than 1 percent of rootstock because of
disease. Kunde insisted that he has sent thousands of cuttings to
UC Davis and not one has tested positive for Black Goo fungi.
</P>
<P>
   Doug Gubler, head of the plant pathology department at UC Davis,
estimates that Vine Decline has hit less than 10,000 of
California's 900,000 or so vineyard acres. That's barely 1 percent
of the state total, and well down the list of grapevine diseases.
Right now, that's not enough to affect grape supplies or wine
prices.
</P>
<P>
   But Gubler acknowledged, ``It is a big problem for those who
have it.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, he ranks Vine Decline as the No.1 policy issue for
California's booming wine-grape industry. ``People are blaming the
university and nurseries for (unwittingly) spreading the disease,
and it's a political nightmare,'' Gubler said.
</P>
<P>
   Vineyard consultant Michael Porter of Forestville, said he has
tested vines from a number of nurseries and found the fungus.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a major problem,'' he said. ``Some little growers have
lost their shirts, and then they are told by the nurseries, `You
screwed up.'''
</P>
<P>
   Porter figures that one reason nurseries are insisting there's
no big problem or it's the customer's fault is that ``saying you
have a problem is like asking an attorney to sue you.''
</P>
<P>
   Even growers who have diagnosed the disease and sent cuttings to
labs to be tested are often mum about the problem. After all, if
the value of an acre of prime vineyard land infected with
Phylloxera drops to $40,000 from $70,000, what might happen to
vineyards that are home to an unpredictable fungus that may sleep
in vines and the soil?
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, some growers are speaking out.
</P>
<P>
   Retired obstetrician Bob Ziegler tends 19 acres of wine grapes
near Healdsburg, and in 1994, he began replanting vines ridden with
Phylloxera with new ones. Several years later, he discovered that
many of the new vines are infested with the Black Goo fungi. UC
Davis lab tests have come back positive, and Ziegler has replanted
4 acres and is watching much of the rest limp along. He also said
he is considering filing suit against Sonoma Grapevines, which
supplied the vines, and figures his losses, including lost
production, top $400,000.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Lerner, who planted 13 acres of new vineyards in the
Russian River Valley with 13,000 vines from a Bakersfield (Kern
County) nursery in June, has watched hundreds die and many of the
rest grow at a puny pace. The canes of many of his new Chardonnay
and Pinot Noir vines are stunted, and he just got news that three
of the four vines he sent to UC Davis for testing came back
positive for Phaeoacremonium.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what to do,'' said Lerner, 52, a former builder
who invested in the land with a few friends. ``The nursery agreed
to replace the dead vines, but the new vines might carry the same
pathogens, so what's the point?''
</P>
<P>
   Stuart Bewley, owner of the 40-acre Alder Springs Vineyard in
Mendocino County, began planting vines six years ago and was
surprised that so many died after a year or two. The former
president of California Coolers figures that about 25 percent of
his vineyards are infected. ``I believe I got Black Goo from all
four nurseries I bought from,'' he said. ``This is a big problem.''
</P>
<P>
   St. Francis Winery partner Joe Martin said, ``Most people are in
denial. They don't want to admit they have a problem.'' He said
some of his own 30 acres is infected with Black Goo, and he worries
that a lot more acreage will go into decline when it should be
thriving.
</P>
<P>
   As a sign of the growing worries about Black Goo worldwide, an
international conference was held 12 days ago in Siena, Italy, to
discuss the problem. About 120 scientists from 20 wine-growing
countries around the world attended the two-day workshop on
organisms that cause Black Goo and related diseases.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is now being recognized as a problem that previously was
attributed to other causes,'' said Lucie Morton, a Virginia vine
consultant who has been sounding the Black Goo alarm for several
years and just returned from the Italian conference.
</P>
<P>
   Nurseries often will replace vines that die after planting. But
that hardly covers the grower's full costs. Phylloxera-resistant
rootstock grafted to a varietal grape vine like Cabernet Sauvignon
or Chardonnay might cost about $3.25 each. For an acre planted with
1,000 vines, the total would be $3,250.
</P>
<P>
   On top of that, it can cost tens of thousands of dollars per
acre to prepare the soil, put in drip irrigation and trellises and
care for the vines until they bear fruit in commercial quantities
after two or three years.
</P>
<P>
   Although Gubler of UC Davis notes that Phaeoacremonium and
Cylindrocarpon fungi have been around for more than 60 years and
are not a new problem, fighting the diseases has become a high
priority. UC has assigned two post-doctorate researchers to the
Vine Decline puzzle.
</P>
<P>
   The American Vineyard Foundation, which represents grape
growers, also is taking action. It recently allocated $50,000 to
research the fungi associated with Black Goo, and a new survey of
members shows that vine decline has jumped to the top third of
grower concerns from the bottom third in the previous survey
several years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Some big growers downplay the problem, perhaps because they are
more selective in accepting rootstock or they get preferential
treatment from nurseries. Kendall-Jackson, the big Santa Rosa grape
grower and winemaker, produces its own root stock and grafts.
Daniel Roberts, K-J's director of wine-growing research, said he
has seen Black Goo only in vines purchased from other nurseries
that were thin and weak to begin with.
</P>
<P>
   Andy Beckstoffer, who owns about 1,600 acres of North Coast
vineyards, said vine decline is popping up as a problem and
recommended carefully studying vines at nurseries before and after
they are grafted and prior to delivery. He also tests soil quality
by sending seven-foot core samples of earth from new vineyards for
lab analysis before planting.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a bib overall and high-buckle boot business,''
said Beckstoffer. ``It's highly technical, and we have Ph.D.s
running it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
