<HEADLINE>
CSUN'S AMERSON FALLS TO SECOND STRING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS BRANAM  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ A shoulder injury cost Aaron Arnold at least two
games. Lackluster effort cost Drew Amerson his starting job.
</P>
<P>
   The Cal State Northridge coaches, after seeing Amerson drop too
many passes in Saturday's 48-27 loss at Montana, dropped him to
second string Tuesday and promoted Ryan Beckwith.
</P>
<P>
   Amerson is second on the team in receptions, with 31, and
receiving yards, 420.
</P>
<P>
   ``Drew didn't show up to play,'' CSUN interim head coach Jeff
Kearin said. ``He needs to understand that. Ryan Beckwith has
practiced hard all year. I've got no problems starting Ryan.''
</P>
<P>
   Beckwith has just five catches for 61 yards and one touchdown
this season.
</P>
<P>
   Kearin also is confident with freshman Joe Gilliam taking
Arnold's place in the lineup. Arnold, who is out of this week's
game against Sacramento State with an injured right shoulder, leads
the Matadors with 38 catches.
</P>
<P>
   As with Beckwith, Gilliam doesn't have a lot of game experience.
He has seven catches for 71 yards and scored his first collegiate
touchdown against Montana.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Gilliam) has done everything right at practice,'' Kearin
said. ``He reminds you of an Aaron Arnold as a freshman.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, replacing Arnold is going to be tough for CSUN, which is
2-3 and 1-2 in the Big Sky. Arnold is CSUN's leader in all-purpose
yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to replace 150 yards of offense,'' Kearin said.
``There's a whole package of stuff that we haven't used.''
</P>
<P>
   Back in there: Senior cornerback Mel Miller, who didn't start
the past two games, is back in the lineup, replacing Karalus Doyle.
Doyle has a team-high three interceptions but Miller in considered
the Matadors' best man-to-man defensive back.
</P>
<P>
   Shrinking: Jaumal Bradley is still losing weight and wasn't able
to participate in all his drills in Tuesday's practice.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley, a senior tailback who leads the Matadors with 314
yards, is down to 193 pounds; is normal playing weight is 215.
Bradley was knocked out of two games with tonsillitis and a viral
infection.
</P>
</TEXT>
