<HEADLINE>
UNIVERSAL STUDIOS TO OFFER AOL HOOKUP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DAVE McNARY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Universal Studios, targeting vacationers who
can't do without e-mail, has announced an extensive cross-marketing
deal with America Online to install AOL kiosks at its theme park in
Florida.
</P>
<P>
   The deal will give Universal a high-profile presence on AOL, the
world's leading online service with 18 million members. Should the
computer terminals prove popular, more AOL kiosks could be
installed at Universal Studios Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   ``AOL is becoming an integral part of people's lives, so we're
betting that they're not going to be able to resist using the
kiosks when they're on vacation,'' said AOL spokeswoman Kathie
Lentz on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Universal recently launched a test program of five kiosks with
terminals at its four-month-old Islands of Adventure theme park in
Orlando, Fla. The terminals are designed to give existing AOL
customers a simple way to receive and send electronic mail, along
with giving potential customers a chance to browse through AOL's
services.
</P>
<P>
   The terminals will also have direct links to
universalstudios.com and uescape.com, which offer information about
its theme parks and travel packages. The deal also calls for AOL to
include a direct keyword link to Universal's sites and provide
cross-promotion of Universal at all of AOL's services, including
CompuServe, Digital City and Netscape Netcenter.
</P>
