A4963 &Cx1f; kan-z
r w BC-CONTRIBUTIONBAN-KAN &LR;      10-12 0899
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
BROWNBACK TAKES HARD STANCE AGAINST SOFT MONEY 
</HEADLINE>
 BC- CONTRIBUTION BAN-KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN MURPHY  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Breaking ranks with most of his Senate Republican
colleagues, Sam Brownback of Kansas said Tuesday he supported a
bill to ban unlimited, so-called ``soft money'' contributions to
political parties.
</P>
<P>
   Brownback said the bill championed by Republican Sen. John
McCain of Arizona and Democrat Russ Feingold of Wisconsin was
necessary to keep big money from influencing elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've spoken frequently in the state during campaign
appearances about the need to do something about soft money,''
Brownback told reporters. ``That's what this bill is about. This is
the best chance we have to more forward.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain and Feingold have long criticized laws that allow
corporations or individuals to give unlimited amounts of money to
political parties, which in turn can use it to support candidates
who otherwise cannot take more than $1,000 from any one source.
</P>
<P>
   Contributions to political parties are called soft money, while
donations directly to candidates are termed ``hard money.''
</P>
<P>
   Soft money ``holds the potential for the appearance of or the
actual abuse on both sides of the political aisle,'' Brownback
said.
</P>
<P>
   Last year and again a month ago the House passed a ban on soft
money. It died in a Senate filibuster a year ago and needs 60 votes
to overcome a potential filibuster this year.
</P>
<P>
   With Brownback's endorsement, eight Senate Republicans, all more
moderate than the Kansan, now support some form of the
McCain-Feingold bill. Assuming all 45 Senate Democrats backed the
bill, it would still fall short of breaking a filibuster.
</P>
<P>
   Brownback said he was unsure whether more Republicans would
follow his lead. ``I'm hearing a number of others who are looking
at it,'' he said. ``I don't have any vote totals on it.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain welcomed Brownback's backing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very important,'' McCain said. ``Sam is a leader here in
the Senate, and he represents the heartland of America. It's a very
significant move on his part and, I might add, a courageous one.''
</P>
<P>
   Brownback also spoke well of McCain, saying he has ``sterling
character.'' But Brownback said he was not yet endorsing McCain or
any other Republican candidate for president.
</P>
<P>
   Last year Brownback opposed the McCain-Feingold bill, largely
because it would have placed limits on when independent groups and
organizations could run issue ads that would indirectly benefit or
hurt a candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Brownback said regulating those ads would restrict free speech.
McCain and Feingold removed that provision from the bill. If it is
resurrected, Brownback will oppose it, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Groups that seek to advertise a point of view should not and I
believe cannot constitutionally be limited from their participation
in the political system,'' Brownback said.
</P>
<P>
   Brownback came under some political fire in his 1996 Senate race
for getting political help from Triad Management Services. The GOP
consulting firm spent $1 million on Kansas issue ads, including
$410,000 in advertising that criticized Brownback's opponent,
Democrat Jill Docking.
</P>
<P>
   In addition Triad had been linked to donations totaling $37,500
from Brownback's in-laws _ Topeka media millionaires John and Ruth
Stauffer _ to eight political action committees that then donated a
total of $36,000 to Brownback's campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The senator said Tuesday that his support for the soft-money ban
was in ``no way'' an effort to make amends. In fact, the Triad fund
raising and spending would not be prohibited under the revised
bill.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Kansas Democrats generally applauded Brownback.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's terrific,'' Docking said. ``I know he's not
always been consistent on the issue of campaign finance. When he
originally started in Congress he wanted to be defined as a
reformer.''
</P>
<P>
   State Sen. Paul Feleciano, a Wichita Democrat who lost to
Brownback last year, also cheered the move.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's taken some giant steps forward in the right direction,''
he said. ``The people of this country want true reform.''
</P>
<P>
   The vice chairwoman of the Kansas Democratic Party remained
skeptical.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's done this switcheroo before,'' Micheline Burger said.
``If he's sincere, I'd say that's great. I'm glad he's on board.
It's about time.''
</P>
<P>
   A Republican, state Sen. Karin Brownlee of Olathe, said she
still had questions about the constitutionality of the
McCain-Feingold law.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a little bit surprised and hope he's heard from the people
of Kansas that this is what they support,'' Brownlee said.
</P>
<P>
   Brownback contended that he had supported limits on soft money
since 1996 as long as issue ads were not affected. He said he would
be more comfortable with limits because a ban may be struck down as
unconstitutional. But he will support the outright ban.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still think this is the best chance we have of dealing with
the soft money issue,'' Brownback said.
</P>
<P>
   Other Republicans besides Brownback who have come out for some
form of the McCain-Feingold bill are Susan Collins and Olympia
Snowe of Maine, John Chafee of Rhode Island, Jim Jeffords of
Vermont, Fred Thompson of Tennessee and Arlen Specter of
Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   Last month a bill broader than the McCain-Feingold legislation
passed the Republican-controlled House on a 252-177 margin.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-12-99 2309EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991012.0435 </DOCNO>
