<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCIENCE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KANSAS EDUCATION OFFICIAL TO REVISE SCIENCE STANDARDS 
</HEADLINE>
 STANDARDS-KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KATE BEEM  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Kansas' new science standards are in Andy Tompkins' lap now.
</P>
<P>
   The state Board of Education on Tuesday directed Tompkins, the
education commissioner, to revise parts of the new standards that
were taken directly from national science organizations' documents.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just get it done,'' said board member Scott Hill of Abilene,
one of the board's three members who removed the emphasis on
evolution from an earlier version of the standards written by a
committee of science teachers and professors.
</P>
<P>
   The standards are guidelines for what Kansas students should
know and be tested on. They omit much of evolution, including the
theory that living creatures share common ancestors and have
changed over time.
</P>
<P>
   Tompkins said after the board's two-day meeting at De Soto High
School that he intended to ask his staff to reword the more than
100 passages taken from the national documents. He will ask a
copyright attorney to review the changes, he said, and the
standards probably will not go back to the board until December.
</P>
<P>
   The rewrite is necessary because three national science
organizations, citing the Kansas school board's August vote to
downplay evolution, last month refused the state's request to use
the copyright material.
</P>
<P>
   The three organizations _ the National Research Council, the
National Science Teachers Association and the American Association
for the Advancement of Science _ said the Kansas standards did not
``embrace the vision and content'' of the groups' national
documents.
</P>
<P>
   Board Chairwoman Linda Holloway said at a break in the meeting
that she was eager for the board to get past this issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to get the standards out to districts,'' Holloway
said.
</P>
<P>
   State science tests to be given in spring 2001 will be based on
the new standards.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Hill's motion to give the rewrite to Tompkins passed
7-3, with moderates Janet Waugh, Val DeFever and Sonny Rundell
voting against it. A related motion that Waugh put forth failed by
the same margin.
</P>
<P>
   Waugh, of Kansas City, Kan., suggested that the board avoid a
rewrite by accepting the earlier standards written by a 27-member
committee of science teachers and professors. The board could then
add a statement saying that local districts could decide whether to
teach evolution, and the state still could leave evolution off its
tests, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Waugh, one of four moderates who voted in August against
downplaying evolution, said she was concerned with the costs
associated with yet another rewrite. In light of Gov. Bill Graves'
recommendation to trim about $22 million from state education
money, Waugh said spending more would not be prudent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a real problem with wasting taxpayers' dollars,'' Waugh
said.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Biles, the board's attorney, told the board he estimated
that hiring a copyright attorney would cost about $3,000. The most
difficult part of the job _ comparing the national documents with
the state standards _ has been completed, Biles said. The board has
paid Kansas City copyright attorney Richard Stitt almost $800 to
date, Biles said.
</P>
<P>
   Carol Williamson of Olathe, a member of the science writing
committee, watched Tuesday as the board ceded the rewrite job to
Tompkins. In discussions Tompkins had said he might ask some
writing committee members to help with the revisions.
</P>
<P>
   Williamson said after the meeting that she wanted no part of the
revisions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would support our commissioner, but I certainly cannot help
him with this task,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, reaction to the science standards continues.
</P>
<P>
   Last week faculty at Southwestern College in Winfield, Kan.,
passed a resolution asking the state board to reconsider its
decision to downplay evolution. The school, which is affiliated
with the United Methodist Church, is among the first church-related
schools in the state to speak out on the issue.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-12-99 2310EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
