u i BC-PAKISTAN-COUP-1STLD-W     10-12 0770
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PAKISTAN-COUP-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAKISTANI GOVERNMENT IS OVERTHROWN BY ARMY COUP 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS to insert new 4th graf. Adds to 3rd graf. Changes spelling of
Musharraf's first name in 3rd graf, from Pervez to Pervaiz.)  (See also PAKISTAN-MUSHARRAF) 
(ART ADV: Photos _ NYT4,5,6 _ are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can
make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(sw) 
 By CELIA W. DUGGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW DELHI, India _ Hours after Pakistan's prime minister fired
the powerful army chief on Tuesday afternoon, the army struck back
with a swift, apparently bloodless coup.
</P>
<P>
   Troops surrounded the prime minister's home, closed all the
major airports and shut down the state-run television and radio
stations for several hours.
</P>
<P>
   At 2:50 a.m. on Wednesday, the army chief, Gen. Pervaiz
Musharraf, addressing the nation on state television in a tone of
patriotic earnestness, said the military had ousted Prime Minister
Nawaz Sharif and his government to stop any further politicization
or destabilization of the military. The general offered no
timetable for elections, nor did he say whether he would rule
personally or whether the army would install a caretaker
government.
</P>
<P>
   He was apparently referring to Sharif's efforts to strengthen
his hold over the courts and the military, and to his success at
pushing through a constitutional amendment that had ended a
president's power to dismiss an elected prime minister _ a vestige
of military rule.
</P>
<P>
   ``Despite all my advice,'' said the general, neatly attired in a
camouflage uniform and wire-rimmed glasses, ``they tried to
interfere with the armed forces, the last remaining viable
institution in which all of you take so much pride and look up to
at all times for stability, unity and integrity of our beloved
country.''
</P>
<P>
   In Pakistan, where generals have ruled for almost half its 52
years as an independent nation, Sharif's sudden, unexplained
decision to fire the army chief was risky and came only a year
after he had replaced another army chief who had sought a greater
role for the army in running the country.
</P>
<P>
   There was virtually no public protest against the coup and some
processions celebrated Sharif's demise, including one near
Parliament House in Islamabad. Sharif, whose party won a landslide
victory in February, 1997, had become increasingly unpopular in
recent months because of the country's deteriorating economy and
out-of-control sectarian violence, as well as Sharif's handling of
a crisis with India over Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
   The military takeover is likely to have serious international
repercussions for economically troubled Pakistan, which is
desperately in need of assistance from international lenders. A
State Department spokesman said that if a coup was confirmed, the
United States would call for the earliest possible restoration of
democracy and would not carry on ``business as usual'' with
Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
   India, too, voiced ``grave concern'' about the coup and placed
its military on high alert along the border it shares with
Pakistan. The deepening political crisis in Pakistan raises new
questions about the prospects for restarting peace talks between
Pakistan and India. These two new nuclear powers, bitter
antagonists who have fought three wars, edged close to a fourth
conflict this summer over the disputed territory of Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
   Relations between Sharif and the military had soured over his
handling of that conflict with India. India fought intensely for
over two months this summer to drive out infiltrators who had
crossed from Pakistan to occupy Indian-held portions of Kashmir,
the Himalayan territory both Pakistan and India want for their own.
</P>
<P>
   After meeting with President Clinton in July, Sharif had called
for the withdrawal of forces that Western analysts now believe were
mainly Pakistani soldiers. Army leaders, including Musharraf saw
the withdrawal as a capitulation to American pressure, the
surrender of a rare military victory over India and a humiliation
of the army, according to analysts and reports in the Pakistani
press.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the timing of the coup was curious. Only two weeks ago,
apparently attempting to quash rumors about a clash between the
country's civilian and military leaders, Sharif had publicly stated
that the army chief would complete his tenure. It was not clear
whether something had happened since than that inspired Sharif's
abrupt decision to fire the general while the army chief was in Sri
Lanka.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The drama began to unfold just a few hours after the state news
service reported at about 5 p.m. Tuesday that Musharraf was being
immediately retired.
</P>
<P>
   Troops began moving through Islamabad. They seized the Cabinet
building and climbed over the fence around the television station.
All flights were canceled as the troops took over the major
airports.
</P>
<P>
   Musharraf said in his speech that as he tried to return to
Pakistan from Sri Lanka, his commercial flight, short of fuel, was
ordered to land outside of Pakistan, endangering the lives of all
the passengers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thanks be to Allah, this evil design was thwarted through
speedy army action,'' said the general, whose flight landed in
Karachi.
</P>
<P>
   Sharif's home was cordoned off and the road to it blocked. He
was reported to be inside. There were also reports that the
information minister, Mushahid Hussain; the foreign minister,
Sartaj Aziz, and the Kashmir affairs minister, Majid Malik, were
under house arrest.
</P>
<P>
   As accounts of the army's takeover of government buildings began
to come in from witnesses, there was confusion about exactly what
was going on.
</P>
<P>
   Telephone calls to government and army spokesmen in Islamabad
rang unanswered. The television station went dark soon after
announcing that the prime minister had fired the general.
</P>
<P>
   The first official confirmation that the army had taken action
against the government came at 10:15 p.m., when the state
television came back to life and a news reader announced that
Sharif had been dismissed. After midnight, the state television
announced that all banks would be closed on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Then, finally, at almost 3 a.m., the general laid out the
reasons for the coup.
</P>
<P>
   He said the country was in a state of ``turmoil and
uncertainty,'' and the economy in a state of collapse. He accused
Sharif's government of systematically destroying the institutions
of Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
   The armed forces had taken over as a last resort to restore
stability, he said, and he pleaded with the public to continue to
be calm.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have done so with all sincerity, loyalty and selfless
devotion to the country,'' he said. ``And the armed forces are
firmly behind me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-12-99 2315EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991012.0438 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-12 23:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4983 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f BC-UTILITIES-MERGER-1STL     10-12 1054
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UTILITIES-MERGER-1STLD-WRITETHRU-510&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CON ED IS SAID TO BE BUYING NORTHEAST UTILITIES FOR $3.29 BILLION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Complete writethru to lengthen and revise)  
(Eds: This story was added to the New York Times front page) 
(ATTN: N.Y., Conn., Northeast points) (bl) 
 By AGIS SALPUKAS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Consolidated Edison Inc. on Tuesday night agreed to
buy Northeast Utilities for $3.29 billion in cash and stock,
according to people close to the talks, in a deal that could
eventually bring less-expensive power to its customers.
</P>
<P>
   The deal, which will give Con Edison access to lower-cost
electricity, is the company's biggest move so far to protect its
base of 3 million customers, who are being courted by outside
companies to buy power at lower rates as New York deregulates its
utility market. Con Edison will raise its customer base to 4.7
million and extend its reach as far north as New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   The deal is also a bid by Con Edison Eto become more competitive
in the fast-paced environment of deregulation, which allows
customers to choose their provider of electricity. Northeast, the
largest utility in New England in terms of customers, has been
aggressively preparing for the new era in Connecticut,
Massachusetts and New Hampshire, which are in various stages of
deregulation. Though Northeast had to spin off its power-generating
plants as part of the deregulation, it has bought plants and built
up a source of cheap power, which Con Edison could sell to its
customers, possibly lowering their rates eventually. Northeast has
also built an organization to market that power throughout the
region.
</P>
<P>
   And in a sign of the perceived value of nuclear power plants,
the deal values Northeast at a higher price if it sells two units
of its Millstone nuclear plant in Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   Dale Bryk, a lawyer with the Natural Resources Defense Council,
said the transaction could be positive for consumers and
environmentalists because it could result in a fresh evaluation of
the Millstone nuclear complex independent of Northeast Utilities.
</P>
<P>
   Deregulation has thus far moved slowly for residential customers
because the companies that want to market power have not been able
to make much money in the early stages, but competition is expected
to become more fierce with time.
</P>
<P>
   Most residential customers have benefited through rate cuts. For
example, Con Edison agreed to cut its rates 10 percent under its
agreement to deregulate in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   As more Con Edison customers are made available to outsiders to
sell them power, consumers will be able to choose from more
alternate suppliers that should offer further cuts in the cost of
electricity.
</P>
<P>
   The reductions will not be large, however. The cost of power in
an average residential bill _ about $50 a month _ is only a part of
the total bill, with most charges actually covering the cost of
delivery of the power; those charges will remain regulated. New
Yorkers, however, can expect an aggressive marketing pitch from the
subsidiaries of the merged utility, which are competing with other
marketers.
</P>
<P>
   Under terms of the deal, which the boards of both companies
approved Tuesday, Con Edison, based in Manhattan, will pay $25 a
share in cash and stock for the outstanding shares of Northeast,
based in Berlin, Conn. Another $1 a share will be paid if units 2
and 3 of Millstone are sold.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Millstone has had one of the nation's most troubled histories
for a nuclear plant. Unit 1 of Millstone is to be retired and
decommissioned. The other two units have cost Northeast dearly,
with huge expenses for maintenance and the cost of buying power
when they were not operating. In 1997 and 1998, the utility had
large losses because of its troubles and suspended its dividend for
four years.
</P>
<P>
   The two operating nuclear units have been put up for sale but
are expected to bring low offers. Some analysts said that should
mean that Northeast will sell them at a loss.
</P>
<P>
   But the sale of the plants is important to Con Edison, which
analysts said did not want to acquire more nuclear plants.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, Con Edison is buying a company that is emerging from its
troubles and was planning to reinstate its dividend in December.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Northeast Utilities rose 12.5 cents Tuesday, to
$21.25, while Con Edison fell 75 cents, to $36.4375. Based on
Northeast's closing price, the deal represents a 17.6 percent
premium.
</P>
<P>
   The people close to the deal said the two utilities expected
savings of $1.3 billion to $1.4 billion in the next 10 years.
Whether there will be layoffs has yet to be determined, the people
said.
</P>
<P>
   Eugene McGrath, the chairman and chief executive of Con Edison,
will hold those positions in the merged company, while Michael
Morris, the chairman, president and chief executive of Northeast,
will become president, according to people close to the deal.
</P>
<P>
   McGrath did not have an easy time reaching the agreement. Since
word leaked out last week that talks with Northeast were under way,
Con Edison's stock has been pummeled on concern that a merger with
Northeast would depress Con Edison's strong earnings. Northeast has
had large losses in recent years and had to suspend its dividend
four years ago because of financial pressures caused by problems
with its nuclear plants. But Northeast has put a lot of its
troubles behind it and has seen its earnings recover.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement to acquire Northeast is the second step to expand
Con Edison's reach.
</P>
<P>
   In May 1998, Con Edison acquired Orange &AMP; Rockland Utilities for
$1.5 billion, adding to its customer base and expanding its reach
northward. The agreement to buy Northeast, however, puts McGrath
and his company on a national stage to compete with other major
utilities. Pacific Gas &AMP; Electric of California, for example, is
building up its presence in New England by buying up power plants
and setting up a marketing arm.
</P>
<P>
   Under Morris, Northeast has also moved quickly and aggressively
to prepare iself for deregulation.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have a lot of access to customer throughout the
Northeast,'' said Robert Rubin, a utility analyst with Bear
Stearns.
</P>
<P>
   Of Con Edison's strategy, he said: ``This no surprise. They are
not doing anything crazy.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
