<SLUG> BC-DRUG </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWMAKERS EXPLORE HANDLING OF SEIZED DRUG MONEY 
</HEADLINE>
 MONEY-KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KAREN DILLON  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ Armed with a new state auditor's report, a
legislative committee Tuesday looked for ways to get police in
Missouri to follow state laws when seizing drug money.
</P>
<P>
   In the hearing at Harris-Stowe State College, the debate
sometimes became heated as legislators tried to determine whether
law enforcement had intentionally circumvented state laws in order
to keep the drug money.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers also asked Auditor Claire McCaskill about how police
were getting around the laws, which require police to report drug
money they seize to county prosecutors. Under the laws, state
courts then would determine how to distribute the money, normally
sending it to public education.
</P>
<P>
   The Kansas City Star reported in January that in many cases,
police simply handed the money off to federal agencies, which kept
part and sent the rest, usually 80 percent, back to police.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're talking about a substantial amount of money that is
loose,'' said Sen. Harry Wiggins, a Kansas City Democrat. ``We've
got to set up proper guidelines.''
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after a news conference Tuesday morning, McCaskill spoke
at the joint legislative committee hearing, which was attended by
about 50 politicians, educators and law enforcement officials.
Later she presented the audit in Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   At the St. Louis hearing, co-chairman Wiggins said the committee
planned to present a report to the legislature based on findings
from research, hearings, the auditor's report and meetings with
federal officials.
</P>
<P>
   The auditor's report said police had been able to circumvent
state laws because of flaws in drug statutes, such as not defining
when money is actually seized.
</P>
<P>
   In many cases police have said that they are not violating state
law, because they are not really seizing property or money.
Instead, they have said that they are only detaining the person and
property until a federal agent can officially seize it.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. David Klarich, a St. Louis County Republican, echoed other
legislators when he said he and his law partners did not understand
how police could come to such a legal conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   McCaskill and legislators agreed that a seizure legally occurred
when an officer discovered cash or property while detaining someone
suspected of wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got $700,000 in the backseat of a car stopped by the
Highway Patrol,'' McCaskill said. ``Does anybody think that (the
driver) can pick up the money and walk away with it? I don't think
so.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, McCaskill said adding a simple definition to
Missouri law would stop police from handing off cash to federal
agents whom they had called.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would reduce the ability of the police to say, `I didn't
really seize it _ I waited for (a federal agent) to get there, and
they seized it,' '' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Legislators wanted to know whether police were sending the money
to federal agencies so they could intentionally avoid the state
requirement to send money to education.
</P>
<P>
   McCaskill said that, no, she believed police were only trying to
take the money away from the ``bad guys'' the best way that they
could.
</P>
<P>
   At that explanation, Republican Sen. Larry Rohrbach, became
indignant.
</P>
<P>
   ``If someone knows they can get $700,000, they know that would
be a significant thing,'' Rohrbach said. ``You know that would be a
significant thing. I know that would be a significant thing.
Everybody knows that would be a significant thing.''
</P>
<P>
   A debate Tuesday over a felony-conviction requirement in
Missouri law probably reflected a debate to come in the
legislature.
</P>
<P>
   Missouri law requires that if someone with property is charged
with a drug crime, they must be convicted of a felony before
property can be confiscated. McCaskill suggested that the law
should have some exemptions.
</P>
<P>
   Both Klarich and Rohrbach raised concerns, saying the felony
requirement protected people's civil rights.
</P>
<P>
   McCaskill pointed out that the federal law did not require a
felony conviction. In fact, under federal law, a person must prove
that the property was not involved in a crime _ as opposed to state
law, which requires the state to prove the property was involved in
a crime.
</P>
<P>
   McCaskill said that unless the federal and the state laws
mirrored each other, the forfeiture issue would never be fixed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to fix the discrepancies between the two laws while
protecting due process as much as possible,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   St. Louis Police Chief Ronald Henderson and his officers also
testified, explaining how they conducted forfeitures.
</P>
<P>
   Henderson said that he was being forced to cut his budget this
year by several million dollars and was decreasing the number of
officers by 200 through attrition. He pointed out that although
forfeiture money could not be used for salaries, it was important
to buy needed equipment.
</P>
<P>
   He told the legislators that his department had paid $1.9
million to schools since 1989. When he was asked, however, he could
not say how much his department had been receiving back from
federal agencies.
</P>
<P>
   In three years from 1996 to 1998, his department received $3.5
million, according to the auditor's report.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey Simon, president of the Kansas City Board of Police
Commissioners, and police officials declined to comment, saying
they had not seen the report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
