<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ENVIR-LAWSUITS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGH COURT IS URGED TO UPHOLD `CITIZEN SUIT' TO CURB POLLUTION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: S.C., Va., N.Y., Conn.)   (af)  
 By LINDA GREENHOUSE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ When Congress passed the Clean Water Act 27 years
ago, it included a ``citizen suit'' provision authorizing private
individuals to sue polluters and collect fines that would go not to
the successful plaintiffs but directly to the federal Treasury.
</P>
<P>
   In the face of growing judicial hostility to such suits, a case
argued before the Supreme Court Tuesday could determine whether
that provision, and similar clauses in other federal environmental
laws, would continue to be of much use.
</P>
<P>
   The case, an appeal by Friends of the Earth and other
environmental groups from a ruling that dismissed their suit
against the operator of a hazardous waste incinerator on a river in
South Carolina, has galvanized the environmental movement as have
few Supreme Court cases in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   The hourlong argument was highly technical, laced with
references to Supreme Court precedents on jurisdictional issues
like standing and mootness, but the policy debate at the heart of
the case peeked through.
</P>
<P>
   ``What cases do you know,'' Justice Antonin Scalia asked the
environmental groups' lawyer, Bruce J. Terris, that consider it ``a
proper function of the courts to impose a public penalty in private
litigation?''
</P>
<P>
   Scalia, perhaps the judiciary's strongest critic of citizen suit
provisions, said such suits usurped the ordinary function of the
executive branch and brought about ``a major alteration of power
between the various branches of government and between the federal
and state governments.''
</P>
<P>
   When Terris replied that in the view of Congress, citizen suits
were not really private lawsuits but served to ``carry out a public
function,'' Scalia cut him off.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand that Congress has said it,'' he said. ``The
question is whether it's constitutional.''
</P>
<P>
   No other members of the court appeared eager to take up Scalia's
effort to turn a discussion on the meaning of a federal statute
into a major constitutional debate over the separation of powers.
Nonetheless, the exchange was a reminder that although the
environmental groups were relieved last spring when the justices
agreed to hear their appeal of what they considered a very damaging
lower court ruling, that relief could prove to be premature.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court, which itself has restricted citizen suits in
several recent rulings, could use this case, Friends of the Earth
vs. Laidlaw Environmental Services, No. 98-822, to restrict such
suits further.
</P>
<P>
   The 4th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals , in Richmond, made new
law in this case in two respects. First, it ruled that the suit had
to be dismissed as moot because, although the incinerator was still
discharging excess levels of mercury into the North Tyger River
when the suit was filed, in 1992, the operator acquired new
anti-pollution equipment and stopped the discharges soon
thereafter.
</P>
<P>
   Second, the appellate court said, since the plaintiffs had not
``prevailed'' in their litigation, they were not entitled to
reimbursement of their lawyers' fees and court costs. The fourth
circuit thus became the only appellate court to reject what has
become known as the catalyst theory, under which environmental and
civil rights plaintiffs who can show that their lawsuit brought
about a change in the defendant's behavior can recover their fees
and costs even if the lawsuit did not result in an official court
judgment.
</P>
<P>
   Both aspects of the fourth circuit's ruling are before the
Supreme Court. The plaintiffs are arguing that if a defendant can
avoid all liability by modifying its behavior once a suit is filed,
citizen suits will become economically impractical.
</P>
<P>
   A separate question the court may need to address is whether the
closing of the plant in May, two months after the justices agreed
to hear the case, means there is no longer a live issue for them to
resolve and, if so, whether the fourth circuit decision should
remain on the books.
</P>
<P>
   New York, Connecticut and 12 other states entered the case on
the side of the environmental groups, arguing in a brief that
citizen suits fill gaps in enforcement and ``help states focus
their regulatory aims.''
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration also supports the plaintiffs. Jeffrey
P. Minear, an assistant solicitor general, told the court Tuesday
that the fines imposed in these suits are valuable deterrents
against continued violations.
</P>
<P>
   Donald A. Cockrill, arguing Tuesday for the company, now known
as the Safety-Kleen Corp. and based in Columbia, S.C., said the
$405,000 in penalties the federal district court imposed on his
client ``had no deterrent effect.'' He said that while ``deterrence
to me implies that someone doesn't want to do what's right and you
have to goad them into it,'' the company was already close to
compliance by the time the suit was filed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
