<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WILT-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BASKETBALL STAR WILT CHAMBERLAIN DIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BLAIR KERKHOFF  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Basketball star Wilt Chamberlain, perhaps the most dominant
player of his day, died Tuesday at 63 at his Los Angeles home.
</P>
<P>
   Chamberlain played for three years at the University of Kansas,
two on the varsity team, before embarking on a record-setting
professional career.
</P>
<P>
   When he retired in 1973 after 14 NBA seasons, he was the game's
career scoring leader.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a shocker for everyone who knew him,'' said Jerry Waugh,
an assistant coach for the Kansas teams that included Chamberlain.
``We thought of him as invincible, a big, strong man who always
took care of himself. This is a very sad day.''
</P>
<P>
   Numbers defined Chamberlain's career and life. He was the game's
first 7-foot center with agility, who came along at a time when
organized basketball was mostly segregated.
</P>
<P>
   He was the only player in NBA history to score 100 points in a
game, setting the famous record on March 2, 1962, when his
Philadelphia Warriors defeated the New York Knicks 169-147.
</P>
<P>
   That year Chamberlain averaged 50.4 points. Nobody else in NBA
history averaged as many as 40 points in a season. He won the
scoring title seven straight seasons, beginning with his NBA most
valuable player and rookie of the year season in 1959-60. Only
Michael Jordan has won as many consecutive scoring titles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wilt Chamberlain had a great deal to do with the success of
the NBA,'' said Red Auerbach, former Boston Celtics coach.
</P>
<P>
   Chamberlain scored 31,419 points in his career. He held the NBA
record for 55 rebounds in a game. Remarkably, he never fouled out
in 1,205 regular-season or playoff games. He even led the league
once in assists.
</P>
<P>
   After taking Overbrook High School of Philadelphia to three
public-schools championships, titles eluded Chamberlain until later
in his career. His first NBA title came with the Philadelphia 76ers
in 1967. His only other title came with the 1972 Los Angeles
Lakers, a team that won 33 straight games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wilt was one of the greatest ever, and we will never see
another one like him,'' said former NBA great Kareem Abdul-Jabbar.
</P>
<P>
   Chamberlain was known as ``Wilt the Stilt'' and ``The Big
Dipper.'' At Kansas friends shortened it to ``Dippy.''
</P>
<P>
   At Kansas, Chamberlain changed the rules because of his
extraordinary size and power. No longer could players leave the
free-throw line immediately after releasing the ball. Chamberlain
could essentially bank a missed free throw to himself. He was also
responsible for the rule that prohibits offensive goaltending.
Before Chamberlain, it was legal to guide a teammate's shot into
the basket.
</P>
<P>
   The NBA widened the lane to keep Chamberlain farther away from
the basket when rebounding free throws.
</P>
<P>
   His Kansas years were an emotional roller coaster. He selected
the Jayhawks over some 200 other schools. The program was widely
accused of cheating, but NCAA investigators found nothing improper
about the recruiting process. Kansas later received two years of
probation for providing tires for Chamberlain's cars.
</P>
<P>
   Chamberlain's arrival was eventful before he ever got to
Lawrence. He was refused service at a Kansas City restaurant
because he was black. It was not the last time he faced racial
prejudice in the area.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was such a remarkable guy, as he came at a time when he
couldn't be an ordinary student, or an ordinary person,'' Waugh
said.
</P>
<P>
   He showed his prowess in other sports by winning the high jump
at the Kansas Relays the first time he attempted the event.
</P>
<P>
   On the court, college basketball had never seen anything like
him. As a first-year player when freshman could not play on the
varsity, Chamberlain scored 42 points in leading his team to
victory over the Jayhawk regulars, playing before a packed house.
</P>
<P>
   In his varsity debut, Chamberlain exceeded everybody's wildest
dreams by scoring 52 points and grabbing 31 rebounds in a victory
over Northwestern. The scoring output remains a school record, and
only a 36-rebound effort the next season against Iowa State topped
Chamberlain's debut.
</P>
<P>
   Chamberlain led the Jayhawks to the NCAA championship game as a
sophomore, but the Jayhawks fell to North Carolina in triple
overtime in one of college basketball's most-storied games.
Chamberlain called it the toughest loss of his career, and it
turned out to be his last tournament loss as a college player.
</P>
<P>
   When he returned to Kansas for a jersey retirement ceremony in
1998, Chamberlain apologized to the crowd for the loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``Forty years ago I lost a heartbreaking battle, losing to North
Carolina by one point in triple overtime,'' Chamberlain said. ``It
was a devastating thing for me, because I felt like I let the
university down. I let KU down.''
</P>
<P>
   Kansas did not reach the tournament in Chamberlain's junior
year. Tired of defenses ganging up in him, Chamberlain decided to
leave Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   Rules at the time prohibited underclassmen from jumping to the
NBA before their class graduated. So Chamberlain played a year with
the Harlem Globetrotters. A year later he signed with the
Philadelphia Warriors. He also played with the franchise when it
transferred to San Francisco. Later he was traded to the 76ers and
then to the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   Chamberlain continued to make news after his playing days ended.
He briefly served as a coach for the San Diego Conquistadors of the
American Basketball Association, but his attention turned to other
sports and activities and even controversy.
</P>
<P>
   He played competitive volleyball, racquetball and tennis. He
appeared in a few commercials and movies. But perhaps Chamberlain
became best known for his claim in an autobiography that he slept
with 20,000 women.
</P>
<P>
   ``The women I have been most attracted to, the most in love
with, I've pushed away the strongest,'' Chamberlain said in a 1991
interview with the Associated Press. ``There are about five women I
can think of that I could have married. I cared for them a lot, but
not enough to make a commitment.''
</P>
<P>
   That is not how former friends chose to remember Chamberlain. Al
Correll grew up four blocks from Chamberlain and was three years
younger than his hero. Because of Chamberlain, Correll attended
Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1962, I was going back to KU, and I went over to his house
to say goodbye,'' Correll said. ``He asked me if I needed anything,
and I told him I was broke as most college kids are. He said,
`Here's $50.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there will be another Wilt Chamberlain. We hear
that kind of thing quite a bit, but he did some things that nobody
will ever do again. Nobody will ever score 100 points again; that
will just never be done.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
