u s BC-BBN-BRAVES-METS-COX     10-12 0444
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-METS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Maddux silences Mets 4-2 in NLCS opener
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The talking was supposed to finally stop at 8:16 p.m.
Tuesday at Turner Field, but Game 1 of the National League
Championship Series played out like an ongoing argument between the
Mets and Braves.
</P>
<P>
   For every statement the Mets tried to make, the Braves had an
answer, and maybe that's exactly as it should have been in the
reunion of the first NLCS in 1969 between these two.
</P>
<P>
   But as has been the case for the better part of the 1999 season,
the Braves got the last word and took Game 1 with a 4-2 win.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves have beaten the Mets 10 times out of 13 this season,
and 14 of the last 15 games against them at Turner Field. Ever
since the Braves lost Game 1 of the 1991 NLCS to the Pirates and
won the series, the winner of Game 1 has gone on to win each of the
last six NLCS.
</P>
<P>
   Note to Mets fans: It wasn't Chipper Jones doing the
``talking.'' It was the soft-spoken Gerald Williams, who had two
hits and drove in the go-ahead run, and the non-controversial Eddie
Perez, who homered to left field for the first breathing room of
the game.
</P>
<P>
   Greg Maddux quieted the Mets offense with seven effective
innings, allowing five hits and one run, walking one and striking
out two.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves jumped ahead 1-0 on back-to-back hits to start the
game, then Masato Yoshii retired the meat of the Braves order. The
Braves went ahead 2-1 on a Williams single to left in the fifth
inning. They were headed for more but Roger Cedeno made a
spectacular catch in right field, fully extending to snare a Bret
Boone liner that would have meant at least another run.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets' heralded infield booted a ball to allow Ryan Klesko to
reach first in the sixth, but came back with a beauty of a double
play on Edgardo Alfonzo's flip to Rey Ordonez for the bare-handed
heroics.
</P>
<P>
   Perez took a 2-1 Pat Mahomes pitch and deposited it in the
left-field bleachers for his first home run of this postseason and
a 3-1 lead. Walt Weiss' RBI single in the eighth made it 4-1.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets had kept Chipper Jones in check by pitching around him
and didn't let Brian Jordan hurt them either. They had finally got
one of their .300 hitters in a groove against a Braves pitcher.
Edgardo Alfonzo, who'd hit .159 off Braves pitching during the
regular season, doubled twice off Maddux and scored a run on a
broken-bat Mike Piazza grounder to tie the score 1-1.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll Rogers writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
