<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-12 23:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4990 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-CLERGYCHASTISESEN.BON     10-12 0869
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLERGY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLACK CLERGY CHASTISE BOND FOR HIS VOTE ON JUDGE'S NOMINATION 
</HEADLINE>
 CHASTISE SEN. BOND-KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID GOLDSTEIN  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Looking for support for his re-election run a year ago, Sen. Kit
Bond of Missouri met over lunch with a group of black clergy in St.
Louis.
</P>
<P>
   Black voters traditionally back Democrats, but many were unhappy
with Missouri Attorney General Jay Nixon over his role in school
desegregation cases. And the Republican Bond had allies in the
black community because of his support for urban issues.
</P>
<P>
   Among the topics discussed was the languishing nomination to the
federal bench of Judge Ronnie White, the first black person to
serve on the Missouri Supreme Court. It was one of the group's
priorities.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides differ in their recollection of that talk. Bond said
he pledged only to support White through the nominating process,
not necessarily when it reached the floor of the Senate. His
audience said he offered no qualifiers.
</P>
<P>
   The fallout in light of the pivotal role Bond played last week
in the Senate's rejection of White could have a far-reaching effect
on his political relationship with black voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was stunned,'' said former Kansas City Mayor Emanuel
Cleaver, a Democrat who has been a close political ally of Bond.
``My spirit has been dampened considerably by the killing of Ronnie
White's nomination.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. W. Bartalette Finney Sr., a presiding elder of the
African Methodist Episcopal Church in western Missouri, Was harsher
still.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's dead in the African-American community,'' said Finney,
who has worked with Bond for several years and helped him make
inroads into the black community during his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Bond won a third term last fall, and key to his victory was
capturing 33 percent of the state's black vote. That is a
significant accomplishment for most Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   He said he had been weathering criticism in the last week from
former supporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I obviously know a lot of my friends are going to be
disappointed,'' Bond said Tuesday. ``On something like this, when
you have good friends on both sides, it's a very, very tough
decision. I have worked through my career to promote qualified
African-Americans and will continue to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   White's defeat on a party-line vote in the Senate also could
have political implications for Bond's Missouri colleague,
Republican Sen. John Ashcroft, who orchestrated the opposition to
the judge. Ashcroft contended that White was not an unequivocal
supporter of the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   Ashcroft faces a difficult re-election battle of his own next
year against Missouri Gov. Mel Carnahan, a Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   Cleaver, minister at St. James United Methodist Church in Kansas
City, said he and other black clergy planned to meet this week to
begin developing an ``action plan'' in the aftermath of the White
episode.
</P>
<P>
   Said Finney: ``We're clergy persons. We've had prayer about
this. We've turned it over to God. But we're going to be a God
squad. That means anybody we can tell about this awful, terrible
experience, we're going to do it. Do not trust Christopher Bond on
any issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Bond called Finney ``a fine man,'' but said it was inappropriate
for Finney to question his integrity.
</P>
<P>
   The episode also touched off a heated debate over what role race
played in the vote. Democrats suggested it was a factor;
Republicans said the vote turned solely on White's qualifications.
</P>
<P>
   Ashcroft has been using the crime issue _ and the death penalty,
in particular _ as a weapon in his campaign against Carnahan. He
offered statistics about the number of times that White voted to
reverse death sentences. But Democrats later pointed out the
numbers were not that much different from those of two judges
Ashcroft appointed to the state Supreme Court when he was governor.
</P>
<P>
   Bond had been supporting White but announced his opposition at
the Republicans' weekly lunch the day of the Senate vote. The
bottom then fell out of the nomination. Without backing from either
of Missouri's two senators, others who had previously endorsed
White withdrew their support.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people are not surprised at Ashcroft,'' Cleaver said.
``People are extremely surprised'' about Bond.
</P>
<P>
   He said Bond probably turned against White as a political favor
for Ashcroft.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it had anything to do with anything other than
Ashcroft pleading with Kit Bond to support him on something he
needed,'' Cleaver said. ``He (Ashcroft) has the contest of his
career.''
</P>
<P>
   Bond said he based his vote on the case Ashcroft made about
White's record as a judge. He said White was ``just not
appropriate.''
</P>
<P>
   Bond said that when he met with the black clergy in St. Louis
last fall, he pledged only to get White's stalled nomination out of
committee and onto the Senate floor for a vote.
</P>
<P>
   The ministers remembered it differently.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was put to him very succinctly: `Will you support the
nomination of Judge White?'' recalled the Rev. Sammie E. Jones,
president of the Missionary Baptist State Convention of Missouri.
``That was one of our primary concerns. His answer was, `Yes, I
will.' We put it to bed after that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-12-99 2330EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
