<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-12 23:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4991 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w BC-TREATY-DEBATE-2NDLD-W     10-12 1043
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TREATY-DEBATE-2NDLD-WRITETHRU-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE CONSERVATIVES REJECT PLAN TO POSTPONE VOTE ON TEST BAN
TREATY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs throughout for additional information and clarifications;
most of major new material is in first 3 grafs)  (ART ADV: Photo NYT14 is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(sw) 
 By ERIC SCHMITT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Senate conservatives on Tuesday rejected a
compromise by the Republican and Democratic leaders to postpone
action on a treaty banning underground nuclear testing.
</P>
<P>
   Both leaders said they would resume talks Wednesday to find
wording acceptable to all senators, since the approval of all 100
would be needed to postpone the vote. Short of that, there are
other parliamentary maneuvers available to the leaders that require
only a simple majority.
</P>
<P>
   Republican Majority Leader Trent Lott said that if 100 votes
cannot be rounded up for postponement, he is willing to let the
treaty go to a vote. One way or another, top Senate aides said, the
issue was likely to be settled, with the only question being
whether the Senate soundly defeats the treaty or finds a
face-saving way to withdraw it. Both sides acknowledge that the
treaty lacks the two-thirds majority needed to pass.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The situation illustrates the tricky political position
confronting the Lott. He is juggling the demands of 55 diverse
Republicans, many of whom want to delay a treaty vote to avoid a
diplomatic embarrassment and others who want to kill the pact
regardless of the international repercussions. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, Lott took a step toward averting a vote when he
signaled that he would accept assurances from Senate Democrats to
delay action on the treaty until President Clinton leaves office.
Republicans had insisted that Clinton make that pledge, but he has
refused, and there was no sign that he would have any change of
heart on this matter.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``If we can be guaranteed that it would be set aside and not
come up in this Congress, then we could accept that,'' Lott told
reporters after a spirited luncheon with other Senate Republicans.
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After that, Democratic Minority Leader Thomas Daschle answered
Lott's call, saying in a letter that he would support Clinton's
request to postpone the vote and would agree not to reschedule the
treaty for a vote, absent ``unforeseen changes in the international
situation.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Republicans balked, and Daschle changed the phrase to
``extraordinary circumstances,'' as defined by the two leaders.
Democrats insisted on that provision in the event that Pakistan or
India, for instance, resumed nuclear weapons tests. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But the wording still did not satisfy hard-liners like Sens. Jon
Kyl, R-Ariz., and Jesse Helms, R-N.C., who complained that
Democrats would use the ``loophole'' to seize upon the slightest
global disturbance and wield the treaty as a campaign issue next
year.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The objections killed a proposed deal that would have unfolded
on the Senate floor between Lott and Daschle that could have
defused the political and procedural brinkmanship that has engulfed
the treaty since Lott surprised Democrats two weeks ago by
answering their demand to bring it up and called for an early vote.
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Under the tentative deal, Lott proposed sending the
Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty back to the Foreign Relations
Committee for hearings for the rest of Clinton's presidency, as
long as Daschle agreed not to try to bring it to the floor. Daschle
was to have agreed, barring the ``extraordinary circumstances.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Despite Tuesday's setback for the treaty, a growing number of
Democrats and Republicans seemed eager to postpone the vote. Sens.
John Warner, R-Va., and Daniel Patrick Moynihan, D-N.Y., released a
letter Tuesday to their two leaders, endorsing efforts to delay
Senate action on the treaty until the next Congress convenes in
2001. About a dozen senators have signed the letter so far.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine Albright telephoned half a dozen
moderate Republicans, urging them to consider the diplomatic
consequences of allowing the treaty to be defeated.
</P>
<P>
   Treaty supporters have warned that a Senate defeat of the accord
would send a dangerous signal to emerging nuclear nations that it
was acceptable to continue testing. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, amid reports of a military coup in Pakistan, Lott
scoffed at those concerns and said the unrest in Pakistan would not
have any bearing on the Senate's action.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Why should it have any bearing on this debate?'' Lott said.
``What we're talking about in this treaty is the national security
of our own country. Nothing we do here will have any effect on the
government in Pakistan.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The behind-the-scenes maneuvering overshadowed the Senate's
second day of debate on the treaty itself. Critics and supporters
mostly read from prepared statements, speaking to a largely empty
chamber.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats expressed astonishment that Republicans would insist
on voting on a pact that the President requested be withdrawn for
national security reasons.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The opponents of the treaty have won, for now,'' said Sen.
Joseph Lieberman, D-Conn. ``Why push for this vote if the president
of the United States has asked for delay because of his fears? This
isn't politics. This goes to the heart of our security.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But critics argued that the pact would permanently bind the
ability of the United States to perform tests while rogue nations,
and perhaps even China and Russia, might conduct nuclear explosions
that would erode America's atomic deterrent. They have also said
the treaty could not be adequately verified.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The treaty is based on noble, idealistic goals, but it fails
the hard-reality test,'' said Sen. Jim Bunning, R-Ky. ``The U.S.
usually lives up to the agreements it signs. But there is no
guarantee that other nations would follow the letter of the law.''
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   To put the treaty into effect, ratification by 44 nations
believed to have a nuclear capacity is needed. Only 26 countries,
including Britain and France, have done so. China, which has not
ratified the pact and is taking its lead from the United States,
Tuesday urged the Senate to approve it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
