<SLUG> BC-BBN-NLCS-SIDE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Master Maddux handles mighty Mets
 &HT;    By Karen Rosen
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Much to the Mets' chagrin, the Greg Maddux they faced
Tuesday night was nothing like the pitcher shelled two weeks ago in
Shea Stadium. This was the master, who moved back into the
postseason victory column with the Braves' 4-2 victory against New
York.
</P>
<P>
   Maddux, now 10-9 after 23 postseason starts and 4-6 in the NLCS,
gave up five hits and one run in seven innings.
</P>
<P>
   He won his first post-season game since the division series
victory against the Cubs last year. Proving that his New York state
of mind works best in Georgia, he now has a 9-2 record against the
Mets in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Maddux, who was 19-9 in the regular season, won his fourth game
of the year against the Mets. His only loss to New York was his
last outing on Sept. 29 in Shea Stadium, when he gave up 11 hits
and eight runs (seven earned) in three innings.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Maddux retired the first six batters before allowing
Roger Cedeno a double in the third. But after two ground balls,
Perez got Cedeno out on a botched squeeze play with pitcher Masato
Yoshii at the plate.
</P>
<P>
   In the fourth, Edgardo Alfonzo doubled and John Olerud, who hit
the grand slam off Maddux in New York, got a single. Maddux had an
0-2 count on Mike Piazza and thought he struck him out on his next
pitch. But it was ruled a ball. Then Piazza hit a broken-bat
grounder to third to drive in Alfonzo.
</P>
<P>
   Maddux had a 1-2-3 fifth, then Alfonzo doubled again in the
sixth. He got Olerud to fly out to center and Piazza to ground out
again. After a two-out single by Cedeno in the seventh, Rey Ordonez
hit a line drive straight back to Maddux, who caught it as he was
whirling away.
</P>
<P>
   Maddux got up to pitch in the eighth, but was immediately lifted
for Mike Remlinger when left-hander Matt Franco was announced as
the pinch-hitter. In a double switch, Brian Hunter came in at first
base to replace Howard Battle, who had never played first.
</P>
<P>
   Mets pitcher Kenny Rogers, who will start today, said that when
he tries to learn from good pitchers, ``I always refer to Maddux,''
he said. ``I'm sure everybody _ every big-leaguer or minor-leaguer
has watched him meticulously at times just to try to find out what
he does that makes him so good.''
</P>
<P>
   Rogers said that Maddux dominates with movement and location,
``and that's a sign for all the other pitchers that when you get to
a certain level you don't have to throw 95 or 100 (mph) to get
people out.''
</P>
<P>
   Maddux, who led the team in bunts this season with 13, had a
sacrifice bunt in the fifth to advance Walt Weiss to third. Weiss
later scored. Mets pitcher Masato Yoshii injured himself fielding
the ball, but stayed in the game.
</P>
<P>
   Karen Rosen writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
