<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-WILLIAMS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Williams gets praise from Cox
 &HT;    By Al Levine
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Before Tuesday night's game, Braves manager Bobby Cox
was asked to rate this year's team among the eight he's taken to
the NLCS. He answered with a big compliment to leadoff hitter
Gerald Williams.
</P>
<P>
   And then Williams went out and made the skipper look like a
genius.
</P>
<P>
   Williams had a hand in both of Atlanta's first two runs. He led
off the Braves' first with a single to center off New York starter
Masato Yoshii and scored on Brett Boone's single to right.
</P>
<P>
   In the fifth, Williams singled home Walt Weiss, who had opened
the inning with a double and was sacrificed to third by pitcher
Greg Maddux.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, Mets leadoff hitter Rickey Henderson did little to
help his team, going 0-3 his first three times at bat.
</P>
<P>
   Williams' performance in the postseason is not a surprise to
Braves fans. He hit .281 with 14 home runs and 53 RBIs in 73 games
in the leadoff spot. He had a career-high 15-game hitting streak in
late July, early August that was the longest Braves streak of the
season.
</P>
<P>
   In 26 games through September-October, Williams is hitting .298
with five homers and 15 RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   He was 7-18 (.389) in the Division Series against Houston, with
a double, three RBIs, two runs scored and a stolen base. The Mets
should know Gerald Williams: He stole three bases against them July
3 in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this year's club is a very good base-running club,''
Cox said in a pre-game news conference. ``There's nothing I've done
to make them better baserunners; it's just the fact that we've run
the bases very well this year, stolen a few more bases.''
</P>
<P>
   And then the tribute to Williams.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got clutch performances from guys like Gerald Williams
all year long,'' Cox said. ``Once he got in the lineup and stayed
there, I left him in there. He's a much better player than just a
platoon type guy. We don't ever pinch-hit for him anymore. He's
gotten a lot of big hits.''
</P>
<P>
   Al Levine writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
