<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-SIDE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mets offense shut down for most part in Game 1
 &HT;    By Michael Lee
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ If Mike Piazza doesn't break his bat in the fourth
inning, Chipper Jones not misplay a grounder in the ninth, there is
no guarantee that the Mets even score on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   It's not that New York didn't have many opportunities to score,
it's just that when it did, only once did the Mets get a break.
</P>
<P>
   After Greg Maddux breezed through six batters in the first two
innings, Roger Cedeno hit a double to left field and wound up on
third after Gerald Williams' throw missed cut-off man Bret Boone.
Just when it looked like the Mets would make something happen, they
fell apart.
</P>
<P>
   Rey Ordonez hit a ball that bounded high over his shoulder and
edged foul, but catcher Eddie Perez scooped it up and threw him out
at first. Then it got even uglier. Mets manager Bobby Valentine
called for a squeeze. It might have worked had Masato Yoshii made
contact on his bunt. Instead, Cedeno was tagged out between third
and home, and Yoshii ended the inning with a weak grounder to
Maddux.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets threatened again in the fourth inning after an Edgardo
Alfonso double and a John Olerud single had runners on first and
third with one out. Mike Piazza's broken bat grounder surprised
Braves third baseman Chipper Jones, who bobbled the ball before
getting Piazza at first. Alfonso scored from third, but that was
all New York could muster.
</P>
<P>
   Alfonso doubled again in the sixth, but was he left stranded
when Olerud lined out to Andruw Jones and Piazza grounded out Walt
Weiss to end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets added their final run in the ninth, when Shawon Dunston
reached on Jones' error, moved to second on a wild pitch and scored
on Todd Pratt's single to left.
</P>
<P>
   The final threat ended when Ordonez grounded out to Jones.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Lee writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
