A5004 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BBN-BRAVES-PEREZ-COX     10-12 0368
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-PEREZ-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Perez puts it on the line
 &HT;    By Michael Lee
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Usually, the sight of a grown man running home like a
scared child doesn't insight a standing ovation. But Tuesday night,
it was well deserved for Braves catcher Eddie Perez.
</P>
<P>
   Perez had just laid down a sacrifice bunt for Andruw Jones and
to ensure that Jones made it to second, he made a U-turn to make
Mets pitcher Turk Wendell tag him. Fans at the Ted rose to their
feet and began to chant, ``Eddie! Eddie!''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, it was for that play. But more than anything, it was for
his overall performance in Game 1 of the NL Championship Series.
Perez came through with the play of the game with his glove and
helped pad Greg Maddux's lead with a bases-empty home run in the
sixth. And he called a pretty good game, too.
</P>
<P>
   In the third inning, Perez crushed a Mets rally by showing some
speed despite his bad knees. With Roger Cedeno on third base with
nobody out, Perez snagged a ball that nearly went foul off the bat
of Rey Ordonez, then he threw out Ordonez. And after Masato Yoshii
failed to meet his end of a squeeze, he chased Cedeno and tagged
him out.
</P>
<P>
   After Edgardo Alfonso and Rey Ordonez turned a breathtaking
double-play, it looked as though New York would enter the seventh
inning down just one run. But Perez changed all that, bursting the
Mets bubble again, when he turned on a 2-1 fastball and sent it
deep into the left-field bleachers. And for the first time, Tuesday
evening, Braves fans expressed their love with chants of ``Eddie.''
</P>
<P>
   Eddie Perez still would've have been in position to be a NLCS
Game 1 hero, the season-ending knee injury to Javy Lopez
notwithstanding. That's because he is Maddux's personal catcher.
But this entire postseason, he has played every inning, despite
having torn cartilage in his left knee.
</P>
<P>
   While Perez is here, he's making the most of the postseason
spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   And while he does, Braves fans will continue to chant, ``Eddie!
Eddie!''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Lee writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
