</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-NUHN-COLUMN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Game 1 vintage Maddux
 &HT;    By Gary Nuhn
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It was a difficult season for Greg Maddux.
</P>
<P>
   A game that he had reduced to simple repetition over the past
decade _ fast ball, change-up, fast ball, change-up; see the
hitters curse under their breath _ suddenly was as complicated as a
Joy Clark explanation.
</P>
<P>
   His earned run average, 3.57, would have been a lifetime best
for most pitchers in the arm-poor game that passes for major league
baseball these days. But for Maddux, it was his worst since 1987,
his rookie season with the Cubs.
</P>
<P>
   There is still a question of whether this was an aberration or
whether the league's once-confused batters have figured him out as
they might a bus schedule in Tokyo if they put in 11 years of
study.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night in the ballpark known hereabouts as The Ted,
Maddux unfurled one of his vintage performances in Game 1 of the
National League Championship Series.
</P>
<P>
   Pitching against the New York Big Apple Mets, a team that with
prodding from the New York Big Apple media thinks of itself in
terms of destiny, Maddux buried destiny in a hole behind the
pitching rubber for seven innings and turned a 3-1 lead over to the
usually reliable Braves' bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   The Big Appleonians were fodder in the regular season, losing 9
of 12 to the Braves.
</P>
<P>
   Said Mets manager Bobby Valentine, ``I heard (Yankee manager)
Joe Torre say when you get to the postseason, you have to rip up
what happened in the past. I like that statement.''
</P>
<P>
   For one night, however, there was no ripping. This was the same
old same old between the two squads of multi-millionaires.
</P>
<P>
   After the Braves whipped the Mets 5 of 6 in late September,
seemingly sweeping them out of the playoffs, Atlanta's Chipper
Jones suggested Mets fans become cross-dressers and switch to
Yankee apparel.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets took this as if Chipper defamed their mothers.
</P>
<P>
   When Braves' reliever John Rocker was overheard saying he hated
the Mets, that became headlines in the Big Apple Tabloids.
</P>
<P>
   Valentine, who never met a controversy he didn't embrace, has
tried to turn Jones and Rocker into Big Apple Public Enemy Nos. 2
and 3 (behind Hillary Clinton).
</P>
<P>
   Said Maddux on the mini-controversy: ``I'm not sure what's being
said. Ever since I had kids, it's no more ESPN. Now we're watching
Franklin and stuff like that. I've kind of missed the gossip that
goes around the game now, and I don't know what either of those two
guys really said.''
</P>
<P>
   Atlantas yawned, too. Vast expanses of the outfield upper deck
were empty _ six full sections in right field; one in left _ as
Braves' fans balked at the idea of $45 baseball, playoffs or no
playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Maddux clawed out of three tough situations, including a
man-on-third, nobody-out drama in the third.
</P>
<P>
   With the Braves up 3-1 in the eighth, manager Bobby Cox began
micro-managing, lifting Maddux even though he had thrown only 86
pitches.
</P>
<P>
   The eighth came down to the Mets' John Olerud vs. John Rocker,
the Braves' rocket-launching lefty who came into the game to the
mellow strains of Twisted Sisters' I Wanna Rock.
</P>
<P>
   Rocker turned Olerud into a twisted sister: He threw a 97-mph
strike one called, 94-mph strike two called and finished the
operation with a 97-mph strike three swinging, if you can call
Olerud's wave a swing.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Nuhn writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
E-mail: gnuhn(AT)coxohio.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
