<DOCNO> NYT19991012.0453 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-12 23:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5010 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBN-METS-BRAVES-ART-2     10-12 1041
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-BRAVES-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRAVES WIN NLCS OPENER, 4-2 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos are being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(sw) 
 By JUDY BATTISTA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Steve Phillips, the general manager of the New York
Mets, tested an analogy about his team the other day, suggesting
that the last time the Mets had seen the Braves, they were sliding
down a slippery slope and that now, reinvigorated by their rush
into the National League Championship Series, they were climbing
the mountain wearing spiked boots.
</P>
<P>
   But when Roger Cedeno sprayed white chalk on the green infield
grass in his frantic attempt to get back to third base after Masato
Yoshii failed to squeeze him home in the third inning, it was clear
that the crampons were failing.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets, in a renewal of the late-season failure to get timely
hits that nearly doomed their bid to make the playoffs, lost their
grip on a closely played game on Tuesday night and lost 4-2 to the
Braves to drop the opener of their four-of-seven league
championship series.
</P>
<P>
   If the third-base line was too oblique a symbol for the Mets'
continuing woes against the Braves, who dominated them in their
regular season series, then the sight of Melvin Mora, standing on
third base while Braves reliever John Rocker zipped fastball after
fastball by John Olerud to end an eighth-inning threat, was more
direct.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets, who had been sent into a nearly fatal funk by Braves'
pitching just three weeks ago _ Rocker saved all three of those
games _ had provided entertaining theater in getting back to
Atlanta. But from the looks of this game, they hadn't gained much
ground on the decade's premier National League team.
</P>
<P>
   The bad omens were starting to pile up for the Mets before the
first inning was over.
</P>
<P>
   Greg Maddux, whom the Mets had somehow managed to hammer for
their only victory in their six games against the Braves in the
last 10 days of the season, had retired the side in the first
inning on just nine pitches.
</P>
<P>
   The next chilling omen came in the form of Orel Hershiser, the
starter sent to the bullpen for long relief in the playoffs, who
was warming up after Yoshii had faced just three batters.
</P>
<P>
   Yoshii has had mixed results against Atlanta this season. He was
0-2, with a 5.94 era against the Braves, but in his last appearance
he hadn't figured in the decision during the Mets' heartbreaking
extra-innings loss to the Braves that most figured had ended the
Mets' season.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday night, Yoshii had none of the control early in the
game that had made him the Mets' most consistent starter since
August. Gerald Williams smacked Yoshii's first pitch of the game up
the middle for a single and stole second. Bret Boone stretched up
to reach a full-count, shoulder-high pitch for a chopper up the
middle that scored Williams to give the Braves a 1-0 lead,
something that looms when Maddux is on the mound.
</P>
<P>
   With Chipper Jones waiting at the plate, the pitching coach,
Dave Wallace, made a hasty trip to the mound and Hershiser got up.
Yoshii walked Jones _ it was not intentional _ but got out of a
worse mess, retiring Brian Jordan, the Braves' hottest hitter, Ryan
Klesko and Andruw Jones to end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   Yoshii seemed to get stronger as the innings rolled on. But in
the top of the third came the strongest signal yet that perhaps the
pixie dust that had glistened on the Mets for the last 10 days had
worn off a bit.
</P>
<P>
   Roger Cedeno doubled to lead off the inning, the first hit the
Mets got off Maddux. Cedeno's shot went into left field and
Williams, the left fielder, threw the ball in to Boone, the second
baseman and cut-off man. But Boone had to travel 30 feet to even
get close to the ball, which he missed. As the ball rolled away,
Cedeno went to third base on the error.
</P>
<P>
   Then came a fiasco that may go down as one of the significant
lost chances of this series. Rey Ordonez topped a pitch, the ball
rolling along the third-base line. Ordonez stood still watching it.
But the Braves' catcher, Eddie Perez, astutely picked up the ball,
which had remained fair, and threw to first base, getting Ordonez
out without even having to check third to make sure Cedeno was not
moving.
</P>
<P>
   Worse was what came next. On a 2-0 count, Yoshii had received
the sign to bunt, to start a suicide squeeze to bring Cedeno home.
But Yoshii missed the ball entirely and Cedeno was caught in
no-man's land, already more than halfway home. Perez ran him down
and the skid marks Cedeno left, which sprayed the white chalk into
the infield grass, were symbolic of the Mets' perilous mistake.
Yoshii grounded out weakly to Maddux to end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   In the fourth inning, though, Maddux faltered just long enough
to allow a narrow opening for the Mets. Edgardo Alfonzo smashed a
double into left-center with one out and after John Olerud's single
to shallow right failed to score him, Mike Piazza, who had grounded
out to third in his first at-bat since missing two games with a
swollen thumb, grounded to third again.
</P>
<P>
   This time, Chipper Jones bobbled the ball, first against his
chest, then off his glove. By the time he had it in his grasp,
Alfonzo was on his way home to tie the score at 1-1 and Jones could
only get Piazza out at first. Maddux walked Robin Ventura next, but
Darryl Hamilton grounded out to Maddux, the third of four innings
Maddux had ended by fielding the ball himself.
</P>
<P>
   Yoshii had allowed just one base runner since the first inning,
but in the fifth, he encountered trouble again. Walt Weiss, whom
Atlanta Manager Bobby Cox had put into the lineup at shortstop
because of the defensive skill that may have saved the Braves'
season during the division series against Houston, smacked a
leadoff double into right field.
</P>
<P>
   Maddux bunted back to the mound to move Weiss to third, but
Yoshii came off awkwardly and appeared to turn his left ankle
before throwing Maddux out. The Mets' trainer, Fred Hina, and
Manager Bobby Valentine came out to check on Yoshii, and in his
warm-up pitches, he seemed to hop a little on the left foot. But he
remained in the game to face Williams.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   It was a bad decision. Jumping on Yoshii's first pitch again,
Williams hit a single to left field. Rickey Henderson overran the
ball, Weiss scored to give the Braves a 2-1 lead and Williams went
to second base.
</P>
<P>
   But the Braves again failed to batter the Mets. Cedeno made a
full-extension diving catch of a Boone fly ball for the second out
and, after Chipper Jones was intentionally walked and Yoshii
removed for Pat Mahomes, Jordan flied out to end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   Yoshii, apparently bothered by his ankle, had been chased after
he held the Braves to just two runs in four and two-thirds innings.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves' failure to pile up runs might have had more impact
on the game if the Mets could have made something of their at-bats.
But that is a nearly impossible task when Maddux is pitching. He
was 3-1 this season against the Mets (the one loss was the game in
which the Mets scored eight runs in what may have been the worst
inning of Maddux's career) and had a 3.71 earned run average. He
rolled through the Mets on Tuesday night, retiring them in order in
the fifth, allowing just an Alfonzo double in the sixth and a
single to Cedeno in the seventh.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves had added another run in the sixth inning, but again,
they could have done so much more. Klesko, the leadoff batter,
reached base on a rare error by Olerud, who failed to field a
bouncer in front of the plate. But Andruw Jones grounded into a
double play to clear the bases before Perez slammed a solo home run
into the second row of the left field seats to extend the lead to
3-1.
</P>
<P>
   It only felt as if the Braves were beating the Mets worse than
they were, a fitting continuation of the Mets' seasonlong struggle
to inch up to the Braves.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
