<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-12 23:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5017 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BKO-WILT-APPRECIATION     10-12 1454
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKO-WILT-APPRECIATION-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Heart attack fells one of NBA's most dominant forces at 63
 &HT;    By Ethan J. Skolnick
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Wilt Chamberlain, so dominant a
basketball player that he once scored 100 points in a single NBA
game, died Tuesday at his Bel-Air home of an apparent heart attack.
He was 63.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Chamberlain's body was found by authorities who were called
to his home shortly after noon Los Angeles time. Mr. Chamberlain,
who spent much time during the past decade at the suburban Boca
Raton restaurant that bears his name, was hospitalized with an
irregular heartbeat in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've lost a giant of a man in every sense of the word,'' NBA
Commissioner David Stern said of the player considered by many to
be the greatest of all time. ``The shadow of accomplishment he cast
over our game is unlikely ever to be matched.''
</P>
<P>
   Known as ``Wilt the Stilt'' and ``The Big Dipper,'' the
outspoken, 7-foot-1 Mr. Chamberlain had a presence wherever he
went, from his birthplace of Philadelphia to Boca Raton, where he
could be spotted this decade playing polo and tennis, commentating
at slam-dunk contests at Florida Atlantic University, and strolling
through the Glades Road restaurant he and business partners opened
in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Vittoroulis, the general manager and owner of the
restaurant, said today's proceeds will be donated to a charity, and
flowers and a picture of Wilt will be placed outside the front
doors.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, Mr. Chamberlain began sponsoring the annual Rising Star
Shoot-out just down the street at Olympic Heights High School.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is totally refreshing for me,'' Mr. Chamberlain said
before the first Shoot-out. ``Totally, totally, totally. I'm
looking forward to getting involved with these kids, talking with
them, maybe getting them some things to think about their future.''
</P>
<P>
   By then, Mr. Chamberlain's past had inspired tall tales of all
sorts. His accomplishments and appetites could only be quantified
with enormous numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Chamberlain played 14 seasons in the NBA, for the
Philadelphia (later the San Francisco) Warriors, the 76ers and the
Lakers, scoring 31,419 points, a record until Kareem Abdul-Jabbar
broke it in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wilt was one of the greatest ever, and we will never see
another one like him,'' Abdul-Jabbar said.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Chamberlain never fouled out in a 1,205 regular-season and
playoff games. He holds the record for career rebounding with
23,924, and for single-game rebounding, with 55 against Boston in
1960. He averaged 30.1 points per game in his career, including a
record 50.4 in the 1961-62 season with Philadelphia. He won the
Rookie of the Year Award in 1959-60, the MVP award four times and
the league's rebounding title 11 times. He even led the league in
assists in 1967-68.
</P>
<P>
   He may not have changed the game, but the NBA did because of
him, widening the lane to try to keep him farther from the basket.
</P>
<P>
   Only one man ever had much luck at that _ Bill Russell of the
Boston Celtics. Russell and Mr. Chamberlain staged one of the
longest and most compelling rivalries in modern sports history,
while maintaining a close friendship off the court. Mr. Chamberlain
led his teams into the playoffs 13 times, but won only two NBA
championships, in 1966-67 with the 76ers and in 1971-72 with the
Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   Seven times Russell's Celtics ended Mr. Chamberlain's season,
twice in the championship series and five times in the conference
finals. Three times, a series was decided by a seventh game that
Boston won by either one or two points.
</P>
<P>
   ``To Russ, winning at basketball was everything,'' Mr.
Chamberlain later said of his rival, whom he would invite to his
house for dinner before they faced each other. ``It was a test of
his manhood. I looked at basketball as a game, not a life-and-death
struggle. There are too many other beautiful things in life _ food,
cars, girls, friends, the beach, freedom.''
</P>
<P>
   The Celtics' success did not diminish their respect for Mr.
Chamberlain.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wilt Chamberlain had a great deal to do with the success of
the NBA,'' former Celtics coach Red Auerbach said. ``His dominance,
power, demeanor and the rivalry with Bill Russell says it all.''
</P>
<P>
   If one game said it all, it occurred on March 2, 1962. Mr.
Chamberlain scored 100 points in the Philadelphia Warriors' 169-147
defeat of the New York Knicks in Hershey, Pa. No one has approached
that mark, with David Thompson's 73 points in 1978 coming closest.
Mr. Chamberlain scored at least that many four times.
</P>
<P>
   ``I spent 12 years in his armpits, and I always carried that
100-point game on my shoulders,'' said Darrall Imhoff, a 6-foot-10
rookie for the Knicks in 1962. ``After I got my third foul, I said
to one of the officials, Willy Smith, `Why don't you just give him
100 points and we'll all go home?' Well, we did.''
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Chamberlain's first home was in Philadelphia. He was born on
Aug. 21, 1936, and didn't begin playing basketball until the
seventh grade. He grew 4 inches in three months when he was 15, and
was 6-foot-11 when he entered Philadelphia's Overbrook High School.
</P>
<P>
   After leading Overbrook to three public school championships and
two all-city titles, Chamberlain was recruited by more than 200
colleges.
</P>
<P>
   He chose the University of Kansas and Hall of Fame coach Phog
Allen. In his first freshman game against the Kansas varsityhe
scored 50 points before a packed Allen Fieldhouse crowd of more
than 15,000.
</P>
<P>
   The next year, Mr. Chamberlain scored 52 points against
Northwestern in his first game, a total he never surpassed in
college, partly because of zone defenses designed to keep him from
the ball.
</P>
<P>
   As a junior, he led the 1957 Jayhawks to the NCAA Tournament
final, where Kansas lost to unbeaten North Carolina in triple
overtime in his final college game. Disgusted by being smothered by
the zone defenses, Mr. Chamberlain left Kansas the next year and
joined the Harlem Globetrotters.
</P>
<P>
   Extremely agile for his size, Mr. Chamberlain ran cross-country
in high school and was an outstanding high jumper and shot-putter
at Kansas. He had remained active after his NBA career and was
considered an outstanding volleyball player. He also ran the
Honolulu Marathon recently.
</P>
<P>
   In January 1998, Mr. Chamberlain made his first official visit
to Kansas since his college career ended. His jersey was raised to
the rafters of Allen Fieldhouse. ``I've learned in life that you
have to take the bitter with the sweet, and how sweet this is,''
Mr. Chamberlain said then.
</P>
<P>
   He seemed genuinely surprised at how much he was loved by the
rabid Kansas fans after staying away for 40 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Forty years ago I lost a heartbreaking battle, losing to North
Carolina by one point in triple overtime,'' he told the crowd. ``It
was a devastating thing for me because I felt like I let the
university down, I let KU down.''
</P>
<P>
   The crowd interrupted, yelling, ``No, no,'' before resuming
another standing ovation.
</P>
<P>
   He did not receive such rave reviews in 1991 after releasing his
autobiography, A View From Above, in which he boasted that he had
sex with 20,000 women. The book, which Mr. Chamberlain said had
been written two years earlier, was released shortly after Earvin
``Magic'' Johnson, another of the NBA's greatest players, revealed
he was HIV-positive.
</P>
<P>
   ``The women who I have been the most attracted to, the most in
love with, I've pushed away the strongest,'' the lifelong bachelor
said in a 1991 interview. ``There are about five women I can think
of I could have married. I cared for them a lot, but not enough to
make a commitment.''
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Chamberlain said later he regretted that readers focused so
much on that one number, and not on other points he made in the
book. Mr. Chamberlain was often critical of modern NBA players, and
openly envious of their salaries. He estimated that he made about
$2.2 million during his professional career, including $425,000 in
his final season.
</P>
<P>
   ``To put that in perspective, Patrick Ewing makes more in 10
games _ 10 games _ than Wilt Chamberlain made in 14 years of
playing basketball,'' he told the Post in December.
</P>
<P>
   During those 14 years, he played 47,859 minutes, proving to be
as durable as he was unstoppable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that my legacy should be that I gave credence that you
could be big, bigger than most and still have athletic ability,''
Mr. Chamberlain said in 1996, when he was interviewed as one of the
NBA's 50 greatest players.
</P>
<P>
   Ethan J. Skolnick writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm
Beach, Fla. Wire services contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
