<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-12 23:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5018 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-U.N.-KOSOVO-DEATH-NYT     10-12 0812
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-U.N.-KOSOVO-DEATH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.N. WORKER SLAIN IN KOSOVO WAS RESIDENT OF NEW YORK 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ANDREW JACOBS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The United Nations employee who was killed on his
first day in Kosovo on Monday was a Queens resident who had spent
years working toward a peacekeeping assignment with the
organization.
</P>
<P>
   Valentin Krumov, 38, who lived in the Flushing section of
Queesn, was beaten and then shot to death as he took an
after-dinner stroll on Mother Teresa Street, the main pedestrian
thoroughfare in the capital Pristina, the authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   Krumov was killed after he spoke Serbo-Croatian to a group of
ethnic Albanian teen-agers, one of whom had apparently asked him
the time in Serbo-Croatian, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``A crowd of local citizens assaulted him. He was taken by a mob
... and shot dead,'' Lt. Col. Dmitry Kapotsev told The Associated
Press. He said the youths, seeking revenge on Serbs, who they blame
for years of repression, may have assumed he was Serbian.
</P>
<P>
   A black jacket he was wearing, inscribed with the words ``United
States, New York,'' was found nearby, splattered with blood.
</P>
<P>
   He was killed by a single bullet to the head, Kapotsev said.
</P>
<P>
   Krumov was the first international worker from the United
Nations to be killed since it moved into Kosovo in mid-June. The
mission, which followed the 11-week bombing of Yugoslavia and the
departure of Serbian forces, is setting up an interim government in
the province. Krumov was to work on the creation of Kosovo's new
government .
</P>
<P>
   A native of Bulgaria and the son of engineers, Krumov had lived
in New York off and on since 1994, when he got his first position
at the United Nations as an intern, said Marie Okabe, a spokeswoman
for the organization. Besides brief stints in the Slovak Republic
and in the former Soviet Georgia, this was his first long-term
mission with the United Nations, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
   His supervisor, Franco Bechi, said Krumov was ecstatic about the
assignment, which was to run until April with the opportunity for
an extension. ``He was looking forward to a long career with the
U.N.,'' said Bechi, who saw Krumov the night before his departure.
``He had a great soul. He was friendly, polite and very
hard-working.''
</P>
<P>
   A former major in the Bulgarian army, Krumov had received a
doctorate in political science from the University of Georgia in
December. He was an expert in Eastern Europe and Balkan affairs and
spoke six languages.
</P>
<P>
   ``His language skills were his assets,'' Bechi said, ``and in
the end, they were his problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Ivan Damyanoff, 67, a friend and a neighbor, said Krumov was
remarkably idealistic and saw the United Nations as a powerful
force for healing broken nations. ``Most of us start out starry
eyed and become cynical,'' he said. ``But Valentin stayed that way.
He really believed he could change the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Another friend, Vinya Nick, 53, described Krumov as an
open-minded, exuberant man who loved to dance, cook, write poetry
and talk politics. ``Without exaggeration, he was one of the most
cultured people I ever met,'' she said. ``He had an incredible
appetite for learning.''
</P>
<P>
   But Krumov's openness could also be a weakness, Ms. Nick said.
``He was the kind of person who would talk to anyone,'' she said.
``If only he had been more suspicious.'' She said he had been
zealously studying Albanian during the last few weeks because he
wanted to get closer to the local people. ``He was so tolerant, so
vibrant, a real citizen of the world,'' she said. ``This has all
the elements of a Greek tragedy.''
</P>
<P>
   After checking into Pristina's Grand Hotel on Monday and eating
dinner, he joined two newly arrived colleagues for a walk down the
city's liveliest street, which is closed to vehicular traffic at
night. It was thronged with young people taking in the evening air
when he was approached by the group of teen-agers, the authorities
said. Soon after he responded in Serbo-Croatian, police said, he
was attacked.
</P>
<P>
   A suspect escaped on foot, apparently helped by other residents
crowding the street, they said. The two other employees were not
hurt.
</P>
<P>
   A Polish police officer who did not want to be identified told
The Associated Press that he never spoke his own language because
it could be mistaken for Serbian: both are Slavic languages and can
sound similar to those unfamiliar with Polish. Albanians themselves
have reported threats when speaking Serbo-Croatian with visitors
from Bosnia or Croatia.
</P>
<P>
   A few hours before Krumov left for the airport in New York, Ms.
Nick said she lectured him on the phone about his naivete. ``Be
vigilant, be careful, and remember, sometimes it's better not to
say anything,'' she recalled telling him.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations will fly his body to Bulgaria Wednesday,
where he will be buried by his family.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
